<SLUG> BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENSIVE PRESSURE IS WORKING FOR MIAMI 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVIE, Fla. _ First, they invariably attack the passer with more
than the usual four rushers. At the same time, their cornerbacks
are sticking to the opponent's wide receivers like chewing gum.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the two strategies that have catapulted the Miami
Dolphins almost overnight into the National Football League's most
productive interception team.
</P>
<P>
   They blitz and they press, and the combination has produced 26
interceptions, 16 more than all of last season and just six away
from the team record set in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the Dolphins, who face the Jets in Miami on Sunday
night in a battle for first place in the AFC East, have yielded an
NFL-low 14.2 points a game.
</P>
<P>
   Miami did a fair amount of blitzing last season. ``But now
that's like our base defense,'' cornerback Terrell Buckley said
Wednesday. ``We bring it.''
</P>
<P>
   What's new is Coach Jimmy Johnson's decision to simplify pass
coverage by assigning his regular cornerbacks _ Terrell Buckley and
Sam Madison _ to a receiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it allows us to play better defense,'' Johnson said.
``With the people we have, with the talent we have, it prevents
teams from taking the ball and driving it and keeping it away from
our offense. We make more plays.''
</P>
<P>
   The result: Buckley and Madison have become Pro Bowl candidates
with seven interceptions each. In fact, Johnson recently called
Madison _ a second-year pro from the University of Louisville _ the
best cornerback he has ever coached.
</P>
<P>
   The best part for Johnson is that seven of his players have made
interceptions. Even stubby inside linebacker Zach Thomas has three,
two returned for touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it takes a special player to get out there and do what
we do,'' Buckley said. ``We're up in your face.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Madison: ``We press every play, every down, when we're
tired, sweaty, when it's raining, in sleet, snow, whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   Dissatisfied that his team was giving up too many easy passes,
Johnson huddled with defensive coordinator George Hill in the off
season. Pressing coverage had worked for Johnson in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted to tighten our coverages,'' Hill said. ``He felt
like we needed to be more aggressive there. You know, some people
don't realize what a bright football coach Jimmy is. They think of
him as a head coach, but he was a fine defensive coach before
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The press technique is not for the faint-hearted. The danger
exists on every play that with a slip here, a bump there, someone
could be running for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins have given up 22 pass plays of at least 25 yards
this season, and Buckley was burned for a 56-yard game-loser
against Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when evaluated as part of the big picture, Johnson and Hill
are almost giddy about the move. The Dolphins also have 42
quarterback sacks, which is within seven of the team record, set in
1983.
</P>
<P>
   Six of the Dolphins' interceptions came last week against the
Oakland Raiders. Thomas and fellow linebacker Robert Jones had two
each, with a touchdown apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Derrick Rodgers was asked Wednesday why he was the only Miami
starting linebacker who failed to produce a touchdown in the game.
``I don't know,'' he said, smiling. ``I guess it's a conspiracy.''
</P>
<P>
   As much fun as the Dolphins had in beating the Raiders, they
understand that defending against the Jets' Keyshawn Johnson and
Wayne Chrebet on Sunday likely won't yield as many chuckles.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do a good job of feeding those guys,'' Buckley said.
``They do a lot of different things to get them open _ more than
most teams. Sure this looks like one of our biggest challenges.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet when it was pointed out that the Jets have scored 80 points
in the last two games, Buckley grew feisty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've played a lot of teams that scored a lot of points the
week before,'' he said. ``Teams play a different type of defense
than we do. So it's an opportunity to go out and prove we have a
good defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's height _ he's 6 feet 3 inches, compared to the 5-9
Buckley and 5-11 Madison _ didn't seem to faze Buckley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since pee wee ball, Sam and I have played guys 6-3, 6-4,'' he
said. ``That doesn't matter. What matters is whether you can play
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Madison isn't shy about acknowledging his and Buckley's
contributions to the Dolphins' success. He noted that the team is
leading the league in pass defense primarily because of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we get it done,'' he said, ``most of the time the team
comes out victorious.''
</P>
</TEXT>
