<HEADLINE>
TOLEDO HAS COLLISION WITH REALITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA _ The bright yellow balloon was bobbing in the
passenger seat of the red Buick Regal, a giant smiley face grinning
at UCLA football coach Bob Toledo and his assistant, Mark Weber. As
the balloon grew bigger and bigger and bigger, so did the two men's
pupils.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds like a scene straight out of a Farrelly brothers
movie. You see a giant smiley face right before your life flashes
in front of your eyes. Bruins offensive lineman Kris Farris, an
amateur movie critic, would pan the sight gag as a cheap use of
irony.
</P>
<P>
   But this was not a movie Toledo was talking about Wednesday at
the Rose Bowl headquarters, it was his life. Or rather, his near
death.
</P>
<P>
   It was Monday afternoon, less than 48 hours after the the Bruins
had been broadsided in Miami on their way to an undefeated season
and a national championship. Toledo and Weber were traveling in the
slow lane of a six-lane highway, heading toward the Atlanta airport
after visiting a punting recruit in nearby Norcross.
</P>
<P>
   Weber was driving their rental car, a four-door Chevy Malibu.
Toledo, 52, was sitting beside him, sipping a soda. They were
babbling about what good time they were making when the red car
appeared out of nowhere. It was bearing down on them from their
left, the female driver's view clearly obstructed by the balloon
riding shotgun.
</P>
<P>
   After two days of haranguing and hand-wringing over the Bruins'
49-45 loss to the Hurricanes, it took only a split second for the
blown call on Brad Melsby's late fumble and the defense's dismal
display throughout to be totally trivialized.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, man,'' Toledo had time to scream before the woman struck
their car on the driver's side, between the front and rear doors.
Weber was traveling 50 miles an hour at the time. Had he been
going, say, 49.9, they probably would have had to pick Weber off
the front grill of the woman's car.
</P>
<P>
   The impact turned the Malibu into a flicked bottle top that spun
and spun in traffic until it came to a standstill, facing oncoming
cars. It was all over in a matter of seconds but it seemed to
Toledo that he and Weber would never stop spinning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never spun around like that. It was like in slow
motion,'' Toledo said. ``That was a scary moment in my life. I
thought I was dead.''
</P>
<P>
   When he realized, to his immense relief, that he was mistaken,
Toledo reached for his cellular phone. But his fingers were
trembling so, he couldn't punch in 9-1-1.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't matter. Within minutes an ambulance, a fire truck and
squad cars were parked at the scene. One of the police officers
eyed Toledo quizzically.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look familiar,'' he said, sizing up Toledo warily. ``Did I
arrest you before?''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo's tongue was working about as well as his fingers, and as
he fumbled for a response the cop's expression softened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know who you are,'' he said. ``You're that coach that was on
TV the other day. The guy from UCLA.''
</P>
<P>
   But, of course. Toledo's shellshocked expression was a dead
giveaway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaken, scared, nervous'' is how Toledo described his emotions
after his second pile-up in three days. Not that there's any
comparing a football collapse with a car crash.
</P>
<P>
   No one in a uniform hauled away in handcuffs any of the
offending Bruins defensive backs, as the police did the other
driver after determining she had a suspended license and no
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the degree of devastation. As he watched the tow
trucks haul off the demolished rental car and the destroyed red
car, Toledo couldn't help thinking, that wasn't a life-altering
loss he and the Bruins had suffered Saturday, it was simply a
defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Weber and I, we're just lucky to be alive,'' said
Toledo, who escaped with a stiff neck, a separated left shoulder
and a headache that refuses to recede. ``It put that game in Miami
in perspective, trust me.''
</P>
<P>
   When a cab came and whisked Toledo and Weber to the airport _
amazingly, in time to make their scheduled flight to their next
recruiting port of call _ Toledo thought the worst of the day was
behind him. He was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Upon arriving at his hotel, his message light was flashing
ominously. The UCLA football program had been involved in a
hit-and-run.
</P>
<P>
   A report had been filed on the Internet earlier in the day
claiming the football team was racked by dissension, with players
of different races divided over the issue of affirmative action.
Toledo was dumbstruck.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, the allegations remained an open sore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing,'' Toledo said during a press conference that
also featured Wisconsin coach Barry Alvarez, whose team will face
the Bruins on Jan. 1. ``We've done so many good things. Then we
lose one game and everybody gets emotional and upset and says
ridiculous things. It's sad.''
</P>
<P>
   What's regrettable is a team that strung together a
nation-leading 20-game winning streak with 18 starters that graced
the school Honor Roll is having to defend itself at all. It's a
good thing the Bruins are smart enough to distinguish fact from
fiction.
</P>
<P>
   After the week Toledo has had, you can be sure he'll drive home
to his players the difference between sports and life. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
