<HEADLINE>
2 ASTRONAUTS INSTALL ANTENNAS ON SPACE STATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for updating, rewriting throughout)  (sw) 
 By WARREN E. LEARY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NASA's astronaut construction workers on Wednesday
added communications antennas and removed unneeded equipment from
the exterior of the space station in another space walk from the
shuttle Endeavour.
</P>
<P>
   Col. Jerry Ross of the Air Force and Dr. James Newman, a
physicist, completed a seven-hour space walk on Wednesday night
after emerging from Endeavour's airlock earlier than planned, at
3:33 p.m. ET. They accomplished all of their tasks, including
improving the communications systems aboard the two station
sections docked to the shuttle's cargo bay and freeing a stuck
antenna.
</P>
<P>
   The main objective was to install two, 100-pound communications
antennas on opposite sides of the American-made Unity connecting
module. The astronauts wrestled with the suitcase-size antennas as
they pulled them through a narrow tunnel into the cargo bay. Then,
with Ross riding the shuttle's robot arm and Newman moving up the
side of the module on a tether line, they moved the antennas
halfway up the 35-foot-tall module.
</P>
<P>
   Each astronaut installed an antenna, and Newman hooked his to a
video cable running down from the Russian-built Zarya module. On
Thursday, when the six-member crew enters the station modules for
the first time, the astronauts will hook the antennas to equipment
on the inside and test a video conferencing system that will be
used in the early stages of station construction.
</P>
<P>
   Wedneday's space walk was the second of three planned for the
12-day mission.
</P>
<P>
   The new antennas also will give NASA's Mission Control at the
Johnson Space Center in Houston the ability to monitor Unity and to
have direct control over operations on the station without having
to go through Russian ground stations.
</P>
<P>
   The astronauts quickly moved through the other objectives of the
walk, including erecting a folding sunshade over a computer mounted
outside of Unity and bundling loose cables along the exterior.
</P>
<P>
   Working around the 7-story, 35-ton Zarya-Unity stack, the
astronauts also removed restraints used to stablize four Unity
hatchways during launching. These hatches will be docking ports for
other station modules, including the framework for a solar array
and a cupola viewing port, that will be added in the station's
five-year construction period.
</P>
<P>
   As the astronauts worked their way around the station's aluminum
exterior, bright sunlight illuminated the blue-lettered ``Unity''
emblem, which includes small representations of the American Flag
and NASA's insignia. Noticing it, Ross remarked to his partner,
``Kind of neat working up here right by the Unity sign, isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before the space walk, ground controllers gave the
astronauts permission to try to unstick one of two rolled-up
antennas on Zarya. The astronauts confirmed on Monday that
explosive bolts that were to unfurl the four-foot long antennas had
fired after Zarya was launched on Nov. 20 but failed to deploy the
devices, to be used to help dock ships to the Russian module.
</P>
<P>
   Newman tapped the antenna free with a 10-foot-long extendable
grappling hook. The astronauts will try to free the other antenna
on the third space walk on Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
