<HEADLINE>
UCLA'S YOUNG READY TO RUN AND GUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Freshman guard Ray Young is one of UCLA's best
athletes, with strength, quickness and an anti-gravity vertical
jump. But until recently, he couldn't scale a tall wall.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it wasn't so much tall as long _ two hours long.
</P>
<P>
   ``In high school, we'd practice about two hours and go all
out,'' Young said. ``Here, it's a different philosophy. We go three
or three-and-a-half hours. I'd hit the wall about after two hours.
I had to break through it.''
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, he did, and the results were immediate: He was
tougher, more confident and more productive. After a slow start,
Young, from Alameda, has become a quiet contributor and one of
UCLA's best defensive players.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last three weeks, he's played as well as anybody in
practice and in games,'' coach Steve Lavin said. ``He's been very
productive without a lot of minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Torn ankle ligaments made Young's transition to college
practices doubly difficult. He spent part of the summer on crutches
and was several strides behind when the Bruins began practice in
October.
</P>
<P>
   The nadir came against San Francisco in the Puerto Rico
Shootout. Young didn't play, but his high school rivals, Ali Thomas
and LyRyan Russell, got plenty of time for the Dons.
</P>
<P>
   Young considered transferring.
</P>
<P>
   ``That definitely came into play,'' he said. ``I saw those kids
I knew from home getting more playing time. But I'm here, and I
believe in the program.''
</P>
<P>
   Young gradually played himself into shape, over the wall and
onto the court. He had five points and three rebounds in six
minutes against Oklahoma State.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's come the furthest since Oct. 15,'' Lavin said. ``There
was a point where he was buried.... But he kept working. We have to
find a way to get him more time.''
</P>
<P>
   Back to basics: Freshman forward JaRon Rush has been removed
from the starting lineup because nagging back pain limits his
practice time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has less to do with performance and more to do with
practice time,'' Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   Rush injured his lower back several years ago and never
strengthened the muscles in his lower back and stomach. Bruins
trainer Jeff Smith has prescribed a series of exercises, including
sit-ups, to strengthen the muscles in Rush's ``trunk.''
</P>
<P>
   ``JaRon just has a weak trunk,'' Smith said. ``It'll probably
bug him most of this year. But once we get into the offseason,
that's all he'll be doing and it should improve.''
</P>
<P>
   A nice check: Sophomore guard Ryan Bailey has been placed on
scholarship. Bailey, the brother of ex-Bruin Toby, transferred from
Penn State last season as a walk-on.
</P>
<P>
   UNLV update: UCLA's opponent Saturday, Nevada-Las Vegas, is a
talented but chaotic team with a 4-3 record that includes losses to
USC (71-68) and Arizona State (79-70).
</P>
<P>
   ``They aren't playing exceptionally well, but they're a
dangerous team,'' Lavin said. ``They're searching for their
identity, like ourselves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
