<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 00:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2250 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-CLEMENS-HNS &LR;      12-10 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-CLEMENS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
Toronto Blue Jays general manager Gord Ash said Wednesday he has
received at least one acceptable offer for pitcher Roger Clemens.
But it isn't believed to have come from one of the three teams _
the Astros, Texas Rangers and New York Yankees _ considered the top
contenders for his services.
<TEXT>
<P>
   So who is this mystery team?
</P>
<P>
   Ash did not identify the club, nor, he added, have the Blue Jays
accepted an offer for baseball's only five-time Cy Young Award
winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have an offer from a club that from a player point of view
satisfies our needs,'' Ash said. ``What I've suggested to that club
is that they get guidance from Roger's representatives
(Houston-based agents Alan and Randy Hendricks) on how they should
proceed from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland was rumored Wednesday as the likely team, but Indians
GM John Hart quickly shot down any reports that the Indians were
the club. Anaheim, Colorado, Atlanta, Los Angeles and the New York
Mets were not believed to be the clubs, either, baseball sources
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ash said the club that made the proposal did not contact him
Wednesday and that he talked with just two teams during the day,
one of which was the Rangers. Texas general manager Doug Melvin met
with Ash for 90 minutes Tuesday, and the two had breakfast
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess what I'm directing that club to do is make sure they
qualify,'' Ash said. ``They had a lot of questions for me that I
couldn't answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens on Dec. 2 asked for a trade closer to his home in
Houston or to a contender after concluding the Blue Jays were
unwilling to spend money to build a competitive club. He can block
a trade or force potential clubs to renegotiate his contract, which
calls for salaries of $5 million next year and $6.35 million in
2000. Toronto owes $5 million in deferred money from the first two
seasons of the deal, which currently guarantees a minimum of $31.5
million over four years.
</P>
<P>
   As a veteran traded in the midst of a multiyear contract,
Clemens could file an official trade demand after the 1999 season
if he decides not to ask for renegotiation.
</P>
<P>
   Ash had hoped to finalize a deal for Clemens, 36, prior to
leaving tonight for the winter meetings in Nashville, Tenn.,
although that seems unlikely after Wednesday's slow progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say from the lack of conversation today, this is going
to drag into the weekend for sure,'' Ash said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Ash said he had narrowed the number of teams
the Jays might deal with to six. Apparently, however, the field has
expanded.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on their bid to lure free-agent pitcher Kevin Brown,
the St. Louis Cardinals have reportedly expressed interest in
Clemens, who went 41-13 and won a pair of Cy Youngs in two seasons
with Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have made a late push with a deal that would feature
infielder Edgardo Alfonzo as the centerpiece of a package that also
could include righthander Bobby Jones and either pitching prospect
Octavio Dotel or outfield prospect Jay Payton. And Colorado is said
to be offering second baseman Mike Lansing, righthander Darryl Kile
or righthander Pedro Astacio, and one other player.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've talked, but we're not optimistic,'' Rockies GM Bob
Gebhard said. ``But we are talking, and I'll leave it at that.''
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore, too, joined the picture late Wednesday night. The
Orioles have reportedly offered Toronto a package that includes
lefthanded reliever Arthur Rhodes and two prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta is believed to have pulled out of the bidding, as Braves
GM John Schuerholz is likely finished with any additions after
acquiring Bret Boone, Brian Jordan and Otis Nixon during the
offseason. The Braves are currently operating with what would be a
$72 million budget for next season, $5 million more than the club
desires.
</P>
<P>
   Most teams believe it will take at least three players to pry
Clemens away from the Blue Jays. There is also the possibility of
the Clemens sweepstakes turning into a three-team deal, sources
said.
</P>
<P>
   Astros owner Drayton McLane Jr. has said his team has put one
offer on the table. The identities of the players involved have not
been disclosed, but the Blue Jays have shown interest in outfielder
Derek Bell and pitcher Scott Elarton.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Shane Reynolds was at one point mentioned as a trade
possibility, but the Astros are said to be working toward a
contract extension for the righthander that could come as early as
today. Reynolds, who won 19 games in 1998, has one year remaining
on his current contract.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
