 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
MickeyHerskowitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WHEN Roger Staubach was in his prime, and the Dallas Cowboys all
but had their own church, he once said that he pictured heaven as a
place where quarterbacks ``completed all their passes.''
</P>
<P>
   One writer, a cynical sort as most of them are, asked, ``What
about defensive backs?''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no defensive backs in heaven,'' Roger replied,
kidding on the square.
</P>
<P>
   By the same token, there must be a special place somewhere for
college coaches. A place where quarterbacks play on one leg and a
team given no chance to win rallies from 15 points behind to claim
a championship.
</P>
<P>
   R.C. Slocum found such a place last weekend in St. Louis. His
Texas A&AMP;M Aggies were coming off a killer loss to the Texas
Longhorns, as dominated as a team can be when it loses by two
points. And Saturday, the Aggies fell behind by margins of 17-3 and
27-12 and trailed by 15 points going into the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   They had started their backup quarterback, Branndon Stewart, who
strained a knee in the first quarter and had to be helped to the
bench. On the Aggies' sideline, the punter, Shane Lechler, loosened
up his arm. He would go into the game as the emergency quarterback
if Stewart were unable to continue.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the Aggies, and their grandkids as yet unborn,
Stewart made it back onto the field and then produced one of the
great and gritty comebacks in the school's history.
</P>
<P>
   As much as Aggies fans would love it, we can't repeat the
play-by-play of the fourth quarter and overtime in the space
available to us. But in a quarter and a fraction, Stewart completed
11 of 20 passes for 235 yards and three touchdowns, two of them to
Sirr Parker, including the game-winner. The same pair combined for
a two-point conversion.
</P>
<P>
   For those watching at home, or on their bar stools, it was
exciting listening to the announcers, Brent Musburger and Dan
Fouts, remind us that Kansas State was 30 minutes away from
qualifying for the Fiesta Bowl and a national-championship game.
Then the Wildcats were 15 minutes from Tempe, and now 10. Then they
stopped counting.
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies, down all day, were roaring back. Stewart, who had
struggled for three years, suddenly looked like Unitas or Marino or
Peyton Manning, whose large shadow caused Stewart to transfer from
Tennessee. After all the criticism and all the disappointments,
Branndon was rifling his passes to Chris Taylor, Derrick Spiller
and Leroy Hodgel. Suddenly, he was the can't-miss guy. In overtime,
Max Baumgardner made a circus catch to set up Parker's final dash
in a 36-33 stunner.
</P>
<P>
   Sirr might have scored in the first half, except that he began
to celebrate at the 15-yard line, which is not often mistaken for
the goal line. But oddly, in a year when they won 10 in a row and
upset then-second-ranked Nebraska, the Aggies' celebrations have
been short-lived. They were buried by many of the fans and all of
the media after falling to Florida State in August, and again after
Ricky Williams did his tap dance on their heads.
</P>
<P>
   In St. Louis, in spite of injuries and the odds and all that
Kansas State had going for it, the Aggies wouldn't surrender. Every
time the Wildcats thought they had nailed the coffin shut, the
Aggies jammed their first through the lid.
</P>
<P>
   One game might not be compensation for three years of waiting,
but Stewart in the clutch was the quarterback of Aggie dreams. And
Parker, who was hurt at the start of the season and never quite
found his role in a sputtering Aggies offense, topped K-State's
Michael Bishop.
</P>
<P>
   In Bishop, the Wildcats might have the most exciting player in
college football, a quarterback who can beat you running or passing
or thinking. But his fumble gave the Aggies a reprieve.
</P>
<P>
   You won't convince anyone on the Kansas plains that this is what
makes college football great, this kind of whiplash shift of
fortune, but R.C. Slocum believes it.
</P>
<P>
   Slocum's teams have averaged 9.3 wins a year since he succeeded
Jackie Sherrill 10 years ago. The Aggies were undefeated for three
straight years in the Southwest Conference. Now, after finishing in
the Top 10 five of the past seven years, they have won their first
Big 12 title.
</P>
<P>
   As one of the winningest coaches in the land, and least
recognized, Slocum has never been a finalist for the Bear Bryant
Coach of the Year Award. The 1998 trophy will be presented at the
Westin Galleria tonight at the annual dinner for the benefit of the
Heart Association. You recall the praise heaped upon K-State's Bill
Snyder from the TV booth in St. Louis. Musburger quoted Barry
Switzer, no less, as saying, ``He ought to be Coach of the
Century,'' for turning around a program that was almost deceased.
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies might stop short of claiming the only title left,
Coach of the Millennium, for their man. But one fine day, R.C.
Slocum ought to have a place at the table.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-98 0053EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
