<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 00:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2253 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-JUDGE-APPOINTED-NY     12-10 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-JUDGE-APPOINTED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI MAKES APPOINTMENT TO COURT OF APPEALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seizing a chance to reshape a court he has repeatedly assailed
as too sympathetic to criminal defendants, Gov. George Pataki
Wednesday nominated Albert Rosenblatt, a state appeals court judge
and a former Dutchess County prosecutor, to replace one of the
state's most liberal jurists on New York's highest court.
</P>
<P>
   If confirmed by the state Senate _ a step that is all but
certain _ Rosenblatt, who sits on the Appellate Division of state
Supreme Court in Poughkeepsie, would become Pataki's second
appointment to the seven-member Court of Appeals. Rosenblatt would
replace Judge Vito Titone of Staten Island, the court's
longest-serving member, who had been appointed in 1985 to the
position by his friend, Gov. Mario Cuomo.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's selections to the Court of Appeals are closely
watched, both because of the court's historic stature as one of the
nation's most influential and once liberal benches, and because of
Pataki's obvious dissatisfaction with some of its views. Pataki has
long identified himself with criminal justice issues and campaigned
in 1994 on a pledge to reinstate the death penalty. He has often
criticized Court of Appeals decisions, such as one making it harder
for police officers to gather evidence against criminal defendants.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in Albany, Pataki chose not to reiterate
his frequent criticism of the court and instead cast his decision
in broader terms than judicial ideology. The Republican governor
invoked Rosenblatt's breadth of experience, particularly his two
years as the state's chief administrative judge, in addition to his
judicial writings and personal bearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at his opinions,'' Pataki said, ``they are just
really thought out and intelligently written and have that
combination of judicial wisdom and common sense that I think makes
for an outstanding judge.''
</P>
<P>
   All seven members of the Court of Appeals who were sitting when
Pataki took office in 1995 had been appointed by Cuomo, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenblatt, 62, began his legal career as a prosecutor in
Dutchess County in 1964, where he worked until he was elected a
county judge in 1975. He also was the last judge in New York to
sentence a defendant to death prior to the reinstatement of the
death penalty: Lemuel Smith, for killing a prison guard, in 1981.
Smith's sentence was converted to 25 years-to-life in prison after
the state's highest court overturned the portion of the death
penalty law under which he had been sentenced.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was far from certain that Rosenblatt's arrival on the
bench would be a sign of a significant shift in the court's
direction. For one thing, the Court of Appeals is no longer viewed
as being as sympathetic to the rights of defendants as it was in
the 1980s, when it was led by Sol Wachtler as chief judge.
</P>
<P>
   And at least in the way it presents itself to the public with
its written decisions, it has been relatively free of the kind of
sharp ideological discord that is associated with the U.S. Supreme
Court. Last year, for example, 93 percent of the New York high
court's decisions were unanimous.
</P>
<P>
   Titone resigned Sept. 1 at the age of 68 to take a position with
a private law firm. At the age of 62, Rosenblatt is nominated to a
14-year term with a mandatory retirement age of 70.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenblatt was selected from a list of seven candidates provided
to Pataki by an independent judicial screening committee. He had
been recommended once before to Cuomo.
</P>
<P>
   He is a registered Republican. With his appointment, the court
will consist of three Republicans, three Democrats and an
independent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
