<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINDY-DANGER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINDS KNOCK OUT POWER IN LOS ANGELES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY LISA VAN PROYEN   AND JESSE HIESTAND  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Powerful Santa Ana winds blew across Southern
California on Wednesday, toppling trees, littering streets and
knocking down power lines, leaving thousands in Los Angeles without
electricity.
</P>
<P>
   With humidity low and winds as high as 76 mph in the San Gabriel
Mountains, 69 mph in suburban Calabasas and 58 mph in Malibu,
firefighters were on critical-level alerts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Southern California is a tinder box and we're never really out
of danger,'' said Los Angeles Fire Department spokesman Brian
Humphrey. ``We are certainly ready to move in a moment's notice.''
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters in Glendale battled a wind-whipped blaze in the
steep Hillcrest Avenue area Wednesday afternoon, and downed power
lines were blamed for two small brush fires in La Canada Flintridge
earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Those fires burned about an acre of grass at 7:50 a.m. About 100
firefighters had them out by 8:13 a.m., said Inspector Henry
Rodriguez of the Los Angeles County Fire Department.
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service issued a high-wind warning for the
entire region through today.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Anas are caused by high pressure building up from the
Great Basin, including Idaho, Nevada and the western parts of Utah,
said Dennis Tussey, a meteorologist for the Weather Service in
Oxnard, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The high winds snapped trees like toothpicks, temporarily
blocking lanes of traffic in suburban Burbank and Woodland Hills,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In Sunland, a one-acre grass fire reported at 12:45 p.m. at
Mount Gleason and Big Tujunga Canyon roads &UR;  &LR; was out in 13 minutes,
said Los Angeles Fire Department spokesman Jim Wells. The cause was
under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   City and county fire departments Wednesday declared red-flag
alerts -- a warning issued when winds hit 25 mph or higher and
humidity levels dip below 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of November, city fire officials called an end to the
wildfire season because of rains.
</P>
<P>
   With the Santa Anas back, officials predeployed extra equipment
and firefighters to the more volatile areas in the San Fernando and
Santa Clarita areas.
</P>
<P>
   West Los Angeles Basin firefighters were sent to the Porter
Ranch, Sun Valley, Woodland Hills and Laurel Canyon areas, Humphrey
said. Teams from downtown were sent to Mission Hills, Sherman Oaks
and West Hills in the San Fernando Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The highly flammable chaparral along the Santa Monica Mountains
from Griffith Park to Point Mugu is a particular concern, Humphrey
said.
</P>
<P>
   County fire officials also sent strike teams and equipment &UR;  &LR; to
Santa Clarita and Malibu, where winds gusted to 57 mph Wednesday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   The Malibu-Topanga chapter of the volunteer Community Arson
Watch went on full alert Wednesday, putting 40 monitors in the
field to watch for downed lines, spot fires and suspicious activity
in the Santa Monica Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any little fire when you have 40 or 50 mph winds going just
runs ahead of the fire department and you can't stop it,'' said the
group's coordinator, Allen Emerson. ``So we want to be able to jump
on it as quickly as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, about 4,000 customers were without power at 3 p.m. in
Tujunga, Woodland Hills, Eagle Rock, Hollywood and Los Feliz after
high winds snapped tree limbs that hit power lines, said Walter
Zeisl, a spokesman for the Los Angeles Department of Water and
Power.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
