<HEADER>
A2269 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HIRSCHFELD-INDICTED-N     12-10 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIRSCHFELD-INDICTED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABE HIRSCHFELD INDICTED IN PLOT TO KILL BUSINESS PARTNER 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Abe Hirschfeld, the New York real estate developer,
millionaire and perennially aspiring politician, has been indicted
by a Manhattan grand jury in connection with a plot to kill his
longtime business partner, his lawyer said on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer, Theodore Kupferman, said that Hirschfeld planned to
turn himself in on Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment centers on allegations that Hirschfeld tried in
late 1996 to arrange the contract killing of Stanley Stahl, a real
estate magnate with whom he was involved in a bitter feud and a
``survivor take all'' agreement covering several properties they
held jointly.
</P>
<P>
   Hirschfeld, 79, and Stahl, 73, were partners in numerous
business ventures for decades, but have been engaged in acrimonious
civil litigation since 1993, when Hirschfeld sued Stahl, claiming
he had an ``unlawful bias against renting to blacks'' in three of
their buildings. Stahl denied the charges.
</P>
<P>
   Kupferman said he did not know the specific charge against
Hirschfeld.
</P>
<P>
   Hirschfeld did not return a call to his office on Wednesday, and
his home number is unlisted. But in interviews with several
television stations on Wednesday night, he denied the allegations.
``Everybody knows that I can't kill a fly,'' he told WWOR-TV news.
</P>
<P>
   Hirschfeld told WWOR that he had testified before a grand jury
for six hours two weeks ago, and that law enforcement officials
possessed a tape recording of a telephone conversation between him
and two men who were allegedly participants in the plot.
</P>
<P>
   Hirschfeld said that the two men were collaborating to kill
Stahl. ``I told them I'm not paying nothing, I have no interest in
killing him, and I hanged up,'' Hirschfeld said in the television
interview. ``They seriously thought they were doing it for my
benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he had not known that his telephone was being tapped,
nor did he call the police about the possible threat to Stahl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should I call the police?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate interview with WABC-TV, Hirschfeld implied that he
had been blackmailed: ``They had the guys call and said if you
won't give us half a million dollars to kill Stahl, we will notify
the police.''
</P>
<P>
   Stahl came to no harm. A law enforcement official said last year
that Hirschfeld had pulled out of the deal after an intermediary he
was using to arrange the killing _ and to whom he had paid a
substantial amount of money _ was roughed up by someone who may
have been a killer's contact. The intermediary had become a
cooperating witness, the official said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear who the two people are in the tape-recorded
conversation Hirschfeld referred to, but Kupferman said the content
had been misconstrued, and that Hirschfeld, who made much of his
fortune developing parking lots, was talking to the two men about
finishing work on a parking garage. When Hirschfeld made a comment
like ``You didn't do what you were supposed to do,'' Kupferman
said, it was being wrongly interpreted as meaning the men had not
murdered Stahl.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was talking to them about a garage, and some people
misinterpreted the conversation,'' Kupferman said. ``He was talking
about they didn't finish the garage.''
</P>
<P>
   Kupferman called Hirschfeld, who was born in Poland and
emigrated from Israel to the United States in his mid-30s, and
Stahl, the son of a Brooklyn butcher, ``one odd couple.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One doesn't try to kill the other; they just keep arguing,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hirschfeld, who is already facing charges that he avoided paying
state taxes for seven years, is a colorful figure in New York: he
has run quixotic and expensive campaigns for Congress, and
Manhattan borough president, among other offices, and had a brief
and stormy tenure as publisher of The New York Post. He recently
offered to pay Paula Jones $1 million to drop her lawsuit against
President Clinton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
