<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-SHARKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS RELIEVED WITH TIE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Ken Hitchcock admits he made a strategic mistake in his
handling of defenseman Darryl Sydor this season.
</P>
<P>
   When the Stars coach moved Sydor to left wing on two separate
occasions for extended periods, Sydor seemed to struggle when he
tried to move back to his regular spot on defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We screwed him up,'' Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   After last night's performance, however, Hitchcock said that
Sydor is back on defense to stay. The 26-year-old, who was an
All-Star participant last season, had a goal and two assists to
lead the Stars to a come-from-behind 3-3 tie with the San Jose
Sharks.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars move to 15-5-4 with the tie and fall one point behind
the Phoenix Coyotes in the Pacific Division. The Coyotes were 4-2
winners against the Montreal Canadiens.
</P>
<P>
   With the three points, Sydor is tied with Larry Murphy of the
Detroit Red Wings for the NHL lead in defenseman scoring at 21
points. Sydor's eight goals are second on the Stars to Jere
Lehtinen's nine, and his points trail only Mike Modano's 24 on the
Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a lot of confidence both offensively and
defensively,'' teammate Craig Ludwig said. ``He's skating well and
he knows he can take chances, because he has the speed to come back
and cover for it if the puck is going the other way.''
</P>
<P>
   Sydor simply calls it good solid defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just trying to play sound in my own end,'' he said. ``The
points will come.''
</P>
<P>
   Sydor's effort helped the Stars overcome a horrendous first
period and survive with a tie that was needed after a long road
trip. After arriving Tuesday at 4 a.m. from Calgary, the Stars
looked as if they had jet lag in the opening frame. They trailed
3-1 after the first period and were obviously outplayed by the
Sharks, who are 5-13-7.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock stepped in and delivered a heated sermon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we can say any of it on the air,'' winger Jamie
Langenbrunner confided to the media's microphones after the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars then responded with another spirited second period as
they scored twice on the power play en route to a 3-for-5 night
with the man advantage. The Stars have outscored opponents 31-9 in
the second period this season and lead the NHL in power play goals
with 30.
</P>
<P>
   Sydor slipped his goal-scoring shot through the legs of Sharks
goalie Mike Vernon after a great setup off a faceoff win by Joe
Nieuwendyk. Sydor was given a clear path to the net after
Nieuwendyk won maybe his biggest draw in a night when he went 20-1
in the faceoff circle.
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk also had a hand in the second power-play goal as he
and Tony Hrkac were setting screens in front of Vernon on a Sydor
shot. Hrkac ended up tipping the puck for his fourth goal of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Sydor's other assist came on a first-period power-play goal by
Lehtinen. That was about the only good thing to come out of the
first period as the offensively-struggling Sharks, who came into
the game with the league's fewest goals, scored three times.
Patrick Marleau started things with a 4-on-3 power play goal at the
3:57 mark. Owen Nolan was credited with a gift goal after Stars
defenseman Derian Hatcher tipped a pass past Stars goalie Ed
Belfour at the 12:18 mark. And Mike Ricci scored just 28 seconds
before the first period ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming off the road, we knew we were going to be in trouble,''
Hitchcock said of the first period. ``But I thought this was a good
point.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars matched the Sharks' energy for the remainder of the
game and both teams played a third period worthy of a playoff game.
It was the fifth time the two teams have met this season (the Stars
are 3-1-1 in those games) and there was plenty of familiarity
between the players. That led to some borderline hits on both
sides, some great scoring chances and tremendous goaltending by
veterans Belfour and Vernon before the game was called a draw after
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   And while critics might say there was nothing decided on the
scoreboard, Hitchcock said he has made a decision on Sydor.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I flipped him back and forth there _ as much as it helped
the team at that time, it probably hurt Syd,'' Hitchcock said. ``I
think he's back on now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
