<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2273 &Cx1f; tab-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAZDA-BORN-AGAIN-ASAH     12-10 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAZDA-BORN-AGAIN-ASAHI-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAZDA CHANGES GEARS, ROARS INTO THE FAST LANE  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Business Desks)   (This 1,025-word ``separate buy'' article is from the Asahi News
Service.)  
  
 (EDITORS: Get your news from Japan and the Pacific Rim straight
from the source _ the Asahi News Service. Its Monday through Friday
report of news, features and distinctive analysis is culled from
The Asahi Shimbun, Japan's foremost newspaper, renowned for its
integrity and thoroughness (with a daily circulation is 12
million.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from New York Times
Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``f''
financial news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``i'' international
news files.)  
  
 By PETER MCGILL  
 c.1998 Asahi News Service  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HIROSHIMA, Japan _ When Mazda Motor Corp. appointed its first
non-Japanese president in 1996 the reaction of some Japanese was as
if the ``Black Ships'' of Commodore Matthew Perry had docked at
Hiroshima and seized control of the castle.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor Co. had just increased its stake in Mazda to 33.4
percent from 24.5 percent, and making Henry Wallace, a Scotsman
seconded to Mazda from Ford, seemed to Japanese nationalists the
beginning of the end for a proud company founded in Hiroshima in
1920.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, with a second non-Japanese from Ford as new
president, the remarkable turnaround of Japan's fifth-largest auto
maker has banished such dark thoughts in a dazzle of its
headlights.
</P>
<P>
   Giant Nissan Motor Co. posted a parent net loss of 32.5 billion
yen ($217 million) for the six months ending Sept. 30, down 71
billion yen from the same period in 1997, has sold its head office
in Tokyo's swank Ginza district, and sought public funds from the
Japan Development Bank to winch it out of the mud.
</P>
<P>
   Mazda has swung into the fast lane. Net income of the parent
company for the first half was 5.5 billion yen, up 4.9 billion yen;
and on a consolidated basis for the whole Mazda group, 8.5 billion
yen, an increase of 18.2 billion yen. This was achieved in the
teeth of economic recession in most of Asia.
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, where auto sales are at their lowest level since 1985,
Mazda slightly increased its market share to 5.8 percent. It also
sold more vehicles in the United States and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Equally important to Gary Hexter, a Ford executive with Mazda
since 1994 and now a senior managing director and its chief
financial officer, is that Mazda can comfortably finance its debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we sat here in 1994, we saw a parent company debt level
of a little over 580 billion yen, and in a relatively short period
of time, in 1998 and 1999, we saw almost 200 billion yen of bonds
maturing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a scenario unfolded where we couldn't fix the business as
quickly as we hoped, if we couldn't generate cash to the level
required, if there were a change in the liquidity situation in
Japan, we would be in serious, serious trouble as a corporation,''
recalls Hexter.
</P>
<P>
   ``So almost the first thing we did was to focus on cash-flow
management and debt reduction. This was an emphasis that
historically did not exist at Mazda, and at many other Japanese and
Asian companies as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Borrowing rates were low; credit was readily available; and so
people tended to have the ability to very rapidly borrow their way
into trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   While Wallace and new Mazda President James Miller, who is also
from Ford, have occupied the limelight, insiders give most credit
for rebuilding Mazda's finances to 54-year-old Hexter, an
Australian apostle of Ford's ``bottom line'' culture.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to joining Mazda, Hexter was based at Ford headquarters in
Detroit, and from 1991 to 1993 was instrumental in halting the cash
hemorrhage at Jaguar, the famous British luxury car maker purchased
by Ford in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Hexter cautions against comparing Jaguar, ``a relatively small
operation'' which bottomed at 22,000 units a year in 1991, ``with a
company as large and complex as Mazda.'' He acknowledges, however,
that they both had ``excellent engineering'' and ``severe financial
difficulties.''
</P>
<P>
   Mazda also possesses the ability, ``consistent with many
Japanese companies,'' of bringing a new model from concept to
production in less time, and with ``substantially less'' financial
investment than Hexter had ``previously experienced,'' together
with a ``tremendously loyal, capable work force, supported by an
excellent union.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford was unimpressed, however, by the freedom allowed Mazda's
engineers to indulge their dreams, rather than responding to what
most customers wanted to buy.
</P>
<P>
   Mazda's long and costly love-affair with the ``revolutionary''
rotary engine in the 1970s and 1980s yielded a trove of patents,
but is now solely used in the RX-7 that sells only in small volume
in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Mazda's nifty Roadster (sold as the MX-5 in Europe, and Miata in
the United States), was eulogized recently by the editor of Car
magazine as ``the world's most commendable open-top sports car,''
but as Hexter points out, ``you can't build a company on a niche
product.''
</P>
<P>
   The more conventional and less exciting 626/Capella ``global
car'' and the compact Demio, both introduced in 1996-97, are part
of a new strategy to ensure that Mazda has a ``good and strong
presence in the key segments of the market,'' says Hexter.
</P>
<P>
   He traces Mazda's near-nemesis in the 1990s to an ill-conceived
``Five Sales Channel Strategy'' it launched at the start of the
asset-inflated boom of the 1980s to expand its volume worldwide,
especially in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The company expanded the number of its models to match the
multiplication of new sales channels for different types of car,
and built a new Mazda factory in Hofu, Yamaguchi Prefecture, and in
a joint venture with Ford, a plant in Flat Rock, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of that led to a substantial amount of capital investment,
and added significantly to Mazda's fixed costs. Mazda had seven
consecutive years of negative cash flow, and debt almost tripled,''
says Hexter.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the investment went in, all the cost was added, and with
the bursting of the bubble economy in Japan, and rapid decline in
(sales) volumes, Mazda never achieved the sales to justify the
original investment.
</P>
<P>
   That was compounded by a number of products that were less than
successful, which further exacerbated the problem of declining
industry sales. The net result was that in the year ended March 31,
1994, Mazda lost about 44 billion yen as a parent company.''
</P>
<P>
   Mazda had also had structural weaknesses peculiar to large,
non-holding Japanese corporations: numerous affiliates and
subsidiaries with ``poor financial results and fairly high levels
of debt,'' and a large portfolio of shares held in other
companies. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
