<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 01:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2287 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     12-10 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAGLIABUE SHOULD CALL SCHRAMM FOR HELP, TOO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One question for Mr. Commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Why stop with Jerry Jones when you also could and should bring
back Tex Schramm?
</P>
<P>
   Funny, huh, how this stuff works? The NFL has itself a public
credibility crisis brewing because of an outbreak of officiating
goofs during games.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Paul Tagliabue seeks help by reaching for the phone
and dialing the 972 area code, meaning Irving. Tag-Man now wants
Jones next to him in the foxhole. Just a few short years ago, these
two were slapping each other around with lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, with America's sports' media also seeking answers to
current NFL problems, the phone is ringing constantly at a home in
the 214 area code, meaning Dallas. Schramm lives there.
</P>
<P>
   There are people in the NFL of today who don't like Jones _ in
fact, that line would stretch all the way to Texarkana.
</P>
<P>
   There were people in the NFL of yesteryear who didn't like
Schramm. Way too much power, they thought, with then commissioner
Pete Rozelle.
</P>
<P>
   And while Jones and Schramm reside near each other, dinner dates
have never been exchanged in the 10 years since their hello-goodbye
at Valley Ranch.
</P>
<P>
   Once Schramm was gone from the Cowboys and the NFL, an
executive-level leadership void developed that has never been
filled.
</P>
<P>
   What Schramm brought to the league was a strong personality, a
fertile and imaginative football mind, combined with a fierce and
protective love of the NFL. Texas E. Schramm never played the game
beyond his high school days in San Gabriel, Calif. But he was and
still is a ``football guy'' to the core, with modern on-the-field
ideas respected and accepted by the likes of Lombardi, Halas,
Shula, Paul Brown, etc.
</P>
<P>
   The closest thing to Schramm among the NFL hierarchy of today?
Don't look now, but it's probably Jerry Jones. No, he's not in
Schramm's esteemed league, but he's the pick of a runt litter, so
to speak.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Tagliabue turned to Jones this week, asking him, in
an unprecedented move, to be a December addition to be the NFL's
powerful Competition Committee. Tagliabue desperately needs
leadership as he plunges ahead with the sudden idea of adding an
instant-replay mechanism to supplement officiating during the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Jones is a former Competition Committee member. This group, more
than the commissioner's office, is the actual governing body of the
NFL.
</P>
<P>
   It says plenty about the current seven-member CC that Tagliabue
is calling in Jones. The commissioner needs a go-getter and doesn't
believe he has one in place.
</P>
<P>
   What does it also say when Schramm's phone won't stop ringing?
The media want to hear an expert opinion on instant replay and the
other ills of the NFL. Schramm's views are still respected, I'd say
far more than anyone in the current NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever the reason, I like to hear the phone,'' said Schramm
yesterday. ``I don't like sitting around on my butt, doing
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   At 78, Schramm remains sharp and in tune with the NFL. Elected
to the Hall of Fame in Canton, Ohio, because of his contributions
to the league, Schramm would be a perfect wild-card member to
today's Competition Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The thing about Schramm is he always has more questions than
answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``My philosophy,'' he said, ``is to think of ideas, and then go
seek answers from a multitude of experts on how to best get it
done.''
</P>
<P>
   Schramm was the original chairman of the Competition Committee
and held the office for 25 years. His first committee members were
the threesome of Vince Lombardi, Paul Brown and Al Davis. Oh, to be
a fly on the wall in those meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Schramm is the daddy of instant replay, and is extremely irked
it didn't work right the first time. He strongly blames the
implementation, not the concept.
</P>
<P>
   The sideline radios in quarterback helmets? It was once
controversial, but now no one notices. That was Schramm's idea. So
were quicker games, where a 45-second play clock (now 40) started
immediately after the whistle blew on the previous play.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years, I also pushed for the elimination of the huddle,''
Schramm said. ``The huddle is useless and time-consuming. You could
run 20 additional plays a game. Maybe more.''
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Wilson, the owner of the Bills, went on a tirade against
Tagliabue and NFL officiating last week. Wilson charged there was
no longer an emphasis on football in the NFL, but on the bottom
line instead.
</P>
<P>
   Schramm said it best: ``This is now a league built around
marketing. It used to be a league built around the product on the
field. Marketing ain't worth a damn if you don't have the right
product.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Tagliabue, you need to be hearing that. And often.
</P>
<P>
   (Randy Galloway is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
