</P>
<P>
   NY-FINANCIAL-DISTRICT (New York) _ At 8:30 on a Saturday night,
the holiday shooting stars suspended above Nassau Street are aglow,
illuminating blocks of rolled-down aluminum security shutters.
There are no coffee shops still open, no magazine shops, no bars _
and even more strikingly _ there are no people. ``When I moved in
last February, there was supposed to be a grocery store coming,''
said Tracey White, looking back pointedly at the still-black
windows on the ground floor of her building, one of the new rental
conversions in the financial district. ``It's really dead.'' By
Tracie Rozhon.
</P>
<P>
   BLECKNER-BENEFIT (New York) _ ``I never invite people over _
it's so anxiety-producing,'' Ross Bleckner said, contemplating the
imminent arrival of 120 guests, many of them uptown swells who had
paid $1,000 for the privilege of climbing six flights of stairs for
cocktails and dinner with the celebrated artist. An avowed recluse
who resists forays north of Union Square, Bleckner was the host of
a benefit last week for Community Research Initiative on AIDS in
the minimalist Xanadu that is his home, a former loft building that
he owns in TriBeCa. By Christopher Mason.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   TENEMENT-MUSEUM (New York) _ For the descendants of Abraham and
Fannie Rogarshevsky, history came between the dill pickles and the
corned beef sandwiches. Family memories, some of them coaxed over
lunch, have been vital in recreating the Rogarshevskys' vibrant,
three-room Orchard Street apartment, circa 1918, a permanent
exhibit at the Lower East Side Tenement Museum. It is the fifth
apartment the museum has restored in its 1863 red-brick landmark
tenement. By Patricia Lee Brown.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   PALM-PILOT (Undated) _ What the Furby electronic pet is to the
single-digit set, the leather Palm Pilot case is to the adult
digital one: the hottest gift item of the season. Encasing the Palm
Pilot in lizard or saddle leather is part of the fervid culture
that has grown up around this digital record keeper, calendar,
address book and organizer. By Phil Patton.
</P>
<P>
   NY-WINTER-GARDEN (New York) _ After a visitor the clatter of
miniature electric trains and the Christmas tree with twinkle
lights that tickles the glass roof of the Enid Haupt Conservatory
came the moment of truth. ``It smells like winter out here,'' said
Ashali Bhandari, 7, of Manhattan. It should have: she was looking
at the winter solstice garden at the New York Botanical Garden in
the Bronx. By Mac Griswold.
</P>
