<HEADLINE>
DIFFERENCE FROM TOP TO BOTTOM SHRINKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   And here we thought the NCAA Tournament was unpredictable. The
double U factor _ Upset Uncertainty _ has seeped out of March and
into the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Northern Arizona wins at Arizona State, Florida Atlantic wins at
Oklahoma State, Murray State wins at Oklahoma, Stephen F. Austin
wins at Texas Tech (note to Big 12 Conference: You don't have to
work so hard contributing to this trend).
</P>
<P>
   College basketball's Little Guys have grown up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's wonderful for all schools of our size to do what Florida
Atlantic did,'' Valparaiso coach Homer Drew said about the Owls'
victory at Oklahoma State. ``It gives everyone an opportunity. It
brings the excitement back to the players.''
</P>
<P>
   Drew's Valparaiso team might have started the trend last March
with their inspirational trip to the Sweet 16. And while Drew's son
Bryce is no longer the team's star, Valpo is 8-1 this season going
into tomorrow night's game at Purdue.
</P>
<P>
   Why is this happening? The scholarship limitations continue to
spread the talent. More schools have more players.
</P>
<P>
   And, the teams being upset are not college basketball's royalty.
Kentucky has victories against Eastern Kentucky and Mercer;
Connecticut has defeated Quinnipiac and Hartford; Duke has beaten
Fairfield and South Carolina State.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between No. 25 and No. 310 in Division I is
shrinking.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask College of Charleston. Two years ago, the Cougars were
an NCAA Tournament darkhorse. The school from South Carolina's Old
South city upset Maryland in the first round before losing to
eventual champion Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Charleston returned five starters and moved up in
class to the Southern Conference. On Dec. 1, the Cougars beat
Massachusetts, a preseason Top 25 team. Last Saturday, they upset
No. 3 North Carolina in Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely. We know what this means,'' said Danny Johnson, a
senior guard who made the winning shot to beat the Tar Heels. ``I'm
from North Carolina, so I know all about the school's tradition,
with all the national championships and everything. For a team like
College of Charleston to come in and upset them is great.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The time to shine and produce was certainly a stage we needed
on this occasion,'' Charleston coach John Kresse said. ``Programs
are made and schools are made because of victories of this
nature.''  &LR; tagtop:Wendell Barnhouse, (817) 390-7238
 &LR; tagbottom:wbhoops\Nstar-telegram.com
IN THE LANE
HOGS ROOT FOR TITLE RINGS The football team has had a marvelous,
surprising season that will end in a New Year's Day bowl. Now,
Arkansas' basketball team is hoping that it can reach back and
revive some of the glory of days past.
</P>
<P>
   The Razorbacks (6-2) have a solid team that is led by three
seniors _ guards Pat Bradley and Kareem Reid and forward Derek
Hood. None of those players was involved with the Arkansas teams
that won the national championship in 1994 and finished second in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, since then, the Razorbacks have yet to win a
championship. Not a Southeastern Conference West Division title nor
an SEC tournament title. Every player recruited by coach Nolan
Richardson who has stayed for four seasons at Arkansas has won at
least one championship.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, who turns 57 this month, says he doesn't figure
he'll coach beyond 60. But while he keeps hinting at retirement, he
doesn't want to quit just yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to win another national championship before I retire,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   For Arkansas' three seniors, earning a championship ring _ what
kind doesn't matter _ is what this season is all about.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Arkansas, teams are measured by the championships they've
won,'' said Bradley, the team's 3-point shooting threat. ``We want
to win a championship before we leave here. We don't want to be
known as the senior class that didn't win one.''
</P>
<P>
   The past three seasons, Bradley, Reid and Hood have played for
Arkansas teams that have won 62 games, played in two NCAA
Tournaments and made it to the NIT Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   Arkansas figures to be the top team in the SEC West, which has
been dominated by Mississippi the past two seasons. Last season,
the Razorbacks fell apart down the stretch and watched the Rebels
erase a three-game deficit to win the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been here three years, and we haven't tried on a ring
yet,'' Reid said. ``Last year, we had the ring in our hands and we
lost it. We're going to get the ring this year. If we don't, I'm
going to feel like we cheated the school and cheated ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   FREE THROWS
QUOTABLE
Utah coach Rick Majerus on his depleted team, which lost three
players _ including probable starter Britton Johnsen _ to two-year
church missions:
</P>
<P>
   ``If prayer counts, we should be winning games. But I don't know
if they're praying for us or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State guard Eddie House, who suffered a broken jaw Oct.
22 and spent about six weeks living on high-protein shakes, ice
cream and Cream of Wheat, on his first meal of a salad and two
cheeseburgers:
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to eat the salad first because my teeth and gums were
tender. Then I went straight for the burgers. Everything tastes
pretty good right now. I don't leave nothing on the plate
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   During its trip to Puerto Rico, UCLA wore black uniforms. Coach
Steve Lavin said the new unis were the players' idea and that they
could boost recruiting. Here's former UCLA coaching legend John
Wooden's opinion:
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't really matter what I think, does it? I would have
stuck with the school colors. I don't think the inmates should run
be running the asylum.''
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota coach Clem Haskins on 7-1 freshman center Joel
Przybilla, who is blocking five shots a game but whom Haskins
believes is not getting the breaks on officiating calls:
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want officials to know that we have the premier shot
blocker in America. I don't want the officials to call any cheap
fouls on him just because he's 7-1 or because he's a freshman. Let
him play. . . . They need to let him block shots because Joel can
block shots. I want the officials to recognize that.''
BRIEFLY
Stanford reserve forward/guard Ryan Mendez, perhaps the Cardinal's
best outside shooter, could be out the rest of the month. Mendez,
from Burleson, is sidelined with a stress reaction in his right
knee, the same knee he had off-season surgery on to try to cure
tendinitis.
</P>
<P>
   In the past four seasons, Kansas is 43-6 in November and
December and 8-4 in NCAA Tournament games.
</P>
<P>
   Houston plays at North Carolina State on Saturday. It's only the
second meeting between the teams since the Wolfpack upset the
Cougars in the 1983 national championship game. That was the last
collegiate game for current Houston coach Clyde Drexler.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes time to fill out your NCAA Tournament bracket for
the office poll, don't pencil in North Carolina or Syracuse for the
Final Four. Both are pretourney jinxed. The Tar Heels won the
Pre-Season NIT, the Orangemen the Maui Classic. Since 1989-90, none
of the 18 teams that has won either even made it to the Final Four
that season.
</P>
</TEXT>
