<HEADLINE>
BLUE JAYS RECEIVE SATISFACTORY OFFER _ BUT NOT FROM RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The Toronto Blue Jays, attempting to trade
right-hander Roger Clemens, received a proposal for the five-time
Cy Young Award recipient yesterday that ``satisfies our needs,''
general manager Gord Ash said.
</P>
<P>
   That trade proposal did not originate from Rangers general
manager Doug Melvin.
</P>
<P>
   Ash yesterday spoke only to Melvin and New York Yankees general
manager Brian Cashman regarding Clemens, but the Blue Jays' general
manager later acknowledged the satisfactory proposal did not
originate from either of those organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston Astros, New York Mets, Cleveland Indians and Anaheim
Angels remain in pursuit of Clemens, and the Colorado Rockies, Los
Angeles Dodgers, St. Louis Cardinals and San Diego Padres also
could be involved.
</P>
<P>
   Ash plans to forward the proposal today to Clemens'
representatives, Alan and Randy Hendricks. Clemens, who resides in
the Houston area, informed the Blue Jays on Dec. 2 of his desire to
be traded to an organization closer to his home or a playoff
contender.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess what I'm directing that club to do is make sure they
qualify,'' Ash said of Clemens' preference in locale. ``They had a
lot of questions for me that I couldn't answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, though, can veto any trade, empowering the 36-year-old
pitcher. Clemens, who will earn $8 and $8.1 million the next two
seasons, can force potential suitors to renegotiate his existing
contract _ in length and/or value _ before granting consent to any
trade made by Ash.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I've suggested to that club,'' Ash said, ``is that they
get guidance from Roger's representatives on how they should
proceed from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin returned from Toronto yesterday after meeting with Ash
for 90 minutes Tuesday afternoon and another hour yesterday morning
over breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a better sense of what they're looking for and had more
\Rdialogue\S than had I been doing it over the phone,'' Melvin
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays seek three or four major-league players for
Clemens. This past weekend, Melvin called it ``very unlikely''
catcher Ivan Rodriguez or left fielder Rusty Greer would be
involved in the Rangers' proposal, and the Blue Jays' insistence on
receiving major-league talent likely rules out minor-league center
fielder Ruben Mateo.
</P>
<P>
   Right fielder Juan Gonzalez's contract contains a limited
no-trade clause that prevents him from being traded to the Blue
Jays, and first baseman Rafael Palmeiro's contract also includes a
no-trade clause. Shortstop Royce Clayton cannot be traded after
being signed this month as a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Melvin few alternatives for trade proposals if the
Blue Jays seek young, major-league talent at a reasonable price.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers do not want to part with right-hander Rick Helling,
and right-hander Aaron Sele's ability to become a free agent after
the 1999 season does not fit the Blue Jays' interests.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves right-hander Esteban Loaiza as a likely candidate to
be involved in the Rangers' proposal for Clemens. The Blue Jays
also seek power to replace designated hitter Jose Canseco, who
signed yesterday with the Tampa Bay Devil Rays.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers designated hitter Lee Stevens, who earned only $1.2
million in base salary this past season, cannot become a free agent
until after the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, though, would be required to offer more.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a concern there when you're talking about giving up
that many players,'' Melvin said without reference to specific
players. ``You may be better on the days \RClemens\S pitches, but
you may not be better on the other 128 days when he's not.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin appeared unsure whether the Rangers have a realistic
opportunity of acquiring Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't really tell,'' he said. ``The problem is things can
change so fast, but our location keeps us in it. Our being a
contender keeps us in it.''
LEFTY TO TRIPLE A
The Rangers signed left-hander Rich Robertson yesterday and
assigned the 30-year-old pitcher to Triple-A Oklahoma of the
Pacific Coast League.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson made five appearances in relief for the Anaheim Angels
this past season and accumulated a 15.88 earned-run average during
those 5 2/3 innings. Robertson spent the remainder of the season
with Triple-A Vancouver of the PCL and went 11-12 with a 3.81 ERA
during 27 starts.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson will compete for a berth in the Rangers' bullpen this
spring and earn $300,000 if he spends the entire season on the
25-man roster.
</P>
</TEXT>
