<HEADLINE>
ODDS SLIM ON ROCKET LANDING IN ARLINGTON 
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It would have been the best Opening Day at The Ballpark in
Arlington since Van Cliburn played his grand piano at the inaugural
game back in 1994. It would have been the second coming of Nolan
Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   It would have been extraordinary.
</P>
<P>
   It might have even resulted in the first World Series in
Rangers' history.
</P>
<P>
   But we have to face facts.
</P>
<P>
   The Ballpark will not be The Rocket's next launching pad.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Clemens will not be the Rangers' Opening Day starter next
April 5.
</P>
<P>
   This is not an official announcement, just a gut feeling based
on intuition, a little educated guesswork and reading between the
lines as the Clemens' affair has unfolded over the past week.
</P>
<P>
   These calculations have been computed by an experienced and
seasoned authority in hit-and-miss predictions. Do not attempt this
at home alone in a closed room or while imbibing anything stronger
than skim milk.
</P>
<P>
   This deduction has come despite Rangers general manager Doug
Melvin's impressive sneak attack on Toronto on Tuesday afternoon,
when he flew to Canada to meet with Blue Jays general manager Gord
Ash and personally deliver the Rangers' offer.
</P>
<P>
   You might have heard Ash's gales of laughter while hanging your
Christmas lights on the roof.
</P>
<P>
   All kidding aside, there is no truth to the rumor that the
centerpiece of the Rangers' proposal was visiting clubhouse man Joe
Macko and a replacement knee surgery to be named later.
</P>
<P>
   Like Juan Gonzalez, Pudge Rodriguez and Rusty Greer, Macko,
Rangers sources insist, has been deemed untouchable.
</P>
<P>
   Therein lies the problem. The Rangers had apparently hoped to
steal Clemens for the proverbial handful of beans. And they weren't
even throwing in the Beano.
</P>
<P>
   Here's who won't be traded:
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez: He has a limited no-trade clause that eliminates
Toronto as a possible future destination.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez: His agent, Jeff Moorad, left this polite, but pointed
little message on Ash's answering machine warning him that Pudge,
as is his right, will immediately demand a trade if he's sent to
the Blue Jays. Besides, he makes too much money for the Jays'
scaled-down budget.
</P>
<P>
   Greer: He fits every known Jays' criteria _ major-league tested,
relatively low salary, young and without enough service time to
force a trade, plus he's an offensive force _ but the Rangers adore
him for all the same reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Throw in fresh signees Rafael Palmeiro and Royce Clayton, who
have new multiyear deals, and center fielder Tom Goodwin, too.
They're not going anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   The Jays don't want second baseman Mark McLemore or third
baseman Todd Zeile because both can be free agents after next
season.
</P>
<P>
   So, who does that leave for the Rangers to offer for Clemens?
</P>
<P>
   Minor-league outfield prospect Ruben Mateo? Not likely. He's a
year away and the Jays want help right now. Same with other
prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``They won more games than anyone else in the American League in
the second half of the season,'' Melvin said. ``They believe they
can contend and they want players who can play at the major-league
level right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Deduction then leads us to left-handed hitting first baseman Lee
Stevens, right-handed hitting outfielder Mike Simms _ the Jays need
power _ and right-handed pitcher Esteban Loaiza, who has been
attracting interest from a number of teams.
</P>
<P>
   A pair of platoon DHs and a pitcher the Rangers hope can hold
down the No. 5 spot in the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   You can imagine how bowled over Ash must have been, to have
Melvin fly 2,000 miles to lay that out for him.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Rangers officials remain quietly confident they're in the
thick of the Clemens race, and why not? They've apparently survived
the first cut, from 16 interested teams to six.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, Melvin and Ash have a long-standing relationship. Of
course, it could be that Gord appreciates Doug's sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever, there must be more to this deal than this veteran
prognosticator can decipher, because without Rodriguez, without
Greer, without Mateo, I don't see how the Rangers have a prayer of
putting a better offer on the table than the Yankees, the Astros or
the Indians, among others.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, reports last night indicated Ash had forwarded an
offer to Clemens' agent. It was not the one made by the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   If Melvin is somehow slick enough, persuasive enough, to bring
Clemens to Arlington without doing major damage to his team, forget
Siegfried and Roy. The Rangers' GM will be the greatest magician in
the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think \Rthe Clemens trade show\S is going to Nashville,''
Melvin said, referring to the resumption, after a long hiatus, of
baseball's winter meetings tomorrow in the country music capital of
the world.
</P>
<P>
   We wait then with bated breath.
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead, make our Opening Day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
