<HEADLINE>
USC ARRIVES LATE IN VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC trailing Loyola Marymount at halftime was
surprising enough. Then again, few probably realized the Trojans
hadn't trailed anyone this season after 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it was sloppy shooting or good defense, the Trojans shot
just 29 percent and were down by a point to the Lions, a fairly
embarrassing result for a USC team just starting to draw some
national attention.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason for the slow start, it did wonders for the
Trojans' intensity. They played their best half of the season and
outscored Loyola Marymount by 37 points for an eventually easy
79-43 victory over the Lions before 3,050 at the Sports Arena on
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans (6-0) blistered the Lions in the second half,
outscoring them 50-13. Before USC coach Henry Bibby really cleared
his bench, USC had outscored Loyola Marymount, 43-5.
</P>
<P>
   So after three close victories over less-than-imposing
opponents, the Trojans finally enjoyed a blowout, even if it wasn't
that way in the opening half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came in in the locker room and we shot real bad in the
first half,'' USC forward Brian Scalabrine said. ``I knew we
wouldn't do that another half.''
</P>
<P>
   They didn't. USC shot 59 percent in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a matter of we didn't make our shots early,''
Scalabrine said. ``We've just got to make our shots.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans are off to their best start since going 8-0 in the
1974-75 season, heading to their big game Saturday night at Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   The impetus for USC's second-half blitz was guard Jeff
Trepagnier. The sophomore had a game-high 18 points, but more
impressively had a USC-record eight steals along with 11 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   He broke the record of seven steals set by Cameron Murray in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew from watching the tapes that if they got trapped, they
would throw the ball anywhere,'' Trepagnier said. ``I just stepped
into the lanes.''
</P>
<P>
   Trepagnier also blocked three shots, and has entrenched himself
as a starter, despite Bibby's penchant for changing the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not anything we haven't seen,'' Bibby said. ``Jeff is
playing consistent basketball. That's why he's in the starting
lineup. He's been great for us. We just need everybody else to play
at that level.''
</P>
<P>
   Loyola Marymount (3-4) was held to a season low in points, and
converted just five of 35 attempts in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their defense wasn't any different in the second half,'' Lions
coach Charles Bradley said. ``We're the ones who threw it away.''
</P>
<P>
   USC had the same feeling about the first half. The Trojans
missed an extraordinary number of layups and easy shots, and for
the third straight home game, were in a neck-and-neck struggle with
a lesser team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not trying to develop that pattern at all,'' Bibby said.
``We addressed that after the game. We can't wait until the second
half to set the tempo.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes: USC forward Jarvis Turner needed stitches after the game,
after cutting his lip while intentionally fouling Loyola Marymount
guard Robert Davis. Also needing stitches was Trojans assistant
coach Dave Miller, who injured his lip when a ball hit him during
practice. Miller had a whistle in his mouth at the time, which
caused the injury.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; !end! &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
