<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TEXAS-A&AMP;M-COOK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS A&AMP;M COOKING WITH `FATS'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M point guard Clifton Cook II has a ready answer to the
casual inquiry about how he acquired the nickname, ``Fats.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just tell people it's because my game is fat,'' Cook said
with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the Howard College transfer has had a corpulent
impact on the Aggies, who improved to 7-1 by beating Tulane, 69-63,
last night at Reed Arena with Cook leading the way with 18 points.
A&AMP;M already has won as many games as it did all of last season and
is off to its best start since 1980-81. Going into last night's
game, Cook was averaging 14.7 points, 6.6 assists, 2.7 steals and
5.6 rebounds a game, in addition to shooting a respectable 39
percent from 3-point range. He has been honored as the Big 12's
rookie of the week.
</P>
<P>
   But none of that has anything to do with the real origin of the
``Fats'' monicker, so says the man who bestowed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was so overweight when he was a baby that he could barely
walk; he just kind of wobbled,'' recalled the senior Clifton Cook,
a real estate investor in the family's hometown of Dayton, Ohio.
``So, one day I called him a `big old fatso.' Everybody laughed and
the nickname stuck. His friends later shortened it to Fats. There
was a jingle we used to sing . . .''
</P>
<P>
   That, however, is enough about that, the younger Cook says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, he begged me not to tell anybody about the jingle,'' Dad
said. ``Maybe after a while, he won't care.''
</P>
<P>
   So it is that the jingle for the time being remains locked in
the family vault of secrets. But Aggies coach Melvin Watkins has
another designation for his 6-foot-1 point-guard discovery:
indispensable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to imagine where we'd be without him,'' Watkins said.
``I hate to imagine taking him out of a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Cook is a key ingredient in Watkins' rebuilding of a team that
lost its only semblance of a true point guard when Brian Barone
elected to transfer after Watkins replaced his father, Tony, as
A&AMP;M's coach in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clifton is a real point guard, and every team needs one,''
said Watkins, who played the position on a Final Four team as a
senior at North Carolina Charlotte. ``We're very fortunate to have
him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies were certainly lucky that Cook was available in April
after Watkins took the job. Kansas, Kansas State and TCU had shown
intense interest in Howard County's all-region player, who averaged
17 points, eight assists and four steals. Cook, however, remained
unsigned because he had not passed the TAAS test required of Texas
junior-college players in order for them to be eligible to play
Division I basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Watkins was unaware of Cook. But one of his first moves was to
hire then-TCU assistant Steve McClain. And though McClain stayed on
Watkins' staff for only a month before taking the head coaching job
at Wyoming, he left a valuable legacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew we definitely needed a point guard,'' Watkins said. ``I
immediately asked Steve who was still available, and Clifton was
the first name he brought up.''
</P>
<P>
   Watkins set out for Big Spring and watched Cook play in a
pick-up game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though it was only pick-up basketball, I saw two
things,'' Watkins said. ``Here was a kid who was advancing the
basketball and defending the basketball. I didn't know if he could
shoot or score. But I knew I wanted him because of those two
things. We were very fortunate to get a point guard of his caliber
so late. And the charisma he brings to this team just adds to his
value.''
</P>
<P>
   As is his reputation, Watkins' eye for talent proved true. And
Cook says he has found a kindred soul in his new coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really fun playing for a coach who was a point guard,''
Cook said. ``We speak the same language. Sometimes I'm thinking
what he's thinking and sometimes he's thinking what I'm thinking.
We give each other ideas and we see things as one. He knows how to
get open, how plays should go and if you get into trouble, how to
break it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gets onto me about my turnovers and says when he used to
play he never had turnovers like that. I can relate, but I told him
sometime maybe I'd better look at some of his old tapes and see if
he's right.''
</P>
<P>
   Watkins dubbed Cook a natural at the position, where conversions
seldom compare to those born with the knack _ like quarterbacks and
shortstops. Like many youngsters, Cook has been in love with the
game since he used to tag along with his older brother to the
neighborhood recreation center, where young Fatso amazed his
brother's friends and his dad by being able to loft the ball to the
rim as a 4-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I saw that, I put a goal up on the garage,'' Clifton's
dad said. ``Then I started having to leave my car out front when I
got home from work. I couldn't get into the garage because the
driveway was full of kids.''
</P>
<P>
   If anything, Fats became too enamored with the game. His grades
suffered such that he couldn't qualify to attend a Division I
university. So, Dayton's player of the year went the JC route,
though that in itself was an education.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little off track,'' Cook admits. ``But something
dinged me and I said, `What am I doing? I'm throwing all this
away.' I decided I didn't want to be one of those `has-beens' who
sits around and talks about how he could have been this or that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
