<HEADLINE>
GUSTY WINDS CUT SWATH THROUGH L.A. PSYCHES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Editors: Retransmitting to fix error in headline) 
BY PHILLIP W. BROWNE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- As hot, dry Santa Ana winds whipped through Los
Angeles on Wednesday, they stirred up more than fire danger and
dust devils: Anxiety reigned, headaches flared and sinuses clogged.
</P>
<P>
   Some people became unglued.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to this emotional mayhem was the constant, unpredictable
threat of physical danger: A 30-acre fire burned in hills above
Glendale, a suburban community north of Los Angeles, briefly
threatening homes on the 10th anniversary of a blaze that destroyed
15 houses in the San Fernando Valley's Porter Ranch. The winds
toppled trucks, ripped signs, downed power lines and fanned small
fires across Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   And the ``devil winds'' are expected to remain through the
afternoon today.
</P>
<P>
   ``On days like this the anxiety curve accelerates, people's
minds are racing, their senses are on red alert and they burn up
adrenaline,'' said Glendale clinical psychologist Kim Shirin, who
added that our social values teach us to keep control of our world
and focus on completing daily tasks.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the winds come, we realize we don't have control of our
world, so people need to spend . . . time relaxing and being
grounded, and they need to do it periodically through the day,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Some people believe that the Santa Ana winds possess the same
curious power as a full moon, to which some law enforcement
officials attribute increases in strange crimes during that point
in the lunar cycle.
</P>
<P>
   So how do we do it in the frenzy called Los Angeles? How about a
therapeutic massage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a huge influx of walk-in customers and phone
calls,'' said Maria Montoya-Kaye, an employee at Massage Masters in
suburban Sherman Oaks. ``People are complaining of headaches and
back spasms and sinus problems. We've got 70 customers booked today
when the average is about 45 -- it's like the full moon effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Troy Minnehan, 24, of nearby Encino found temporary peace in a
mocha java and a menthol cigarette. He took the day off from his
auto-repair job to avoid the frustrations of working in the wind.
</P>
<P>
   ``. . . It would just be too tough to work,'' Minnehan said,
standing in an alcove outside a Starbucks coffee shop in Encino.
``It's a better day for a jacket and a good cup of coffee.''
</P>
<P>
   Hard-boiled crime novelist Raymond Chandler wrote of these devil
winds as enough to make your nerves jump. ``On nights like that,
every booze party ends in a fight. Meek little wives feel the edge
of the carving knife and study their husbands' necks,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   While reality might not always be that extreme, experts agree
the key to keeping sane on these wild, windy days is to learn how
to relax; like director David Lynch wrote into the ``Twin Peaks''
television series: ``Every day, once a day, give yourself a
present.''
</P>
<P>
   University of Southern California professor Henry Gong Jr. said
people who work outside or have allergies probably should stay
indoors when the Santa Anas come. On such days, Los Angeles
residents are exposed to desert allergens and particles that they
don't normally experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Studies indicate that on the Westside, small particles get
inhaled and can cause inflammation of asthma, hay fever and
pneumonia,'' Gong said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a result, people's moods can alter and in severe cases they
could go to the emergency room. It's good to stay inside if
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The same also might be said about braving the weather to get a
haircut and styling.
</P>
<P>
   But contrary to the belief that the winds might whip hair into a
frenzy, those gusts can become an integral part of your fashion
statement, said Richard Glen, a stylist at Juan A Salon in Sherman
Oaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more wind-blown your hair is, the more beautiful it is,''
Glen said. ``We make sure we do more layering and tell people to
keep a bottle of hair spray with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday wasn't as relaxing for Christmas tree lot workers
dealing with droves of downed timber and tents. But one manager in
the San Fernando Valley's Woodland Hills remained optimistic about
his operation and customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, as long as you've got the Christmas spirit, shopping for
a tree can be fun at any time,'' said Andy Santiago, manager of Mr.
Christmas Tree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides, we've got two huge tents here that let people shop
during rain, sleet or snow.''
</P>
<P>
   On the law enforcement front, California Highway Patrol Officer
Dwight McDonald said tensions on the road can become heightened
with flying debris and aggravation from other drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``People need to be patient, slow down and allow more time to
get to their destination,'' McDonald said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things could be blowing off of houses, or off the sides of
hills, so drivers need to also anticipate those problems and be
mindful of their surroundings.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-98 0203EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
