r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-KINGS-LBPT     12-10 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS END SKID WITH SOLID EFFORT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ As Wednesday dawned, there was no guarantee
the gloom that has enveloped the Kings all season would dissipate
anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   With thoughts of their struggles never far away, the Kings went
through their morning skate at the Forum, preparing for that
night's meeting with the Washington Capitals and hoping the outcome
would be different than it had been in 11 of the previous 12 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us are trying to stay as positive as we can,'' Kings
coach Larry Robinson said following the morning skate. ``It's very
easy to be negative. Anytime you're (in a slump), you can't say
things are going rosy.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think we've gone through probably the most difficult
part of our schedule. So at least now, we'll be able to have some
quality practice time, and travel fatigue won't be a question.''
</P>
<P>
   And as the day ended, things indeed were looking a little
brighter for the Kings (7-17-3), who snapped a five-game losing
streak with a 2-1 victory before an announced crowd of 9,816.
</P>
<P>
   It was just the third victory for the Kings (7-17-3) in 13 games
at the Forum this season, coming against a Capitals team missing
five injured players. The Capitals (8-14-3), Stanley Cup finalists
last season, have lost seven of their last nine games.
</P>
<P>
   Stephane Fiset, playing in his 300th NHL game, stopped 32 shots
to record his first win since he and Manny Legace combined for a
4-0 victory Oct. 28 at New Jersey. The only dark spot of the night
was that winger Steve McKenna, back in the lineup after missing a
month with an abdominal strain, appeared to aggravate the injury
late in the game.
</P>
<P>
   The most unusual aspect of the game was the Kings' first-period
offensive outburst, which accounted for both their goals. Entering
the game, the Kings had scored just one goal in their previous 10
opening periods.
</P>
<P>
   But 9:23 into the game, Luc Robitaille gave the Kings a 1-0 lead
_ their first lead since a 5-0 over Chicago 18 days earlier _ when
he beat Capitals goalie Olaf Kolzig with a slap shot from the right
faceoff circle after receiving a cross-ice pass from defenseman
Doug Bodger.
</P>
<P>
   The goal was Robitaille's team-high 13th this season, just three
fewer than he scored last season. Robitaille needs nine goals to
reach 500 in his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times, when things aren't going well, I think you're
tentative,'' Robinson said when asked about the Kings' first-period
offensive drought. ``You don't want to make foolish mistakes and
get down early. You have more of a tendency to be tentative, to do
more standing around and trying to think too much instead of
playing with the ease you normally play with.''
</P>
<P>
   Less than five minutes after Robitaille's goal, Glen Murray made
it 2-0, capitalizing when the Capitals made the sort of defensive
mistake that has been devastating the Kings all season.
</P>
<P>
   With Washington pressing for the tying goal, four of the five
Capitals on the ice got caught deep in the Kings' zone. This
allowed the Kings a 3-on-1 rush, with Murray completing the play
after passes from Robitaille and Yanic Perreault.
</P>
<P>
   Through 40 minutes, the Kings had the game under complete
control, a Jozef Stumpel in-the-crease violation costing Craig
Johnson a goal midway through the second period that would have
made the score 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   Still, 3:54 into the third period, Steve Konowalchuk cut the
Caps' deficit to one goal, scoring off a pass from Andrei
Nikolishin.
</P>
<P>
   But the Kings hung on, with Fiset robbing Kelly Miller's
point-blank shot with 3:15 to play. In the final minute, with
Kolzig pulled for an extra skater, the Capitals were unable to
mount a serious threat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
