A2314 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-HEISMAN-TRIVIA-TE     12-10 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HEISMAN-TRIVIA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIVIAL PURSUIT IN HEISMAN TERMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who was the first Heisman Trophy winner playing for a school in
his home state?
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota running back Bruce Smith, a native of Faribault, Minn.
</P>
<P>
   Which two high school or prep schools have produced more than
one Heisman Trophy winner?
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State's Eddie George and Miami's Vinny Testaverde attended
Fork Union Military Academy in Virginia; TCU's Davey O'Brien and
Notre Dame's Tim Brown attended Dallas' Woodrow Wilson High School.
</P>
<P>
   What was unique about the Heisman Trophies awarded from 1942-45?
</P>
<P>
   Because of World War II rationing, the Heismans were made of
scrap metal donated by members of the Downtown Athletic Club. After
the war, the winners received replacement Heismans.
</P>
<P>
   Who is the only Heisman Trophy winner to win the national
championship as a coach?
</P>
<P>
   Steve Spurrier won the Heisman for Florida in 1966. The Gators
won the national championship under Spurrier in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Who was the first black to receive the Heisman?
</P>
<P>
   Syracuse running back Ernie Davis in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   Which was the closest Heisman race?
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, Auburn running back Bo Jackson had a 45-point margin
over Iowa quarterback Chuck Long.
</P>
<P>
   Which year had the biggest voting landslide?
</P>
<P>
   1968. Southern California running back O.J. Simpson had a 1,750
point margin over Purdue running back Leroy Keyes.
</P>
<P>
   Has a Heisman winner ever won the award without getting the most
first-place votes?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, twice. Paul Hornung in 1956 and Billy Sims in 1978. The
Heisman voters list their top three players, with the vote getters
receiving three points for first, two points for second and one
point for third.
</P>
<P>
   Not only was Michigan's Charles Woodson the first defensive
player to win the Heisman Trophy, there was another distinction
that went along with his award. What was it?
</P>
<P>
   Woodson was the first player to win the award on a team that was
undefeated and untied since Pittsburgh's Tony Dorsett in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Which are the only schools with Heisman Trophy winners in
consecutive years?
</P>
<P>
   Army and Ohio State. Army's Doc Blanchard (Mr. Inside) won the
award in 1945 and Glenn Davis (Mr. Outside) won it in 1946. Ohio
State's Archie Griffin won the award in 1974 and 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Who are the only players to finish in the top four vote getters
three consecutive years?
</P>
<P>
   Army's Glenn Davis and Doc Blanchard (1944-46) and SMU's Doak
Walker (1947-49).
</P>
<P>
   Who is the only Heisman Trophy winner to win the award in two
consecutive years?
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State running back Archie Griffin won it in 1974 and 1975.
</P>
<P>
   True or false. A sophomore has never won the Heisman.
</P>
<P>
   True.
</P>
<P>
   Which Heisman Trophy winner was not a consensus All-American?
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame's Paul Hornung, playing for a 2-8 Irish team in 1956.
The consensus All-American backs that year were Syracuse's Jim
Brown, Tennessee's Johnny Majors, Oklahoma's Tommy McDonald and
Stanford's John Brodie.
</P>
<P>
   Which Heisman Trophy winner is the father of an actor?
</P>
<P>
   Tom Harmon is the father of actor Mark Harmon.
</P>
<P>
   Which Heisman Trophy winner also played in college basketball's
Final Four?
</P>
<P>
   Oregon State's Terry Baker won the Heisman in 1962 and played
for the Beavers in the 1963 Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   Who is the only player to finish second twice who didn't win the
Heisman?
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina's Charlie Justice finished second to SMU's Doak
Walker in 1948 and to Notre Dame's Leon Hart in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   Who is the shortest Heisman Trophy winner?
</P>
<P>
   TCU's Davey O'Brien, the 1938 winner, was 5-7. He's also the
lightest, at 150 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Who is the tallest Heisman Trophy winner?
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame's Leon Hart, the 1949 winner, was 6-5. He's also the
heaviest, at 260 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   How many Heisman Trophy winners are currently playing in the
NFL?
</P>
<P>
   Nine _ Buffalo's Doug Flutie (Boston College, 1984); Baltimore's
Vinny Testaverde (Miami, 1986); Oakland's Tim Brown (Notre Dame,
1987); Detroit's Barry Sanders (Oklahoma State, 1988); San
Francisco's Ty Detmer (BYU, 1990); Oakland's Desmond Howard
(Michigan, 1991); Tennessee's Eddie George (Ohio State, 1995); New
Orleans' Danny Wuerffel (1996, Florida); Oakland's Charles Woodson
(Michigan, 1997).
TEXAS TIES
</P>
<P>
   The following players were Texas natives who won Heisman
Trophies or who won Heisman Trophies while playing at Texas-based
schools: 1938 Davey O'Brien TCU Dallas 1948 Doak Walker SMU Dallas
1957 John David Crow Texas A&AMP;M Springhill, La. 1977 Earl Campbell
Texas Tyler 1978Billy Sims Oklahoma Hooks 1987 Tim Brown Notre Dame
Dallas 1989 Andre Ware Houston Dickinson 1990 Ty Detmer BYU San
Antonio 1998 Ricky Williams Texas San Diego
WINNINGEST SCHOOLS
</P>
<P>
   The following schools have produced more than one Heisman Trophy
winner: School No. Most recent winner Notre Dame 7 Tim Brown, 1987
Ohio State 6 Eddie George, 1995 Southern California 4 Marcus Allen,
1981 Army 3 Pete Dawkins, 1958 Michigan 3 Charles Woodson, 1997
Oklahoma 3 Billy Sims, 1978 Auburn 2 Bo Jackson, 1985 Florida 2
Danny Wuerffel, 1996 Georgia 2 Herschel Walker, 1982 Miami (Fla.) 2
Gino Torretta, 1992 Navy 2 Roger Staubach, 1963 Nebraska 2 Mike
Rozier, 1983 Yale 2 Clint Frank, 1937
WINNINGEST STATES
</P>
<P>
   The following states have produced multiple Heisman Trophy
winners: State No. Most recent California 10 Rashaan Salaam, 1994,
San Diego Ohio 9 Charles Woodson, 1997, Fremont Texas 7 Ty Detmer,
1990, San Antonio Pennsylvania 6 Eddie George, 1995, Philadelphia
Georgia 3 Charlie Ward, 1993, Thomasville Massachusetts 3 Doug
Flutie, 1984, Natick Alabama 2 Bo Jackson, 1985, Bessemer Illinois
2 Johnny Lattner, 1953, Chicago Louisiana 2 Billy Cannon, 1959,
Baton Rouge Nebraska 2 Johnny Rodgers, 1972, Omaha New York 2 Vinny
Testaverde, 1986, Elmont Oklahoma 2 Steve Owens, 1969, Miami --
Archie Griffin of Columbus won the award twice, but he is counted
just once in this tally.
WINNINGEST CITIES
</P>
<P>
   These cities have produced more than one Heisman winner:
Columbus, Ohio (Howard Cassady, Ohio State, 1955 and Archie
Griffin, Ohio State 1974-75) San Diego (Marcus Allen, USC, 1981 and
Rashaan Salaam, Colorado, 1994) Omaha (Nile Kinnick, Iowa, 1939 and
Johnny Rodgers, Nebraska, 1972) Dallas (Davey O'Brien, TCU, 1938;
Doak Walker, SMU, 1948, Tim Brown, Notre Dame, 1987).
SUPER BOWL MVPs
</P>
<P>
   The following Heisman Trophy winners were named most valuable
player in a Super Bowl: Player Team Super Bowl Roger Staubach
Dallas Cowboys VI Jim Plunkett Oakland Raiders XV Marcus Allen Los
Angeles Raiders XVIII Desmond Howard Green Bay Packers XXXI
MULTIPLE SPORTS
</P>
<P>
   These Heisman Trophy winners also saw action on their school's
basketball teams (includes freshman, junior-varsity, varsity
action): Terry Baker, Oregon State Ernie Davis, Syracuse Tom
Harmon, Michigan Larry Kelley, Yale Nile Kinnick, Iowa John
Lattner, Notre Dame Roger Staubach, Navy Charlie Ward, Florida
State
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
