<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-NOTES-WRITETHRU-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS ASK FANS TO BE PATIENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Concerned about the effect of the Kings' struggles on their
season-ticket holders, team president Tim Leiweke recently dropped
them a line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still believe in this team and we are still confident that
we will be back in the playoffs once we get our key players back on
the ice,'' Leiweke wrote in a letter sent to the team's 8,500
ticket-holders. ``Hopefully, you will judge us on the entire
season, not just last month.''
</P>
<P>
   After the first period of Wednesday night's sparsely attended
game against Washington at the Forum, Leiweke explained the
decision to write the letter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where we are at is not where we wanted to be,'' he said. ``I
felt really bad for them. ... I think if the fans hang in there,
the team will be there at the end of the day.''
</P>
<P>
   Leiweke said he'd already gotten responses from some recipients
of the letter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some said, `Class act,' '' Leiweke said. ``Others said, `If
you don't make the playoffs, it will be our last year.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Jokinen sits (subhed)
</P>
<P>
   For the second time since he was recalled from the minors more
than a month ago, rookie center Olli Jokinen was a healthy scratch
Wednesday night, when the Kings played host to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Larry Robinson said he didn't want both Jokinen and fellow
rookie Josh Green playing on the top two lines, and Robinson added
that Green was better suited than Jokinen to go into the corners
and battle along the boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'd like to see is him getting in there and battling
more,'' Robinson said of Jokinen, 19. ``He is a playmaker, but I'd
like to see a little more grit.''
</P>
<P>
   Jokinen's ice time has declined in his last five games. In his
first nine appearances, Jokinen averaged nearly 18 minutes a game,
and he had four goals, eight points and a plus-6 rating. In his
last five games, he has averaged about 11 minutes, had no points
and is minus-3. In his last game, a 4-3 loss Saturday to Detroit,
Jokinen played a season-low 6:41.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think about why I don't play,'' Jokinen said. ``I have
to work hard every game and practice. ... It's pretty hard when you
only go on the ice every 10 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Loose pucks (subhed)
</P>
<P>
   The Kings activated winger Steve McKenna before the game, and he
returned to the lineup for the first time since suffering an
abdominal strain on Nov. 5 in a fight with Tony Twist of the St.
Louis Blues. But McKenna aggravated the injury in the final two
minutes against Washington and will be examined today. ... After
the game, the Kings assigned center Brandon Convery to the Long
Beach Ice Dogs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
