r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-KINGS-WRITETHRU-L     12-10 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-WRITETHRU-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS END SKID WITH 2-1 VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ Esthetics? They didn't much matter.
</P>
<P>
   To Kings coach Larry Robinson and his players, it might as well
have been a 10-goal blowout with picturesque goals against a
powerhouse opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Kings hung on for a nervous 2-1 victory Wednesday
night over the injury-depleted Washington Capitals before an
announced crowd of 9,816 at the Forum, but when you've lost 11 of
your last 12 games, who cares what the score is so long as you're
on the right end of it?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a win,'' Robinson said. ``It's much easier to build on a
win. They've been few and far between. It's a step in the right
direction. You've got to get confidence from wins, and we'll take
anything we can get right now.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a novel night in many ways. The Kings (7-17-3) scored
both their goals in the first period _ by Luc Robitaille and Glen
Murray _ after scoring just once in their previous 10 first
periods.
</P>
<P>
   Goalie Stephane Fiset, who has missed much of the season with
groin injuries, stopped 32 shots to record his first victory since
he combined with Manny Legace to defeat New Jersey on Oct. 28. And
the victory was just the third for the Kings in 13 home games this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fiset didn't give up many rebounds and their defense did a
good job after the initial shot at tying our players up,'' said
former Mighty Ducks coach Ron Wilson, the coach of the Capitals
(8-14-3), who have lost seven of nine.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings took the lead 9:23 into the game, when Robitaille
scored his team-high 13th goal _ three fewer than he had last
season _ off a cross-ice feed from Doug Bodger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's the key,'' Robitaille said of the Kings' rare
quick start. ``The last two games before this one, we really played
hard, but we didn't come up with anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Less than five minutes after Robitaille's goal, they came up
with something else when the Capitals made the sort of defensive
mistake that has been devastating the Kings all season.
</P>
<P>
   With Washington pressing for the tying goal, four of the five
Capitals on the ice got caught deep in the Kings' zone. This
allowed the Kings a 3-on-1 rush, with Murray completing the play
after passes from Robitaille and Yanic Perreault.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen some of their films,'' Robinson said. ``We noticed
they do sometimes get four guys caught down low. One thing we
stressed was if we played well positionally, they'd give us enough
chances to win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Through 40 minutes, the Kings had the game under complete
control, a Jozef Stumpel in-the-crease violation costing Craig
Johnson a goal midway through the second period that would have
made the score 3-0. The goal was denied by referee Mark Faucette,
whose ruling was upheld by the video goal judge even though
Capitals goalie Olaf Kolzig was lounging on top of Stumpel as
Johnson fired the puck into the net.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, 3:54 into the third period, Steve Konowalchuk cut the
Capitals' deficit to one goal, scoring off a pass from Andrei
Nikolishin.
</P>
<P>
   But the Kings hung on, with Fiset robbing Kelly Miller's
point-blank shot with 3:15 to play. In the final minute, with
Kolzig pulled for an extra skater, the Capitals were unable to
mount a serious threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're struggling, you can't pinpoint one thing,''
Robitaille said. ``The key thing the last three games is that
everybody is doing the little things. You see guys finishing
checks, making the right little plays. We're playing for each other
now. We want to be the hardest-working team in the league. If we do
that, we'll be OK.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
