A2381 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VOLCANO-MONITORING-SF     12-10 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOLCANO-MONITORING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SATELLITES GIVE SCIENTISTS ADVANCE WARNING OF VOLCANO ERUPTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID PERLMAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Scientists in Hawaii are exploiting the
heat-sensing eyes of satellites to warn when dangerous volcanoes
threaten to erupt.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists are now monitoring many of the most active
volcanoes in North and South America.
</P>
<P>
   A global network of the specialized satellites could provide
advance warning of eruptions anywhere in the world, they said, and
also warn when wildfires threaten to flare out of control in remote
forests.
</P>
<P>
   In reports to the annual fall meeting of the American
Geophysical Union in San Francisco, the volcano experts said they
have successfully forecast eruptions on eight of the nine volcanoes
they are now watching regularly from space.
</P>
<P>
   Luke P. Flynn and his colleagues at the University of Hawaii
have developed a new system to process information from two weather
satellites flying 22,300 miles above the earth _ an orbit that
keeps them hovering over the same areas of the Western Hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   They are known as GOES, an acronym for Geostationary
Environmental Satellites, and in addition to cameras that
constantly transmit images of the clouds and storms used on
television weather reports, they also carry infra-red sensors that
make them extremely accurate long-distance thermometers, Flynn
said.
</P>
<P>
   The GOES satellite data is transmitted automatically every 15
minutes to the Naval Research Laboratory in Monterey, and, when
cracks open in the bulging dome of a hot volcano's summit, or fresh
flames rise above the canopy of a rain forest, the images of the
``hot spots'' are sent instantly to Hawaii and then displayed on a
special Internet site.
</P>
<P>
   The satellites have already enabled the Earth-bound scientists
to forecast an eruption of the Pacaya volcano in Guatemala nearly a
week before it sent a huge ash cloud over the region, Flynn said,
and then spotted a new lava flow on the volcano's flanks in
September.
</P>
<P>
   On the big island of Hawaii the satellites continuously monitor
the Kilauea lava flow to warn scientists at the U.S. Geological
Survey's volcano observatory there when fresh lava is flowing over
the ground or when it is reaching the ocean through underground
lava tubes.
</P>
<P>
   At the famed Popocatepetl volcano in Mexico, the GOES satellites
detected new heat emerging from lava inside a rising dome on the
summit a full week before observers on the ground detected it,
Flynn said. And a fresh ``hot spot'' atop the remote Lascar volcano
in northern Chile has been under constant satellite observation,
although so far the volcano has not erupted.
</P>
<P>
   There is good news, too, from the satellite observations, for
they show that the deadly Soufriere Hills volcano that killed
dozens and ravaged the Caribbean island of Montserrat in an
eruption three years ago has been cooling steadily since last May.
Its dome now appears stagnant, Flynn said.
</P>
<P>
   A global array of a dozen satellites like the GOES system could
monitor every active volcano in the world with a fresh warning of
increasing heat every 15 minutes, and provide warnings just as
rapidly when major fires break out unobserved in inaccessible
forests.
</P>
<P>
   GOES satellite images of volcanoes and wildfires from the
University of Hawaii are on the Internet at
http://volcano1.pgd.hawaii.edu &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
