A2383 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRLINE-VOLCANO-SFCHR     12-10 0343
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINE-VOLCANO-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARNING SYSTEM LETS JETS AVOID DANGER FROM ASH 
</HEADLINE>
   By CARL T. HALL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
    SAN FRANCISCO _ A sophisticated new international tracking
system has been set up to warn jet aircraft away from deadly clouds
of volcanic ash.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scientists described a network of nine Volcanic Ash Advisory
Centers Wednesday during a meeting of the American Geophysical
Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``The system is in place, and it has been working,'' said Thomas
Casadevall, associate director of the U.S. Geological Survey.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the world's busiest air traffic lanes, including the
so-called ``great circle route'' connecting North America and Asia,
fly over territory dotted with volcanoes. The main danger comes
from airborne debris jamming engines.
</P>
<P>
   No jets have crashed as a result of encounters with volcanic
eruptions, but there have been about 100 near-misses in the modern
era of jet travel, including nine incidents in which ash-clogged
engines stalled in midflight.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1989, for example, a Boeing 747 bound for Tokyo with
243 people aboard hit a volcanic cloud while approaching Anchorage,
Alaska, for a refueling stop.
</P>
<P>
   All four engines failed when the pilot tried to climb out _ now
regarded as exactly the wrong thing to do in such situations. The
plane came within about 60 seconds of slamming into a mountain
range before the pilot, on the 11th attempt, managed to get the
engines restarted.
</P>
<P>
   Now, methods are in place to detect restless volcanoes in
advance, quickly analyze trouble zones and issue detailed status
reports to commercial and military authorities. Along with training
in evasive maneuvers, pilots get printouts before every flight
showing what to watch out for.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists described the risk of air disasters as one of the
most significant volcano-related hazards of the modern age. Despite
the high-tech gear, experts concede that the danger has not been
eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many cases, the pilot may be the first one to detect an
eruption,'' Casadevall said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
