<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 09:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2579 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANCOCK11-COX     12-10 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANCOCK11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The once and always inimitable Herbie Hancock
 &HT;    By Michael Point
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Herbie Hancock visibly winces at the mention
that he might be the most widely imitated jazz pianist of modern
times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I don't know about that,'' he says with a resigned sigh
that indicates he's heard the notion before. ``I guess some people
think so, and I do occasionally hear some familiar phrases when I
listen to other pianists. But I always wonder just which version of
me people think they're imitating.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a good question because the 58-year-old Chicago native
quietly has amassed one of the deepest and most diverse bodies of
work in the history of jazz. Only the work of his former employer
Miles Davis compares, and even Davis' work is beginning to lose
pace as Hancock expand-- and embellishes his artistic reach. Like
Davis, Hancock's endlessly exploratory nature consistently
exasperates old fans while adding new devotees. Each startlingly
new musical direction generates equal amounts of controversy and
commendation.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock views his chameleon-like musical mutations not as
stylistic contradictions but as expressions of his expansive, yet
unified, artistic vision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe, or, at least, I hope, that all my music has my
personal creative imprint on it,'' the pianist explains. ``All of
it, no matter how different, is just part of a musical whole.''
</P>
<P>
   Jazz by nature always has been open to experimentation, but
Hancock's relentless quest for new expressions has set him far
apart from his contemporary peers while he has maintained his
mainstream significance. After all, how many jazz legends were
performing Mozart on stage with the Chicago Symphony as a preteen
or achieving MTV fame with a ground-breaking video such as
``Rockit'' while establishing themselves as the most copied jazz
pianist of the era?
</P>
<P>
   Hancock's mercurial music, always a conspicuous component of the
jazz world, quite simply has become the most pervasive sound on the
scene. The pianist/composer is in the midst of an unusually
prolific period, and his former record companies have taken
advantage of his ever-growing stature to reissue much of his
classic early work. As a result, Hancock's entire four-decade
career is currently on prominent display at your local CD store,
and the world is a much better and more musical place because of
it.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the current attention to Hancock's artistry is a result
of the phenomenal success of ``Gershwin's World,'' the most
adventurous and successful of the torrent of tributes to the Jazz
Age classical creator. The brilliantly conceived and flawlessly
executed project has been at the top of the jazz charts since its
release and, in classic Hancock tradition, has introduced his
musicianship to yet another group of fans.
</P>
<P>
   The elaborate production of the star-studded ``Gershwin's
World,'' which includes everything from African percussionists to a
symphony orchestra, follows Hancock's 1997 group recording ``New
Standard,'' a straight-ahead jazz outing _ with a typical twist.
Hancock's take on standards included compositions by the likes of
Peter Gabriel, Kurt Cobain and Prince, none of whom immediately
come to mind when the standard jazz repertoire is discussed. The
year before ``New Standard,'' Hancock reunited with fellow Davis
bandmate Wayne Shorter for ``1+1,'' a sublime album of
impressionistic acoustic piano-sax duets whose sensibilities were
as distant from Nirvana as Seattle is from Saturn.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Hancock's pioneering funk-fusion reissues ``Thrust''
and ``Sextant,'' supersaturated with synthesizers and streetwise
beats, are back in the stores in CD form so that hip-hoppers can
discard the vinyl versions they've been sampling for years. And, in
addition to his own work, Hancock's music is front and center on
the new ``Fingerpainting'' tribute, an album featuring a trio of
the jazz scene's current young lions _ trumpeter Nicholas Payton,
bassist Christian McBride and guitarist Mark Whitfield _ performing
classic Hancock compositions.
</P>
<P>
   But all those tasty treats are merely appetizers for the musical
banquet of Hancock's core catalog. The stunning compilation ``Miles
Davis Quintet 1965-'68,'' the definitive documentation of what many
critics and fans feel was the most exceptional acoustic ensemble of
modern times, has been joined in the stores recently by its logical
companion set, the electrifying ``Bitches Brew.'' The beautifully
boxed and musically expanded ``Bitches Brew,'' one of the most
significant recordings in the history of American music, arrives
just in time for Christmas, but it will light up your speakers any
time of year with its trail-blazing ferocity.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock's work in the Davis bands is the stuff of legend, but
his personalized jazz genius comes out clearest on his own
recordings from the period. And, again, just in time for Christmas,
they are freshly available via ``The Complete Blue Note Sixties
Sessions,'' a six-disc collection showcasing some of Hancock's best
work and some of the best jazz of the decade, if not some of the
best music the genre has produced in many decades.
</P>
<P>
   It's an overwhelming amount of powerful music, and listening to
it years later is a mixed, although overall positive, experience
for the musician who originally created it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are things you wish you had done differently, but
primarily you're pleased so many things turned out so well,''
Hancock explains. ``As a player you're more critical of your work
than as a composer, but I've always had the good fortune to work
with master musicians, so most of it still moves me.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Blue Note collection, an absolutely essential addition
to every jazz collection, best expresses the reasons Hancock is
held in such high regard in the jazz world, ``Gershwin's World'' is
undoubtedly the most impressive and representative example of his
remarkable eclecticism. Whether performing with Joni Mitchell and
Stevie Wonder or classical soprano Kathleen Battle, Hancock is
note-perfect in his playing and fearlessly inventive in his musical
vision. Two tracks with Hancock in front of the Orpheus Chamber
Orchestra and a grand finale of a solo interpretation of
``Embraceable You'' further exhibit his enlightened approach and
prodigious talent.
</P>
<P>
   So, what's next?
</P>
<P>
   Who knows, but expect it to be new, different and masterfully
imagined and executed.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point in my career I'm very interested in special
projects, recordings that are events instead of just variations of
what I've already done,'' Hancock says. ``I've got a lot of ideas
and musical areas I'd still like to explore, and I'm very open to
to any ideas others might have. I really don't know where my music
is going next, and that's a very exciting feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
