<SLUG> BC-DOLL-LADY11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Doll collector's motto: `Always room for more'
 &HT;    WITH PHOTO
 &HT;    By Douglas Kalajian
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Eva Becker doesn't leave home all that
much. Just doesn't care to. Getting groceries is husband Mike's
job, and darn-near everything else comes in the mail.
</P>
<P>
   It's amazing how much you can send away for when you dislike
malls as much as Eva does. ``I got 32 catalogs in the mail the
other day,'' she says. ``The mailman didn't know what to make of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   What Eva really likes is TV shopping. Some of those shop-at-home
shows have the best guests, such as Marie Osmond and designer Bob
Mackie. (``I just love it when he's on.'')
</P>
<P>
   That's how Eva got involved with dolls: She ordered one from TV.
That was about 20 years and 700 dolls ago. She wasn't thinking
about a collection, much less an obsession.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just started buying them because they were cute, and it was
so easy to do,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   She still doesn't think like a collector. No selling, no trading
and, most definitely, no scrounging around flea markets. Eva just
tunes in, calls up and waits for more to arrive.
</P>
<P>
   When they do, she somehow manages to live up to her posted motto
``Always room for more,'' even though there are already dolls
everywhere in her Boynton Beach house beyond the double-size
bedroom she calls the Doll Room.
</P>
<P>
   Dolls on shelves, on cabinets, on ledges and floors. Dolls on
beds and bureaus. Dolls in the bathrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Dolls that dance. Dolls that wave their arms. Dolls that cry.
</P>
<P>
   Royal Doulton dolls that match her china. Barbie dolls in nearly
every dress and pose, including Barbie loves Elvis. She has six
Qqueens of England. One Eempress of Russia (her most expensive, at
$1,500). And, of course, lots of dolls designed by Marie Osmond and
lots more dressed by Bob Mackie.
</P>
<P>
   The effect is heightened this time of year, when Eva snuggles
her Santa dolls in with all the rest and turns the house into one,
big Christmas doll display.
</P>
<P>
   It's usually a treat reserved for family and neighbors, but this
season already brought a special visit from 71 new friends, members
of the Salvation Army Home League.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of those ladies had to use walkers, but they took their
time and looked at every doll,'' Eva says. ``They were so thrilled,
and I was so thrilled.''
</P>
<P>
   The thrills resulted from Eva's one annual exception to her mall
aversion. For nine years now, she and Mike, who owns a plaster and
stucco business, have been faithful visitors to the Salvation Army
Angel Trees. They pick paper angels with the names of children who
need toys.
</P>
<P>
   Eva has about 40 angels, one for each child who's gotten a toy
from them. This year, Eva made one extra and very personal
donation. She wrote a poem.
</P>
<P>
   The mall was filled with the Christmas spirit,
</P>
<P>
   We knew that God above could hear it.
</P>
<P>
   Now every year Mike and me
</P>
<P>
   Go to visit the Angel tree.
</P>
<P>
   The poem made such a hit with the local Salvation Army folks in
Broward County, where the Beckers used to live, that it's being
passed along to the national headquarters and may be published,
said volunteer coordinator Jean Gerber. Just knowing she touched
someone with her words has Eva excited.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not always sure where to put the punctuation, but every
once in a while something comes out,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Although she has no training, she started writing poems as a
child with her father and hasn't stopped. They're in a big notebook
titled ``Daddy and Me.''
</P>
<P>
   She even wrote a few songs and made a record back in the
mid-'70s. A couple of newspaper clippings on the hallway wall
recount her brief career as a country singer in Nashville. Her
sisters even heard her songs on the radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were getting played all over the country,'' Eva says.
``The record company wanted me to do promotions. Travel around and
sing.''
</P>
<P>
   That didn't appeal to Eva. Fame and fortune just didn't seem
like good enough reasons to leave home.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
