<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Women to march again in remembrance, revival of temperance
movement
 &HT;    By Jim DeBrosse
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HILLSBORO, Ohio _ On Christmas Eve morning nearly 125 years ago,
70 scared but very determined women in this charming Southern Ohio
town emerged from the Presbyterian church and marched two-by-two
through the streets of downtown, singing the hymn Give to the Winds
Thy Fears .
</P>
<P>
   Some cried. Some trembled. Some stood tall with eyes upraised.
But all of them were of a single aim: with public prayer and
appeal, they vowed to shut off the flow of liquor from the town's
many saloons, drugstores and hotels and stop the hard-drinking,
brawling behavior ripping apart their families and their community.
</P>
<P>
   Today at 1 p.m., about 30 members of the Woman's Christian
Temperance Union _ still alive and, its leaders say, still very
much needed _ will re-enact the march that gave birth to the
temperance crusade and led to the broader movement for child
protection and voting rights for women.
</P>
<P>
   After today's march, the members will walk the few blocks to the
quaint Colonial home of Mrs. Eliza Jane Trimble Thompson, the
descendent of two Ohio governors who was chosen the first leader of
the temperance movement in 1873. Later, they will lay a wreath at
her simple gravesite north of town.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women really owe a lot to the WCTU and its early organizers,''
said Sarah Ward, president of the Evanston, Ill.-based organization
that has promoted abstinence from alcohol for more than a century.
``Women who had been cloistered up to that point, but who saw the
need for change, found an avenue to make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   The early temperance crusade was the training grounds for many
of the nation's first women activists, including Susan B. Anthony,
who went on to lead the suffragette movement and the fight for
women's voting rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many women suffered deeply because of men who drank up all
their wages. Remember, there was no safety net, no welfare back
then,'' said Gladys Beckwith, a Michigan State University professor
and head of the Michigan Women's Studies Association. ``Alcohol was
really a terrible foe to women, and that's a major reason (the
temperance crusade) allied with the suffrage movement.''
</P>
<P>
   Literally, as well as figuratively, the 70 women of Hillsboro
discovered a voice that would roar, generations later, as the
nation's voting majority. After being drafted by the other women as
their leader, ``Mother'' Thompson was so nervous and frightened she
couldn't bring herself to address the fledgling group until a
minister asked the men in the church to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``These women had no role models'' for public speaking, Ward
said. ``There were no women governors or mayors or even ministers
they could look to.''
</P>
<P>
   Within days, though, the Hillsboro group caught its stride,
kneeling in prayer on sidewalks before the local liquor vendors,
pleading for them to abandon the trade. Within a few weeks, the
Hillsboro crusade had spread across half of America and closed
thousands of saloons.
</P>
<P>
   By the turn of the last century, the temperance union had
successfully lobbied to make the study of alcohol's dangers a part
of every public schoolchild's education. And in 1919, Congress and
the states enacted the 18th Amendment to the U.S. Constitution and
the nation's short-lived prohibition against alcohol began.
</P>
<P>
   The popular image of the early crusaders as dour, axe-wielding
zealots out to trample on personal liberties doesn't hold up to the
truth, chroniclers have said. Hugh S. Fullerton, a famed sports
writer in the early part of the century, grew up in Hillsboro and,
as a child, knew many of the women personally. ``They were the most
modest, quiet, home-loving members of the aristocracy of
(Hillsboro),'' he wrote in a 1919 national magazine article marking
the start of Prohibition.
</P>
<P>
   What spurred the women to action, he wrote, was not only their
deeply-held religious values but a belly full of the town's public
drunkenness, especially on Stock Sales Day, when men gathered to
deal livestock and, afterward, hit the local saloons. ``(It) made
the village a drunken hell with brawling, cutting and shooting,''
Fullerton wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the women also knew the destructive force of alcohol in
their own families, Fullerton wrote, noting that the town's
aristocracy originated from Virginia, the Carolinas and Kentucky
and ``the men, after the manner of their class, drank hard.''
</P>
<P>
   A life-sized portrait of Judge James Henry Thompson, husband of
Mother Thompson, hangs in Hillsboro's Highland House Museum, where
it ``attests (to his hard-drinking) because, as you can see, his
face is all red,'' said Jean Wallis, assistant director of the
museum.
</P>
<P>
   Hillsboro Mayor Sandy Harsha, whose great grandmother marched
side-by-side with Thompson, says the town's major concern these
days is traffic congestion, not public intoxication. With Ohio
routes 42, 73, 124 and 138 all converging in Hillsboro, and
development booming north along U.S. 62, the downtown streets are
often snarled. Hillsboro plans to hire a traffic consultant, ``but
it's nothing we'll solve very quickly,'' Harsha said.
</P>
<P>
   From a peak of 250,000 members in the late 19th century, the
temperance union has dwindled to 8,000 members in 39 states today.
But Ward said the organization is ``still alive and well, and we
still feel we are needed. We continue our crusade, even though we
aren't using the same methods.''
</P>
<P>
   Ward noted that fetal alcohol syndrome, which develops when
women drink during pregnancy, is the leading cause of birth defects
in America. ``Then look at all the efforts to get drunk drivers off
the road, and yet drinking is still responsible for well over 40
percent of all traffic fatalities,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But the union gave up the marches and demonstrations and public
prayer vigils long ago. Those are no longer effective tactics in
today's climate of individual rights at all costs, Ward said.
Instead, the group focuses on education by sponsoring anti-alcohol
literature and contests in the schools. And, as always, it remains
committed to promoting abstinence, one pledge at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're different from other groups today that say, `Don't drink
until you're 21,' or `Don't drink and drive,' `` Ward said. ``We're
still saying a safer approach is not to drink at all. You'll never
become an alcoholic if you never take that first drink.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
