</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With asphalt on march, urban sprawl goes rural
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Dating back to the first Earth Day, every Junior
Ecologist could cite a glossary of environmental villains: DDT,
acid rain, CFCs, dioxin.
</P>
<P>
   It's time we started acknowledging that environmental dilemma
No. 1 is not nearly so exotic. Try asphalt. Asphalt takes green and
makes black. With changing lifestyles, it blackens more and more
green, miles removed from so-called asphalt jungles.
</P>
<P>
   Urban sprawl, commonly associated with major metro hubs, is
loosely defined as low-density development. Instead of high-rises
scraping the sky, we have sprawling super stores, strip centers and
fast-food hives scraping away undeveloped land. With development
chasing customers who have fled the city, the sprawl is not so
urban any more.
</P>
<P>
   Another characteristic: Urban sprawl is growth that doesn't
necessarily reflect increases in population. Rather, it reflects
changes in lifetyle _ principally Americans' willingness to hop in
the car, to spread out and to to abandon inner cities.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, from 1990 to 1996, developed land in Chicago
increased by 40 percent, but population increased by only 6
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Waco's own sprawl
</P>
<P>
   Waco is getting to know urban sprawl in the form of an explosion
of super stores and restaurants. To see this development along
Franklin Avenue, one would think that someone had just struck oil
in suburban Hewitt and spawned a land rush. No. As with most Texas
mid-sized cities, growth here has been modest and grudging.
</P>
<P>
   Developers say the key in our case is that the metro area in the
last five years eclipsed the magic 200,000 population threshold
that many chains require.
</P>
<P>
   Now as the city considers annexing land along the U.S. 84
corridor, a question looms: How much asphalt can an ecosytem stand?
</P>
<P>
   The City of Waco must build into any growth a plan to keep some
areas asphalt-free.
</P>
<P>
   City Manager Kathy Rice talks about planning that would
incorporate green spaces to buffer subdivisions.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, this is a foreign language to mid-sized
communities butting up against rural frontiers. Hey, green we've
got. Look out the window.
</P>
<P>
   Give us some of that, you know, green.
</P>
<P>
   The latter translates, of course, into more asphalt, which means
more air pollution, more runoff (bearing pollution), more noise,
more life-giving soil entombed for eternity.
</P>
<P>
   Open space imperative
</P>
<P>
   If our lifestyles demand more asphalt, our environment demands
that we plan space where it can't reside.
</P>
<P>
   We also must invest in green belts and parks, just like
forefathers who set aside land for our benefit.
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Club, which has pronounced ``Challenge to Urban
Sprawl'' as its signature campaign, has other key suggestions such
as stepped-up efforts to redevelop downtowns, not just as business
centers but also as places where people will want to live.
</P>
<P>
   To make asphalt all-powerful as public policy is nothing more
than to march backward into the dark ages before the environmental
movement.
</P>
<P>
   If you want an irony, consider this: Part of America's
accelerating sprawl is due to the fact that many people have fallen
out of love with the mall, which sapped many downtowns of vitality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Save our mall'' doesn't sound like a chant for Earth Day, but
the fact is that anything that gets people out of their cars
between retail transactions is good for the planet, although
certainly the planet votes for green belts, hike-bike trails and
parks first.
</P>
<P>
   As Joni Mitchell wrote, you don't know what you've got until
it's under asphalt. She also wrote that we had to get back to the
garden. Get back to the, um, mall, Joni?
</P>
<P>
   John Young is the opinion page editor of the Waco
Tribune-Herald. His column appears Tuesday, Thursday and Sunday.
E-mail: jyoung(at)mail.wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
