<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 09:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2589 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-KELSO-COLUMN11-CO     12-10 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-KELSO-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No bull for Mississippi's cutup coach?
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ So, with the University of Texas playing Mississippi
State in the Cotton Bowl on New Year's Day, you're wondering what
surprise moves Jackie Sherrill has up his sleeve.
</P>
<P>
   The Mississippi State coach has hired Lorena Bobbitt as his
offensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, I just made that part up. But Sherrill has been known
to sit on the very cutting edge of football strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Six years ago, he had a bull castrated on a practice field in
front of his Mississippi State players to get them fired up for the
team's season opener against Texas.
</P>
<P>
   What a nutty guy. But that sort of demonstration would be a
great motivational tool for me. ``Uh, Kelso, if you don't stop
doggin' it out there . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   Most coaches take the bull by the horns, but Sherrill got it
backwards and started at the other end of the animal. Actually, he
got someone from the vet school to do the dirty work for him.
Either way, the incident didn't get Mississippi State any bouquets
from People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had almost forgotten about our little bull incident; I'm
afraid it's going to come back and rear its ugly head,'' said
Mississippi State Sports Information Director Mike Nemeth. Nemeth
said the school got a lot of calls from animal rights people around
the country. ``Most of them in outrage,'' he said. ``They came from
New York City and Boston and L.A. In the state of Mississippi, no
one called. This is such a farming state.''
</P>
<P>
   Which explains why the Mississippi State song is ``Old MacDonald
Had a Farm.'' Let's all sing along: ``And on that farm he had some
bulls, e-i-e-i-o. With a snip-snip here, and a snip-snip there. . .
. Old MacDonald had some steers . . . ``
</P>
<P>
   I'm wondering if Sherrill is going to rearrange any animals for
UT and the Cotton Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Because surgery worked so well in 1992, with Mississippi State
beating Texas 28-10 in John Mackovic's first game at UT, you've got
to figure Sherrill might disturb the herd again, right?
</P>
<P>
   Nemeth said Sherrill had no such plans. He said Sherrill
arranged for the cutting the first time around because the UT
mascot, Bevo, is a steer and ``the players had asked what a
Longhorn steer was.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, sure, buddy. In a corn-cob state like Mississippi, where
clean overalls is formal attire, the difference between a bull and
a steer is one of the few things you'd expect a college kid to
understand. If the Mississippi State players had asked Sherrill
what a flush toilet is, I'd believe it. But don't try to give me
some cock-and-bull story .
</P>
<P>
   The bull ploy caused some real problems for Mackovic, though.
Not only did he have to come up with a game plan, he also had to
figure out which wine goes with calf fries. I'd recommend a
chardonnay. And what happened to the evidence? Did Sherrill have
them laminated, then hang them from his rearview mirror?
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people seem to think they taste like chicken,'' said
Rick Spencer, owner of Spencers' Mountain Bar &AMP; Grill in
Centennial, Wyo., where Friday nights are ``Nut and Gut Night'' _
all the Rocky Mountain oysters and chicken gizzards you can eat for
$5.95, cocktail sauce included.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever your dining pleasure, it's too bad Sherrill's team
didn't open the '92 season against Montana. I would have enjoyed
watching the grizzly gnaw off his arm.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso writes for The American-Statesman in Austin, Texas.
He can be reached at 445-3606 or at jkelsostatesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
