<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981210.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 09:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2602 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDEAST-DEVELOPMENT-$     12-10 1164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-DEVELOPMENT-$ADV13 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON VISITS PALESTINIAN ECONOMIES THAT HAVE SHRIVELED DURING
5-YEAR PEACE PROCESS.
 &HT;    With PALESTINIAN-BOX and PALESTINIAN-CHARTER
 &HT;    PHOTOS for this story will be placed in the International folder
on the Cox server.
 &HT;    Advance for release Sunday, Dec. 13, but papers are free to use
it prior to that.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service(at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAZA CITY, Gaza The house painter says he is happy that
President Clinton is coming to town. But he doesn't look happy. He
frowns and is quick to raise his voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't work. That's why I look this way,'' grumbles Shaher
I'leewa(cq), a 30-year-old Gazan, as he leaned on a car in busy
Palestine Square. He has short-term work today, but he has five
kids and has not had a steady job in six months.
</P>
<P>
   Donkey carts make their way among the cars on the streets
nearby. Based on the overall Gaza population, three-fourths of the
people passing here are refugees and a third still live in refugee
camps. Worse still, they make about 20 percent less money than they
did before the peace process began. One out of five, like I'leewa,
is unemployed.
</P>
<P>
   He is one of the people Clinton seemed to be talking about in a
speech to international aid donors last month: A Palestinian who
feels like he has not seen the benefits of the five-year-old peace
process.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Clinton will become the first U.S. president to visit a
Palestinian-controlled area.
</P>
<P>
   He seeks to boost the faltering peace between the Gazans and
their richer neighbors in Israel. For all the diplomacy and peace
treaties, the chances for peace depend largely on whether people
like this painter think they can take care of their families better
now than before. So far, they cannot.
</P>
<P>
   I'leewa's problem is that he cannot work in Israel anymore.
Israel, concerned about security, has tightened the entrance
criteria and excluded, according to some counts, more than half of
the 150,000 Palestinians who used to commute in every day.
</P>
<P>
   I'leewa never cared much about politics, but he agrees with
Clinton that peace and prosperity are connected.
</P>
<P>
   ``With no work, you will go to the Hamas people,'' he says,
referring to the extremist group that sends terrorist bombers into
Israel and runs a social services network that serves the needy.
``If you have work, when Hamas comes to you, you will tell them, 'I
don't need you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the Palestinian areas there are examples of the
complexities that stifle economic opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   In the West Bank city of Ramallah, Khaled Rashadeh helped make
the 14,000 plastic U.S. flags that will drape across streets for
Clinton's visit. He cares about making money, not about politics.
But he has a political problem.
</P>
<P>
   When he went to work in neighboring Jordan a few years ago, he
lost his Israeli-approved West Bank identity card. He has rejoined
his family, but cannot buy a car or a house without an ID even if
he could on $340 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Rashadeh, 36, is married and he would like to put his four kids
in private schools, rather than the school in their refugee camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to just be dependent on Israel,'' he says. ``If
the Israelis and Arabs put their minds together, this would be the
greatest place.''
</P>
<P>
   And, there's the story of West Bank resident Amjad Bader, 30,
studying nearby and trying to rebuild his life after 28 months in
Israeli jails.
</P>
<P>
   Bader was a college activist in the Palestinian uprising that
was known as the Intifada. He organized demonstrations and riots
against Israeli occupation.
</P>
<P>
   ``With me, the political activity is over,'' he says. ``The
dream of my life is to become independent financially.''
</P>
<P>
   He has a wife and daughter and was working two jobs about 16
hours a day. Hoping to sell cosmetics in Jordan, he won approval
from the Israeli supreme court to travel. But, something went wrong
and, in Jordan, he was arrested for having improper immigration
papers and was sent back.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he is learning to be a driving instructor. The class is run
by a group that rehabilitates former prisoners. They have 31,000
others like Bader getting, or waiting for, training, and they have
trouble finding jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The group, the Ex-Detainee Rehabilitation Center, gets its money
from European countries.
</P>
<P>
   Donor countries recently pledged up to $4 billion in aid over
five years to the Palestinian-controlled areas. The U.S. gives $75
million a year now.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds like a lot of money for a population of about 2.5
million people. On the other hand, world powers have long sunk
billions into this region, trying to buy an elusive peace.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. alone gives $3 billion a year to the 6 million
Israelis, who have a per capita income about 10 times that of the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian per capita income has dropped 21 percent since 1992
to just $1,630, according to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Experts see potential in the Palestinian economy. Palestinians
are not as poor as their Egyptian or Jordanian neighbors. Also,
they are well-educated and entrepreneurial.
</P>
<P>
   But, their tiny, $3.3 billion-a-year economy depends on access
to the $100 billion Israeli power house next door. Israel can
isolate their economy literally in minutes, by closing checkpoints
and shipping access.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's trip highlights one solution. He will fly by
helicopter into Gaza International Airport Monday. The $80 million,
donor-funded airport opened a few weeks ago and allows Palestinians
to travel and ship goods with less Israeli interference.
</P>
<P>
   There have been other donor-provided improvements over the five
years since the peace process started. Flood Waters and sewage do
not overflow into the narrow streets of Gaza's eight refugee camps
as much anymore, and the camps all have potable water. Major
streets are paved and dumpsters with ``European Community''
stenciled on the side help eliminate the litter.
</P>
<P>
   On the eastern edge of The Gaza Strip, a 50-acre industrial park
is being built that could ultimately employ 15,000 people in
companies lured by tax incentives. The Palestinian Coca-Cola
distributor is the first big-name tenant.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian economist Hisham Awartani said aid to the
Palestinians will help fix the roads and phone systems needed to
attract investment, but it should be used only in the transition
from occupied territory to a self-sufficient state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many Palestinians are somewhat sensitive about aid,'' he says.
``We are not Bangladesh. Palestine is a relatively rich country.''
</P>
<P>
   He wants it to be easier for painters to get to their jobs, or
Palestinians to get identification cards that let them buy cars or
sell products in Jordan. A crucial sea port, envisioned in the
peace process, still does not have Israeli approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can help us more not just by giving aid, but by twisting
the Israelis arms,'' Awartani says.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
