<P>
   1. AGING BUT INTENSE: SENIOR TENNIS PLAYERS SPEAK OUT In 1993, a
group of veteran tennis stars joined to start a seniors tour. It
now includes players like Bjorn Borg, 42, Guillermo Vilas, 46,
Jimmy Connors, 46, John McEnroe, 39, and Yannick Noah, 38. McEnroe,
who in his prime won 161 tournaments and was ranked No. 1 for 170
weeks, now works as a TV commentator; the fiery player once known
as ``McNasty'' also runs an art gallery. Noah, the 1983 French Open
champ and two-time captain of victorious French Davis Cup teams,
lives in New York, like McEnroe, and is a successful pop singer. In
this interview, the two men discuss the senior tour, the state of
tennis today -- and old rivalries that have been slow to die.
Interview by Jorg Winterfeldt. From Der Spiegel. 1,000 words.
(English translation available.) 2. ARE TODAY'S KIDS HARDER TO
HANDLE? This article looks at why some children are now so
aggressive inside and outside the home, and what can be done to
help them. By Kyle D. Pruett. From Child magazine. 1,000 words. 3.
POETRY IN MOTION Andy Carroll is the 29-year-old director of the
American Poetry and Literacy Project. He raises money from
corporations, foundations and private citizens, uses the cash to
buy poetry books, and then gives them all away in person (e.g. in
supermarkets, hospitals, on trains ... ) or through the mail - more
than 200,000 books. By Tom Dunkel. 800 words + photo. 4. HILARY
STILL HAS A LONG WAY TO GO People have begun to ask whether Hilary
Rodham Clinton is likely to be elected president of the United
States. At this point, the answer is evidently no, but the question
does reflect a remarkable development in her role and the way she
is perceived. By Flora Lewis. 800 words. 5. FETAL CELLS IN MOTHER'S
SKIN MAY CAUSE RASH DURING PREGNANCY French researchers report that
a rash that afflicts many women during pregnancy may be caused by
fetal cells which escape the womb, migrate to the mother's skin,
and trigger an immune reaction. By Michael McCarthy. The Lancet
News Service. 1,000 words. 6. THE 'SON OF GOD' IN THE DEAD SEA
SCROLLS Was a key part of the Christmas story borrowed from the
Dead Sea Scrolls? By Neil Altman and David Crowder. 1,000 words +
photo.
