<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: WHY WYE ISN'T WORKING
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Dec. 13.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``You know that the president is playing with fire
by trying to cut a deal in the Middle East,'' his national security
adviser told me. ``It isn't only that those people don't trust each
other,'' he added. ``They loathe each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Our conversation took place 20 years ago, the day before Jimmy
Carter brought the leaders of Israel and Egypt to Camp David in a
bid to make peace between two nations that had been enemies for 30
years. To the surprise of the adviser, Zbigniew Brzezinski, and his
press aide, Madeleine Albright, Carter managed to plant a cold but
lasting peace between the warring parties.
</P>
<P>
   Carter did so without first having in hand a pre-cooked deal. It
is an axiom in this city that a president should never commit the
prestige of his office to a major foreign policy endeavor unless
the final outcome is known in advance.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has embarked on a similar high-wire act by
seeking to rescue the tenuous land-for-security deal he brokered in
October between Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader, and Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   As he flies aboard Air Force One to Tel Aviv, Clinton could do
worse than to review what emerged from Camp David. The ``Framework
for Peace in the Middle East,'' signed by Menachem Begin and Anwar
Sadat, noted that their peoples ``yearn for peace so that the vast
human and natural resources of the region can be turned to the
pursuits of peace and so that this area can become a model for
coexistence and cooperation among nations.''
</P>
<P>
   Those hopes remain as elusive today as they were back then.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the 1978 document said that ``Egypt, Israel,
Jordan and the representatives of the Palestinian people should
participate in negotiations on the resolution of the Palestinian
problem in all its aspects.'' A three-stage timetable was invoked
for cutting a deal on the West Bank and Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   That timetable was never consummated. A later timetable, forged
in Oslo in 1993, is in deep trouble because Netanyahu &AMP; Co. reject
the notion of a sovereign Arab Palestine and because Arafat Inc.
will settle for nothing less.
</P>
<P>
   The Wye Accord that Clinton brokered supposedly hangs by a
thread in light of Israel's refusal to release Palestinian
political prisoners. These are one and the same folks whom Arafat
hails as ``martyrs and heroes'' and whom Netanyahu brands ``as
killers of innocent women and children.''
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, Sheikh Ahmed Yassin, the founder of Hamas, the
militant Muslim group, who is under Palestinian house arrest in
Gaza, is staging a hunger strike to affirm the ``sacred right'' of
the movement's detainees ``to freedom and dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton can't say in public what, in private, he knows to be
true: the real issue isn't a lack of freed prisoners but a lack of
real trust between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
   With trust in hand, all else becomes either negotiable or
trivial; without it, nothing is possible. That's what Carter
learned at his daring Camp David summit and what Clinton must
discover anew in the aftermath of his equally bold Wye initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington, D.C.-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
