<SLUG> BC-FEATURES-BJT1211-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories for release Friday, December 11, 1998, are
moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports, business and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. All stories have moved
except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   NEW NOTICE: Versions of some of these stories are available in
paginated form: www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   SICKLE _ Twelve-year-old Keone Penn is in a fight for his life,
against an almost unbeatable opponent, sickle cell. The relentless
disease has pushed him into an experimental procedure that may save
his life, and kill the disease _ or kill him. Today, the suburban
Atlanta youth undergoes a cord blood transplant, the first in the
world, at Emory Hospital. If it succeeds, healthy blood cells will
replace his sickle-shaped ones, and he'll live a normal, pain-free
life. (Guthrie, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS and
GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN _ On Christmas Eve morning nearly 125 years ago, 70 scared
but very determined women in this charming, quiet town set among
the rolling hills of the Ohio Valley decided to put an end to the
drunken brawls and shattered homes of its community, and set off on
a peaceful march to shut off the flow of liquor from its many
saloons, drugstores and hotels. Historians say that first march,
which soon spurred women to action across America, marks not only
the birth of the temperance movement but of the women's rights
movement in general. Today, some 30 members of the Women's
Christian Temperance Movement will re-enact the march through
downtown and visit the homestead and gravesite of ``Mother
Thompson,'' the Hillsboro matron who started it all. The Temperance
Union says it's still very much alive and needed today, but the
Hillsboro Mayor says development pains and traffic congestion, not
saloons, are the town's chief problem now. (DeBrosse, Dayton Daily
News). 35-40. WITH PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   DOLL-LADY _ Eva Becker saw a doll advertised on TV and ordered
it. That was about 20 years and 700 dolls ago. She doesn't think
like a collector. No selling, no trading, and most definitely no
scrounging around flea markets. Eva just tunes in, calls up and
waits for more to arrive. (Kalajian, Palm Beach Post). 20. WITH
PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   BURTQ&AMP;A _ Q and A with Burt Reynolds, who stars in and directs
TNT's ``Hard Time'' airing Sunday. To no one's surprise, Reynolds
plays a hard-edged cop framed for a street killing. (Longino,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 39.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   BURT-FILMLIST _ A few hits and outright misses from Reynolds'
many big-screen films _ From Grade A ``Deliverance'' to Grade F
``At Long Last Love.'' (Longino, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 14.
</P>
<P>
   BURT-BIO _ Burt Reynolds bio box. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 7.5.
</P>
<P>
   TEMPEST-REVIEW _ Review of ``The Tempest,'' a new NBC movie
(Sunday) starring Peter Fonda in a drastic remake of Shakespeare's
play, set in the Civil War South. NBC scheduled this during
November sweeps then bumped it. (Kloer, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   HANCOCK _ Herbie Hancock has the No. 1 album on the jazz charts
right now _ a tribute to George Gershwin featuring Joni Mitchell,
Stevie Wonder, a chamber orchestra and opera singer Kathleen Battle
_ and is prominently involved in the reissue of the year (Miles
Davis quintet); the release of the new Hancock Blue Note box (his
solo albums from the '60s), as well as the reissue of his electric
fusion trailblazers of the '70s gives him the widest, deepest and
most successful (in sales and art terms) current catalogs in jazz.
Point profiles his eclectic career, using all the new
releases/reissues as a guide; also trying for interview (Point,
Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TVSURFER-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ Highlights of tomorrow's TV viewing.
ETA: 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE REVIEWS
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-SIMPLE _ Review of ``A Simple Plan,'' a comedy/crime
thriller about two brothers (Bill Paxton, Billy Bob Thornton) who
find a bag of money. Director Sam Raimi's movie is anything but
simple. It's a character-driven black comedy with some powerful
moral-qualm undercurrents. Expertly played by the ensemble cast.''
Grade: B+. (Ringel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SIMPLE _ Review of ``A Simple Plan.'' A snarl of greed and
paranoia entangles friends and family when three snaggly-toothed
hayseeds find $4 million inside a downed plane. The title, you see,
bubbles with irony. This movie was the talk of this fall's Toronto
Film Festival, and there's been Oscar buzz associated with it ever
since. Stars Bill Paxton and Billy Bob Thornton. (Garcia, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-JACKFROST _ Review of ``Jack Frost,'' a comedy-drama in
which Michael Keaton gets a second chance at being a really cool
dad. Michael Keaton plays a dead dad who comes back as a talking
snowman and teaches his son to play hockey. I'm not making this up.
The synthetic, special-effects driven comedy is another of those
stale Hollywood sermons about taking time out for your kids. It's
less substantial than a snowball in July.'' Grade: D. (StMurray,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   FROST _ Review of ``Jack Frost.'' On the eve of big success in
the music world, Jack is killed in a car wreck on Christmas. He
pops up a year later, assuming _ we kid you not _ the form of a
snowman his kid has built. (Macor, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-CELEBRATION _ Review of ``The Celebration,'' a Danish
film about family secrets. ``At the gala 60th birthday party of his
father, a young man (Ulrich Thomsen) reveals a dark family secret
in this Danish long day's journey into night. A mix of
old-fashioned theatrics, pop psychology and cinema verite
filmmaking, it's a wonderfully compelling melodrama.'' Grade : B+.
(StMurray, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-DEVINE _ Review of ``Waking Ned Devine,'' a gentle farce
about a lottery winner in an Irish village. ``A broad, twinkly
Irish comedy about what happens in a tiny village when it's
discovered that one resident holds a lottery ticket worth nearly $7
million. The movie is a little too eager to please, a little too
Lucky Charms Irish. But the two leads, devilish old-pro codgers Ian
Bannen and David Kelly, are practiced charmers.'' Grade: B-.
(Ringel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   STARTREK _ Review of ``Star Trek: Insurrection.'' The ninth in
the ``Trek'' series: Capt. Picard looks for Data on a desert planet
and makes grand self-discoveries. (Garcia, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-STARTREK _ Review of ``Star Trek: Insurrection,'' the
latest adventure for Captain Jean-Luc Picard (Patrick Stewart) and
crew. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   OPEN _ Limited runs and film notes. (Garcia, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   STRANGE _ Review of ``I Married a Strange Person.'' An animated
film by Bill Plympton: A pair of flying, fornicating ducks crash
into a newlyweds' satellite dish, sending radiation ricocheting
into the base of the husband's brain. Suddenly, he can make
fantasies come true. (Seaborn, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS _ Mini reviews of all currently playing
movies. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
