<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 10:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2670 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DANGEROUS-ROOM-DANCE-     12-10 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DANGEROUS-ROOM-DANCE-ART-2TAKES-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR A CHILD, A FOREST OF DANGERS AT HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 13)  
 (af)  
 Christopher Reardon writes frequently about dance for The Village
Voice.  
 By CHRISTOPHER REARDON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Losing a child is a fate so wrenching that the mere thought of
it can tie a parent's stomach in knots. It can leave one
tongue-tied too, given that there's no better word for it than the
lawyerly predeceased.
</P>
<P>
   A spouse can be widowed, a child orphaned, but how can one
convey the singular grief of the mother and father who must bury
their young?
</P>
<P>
   If you're Susan Marshall, you summon your dancers and create a
work like ``The Most Dangerous Room in the House,'' which opens on
Wednesday at the Brooklyn Academy of Music's Majestic Theater. This
vertiginous 78-minute production, her fifth for the academy's Next
Wave Festival in a decade, revolves around a woman tormented by
visions of a child's death.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Marshall began working on the piece while expecting her
first child, Nicholas, now 19 months old. ``I wanted to play with
the idea of chaos,'' she said in an interview. ``How do you protect
someone in a world that is essentially chaotic, where you have no
control?''
</P>
<P>
   Forever leaping from the personal to the universal _ and seldom
skittish about tempting fate _ Ms. Marshall turned her worries into
an allegory about fear and its ability to dominate people's lives.
It's this sort of brooding humanism that distinguishes Ms. Marshall
from her leading contemporaries like Stephen Petronio and Mark
Morris, who favor abstraction and musical interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dances are about people,'' she has often said. ``They're
not about dancers.''
</P>
<P>
   That maxim also helps explain her devotion to pedestrian
movement and emotional complexity, traits already evident in the
tentative embraces of ``Arms,'' her signature duet from 1984. They
reappeared in the cruel slaps and repentant caresses of ``Les
Enfants Terribles,'' a 1996 collaboration with the composer Philip
Glass.
</P>
<P>
   Both works won her Bessies, formally known as New York Dance and
Performance Awards, for outstanding choreographic achievement.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Marshall, who turned 40 this fall, got her start in Hershey,
Pa., where her parents, a behavioral scientist and a co-founder of
the Pennsylvania chapter of the National Organization for Women,
encouraged her training in gymnastics and ballet. After two years
of modern dance at the Juilliard School, she set out on her own,
forming Susan Marshall and Company a few years later.
</P>
<P>
   Over coffee last month near her Upper West Side apartment, Ms.
Marshall described ``The Most Dangerous Room in the House'' as a
psychodrama whose fractured story line and frantic atmosphere allow
many interpretations.
</P>
<P>
   The title came from a study of bathroom hazards, she said, and
is meant to suggest ``domestic everyday fears'' like drowning,
choking and falling. ``It also hints at the unsettling notion that
the home, the place we're supposed to feel most secure, might not
be such a safe haven after all,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   When her troupe performed the piece last summer at the Jacob's
Pillow Dance Festival in Becket, Mass., audiences saw a central
figure, portrayed by the actress Norma Fire, slam into a wall,
crawl under a chair and brace herself against a whirlwind of seven
airborne aggressors. Shards of spoken text gave glimpses into her
subconscious, as she identified perils looming before a child: an
open window, a brimming bathtub, a sharpened knife.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's as though she's unearthing things _ movements, images,
fragments of her life _ and we're left with the question of how to
interpret them,'' Ms. Marshall said.
</P>
<P>
   The identity of the child (sometimes called Jean, a play on
gene) remains a mystery to the end. Similarly, whether the dance
represents the loss of a child itself, the remembrance of loss or
the fear of loss is never revealed.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Dangerous,'' wailing guitar licks and plaintive piano
melodies give shape to some of these uncertainties. David Lang, who
wrote the score, said Ms. Marshall had given him fresh insights
into his own work.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Susan took music I thought I knew inside and out, and she gave
it new emotional life,'' said Lang, a co-founder of the Bang on a
Can All Stars, an experimental music collaborative that will
provide live accompaniment when the troupe performs this week.
</P>
<P>
   Lang singled out a passage he had conceived as ``bittersweet,
beautiful in a naive way.'' In Ms. Marshall's hands, he said, ``It
took on a dark, romantic feel that I never expected.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, she's reluctant to accept full credit. The program for
``Dangerous'' attributes the choreography to ``Susan Marshall in
collaboration with the company.'' Few dance makers work in
isolation, but Ms. Marshall is known for drawing her performers
deep into her creative process, which entails long hours of
improvising and talking about the results.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of jumping-off points; a lot of what-if's that
don't go anywhere,'' said Mark DeChiazza, who joined the troupe in
1993. ``But Sue can surprise you the way she takes something from
the day before and adds on to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Marshall tried to resist editing with a heavy hand, at least
early on, because she wanted the form to reflect the content. ``I
wanted this piece to be more chaotic,'' she said. ``I wanted to
exert less control and see where that would take the dance.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, she got more disorder than she bargained for.
Susan Blankensop, who had been cast as the central figure, decided
to leave the troupe last year to pursue another career. Changing
tack, Ms. Marshall looked outside the dance world and found Ms.
Fire, 60, an actress who often plays a judge on television's ``Law
and Order.''
</P>
<P>
   The dance was transformed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided that I wouldn't try to look like a dancer, which I
can do,'' Ms. Fire said. ``Instead, let me be a person running
around and never will my toe be pointed.''
</P>
<P>
   With a seasoned actor on hand, Ms. Marshall saw a chance to make
more of the text being written by her husband, Christopher Renino,
a novelist and school teacher. Instead of clarifying the narrative,
his prose adds a new wrinkle.
</P>
<P>
   One passage begins, ``The knife split the melon and the halves
rocked back and forth, sugaring the air.'' Ms. Fire delivers the
line several times, substituting and reordering a few words each
time. Changing by degrees, it becomes, ``My husband cut the melon,
rocking me back and forth, sweetening the air with his seeds.''
</P>
<P>
   More than a word game, it's a window on Ms. Marshall's
choreography. Like Renino, she generates lean, evocative images and
strings them together in different combinations to yield subtle
shades of meaning.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Marshall sees ``The Most Dangerous Room in the House'' as a
metaphor for finding a coherent story of who we are. ``Our inner
lives are a big mush,'' she said. ``It's up to us to figure out
what to make of all these residual experiences, thoughts, and
fears.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite her dark palette, Ms. Marshall maintained that she is
neither a worrywart nor a pessimist. ``The flip side to all these
fears is that there are completely fulfilling moments in our lives
that are just as random,'' she said before heading home to Nicholas
and his father. ``They can happen to you at any moment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
