<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 10:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2677 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FIBERGLASS-ART-2TAKES     12-10 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIBERGLASS-ART-2TAKES-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN AN ERA OF HUMANOID ART, A FORERUNNER FINDS A PLACE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 13) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Elizabeth Hayt is an art historian and critic.  
 By ELIZABETH HAYT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Beginning in the late 1960s and continuing to his death in 1996,
Duane Hanson sought to create in fiberglass and resin a catalogue
of American social types _ the tourist, the waitress, the cowboy.
Shamelessly realistic and reeking of pathos, Hanson's life-size
figures, their verisimilitude enhanced by props suggesting a
narrative, were widely popular. But they never received critical
acclaim.
</P>
<P>
   To some, his sculptures seemed gimmicky, even hokey. Like a blip
in the history of modern art, Hanson's renditions of weary, forlorn
middle Americans might easily have been forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   But today, Hanson's figures no longer seem anachronistic or
insignificant. In view of the current rage for hyper-realistic
figuration among 90s artists, particularly the widespread use of
mannequins, Hanson's men, women and children _ so lifelike they
have actually been mistaken for real people _ seem right up to
date.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, a retrospecitive of his work, ``Duane Hanson: A Survey
of His Work From the 1930s to the 90s,'' opens on Thursday at the
Whitney Museum of American Art.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always felt Duane Hanson is a love that dare not speak
its name,'' said Robert Rosenblum, a professor of fine arts at New
York University who included the artist in his list of ``the best
of 1997'' for Artforum. ``He's been rediscovered by serious people.
He's the father of virtual reality, humanoids, or substitute
humans. Without him, everyone from Robert Gober, Charlie Ray and
Vanessa Beecroft would be unthinkable.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenblum said that Hanson's figures also touched on the issues
of cloning and what it meant to be human today. ``Reality is just a
facsimile now,'' he said. ``When it gets down to human beings, it's
creepy and topical. Duane Hanson is in tune with much of the art of
the last decade.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a movement _ first identified as mannequin art by the
artist Mike Kelley in ``The Uncanny,'' a 1993 show he organized _
has been gaining momentum in the 90s. Mannequins made their debut
in Eugene Atget's pre-World War I photographs of store windows,
reappearing in later Surrealist work like Hans Bellmer's dolls.
</P>
<P>
   A resurgence of mannequins, as well as figures cast from life,
occurred in the 60s in the sculptural tableaux of George Segal,
Edward Kienholz, John de Andrea, Yayoi Kusama and, of course,
Hanson.
</P>
<P>
   In the 70s, Dennis Oppenheim continued the tradition, and in the
late 80s, Laurie Simmons's photographs of female mannequin legs
perched atop objects like a house, a camera or an hourglass
provided feminist commentary on the objectification and
domestication of women. At the same time, Cindy Sherman's use of
medical prosthetics in her photographs took the theme to a
grotesque extreme.
</P>
<P>
   But today, more artists than ever are relying on artificial
human surrogates, whether actual mannequins or trompe l'oeil
figural sculptures, to question what is ultimately real.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the fake body is a permanent body at a time when real
bodies seem enormously fragile,'' said Robert Storr, a curator in
the department of painting and sculpture at the Museum of Modern
Art, explaining why mannequins and similarly life-like
representations are proliferating. ``With the AIDS crisis, along
with a culture that is so focused on youth, prosperity and infinite
horizons, the reminder that people age and die is a cold shower. A
lot of work about the body has to do with that.''
</P>
<P>
   British artists seem particularly drawn to mannequin-style
figures as a way to memorialize human beings. In ``Sensation,'' a
show at the Royal Academy of Arts in London last year, Ron Mueck,
40, created a stir with ``Dead Dad,'' (1996), a three-foot
reproduction of his father's naked corpse presented on a low
plinth.
</P>
<P>
   Made from a clay model cast in silicone, the extraordinarily
detailed figure, complete with individual strands of synthetic
hair, was meant to commemorate the passing of Mueck's father, who
died of cancer that year. But with its elegiac tone and diminutive
scale, the work also suggests the physical vulnerability and loss
of dignity that accompany the body's passage from life to death.
</P>
<P>
   On a more mischevious note, two British artists, Dinos Chapman,
32, and his brother, Jake, 36, delight in rendering a freaky
alternative to mortality. In their 1997 installation, ``Six Feet
Under,'' at the Gagosian Gallery in SoHo, they transformed the
space into a massive grave, creating an underworld filled with
``zygotic'' figures, as the artists call their fiberglass and resin
sculptures.
</P>
<P>
   Looking as if they have been struck with a particularly virulent
strain of erotomania, these androgynous, child-size mutants,
wearing only sneakers and wigs, sprout extra limbs and heads, as
well as genitals in unlikely places _ phalluses project from
orifices, navels and noses.
</P>
<P>
   A vision of sex and science gone awry, the work is a spoof of a
future of bio-engineered bodies that can be replicated but that
cannot reproduce. ``Our work is cyber-erotica,'' said Jake Chapman.
``The human body is obsolete. We take pleasure in that.''
</P>
<P>
   Storr finds many connotations in such mannequin art. ``The
mannequin is under the complete control of the person looking at
it, but it can never offer a response,'' he said. ``It cannot
interact. It's morbid eroticism or sci-fi eroticism, a kind of J.G.
Ballard eroticism.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   This sort of virtual eroticism surrounds Charles Ray's mannequin
sculptures. A retrospective of his work is on view at the Los
Angeles Museum of Contemporary Art through March 14. In 1990, Ray,
now 45, created ``Male Mannequin,'' one of his first works to
incorporate a standard department store dummy.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the figure's Ken-doll-like features, it is startling.
The mannequin's perfected physique is thrown off kilter by its
all-too-real looking genitals _ cast from Ray's body _ that the
artist has added.
</P>
<P>
   Paul McCarthy, 53, conjures a different kind of virtual reality
with his mechanized mannequin installations that he first began in
the mid-80s. His fabricated realities have all the imaginative fun
of a Disney theme park but none of its innocence. In ``Yaa-Hoo
Town,'' his 1996 installation at Luhring Augustine Gallery, he
created an X-rated version of the Wild West with robotic cowboys
and bar maids, some with oversize human heads, others with animal
faces, all are made of fiberglass and resin.
</P>
<P>
   They booze it up, masturbate and sodomize one another in a
makeshift saloon and bunk house, accompanied by the sounds of
ragtime music, distant gunshots and a train whistle. By
constructing his installation with deliberate shoddiness, allowing
the mechanics and motors of the moving figures to remain visible
and painting the forms bright, cartoon colors, McCarthy slyly mocks
the seamlessness of places like Disneyland and Hollywood that are
his inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, with Mickey Mouse in mind, Maurizio Cattelan, 38, an
Italian artist who lives in New York, staged a performance at the
Museum of Modern Art featuring a living mannequin dressed as
Picasso. An actor wearing a giant, comic book-style head of the
artist greeted visitors entering the museum. Recasting Picasso as a
Magic Kingdom idol, Cattelan's performance toyed with the exchange
between fine art and popular culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not poking fun at Picasso,'' said Laura Hoptman,
assistant curator at the Modern, who organized the performance.
``It's poking at the face in the Microsoft ads.'' Whereas Cattelan
creates a hybrid of man and mannequin, Vanessa Beecroft, 29,
another Italian-born artist who lives in New York, inverts the
relationship altogether, taking mannequin art one step further.
</P>
<P>
   If store dummies function as substitutes for humans, Ms.
Beecroft challenges humans to act like mannequins in her
performance art.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1998, she staged ``Show'' at the Guggenheim Museum,
presenting 20 statuesque female models, five of whom were nude save
for ruby red rhinestone stilettos. The rest, similarly shod, wore
crimson string bikinis. The models also wore body make-up, which
gave their skin an artificial, idealized appearance. The women,
arranged in a loose grid formation in the rotunda of the museum,
stood in place for three hours, occasionally stretching, shifting
legs or sitting down.
</P>
<P>
   ``One does a double take entering one of Vanessa's
performances,'' said Jeffrey Deitch, her dealer. ``It's unclear
whether you're looking at artificial mannequins or real people.
It's a strong, unique vision about identity in the contemporary
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Fusing the classical ideal of beauty with the glamour and
spectacle of a fashion show, Ms. Beecroft uses
models-cum-mannequins as a girl-power attempt to reclaim and
perhaps glorify the mindless superficiality associated with
representations of femininity today.
</P>
<P>
   With so many contemporary artists using mannequins and similarly
lifelike figures to question the distinction between artifice and
reality, Hanson's sculptures presage much recent art. Not that
Hanson saw himself as a forerunner of art to come. And today's
artists are certainly not quick to point to him as a source. But by
recognizing aspects of his work that have hitherto gone unnoticed,
contemporary artists inadvertently establish a lineage to him. In
addition, they also identify a pre-occupation of late-20th-century
art: virtual reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hanson carries the spectacle of reality further than
mannequins,'' said McCarthy, the artist. ``I'm kind of fooled by
his things. You walk up to them in a room slowly. You almost
believe their realism. It has to do with the inability to
distinguish between reality and a reflection of reality. They're
hyper-real. That's what makes them interesting today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-98 1049EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
