<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON BASKETBALL TEAM FAILING `BENDER TEST' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Washington Huskies have lost three straight
basketball games, something that has not happened around here since
1994-95. They are 4-3. They are doomed to drop out of the Top 25.
</P>
<P>
   From No. 14 to No. 16 to No. 22 to off the radar screen, the
Huskies' stature has slid faster than firefighters down a greased
pole.
</P>
<P>
   And the icing on the cake? Wednesday, the Dawgs came limping
back to Montlake from that little city by the river, Spokane, where
the mighty Gonzaga Bulldogs sank their canines deep into the necks
of the Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, Gonzaga is the ancestral home of John Stockton, which
gives it good hard-court karma. And the Bulldogs' coach, Dan
Monson, will one day get his shot at a Pac-10 job, so there is no
embarrassment in losing to a coach and program hellbent on putting
themselves squarely, rightfully, on the college-basketball map.
</P>
<P>
   Still, is that blood on the tracks of the so recently darling
Huskies?
</P>
<P>
   With college basketball enjoying an unprecedented run as top dog
in the NBA-less land of America, it makes the Huskies' drop off the
Billboard chart a much greater disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   The explosive Deon Luton was 1-for-9 against Gonzaga on the
heels of a serious Houdini act against UConn in the Great Eight
Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Thalo Green has looked like a shadow of the stalwart forward who
helped drive the Huskies to their NCAA splendor last March.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Dickau and Senque Carey are trying hard to be Top 25-caliber
point guards, but the Huskies are showing their youth in that
most-critical position. Without the defensively proficient Donald
Watts (ankle sprain) the Huskies lacked so much identity, Gonzaga
not only creamed the Dawgs but also stole their drivers' licenses.
</P>
<P>
   Todd MacCulloch's soft hands and 28 points could not cover the
multitude of other breakdowns that apparently prompted Husky coach
Bob Bender to vigorously exercise his vocal chords in the postgame
locker room.
</P>
<P>
   If not for one very specific, very good reason _ Bender _
college basketball enthusiasts around here would have no choice but
to figure the Huskies are hemorrhaging.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it was Bender _ in whom we all trust _ who decreed that this
sort of trial by fire was the sort of test his team needed.
</P>
<P>
   From the Big Island Tournament victory in Hawaii to an
all-nighter flight to Chicago to gritty little pit stops in Boise
and Spokane, Bender has tried to test his team the way Patton once
tested his Army troops.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem with that test is it might have provided the
very answer we all suspected about the Huskies: They truly are not
that resilient. They might have ridden a hot streak in last
spring's Sweet 16 that elevated expectations beyond the their level
of competitive will and, to some degree, talent.
</P>
<P>
   Not that we want to hammer the poor fellas, who so recently
spoke of their Pac-10 championship aspirations. That's why they
have Bender.
</P>
<P>
   The charismatic, demanding and dynamic coach was, we have to
guess, prepared to take whatever lumps came out of the six-game,
11-day ``Road Warrior'' experiment. If the Huskies are to have a
Top 25 reputation, it's better to get it parboiled early.
</P>
<P>
   That is the trend in college basketball these days. And this
season, there seems to have been an extra premium placed on
big-game preseason match-ups. We have been fed such a rich and
steady diet of great games this autumn, we are all destined to be
fattened like a Christmas goose before the conference schedules
even begin in January.
</P>
<P>
   Duke-Cincinnati. Stanford-Maryland. Carolina-Stanford.
UConn-Michigan State. UCLA-Oklahoma State. Kansas-Iowa.
Indiana-Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   The list of great games reads like a who's who in college
basketball, thanks largely to the growing number of big-money TV
tournaments and the rabid desire by schools to solidify their
ever-important power rankings.
</P>
<P>
   But there are pitfalls for teams taking on too much, too soon,
especially if its confidence emerges like something pushed through
a wood chipper.
</P>
<P>
   Some of us around here are still prepared to settle in for a
long, glorious winter of Washington games that really, really
matter. And at this point, the Huskies can take some solace in what
other Top 25 teams have done this November and December.
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen of the Top 25 teams have already lost this season. It
proves parity lives among the senior-depleted ranks of college
hoops. It shows that undefeated streaks produced last season by
Stanford and Utah were flukes.
</P>
<P>
   Still, while Duke has already lost to the Bearcats, while mighty
North Carolina got bounced by the College of Charleston, and while
Stanford is already 0-2 against the ACC, the Huskies' three-game
slide is different.
</P>
<P>
   Washington is still in a position where it must build upon its
success of last March. That is what a program on the upswing must
accomplish, yet so far, the preseason ``Bender Test'' has revealed
the Dawgs are not keeping up with the big dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
