<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 11:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2708 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI &LR;      12-10 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALLOWAY TIRES OF LOST AND FOUND TREATMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. _ Joey Galloway is frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   Catching two long touchdown passes in the first quarter of a
game and then having no receptions for the next three quarters will
do that. But Galloway's disenchantment goes beyond what happened in
Sunday's one-point loss to the New York Jets.
</P>
<P>
   That now-you-find-him, now-you-don't scenario was the latest
example of what has been a season-long problem for Galloway and the
Seahawks offense.
</P>
<P>
   When an opponent attempts to defend Galloway with one
cornerback, the Seahawks can't wait to get him the ball. But when
the same burned-and-learned opponent reverts to playing well off
Galloway and using a second player to help cover him, the Seahawks
can't find a way to get him the ball.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened Sunday. That's what has been happening all
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is driving me nuts, and it has been driving me nuts,''
Galloway said Wednesday. ``When I get single coverage, I beat my
man. When I get double coverage, we just tend to go other places.''
</P>
<P>
   Entering Sunday's game against San Diego at the Kingdome _ the
14th game of the season _ the Seahawks continue to wring their
hands about finding ways to get the ball into Galloway's hands.
Just as they have been doing since making him the eighth pick
overall in the 1995 NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to have a plan to get the ball to him, which we
always have a plan to get it to him. But you've got to get it to
him, too,'' coach Dennis Erickson said. ``Sometimes we have, and
sometimes we don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Why not? Who's at fault here?
</P>
<P>
   Jon Kitna tried to shoulder all the blame Wednesday. But this
goes beyond a young quarterback still learning to give his best
receiver time to get open against double coverage. It involved the
play-calling, and Galloway also must accept some of the burden.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start with Galloway.
</P>
<P>
   There is no disputing his talents. Galloway has used his unique
combination of incredible speed, remarkable quickness and deceptive
strength to average 33.1 yards on his 34 career touchdown
receptions. Since the start of the '95 season, only Minnesota's
Cris Carter (49), Green Bay's Antonio Freeman (43) and Atlanta's
Tony Martin (36) have caught more touchdown passes than Galloway.
</P>
<P>
   This season, he is averaging 41.1 yards on eight touchdown
catches, including his 70- and 57-yard scoring plays against the
Jets. But Galloway has just 50 receptions, a pace that will produce
a 61-catch season _ the second-lowest of his career in a season
that started with talk of Galloway becoming a 100-catch receiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's getting the big play, which is what it's all about as far
as that part is concerned,'' Erickson said. ``But we've also got to
get him the ball underneath where he can run with it a little bit,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   That leads to the play-calling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, we work at it,'' offensive coordinator Bob
Bratkowski. ``I carry a list around every week in case (Galloway)
is not getting the ball through the normal process of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the list isn't long enough. At the top is the go route.
Few, if any, receivers in the league can put the go in a go-route
like Galloway. But when the go won't go because of double coverage,
the Seahawks have to use other routes, shorter routes, to get
Galloway open and involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joey's certainly one of the guys you try to take away from
Seattle. But you can only do so much. Sooner or later, he gets
you,'' Chargers coach June Jones said Wednesday. ``You can't do it
the whole game. You've got to keep mixing it. ... But sooner or
later, they can formation you and put you in different things where
you can't get a double on him.''
</P>
<P>
   So why doesn't it happen more often? That's what many, including
Galloway, are wondering.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to call plays that beat those double coverages,'' he
said. ``You've got to take what they give you. At times, when a
defense takes away some things from us, we tend to say, `OK, we'll
try other things.' Instead of saying, `We're going to do what we
do. You give us your best shot and we're still going to do what we
do.'''
</P>
<P>
   Five 10-yard outs or slants are just as effective as a 50-yard
pass. But if that's what the defense is going to give Galloway, the
Seahawks have to be able to take it.
</P>
<P>
   However, it takes more than speed to be effective running slants
across the middle or out patterns in the flat. At 5-foot-11 and 188
pounds, Galloway is not the biggest or most physical receiver
around. He isn't as adept at catching the ball while covered in the
middle of the field as he is at blowing past defenders while
running up the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   Galloway also isn't the most vocal player on the team. When
running back Ricky Watters feels he isn't getting the ball enough,
everyone in the stadium is aware of it. When Galloway feels
slighted, he is more likely to brood silently.
</P>
<P>
   Galloway did confront Erickson after last week's game, and Kitna
went to Galloway Wednesday and told him to be more forceful with
him as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Joey, `I'm just trying to start understanding how to
get you the ball,''' Kitna said. ``Heck, if he's in the third
quarter and he feels like he's not getting the ball, I'd love for
him to come and tell me that.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Kitna, he has been thrust into a difficult situation. If
he knows Galloway is occupying two defenders on one side of the
field, it means Mike Pritchard, James McKnight, tight end Christian
Fauria or Watters will be getting single coverage elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take full responsibility for it,'' said Kitna, who will make
his third start of the season this week. ``I just haven't gotten to
the point yet to understand that, yeah, the defense may be giving
me the hitch over here, but at the same time they could be giving
me a 12-yard curl with Joey. ... It isn't bad to go to the other
guys, but at the same time I have to get the ball to Joey. You get
the ball to No. 84 and he's going to make things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Teams are not going to stop using double coverage on Galloway.
As Erickson put it, ``The problem is, he's got a number on him.
They identify that number and they double him. They can double him
if he's in the stands if they want.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why the Seahawks must make a commitment to getting
Galloway the ball even when he is being dogged by two defensive
backs. And they had better start this week against the Chargers'
No. 1-ranked defense that has not allowed a 100-yard rusher all
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely frustrating,'' Galloway said. ``Especially
because we're not winning. It's another year where it looks like
we'll be heading home for the holidays. With the talent we have
that shouldn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, with the talent Galloway has he should never go three
quarters without catching a pass.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
