<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 11:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2738 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADVxx-     12-10 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADVxx-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARLES DICKENS STILL DRAWS A CROWD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Thursday Dec. 17)  
 By MARY J. LOFTUS   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The celebration of Chistmas was on the decline in England at the
beginning of the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   The singing of carols had nearly disappeared, and because the
holiday traditions combined pagan and Germanic traditions, such as
yule logs and decorating trees, they were criticized by the
Puritans. Also, with the Industrial Revolution, adults and children
alike worked long hours in factories.
</P>
<P>
   It was a grim, gray period, with little time or money for
frivolity.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, however, like a thaw after a heavy frost, signs of
Christmas began to re-emerge. Christmas cards appeared in the
1840s.
</P>
<P>
   And, in December 1843, English author Charles Dickens, a young
man of 31, finished what he called a ``Ghostly little book,''
intended to ``raise the Ghost of an Idea, which shall not put my
readers out of humour with themselves, with each other, with the
season, or with me. May it haunt their houses pleasantly ...''
</P>
<P>
   The first printing of the book sold out, and 2,000 copies were
on reserve before the second printing.
</P>
<P>
   So it is, then, that in December 1998, my 7-year-old and I found
ourselves milling about outside the Alliance Theatre Company of
Atlanta, queuing up for their annual production of ``A Christmas
Carol.''
</P>
<P>
   This multicultural version of the play, which includes gospel
music and a Ghost of Christmas Present with knee-length dreadlocks,
has been a holiday tradition at the Alliance for nine years,
meaning that Dickens can still pack a theater house more than 100
years after his death.
</P>
<P>
   While the characters may reflect a broader community, the period
costumes and dialogue stay true to Dickens' version of the
moralistic tale.
</P>
<P>
   ``This immortal story ... embraces the idea that you can get up
in the morning and start your life newly inspired,'' says Kenny
Leon, artistic director.
</P>
<P>
   The meaning is as clear, and as vital, today as it was in
turn-of-the-century England.
</P>
<P>
   As Adam and I settled into our seats, the lights dimmed to find
a beggar woman singing softly, an a cappella carol. Soon, Scrooge
appears, and his stingy ways become apparent as he limits his
good-hearted clerk Bob Cratchit to one small piece of coal and a
half-day off for Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Adam enjoyed the arrival of the Spirits _ a bouncy, fun-filled
woman-child in a red dress to guide Scrooge through his past; a
bagpipe-toting Rastafarian Spirit of Christmas Present, spreading
good will; and a silent, towering Ghost of Christmas Yet to Come.
(``Answer me one question,'' pleads Scrooge. ``Are these the
shadows of the things that Will be, or are they shadows of things
that May be, only?'')
</P>
<P>
   To my disappointment, a powerful section of the novel never
makes it into theatrical adaptations, probably because of the
practical hardships of showing hundreds of chained and shackled
phantoms floating outside Scrooge's window.
</P>
<P>
   It is a pivotal moment when Scrooge realizes that, ``The misery
with them all was, clearly, that they sought to interfere, for
good, in human matters, and had lost the power for ever.''
</P>
<P>
   But my favorite lines, whether in Dickens' prose or theatrical
dialogue, were in evidence that night as Jacob Marley, dead these
long seven years, tries to convince Scrooge to change his selfish
ways.
</P>
<P>
   These are the thoughts I will carry with me into the holiday
season, the words that echoed within my heart as I left the
theater, holding my son's hand and stepping into the windy Atlanta
night:
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh,'' Marley moans, ``not to know that any man working kindly
in its little sphere, whatever it may be, will find its mortal life
too short for its vast means of usefulness. Not to know that no
space of regret can make amends for one life's opportunities,
misused.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mankind was my business. The common welfare was my business;
charity, mercy, forbearance and benevolence, were, all, my
business. ...''
</P>
<P>
   (Mary J. Loftus writes for the New York Times Regional
Newspapers. She has master's and specialist degrees in marriage and
family counseling.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
