<DOCNO> NYT19981210.0094 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 11:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2756 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PALESTINIAN-CHARTER-$     12-10 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PALESTINIAN-CHARTER-$ADV13 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON TRIP BASED ON PUZZLING CASE OF THE PALESTINIAN CHARTER
 &HT;    With MIDEAST-DEVELOPMENT and PALESTINIAN-BOX
 &HT;    Advance for release Sunday, Dec. 13, but may be used prior to
that.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service(at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAZA CITY, Gaza Strip President Clinton will make a historic
visit here Monday in hopes of witnessing the removal of a major
irritant in the quest for peace in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   He is coming to see that leaders of the Palestine Liberation
Organization reaffirm a letter that Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat wrote to Clinton in January. The letter outlines which
portions of the Palestine National Charter, the 30-year-old mission
statement of the PLO, have been rescinded.
</P>
<P>
   The charter debate is one of the most stubborn snags in the
troubled five-year-old Oslo peace process that officially began
with the September 1993 signing of accords by Arafat and then
Israeli leader Yitzhak Rabin at the White House. The charter
controversy is one of the issues that has one-time allies of
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu now threatening to topple
his government.
</P>
<P>
   Oslo outlines a plan for Israeli troop withdrawals from parts of
the Gaza Strip and the West Bank, areas Israeli captured in the
Middle East War. In return, the PLO was supposed to end hostilities
against Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Steeped in the revolutionary language of the 1960s, the 6-page
charter calls repeatedly for war against Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Armed struggle is the only way to liberate Palestine,'' it
states, ``. . . the Arab Palestinian people, expressing themselves
by the armed Palestinian revolution, reject all solutions which are
substitutes for the total liberation of Palestine.''
</P>
<P>
   The Palestine National Council met in April, 1996, to rescind
parts of the charter.
</P>
<P>
   American and Israeli officials applauded the move. But the
Palestinians never issued a new charter with the changes _ a move
American officials say is not required anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Left wing Israelis who support the peace process say progress
was made, but acknowledge that the revision was neither clear or
complete. The Israeli government changed in 1996 and the new
government headed by Netanyahu, and fueled by its right wing,
demanded clarification.
</P>
<P>
   They have asserted that Arafat's January letter to Clinton was
not enough.
</P>
<P>
   In talks Clinton mediated last October at the Wye River
Plantation in Maryland, an effort at restarting the stalled Oslo
process, the Israelis and Palestinians agreed to have Clinton come
to the Middle East to serve as a high-profile witness while the PLO
meets to ``reaffirm'' Arafat's letter. In going to Gaza Monday,
Clinton will become the first U.S. president to visit a
Palestinian-controlled area.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian political analyst Ghassan Khatib said the charter
has little influence over modern Palestinian thought. But, he said
Arafat has held back the revision because it was a bargaining chip.
</P>
<P>
   He may have cashed it in for the prestige of the Clinton visit.
</P>
<P>
   But, whatever will be done in Gaza could anger hard-liners on
both sides. Israelis are angry that Wye only requires a vague move
to ``reaffirm'' the letter, not a vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are required to give these people land and authority and
everything similar to a state without them changing their goal of
destroying us? It looks crazy to me,'' said Michael Kleiner, a
member of the Israeli parliament.
</P>
<P>
   He said Clinton should stay away.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, many PLO members are outraged at having to repeat,
upon Israeli demands, a revision they say they have made.
</P>
<P>
   Mahmoud Ajrami, a leader of the PLO faction known as the
Democratic Front for the Liberation of Palestine, is organizing a
boycott of the meeting. He believes that both Israel and the
Palestinians should exist as states, but does not want to change
the charter this way.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to lead to so many other concessions,'' he said.
Why, he asks, should he officially recognize the Israeli state
while Israelis oppose the formation of a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
