<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981210.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 11:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2762 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-DUCHESS-1000&AMP;     12-10 1595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-DUCHESS-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SILENT DUCHESS
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Dacia Maraini. Translated by Dick Kitto and Elspeth
Spottiswood.
</P>
<P>
   261 pp. New York: The Feminist Press. $19.95. &QL; 
 &UR; -------- &QL; 
 &UR; THE SILENCE &QL; 
 &UR; BY KATHRYN HARRISON &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A little girl, 7 years old, deaf and incapable of speech,
accompanies her father, a Sicilian duke, to witness the execution
of a young criminal, a boy of 13. Because of their social position,
these two aristocrats are permitted to eavesdrop on the child's
confession in his sordid underground prison, then given a ringside
seat at his hanging.
</P>
<P>
   The violence of this spectacle is such that Duke Signoretto
Ucria hopes it will both unstop his daughter's ears and ``unstick
her lips.'' But Marianna Ucria is possessed of an imperturbable
calm. ``For living visitors like Dante,'' she thinks as she watches
the prisoners, ``hell can even be beautiful to look at'' -- a
surpassingly literate and philosophical assessment from such a
young girl.
</P>
<P>
   Thus are we introduced to the early-18th-century heroine of
Dacia Maraini's novel, joining Marianna's father in ``knocking at
the door of her silence.''
</P>
<P>
   What lies behind that door, and who has pushed it shut? We can
ask these questions of stories other than the one Maraini tells in
``The Silent Duchess,'' for we are well acquainted with heroines --
and the occasional hero -- who cannot or will not speak. From the
Greek tale of Philomela to Hans Christian Andersen's Little Mermaid
to Maya Angelou in ``I Know Why the Caged Bird Sings,'' from Ellen
James in John Irving's novel ``The World According to Garp'' to
Estha in ``The God of Small Things,'' by Arundhati Roy, the list
goes on. Can we guess what words, what accusations, their silence
holds? All too often, the clues point to sexual trauma -- in this
case, a childhood rape.
</P>
<P>
   At 13, Marianna Ucria is given in marriage, against her will, to
her mother's older brother (and her father's cousin), Duke Pietro
Ucria. The reason is a simple one, at least as her mother explains
it. ``Uncle Pietro will take you for nothing because he loves
you,'' thus sparing her parents a dowry they can't afford. This
conversation is carried out by means of pen and paper, as are all
of Marianna's communications. Soon she is married to ``that sad,
grumpy man, always dressed in red and known in the family as 'the
prawn.' '' Marianna refers to her cold and peculiar spouse as
``uncle husband.'' During the course of their 27-year marriage, she
bears him five children and presides over his large household. The
duchess herself is considered eccentric, but this has less to do
with her silence than with her devotion to reading.
</P>
<P>
   At 40, Marianna is widowed. After the funeral, she accompanies
uncle husband's corpse to its interment in the catacombs; having
remained innocent of the pleasures of the bedroom, she scrutinizes
the ``fleeting curve'' of his lips, his ``jutting cheekbones,'' as
she tries one last time ``to fathom the secret of his body.'' Soon
thereafter, Marianna takes a young lover, but the discovery of
physical passion cannot tempt her from the life of the mind, from
her addiction to silent, sated hours in her library. As old age
approaches, she spurns the proposal of a kind admirer, a man who
values her intelligence. Escorted by her maid, Marianna sets out to
see what she can of the world. Without giving away the identity of
the man who raped her -- or its bearing on the duchess's betrothal
-- one can set out these summary events of her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's strange how well she's worn,'' her profligate brother,
Abbot Carlo, notes: ``Slim as when she was 20, a fresh, clear
complexion. . . . This dumb sister still has the face of a young
girl. . . . What if it were her dumbness that has preserved her
from the ruins of growing old?'' Dumbness? ``Holiness'' might be a
more fitting word, suggesting the quality of being set apart.
Perhaps it is poetic justice that Carlo has been disfigured by
appetite, lust, cruelty. In contrast, Marianna bears no superficial
trace of sin or suffering. In her innocence, she looks like an
angel -- and in fact she functions as a particular kind of
celestial being, the recording angel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Silent Duchess'' is a leisurely, discursive case history
of an early violation, a narrative that segues (painlessly, without
being polemical) into a treatise on the nature of the writer,
especially the female writer. Marianna's silence is both ``dense
and transparent.'' She sees it as ``both mother and sister'' and
prays to the ``Holy Mother of all silence.'' For Marianna, and by
extension all women, Maraini suggests that creativity implies a
certain defection, a refusal to participate in a forum dominated by
male voices -- voices that exploit, that discount the importance of
the domestic female world, that misrepresent what it is to be a
woman.
</P>
<P>
   Silence does not diminish the duchess; rather, it dignifies her.
For Marianna, separation allows perspective; the abandonment (not
the impairment) of one faculty sharpens the others; deafness even
enhances her perceptions. Because she is spared the chaos and
distraction of noise, Marianna finds that she can read people's
thoughts. Her past violation guarantees her vigilance; she will
always be hyper-alert to her surroundings. Her sense of smell, for
example, is so keen that passages of ``The Silent Duchess'' will
remind readers of another novel set in the same pungent century,
Patrick Suskind's ``Perfume'':
</P>
<P>
   ``Now she has lowered her eyelids so as to rest her eyes for a
while, and her nostrils have begun to draw in the air, recognizing
the smells and meticulously noting them in her mind: the
overpowering scent of lettuce water that impregnates her father's
waistcoat, below that the scent of rice powder mingled with the
grease on the seats, the sourness of crushed lice, the smarting
from the dust on the road that blows through the joints of the
doors, as well as the faint aroma of mint that floats in from the
fields of the Villa Palagonia.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-DUCHESS-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: Villa Palagonia.'') &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Recognizing'' and ``meticulously noting.'' This entire novel
could be described in such terms, filled as it is with observations
that are rich almost to the point of cloying. It's a trick for
historical fiction to avoid awkward pileups of costuming and props.
Maraini, a playwright and essayist who is one of Italy's most
prominent writers, is also a seasoned and elegant novelist. She's
not afraid of excess -- and why should she be? It's entirely under
her control. Her intelligent heroine, well read to the point of
heresy (she imports and eagerly consumes books by philosophers who
comment on the nature of reality, who challenge the vision of the
church and, by implication, the patriarchal rankings of society),
is an apparatus intricately calibrated for perception, for
understanding, for revealing.
</P>
<P>
   What, then, is the sort of world that the duchess describes on
the tablet hung around her neck, in the letters she sends to her
daughters, in the thoughts she shares with the reader? It's
splendid and squalid and violent, a place where women are at once
petted and despised -- a place that seems alive for the reader,
both then and now. But historical fiction is not, of course,
history. Despite its links to Maraini's own family's Sicilian
roots, ``The Silent Duchess'' isn't biography exhumed; instead, it
is fantasy projected onto the usable screen of the past.
</P>
<P>
   IN her afterword, the literary scholar Anna Camaiti Hostert
suggests that Maraini chose to set her story in 18th-century Sicily
because it was dominated by a peculiarly ``arrogant and
hypocritical aristocracy, remarkable . . . in the cruelty of its
oppression of both the poor and women.'' The afterword provides a
useful, if academic, context for the work of a writer who remains
largely unknown to Americans. In her more than 50 books, Maraini's
attention, Hostert tells us, ``has always been concentrated on
women's enforced silence in society as well as in literature, and
on the alternative ways in which a female voice can manifest
itself.'' If this sounds ponderous, the novel itself is anything
but.
</P>
<P>
   As translated by Dick Kitto and Elspeth Spottiswood, ``The
Silent Duchess'' is a story of grace and endurance, not mere
survival. What's more, it acquires a slyly suspenseful quality as
the somewhat pedestrian puzzle of the rapist's identity is
superseded by the more complex tension and mystery of Marianna's
silence itself. What will cure this case of ``hysterical'' -- in
other words, female -- deafness and muteness? There are passages
the reader dreads, afraid to be returned with the duchess to the
spoken word, to the implicit capitulation that would be signaled if
she deigned to talk. Might this happen at the death of uncle
husband? At Marianna's discovery of physical passion, when she
redeems what the rapist stole? When she at last learns (that is to
say, remembers and acknowledges) who raped her?
</P>
<P>
   Any of these would be the manipulations of a lesser writer. The
final and greatest satisfaction of Maraini's novel is that the
duchess remains triumphantly silent.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Kathryn Harrison's most recent books are a novel, ``Poison,''
and a memoir, ``The Kiss.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
