<HEADER>
A2771 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-CAREFULLY-NYT     12-10 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-CAREFULLY-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 OPEN ME CAREFULLY
<TEXT>
<P>
   Emily Dickinson's Intimate Letters to Susan Huntington
Dickinson.
</P>
<P>
   Edited by Ellen Louise Hart and Martha Nell Smith.
</P>
<P>
   323 pp. Ashfield, Mass.: Paris Press. Paper, $19.95.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; TWO BELLES OF AMHERST
</P>
<P>
   BY RENEE TURSI
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   At some point during the late 1870's Emily Dickinson wrote the
following lines to her sister-in-law, Susan Huntington Dickinson:
``Susan knows /
</P>
<P>
   she is a Siren -- /
</P>
<P>
   and that at a /
</P>
<P>
   word from her, /
</P>
<P>
   Emily would /
</P>
<P>
   forfeit Righteousness -- .''
</P>
<P>
   Dickinson's complex relationship with Susan, the wife of her
brother, Austin, remains a knotty one for biographers. Local lore
has handed down a tale of two young impassioned friends who, while
eventually living only ``a hedge away'' from each other on Main
Street in Amherst, Mass., went on to have a 15-year falling-out.
Rumors that Susan was a ruthless social snubber who had wronged
Emily may be problematic, given that their source is Mabel Loomis
Todd, with whom Austin carried on a highly public, lasting affair.
</P>
<P>
   Possibly no more credible is Martha Dickinson Bianchi, Susan and
Austin's daughter, who insisted that the affection between her
much-maligned mother and ``Aunt Emily'' never waned. After all, it
was Susan who prepared the poet's body for burial and wrote her
obituary. At the very least, most scholars agree that Susan was a
force to be reckoned with.
</P>
<P>
   Dickinson's surviving letters to Susan, which began ardently a
few years before Susan's marriage and continued almost until the
poet's death in 1886, outnumber her letters to anyone else. After
an examination of these cryptic messages, Ellen Louise Hart and
Martha Nell Smith have emerged up in arms for Susan. In compiling
``Open Me Carefully'' (which includes more than 20 poems and one
letter not previously connected to Susan), they aim to show that
the women enjoyed a long, close relationship, one whose workaday
exchange of ``letter-poems'' (Susan's term) contributed to ``the
texture of their daily life.'' Even more urgent, however, is their
intent to champion Susan as Dickinson's ``primary reader'' -- the
person they believe exerted the most significant, sustaining
influence on Dickinson's poetic and erotic sensibility.
</P>
<P>
   This claim is probably a stretch, considering Dickinson's rich
correspondence with intellectuals like Thomas Wentworth Higginson
and Samuel Bowles. Nonetheless, Susan not only seems to elicit some
of Dickinson's most exquisite phrasings but also a free and mature
expression of desire. Moreover, it was Susan who recognized that
Dickinson's early poems deserved to be published, unlike both
Higginson and Bowles.
</P>
<P>
   While few of Susan's replies exist, her response to a version of
Dickinson's poem ``Safe in Their Alabaster Chambers'' shows her to
be an astute reader. She observes that the second verse ``does not
go with the ghostly shimmer of the first verse'' -- a critique that
evoked not only a new stanza from Dickinson but also a letter-poem,
apparently in gratitude, that reads: ``Your praise is good -- /
</P>
<P>
   to me -- because I know /
</P>
<P>
   it knows -- and suppose -- /
</P>
<P>
   it means --.''
</P>
<P>
   As Dickinson's biographer Richard Sewall has commented, the
poet's publication history might have been vastly different if her
audience ``had all been Sues.'' Dickinson herself, near the end of
her life, wrote to Susan: ``With the Exception of Shakespeare, you
have told me of more knowledge than any one living -- To say that
sincerely is strange praise --.''
</P>
<P>
   Strange, perhaps. At the age of 20, Dickinson longs to hold her
friend ``in my arms.'' A few years later Susan is told she can ``go
or stay'' because ``we differ often lately, and this must be the
last.'' And when both women had reached their 40s, Dickinson wrote:
``Sue -- to be /
</P>
<P>
   lovely as you /
</P>
<P>
   is a touching /
</P>
<P>
   Contest, though /
</P>
<P>
   like the Siege /
</P>
<P>
   of Eden, impracticable, /
</P>
<P>
   Eden never /capitulates --.''
</P>
<P>
   In her contemplation of Susan, Dickinson mused: ``What depths /
</P>
<P>
   of Domingo /
</P>
<P>
   in that torrid /
</P>
<P>
   Spirit!'' and, using phrases that may neatly compress the
enigmatic quality of their bond, writes: ``In a Life that /
</P>
<P>
   stopped guessing, /
</P>
<P>
   you and I should /
</P>
<P>
   not feel at home.''
</P>
<P>
   With spare commentary, Smith, who teaches English at the
University of Maryland, College Park, and Hart, who teaches writing
and literature at the University of California, Santa Cruz, wisely
let these letters speak for themselves. Most important, unlike
previous editors who altered line breaks to fit their sense of what
is poetry or prose, Hart and Smith offer faithful reproductions of
the letters' genre-defying form as the words unravel spectacularly
down the original page. All the better to appreciate, in a fresh
and overdue context, that poetic voice we have come to know --
iridescent, puzzling, explosive.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Renee Tursi is writing a book on American literary modernism and
habit.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
