<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 11:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2773 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-FRAN-NYTSF     12-10 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-FRAN-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 FINDING FRAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   History and Memory in the Lives of Two Women.
</P>
<P>
   By Lois W. Banner.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 243 pp. New York: Columbia Press. $24.95.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; WORLDS APART
</P>
<P>
   BY GERALDINE BROOKS
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Girls' friendships haven't been well served by either literature
or popular culture. There's no Huck and Jim paradigm; with the
exception of ``Thelma and Louise,'' no notable buddy movies.
Instead, female friendships have mostly been portrayed as perilous
alliances, destined to be undone by sexual rivalry, cattiness,
witchcraft or PMS.
</P>
<P>
   So it's a relief to meet Lois and Fran, inseparable high school
friends in 1950's suburban Los Angeles. Smart, artistic and
athletic at a time when girls were supposed to be watchers, not
doers, they dreamed of adventuring together someday in New York.
Fran would paint, Lois would sing and any brilliant future might be
possible.
</P>
<P>
   But then the two lost touch and years passed. Lois W. Banner
became a feminist historian and a professor at the University of
Southern California. Fran converted to Islam and became Noura,
living behind the veil in the closed Saudi Arabian city of Mecca
before settling with her family in Egypt. Banner, who has
specialized in retrieving women's forgotten histories, decided to
find her own lost friend and write the narrative of their lives,
together and apart.
</P>
<P>
   The result is part memoir, part social history and only partly
successful. I wish Banner had decided to write a story rather than
conduct a study. Instead, she tries to do both. When she allows
herself to be a storyteller, the prose unfolds with affecting
spontaneity. But then she seems suddenly to remember that she's a
professor and starts studding the text with analysis delivered in
language-withering academese.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finding Fran'' is at its best when Banner writes about her
not-always-happy childhood. Her extended family lived in one of the
grandest mansions in the suburb of Inglewood, not because they were
rich but because it was the only house big enough to hold them.
Into an imposing Gothic pile with an Italian marble fireplace and
velvet-embossed wallpaper moved Lois and her three siblings, her
parents, one set of grandparents, a great-grandmother, an uncle and
a threadbare collection of Salvation Army furnishings. Her
description of this setting and its characters is clear-eyed and
convincingly complex, as is her evocation of the depressingly low
expectations for the girls at her suburban high.
</P>
<P>
   But there are two life stories in this book, and while Banner's
is the better told, it isn't the better tale. It is her friend Fran
who has led the more unusual life: fleeing suburbia to join a
famous commune, Lama, on a mountain in New Mexico; then shaking the
place to its foundations by leaving her husband and running off
with one of the community's founders; finally, plunging into the
rigors of a Muslim life that included three years studying in Mecca
-- a city closed to nonbelievers in which few American women have
ever lived.
</P>
<P>
   This is rich material, but Banner approaches it too tentatively.
She fails to delve into Fran's acceptance of Saudi Arabia's
restrictions on women. She hints at the way these restrictions have
created a parallel, separatist female world, but offers
frustratingly few details of Fran's life within it. Likewise,
Fran's current life in Alexandria, Egypt, is barely sketched.
</P>
<P>
   For an academic, Banner is also oddly uncritical of sources like
Jehan Sadat's self-serving autobiography, and occasionally careless
with facts. For example, describing Fran's formative sojourn among
Palestinians in Jerusalem, she writes: ``In the mid-1970's, Muslims
still predominated in Jerusalem; Jews migrating there weren't yet
in the majority. It was still a city of domes and minarets.'' But
in Jerusalem's modern history Jews have been more than half the
population since 1860; by 1967 the city was 75 percent Jewish, and
a considerable portion of the remaining minority was Christian.
</P>
<P>
   What Banner achieves in this book is an insightful portrait of
her own family and her experiences in post-World War II America.
She has found herself. Fran, alas, remains elusive.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Geraldine Brooks is the author of ``Foreign Correspondence'' and
``Nine Parts of Desire: The Hidden World of Islamic Women.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
