<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-FEUD-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 BLOOD FEUD
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Annabel Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   195 pp. Knoxville:
</P>
<P>
   The University of Tennessee Press. $24.95.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; BODY COUNT
</P>
<P>
   BY ANN HARLEMAN
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The title of Annabel Thomas' first novel echoes the narrative's
tone and rhythm -- flat-footed, stark, terse -- and also serves as
a warning. Readers who balk at destruction, mutilation and death
should exercise caution before proceeding. By the time it ends,
``Blood Feud'' is littered with more corpses than ``Titus
Andronicus.''
</P>
<P>
   We hear this grim tale from a winsome, tough-and-tender
13-year-old girl. The scion of one of two feuding families in the
Yamoden Valley of southeastern Ohio, Winnie Clemmer wants to tell
not only the story of the feud -- its origins and culmination --
but the story of her love for Dave Kilkinney, a 15-year-old member
of the other family. ``Here we hang,'' she says, ``like bugs in
amber. Scarcely one among us has a notion how to look back nor an
idea how to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   As it unfolds, ``Blood Feud'' offers the expected ingredients of
a story set in Appalachia during the late 1930's: a coal miners'
strike, a tragic and fatal accident at the mine, incendiary family
rivalries. The challenge that Thomas (the author of two collections
of short stories) sets herself in this novel is to make the
expected surprising, to make the familiar -- or, at any rate, the
cliched -- seem unusual. Does she succeed? Only intermittently.
</P>
<P>
   The characters in ``Blood Feud'' include the ``good'' patriarch,
John Kilkinney, a font of apparently endless wisdom; the ``evil''
patriarch, Cap Clemmer, father of Winnie; Licorice Mary, Dave's mad
mother, who roams the woods; Winnie's cigar-smoking Aunt Charlotte;
Fergus Kilkinney, the bad seed; and Joella Kilkinney, a whore with
a heart of, if not gold, at least stainless steel.
</P>
<P>
   Heroes and villains. It's clear from the outset which is which,
and no one changes his or her stripes as the novel progresses. What
saves these characters from continually falling into stereotype is
their voices. Despite a few too many ``jest's'' and ``yore's,'' the
regional dialect is handled adroitly, allowing its speakers to
reveal themselves as passionate and persuasive individuals. Winnie
herself employs a powerful version of mountain speech with many a
simile, some arresting (``mad as a meat ax,'' ``moody as a miser'')
and some less so (``wet as a muskrat,'' ``sour as persimmons'').
After the first dozen or so, such comparisons begin to wear thin.
</P>
<P>
   IF the characters in ``Blood Feud'' are a bit short on
contradiction and ambiguity, the narrative itself is short on the
texture of life -- the details that would let us feel these
people's experiences. It's as if Thomas were trying to keep her
terrifically strong material from running away with the novel.
</P>
<P>
   Characters who are rigidly defined and unchanging keep human
nature within bounds; a setting sparely described helps keep Nature
under control. Instead of letting both kinds of unruliness
intensify and deepen the novel, Thomas places the story firmly in
the fist of a narrator who points out the significance of every
scene, often before we've had a chance to witness it for ourselves.
Young Winnie is always on top of events, even though they are not
recollected in tranquillity but presented as if happening right as
she speaks. The result -- with the happy exception of first love, a
theme she treats beautifully -- is a loss of mystery, a feeling
that there is nothing here for us to discover.
</P>
<P>
   And that's too bad, because by the end of ``Blood Feud'' we've
come to like this intrepid, vulnerable, too-wise-for-her-years
narrator. Few could fail to be moved by the intensity of Winnie's
desire (some would say it's the deepest desire of the human heart)
to be listened to, to be heard and truly understood. If only her
creator had trusted our reciprocal desire to do just that.
</P>
<P>
   When they aren't constrained by an imposed interpretation or
moral, Thomas's eye and ear can yield graceful and rewarding prose:
``Outside was bright moonlight. The evening was so still we could
hear a cowbell down by the mine. The ground felt hard under our
feet and frost sparkled in the fields, but no snow had fallen. The
hills laid long moon shadows on us as we went up the road.''
</P>
<P>
   As intensely as the young lovers of ``Blood Feud'' long to be
with each other, so the reader will long to be left alone,
unsupervised, with passages like that -- a whole novelful of them.
Maybe next time?
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Ann Harleman is the author of a collection of stories,
``Happiness,'' and a novel, ``Bitter Lake.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
