<HEADER>
A2779 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-JORDAN-NYTSF     12-10 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-JORDAN-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 BARBARA JORDAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   American Hero.
</P>
<P>
   By Mary Beth Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 414 pp. New York: Bantam Books. $27.50.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; THE HEART OF TEXAS
</P>
<P>
   BY PHIL GAILEY
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Jordan came into this world black -- too black, she
learned soon enough. ``Why is she so dark?'' Ben Jordan asked
immediately after his daughter was born on Feb. 21, 1936, in
Houston. Her blackness meant that Barbara Jordan had to overcome
two racial barriers in her life -- one erected by white racism, the
other by black culture. In her early years, she was more conscious
of the latter than the former.
</P>
<P>
   ``Black was not beautiful,'' Mary Beth Rogers writes in
``Barbara Jordan: American Hero.'' ``It was a burden. For a
girl-child, the degree of melanin pigmentation in her skin and the
turn of her features mattered. The shape of her nose or the texture
of her hair determined acceptance, opportunity and status. Ben
Jordan knew all of that, and he knew he would have to demand much
more of his new baby girl to compensate for her blackness. Mind,
will, discipline, work, achievement -- those attributes would be
the hope, and the challenge, for this child.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan met that challenge. She could not change her skin color,
but she was able to use her remarkable mind and her riveting voice
to overcome. And what a voice it was -- clear, resonant, musical,
soaring, inspirational. Its authority and eloquence could be both
uplifting and overpowering, as when she spoke during the House
Judiciary Committee's impeachment proceedings against President
Richard M. Nixon. ``My faith in the Constitution is whole, it is
complete, it is total,'' she told her spellbound colleagues and a
national television audience. ``I am not going to sit here and be
an idle spectator to the diminution, the subversion, the
destruction of the Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   At that moment, on a hot July day in 1974, Jordan, a Democratic
Congresswoman from Texas, became an American hero and patriot.
Before that turning point, she was known as an ambitious politician
who often seemed more comfortable as a political insider than as an
activist for any cause. Idealism had its place, but Jordan was
interested in results. In the deal-making corridors of power in
Austin and Washington, Jordan's pragmatism and willingness to
compromise got results, though she was often criticized by white
liberals, black caucuses and feminists for settling for too little.
She made it clear to the white men who ruled the Texas Legislature
and the United States Congress that she would never betray ``her
people'' but that everything else was on the table. She played a
key role in the battle to extend the Voting Rights Act, but she
also was a reliable vote for her state's oil and gas industry.
</P>
<P>
   If her personal struggle to rise above racism and her
legislative record were the sum of Jordan's life, her story would
be impressive but not extraordinary. She would be remembered
primarily for her ``firsts'' -- the first African-American to serve
in the Texas Senate since Reconstruction, the first black woman
ever elected to Congress from the South and the first black to be a
keynote speaker at a national political convention (the 1976
Democratic National Convention). But Jordan was much more than a
series of firsts. At a time when African-Americans had to look to
the entertainment world and the civil rights movement for heroes,
she became the first black elected official to attain that status.
She became a national hero who transcended race and touched a
nation's conscience.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Barbara Jordan it came together during the impeachment
proceedings,'' Rogers writes. ``As she talked about the
Constitution, she began her transformation from a politician to a
patriot, from an inside player who could get a law passed to an
inspirational leader. . . . Now she had a message that matched her
voice.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers, who is the chief executive officer of public television
station KLRU in Austin, came to know Jordan when their paths
crossed in Texas politics and later at the Lyndon B. Johnson School
of Public Affairs at the University of Texas, where both taught.
Despite her public life, Jordan was a stoic, intensely private
person. Even many of her close friends were not fully aware of her
20-year struggle against debilitating illnesses, including multiple
sclerosis and leukemia, which took her life at the age of 59 in
1996. In her autobiography, ``Self-Portrait,'' Jordan chose to
ignore or gloss over some of the facts. Fortunately, Rogers has
filled in many of the blanks, and between Jordan's autobiography
and this splendid biography, history has an ample and inspiring
account of Barbara Jordan's remarkable life.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Phil Gailey is the editorial page editor and vice president of
The St. Petersburg Times.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
