<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 11:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2781 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-BRIEFS-FICTIO     12-10 1539
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-BRIEFS-FICTION-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKS IN BRIEF: FICTION
</HEADLINE>
  (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 THE DARK ROOM
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Julia Cameron.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll &AMP; Graf, $25. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The initial mystery of why an author of self-help guides for
perplexed writers would chose a detective story for her fictional
debut is solved about a hundred pages into ``The Dark Room,'' a
wildly incredible tale of cops and psycho killers. There Julia
Cameron has her protagonist, the aging but honorable Elliot Mayo,
interrupt his pursuit of a murderer to deliver a lecture about
encountering a Darth Vaderish archetype, devised by the Swiss
psychiatrist Carl Jung, that is supposed to stand for our darkest
desire. And suddenly what had been the increasingly preposterous
mean-streets narrative of a wisecracking, conveniently divorced
police detective being romanced by a kooky female surgeon is
revealed as just an artist-as-hero slog, certain to delight fans of
Jung's arcanely mystical notions but just as certain to leave
conventional whoduniteers stranded. So that quirky Jewish medical
examiner who warns Mayo to bathe in Epsom salts to keep the
Satanists away is not merely a delightful eccentric inhabiting a
dreary Chicago neighborhood -- he's a blazing beacon of Jungian
obscurantism who doesn't make the pages turn any faster. Too bad,
since Cameron's tough-guy prose often sparkles with wry turns and
snappy comebacks. Cameron's wit might have excused her symbolist
excesses if she had simply let her detective detect. Instead, Mayo
is pulled about by a plot that forces him to explore the
all-too-horrifying effects of a sex crime involving his son and
battle evil forces inhabiting a ``power ring.'' These gimmicks --
not to mention the overheated taunts of Mayo's love interest and a
twisted killer bent on doing good -- might make sense in terms of
Jungian symbolism but as plot devices they remain beyond Mayo's
belief, as well as our own. _ BILL KENT
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HYSSOP
</P>
<P>
   By Kevin McIlvoy.
</P>
<P>
   Triquarterly Books/Northwestern University, $24.95. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Red Greet is a strange and wonderful old man. When we meet him,
at the age of 87, he's behind bars and dancing with his jailer, the
son of an old friend. And he's talking. This unusual introduction
pulls up the curtain on an account of Greet's life and leads into a
stream of stories as he takes us on a tour of his memory's
touchstones. An inveterate but strangely honest thief, Greet has
what he himself describes as a ``soul of hard-packed dung'' -- not
exactly pure, but incredibly fertile in raw human emotion. As the
book proceeds, Greet tells of his lifelong love for Recita Holguin
-- a woman he finally marries when they are both in their 80s --
and of his first wife, Cecilia, who dies in middle age, partly
unloved because of Greet's inconstancy. He tells, too, of the
friendships he has made in the New Mexico village of Las Almas,
especially with his ``dearest friend,'' Francisco Velasco, who
becomes a priest when Greet wins over his true love -- Cecilia --
and who eventually rises to become the local bishop. Greet also
tells a fractured tale of religious turmoil, of the molding of
Roman Catholic ritual to everyday reality, symbolized by the
novel's title. (Hyssop is the soul-healing balm that comes of
confession and the sharing of secrets.) Greet is a jackdaw of
memory, collecting shiny, often unrelated bits of the past and
presenting them with effusive joy. _ ERIK BURNS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EXCITABILITY
</P>
<P>
   Selected Stories, 1986-1996
</P>
<P>
   By Diane Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Dalkey Archive, paper, $13.50. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Diane Williams has gathered 107 stories and a 44-part novella in
her latest collection, which takes its title from a story about
romance and nostalgia that appeared in her 1996 volume, ``The
Stupefaction.'' Although the story itself hasn't been included
here, ``excitability'' is an apt precis of this new book's
lightning-quick, innovative style. Williams defies narrative
convention with her disembodied, unnamed characters, whose concerns
include sex, marriage and child rearing and whose predicaments have
no beginning, middle or end. Frequently told in the first person,
her work elicits a reader's voyeuristic complicity and wish to
understand -- if not identify with -- the speaker's state of mind.
At their best, Williams's stories achieve a high degree of lyric
intensity and suggestiveness. But while the brevity and esthetic
discernment of individual stories may be thought-provoking, a
succession of them can seem tiresome, even insubstantial. _ GARDNER
MCFALL
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE CLEFT: And Other Odd Tales
</P>
<P>
   By Gahan Wilson
</P>
<P>
   Tor/Tom Doherty, $23.95. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Gahan Wilson turns his pictures into thousands of words in this
collection of meticulously eccentric stories. But the illustrations
are definitely the icing on this devil's food cake of a book. The
best story is the tenderly heartbreaking ``Frog Prince,'' about a
poor little creature with a recurring dream about a kingly father
and a spell that until broken holds him fast in the loneliness of
his watery world: ``Frog watched from his lily pad, confident that
the magic would work on its own, that his salvation was
approaching.'' Salvation, alas, is not an option for most of
Wilson's characters. Spiders devour the curious, sea gulls wreak
vengeance on the guilty, cats claw their owners to death -- and
what people do to people is even worse. The title story, about
monks decorating the precipitous route to their mountainside
shrine, is a brisk lesson in human folly. In ``The Power of the
Mandarin,'' a fictional character undoes a real-life foe, thinking:
``The idiot had discovered Evan Trowbridge's strength, which was
implacable hatred, but he had shared, and therefore missed
altogether, his weakness, which was a lack of sufficient
imagination.'' Happily, this is a weakness that Wilson doesn't
share. _ ANDREA HIGBIE
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-BREIFS-FICTION-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: ANDREA HIGBIE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WIVES OF THE FISHERMEN
</P>
<P>
   By Angela Huth.
</P>
<P>
   St. Martin's, $23.95. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In her latest novel, Angela Huth (the author of ``Land Girls'')
tells of the lifelong, heartfelt friendship -- laced nonetheless
with rivalry, jealousy and disapproval -- between two women who
live in a tiny, secluded fishing village on the east coast of
Scotland. Myrtle Duns is the plain but intelligent friend of Annie
Mcleoud, a beautiful, frivolous, self-centered charmer. With these
characters, Huth drops curtsies to George Eliot and, in particular,
Jane Austen: Myrtle is deliciously slow to recognize that a man she
sees only as a friend is, in fact, her future husband. (We, of
course, have twigged to this long before she has.) But while Huth
enables readers to be perceptive when it comes to the undercurrents
of her story, she muddles us in other ways. Myrtle and Annie have
televisions and microwaves, yet often Huth's characters express
themselves with 19th-century circumspection. (A marriage proposal
is delivered with sober formality: ``You must know that I would be
far from averse . . . to changing the solitary nature of my
life.'') Luckily, this winds up being charming rather than
disturbing because it puts us into a timeless realm. And the novel
offers the additional pleasure of Huth's precise and piquant
descriptions: the ``velutinous black'' on the horizon where the sea
merges with the sky; the ``plushy warm air of a late summer
evening.'' ``I'm one of those who finds more than enough in a small
world,'' Myrtle concludes. Huth makes us share that sentiment. _
JULIE GRAY
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LET NOTHING YOU DISMAY
</P>
<P>
   By Mark O'Donnell.
</P>
<P>
   Knopf, $22. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   'Twas the day before the night before the night before the night
before the night before Christmas -- or something like that. Fired
from his job, unsure about his sexuality, about to lose his sublet
apartment and suspecting that his doctoral dissertation will never
get written, Tad Leary is remarkably unprepared for revelry of any
kind. But since he's unprepared for anything else either, he
decides to take in a whole succession of holiday parties. In his
frothy second novel, Mark O'Donnell follows Tad through Manhattan
on an expedition to various circles of social hell. He begins with
a strained family gathering on the East Side. (Tad's father is
recovering from a heart attack and one of his brothers from a
bankruptcy-induced suicide attempt; his mother makes tactless
remarks designed to find out if Tad has AIDS.) From there, he flees
to an artistically unsatisfying session of performance art in the
East Village, repairs to the home of a Swedish friend where
everyone speaks in exclamatory sentences (``I see you're in your
trademark jeans and white shirt!'') and briefly crashes the holiday
party of the school that fired him before ending up at a
titanically superficial gala in a garish penthouse on Fifth Avenue.
What can Tad expect (besides a monumental hangover) from this
pilgrimage? Maybe just a bit of peace in the tiny corner of the
world he calls his own. _ JAMES POLK
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
