<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 11:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2783 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-PAPERBACKS-NY     12-10 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-PAPERBACKS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS
</HEADLINE>
  By SCOTT VEALE  (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; SELECTED POEMS: 1960-1990
</P>
<P>
   By Maxine Kumin.
</P>
<P>
   Norton, $17.95. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This collection by a versatile elegist and observer of nature
features vivid poems that are, refreshingly, about something: many
tell stories that serve to preserve her family's history. Last year
in the Book Review, Richard Tillinghast called the book ``a welcome
addition to any poetry library.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A JOURNEY WITH ELSA CLOUD
</P>
<P>
   By Leila Hadley.
</P>
<P>
   Penguin, $14.95. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Invited to India by her estranged hippie daughter, a demanding,
perfectionist mother embarks on a voyage of self-discovery that
takes her from New Delhi to the home of the exiled Dalai Lama, with
epiphanies and emotional awakenings along the way. ``Hadley is a
gifted travel writer with an artist's eye for the composition --
and the look, smell and history -- of every scene,'' Diane Johnson
wrote here last year. In India: From Midnight to the Millennium, by
Shashi Tharoor (Harper Perennial, $14), an expatriate takes a hard
look at his country's first 50 years of independence, and explains
why parliamentary democracy has done so little to relieve poverty,
illiteracy and disease. ``Few books in recent years, if any, offer
such a comprehensive overview of what ails India, its politicians
and its people,'' John F. Burns said here in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOUR LETTERS OF LOVE
</P>
<P>
   By Niall Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Warner, $13.99. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The narrator of this tale of romance and fate is a Dubliner
whose search for one of his artist father's paintings leads him
into the arms of a young woman on the Irish coast. Last year our
reviewer, Katharine Weber, called the novel ``a luminously written,
magical work of fiction . . . filled with marvelous characters,
large and small.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE END OF THE NOVEL OF LOVE
</P>
<P>
   By Vivian Gornick.
</P>
<P>
   Beacon, $12. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Examining the works of writers like Willa Cather and Grace
Paley, a critic argues that literature has lost its faith in the
transformative power of love. ``Gornick makes forceful and dramatic
judgments,'' Elizabeth Frank wrote here in 1997. ``Reading her
essays, one is reassured that the conversation between life and
literature is mutually sustaining as well as mutually corrective.''
The Merry Heart: Reflections on Reading, Writing, and the World of
Books, by Robertson Davies (Penguin, $14.95), is a posthumous
collection of lectures and essays by the Canadian novelist on the
literary life and matters of humane concern. Last year our
reviewer, Sven Birkerts, said that even though much of his public
prose is less successful on the written page, ``Davies was a
relaxed and winning raconteur, a beguiling autocrat of the
rostrum.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAIN WHISTLE GUITAR
</P>
<P>
   By Albert Murray.
</P>
<P>
   Vintage International, $13. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This novel, just restored to print, is about a black boy growing
up in Alabama in the 1920's and his idol, a blues guitarist named
Luzana Cholly. In 1974 in these pages, John Wideman admired the
``long passages of dialogue, monologue, the lyric descriptions of
countryside and fireside, which are nothing so much as the riffs
and choruses of a blues artist translated into speech and action.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE FILE: A PERSONAL HISTORY
</P>
<P>
   By Timothy Garton Ash.
</P>
<P>
   Vintage, $13. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A British historian tells how he found a blurred image of his
younger self in an old East German secret police file, and how he
tracked down the people who had informed on him. The result is ``a
political thriller, reminiscent of Graham Greene and John le Carre,
and a treatise on memory, forgetting and forgiving in the great
tradition of Proust,'' Tomas Venclova wrote here in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HALLUCINATING FOUCAULT
</P>
<P>
   By Patricia Duncker.
</P>
<P>
   Vintage International, $12. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This intricate first novel focuses on a graduate student who
tracks down and falls in love with the subject of his dissertation,
a French novelist in an insane asylum. The result is ``a
fascinating drama of knowledge and power, reason and desire,''
Allen Lincoln said here last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MURDER IN THE MUSEUM OF MAN
</P>
<P>
   By Alfred Alcorn.
</P>
<P>
   Zoland, $13. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   When a university dean is found dead in the Museum of Man, the
museum's courtly recording secretary turns sleuth. The result is a
``stylish, occasionally fiendish detective story . . . out to
skewer glitzy academic corruption,'' Nina Auerbach said here last
year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRUMAN CAPOTE:
</P>
<P>
   In Which Various Friends, Enemies, Acquaintances, and Detractors
Recall His Turbulent Career
</P>
<P>
   By George Plimpton.
</P>
<P>
   Anchor/Doubleday, $16.95. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This chronicle shows how the talented Capote turned fame into an
art form, and finally into a substitute for art itself. His lurid
story is told mostly through the firsthand accounts of fellow
celebrities. In 1997 our reviewer, Julia Reed, found the book to be
filled with old gossip, but said ``some of the best bits reveal
more about the speaker than about the subject.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PILGRIMS
</P>
<P>
   By Elizabeth Gilbert.
</P>
<P>
   Houghton Mifflin, $12. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Many of the pilgrims in this first short-story collection are
working-class folks searching for redemption but skeptical of
spiritual enlightenment. The author ``embraces the bizarre and
fabulous with similar enthusiasm,'' Liam Callanan wrote here in
1997. ``She moves stealthily, avoiding the temptation to
grandstand, moralize or, especially, patronize.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
</TEXT>
