<HEADER>
A2793 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HARD-TO-HANDLE-LIFEBE     12-10 1414
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARD-TO-HANDLE-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARE TODAY'S KIDS HARDER TO HANDLE?
</HEADLINE>
  By KYLE D. PRUETT 
 c.1998 Child magazine 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Emily's long day was finally ending.
</P>
<P>
   The 4-year-old had needed to stay late at school because her
father's train was delayed and he couldn't get to her preschool
until an hour and a half after the usual pickup time.
</P>
<P>
   She wanted to wait for her father in the parking lot so she
could catch the first glimpse of his car rounding the corner. When
told that she would have to wait inside where it was safer, Emily
promptly sank her teeth into the teacher's forearm. Fortunately, no
permanent damage was done, but neither the child nor her teacher
could have been more surprised. Emily had always been a cooperative
and well-behaved kid from a ``nice home.''
</P>
<P>
   Such acts of aggression are occurring more frequently in
childcare settings. As a consultant to private and public daycare
and family-care providers for several decades, I have seen an
increase in this behavior in even the most advantaged and
competently run childcare facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Lola Nash, lecturer in education at Yale University's Child
Study Center, who has established and directed early-childhood
programs in and around Yale for 30 years, observes: ``There's been
a dramatic increase in this kind of aggressive upset in childcare
over the past decade. All the programs I work with are struggling
to develop policies to handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   A teacher in a private kindergarten in a Boston suburb says,
``Often, my classroom feels out of control. The speech is 'in your
face' and 'street talk,' even from kids who were raised in suburban
areas. Verbal aggression, teasing, and sarcasm are common, and most
of us can name children from good families who've decked or bitten
someone in the past year.''
</P>
<P>
   Expressing and mastering aggression is a normal and healthy part
of child development. Aggression is the drive to use our bodies, to
move about in space, to reach out and grab what we want. Aggression
gets us up on our feet and helps us learn to walk.
</P>
<P>
   Violence, on the other hand, is the intended use of physical
force to injure or abuse, and it is certainly not a normal, healthy
part of a child's development.
</P>
<P>
   We say no to babies, toddlers and preschoolers mostly to keep
them safe from the stairs, the street, the poisons under the
kitchen sink, the stranger and the unknown dog. But why should your
child listen to you? ``Because I'm the Dad (or Mom)'' carries
weight occasionally, but the real reason that no works is the child
believes this: Daddy and Mommy say no because they know what's best
for me; they love me and want to keep me safe.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Too many caregivers? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Herein lies a dilemma for many young families who need to divide
the care of their children between people who love them deeply _
parents and other relatives _ and people who may like their
children well enough _ daycare staff and educators _ but are not
invested in them unconditionally.
</P>
<P>
   The more caregivers a child has when he is learning how to
master his aggressive impulses and the greater the variability of
his experience with limit-setting adults, the harder he will find
it to develop the trust that prompts him to behave well for someone
whom he loves.
</P>
<P>
   Young children who are exposed to too much variety in caregiving
situations or to too many caregiver changes may begin to wonder,
``Why should I struggle to master my favorite aggressive impulses
for you? You may like me and know how to bathe and feed me, but you
don't really know me or love me, and I don't know or love you. So
is it really worth it for me to restrict my 'me first' impulses for
you?''
</P>
<P>
   From there, a preschooler can easily conclude: ``Well, then, I
guess it's every kid for himself around here.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Media influence &LR;
</P>
<P>
   We know that young children are susceptible to visual images of
aggression, repeating and mirroring the violence they encounter in
movies, electronic games or cartoons for hours _ or days _
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   As a clinician, I know there's a limit to the number of violent
images that children can absorb before feeling overwhelmed. Their
ability to neutralize the visual toxins emotionally is vastly more
limited than ours; can we be surprised when violence spills over in
their play for days afterward?
</P>
<P>
   Even more than movies, electronic and computer games excite our
young kids with irresistible graphics and attention-grabbing action
sequences. They keep attention levels so high that kids often have
difficulty returning to the more mundane pastels of life among
family and friends.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The voice of authority &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A small crisis in parental self-esteem may also play a part in a
young child's ability to manage everyday aggression. Erin, the
young mother of a 4-year-old daughter, works 30 hours a week
outside the home. ``I do love my work,'' she says. ``But I so want
to be with my daughter that it's hard for me not to spend the first
hour when I get home making up to her for not being there during
the day. When she challenges my authority, all I want to do is make
nice because I've missed her so much! I'm not good at setting
limits.''
</P>
<P>
   Erin's comments help explain why so many working parents place
their children in the driver's seat long before they can see over
the dashboard, then wonder why household routines last only a few
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   This parental expectation that children be catered to also
influences their childcare and schooling. Karen, the suburban
Boston kindergarten teacher mentioned earlier, struggles with the
growing number of well-intentioned parents who urge teachers not to
quash their children's ``spirit.'' While a rigid classroom can
certainly stifle expressiveness, the educator's concern centers on
the difficulty some of these ``overappreciated'' children have in
sharing classroom supplies and equipment
</P>
<P>
   Are there any solutions? Yes. Here are several strategies to
consider:
</P>
<P>
   _ Limit the number of caregivers your young child must deal
with. A few family members and a couple of daycare or school
professionals handling physical and emotional needs is about it for
kids under age 5.
</P>
<P>
   _ Stay in close touch with your childcare providers about how
your child is doing, emotionally as well as physically. If you
don't get clear descriptions or stories that match your own
experience, the staff may be too busy with other kids. Ask the
director to keep an eye on things and to get back to you. When you
collaborate closely with the important people in your child's life,
both you and he are reassured.
</P>
<P>
   _ Keep tabs on what your child is watching and playing. Then
observe her moods. It will be clear to you if your child is
suffering from a toxic accumulation of internal aggression. Don't
worry about being the only parent on earth who won't allow his or
her child to watch the newest multimedia dismemberment spectacle.
Check out the thoughtful, age-appropriate movie and television
guides for kids available at local public libraries.
</P>
<P>
   _ Review the routines that your family follows. What you haven't
any? That might explain why you feel so exhausted. The chaos that
tends to take over when you don't have at least some routines in
place keeps the stimulation and tension levels in you and your kids
fairly high because you can never leave the negotiating table and
get on with life. Kids often embrace routines with enthusiasm; they
offer a sense of order and control, which raises children's
aggression threshold.
</P>
<P>
   _ When you say no to a child, let him know you understand how
much he wants what you've ruled out. Accepting the emotional part
of your child's aggressive drives (``I don't want to go to bed
yet!'') lets him know that he doesn't always have to act out
physically to get his point across. Furthermore, it sets up a way
for you and your child to commiserate about the daily
disappointments of life within the context of the loving
relationship between the two of you.
</P>
<P>
   Because understanding intervenes, your child feels comforted and
the pressure to be aggressive eases.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Kyle D. Pruett, M.D., is a clinical professor of phychiatry at
Yale Child Study Center in New haven, Conn.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
