<SLUG> BC-POETRY-PROJECT-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POETRY IN MOTION
</HEADLINE>
  Includes color photo, available by e-mail, of Andrew Carroll
handing out free poetry books at the St. Louis Zoo. 
 By TOM DUNKEL 
 c.1998 Tom Dunkel 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shirley Armstrong is minding her own shopping business at a
Washington, D.C., supermarket when a friendly fellow walks up and
hands her a paperback booklet.
</P>
<P>
   She figures it for a high-class coupon promotion, her chance to
save big on solid white tuna or barbecue-flavored potato chips.
``The first thing I did (was ask), What kind of food items are on
sale in here?'' says Armstrong, thumbing the pages. ``Then I said,
My God, it's, poetry!''
</P>
<P>
   It isn't 20-percent-off-manufacturer's-suggested-retail-price
poetry, either. This is absolutely free poetry. And grade A
quality: tasty morsels of Robert Frost, Carl Sandburg, Langston
Hughes and other big name bards. ``Now I've got something to do
tonight,'' Armstrong chirps, ``and it' not Blockbuster Video.''
</P>
<P>
   That friendly fellow giving dozens of startled shoppers copies
of ``101 Great American Poems'' is Andy Carroll, the 29-year-old
unpaid executive director of the American Poetry and Literacy
Project, a shoestring nonprofit organization based in Washington,
D.C., with the lofty goal of (pardon the rhyme) awakening America's
poetic soul.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll _ a native Washingtonian who earns his living as a
freelance writer and editor _ encounters Shirley Armstrong on the
second day of a 6,529-mile, New York-to-San Francisco odyssey
dubbed The Great Appleseed Giveaway. The concept couldn't be
simpler: Andy Carroll hops into a rental truck loaded with 100,000
poetry books and heads west, showering literally free verse upon
whomever he meets.
</P>
<P>
   His target destinations aren't made-to-order venues such as
coffeehouses and high-school English classes. He plans to hit jury
rooms, turnpike rest areas, even Elvis Presley's Memphis mansion;
everywhere that everyday folks with time on their hands can be
found.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his supermarket stop, Carroll swings by the
Pentagon (where scores of rigid-posture passersby quickly gobble up
more than a thousand books) and the tourists' entrance to the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Poetry, it's the vegetable of the literary world,'' he
declares while driving across town on his poetry-promotion rounds.
More and more people have begun eating their literary
``vegetables.'' Sales of poetry books are up nationwide, as is the
number of public poetry readings.
</P>
<P>
   Hip-hop music has helped spawn a ``spoken word'' movement. ``It
really does feel like poetry's finest hour,'' says Toni Bevan,
director of marketing and promotion at The Academy of American
Poets. ``There are a lot of things contributing to that. You could
certainly say Andy is one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll wouldn't say that, though. He gives the lion's share of
the credit to the late Joseph Brodsky, the Nobel Prize-winning
Russian-emigre poet. In 1991, in a speech that was printed later in
New Republic, Brodsky lamented the fact that print-based literacy
was gradually giving way to a dumbed-down, visually-oriented
``videocy.''
</P>
<P>
   As an antidote, he proposed making poetry ``as ubiquitous as the
nature that surrounds us ... as ubiquitous as gas stations, if not
as cars themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Brodsky's name didn't really ring a bell with Andy Carroll, who
had taken just one poetry course as a Columbia University
undergrad. Well, actually, it rang the wrong bell: Carroll thought
he was a retired Russian cosmonaut.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Brodsky's call to arms struck a responsive chord.
Carroll immediately wrote him a letter offering to help
saturation-bomb the United States with great poetry. Turns out it
was the only offer Brodsky received, and in 1993, Brodsky and
Carroll launched the American Poetry and Literacy Project.
</P>
<P>
   It has no employees. It sponsors no conferences, publishes no
newsletter. It just raises money from corporations, foundations and
private citizens, uses the cash to buy poetry books, and then gives
them all away in person or through the mail _ more than 200,000
books and counting.
</P>
<P>
   Brodsky died of a heart attack in 1996, and ex-poets laureate
Rita Dove and Robert Hass have since lent their names to the APLP
cause. However, as Carroll notes, ``Joseph was it. In some ways,
he's irreplaceable.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll personally takes care of business in the Washington
area, dropping off books at hospitals, nursing homes and other
sites. But he has also developed a nationwide network of poetry
compadres. Amtrak executives once stocked the cafe car on the
Washington-to-Boston run with 1,500 copies of ``100 Best Loved
Poems.'' One Halloween in Austin, Texas, the county tax assessor
and the local coroner held a ``Death and Taxes'' reading at a
library, dipping into spooky selections from Edgar Allan Poe's
``The Raven and Other Poems.''
</P>
<P>
   After Brodsky's death, Carroll was determined to take to the
road in his memory. In some respects, Carroll was the worst man for
the job. He flunked his driver's test three times before passing
and had never driven more than 400 miles from home.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he possesses the requisite freewheeling spirit for such an
undertaking. He got Ryder to donate a truck. Doubletree hotels
provided rooms on the road. Washington State Apple Growers _
intrigued by the Johnny Appleseed-like notion of reaping and sowing
literacy through poetry plantings _ picked up the tab for the
books.
</P>
<P>
   Today there are plans to compile a book of travel-related
poetry, perfect for slipping into seat pockets on trains and
planes. He's also looking for a corporate sponsor to underwrite the
cost of giving away 1 million books. Sound quixotic? Or crazy?
</P>
<P>
   Either way, don't expect Andy Carroll to sit on the sidelines
watching the demise of Western civilization and the rise of Fox
Network. After all, this is a guy who walked into a swank Las Vegas
casino and was blown away by an innocuous sign in the gambling pit.
``It read: 'You must be present to win,''' says Carroll. ``That's
one of the most poetic things I've ever seen in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Tom Dunkel is a free-lance writer based in Washington, D.C.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS at (800) 972-3550 or fax
her at (212) 499-3382.
</P>
