<HEADER>
A2848 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PUERTORICO-STATEHOOD-     12-10 1244
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUERTORICO-STATEHOOD-$ADV12-CO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PUERTO RICO HOLDS VOTE ON ITS FUTURE, WITH STATEHOOD A POPULAR
OPTION
 &HT;    With PUERTORICO-BOX-$ADV12.
 &HT;    For Use Saturday, Dec. 12 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ In Puerto Rico, a television advertisement shows a young
mother sitting in the sunny back yard of her Florida home,
expounding the virtues of U.S. schools and the U.S. job market.
</P>
<P>
   ``With statehood, things will be just as good in Puerto Rico as
they are here in the United States,'' she says to the camera in
Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   The advertisement, paid for by a political action committee, is
just one tiny part of the battle being waged for votes in
Sunday's(Dec. 13) referendum on Puerto Rico's future.
</P>
<P>
   A century after the U.S. Army wrested the Caribbean island from
Spain, voters will go to the polls to decide whether they want the
U.S. territory to become the 51st state.
</P>
<P>
   If that were to happen, Puerto Rico would be the only largely
Hispanic state in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Rico's pro-statehood Gov. Pedro Rossello called the vote
in July in a gamble designed to push the U.S. Congress to address
what he claims is an outmoded relationship.
</P>
<P>
   The vote doesn't bind the United States to do anything, although
President Clinton has said that Congress should honor the results
and take up the issue next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Congress will address this issue because it's the
right thing to do, and also, if it doesn't, it won't play well with
Hispanic voters across the United States,'' said pro-statehood
Puerto Rican Sen. Kenneth McClintock.
</P>
<P>
   The ballot is even formed as a petition that calls on Congress
to act.
</P>
<P>
   It offers four alternatives: statehood, independence, the
current ``commonwealth'' status, and free association. The last, on
a ballot for the first time, would allow Puerto Rico to be
independent while retaining some ties to the United States, making
it similar to the former U.S. territories of Palau and the Marshall
Islands.
</P>
<P>
   A fifth box allows voters to pick ``none of the above,'' a
choice the pro-commonwealth Popular Democratic Party is pushing as
a way to protest the definition of commonwealth that appears on the
ballot.
</P>
<P>
   The party claims that the ballot is biased toward statehood by
implying that U.S. citizenship and other federal benefits will not
be safe under the current, commonwealth status.
</P>
<P>
   Congress granted U.S. citizenship to Puerto Ricans in 1917, and
made the island a commonwealth in 1952.
</P>
<P>
   During the last non-binding referendum in Puerto Rico, held in
1993, nearly 49 percent of voters chose to retain commonwealth
status, while 46 percent opted for statehood. About 5 percent of
voters favored independence.
</P>
<P>
   Most Puerto Ricans believe the push for statehood has picked up
steam in recent years, an assertion confirmed by recent newspaper
polls that show statehood as the leading choice among voters.
</P>
<P>
   A poll of registered voters released this week by the San Juan
Star newspaper showed statehood edging out ``none of the above'' by
49 percent to 45 percent. Free association received 3 percent of
the vote, independence received 2.4 percent of the vote, and the
current, commonwealth status was favored by less than 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In March, the U.S. House of Representatives approved a bill by
just one vote mandating the first-ever federally authorized
plebiscite allowing Puerto Ricans to vote on their future.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would have given Congress at least 10 years to
decide whether to grant statehood to Puerto Rico if a majority of
voters had opted for that choice.
</P>
<P>
   But the proposal was stalled in the Senate, forcing Rossello to
call his own non-binding plebiscite.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., said that the movement for
statehood won't be over even if statehood fails to win a clear
majority Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But he predicted statehood would win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that would send a strong message to the Congress that
we need to move the process along,'' said Burton, who's in Puerto
Rico for the referendum.
</P>
<P>
   If Congress does take up the issue next year, as is expected,
statehood will be fought hard by many passionate critics, including
Jim Boulet Jr., executive director of English First, a Springfield,
Va.-based organization that wants to make English the country's
official language.
</P>
<P>
   He said Puerto Rican statehood would saddle U.S. taxpayers with
an impoverished, crime-ridden island.
</P>
<P>
   ``The option of statehood is like a fish left out in the sun,''
he said. ``The longer it is out there, the less appetizing it
becomes.''
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out that Puerto Rico's per-capita income of $8,000 is
one-third the U.S. average and less than half that of Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   But statehood advocates argue that the island deserves a new,
fairer status. They say Puerto Ricans have been drafted and have
died for the American flag even though they can't vote for
president and have only one non-voting member in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   They also say statehood would provide an economic boon for
Puerto Rico the same way it did for Alaska and Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   ``Economic growth would double and investment would increase six
times over,'' said Alcides Ortiz, executive director of Puerto
Rico's Federal Affairs Administration, Rossello's office in
Washington, D.C. ``Plus, we'd have some say in Congress on
decisions that directly affect us.''
</P>
<P>
   Under statehood, Puerto Rico would gain two senators and six
representatives in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, commonwealth advocates worry that the
island's Hispanic heritage and culture would be discarded under
statehood, and that Congress would try to make English the dominant
language in Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Rico is a Spanish-speaking territory where at least 75
percent of the population has a problem speaking English.
</P>
<P>
   The island is also a very conservative one, a place where
students in public schools are given five minutes to pray.
</P>
<P>
   Commonwealth advocates also warn that Puerto Ricans would be
forced to pay a whole slew of new taxes, ranging from federal
income taxes to gasoline taxes, if statehood were granted.
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Ricans currently are exempt from federal taxes, although
they do receive federal assistance -- about $12 billion in the last
fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under statehood, Puerto Ricans will die of hunger,'' said Luis
Munoz Marin, the first Puerto Rican governor and the father of the
commonwealth.
</P>
<P>
   In Puerto Rico, the issue of statehood has stirred heated debate
for decades among a population of 3.8 million people who enjoy
their own Olympic team and flag, but who also maintain strong
economic and personal ties to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   For example, about two million Puerto Ricans live on the U.S.
mainland.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last few months, non-stop rallies, parades, and other
political events have built enthusiasm on all sides of the argument
over the island's future.
</P>
<P>
   Those supporting statehood have grown increasingly confident
that they will have the votes this time to prove that an
overwhelming majority of Puerto Ricans are eager to end the status
quo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under commonwealth, investors compare the opportunities of
Puerto Rico to the Dominican Republic and Chile,'' said a
pro-statehood brochure. ``Under statehood, Puerto Rico would be
compared to Connecticut, Montana, New Mexico . . . Which sounds
better?''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
