<SLUG> BC-SHUTTLE-SPACE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASTRONAUTS PUT SPACE STATION'S ANTENNAS INTO PLACE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ U.S. astronauts Jerry Ross and Jim Newman floated
outside the fledgling international space station Wednesday to
equip it with two boxy communications antennas to link it to NASA's
Mission Control Center in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Their nearly 7-hour spacewalk began at 2:33 p.m. CST. The
excursion was the second of three from the shuttle Endeavour on the
first station assembly flight.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle astronauts are scheduled to complete the antenna
installation Thursday when they enter the recently linked U.S.
Unity and Russian Zarya modules, the first two components of the
station, for the first time. The modules were stacked together atop
the shuttle's combination docking mechanism and airlock Sunday,
creating an eight-story tower. The spacewalkers scale the modules
as they work.
</P>
<P>
   Once fully installed, the communications system, using a
National Aeronautics and Space Administration satellite link, will
enable the staff of Mission Control in Houston to monitor the
flight computers aboard Unity and send commands to many other
systems in the two modules. Motion control for Zarya will still be
transmitted by U.S. and Russian staff at mission control in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of what we are doing is basic construction,'' said
Newman, who was moved around the outside of the station on the tip
of Endeavour's 50-foot long robot arm. ``I don't think the tasks
will ever be mundane. The environment we will be working in will
always be very, very exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tremendous view when you come out,'' said Ross, who
lashed himself to the outside of the modules during what was his
sixth career walk in space. ``Wow.''
</P>
<P>
   In the televised views transmitted to the ground, the backdrop
for Wednesday's spacewalk was the silver gleam of the new station
modules against the vast black of deep space and the rich blue hues
of cloud-filled skies over the Earth 245 miles below. At one point,
the astronauts paused from their work, distracted by a far-away
lightning storm.
</P>
<P>
   With Ross assisting, Newman strung a pair of long communications
cables from the Russian to the American module.
</P>
<P>
   One will furnish the signals from the U.S.-financed Russian
module to American controllers as well as a two-way video link that
can be used by the first occupants of the new station to
communicate with the ground. The second will allow communications
for station residents who don Russian suits and use the future U.S.
airlock for spacewalks.
</P>
<P>
   Next, the two men wrestled a pair of 100 pound, suitcase-sized
antennas to installation points on the left and right sides of the
American module. Working separately, they plugged the bulky devices
into the hull of Unity and fastened them down in four places.
</P>
<P>
   The pace of Wednesday's spacewalk was not as frantic as the
first one Monday when Ross and Newman made 40 electrical power and
computer data connections in the Russian hardware.
</P>
<P>
   In this spacewalk there was time for several unusual tasks.
</P>
<P>
   Using a 10-foot-long tool called a ``boat hook'', Newman tugged
free a guidance antenna on the Russian module. Two of the
4-foot-long devices failed to unfurl properly after the Zarya was
launched by the Russians on Nov. 20.
</P>
<P>
   As it was during Monday's excursion, the two spacewalkers worked
in concert with astronaut Nancy Currie, the shuttle's robot-arm
operator, and pilot Rick Sturckow, who served as their timekeeper.
</P>
<P>
   The excursion's only low point was when Ross lost a large piece
of insulation the astronauts were applying to the outside of the
American module.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry, one of the thermal covers got away from you,''
Endeavour Commander Bob Cabana radioed from the shuttle's cockpit,
surprising his colleague.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where did it go?'' a frustrated Ross responded as the
blanketlike material drifted slowly away. ``It was all tethered, I
guarantee you. I don't believe this.''
</P>
<P>
   During Monday's spacewalk, Ross lost two aluminum tools, a
2{-pound socket and an 8{-pound wire carrier, equipment that was
supposed to be secured when not in use.
</P>
<P>
   An effort to recover the blanket was abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got well out behind us and dropped down pretty fast,''
Cabana told Mission Control. ``We lost sight of it in the
darkness.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Cabana was to lead his crew into the Unity and
Zarya modules for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are looking forward to on the ingress is the first
official act on the international space station and that is turning
on the lights,'' said Frank Culbertson, NASA's deputy director for
station operations.
</P>
<P>
   A final spacewalk is planned for Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
