r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VOLCANOES-AIRPLANES-H     12-10 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOLCANOES-AIRPLANES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESEARCHERS GIVE PILOTS ADVICE ON VOLCANO PLUMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ You are the pilot of a Boeing 747 hauling 231
passengers over Alaska on a sunny morning when suddenly the sky
blackens. The passengers start complaining that they smell burning
sulfur.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't an ancient ``Twilight Zone'' episode. It's an ash
plume from Hell's closest terrestrial equivalent: an erupting
volcano.
</P>
<P>
   And unless you stay cool and act fast, the thick, hot ash could
choke your jet engines. It might even shut them down, perhaps
dooming you and your passengers to icy graves in the Alaskan
wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   Such an incident, involving a KLM Royal Dutch Airlines jet,
happened near the Redoubt Volcano in Alaska on Dec. 15, 1989.
Fortunately, the pilot managed to revive the engines _ after 11
tries _ and she landed the jet safely. The damage: $80 million to
replace all four engines.
</P>
<P>
   During the past two decades, some 100 aerial close calls have
been caused by the unpredictable huffing and puffing of volcanoes,
Thomas J. Casadevall of the U.S. Geological Survey told the
American Geophysical Union conference Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   During the KLM flight, the cabin interior grew so dark that the
pilot tried to find her co-pilot ``by reaching out and finding his
shoulder,'' said Casadevall, who is the deputy director of the USGS
in Reston, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Incredibly, no one has died in these bizarre confrontations
between airplane and geology _ not yet, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Air traffic is growing and volcanoes continue to be active,''
Casadevall said. ``To my knowledge, the major carriers are now
giving preflight briefings (to pilots) that include volcanic
information.''
</P>
<P>
   The threat is especially great during night flights, when pilots
can't see the volcanic plumes until they are barreling through
them.
</P>
<P>
   To prevent a volcano-triggered aviation disaster, volcanologists
hope to win NASA permission late next month to launch the world's
first dedicated volcano-monitoring satellite. The orbital probe
would give advance warning of eruptions that might threaten pilots,
Casadevall and colleagues said.
</P>
<P>
   By using special instruments, the satellite would track volcanic
plumes as they migrate thousands of miles from their source. The
instruments would sense the chemical and mineral contents of the
plumes, such as silicate particles and a volcanic gas, sulfur
dioxide.
</P>
<P>
   If approved by the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration, the satellite should cost $50 million, a great
bargain considering the cost of the KLM incident, said a leader of
the project, volcanologist Bill Rose of Michigan State University.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the USGS continues to install ground-based sensors
around volcanoes across the globe. The sensors continually monitor
the shaking, temperature changes, gas emissions and other activity.
</P>
<P>
   ``These volcanic clouds can remain a problem for many days,''
Rose said. ``We have big holes in this kind of coverage now,''
meaning that a pilot can stumble upon an eruption unawares.
</P>
<P>
   Experts advise pilots against increasing engine power and trying
to escape a plume, but instead fly steadily while turning 180
degrees to escape the same way the pilot came in. By increasing
engine power in an effort to rise above the plume, the pilot risks
overheating, and perhaps burning out, the engines.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-98 1257EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981210.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 13:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2890 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-SENATORS-BOS &LR;      12-10 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SENATORS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPRESENTATIVES ELECTED TO SENATE FACE ETHICAL DILEMMA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Includes impeachment definition sidebar.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ One person cannot be both accuser and judge.
</P>
<P>
   So wrote President John Quincy Adams in his diary on Jan. 4,
1804. He later called upon US senators to disqualify members who
voted on impeachment in the House from voting on the same case in
the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Though in this case, involving a federal judge, several members
ended up voting in both the House and the Senate, the issue was
never really settled.
</P>
<P>
   Now, three US representatives _ soon to be senators _ are facing
this dilemma as they contemplate the possibility of casting one
vote on whether to impeach President Clinton, then casting another
vote as senators next year on whether to convict and remove Clinton
from office.
</P>
<P>
   The three are Charles Schumer, Democrat of New York; Mike Crapo,
Republican of Idaho; and Jim Bunning, Republican of Kentucky. They
deliberated, vacillated and finally decided that they are leaning
toward serving as both grand jurors in the House and jurors in the
Senate _ a decision that flies in the face of unofficial precedent
set over the years by members of Congress in the same situation.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has no specific rule on the subject of voting twice,
according to the US Senate Historical Office. And although many
lawyers point to the 1804 trial as a precedent, in the past most
senators in this position have not voted in Senate trials.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, in 1989, four senators who voted as lame duck
House members to send articles of impeachment of federal Judge
Alcee Hastings refused to vote in the Senate trial.
</P>
<P>
   All those refusing to vote were Republican, including Majority
Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi and Dan Coats of Indiana. A member
of Lott's staff said he did not think it ``appropriate'' to vote in
the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Theoretically, one would be concerned about voting as a
prosecutor in the House and then serving as a juror in the
Senate,'' said the staffer.
</P>
<P>
   Senators must take an sworn oath _ under threat of perjury _
before agreeing to participate in Senate impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will do impartial justice according to the constitution and
the law: so help me God.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a legal expert who asked for anonymity, Lott and
the three other Republicans did not vote as senators because they
did not believe they could be impartial.
</P>
<P>
   Bunning, who only a month ago was leaning toward skipping the
House vote in case he had to act as a juror in the Senate trial,
said he has had second thoughts about sitting on the sidelines in
such an historic event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I began to wonder if it was the right decision, and I think
the 50 to 100 calls a day to my office by phone, e-mail and letter
have me convinced that I wasn't elected to pass on this vote,''
said Bunning, who was elected to the Senate in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact,'' he added, ``my constituents have convinced me it is
my duty to vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Bunning has not yet decided how he would vote on the floor next
week, if, as expected, the House Judiciary Committee approves
articles of impeachment. But he said calls from Kentuckians were
running 10 to 1 in favor of impeaching the president. Out-of-state
calls to his office ran 4 to 1 in favor.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer, a House Judiciary Committee member who opposes
impeachment, had declared this fall that he would vote in the House
but not the Senate. He was unavailable for comment Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bunning and Crapo believe that if they do not vote on all
impeachment issues, their states will not be properly represented
in what could be the most significant votes of their term.
</P>
<P>
   ``My preference is to vote in both places unless ethics
requirements of Congress prevent me from doing so,'' said Crapo.
``So far, no ethical objections have been raised. My intention is
to fully represent the people of Idaho in these matters.''
</P>
<P>
   But eyebrows are being raised outside both the chambers. Bruce
Ackerman, who testified on behalf of the White House Tuesday,
argued that entire proceeding was unconstitutional because the
articles of impeachment were being voted on by a lame duck House.
</P>
<P>
   According to Ackerman, a Yale University law professor and
constitutional expert, voting twice ``to both charge and convict
someone does not comport with the ideals of American justice.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
IMPEACHMENT STEPS
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The House:
</P>
<P>
   This week's House Judiciary Committee hearings on the possible
impeachment of President Clinton are only the first step in a
process that could lead to his ouster. The committee is expected to
vote this week on whether to recommend that the full House adopt
articles of impeachment against Clinton. If that happens, the full
House could vote next week on articles of impeachment. If one or
more article is approved, the case would be sent to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Senate:
</P>
<P>
   Under the Constitution, the Senate would hold a trial on whether
to convict _ and thus oust _ Clinton. The senators would sit as a
jury, with Supreme Court Chief Justice William Rehnquist presiding
as the judge. Instead of having a ``prosecutor,'' the House
appoints a special impeachment counsel and members who are
``managers'' of the case. The senators could send questions to
Rehnquist, who would decide whether they could be asked. Witnesses
could be called to testify. In the end, the senators would vote on
whether the evidence shows that Clinton's action fits the
Constitution's vague definition of high crimes and misdemeanors.
Republicans control the Senate by a 55-45 margin. A two-thirds vote
_ meaning 67 senators if all are present _ are needed to convict
the president. Conviction on a single article of impeachment would
lead to Clinton's ouster.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
