<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 13:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2893 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTER-TREK-BOS &LR;      12-10 1099
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-TREK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHIE TREKKIES IN CYBERSPACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a bit of an urban-galactic mission just to wind your way to
the offices of The Screen House, an on-line design and development
firm located somewhere between a crater and a roadblock down on the
waterfront. Once there, you're greeted by a barefoot programmer
with a ponytail who pads across the blue Astroturf and invites you
to relax among the 10 arcade games in the lobby, enjoy a little
chat with the life-size cutout of Captain Jean-Luc Picard and,
heck, have a cup of java.
</P>
<P>
   This quirky little office, down by Big Dig Central, is the place
where a group of young entrepreneurs developed Star Trek:
Continuum, a rare Web site where the gee-whiz technology is
actually appropriate for the content. If you live in the flesh
world (as opposed to the Trek world), Star Trek: Continuum _ part
of Paramount's official Star Trek site _ might seem a little out
there, but to Screen House co-founder Drake Roberts, it's serious
business. His face takes on the look of a child just given the run
of the world's largest toy store when he leads a tour of the site,
which features more than 1,700 pages including an exhaustive
library and a special section called ``Klingon Compendium.''
</P>
<P>
   When he logs on, the site greets him personally, ``Welcome
Skyhopper!'' Roberts, needless to say, is a die-hard Trekkie.
Paramount noticed the start-up company after it produced some
on-line games for E! Online (most notably the fun little
time-waster that enabled users to sink the Titanic last year). ``It
didn't hurt that we were fanatic Trekkies,'' Roberts says,
launching the PADD (personal access display device) that enables
easy navigation of the mammoth site.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you build a site for Star Trek, you can use all your
technical bells and whistles,'' Roberts explains, practically
whistling himself. He clicks into the Klingon Linguistic Studies
area, where newbies like you-know-who can learn the language and
hear the synthesized voice of Majel Roddenberry, widow of Trek
founder Gene Roddenberry; she pronounces and defines vocabulary in
Klingon. For instance, butlh, pronounced ``boock,'' means dirt
under the tips of humanoid fingers. Noted.
</P>
<P>
   The site, of course, includes a section on ``Star Trek:
Insurrection,'' the latest adventure film, which opens next Friday.
And, of course, the Star Trek store is now open on line, part of
the $2 billion entertainment phenomenon that started modestly with
the first television series in 1966 and spawned three additional TV
series, nine feature films, scores of books and action figures,
dozens of unofficial Web sites, as well as thousands and thousands
of fans. And, yes, Star Trek: Continuum, is found at
www.startrek.com.
</P>
<P>
   (at)j
</P>
<P>
   Roberts and his partner Adam Prince, who also produce
non-galactic sites for earthly entities like Fidelity Investments,
seem to have found their dream job with the Trek assignment. But
there's a guy out in Hollywood who has a job that would bring tears
to the eyes of all those Trekkies rushing to see ``Insurrection''
next weekend. His name is Guy Vardaman, and he maintains the
official Star Trek database, which contains more than 30 years of
trivia and lore. The very idea makes your nltlhpachs itch (that's
fingernails, humanoid!).
</P>
<P>
   Vardaman, 33, worked closely with the Screen House folks on the
site, and he's the guy at Paramount responsible for answering
e-mail from the discerning audience. ``I've got a backlog of about
10,000 here,'' he says. He proceeds to read one about a ``warp core
breach.'' ``As you can see, we get a whole bunch of real technical
questions,'' he says, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Vardaman counts himself as a sort of soft-core Trekkie. ``I
watched the original series when I was a kid, but when I reached
adolescence, Captain Kirk came off the wall and Farah Fawcett went
up,'' he recalls. While he was a college student studying
electro-optical engineering, he landed a gig as an extra on one of
the Trek television series, and it turned into a full-time job. ``I
guess star dates and trivia pushed out my knowledge of the indices
of light refraction,'' he says, sighing. ``What can you do? I think
I know more about `Star Trek' than many things in my life I should
know more about.'' Like what? ``Like plumbing. If they could just
make the plumbing in my house look like the Enterprise floor plan,
I could figure it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Vardaman is quick to point out that the only Trek uniform he's
ever worn came out of the costume department. Sure, he loves his
job, but would he ever consider doing anything else? ``Why do you
ask? Do you have an offer? I don't think there are a lot of places
where you can go with a real advanced knowledge of Star Trek and
use it to make a living,'' he says. Well, there's this place down
on the Boston waterfront. Take a left at the crater and a right at
the roadblock. Ask for Skyhopper.
</P>
<P>
   (at)j
</P>
<P>
   Search of the week. Trekkies, by their very nature, have been on
line since the very beginning, back in the day when some of us were
still trying to work our VCRs and other more enterprising types
were trying to figure out how to make money on this thing called
the Internet. The best way to solve the VCR problem is to marry an
engineer. As for the money solution, it's called e-commerce. And
that's the reason some Trekkies are at war in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   A quick search leads Trekkies to Star Trek: WWW (www.stwww.com)
one of the best unofficial sites in intergalactica. Billed as
``Mother of all Star Trek sites,'' it's run by an Italian Trekkie
named Luca Sambucci. Last year, he and other Trekkie Web masters
received letters from Paramount's parent company Viacom, which
charged that they were infringing on copyrights by using Star Trek
images on their sites. Sambucci launched the Online Freedom
Federation, which fired off a petition to Viacom striving to reach
a compromise that enabled the fans to have their fun and enabled
the corporate monolith to generate revenue from its property. By
the latest count, Sambucci has collected 23,881 signatures.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the affected sites have been shut down, and others
continue, with or without the unauthorized images. One of the
funniest of these sites (www.bradley.edu/campusorg/psiphi/mov/)
includes an annotated copy of the letter from Viacom, in which the
Trekkie renegade parses the legalese and corrects the punctuation.
Too bad it isn't written in Klingon. Do`Ha' _ in Klingon, ``That is
unfortunate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-98 1310EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
