<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981210.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 13:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2895 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-APATHY-BOS &LR;      12-10 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-APATHY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAMPANT APATHY MAY HURT CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Apathy may be President Clinton's worst enemy.
</P>
<P>
   Far from the rhetoric and rancor of this week's House
impeachment hearings and debate, Americans for the most part are
minding their pre-holiday business, weary of the hashed and
rehashed Washington story and unalarmed that a moment in history is
at hand.
</P>
<P>
   Across this sunny, oceanside city with its zesty Latin flavor,
where the trunks of royal palms sparkle in wrappings of white
Christmas lights and convertibles cruise for parking spaces at
crowded malls, the news about Venezuela's president-elect draws
more passion than the issue of impeaching the US president.
</P>
<P>
   Many here admit they are battle fatigued, just too bored and fed
up with what looks like raw partisanship in Washington to care much
about Clinton's fate any longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it ever should have gotten this far, but now
it's out of control,'' said Adi Ortigosa, a tourist on her way home
to Chicago. ``I went away for vacation and came back to find
impeachment in full swing.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House itself is playing an inside-the-Beltway game,
targeting a group of moderate House Republicans whose votes against
impeachment could save the president. For Clinton to appeal again
for forgiveness, or to warn that impeachment is a national
nightmare, might simply fall on America's deaf ears.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to sound apathetic, but I think it's over and we
need to move on,'' said Mark Massimino, 31, a salesman from Miami
Beach. ``I'm tired of all the politics, and frankly, it doesn't
matter to me at this point whether Clinton stays or goes.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Americans aren't paying attention. Most people say
they are following the White House story and congressional hearings
closely, and they prove it by citing both details of the sex
scandal and specific allegations made of the president's
wrongdoing, from perjury to abuse of power.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Wheeler, a Miami homemaker who has watched large
chunks of the House Judiciary Committee proceedings on television,
including hearings this week featuring the president's defenders
and foes of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want something to happen,'' Wheeler said as she took a
break from holiday shopping with her 15-month-old son at the huge
Dadeland Mall here. ``I'm personally not scared of impeachment. I
don't think the president's departure would be too disruptive. He
doesn't have that much effect on the economy, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, polls show public opinion has not been influenced much,
if at all, this fall as the House Judiciary Committee set in motion
a high-profile inquiry that is likely to lead to it approving one
or more articles of impeachment later this week. Then, the full
House is expected to be called into session next week to decide for
only the second time in history if a sitting president should stand
trial in the Senate for committing high crimes.
</P>
<P>
   A Gallup survey released Monday showed 32 percent of Americans
are in favor of impeaching Clinton, while 66 percent are against
it. A Gallup poll published in early October showed nearly the same
thing: 34 percent for and 62 percent against impeachment. The
margin of error in each poll was three percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hypothetical questions are notoriously dangerous, and public
opinion might change when the voting actually starts,'' said Karlyn
Bowman, a political analyst at the American Enterprise Institute in
Washington. ``But I'd be surprised. These opinions are incredibly
stable, rock hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative Carrie Meek, a Democrat from the black-majority
district that includes Miami's Liberty City and creole-speaking
Little Haiti, said her constituents overwhelmingly like the
president and don't want him impeached. ``From the beginning, they
have begged Congress not to go against the will of the people,''
Meek said. ``They know the consequences would be dreadful.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet when Meek hosted Republican Representative Dan Miller at a
town hall meeting Wednesday at a busy Head Start center in her
district, neither she nor any of her constituents raised the issue
with Miller, who is from conservative Sarasota and said he still is
undecided about how he will vote if impeachment comes to the House
floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``My constituents strongly think Clinton should be impeached,''
said Miller, noting that calls and mail in his district, across the
state and light years from the rich ethnic stew of Miami, run ``10
or 20 to 1'' against the president.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton was the first Democratic presidential nominee since
1976 to carry Dade County, which includes Miami and its
fast-growing surrounding suburbs. He wooed the elderly who live in
the handsome high-rises along Biscayne Boulevard, the young and
trendy patrons of the art deco clubs of South Beach, the
middle-class blacks and the struggling new immigrants from Central
America, and even the Cuban-Americans, who have been suspicious of
Democrats since President Kennedy's fiasco at the Bay of Pigs.
</P>
<P>
   Today opinions about the president are as deeply divided along
the Calle Ocho, the heart of Miami's Little Havana, as anywhere in
the country. At any one of the many open-air coffee bars, where
Spanish-speaking patrons sip the strong, sweet cafe Cubano from
tiny cups and sample from cases full of cigars, spirited
conversations turn from the upset victory Sunday of Hugo Chavez,
Venezuela's populist president-elect, to the plight of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is sexual misconduct the kind of high crime the Constitution
intended for impeaching a president?'' asked Dan Alvarez, a college
professor who said he has watched all the congressional hearings
and even read a book on impeachment. ``I think it is quite
appalling and embarrassing to trivialize the process and distort
the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez voted for Clinton in 1996 and thinks he should remain in
office. Raul Tejero, retired from the US Army, also voted for
Clinton and thinks he is a perjurer who should be censured. Tony
Cordero, a real estate agent, didn't vote for Clinton and wishes he
would just resign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the whole process is pretty digusting,'' said Cordero,
whose father, a former Cuban government official, fled in 1959,
after Castro seized power. ``My priorities are my family and my
business. I don't think it would matter at all to me if they threw
Clinton out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-98 1311EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981210.0138 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 13:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2896 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HILLARY-CLINTON-IMAGE     12-10 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-CLINTON-IMAGE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY CLINTON IS NO POLITICAL DUMMY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333; fax, 212-499-3382. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By FLORA LEWIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    PARIS _ People have begun to ask whether Hillary Rodham Clinton
is likely to be elected president of the United States. At this
point, the answer is evidently no, but the question does reflect a
remarkable development in her role and the way she is perceived.
 &HT;    Throughout President Bill Clinton's ordeal by sex-lie scandal,
Mrs. Clinton has carried on as though she had no personal concerns.
Her stamina and her strength have made a huge difference in her
husband's ability to weather the attacks so far.
 &HT;    The troubles aren't quite over yet, but the issue now is more
how congressional Republicans are going to get rid of the
impeachment question than it is the fate of the president. Censure
strikes me as a rather pointless, artificial way of avoiding their
responsibility to conclude what has been started.
 &HT;    The argument that some formal punishment must be imposed to show
that Mr. Clinton earned the disapproval of the legislature and many
compatriots is fatuous. That criticism has already been very widely
recorded.
 &HT;    Some do seem to resent, however, that he has borne it all
without any signs of the emotional distress and self-abasement that
would seem inescapable for most people. He is probably sustained by
the same force of confidence that led him to feel he could ignore
the proprieties and get away with it. That trait got him into
trouble, and it is seeing him through, with Hillary's indispensable
help.
 &HT;    She has gone through several transformations in their years at
the peak of American politics. She wanted to share in the rewards
as well as the effort. There was a lively, joyful modern air of
equality and partnership in their early campaign theme of ``two for
the price of one,'' but it boomeranged. Feminism hasn't won that
much support from Americans.
 &HT;    So she shifted to less assertive, less political subjects,
gentled her style, and made more of the wife-and-mother role which
American political usage seems to demand. But that turned out to be
a lot tougher than the traditional routine, and she responded again
with intense, carefully programmed activity. Now she is on the
cover of Vogue, a first for a presidential wife, and will be Time's
Woman of the Year, and American-watchers around the world are
wondering about her future.
 &HT;    Mrs. Clinton is a fine public speaker, poised, generating
conviction, able to think quickly on her feet. In January this
year, not long after the Monica story broke, she appeared at the
World Economic Forum in Davos to talk about education and
development. She showed no diffidence or embarrassment, and the
several thousand business and political leaders present gave her a
standing ovation.
 &HT;    A question was passed up to her. ``Don't you think it's time for
the U.S. to choose an intelligent, capable woman president?''
Without stopping for breath, she laughed and found the perfect
diplomatic answer. ``Yes, and I look forward to voting for her.''
 &HT;    Clearly, the intention was to lure her into declaring a
candidacy for herself, but she is no political dummy. In current
circumstances, it is hard to imagine her name on a ballot. It would
be fun to see her as vice-presidential candidate on an Al Gore
ticket for 2000, but entertaining the voters isn't what campaign
consultants recommend.
 &HT;    Still, Mrs. Clinton has now established herself as an effective
public figure in her own right, both in the United States and in
the many foreign countries where she has made successful trips. She
is too young, too energetic, too full of ideas, too competent to
disappear politely when she is no longer first lady. There have
been rumors that the couple will split up after they leave the
White House, the aftermath of the scandal, but their pact has
proven extraordinarily solid so far.
 &HT;    The issues that were shoved aside and drowned out by Monicagate
are all still there, and she has developed considerable expertise
in addressing them. No doubt she will find a platform to enable her
to continue, whatever her husband chooses as his next career, for
he will have one.
 &HT;    The nearest thing to a precedent for Mrs. Clinton's
self-launched activism was Eleanor Roosevelt, also a stubborn,
persistent, innovative woman who had to put up with a lot. She was
demeaned, even detested, but she kept on with the humane causes she
thought important and now she is remembered with love and
gratitude.
 &HT;    Just where it will take her isn't clear, but certainly Mrs.
Clinton is not coming to the end of her road in 2000.
 &HT;     (Flora Lewis is the former foreign-affairs columnist for The
New York Times.) 
 &HT;     c.1998 Flora Lewis 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ------------ &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
