to continue, whatever her husband chooses as his next career, for
he will have one.
 &HT;    The nearest thing to a precedent for Mrs. Clinton's
self-launched activism was Eleanor Roosevelt, also a stubborn,
persistent, innovative woman who had to put up with a lot. She was
demeaned, even detested, but she kept on with the humane causes she
thought important and now she is remembered with love and
gratitude.
 &HT;    Just where it will take her isn't clear, but certainly Mrs.
Clinton is not coming to the end of her road in 2000.
 &HT;     (Flora Lewis is the former foreign-affairs columnist for The
New York Times.) 
 &HT;     c.1998 Flora Lewis 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ------------ &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
