<HEADER>
A2906 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DELACROIX-EXHIBIT-HNS     12-10 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELACROIX-EXHIBIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXHIBIT OFFERS A REVEALING NEW LOOK AT DELACROIX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVID BONETTI  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ I'll bet I'm not the only art lover today whose
affection for the work of Eugene Delacroix (1798-1863) is tepid, if
not wholly lacking.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Delacroix: The Late Work,'' the exhibition organized to
commemorate the bicentennial of his birth by the Philadelphia
Museum of Art and the French National Museums, nearly made me love
his work in spite of myself.
</P>
<P>
   Forming with poet Victor Hugo and composer Hector Berlioz, a
triumvirate that defined French Romanticism, Delacroix tends to be
too emotionally extreme for modern tastes. His passion, his
outsized gestures, his theatricality, his love of strife and
violence turn us off as much as they turned on at least some of his
contemporaries. During his lifetime his work was received with
extremes of approval and disdain.
</P>
<P>
   The curators of the exhibition were smart to focus on
Delacroix's late works. With some 70 paintings and 40 works on
paper, the show is sizable but not overwhelming. The big pictures
of his youth _ ``The Death of Sardanapalus'' and ``Liberty Leading
the People'' _ gave Romanticism a set of indelible, iconic images
and gave Delacroix a reputation as a public artist of large
sympathies. Yet for all their self-importance, they prove obstacles
for us to get around today.
</P>
<P>
   During the last 15 years of his life, having retreated from
public battles to his country home, struggling almost continuously
with illness, Delacroix made paintings that are no less
representative. But they tend to be smaller, thus allowing us to
see their virtues through the still frequent bombast.
</P>
<P>
   Even Delacroix's contemporaneous detractors admitted that he was
a terrific painter with an unequaled sense of color, even though he
might have painted with a ``drunken broom.'' Those qualities shine
through still. Delacroix obviously loved his medium, and fans of
later painting from Manet to Van Gogh in which the physicality of
the pigment is not smoothed over will relish Delacroix's articulate
facture.
</P>
<P>
   Although our expectations of color largely derive from the
Impressionists and Post-Impressionists, Delacroix set the example
they sought to equal and outstrip. Intense reds, better to paint
blood, and deep blues dominate his palette, but if you look
closely, you can see how he orchestrated a full spectrum of color
across his canvases.
</P>
<P>
   Covering a concentrated period of 15 years, the exhibition is
organized by theme, and there are sections devoted to animals and
the hunt, Morocco, landscapes, still lifes, literary and
allegorical subjects and religion.
</P>
<P>
   Delacroix was a devoted observer of animals, spending hours
sketching lions, tigers and other exotic beasts at Paris' Jardin
des Plantes, and his obsession with the animal kingdom's ruling
species resulted in some of the best animal painting of all time.
</P>
<P>
   Delacroix's understanding of nature is complex and
unsentimental, and in his view, the animal world is marked by a
Darwinian battle for dominance. The titles tell the story: ``Tiger
Hunt,'' ``Arabs Stalking a Lion,'' ``Lion Stalking Its Prey,''
``Struggle Between a Lion and a Tiger,'' ``Lion Devouring a Rabbit,
``Young Woman Attacked by a Tiger.''
</P>
<P>
   Horses take part in this atavistic call of the wild. One of the
most dramatic paintings in the show is ``Horses Fighting in a
Stable'' (1860), in which a brown horse viciously attacks a white
one with gray markings. The horrific incident was observed by
Delacroix on his 1832 trip to Morocco, and it left a strong
impression that remained vivid nearly 30 years later.
</P>
<P>
   The six-month trip to Morocco in 1832 was one of the deciding
events of Delacroix's life, and in his final years he came back to
impressions made then, often recorded in copious notebooks. The
Moroccan landscape with its walled cities provided him with
opportunities to paint some of his most engaging canvases.
</P>
<P>
   Delacroix painted pictures of what he saw as noble Arabs living
a life closer to that of the ancient Mediterranean world than that
by contemporary Europeans. Beneath azure skies on plains that
stretched between the glistening ocean and distant misty mountains,
they lived close to nature, their horses nearly family members.
</P>
<P>
   As hard as it might be to take his rhetoric seriously, Delacroix
painted this atmosphere convincingly. About ``Horses Coming Out of
the Sea,'' an image of a red-robed Arab leading two horses onto a
stony beach, an 1885 observer wrote, ``I do not believe that the
Impressionist school produced a more luminous morsel, one more
deeply infused with the freshness of morning, veiled in a more
transparent mist.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The least persuasive canvases here are those based on literary
themes. A great reader, Delacroix painted many pictures based on
scenes from Shakespeare, Lord Byron, Goethe, Dante and the Italian
poets Ariosto and Tasso. Today they look like curiously overwrought
illustrations.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest surprise of the exhibition might be the devotion
Delacroix, a professed agnostic, brought to religious subjects. A
number of crucifixions are included, and in this central sacrifice
of Christianity, Delacroix stripped away all superfluities. A
near-naked man, in his mind the savior of mankind, hangs on a cross
_ that is all. Profoundly moving.
</P>
<P>
   Delacroix might very well be the last artist to paint convincing
religious paintings. After him came Courbet, who sullenly said he'd
paint an angel when he saw one. But in several ways, Delacroix was
the last of one line _ and the first of the next. The exhibition
makes clear that he occupied a fulcrum position in Western art. He
inherited Rubens' and the Venetians' atmospheric color and roiling,
pulsing movement, and he passed on his love of the exotic and the
sensuous to Matisse.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ( ``Delacroix: The Late Work'' continues through Jan. 3 at the
Philadelphia Museum of Art. Ticket prices are $10 for adults, $7
for seniors, children 5 to 17 and students. Tuesdays, prices are $1
less. Advanced tickets may be purchased by calling 215-235-7469.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
