<HEADER>
A2907 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS &LR;      12-10 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO REMOVE OLD TILE, INSERT CHISEL AND PRAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am retiling around the tub and backsplash. I am wondering
how I can remove the old tiles? They are set on concrete board and
none is loose that I know of.
</P>
<P>
   GAIL RIEP, Acton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. How easy or difficult the tiles will be to remove depends on
how they are set on the concrete board. If they are set with
adhesive, it should be easy. Insert a chisel at the edge of a tile,
tap with a hammer and it should pop off, or come off with a litle
more tapping. Now, you can scrape off any residual adhesive and put
up the new tiles with the same type of tile adhesive. If the tiles
are set with a thin-set mortar, it will be tougher. Tiles set with
thin-set on concrete board is akin to a mud job; very strong and
difficult to demolish. But you can still try the same technique as
with tiles installed with adhesive. Slip a chisel under an edge and
tap lightly. If the tile does not pop, you will have to keep
tapping and prying, which may break up the tile; then each piece
must be chiseled off. Once removed, scrape off as much of the
thin-set as possible, then install the new tiles with thin-set. You
have to scrape all the old thin-set from the concrete board so the
tiles will lie flat and even.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I inherited an antique bed, but it has no rails. Where can I
find rails?
</P>
<P>
   JOHANNA DONLON, Beverly, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Try the Woodworkers Store; or call the catalog number,
800-279-4441.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. A candle on a windowsill caused a small fire and dripped
sooty wax on a grasscloth wall, leaving a small streak of black wax
on it. How can I remove the black streak?
</P>
<P>
   CONNIE, from Milton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Try scraping it with a credit card held at a slight angle.
Scrape gently to get as much off as possible. Then tape a piece of
brown paper (grocery bag) over the stain and place a warm-to-hot
iron over it; you will see the paper absorb the wax. Repeat as
necessary. Dissolve the rest of the wax, if any, with rubbing
alcohol, but test an obscure area of the grasscloth to make sure
the alcohol does not fade or bleach it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have an 1/8-inch gap between my tongued-and-grooved
floorboards. I'd like to fill them, and a man suggested mixing glue
and sawdust.
</P>
<P>
   CONNIE MAGEE, Wilmington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. The old-fashioned sawdust and glue just might work; the glue
may not get overly hard, and therefore might follow the natural
movement of the boards. I am skeptical, but if it's an
old-fashioned concoction it is likely to work. There is nothing
else you can put in those gaps because they are too shallow (only
1/4-inch deep) for any insertion.
</P>
<P>
   Filling them with a modern filler that hardens also won't work
because when that hard filler breaks up (and it will) it will look
a sight worse than what you have now.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have an arched wall in my shower stall and the shower head
keeps breaking up the plaster, due to thermal expansion and
contraction. I can't put a bell over it because of its arched
shape. What's a practical thing to do?
</P>
<P>
   ROBERT PAYNE, Wellesley, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. You might be able to chip out a bit of the plaster around the
shower-head pipe so that it is flat, and then the bell can fit
snugly around it. Or, chip out any broken-up plaster around the
shower-head pipe and install caulking, which will expand and
contract along with whatever else is expanding and contracting. I
have used PhenoSeal, an adhesive caulk, for many purposes and I
find it works wonderfully. It is paintable, if that is needed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. We received a used refrigerator for our program, and as with
any refrigerator stored for awhile, it had an odor. How can I get
remove that odor?
</P>
<P>
   JANICE ABBATANGELO, Norwood, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Let me count the ways. There are so many of them, almost all
``home remedies,'' that is is hard to suggest just one:
</P>
<P>
   You could wash with a solution of 1 part bleach to 3 parts
water, let dry, then wash with a strong solution of baking soda and
water.
</P>
<P>
   Or, wash with white vinegar. A dish of vinegar or vanilla
extract set on the bottom will help.
</P>
<P>
   Or, put a small amount of sage in a dish and ignite it, then put
the residue in the refrigerator. After five days, wash with baking
soda and air-dry for a week.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the odor is caused by the gaskets and door edges, so
be sure to treat those, too. Soak a ball of cotton with vanilla
extract and wipe all the gaskets and around all the doors.
</P>
<P>
   As you are doing all these things, keep the door open for good
air drying.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107. The
Handyman chats on line Thursdays, 1-2 p.m, at
http://www.boston.com, keyword: Chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-98 1314EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981210.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2911 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INSANITY-DEFENSE-BOS &LR;      12-10 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSANITY-DEFENSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GAMBLE FOR THE DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RIC KAHN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Eric Brown, accused in a double murder, is set to play
a Jekyll-Hyde role in a real-life courtroom scene that could match
the high drama of the 19th century tale of good and evil trapped
within one soul.
</P>
<P>
   Exploring an insanity defense that could help his client avoid
life in prison, attorney Bernard Grossberg hopes to display
conflicting faces of the 30-year-old first-degree murder suspect,
who is charged with gunning down two gay men on a gaslit South End
street in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   If Grossberg gets his way, a jury will get to see what he says
are the two sides of the Roxbury man. One is a jumpsuited suicidal
schizophrenic being held at Bridgewater State Hospital. The other
is a stable defendant in a jacket and tie, whose handshake is as
firm as his grasp of the legal hurdles he will face in court, now
that he's taking antipsychotic medicine twice a day.
</P>
<P>
   In a case that blends potential plot lines from TV's ``Law &AMP;
Order'' and ``ER,'' Grossberg last week asked a Suffolk Superior
Court judge to allow Brown to temporarily stop taking his
normalizing drug regimen so Grossberg and doctors can view _ and a
videographer can tape _ Brown in his full-blown psychotic state.
</P>
<P>
   Then, using the doctors' assessments and video as evidence,
Grossberg could present an insanity defense that argues that
although a medicated Brown now is sane enough to stand trial, he
once may have been so tortured from hearing inner voices that he
couldn't keep himself from killing.
</P>
<P>
   Under Grossberg's proposal, by letting his mind be bent back to
the depths of paranoia, Brown could help set himself free from the
lifetime in prison a first-degree murder conviction would bring.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will make him mentally ill,'' Grossberg sighed at the
thought of having to manipulate his client's mind to balance the
scales of justice. ``But if he's found not guilty by reason of
insanity, he doesn't get punished _ he gets treated. Presumably he
could get better and be released. Right now, time is going by.''
</P>
<P>
   A hearing on Grossberg's unusual request is scheduled before
Judge Peter M. Lauriat on Dec. 10, the prelude to a full trial that
could start as early as spring.
</P>
<P>
   The Commonwealth has not yet filed its response. David Meier,
chief of the Suffolk district attorney's homicide unit, this week
declined to talk specifically about the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am confident that when all the facts are presented at trial
that Mr. Brown will be held fully accountable for his conduct,''
Meier said.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Brown had displayed erratic behavior before he was
diagnosed as a paranoid schizophrenic following the slayings on
Appleton Street, according to his lawyer and family.
</P>
<P>
   He worked as a lab technician at Massachusetts General Hospital
and liked to dance and play checkers after hours. But he also once
allegedly tried to run a woman over with her own car and displayed
a fascination with firearms.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say that on June 15, 1996, Brown fired a 20-gauge
shotgun into the air near his home.
</P>
<P>
   Early the next day, prosecutors say, Brown headed for Appleton
Street, a late-night gay cruising area they say he had frequented.
</P>
<P>
   First, prosecutors say, Brown allegedly pumped two shots into
Athos Oliveira, 30, as the Somerville optometrist stood on the
sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   As he fled, prosecutors say, Brown allegedly crossed paths with
Thomas Meyer, a 38-year-old marketing executive from San Francisco
who was in Boston for a friend's wedding. Police say Brown fired a
fatal shot into Meyer's face.
</P>
<P>
   Ten days later, police officers in Lincoln stopped Brown for
what they said was a routine motor vehicle violation. Inside the
van he was driving, they found a shotgun. Ballistics specialists
later matched the weapon to the shots fired.
</P>
<P>
   Brown was charged with both killings. In court papers,
prosecutors have not specified a motive.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after his arrest, Brown was deemed a danger to himself, and
was transferred from the Nashua Street Jail to Bridgewater State
Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   There, he was prescribed an initial series of antipsychotic
drugs that didn't work, Grossberg said. Brown, he said, was distant
and spoke nonsense, unable to answer simple questions from his
lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   In April, a judge determined that Brown was not competent to
stand trial and ordered him back to Bridgewater.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, however, doctors gave Brown a new set of drugs.
Since then, Grossberg said, Brown's mind has come alive, and he has
been able to focus on his own legal matters _ including whether he
should stop taking his medicine.
</P>
<P>
   In October, a mental health supervisor at the hospital filed a
report recommending that Brown was competent to stand trial.
</P>
<P>
   Now, hoping to test whether Brown was not criminally responsible
for his actions and thus a candidate for an insanity defense,
Grossberg wants to send him on a journey back through his own
psychoses, to perhaps be haunted once again by the voices only he
can hear.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
