<HEADLINE>
YOUNG UNLIKELY CANDIDATES FOR REPETITIVE STRAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY FOREMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Children who play on new kiddie computers are unlikely to suffer
repetitive strain injuries such as carpal tunnel syndrome because,
unlike adults, they don't usually sit still at a computer hour
after hour, day in and day out.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's the prediction of Robert Follansbee, director of
the computer learning program in the communication enhancement
center at Children's Hospital in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is some evidence that kids using video games get some
RSI,'' he says, referring to repetitive strain injury, but ``that's
with a huge amount of use. It seems unlikely that most kids would
use a computer intensively enough to develop'' the problems that
adults or college students do. ``Many difficulties that adults get
come from massive amounts of touch typing day after day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most kids don't use the keyboard that way. They type slower
and not for long periods of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Children also tend not to stay seated in the same position for
hours on end the way adults do. Instead, they get up and down and
move around, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Whether small children would be better off doing something other
than using computers is another question, and one for which there
are no clear answers yet because computers designed for children
are so new.
</P>
<P>
   The American Academy of Pediatrics has no guidelines for
computer use among small children. It does say, however, that ``the
amount of time that a child spends watching TV is a major concern.
If your child spends three to four hours a day watching TV, then
time for other activities is limited.'' The academy advises
limiting children's screen time _ including video games _ to less
than two hours a day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
