<SLUG> BC-MEDNOTES-SCI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
_BRAIN DATA ECHOES `FIRST DO NO HARM'   
 _LEAD EFFECTS SEEN TO SADDLE CHILDREN   
 _TUMOR-STARVING DRUG TO BE TESTED  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Brain data echoes `first do no harm'
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A cerebral aneurysm, sometimes called a ``time bomb in the
brain,'' presents one of the most difficult medical questions:
whether to operate before it ruptures or to leave it alone.
</P>
<P>
   When aneurysms, or the ballooning of weak spots in blood
vessels, rupture suddenly, they are often fatal or severely
damaging to the brain. But the risks of surgery are also
significant. A study suggests that many asymptomatic brain
aneurysms _ especially smaller ones _ have a low risk of rupture,
and doing nothing may be best.
</P>
<P>
   A report in The New England Journal of Medicine on a sample of
2,621 patients in the United States, Canada, and Europe concludes
that the risks of surgery outweigh the benefits in some people who
have brain aneurysms less than 10 millimeters (a bit less than half
an inch) in diameter. For those who have had previous bleeding in
the brain, the risk of another aneurysm bursting is higher and may
be a reason for preventive surgery, said the investigators, led by
Dr. David O. Wiebers at the Mayo Clinic.
</P>
<P>
   More and more aneurysms are being found incidentally during
brain scans, and are posing dilemmas, said Dr. John Marler, a
neurologist at the National Institute of Neurological Disorders and
Stroke, who supervised the trial.
</P>
<P>
   The findings, he said in an interview, ``will come as a
tremendous relief to patients and physicians advising them''
because they provide more information on which to base a decision.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lead effects seen to saddle children
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cognitive deficits caused by environmental lead in early
childhood are largely irreversible, with children failing to
improve very much even when the exposure to lead is reduced,
according to a study from Australia.
</P>
<P>
   The authors of a report in the Journal of the American Medical
Association said children in families living near a lead smelter in
Port Pirie, South Australia, have been tested for lead in their
blood and monitored for cognitive performance beginning in 1979. In
general, the lead levels in children's blood declined substantially
after age 2, though some children still had high levels at 11 to
13, said the researchers from the Queensland University of
Technology in Brisbane.
</P>
<P>
   The cognitive scores of children who had the biggest drop in
lead exposure were only slightly better than those of children
whose blood lead concentration declined the least, said the
authors, suggesting the cognitive damage was largely irreversible.
</P>
<P>
   The findings, the authors wrote, make it ``increasingly
important'' to reduce exposure to lead from an early age.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Tumor-starving drug to be tested
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The National Cancer Institute has agreed to test a drug made
from shark cartilage that starves tumors of their blood supply, and
which is considered an alternative or complementary treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The drug, known as AE-941/Neovastat, will be given in
combination with radiation and chemotherapy to more than 250
patients with inoperable lung cancer, said Dr. James Pluda, a
research official at the institute, in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   The drug is made by Aeterna Laboratories Inc. of Sainte-Foy,
Quebec, and has previously been tested in animals and in patients
with cancer in advanced stages.
</P>
<P>
   Pluda said that part of the funding for the trial comes from the
National Institutes of Health's Center for Alternative Medicine.
The hope, he said, is that the drug _ one of a promising category
of agents called angiogenesis inhibitors because they block blood
vessel growth _ will work in combination with conventional
treatments to prolong patients' survival.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
