<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2935 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIA-NOTES-BOS &LR;      12-10 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-NOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKING FOR LESSONS IN THE HUFFINGTONN PARADOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Somewhere, there's a moral to this story.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 3, pundit Arianna Huffington wrote a column in which she
decried the media's interest in the life of the loins. Fuming that
ABC's Diane Sawyer had quizzed Kenneth Starr about his sex life on
``20/20,'' Huffington wrote, ``We are clearly not going to be able
to stop the media from asking inappropriate questions about the sex
lives of public figures. So it's up to the figures themselves to
stop answering them.''
</P>
<P>
   Just three days later, The Washington Post broke the news that
Huffington's ex-husband Michael had answered one of those questions
in the January issue of Esquire. In an interview with David Brock _
a journalist who came out of the closet in a 1994 interview with
the Post _ Huffington, who as a conservative Republican lost a 1994
California Senate race, acknowledged his homosexuality after
decades of personal turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   Huffington ``wants you to know that all the other things you may
know him for _ getting a Harvard MBA . . . being a
multimillionaire, marrying Arianna Stassinopoulos, serving in
Congress, running for the Senate _ pale in comparison with the
thing he's doing right now,'' writes Brock. Brock knows about such
epiphanies. Not only did he publicly announce his homosexuality.
Earlier this year, the one-time Clinton-basher who first unearthed
Paula Jones in an American Spectator story, apologized for invading
the president's personal life.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not the only strange twist. In the January Esquire
story, Brock says a deeply unhappy Huffington actually wanted to
lose his 1994 Senate challenge to Democrat Dianne Fienstein _ a
strange race in which he spent nearly $30 million of his own money
and was widely dismissed as an enigmatic empty suit being
manipulated by Arianna, his Svengali wife. While Arianna eagerly
courted attention in the campaign, Michael ducked for cover _ and
paid the price. The American Journalism Review concluded that ``Not
Richard Nixon, not even Dan Quayle was pummeled by the press the
way Rep. Michael Huffington was.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, after word of Huffington's disclosures, the
San Jose Mercury News ran a story saying rumors of his sexuality
were well-known within journalistic and political circles back in
1994. Why didn't word seep out then? ``Lack of relevance,
professional restraint and in the end, stonewalling from the
candidate himself,'' said the Mercury News.
</P>
<P>
   Arianna has a point in her Dec. 3 column. We have clumsily
trespassed on the boundary between public figures and private
lives. And the press's decision not to go with the 1994 Huffington
rumors seems a rare nod to their better angels.
</P>
<P>
   But in light of this week's events, perhaps Huffington would
have been better off confessing to Brock five years ago. It would
have saved him considerable personal anguish, $30 million, and the
nastiest press pounding in recent memory.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of people who looked at me (strangely) when I
started this,'' says Tripp Jones. And with good reason. The
executive director of the nonpartisan think tank, MassInc. bucked a
tidal wave of conventional wisdom when he began publishing
CommonWealth magazine in April 1996.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when public interest in government is noticeably
waning, CommonWealth bills itself as the magazine of ``politics,
ideas and civic life in Massachusetts.'' (In the recent past, two
other local political journals _ Otherwise and Beacon Hill _ have
gone belly up.) In this age of mega-media conglomerates, the
quarterly periodical has an annual budget of about $250,000. And
the magazine's motto as espoused by editor Dave Denison _ ``We will
print nothing stupid'' _ doesn't quite have that austere New York
Timesian ring.
</P>
<P>
   But with 10 issues under its belt, an impressive list of
sponsors from Bell Atlantic to the Massachusetts AFL-CIO, a
masthead that includes Nieman Foundation curator Bill Kovach and
former Globe editor Tom Winship as advisers, and a savvy
sensibility for mixing policy and personality (such disparate
luminaries as Mo Vaughn and Tommy Finneran have graced its cover),
CommonWealth is a legitmate good news story.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the credit goes to Dennison, who is attempting a feat
that has eluded most of our political leaders _ convincing citizens
that ``there are real connections between what happens in the
public sphere and what happens in people's lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The current issue reflects CommonWealth's quirky recipe for
readability. Throw in a helping of serious policy: a cover story on
how the ``new urbanism'' _ a concept for constructing communities
to physically enhance neighborhood empowerment and interaction _ is
being tried in places like Mashpee and Holyoke. Add a smidgeon of
spice: a provocative, if self-serving piece on the local media's
failings in covering state government. And bring out the dessert: a
engagingly voyeuristic feature matching local millionaires to their
mansions. (The winner is former Continental Cablevision CEO Amos
Hostetter Jr. who resides in a $1.87 million Louisburg Square
townhouse.)
</P>
<P>
   Right now, CommonWealth is more inside baseball than household
word, with nearly 90 percent of its 6,500 copies mailed to a target
audience of activists, pols, and policy makers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you run into people who haven't heard of
CommonWealth and that's frustrating,'' says associate editor Carol
Gerwin. It deserves better than to be a well-kept secret.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
