<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-NANKING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIARY OF THE `SCHINDLER OF NANKING' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
THE GOOD MAN OF NANKING 
The Diaries of John Rabe 
Edited by John Wickert; translated, from the German, by John E.
Woods 
Knopf, 294 pp., illustrated, $26 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As conquering Japanese troops swept down on the Chinese capital
city of Nanking in September 1937, every person who could do so
fled _ Chinese officials, professionals, businessmen, foreign
diplomats. Everyone, that is, except for the poor, and a handful of
Western businessmen and missionaries who remained behind to protect
and care for those who could not flee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rich are fleeing, the poor must remain behind'' in grave
danger ``of being slaughtered in great numbers,'' wrote German
businessman John Rabe in his diary. ``Shouldn't one make an attempt
to help them? Save a few at least?'' Rabe did stay, and did save
many more than a few from the horrific event that is known as ``the
rape of Nanking.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabe's diaries, in which he recorded in vivid detail the horror
that took the lives of at least 260,000 people, were a major source
for Iris Chang's 1997 bestseller, ``The Rape of Nanking,'' in which
she calls Rabe ``the Oscar Schindler of Nanking.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabe was an ``old China hand'' in 1937, having ``gone out'' (as
they used to say) in 1909 as a representative of the German
manufacturing firm, Siemens. Like many expatriates of his day, Rabe
never learned Chinese but studied the culture and collected its
art. He was recalled to Germany in 1938 after the worst was over in
Nanking and died in 1950. The editor had met Rabe in Nanking in
1936 and was later Germany's ambassador to China.
</P>
<P>
   The diaries are of primary interest for their eyewitness account
of the Japanese terror. Rabe tells of driving through the streets
and seeing the decomposing bodies being ravaged by dogs. He tells
of looting by Japanese soldiers, often as their officers looked on.
And he records the literal ``rape of Nanking.'' ``You can't breathe
for sheer revulsion,'' he writes, ``when you keep finding the
bodies'' of women who had been raped, multilated, and killed.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these events were also reported by the few foreign
journalists allowed to remain in Nanking, but Rabe is the principal
witness for the efforts that he organized to protect Chinese
civilians. The major effort being the establishment of a safety
zone in which at one time or another some 250,000 Chinese were
protected, fed, and housed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just received a Christmas present better than any I could
have wished for,'' he wrote on Dec. 26. ``I have been given 600
human lives'' _ men who were to have been shot as suspected
ex-Chinese soldiers but for whom Rabe was able to secure refugee
status.
</P>
<P>
   Unexpectedly but movingly, the diaries are also revealing of the
thoughts of a rather ordinary man caught up in horrifying events.
``If I were to write that I was not afraid, I'd be lying.'' But
fear, he writes, ``is there to be conquered.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabe also records events that will strike the reader as nothing
less than bizarre. Rabe had great hopes that Hitler would intervene
with the Japanese to stop the killing. But while those hopes were
unfounded, Rabe did flash his swastika armband at Japanese soldiers
when the occasion demanded.
</P>
<P>
   Even more surprising were the relations with Japanese officials.
Just four days after Rabe records with revulsion that ``the body of
that Chinese soldier shot while tied to a bamboo sofa is still
lying out in the street,'' he reports attending a dinner at the
Japanese Embassy along with eight other members of the
international committee that operated the security zone. It ``went
off without incident,'' he reports.
</P>
<P>
   And amid the horror, he finds the macabre. The Japanese ``have
come up with the fabulous idea of erecting a military bordello,''
he writes with a note of sarcasm. ``With hands clenched in
horror,'' Minnie Vautrin, an American woman member of his
committee, ``is forced to watch'' as Japanese force their way into
the assembly hall of the Ginling Girls College (where just 10 days
before some 100 young women had been raped). But ``lo and
behold!,'' a number of young women step forward. ``Evidently former
prostitutes, who are not at all sad to find work in a new bordello.
Minnie is speechless!''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, John Rabe's diaries _ and the letters and reports that
he included in them _ are primary source materials for the history
of World War II. But they are equally important as a document of
the power of the human will.
</P>
<P>
   On a day after he had heard ``thunder of cannons, rifle and
machine-gun fire'' all night long, Rabe reports that an American
missionary was reluctant to open a Red Cross station without
approval from the Red Cross. ``What a shame!'' he writes. ``In his
shoes I wouldn't think twice. If you can do some good, why
hesitate?'' A quarter-million Chinese survived the horror of
Nanking because John Rabe didn't hesitate to act.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
