<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARROLL WILL SEE WHAT MIGHT HAVE BEEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ On those days when he is cast into the
shadow of Bill Parcells and his shortcomings are endlessly
scrutinized, Pete Carroll probably wishes he had taken the St.
Louis Rams' coaching job.
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   After going 10-6 and taking the Patriots to the second round of
the playoffs a year ago, and now overcoming a 5-5 start to win the
last three games, Carroll must realize he made the right choice two
years ago when the Rams were pursuing him along with New England.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll took a lot of heat during the courting process with Rams
president John Shaw when it was reported that he had made
exorbitant demands _ like Super Bowl tickets, luxury boxes, and
other perks _ in an effort to force St. Louis's hand, thus ensuring
him a great deal in the Midwest or leaving a clear field for the
Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can produce the proposal to show that what came out was
bull,'' said Carroll Wednesday. ``The guy (Shaw) said to me, `Would
you take the job if it was offered to you?' I said, `I can't take
it right now as presented. I need more information.' And there was
a lot of business that had to take place. I wasn't ready to take
it. Plus, John Shaw is a big-time business guy. He's very shrewd,
and I wasn't going to deal with him on any of the business issues
because he'd eat me up.''
</P>
<P>
   After what Carroll described as a ``great interview'' that left
him completely impressed with Shaw, owner Georgia Frontiere, and
the entire Rams organization, he had his agent, Gary Uberstine,
take over the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got my guy to talk to him the next day,'' said Carroll, who
at the time was the 49ers' defensive coordinator. ``A couple of
days later, a release comes out about all of these demands. It came
out of nowhere about all these crazy things I'm asking for, and it
wasn't even close to being accurate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called John and I said, `What is this?' And he apologized
and said he didn't have anything to do with it and didn't know
where it came from and reinforced to me that it had nothing to do
with us. He said if anyone called about it, he would tell them
exactly what happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really angry about it. It wasn't true and it made me
look like a jerk. It came from somebody else who was trying to get
the job. Somebody who was representing somebody else put that out,
because Shaw swore he didn't say anything about it. It was once
again a big media thing that you can't do anything about.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get slammed and there's nothing you can do about it.
John's a heck of a guy and he didn't do it. Nobody ever called me
to ask me about it. It just hit the Philadelphia papers and
everyone ran with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots job hadn't become open, but all the signs pointed
to a nasty divorce between Parcells and New England owner Bob
Kraft. Carroll held out and declined the St. Louis job, which
ultimately went to Dick Vermeil, who went 6-10 last year and is
3-10 entering Sunday's matchup against . . . Carroll's Patriots,
who are in prime playoff contention again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad the way it turned out,'' said Carroll. ``At the time,
I wasn't ready to do that (in St. Louis) and I was hoping something
else would happen that I would have the opportunity to go for. (The
Rams) wanted someone to take the job right away. Nobody took the
job right off.''
</P>
<P>
   Now for the first time since he made his choice, Carroll faces
the Rams and Vermeil.
</P>
<P>
   It would be difficult to guess how Carroll would have fared with
the Rams. Certainly, there wouldn't have been the media scrutiny he
faces in New England, where some look at his job status as game to
game, when in actuality, it has never been in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the way he has led the Patriots back from near oblivion
has put him very much in the driver's seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is that after this year, I have three years left on
my contract, and I'm very happy about that,'' said Carroll. ``I
love this job and this situation.''
</P>
<P>
   After keeping the Patriots up the last three weeks, he must
guard against a letdown against the Rams, who have beaten the Jets
and the Bills and lost to the Dolphins. He knows any era of good
feeling could go up in smoke if the Patriots lose Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've done things against teams in our division that some of
us haven't been able to do,'' said Carroll. ``The first five or six
games, they played very well and then they had some people hurt and
it got away from them. But we have an opportunity to go in there
and play hard and come away with a road win. The entire NFL season
has proved to us that anyone can beat anybody else on any given
week. Our guys are well aware of that. We've talked about that all
week, and there'll be no letdowns on the part of our players.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll warned about the Rams' defense, calling it ``very
strong. They're No. 1 in the NFC against the pass. They have guys
like Todd Lyght and Ryan McNeil who are very good (defensive)
backs.''
</P>
<P>
   He also warned that quarterback Tony Banks ``is a very mobile
guy. He can make big plays.'' And he said that despite the absence
of Isaac Bruce, their best athlete on offense, he is worried about
Bruce's replacement, Eddie Kennison, who has caught only 15 passes
this year but in the past has been a big factor.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll plans to do some things in practice to help improve some
problem areas. For one, he expects to use a game clock because he
felt the team ``lost concentration of the game clock on some
delay-of-game penalties.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive coordinator Steve Sidwell, who along with Carroll came
up with an effective plan to stop the Steelers last week, credits
Carroll for keeping the team in the hunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``People just don't understand him,'' said Sidwell. ``He'll
probably never get his due until he wins a Super Bowl, but I've
been on a lot of teams and coached under a lot of different guys.
I've never seen a guy who practices harder and prepares better for
an opponent than Pete. He's won the respect of a lot of people
around here. Nobody wants to write that, but that's the truth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
