<HEADLINE>
CELL-PHONE SET NEEDS TO GET THE MESSAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mobile phones. You love them. Well, maybe you love them.
Possibly you hate them, at least when they're in the wrong hands,
and they so often seem to be in the wrong hands.
</P>
<P>
   Why can't people shut up? Would it kill them not to be in
constant telephone contact? Would their lives fall apart if they
weren't able to jabber on their phones in restaurants, theaters,
concert halls, trains, cars? Don't they know they're bothering
other people? Or don't they care?
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to ``Wireless Etiquette: A Guide to the Changing
World of Instant Communication,'' a little book on a big subject,
by Peter Laufer. I reached the author on his mobile phone, on the
road, in Mill Valley, California. ``I'm on the highway,'' he said,
``Let me do what my book instructs and pull over so I won't kill
myself and others.''
</P>
<P>
   That's nice, I thought. A man who practices what he preaches. At
least when he gives interviews. Laufer said he's a self-appointed
expert on mobile phones, having used them for more than 20 years.
``Wireless Etiquette'' is published by Omnipoint, distributors of
digital wireless phone service. According to a press release, the
book is based on ``a simple notion _ that as our technology often
develops faster than our ability to cope with it, we need to agree
on some rules of common courtesy.''
</P>
<P>
   We may need to agree, but can we?
</P>
<P>
   Reaction to the book has been good, Laufer said. ``It's a
universal subject. Everybody has a cell phone story.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. I have several, most of which involve nearly getting
killed by somebody driving and talking on a phone at the same time.
In ``Wireless Etiquette'' Laufer lays down the basic rule for using
a car phone: Driving comes first, talking second.
</P>
<P>
   This is a difficult notion for some people to grasp. The
problem, he says, is that people become so involved in their phone
conversations that they tend to lose touch with what's going on
around them, whether it's a truck bearing down on them or a couple
trying to have a quiet conversation at the next table. ``Often they
don't realize they're being rude,'' Laufer said, ``they're doing it
mindlessly, because of the intensity of the relationship we have
with the telephone.''
</P>
<P>
   So they don't mean to be rude, they just are rude. The basic
problem, as Laufer writes, is lack of common sense, often perceived
as lack of common courtesy, hence the need for ``Wireless
Etiquette.''
</P>
<P>
   Laufer lists places where mobile phones should never be used,
among them, lecture halls, churches, classrooms, concerts, live
performances, movies, crowded elevators. Restaurants are not on
Laufer's list of phone-free zones, even though he says that,
personally, he finds people who talk on cell phones in restaurants
``really offensive.'' If you must take calls in a restaurant, he
advises, answer the phone as you're excusing yourself from the
table, ask the caller to hold on for a few seconds until you find
an appropriate place to talk, an alcove, the street, a telephone
booth.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, cell phone users are being asked politely, or
coerced, into switching off their instruments. As Laufer notes, all
over the world, more and more places are prohibiting the use of
mobile phones. In Milan, Italy, a sign at La Scala instructs
opera-goers to leave ``telefonini'' in the checkroom. At Carnegie
Hall, the program asks that cellular phones be turned off during
performances, or left at home. In the U.K., phone-proof railway
cars have been introduced for passengers who don't want to be
disturbed by mobile phone callers. In Japan, mobile phone jammers
are selling almost as briskly as mobile phones.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, jammers are illegal in the U.S. Instead, we have
``Wireless Etiquette.'' Will anyone take heed? That remains to be
seen. Meanwhile, drive cautiously.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-98 1334EST &QL; 
