<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKI-WEATHER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER A SLOW START, RESORTS HAVE NO TIME TO WASTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Question for a strange season: How long does it take a ski area
to recover from a heat wave of historic proportions and deliver
enough skiing to get through one of the major vacation periods?
</P>
<P>
   Last Monday, if you weren't in a canoe in the north country
mountains, you might have been swimming for your life. Certainly
skis were useless.
</P>
<P>
   Following a season that started with a bang _ last year's
Thanksgiving dump throughout ski country, a modern record for so
much so early _ this year's late and long Indian summer could have
been a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it had gone on much longer,'' said Barbara Thomke of
Smugglers Notch Resort in Vermont, ``we'd have worried.''
</P>
<P>
   With Christmas about two weeks away, and some vacations
beginning sooner than that, it took a seasoned eye and long memory
to recognize that weather extremes rarely hold on very long, and
not get rattled about the warm spell. But at least one
climatologist, Cliff Harris from northern Vermont, sees a favorable
trend for snow lovers this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``For every extreme,'' said Harris, whose business, Harris &AMP;
Mann Climatology, is used by several ski areas and about 2,000
farmers in the Northeast, ``there is an opposite extreme. We're in
a La Nina period, and when that happens it reverses the El Nino
pattern.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: In the second half of the season _ January to April
_ we'll have well above average snow and cold.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, all ski areas really want at this point is a string
of nights in the 20s in order to keep the snow guns running.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be all right,'' said Sugarloaf's Jim Costello, who
acknowledges that the 55-degree period was not a pleasant
experience at the sprawling destination resort in central Maine.
``At least,'' he said, ``we didn't get any rain.''
</P>
<P>
   Sugarloaf managed to keep 18 trails open through the tepid
spell, including a halfpipe for boarders _ a rare sight in such
warmth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're into heavy snow production right now,'' said Costello.
``We've been able to make snow most nights (since), and by
Christmas time we'll have all terrain on all areas off the Summit
Chair and several off King Pine Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   The warmth melted away so much hard-earned machine snow at some
areas that it actually closed a few.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to close _ suspend ski operations last Friday and
Saturday,'' said Thomke. ``On Monday, it was 69 degrees, and by
Tuesday it was 17 and snowing. Incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomke said Smugglers Notch subscribes to Harris &AMP; Mann and has
been reassured that the heavy dump is on its way before the end of
the year. But in case it's late, Smugglers, which is across a
mountain pass from Stowe (they connect at one point), is under way
rebuilding snow on all its terrain in time for the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have plenty of snow,'' said Thomke, ``but it would be
nice to get a dump of natural. It just looks and feels so much
better around here with snow on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   And if the unthinkable happened, as it has throughout ski
country on rare occasions, and a holiday meltdown should occur? At
Smugglers, whose Christmas bookings are strong this year, a whole
range of alternatives is brought into play _ from volleyball to
miniature golf _ from the resort's off-season activity menu.
</P>
<P>
   But no one is thinking in that direction yet, least of all
Harris. ``The warmest weather is over with,'' he said. ``Cold waves
peak with the full moon cycle, and that means it will be 10 below
zero early in January.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris claims that in 85 percent of the years that have started
with a warm spell such as the one New England experienced last
week, the second half of the season is colder and snowier that
usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``El Nino reverses everything,'' he said. ``Last year (an El
Nino season), we started with a big snowstorm at Thanksgiving, but
it got warm and there was a snow drought later.
</P>
<P>
   ``With La Nina, it takes the normal pattern to extremes. In
'93-94 and in '95-96, from January to April, it broke records. And
the same with '82-83: We got blizzard after blizzard. That's what
kind of winter we're into this year.''
</P>
<P>
   All of which is encouraging news to Rene Reimer and her
boyfriend, Scott Barry, who managed to snowboard at Waterville
Valley the weekend after Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked terrible,'' said Reimer. ``You didn't see any snow
driving up, until you got there, got on the lift, and up some
elevation. Then it was amazing; the snow was pretty good. I mean,
for the first day, it was great.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost as much as real snow drought, ski area managers fear the
perception of snowlessness. At Okemo, where Pam Crukshank went from
hitting golf balls last weekend to scraping the thick snow off her
car on Tuesday, reservations for Christmas vacation are up 17
percent over last year's high.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all spoiled by last season's big early storms,'' said
Crukshank, whose area gave out $20 coupons to skiers who bought
tickets during the meltdown last week. ``We want to get those
skiers back here. It would be nice to get some snow in people's
backyards.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
