<SLUG> BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIMAGGIO _ AN ATHLETE TURNED ICON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He's fighting for his life in a Florida hospital. There are
daily updates on his condition, and fear exists that 84-year-old
Joe DiMaggio may not recover. Young people perhaps don't understand
why there is so much concern about an ex-ballplayer who last played
in 1951.
</P>
<P>
   This is why Joe DiMaggio matters . . .
</P>
<P>
   He's up there with Kennedy, Nixon, Sinatra, Elvis, and Brando
among the compelling American figures of the century. DiMaggio is
the rare US sports figure who seamlessly crosses into popular
culture.
</P>
<P>
   People who know nothing about baseball know of the great
DiMaggio. Try this quiz on your non-sport-fan friends: Name four
things about Joe DiMaggio that have nothing to do with baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Answers:
</P>
<P>
   1. He was married to Marilyn Monroe (men generally come up with
this answer first).
</P>
<P>
   2. He was ``Mr. Coffee.''
</P>
<P>
   3. Paul Simon wrote, ``Where have you gone, Joe DiMaggio?'' in
``Mrs. Robinson,'' part of the soundtrack for ``The Graduate.''
</P>
<P>
   4. Ernest Hemingway wrote about him in ``The Old Man and the
Sea.''
</P>
<P>
   All the above suggest that in addition to winning three MVP
Awards and appearing in 10 World Series, Joe D contributed to an
Academy Award, a Grammy, and a Nobel Prize. His second wife was the
first Playboy centerfold, and he may be the only athlete who could
simultaneously grace the covers of Sports Illustrated, Life, Look,
People, Esquire, Rolling Stone, Ad Week, Premiere, and the New York
Times Book Review.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what Santiago has to say about Joe in ``The Old Man and
the Sea'': ``The great DiMaggio is himself again . . . I would like
to take the great DiMaggio fishing . . . Do you believe the great
DiMaggio would stay with a fish as long as I will stay with this
one? . . . I think the great DiMaggio would be proud of me today .
. . San Pedro was a fisherman as was the father of the great
DiMaggio.''
</P>
<P>
   Amazing. Muhammad Ali and Michael Jordan may be as big, but as
great as Ted Williams and Mickey Mantle were, they never touched so
many areas of American life. This is why DiMaggio is important.
Every time we lose a giant like Joe D, our country is another step
removed from a time when celebrities were famous for more than 15
minutes and people were accountable for their actions. There was a
grace and dignity about DiMaggio that's totally absent in today's
crotch-grabbing, end-zone-dancing sports culture.
</P>
<P>
   Ted was Joe D's contemporary rival. They fought for supremacy in
the American League (the Yankees almost always won), MVP crowns,
and the distinction as the best ballplayer. The two men could
hardly have been more different, and they carried their differences
into retirement. While Ted became more gregarious in his later
years, DiMaggio withdrew even further. When David Halberstam,
perhaps the finest historian of his generation, solicited
interviews with members of the 1949 Red Sox and Yankees, DiMaggio
was the only person on either team who resisted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe's a great guy,'' Rex Barney, the late Brooklyn Dodgers
pitcher, used to say. ``He just hates to be bothered.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Joe D got off some pretty good quotes in his day. When
Miss Marilyn came back from a tour of US Army bases in Korea, she
said, ``Joe, you never heard such cheering,'' and DiMaggio replied,
``Yes, I have.''
</P>
<P>
   When a reporter asked DiMaggio what kind of salary he would
command in the modern market under George Steinbrenner, DiMaggio
said, ``I would have sat down and said, `George, you and I are
about to become partners.' ''
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio played with Lou Gehrig. That alone makes him important.
When Cal Ripken saved baseball in the post-strike summer of 1995,
DiMaggio was summoned for Ripken's historic consecutive game No.
2,131. As ever, he insisted on being introduced as ``the greatest
living ballplayer.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe DiMaggio matters because he gave Italian Americans great
pride when he patrolled center field for the Yankees in the 1940s.
He matters because he hit in 56 consecutive games in 1941. He
matters because, with Williams, he is the link to the great
Yankee-Red Sox rivalries of the 1940s. He matters because he
attached his name to a Florida children's hospital where the motto
is, ``Whether rich or poor, no child is turned away.''
</P>
<P>
   The most private of men, despite his celebrity, he no doubt
would hate these daily disclosures of his medical condition.
</P>
<P>
   But Joe D matters. He is, after all, the great DiMaggio.
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
