<SLUG> BC-FBN-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KRAFT ENCOUNTERS LITTLE RESISTANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn _ Bob Kraft should be on the phone. He should be
talking to Allied. Or Ryder. Or the family moving company down the
street. He can wait for the voters of Connecticut to speak
officially, if he wants. He'll be wasting his time. The Patriots
are definitely moving to Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft came to a brick building at the corner of Capitol and
Broad Streets Wednesday. He and others were led to believe that
people would be throwing political bricks during a public hearing
at the state's legislative offices. Many would be unhappy and
angry. They would tell the Patriots owner that he can't come here,
relax in a posh $350 million stadium constructed with their money,
and contribute to their community by depositing his excess cash in
a local bank.
</P>
<P>
   So just before 4 p.m., Kraft sat at a table and faced his
legislative interrogators. It wasn't exactly Sharon Stone facing
the firing squad in ``Basic Instinct.'' That's not to say there
wasn't opposition. Representative Ernie Newton from Bridgeport
spent all day saying he had a problem with Kraft not spending his
own money to move his team to Connecticut. And Newton would
eventually say, ``He was willing to put up $200 million of his own
money in Boston. He ain't puttin' up jack here. This is a home run
for Kraft. If it wasn't, he'd be keeping his behind in Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   These may be fierce words for the locals to hear. But Kraft and
his son Jonathan must have been like grade-schoolers trying to
contain their giggles as legislators asked their ``tough''
questions. This was it? This was the war? What a tame
confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   The Krafts remember their times in South Boston, times when they
found themselves in personal and political confrontations with an
entire community. Once, outside the South Boston Community Health
Center, an elderly man got in Jonathan Kraft's face and told him he
wasn't going to bring his team to Southie. The man pushed the
younger Kraft a few times, too. There were words exchanged with
City Council president Jim Kelly. And the famous disagreements with
House Speaker Tom Finneran.
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing like that Wednesday. One group of protesters
handed out pieces of cheese, subtle reminders that people will
still be hungry when a new stadium is built. And at about 4:20,
with Kraft still answering legislators' questions, a disruption
could be heard outside. Those who took a peak saw about 50 men and
women in purple berets chanting, ``Union jobs!'' Many of them also
took up another credo: ``No union, no peace.'' They came up an
escalator, walked by Room 2C, and quickly went down an escalator
and out of the building. That was it. It did not remind anyone of
the Black Panthers wielding guns at the California Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   At times, Kraft seemed nervous when he spoke. Maybe he was
having flashbacks to his turbulent political days in Massachusetts.
But he had no reason for uneasiness here. Many of the legislators
and citizens who spoke focused on their own agendas rather than
picking apart the details of the memorandum of understanding Kraft
signed Nov. 19. One man wanted to know what the Patriots were going
to do for Hartford's crumbling schools. There was a janitor who
wanted to know about union jobs. Another man said he would blow up
the new stadium if it took money out of his pocket (he was quickly
reminded that he will be heading to jail if he decides to become an
Adriaen's Landing terrorist). There was a representative from the
National Organization for Women. There was another woman who wanted
to know about affirmative action and the prospects for women. One
man wanted to know why the state doesn't build a small minor league
baseball stadium rather than a 68,000-seat football stadium. A
legally blind woman wanted to know how the new construction would
benefit her.
</P>
<P>
   There were many excellent points made, but Connecticut proved
its pro sports naivete the entire day and evening. The hearing did
not expose a community willing to go to war with Kraft. Far from
it. The hearing exposed a desperate city. The hearing exposed a
needy city. Is it a city that wants pro football? Certainly. But it
also wants better schools, jobs, and government programs. Since so
much is lacking, many of the people came here expecting the
Patriots to be regional saviors rather than a region's football
team. There were no punches thrown here, just pleas.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the night, many people were not venting about a
generous stadium plan. They were talking about their personal
disappointments in life. They talked about how their neighborhoods
were razed in the name of good intentions. They talked and talked,
and after a while, you got the feeling that many people simply
wanted someone to listen.
</P>
<P>
   And that's why Kraft should get ready for the move in 2001. He
knows how to listen now. He recognizes the faces of the politically
naive because he was one of them when he approached the people of
Southie. He knows better now. He knows the people who came here
Wednesday and pounded tables and raised their voices do not
represent the majority of voters. He also knows how to speak to the
majority.
</P>
<P>
   The majority was at the Civic Center Mall Tuesday, participating
in a pep rally with Kraft, Bruce Armstrong, and Tebucky Jones. They
are the ones who want the glow of pro football shining on a
Hartford skyline that is dark on many nights. They believe the NFL
makes a town feel better, even if that town has schools on the
verge of losing accreditation.
</P>
<P>
   Those issues will be raised in the next few weeks. But they
won't stop this deal. The Patriots are coming to Hartford because
Hartford wants a lot of things. Football being one.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Michael Holley is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
