<SLUG> BC-SKI-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SOME, MOUNTAINS HOME, BITTERSWEET HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are people who go skiing (with emphasis on the verb) and
people who are already there. The twain do meet, and often.
</P>
<P>
   Folks who drive up to the mountains for ski weekends and
vacations often know only one phase of life there: the one that
they create. People who live in ski country understand that the
mountain _ that ammusement park full of manmade snow, halfpipes,
terrain parks, brew pubs, pizza bars, skating rinks, health clubs,
sleigh ides, snowmobile rides, cross-country trails, and whatever _
is just one part of the community.
</P>
<P>
   There are also the people who live there.
</P>
<P>
   I knew a fellow who ran a motel in Rangeley, Maine, many years
ago. Those were better days for Saddleback Mountain, and the town
filled every Friday with skiers from Farmington, Orono, Portland,
and even Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of the week, my motelier friend said, the whole
town got into an excited buzz with the anticipation of the ski
crowd coming in, and Sunday night he described a ``kind of
depression'' as the town emptied out again.
</P>
<P>
   These days, the snowmobile crowd has transformed Rangeley into a
mecca of motorized sleds, Castrol smoke hanging in the air, a kind
of Harley crowd carousing through the nights in the little country
town in the middle of Maine's spectacular lakes region.
</P>
<P>
   But from Tijuana, Mexico, to Cuttyhunk, Mass., all tourist towns
are roughly alike. The periodic influx of tourism _ weekly or
seasonally _ transforms them. The very character and identity that
people seek when they visit such places is threatned by their sheer
numbers crashing in. For the locals, it's a love/hate sort of
thing.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Cape Cod residents wave a giddy goodbye to the last of
the retreating summer folk as their tail lights disappear over the
Sagamore Bridge, so do the residents of winter-weary ski towns of
the north feel a thinly disguised sense of
good-riddance-to-all-that as the snow melts in April, wildflowers
bloom in the high country, and the ski/board crowd recedes to the
flatlands. Tide going out.
</P>
<P>
   This time of year, the opposite effect is also seen as winter
vacationers return to a blustery cheer at the inns, hotels, and
restaurants of the northern mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere in New England has this two-culture effect been so clear
as in Vermont, a state so attractive to city folks that despite its
harsh northern winters, the state has become almost the symbol of
what retirement to God's country means. Vermont. Green mountains.
Black-and-white cows. Ice cream white mountains. How sweet!
</P>
<P>
   How many inn keepers have we met through the years who fall into
this description: Middle-aged couple decides to throw off all the
complications of the affluent, hectic life near New York (Boston,
Philly, etc.) and put the life savings into a Vermont business
hoping to live happily in the green hills ever after?
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the rueful joke is that towns like Woodstock and Stowe
are Vermont as created by the imagination of a Connecticutite.
</P>
<P>
   But the clash of cultures can be more serious than a Ralph
Lauren factory outlet. When organized no-growthers continued to
find ever new ways to hold up Sugarbush's plans for expansion of
its snowmaking water capacity, locals from the Mad River towns of
Warren and Waitsfield went to Montpelier to voice their support the
ski area.
</P>
<P>
   The locals knew in their boots that the no-growthers had no
evidence for their case against Sugarbush, and they were not about
to be pushed around by a bunch of outside egg heads and theorists.
Gov. Howard Dean, a native New Yorker himself, stood foursquare
behind Sugarbush, and so gave substance to his oft-lyricized
passion for skiing and boarding.
</P>
<P>
   But today the Green Mountain State faces a much more complicated
problem, created in part by the success of ski tourism in the
state. Or at least on the part of the state known as ``gold
towns.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago the state supreme court ruled that Vermont must
equalize its school funding across the state, spreading the wealth
from the gold towns _ the Stowes and Killingtons _ to the poor
towns whose schools do not benefit from ski tourism, which is by
far the biggest dollar engine in any ski community.
</P>
<P>
   In this case Dean, a 49-year-old, Yale-educated MD, stood
squarely behind Act 60, the legislation aimed at equalizing the tax
burden of education by, essentially, taking from the rich and
giving to the poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Socialism!'' cried some opponents of the measure, which
created a 70 percent tax increase in Killington, a 50 percent boost
in Stowe. But Dean, who entered politics as a Jimmy Carter campaign
worker, once again stood for his principles, which in this case
were: ``Everyone starts with the same chance.''
</P>
<P>
   That Dean's election win last month was closer than expected _
at least by the early polls _ is proof to some in the ski industry
that while the electorate still admires its governor and feels he
has Vermont's interests at heart, it opposes Act 60.
</P>
<P>
   Gold towns may be gold to the huge ski conglomorates, say many
opponents, but there are many small and marginal business owners,
fixed-income residents, and just plain lower-income property owners
who can't afford such skyrocketing taxes.
</P>
<P>
   To date, there is no perfect solution, though Dean and the state
legislature are working on the many hardship cases created by Act
60. Still, the question is brutally difficult. No one can end up
really happy about the solution.
</P>
<P>
   But it may be worth remembering, as we are about to sweep
northward again up Interstates 91, 93, 89, and 95, that the places
we are bound for are more than theme parks for our pleasure and
relaxation. They are living, breathing communities of human beings
wrestling with the same problems of living we seek to escape for 48
hours or so when we go there.
</P>
<P>
   And often, we should also note, their problems are of our
making. To forget this _ and we often do _ is arrogance in the
extreme.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Tony Chamberlain covers skiing for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
