<SLUG> BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT THE US MUST DO TO COMBAT BIOLOGICAL WEAPONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the middle of this century, mankind developed weaponry
capable of ending human life on the planet. At the end of this
century, mankind has created biological weaponry capable of doing
much the same thing, only more selectively and more efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, biological weaponry does not require the
infrastructure and technical sophistication of a nation-state.
Outlaw states and terrorist organizations can concoct viruses,
poxes, and nerve gas agents with a few million dollars and a
handful of scientists.
</P>
<P>
   They are doing just that. Tuesday, William Broad and Judith
Miller of The New York Times reported that Iran has become the most
recent entry into this deadliest of games. Reporting from Moscow,
they filed what may be the most chilling account yet of the bidding
war that has broken out for graduates of the Soviet Biopreparat, or
germ warfare program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Iran is scouring the former Soviet Union,'' Miller and Broad
reported, ``to hire scientists who worked in laboratories tied to
Moscow's vast germ warfare program and has succeeded in recruiting
some of them to take jobs in Teheran, according to Russian
scientists and American officials. Iranian officials who report to
their leadership have approached dozens of scientists who once made
germ weapons, offering as much as $5,000 a month to people who make
far less than that a year in the increasingly chaotic Russian
economy.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, it was believed that biological and chemical weapons
were too unstable for use in warfare. ``Most national
governments,'' says Juan Enriquez of the David Rockefeller Center
at Harvard, ``agreed to stop producing and have renounced the use
of chemical and biological weapons. They did so partly because
these weapons were considered militarily ineffective.''
</P>
<P>
   For this and other reasons, the United States signed the
Biological and Toxic Weapons Convention in 1972, an agreement that
banned the ``development, use and stockpiling of biological
weapons.'' Some 140 nations have since signed the convention.
According to Richard Preston of The New Yorker, however, the Soviet
Union ``continued to believe that the United States had not ended
its bioweapons program but simply hidden it away, turning it into a
`black' weapons program.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, in 1973, the Soviet Union set up Biopreparat, or The
``System'' as it was called by those who worked there, and pressed
ahead with research and development of biological weaponry. At its
zenith, Biopreparat employed 32,000 people whose mission was to do
for the Soviet Union what the Manhattan Project (development of the
atomic bomb) had done for the United States. In 25 short years, the
success (if that's the right word) of the Biopreparat program has
altered the nature of warfare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,'' says Enriquez, ``despite biowarfare conventions, gene
technology is creating nightmares for military officials throughout
the world. Analysts are revisiting the issue of chemical and
biological warheads as strategic weapons. As bioweapons become
stable, easy to disperse, and have specific and limited time
effects, some nations may be tempted to develop them as strategic
weapons. Technology is increasing their military value,
particularly since they can be dispersed quietly and are hard to
trace. If gene research can target medicines to particular
individuals, it can also target weapons. Conceivably, specific
ethnic groups could become targets.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States is almost clueless when it comes to this new
genetic technology of warfare. As Preston reported, ``one of the
side effects of the closing of the American bioweapons program was
that the United States lost its technical understanding of
biological weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States should take these steps:
</P>
<P>
   --Enter into the bidding war for graduates of Biopreparat. An
allocation of $1 billion from the federal budget surplus would more
than cover the cost and would alert the global scientific community
that the US was serious about stopping the spread of bioweapons.
</P>
<P>
   --Insist that Russia deliver a full report on what exactly
Biopreparat accomplished over two decades and where exactly the
scientists of Biopreparat now reside.
</P>
<P>
   --Greatly enhance our intelligence capabilities regarding
biowarfare. If the Central Intelligence Agency does nothing else
for the next 20 years, it would be time and money well spent.
</P>
<P>
   --Develop a plan for massive retaliation in the event of
biowarfare outbreak. That plan should be made public and broadcast
around the world. One way for biological agents to ``blow back'' on
those that launch them is nuclear retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   Biological warfare and genetically engineered viruses represent
the most serious threat to US national security interests since the
Cold War. This time, though, the adversary could be Iraq or the
Islamic Jihad.
</P>
<P>
   What was once the stuff of science fiction and James Bond movies
is now reality. As things now stand, the US is virtually powerless
to combat these new weapons of war.
</P>
<P>
   (John Ellis is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
