<HEADLINE>
LEGENDARY MANAGER PEERS WARILY AT MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Investment legend Peter Lynch may appear to be everywhere these
days, but you rarely hear from the second most-famous mutual fund
manager of the Lynch years.
</P>
<P>
   John Neff made his mark over 30 years working for Boston's
Wellington Management Co. as the manager of the Vanguard Windsor
Fund. He became famous by routinely doing what few mutual fund
managers achieve today, outperforming the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
stock index in 20 of the 29 full calendar years he ran Windsor.
</P>
<P>
   Neff, who retired nearly three years ago, manages only his own
money and a small sum for alma mater Case Western University. But
he looks at today's stock market and knows what he thinks. It's not
an upbeat report.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has kind of stabilized a bit, but the basic problem is
profits have quit growing,'' said Neff, who lives and has always
worked from offices in Pennsylvania. ``Here we are paying 25 or 26
times earnings at this point, which we've never paid before, for a
market in which earnings aren't growing.''
</P>
<P>
   He said weaker corporate earnings and individual investors who
cut back sharply on mutual fund purchases when the market slumped
in the summer are potential warning signs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me you've got a marketplace that's very very high
and there's not much excitement,'' Neff said. ``Over the next five
years or so, it's going to be a very moderate return.''
</P>
<P>
   Neff spends most of his time serving on a variety of profit and
non-profit boards, including that of Chrysler Corp. until its
merger with Daimler-Benz, and has taught at the Wharton School of
Business. He's also at work on a book on his investing style,
expected out in about a year.
</P>
<P>
   Neff made his name as a contrarian investor, buying big stakes
in cheap and out-of-favor stocks he believed would come back. That
style worked most years and very well over the long run, but it did
not fit every market cycle.
</P>
<P>
   Neff's experience 25 years ago might be of interest to critics
of Charles Freeman, who took over management of the Windsor fund in
1996 and runs it in a similar value style.
</P>
<P>
   Freeman's Windsor fund has struggled in a period that favors a
very small group of wildly popular stocks like Microsoft Corp.,
reminiscent of the early 1970s and its Nifty Fifty stocks. Windsor
has lost about 1 percent this year, while the S&AMP;P 500 advanced 22
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Neff actually managed Windsor, then a $500 million fund, during
the Nifty Fifty era, and it wasn't pretty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got killed for three years,'' he recalled Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Windsor earned only half the S&AMP;P 500 return in 1971 and 1972. It
got uglier the next year, in the early stages of the following bear
market: Windsor lost 25 percent while the market sunk by 14.7
percent.
</P>
<P>
   But then Neff's value-oriented portfolio began to turn around
and Windsor's very best years were near. The fund lost 16.8 percent
in 1974, less than the market's 26.3 percent decline. Then Windsor
soared by 54.5 percent in 1975 and another 46.4 percent the next
year, easily outdistancing the overall market each time. ``We did
twice as well because the marketplace simply went the other way,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Neff avoids comment about the operation of his old fund and
professes no particular opinion about any other managers running
money. He will politely acknowledge problems fund managers face
today, the ones usually cited as reasons why so few can outperform
the market. Popular funds are much bigger and often more
constricted in the investments they may persue.
</P>
<P>
   But Neff also points out that his contrarian style, buying when
the market wants to sell and getting out when a stock has gotten
hot, should be managable for bigger funds because it takes
advantage of the market's trading tides. And, he said, stocks that
are overvalued or underpriced by the market are at least as easy to
find today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if anything, to a degree the market is less
efficient,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Neff may be retired from professional investing, but he still
has some favorite stocks. He likes smaller home-building companies
like Beazer Homes USA Inc., M/I Shottenstein Homes Inc. and D.R.
Horton Inc. He finds airlines like UAL Corp. and Delta Air Lines
Inc. attractive. A few investment categories, like cyclical
commodity stocks and real estate investment trusts, are
sufficiently beaten down to attract Neff's attention.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   David Smith, a former State Street Global Advisors employee who
operates an Internet site devoted to criticizing the company, has
lost a key round in his case before the Massachusetts Commission
Against Discrimination. The MCAD staff last week ruled that Smith
had failed to demonstrate that he was fired because he was gay or
in retailation for complaining about another employee's misconduct.
Smith had charged that SSGA, the big Boston money manager, had
fired him after the other employee had misused the office computer
system to reveal Smith was gay. SSGA denied it had discriminated
against Smith and said he was fired for refusing to cooperate with
an internal investigation; an MCAD compliance supervisor agreed. An
SSGA spokeswoman said the company has strictly defined policies to
fight discrimination and harassment. ``And the MCAD decision shows
those policies are working,'' she said. Smith says he plans to
appeal to the full commission.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
