<SLUG> BC-1998-GOOFBALL-AWARDS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S THE 1998 GOOF AWARDS! 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of Richard Roeper's popular
weekly columns, now being offered as a regular New York Times
Syndicate feature. For a bio &AMP; photo _ as well as special contract
rates _ please contact your sales representative:
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Eastern time zone or Canada, call BOB FARNELL
at 1-800-535-4425. Or send a fax to him at (717) 646-4850.
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Central time zone, call CONNIE WHITE at
1-800-444-0267. Or fax her at (816) 822-1444.
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Pacific or Mountain time zones or in Latin
America, call OLIVIA VASQUEZ at (310) 996-0075. Or fax her at (310)
996-0089.
 &HT;    
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.1998 The Chicago Sun-Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Unlike the Academy Awards or the Tonys or the Emmys, there's
never a shortage of deserving nominees when it comes time for the
annual GOOF (Greatly Overhyped and Overexposed Fool) Award.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's winner was Jerry Springer. The year before that, it
was Dennis Rodman. You get the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, no one aspires to the GOOF _ a gigantic trophy made
entirely of goat cheese carved into the image of the original
winners, Milli Vanilli _ but every year, dozens of worthy
contenders emerge, and 1998 was no exception.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the glittering nominees, though, only one gets to take
home the GOOF.
</P>
<P>
   Before we crown our winner, let's pay tribute to the 1998
nominees. Please hold your applause _ and your guffaws _ until all
the names have been read.
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ OPRAH WINFREY. For singing her own theme song, for hammering
us over the head with her charitable greatness, for making the
nearly-unwatchable bomb ``Beloved,'' and for the New Age nuttiness
on her show that threatened to drive away a good portion of even
her most devoted fans. And what's with that disingenuous ``street''
voice she lapses into when she's dishing with someone like Whitney
Houston? What's that about?
</P>
<P>
   _ PRESIDENT BILL CLINTON. Liar.
</P>
<P>
   _ JOEL SHERMAN. You've never heard of him, but he's the New York
Post sportswriter who honored Mark McGwire's 70-homer season by
placing McGwire seventh on his Most Valuable Player ballot.
</P>
<P>
   I think I'll take Sherman out for some appetizers so we can
discuss this ridiculous decision. And then we can have an
appropriately New York Postian headline: ``Headless Writer in Tapas
Bar.''
</P>
<P>
   _ MARY KAY LETOURNEAU. The Seattle schoolteacher and her
teen-age lover, who's now all of 15, brought another baby into this
world and penned a self-pitying book, ``Un Seul Crime, L'Amour''
(``Only One Crime, Love''), which for now is available only in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about a busy gal! Just think of all she could accomplish if
she wasn't behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   _ LYING REPORTERS and THEIR ENABLING EDITORS. Twentysomething
wonder boy Stephen Glass concocted intricate, elaborate and wildly
implausible feature stories for The New Republic, Rolling Stone,
George and other national publications, while his editors ignored
protestations from subjects who quibbled with his pieces by saying
things like, ``Um, that never happened.'' Somehow Glass was able to
produce literally dozens of bogus pieces before the piles of lies
caught up with him.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Boston Globe stars Mike Barnicle and Pat Smith were
fired for writing fiction disguised as newspaper columns. (Barnicle
also was busted for publishing jokes by George Carlin as his own.)
While Barnicle wasn't particularly repentant, he at least spared us
the sanctimonious stance of Smith, whose final ``apology column''
was filled with self-pity and insulting excuses, and who has since
turned her dismissal into performance art poetry.
</P>
<P>
   Are any of these people ever going to apologize to the
colleagues whose livelihoods and reputations they jeopardized with
their elaborate deceits?
</P>
<P>
   I'd like to hear a poem about that.
</P>
<P>
   _ RYAN LEAF. ``I'm a big, rich, goodlooking, talented
quarterback in the NFL! Waaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaah!!!!!''
</P>
<P>
   _ DR. LAURA SCHLESSINGER. The syndicated sensation _ who is
raking in tens of millions of dollars with her unique brand of
common-sense advice peppered with niceties like, ``Don't be a
loser!'' and ``No wonder you don't have any friends!'' _ was
humiliated twice this year, first when Vanity Fair published a
scathing profile, and then with the publication on the Internet of
nude photos from about 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, though, the photos weren't all that humiliating. Dr.
Laura was smokin' back in the '70s!
</P>
<P>
   _ JACK KEVORKIAN. For co-starring in and producing the first
prime-time network-broadcast snuff film in TV history.
</P>
<P>
   _ ALAN DERSHOWITZ. One of the great legal minds of our time is
apparently addicted to cable TV appearances _ which only serve to
shine a spotlight on his horrifically brownish teeth. Cancel
Geraldo and get thee to a dentist, Dershowitz!
</P>
<P>
   _ KENNY ANDERSON. According to The New York Times, Anderson
budgeted $120,000 for ``hanging out money'' during the NBA lockout,
but he was considering a few cost-cutting moves like selling one of
his seven luxury cars (the Mercedes) and he was concerned about
being able to support the four children he has fathered with three
women.
</P>
<P>
   The piece unleashed a torrent of criticism, but Anderson said he
wasn't upset because ``some people don't even know of The New York
Times. They don't even read The New York Times. ... The corporate
world probably reads it. But a lot of my friends who I deal with,
they read the New York Post comics and look at the pictures.''
</P>
<P>
   _ MARY BONO. Mourned Sonny, ran for Sonny's congressional seat,
won Sonny's congressional seat, sheared and darkened her blond
hair, turned against her mentor Newt and called for his
resignation, dissed Sonny for drug use in TV Guide, took up with a
country singer stud and lobbed Kathie Lee-type questions at Kenneth
Starr, all within the span of a single year!
</P>
<P>
   Now, if only she'd marry U2's Bono, divorce him and marry NFL
quarterback Steve Bono, she'd be Mary Bono Bono Bono.
</P>
<P>
   _ HOWARD STERN. Still a comedic genius, but his weekly show on
CBS is behind ``Saturday Night Live'' in the ratings, and there
have been numerous cancellations from affiliates who are disgusted
with the freak-show theatrics.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem: It's one thing to hear Stern on the radio
as he pokes fun at the raggedy collection of losers who parade into
his studio _ but when you actually see some of these people reduced
to tears, it's just not that hilarious. There's too much of an
imbalance of power; when a famous millionaire star is shown mocking
the uneducated and the physically unfortunate, he comes across not
as a rebel but a bully.
</P>
<P>
   _ PAULA JONES. Was rendered nearly attractive by nose job and
total makeover, but she still grated with her ``Roseanne''
appearance by repeatedly opening her mouth, whether it was to crack
her chewing gum or assault our ears with her piercingly high voice
and her stupid opinions.
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Worthy honorees, one and all. Just being nominated is
accomplishment enough _ and in previous years, any of the above
might have taken home the GOOF.
</P>
<P>
   This year, though, was particularly stupid. So without further
ado, the winner is ... wait a minute, we have a tie! The co-winners
of the 1998 GOOF are:
</P>
<P>
   LINDA TRIPP and MONICA LEWINSKY!
(Clap-clap-clap-clap-clap-clap-clap...)
</P>
<P>
   Congratulations, gals. Your telephonic chatterboxing produced
tape after tape of scintillating conversations about the sad little
sexcapades of poor deluded Monica and our pathetically horny
president, aka ``Butt-head.''
</P>
<P>
   Chowing on junk food, watching TV and clattering endlessly like
a couple of sophomores who can't stand those phonies from the
``in'' group, you two set back the women's movement 10 years and
helped fuel the most ridiculous and unnecessary political scandal
in modern history. At this time last year, only a few Washington
insiders knew your names, but now you're as famous as Lorena
Bobitt, Jessica Hahn, Donna Rice or Tonya Harding.
</P>
<P>
   Accept this GOOF in good health, and bicker among yourselves
about who gets to take it home.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard Roeper is a columnist for the Chicago Sun-Times, a
