<SLUG> BC-CRISIS-PR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PG&AMP;E TURNS PAGE IN HANDLING CRISES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WENDY TANAKA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Pacific Gas and Electric Co. took a
decidedly different tack in how it handled the crippling power
outage that crippled the San Francisco area on Tuesday. Call it
corporate perestroika.
</P>
<P>
   The company, a subsidiary of the PG&AMP;E Corp., trotted out its
chief executive at two news conferences to explain what had
happened, accepted blame, and apologized for the inconvenience and
damage the blackout caused.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the company's public relations staff gave radio and
television interviews throughout the day in order to update the
public about when power would be restored.
</P>
<P>
   A mistake made by a Pacific Gas &AMP; Electric Co. work crew shut
down a power substation just after 8 a.m. Tuesday, triggering an
outage that left 1 million people without electricity for hours.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Singer, president of Kamer-Singer &AMP; Associates Inc., a
public relations and crisis management firm, said PG&AMP;E's response
to the catastrophe was a sea change from the way the utility had
historically dealt with crises.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the company took a pounding for not availing itself
more to the public during storm-related power failures in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``We learned a lot from the storms in terms of communications
and the emphasis customers place on communications,'' PG&AMP;E
spokesman Cory Warren said. ``They said, `You don't have to turn on
my lights in an hour. Just tell me when you're going to turn them
on.'''
</P>
<P>
   Singer also pointed to deregulation of California's $80 billion
electricity market as the other main reason PG&AMP;E had decided to
enhance its public relations efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an open, competitive economy,'' Singer said. ``Now,
customers have a choice. PG&AMP;E recognized they can't be the monopoly
of old.''
</P>
<P>
   All told, the San Francisco-based utility received mixed reviews
from crisis management specialists for the way it handled the
blackout.
</P>
<P>
   Singer applauded PG&AMP;E for having the company's chief executive,
Gordon R. Smith, conduct the news conferences and accept
responsibility for the outage.
</P>
<P>
   ``They get a 10 on a scale of 10 in terms of dealing with the
public and the media,'' said Singer, whose clients have included
the Chevron Corp. and San Francisco International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``You only hear from a utility once a month when you get a bill
and when something goes wrong, so you'd better do a good job of
delivering bad news,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Singer also liked the fact that PG&AMP;E's public relations machine
had been on top of the situation, providing frequent updates about
the blackout to radio and television stations.
</P>
<P>
   ``They continued to communicate to the public throughout the
day,'' he said. ``That builds customer, consumer and public
confidence. It makes it appear they're trying to be a good
company.''
</P>
<P>
   Sean Garrett, who specializes in crisis communications for the
San Francisco office of Alexander Ogilvy Public Relations, wasn't
as impressed. Garrett said he had heard conflicting information in
radio reports Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the main problems was the difference of opinion from
(Mayor Willie Brown's) office and PG&AMP;E,'' he said. ``The mayor said
the power is going to be back on in 45 minutes. Then, someone from
PG&AMP;E said it's going to take longer. ... (And) at about 2 p.m.,
PG&AMP;E said all the lights are on, but people called into (radio
station) KCBS saying, `not for us.' ... If they're going to be
proactive, make sure it's right. That's what people are going to
remember you by.''
</P>
<P>
   Warren said the company had done the best it could under the
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation was constantly in flux,'' he said. ``Information
that seemed good at the time was replaced later. That's how
emergencies operate.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Both Garrett and Singer had numerous suggestions for how PG&AMP;E
should handle fallout from the blackout.
</P>
<P>
   Garrett said PG&AMP;E should take out full-page newspaper ads
apologizing for the power failure and telling customers how it
planned to avert a recurrence. Singer said PG&AMP;E should consider
offering rebates to customers to stave off a flood of claims
against the company.
</P>
<P>
   Warren said the company had already apologized and wouldn't know
its next steps until an investigation of the blackout was
completed.
</P>
<P>
   But Singer expects PG&AMP;E to make more public announcements about
the blackout.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trend is toward honesty in corporations,'' he said. ``They
see if they get caught in a lie, it'll only come back and hurt
them. People who (aren't honest) can lose market share.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
