<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
. 
The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following stories
today for use by NYTimes News Service clients. They will move in
the ``e'' entertainment news file. For questions, contact Jimmy
Johnson at the Daily News, (818) 713-3695. 
. 
STARTREK-MOVIE (Los Angeles) _ In ``Star Trek: Insurrection,'' the
ninth movie about a Starship Enterprise that goes to increasingly
familiar-looking places no one has gone before, things aren't going
well. The fabled Federation of Planets is in decline, facing
challenges from opportunistic alien forces on all sides, not unlike
the television series ``Deep Space Nine'' and ``Voyager,'' which
have steep competition in the ratings these days. By Bob Strauss. 
. 
RUSHMORE-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ Remember that smart but misguided,
attractively energetic but abnormally obsessive geek in school? You
can bet film critics do, and that's why you're going to have a hard
time finding negative reviews of ``Rushmore.'' Undeniably charming
and ultra-quirky in a generally pleasing way, this latest study of
oddballs-on-the-outs from director Wes Anderson was built to be
overpraised. 3 stars. By Bob Strauss. 
. 
SHAKESPEARE-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ ``Shakespeare in Love'' is a
smart, funny and sexy romp through Elizabethan times that will
satisfy both theatrical scholars and people who have never cracked
open the great Bard's work. 4 stars. By Glenn Whipp. 
. 
SIMPLE-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ ``A Simple Plan'' boasts great
performances, mesmerizing suspense sequences and a consistent
intelligence rarely found in thrillers today. It's just a shame
that it winds up being fundamentally simple. 3 stars. By Bob
Strauss. 
. 
STILL-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ `While `Still Crazy'' bears a
resemblance to Rob Reiner's classic satire ``This Is Spinal Tap,''
it aims deeper to explore the harsh reality that follows people who
peaked too soon in life and now must cope with boring, routine,
everyday sameness. 3{ stars. By Glenn Whipp. 
. 
STAR-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ ``Star Trek: Insurrection'' continues
the dubious tradition of not being as good as any of the
even-numbered entries in the venerable sci-fi series. 2{ stars. By
Bob Strauss.
<TEXT>
<P>
   . &QL; 
SHARPS-MUSIC (Losm Angeles) _ The winner of MTV's ``The Cut''
program will be announced Saturday, and one of the finalists is a
Northridge-based alternative-pop singer. By Fred Shuster. &QL; 
. &QL; 
WEAPON-VIDEO (Los Angeles) _ In ``Lethal Weapon IV,'' you wouldn't
expect Warners to tamper with the most successful of any buddy-film
series, not to mention a lucrative one. Instead director Richard
Donner adds a few spices to the meat and potatoes of Riggs and
Murtaugh (Mel Gibson and Danny Glover). By Rob Lowman. &QL; 
. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
