<SLUG> BC-SHARPS-MUSIC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINGER RIDES MTV WAVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The winner of MTV's ``The Cut'' program will be
announced Saturday on the cable music network, and one of the
finalists is a Northridge-based alternative-pop singer.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Wilson says the entire process was ``amazing _ just being
part of it was great.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, 22, relocated to Northridge from Brockport, N.Y., three
months ago to try to make it as a singer in the City of Angels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a following back home, but I felt it was time to give it
a go,'' he said. ``On a whim, I mailed my demos to MTV, and they
got back to me almost instantly.''
</P>
<P>
   The cable program, hosted by Lisa ``Left Eye'' Lopes of the
group TLC, provides an arena for undiscovered acts to present their
skills. More than 10,000 tapes were submitted to the production,
and more than 160 acts have been featured on the daily half-hour
program, according to executive producer Kathy Cotter,
</P>
<P>
   The finals of ``The Cut'' air at 12:30 p.m. Saturday when 10
finalists, including Wilson, compete against each other.
</P>
<P>
   `` `The Cut' has been a great way for MTV to showcase the
talents of undiscovered performers,'' said Brian Graden, MTV's
executive vice president of programming. ``It's been a great way
for us to see the many talents of our audience in action each
week.''
</P>
<P>
   The grand prize winner will appear in an MTV-produced video,
which will go into rotation on the channel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've already gotten quite a lot by being involved,'' Wilson
said. ``I've been contacted by several record labels and
promoters.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson says he enjoys living in the area because ``I'm
surrounded by people trying to do the same thing I'm going
through.''
</P>
<P>
   POORMAN WANTS YOU: Jim (Poorman) Trenton returns to the airwaves
with his ``Anti-Radio'' simulcast at 4 p.m. Monday on KYPA-AM
(1230) and KMNY-AM (1600). Trenton asks unsigned musicians to send
tapes, CDs or vinyl to: Poorman, 177 Riverside Ave., Newport Beach,
92663. Information: (949) 722-8785.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-98 1407EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
