<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`A SIMPLE PLAN' BASICALLY WORKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 3 Stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``A Simple Plan'' does so much so well that it's a
shame it ends up so fundamentally, well, simple.
</P>
<P>
   A beautifully shot, wintry film noir that signals a profoundly
mature step in director Sam Raimi's development, the movie digs
deep into areas of behavior good people never want to know they
possess. ``Simple Plan'' also boasts impressive tonal consistency,
a good sense of paranoia, great performances, mesmerizing set
pieces and an intelligence rarely found in thrillers today.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that precious little in this movie comes as a
surprise. While lead actors Bill Paxton, Billy Bob Thornton and
Bridget Fonda play their small-town Minnesota characters with
depth, passion and something like the spontaneity of real people,
the outline of their moves is predetermined almost to the point of
ritualism. If you've ever seen a movie where a trove of unearned
money destroys everyone that touches it, then you know where this
unforgiving morality play is headed from the opening credits.
</P>
<P>
   Getting there, however, is all the fun. Based on Scott Smith's
novel (he also wrote the screenplay), the film spins a lesson of
biblical dimensions out of the classic concept that a little
knowledge is a dangerous thing.
</P>
<P>
   Our in-over-his-head smart guy is Paxton's Hank Mitchell, and
his grand tragedy lies in his painful discovery of how thorough a
jerk he can be. The only college graduate from a family of former
farmers, Hank initially sees nothing wrong with his humble
accounting job at the local feed store. It's enough to afford him a
nice, modest house, which his massively pregnant wife Sarah (Fonda)
seems content enough in.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to that of his dim-witted, unemployed older brother
Jacob (Thornton), Hank's life is indeed perfect. Every inch the
Midwestern geek with his long greasy hair, Coke-bottle glasses and
perpetually stubbled cheeks, Jacob has lived in a trashed-out
apartment with his mangy dog ever since the family farm got
foreclosed on.
</P>
<P>
   When Hank, Jacob and Jacob's only friend, a drunken lout named
Lou (Brent Briscoe), find some $4 million in a downed airplane,
it's educated, self-controlled Hank who decides to sit on the
obviously illicit money until spring, then dig in if nobody claims
it. It's the first of many bad decisions, many of which spring from
the greed-addled Sarah, who morphs convincingly from sweet
expectant mom into Lady Macbeth of the 10,000 Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   The subtlest changes come across Hank, though. He's not wrong in
thinking he's the most decent, smartest conspirator involved in
this increasingly birdbrained and blood-spattered cover-up. But
it's amazing how his every strategy reveals an unexamined contempt
for everybody he thought he held dear.
</P>
<P>
   Beautifully balancing Hank's descent into his own misanthropy,
Jacob's wounded human dignity blossoms under pressure (even as his
limited intellect cracks from the same force). This is Thornton's
finest idiot/saint yet, a man whose resentments are so poignantly
intertwined with his longing for love he will surely break the most
cynical viewer's heart.
</P>
<P>
   Raimi, a cracked near-genius who usually makes overcaffeinated
comic book movies like ``Darkman'' and ``The Evil Dead,'' reveals
these layers of humanity at a deliberate but perfectly timed pace.
He also knows exactly when to goose the proceedings along with
judiciously constructed shock bits; the scene in which Hank
insensitively forces Jacob to choose between his only friend and
his only brother may be the best stretch of film since Spielberg's
Omaha Beach.
</P>
<P>
   All that said, the mechanistic puritanism that drives ``A Simple
Plan'' is hard to take. After the recent ``Waking Ned Devine'' made
such worthy fun of knee-jerk moralism and ``Very Bad Things''
splattered the whole concept into a million preposterous pieces,
you just wish these fascinating individuals could live a nightmare
that was worthy of their complexity. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-98 1409EST &QL; 
