<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 14:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3038 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRJOY-COLUMN-$ADV11-N     12-10 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRJOY-COLUMN-$ADV11-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAUGHTER'S DIARY SENDS A SCARY MESSAGE 
 FOR USE FRI., DEC. 11, OR ANYTIME THEREAFTER.
</HEADLINE>
  By DR. JOY BROWNE 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUESTION: I just read my 16-year-old daughter's diary and found
out she's having sex. Do I confront her and admit I'm a snoop or
take the easy way out and pretend I don't know?
</P>
<P>
   ANSWER: If you tell your daughter you've been reading her diary,
she will rightly say there's no reason for her to try to earn your
trust, since she can't trust you. You two have some important
business to transact that has nothing to do with snooping.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to admit that you've read her diary (she may have
fantasized or hoped you'd find it), but you do have to make sure
she knows the basics about sex. She needs to know how you get
pregnant and how you don't, how to protect herself from unwanted
venereal disease (which means using a condom and spermicide EVERY
time to protect against AIDS).
</P>
<P>
   Most importantly, she needs to know that she can say yes, but
she can also say no.
</P>
<P>
   This is also a terrific time to share some personal experiences,
if you can remember them, and not preach or judge. It's OK to
confess some of your own misgivings and mistakes. It will make her
feel less alone.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, it's a good time to involve her father in talking about
sex. When only mothers talk to daughters and fathers to sons, it
perpetuates the notion that sex is a dirty little joke.
</P>
<P>
   An ostrich approach to her sexuality may be more comfortable for
you, but it's dangerous for her.
</P>
<P>
   QUESTION: We had a wonderful dinner together, talked the evening
away, went dancing and ended up at my front door where he kissed me
sweetly and murmured, ``I'll call you soon.'' I thought he might
even call me from his cell phone on the way home to tell me how
terrific I am.
</P>
<P>
   But the phone didn't ring then or at work the next day or for a
whole week. When he finally called, I told him to forget it. I
wasn't going out with him ever again. Now I'm having second
thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   DR. JOY: Einstein said time is relative, and he didn't know the
half of it. It's not only relative, it's sexual. There's a vast
difference between girl time and boy time.
</P>
<P>
   When a guy says, ``Call you soon,'' he means when I get around
to it, if I remember, when I've straightened out my love life, when
I get my finances in order, once the basketball season is over, or
never.
</P>
<P>
   To a woman, ``soon'' means within the next 24 hours at most, but
preferably when he gets home since he's so smitten he can't sleep
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Guys, when you say you're going to call, never use the word
``soon'' and never say you're going to call unless you think there
is at least a 75 percent chance you might within the next week.
</P>
<P>
   Gals, if he says, ``I'll call you soon,'' you can say, ``I'm
going to be in and out for the next couple of days--why don't you
give me your number and I'll call you in the next week?''
</P>
<P>
   A final point: Guys, if you really do intend to call, you'd be
amazed at the benefits you'll reap from calling sooner rather than
later.
</P>
<P>
   QUESTION: I had been living in a furnished sublet for three
months following my separation when I met a terrific woman at a
singles dance. After six weeks of seeing each other every night, we
decided it was perfectly logical for me to move into her place. So
I did. She had been divorced four years and was ecstatic that we
were together.
</P>
<P>
   Three months later I'm wondering if I haven't made a colossal
mistake. She didn't talk about commitment during our whirlwind
romance, but all of a sudden she has become as possessive as a
prison warden and as jealous as my wife.
</P>
<P>
   DR. JOY: Lots of warning signs here. She views living together
as marriage with training wheels; you view it as a welcome
alternative to a dreary bachelor pad.
</P>
<P>
   As for your relationship, you ought not to be dating at all.
Separated means still married and married people don't date. If you
were single and had been dating each other for six to nine months,
you might have been able to compromise on a couple of nights
together at her house, a couple at yours and a couple alone,
allowing the process of disovery to unfold a bit more slowly.
You're moving at the speed of light past things you ought not to be
moving past at all.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly relationships aren't always sensible, but dealing
with your underlying convictions now will at least give impetuosity
a firmer base. In this relationship, she must acknowledge that your
unwillingness to be alone isn't the same as being committed to her.
And you need to remember that living together is a larger
commitment to her than to you.
</P>
<P>
   Move out, get your head together, your divorce in place,
apologize to this woman and make your life work for you. If you're
lonely, find a same-sex roommate or a puppy--don't prey on someone
with a nice living room.
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
<P>
   Questions may be sent to Dr. Joy Browne at drjoy &LR; nytsyn.com, or
by letter c/o The New York Times Syndication Sales Corp., 122 E.
42nd St., New York, NY 10168. Dr. Joy regrets that unpublished
letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   Copyright 1998 by Dr. Joy Browne Distributed by New York Times
Special Features
</P>
