   MOTHS _ The gypsy moth, that bane of the Northeastern forests
for a century, is slowly munching itself southward and for the
third time this decade has infested an area of North Georgia's
mountains. Federal and state forestry officials plan the aerial
spraying of biological insecticides across some 30,000 acres of
rugged and picturesque mountains along the Georgia-North Carolina
near Highlands, N.C. The area includes the remote Ellicott Rock
Wilderness in Rabun County, Ga. as well as South Carolina. (Harmon,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
