<TEXT>
<P>
   Weekend Section stories from The New York Times News Service for
Friday, Dec. 11.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   APPLES-WASHINGTON (Washington) _ Like Brasilia, Canberra and
other created capitals, cities custom-built as seats of government,
Washington has been bad-mouthed from the very beginning. Jefferson
called it ``that Indian swamp in the wilderness.'' John F. Kennedy
famously remarked that our fair capital was full of ``Northern
charm and Southern efficiency.'' But most visitors come not to
tut-tut at the hard streets where the city's poor live, not to
count the ways the government falls short of the Founding Fathers'
ideals, but to pay homage to the ideals themselves, to keep the
ideals alive and try to imbue the kids with them. That is why
Washington is thronged several times each year with family groups,
shod in their Reeboks, maps in hand, taking in the American dream.
By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   OFF-BROADWAY (New York) _ On the growing recognition that Off
Broadway and Off Off Broadway nonprofit theaters are receiving.
Typically these theaters have toiled in obscurity and struggled to
make ends meet. But the critical success of recent productions like
``Wit,'' ``This Is Our Youth'' and ``Killer Joe'' has lured more
conventional theatergoers below Times Square, boosting ticket
sales, building new audiences and attracting commercial Broadway
producers to sniff around for possible imports. By Robin Pogrebin.
</P>
<P>
   MONSTERS-OPERA-REVIEW (New York) _ ``Monsters of Grace,'' the
``digital opera in three dimensions'' at the Brooklyn Academy of
Music.
</P>
<P>
   MET-COSTUME-REVIEW (New York) _ ``Cubism and Fashion'' at the
Metropolitan Museum of Art's Costume Institute. Reviewed By Roberta
Smith.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVIES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ATHEY-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Hallelujah! Ron Athey: A Story
of Deliverance''; Catherine Gund Saalfield, director; a
documentary. Reviewed by Stephen Holden.
</P>
<P>
   FROST-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Jack Frost'': Troy Miller,
director. with Michael Keaton, Anthony Edwards, Kelly Preston, Mark
Addy. Reviewed by Janet Maslin.
</P>
<P>
   OGRE-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``The Ogre'': Volker Schlondorff,
director; with John Malkovitch, Armin Mueller-Stahl, Marianne
Sagerbrecht, Heino Ferch. Reviewed by Stephen Holden.
</P>
<P>
   SHAKESPEARE-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Shakespeare in Love'':
John Madde, director; with Gwyneth Paltrow, Joseph Fiennes, Judi
Dench. Reviewed by Janet Maslin.
</P>
<P>
   SIMPLE-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``A Simple Plan'': Sam Raimi,
director; with Billy Bob Thornton, Bridget Fonda, Brent Briscoe,
Gary Cole, Chelsie Ross, Bill Paxton. Reviewed by Janet Maslin.
</P>
<P>
   STARTREK-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Star Trek: Insurrection'':
Jonathan Frakes, director; with Patrick Stewart, Frakes, Brent
Spiner. Reviewed by Stephen Holden.
</P>
<P>
   FILMS4KIDS (Undated) _ Assessing the current cinema for children
of different ages.
</P>
<P>
   AT-THE-MOVIES (Hollywood) _ News of the silver screen. By
Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-IN-BRIEF (Undated) _ Capsule reviews by New York Times
critics.
</P>
<P>
   HOMEVIDEO (Undated) _ Short items on what's news in home video
and short reviews of what's new in home video. By Peter M. Nichols.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER ENTERTAINMENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SADE-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``At Home With the Marquis de
Sade,'' by Francine du Plessix Gray (Simon &AMP; Schuster) and ``Sade:
A Biographical Essay'' by Lawrence Bongie (University of Chicago
Press). Reviewed by Richard Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   TV-WEEKEND (Undated) _ Caryn James spotlights the weekend's
television fare: Sunday on NBC, ``The Tempest.''
</P>
<P>
   THEATER-NOTES (Undated) _ News of The Great White Way.
</P>
<P>
   ART-NOTES (New York) _ Art world news and notes. By Carol Vogel.
</P>
<P>
   ANTIQUES-COLUMN (New York) _ The Antiques Column. By Wendy
Moonan.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (888)
346-9867 or (212) 556-1927. And be sure to look for other
entertainment stories from our partners: Bloomberg News The Boston
Globe, Cox News Service, Hearst Newspapers, The Houston Chronicle,
The Arizona Republic, Kansas City Star, Fort Worth Star-Telegram,
Los Angeles Daily News, San Francisco Chronicle and Seattle
Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
