<SLUG> BC-NEW-SCIENTIST-BUDGET-NYTSF </SLUG>
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This budget has been transmitted three times _ into
the ``v'' advisory, ``l'' lifestyle news and ``a'' general news
files.)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ATTENTION EDITORS: &LR;  The following is the budget for the New
Scientist for material available the week of Mon., Dec. 14 and
anytime thereafter. This material is free for use for New York
Times News Service clients. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DIRTY UNDERWEAR COULD LEAD TO SPACE FUEL &LR;  _ Waste-guzzling
microbes could help solve one of space travel's most pressing
problems: what to do with dirty underwear. Russian scientists are
designing a cocktail of enzyme-producing bacteria to digest
astronaut's special-issue underpants _ and the resulting methane
gas could even be used to power spacecraft. By Bronwen McLaren. 300
words (slugged: BC-DIRTY-UNDERWEAR-IN-SPACE-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPEEDTRAP CAMERAS CAN BE FOOLED BY FLASH GUNS &LR;  _ Flash guns can
prevent police speedtrap cameras from identifying cars that are
breaking the speed limit. A British photographer has patented a
flash gun which when mounted on a moving car can dazzle any
roadside law-enforcement camera. By Barry Fox. 500 words. (slugged:
BC-SPEEDERS-HAVE-NEW-WEAPON-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IN-VITRO FERTILIZATION IS A PAIN IN THE BACK &LR;  _ Researchers in
Sweden have found that women with in-vitro fertilization
pregnancies suffer twice as much back pain as those with natural
pregnancies. Those with the most pain also seemed to have the
highest levels of the hormone relaxin in their blood. By Jon
Copley. 300 words. (slugged:
BC-IN-VITRO-PREGNANCIES-AND-BACK-PAIN-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRANSPLANTS GO BETTER WITH THE RIGHT TIMING &LR;  _ Problems with
liver transplant rejection may be reduced by delaying the use of
immunosuppressant drugs by a few days. Research from Sydney has
shown that the use of drugs along with a new liver can disrupt the
organ's ability to induce immunological tolerance. By Rachel Nowak.
300 words. (slugged:
BC-TRANSPLANTS-AND-TIMING-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF) &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
