<HEADER>
A3084 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SF-TRAFFIC-HNS &LR;      12-10 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-TRAFFIC-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURVEY SHOWS GRIDLOCK IS MAJOR CONCERN IN BAY AREA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DIANA WALSH  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Frustrated by increasingly sluggish traffic, a
record number of residents in the San Francisco Bay area believe
transportation is the region's biggest problem, according to a new
poll.
</P>
<P>
   Although transportation has long held a top ranking in the list
of regional concerns, it soared to a new high in the annual poll,
with 40 percent of all those surveyed citing it as the most
important problem facing the Bay area.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an emphatic response,'' observed Sunne Wright McPeak,
president and chief executive of the Bay Area Council, a public
affairs organization sponsored by regional businesses. ``The fact
that this many Bay-area residents cite transportation as our top
problem, in response to an open-ended question nonetheless, should
send an unmistakable message to the region's policy-makers.''
</P>
<P>
   Education, which in the last poll ranked as the seventh overall
concern, rose to a distant second, with 14 percent listing it as
their top worry. In the last poll, 6 percent listed education as
their top worry in the last poll.
</P>
<P>
   The poll, which has been conducted by the Bay Area Council
annually _ with the exception of last year _ since 1980, is
sponsored by businesses to gauge opinion about quality of life and
business development.
</P>
<P>
   The Field Research Corporation interviewed 603 residents in the
nine Bay-area counties during October in compiling the survey. The
margin of error is plus or minus four percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-one percent of those surveyed said the region's highway
system was worse than the previous year, while 48 percent said road
conditions had deteriorated and 36 percent said public
transportation was worse.
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers are probably best explained by the ever-increasing
amount of time people are spending in their cars.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, motorists in the Bay area lost an average of 90,000
hours per day sitting in gridlock. That's an increase of 31 percent
over 1996 when the average stood at 68,000 hours per day, according
to Russell Hancock, vice president of the Bay Area Council.
</P>
<P>
   If all of the area's congested freeways were placed end to end,
the number of gridlocked roadways would measure 284 miles on any
given day, compared to 217 in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   As crime rates locally and nationally have continued to drop in
recent years, so has concern over personal safety. Listed as the
top concern four years ago, with 34 percent of all respondents
defining it as the Bay area's biggest problem in 1994, it fell to
24 percent in the last survey in 1996, and to 12 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``All measures for serious crimes, murders, assaults and battery
have been dropping nationwide, so we can take heart in those
numbers and it's only fitting that people feel better about that
issue,'' said Alexander Winslow, director of communications for the
Bay Area Council.
</P>
<P>
   Concern over the economy also dropped significantly as the
region, which five years ago wallowed in a recession, experienced
one of the nation's strongest economic booms. Only 6 percent cited
the economy as their biggest worry in 1998 compared with 10 percent
in 1996 and 32 percent in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``These responses are a reflection of the good economic times
that the Bay area has enjoyed for some three or four years now,''
McPeak said. ``During this period, the Bay area has displayed one
of the nation's most robust regional economies.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the region's real estate market, with
skyrocketing prices, struck a nerve when respondents were asked
about their quality of life. Reacting to housing prices, which
soared to record levels for the year before cooling slightly in the
fall, four out of five surveyed said that the cost of houses had
gotten worse over the past year. When that same question was asked
in 1995, 30 percent of the respondents said housing costs were
worse than the previous year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-98 1438EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
