<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981210.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 15:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3133 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-CELEBRATION11-     12-10 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-CELEBRATION11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Danes' dark tale no piece of cake
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's something rotten in the state of Denmark, particularly
at the country estate of Helge (Henning Moritzen), who is
celebrating his 60th birthday with a nightlong celebration of
drinks, dinner, dancing.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and don't forget the toasts _ especially the one given by
his eldest son, Christian (Ulrich Thomsen). He's a pale, guarded
young man whose emotional distance may be a legacy of what he
reveals to the family members and friends gathered in the dining
room: that he and his twin sister, as children, were sexually
abused.
</P>
<P>
   That's the powder-keg plot of ``The Celebration,'' which fuses
documentary-style filmmaking with some of the melodramatic family
psychology of Ingmar Bergman and Eugene O'Neill. The Danish film,
winner of the special jury prize at this year's Cannes Film
Festival, manages to be both cutting edge and old hat.
</P>
<P>
   We meet the key players as they're arriving at the immense
family home. Christian, walking from the airport, gets a lift from
his hothead kid brother Michael (Thomas Bo Larsen). Michael is the
kind of guy who makes his wife and children walk a mile in order to
give Christian a ride. Then there's Helene (Paprika Steen), a
second sister, whose fondness for black men is only another of the
family bombshells.
</P>
<P>
   The visit is notable for more than their father's birthday. It's
the first time they've been together since the suicide of
Christian's twin, a loss that motivates the action and adds a
satisfying supernatural edge.
</P>
<P>
   Though the movie has the breezy rush of improvisation, the
script (by Mogens Rukov and director Thomas Vinterberg) is
thematically polished. When a couple of elderly dinner guests argue
over the consistency of the soup (salmon? lobster? tomato?), it
foreshadows the movie's strongest dramatic question: Is Christian's
accusation true? Or is he lying? Or does he somehow believe it's
true, although it never happened?
</P>
<P>
   The strongest section of ``The Celebration'' is the
excruciating, protracted reaction to Christian's toast. His mother,
Elsa (Birthe Neumann), smiles her social smile and insists that
Christian, ``a creative child,'' is playing a twisted prank. The
guests try to beat a polite retreat.
</P>
<P>
   They can't. The estate's chef, Kim (Bjarne Henriksen), a
childhood friend of Christian's, has ordered his cooks to steal all
the car keys from the guests, so that the family (nuclear and
extended) is forced to confront the truth. Whatever that happens to
be.
</P>
<P>
   Playing like a contemporary, domesticated version of ``Hamlet''
peppered with black humor, the movie also has the
upstairs-downstairs tensions and supernatural tone of ``The
Kingdom'' by Lars Von Trier. Not surprisingly, he's one of the four
Danish filmmakers, including Vinterberg, working under something
they call Dogme 95. Under this manifesto, the directors shoot on
location, using hand-held cameras and only natural lighting and
ambient sound.
</P>
<P>
   This ``dogma'' approach has its downside, including the motion
sickness you get from the shaky camerawork (like Von Trier's
``Breaking the Waves''). Some of the night scenes in
``Celebration'' are murky to the point of distraction. And the
video-to-35mm transfer can make things look cheap.
</P>
<P>
   You probably won't mind, thanks to the potboiler plot and strong
acting. Thomsen's enigmatic performance suggests what Hamlet might
be like in Copenhagen in the 1990s, while Moritzen's father is by
turns deeply sympathetic and frightening. In many ways, though, the
movie's biggest arc is acted by Larsen, who transforms Michael from
a drunken wreck into an unlikely hero.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Dogme 95 proves to be a strong basis for future films or
just a gimmick remains to be seen. But the approach, and the
material, work beautifully in ``The Celebration.'' It's not
terribly original, but it's terrifically compelling.
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``The Celebration''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Ulrich Thomsen,
</P>
<P>
   Henning Moritzen, Thomas Bo Larsen and Paprika Steen. Directed
by Thomas Vinterberg. Rated R for strong sexual content and
language, including references to sexual abuse. At Garden Hills. 1
hour,
</P>
<P>
   45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: An old-fashioned psychological drama with a dash of
ghost story, blended with edgy contemporary style.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
