A3134 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-DEVINE11-COX     12-10 0287
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-DEVINE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Luck of the Irish gets iffy in `Devine'
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton may have been right after all. It does
take a village. At least it does in ``Waking Ned Devine,'' a broad,
twinkly Irish comedy about what happens in the tiny town of
TullyMore (population 52) when it's discovered that one of its
residents holds a lottery ticket worth nearly $7 million.
</P>
<P>
   The first challenge is finding out who the lucky winner is, a
task that two lifelong buddies _ blustery, cunning Jackie (Ian
Bannen) and spindly, gullible Michael (David Kelly) _ undertake
with considerable gusto. After all, it doesn't hurt to be on the
good side of someone who's just come into a handsome amount of
money.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is a little too eager to please, a little too Lucky
Charms Irish. But Bannen and Kelly are professional charmers, and
there are dozens of winning little moments _ whether it's Kelly's
frazzled, full-monty motorcycle ride or a chicken dinner thrown by
Jackie and his wife (Fionnula Flanagan) to sniff out the ticket
holder.
</P>
<P>
   A few unexpected twists give the movie a last-minute lift,
making it relatively easy to overlook the earlier irksome aspects.
But if you're looking for something with edge or sophistication,
best look elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``Waking Ned Devine''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Ian Bannen and David Kelly. Directed by Kirk Jones.
Rated PG for senior citizen nudity and sexual themes. At Phipps. 1
hour, 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: How do you say ``twee'' in Celtic?
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringle writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
