<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-JACKFROST11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Jack Frost' bites the big Snowball and melts into slush
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   George Clooney was supposed to star. Sam Raimi signed on to
direct. Then they bailed.
</P>
<P>
   They must have read the script.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jack Frost'' comes to theaters starring Michael Keaton
instead, with Troy Miller directing. What was once described as a
live-action version of ``Frosty the Snowman'' ends up being an
uninspired ``inspirational'' high-concept Hollywood mess.
</P>
<P>
   Keaton plays Jack Frost, lead singer in a mediocre rock band,
whose gigs keep him away from wife Gabby (Kelly Preston) and son
Charlie (Joseph Cross). In fact, it's when he's driving back from
an out-of-town show that he loses control of his car and bites the
big snowball.
</P>
<P>
   One year later, fatherless Charlie has grown withdrawn and
sullen. He's even quit the hockey team. But a dose of self-worth
comes via a peculiar kind of reincarnation: Dad reappears in the
front yard as a talking snowman.
</P>
<P>
   Checking out his new self, the frigid father wonders, ``Can the
universe really be that unoriginal?'' No, but four screenwriters
apparently can.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's big-stakes issue is to let Jack have a second chance
to be a good father and teach Charlie how to swat a hockey puck
really, really well. It's a celluloid mea culpa devised by West
Coast show-biz dads who feel guilty about not spending more time
with their kids. They should feel guilty _ not for neglecting their
families, but for inflicting junk like ``Jack Frost'' on ours.
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``Jack Frost''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D
</P>
<P>
   Starring Michael Keaton and Kelly Preston. Directed by Troy
Miller. Rated PG for mild profanity. At metro theaters. 1 hour, 36
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: This ridiculous high-concept flick is as
substantial as a snowball in July.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
