<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-SIMPLE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Simple Plan' weaves tangled web of greed
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Simply put, ``A Simple Plan'' is eerily similar to the season's
other Murphy's Law movie, ``Very Bad Things.'' In both, a bunch of
guys make a series of decisions that have increasingly disastrous
consequences. The major _ make that crucial _ difference is a
matter of tone. ``Very Bad Things'' is a purposely tasteless black
farce, while Sam Raimi's picture is a character-driven black comedy
with some sober, conscience-nudging undercurrents.
</P>
<P>
   It begins in the deep snow outside a small Minnesota town.
(Echoes of ``Fargo''? You betcha.) Three men stumble across a
wrecked small plane. Inside are the dead pilot _ and more than $4
million in crisp $100 bills. Sensible Hank (Bill Paxton), a regular
guy with a steady job and a pregnant wife (Bridget Fonda), suggests
that they call the local sheriff. He's overruled by his brother,
Jacob (Billy Bob Thornton), a deceptively complex simpleton, and
Jacob's best buddy, a greedy lunkhead named Lou (Brent Briscoe).
</P>
<P>
   So they devise a simple plan. But the best-laid plans of mice,
men and Minnesotans . . .
</P>
<P>
   Before long, the three men are up to their ears in blackmail,
murder and other troubling matters.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Scott Smith's best seller, ``A Simple Plan'' is an
unflattering yet undeniably funny study of the tangled webs we all
weave. Especially effective is the way each incident builds on the
last. Even the discovery of the downed plane is a kind of
``Mousetrap'' series of idiotic events that begin with a fox
crossing a road. It's enough to make you think that God must have
an awfully infantile sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Raimi's bent for malicious black comedy throws
the movie a bit off balance. There's some powerful stuff here about
corruption, brothers, family skeletons, the illusionary lure of the
One Big Chance. And some of that gets lost among the laughs.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the movie's focus is on Thornton, who's quite a
spectacle in his lank-haired fright wig and Alfred E. Neuman
dentures. But it's Paxton who holds the film together. He's the
quietly decent man quietly corrupted by so much money. As Fonda, a
Lady Macbeth in a bathrobe, says, her voice aching with love,
support and maybe a little greed: ``You gotta remember how people
see you. You're just a decent, normal guy. Nobody would believe
you're capable of what you've done.''
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``A Simple Plan''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Bill Paxton, Billy Bob Thornton and Bridget Fonda.
Directed by Sam Raimi. Rated R for language and violence. 1 hour,
57 minutes. At metro theaters.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A movie that's anything but simple.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel writes for the Atlanta Journal-constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
