</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-STARTREK11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lighthearted `Trek' sequel stages space vaudeville act
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The writers of ``Star Trek: Insurrection'' apparently based
their plot on Malibu cocktail chatter between aging movie
executives and their trophy wives. Namely, how far would you be
willing to go to preserve your youth and great skin, without the
inconvenience of elective surgery? Destroy a planet? No prob.
</P>
<P>
   In this largely lighthearted entry in the ``Next Generation''
big-screen series, the Enterprise crew has to defend an agrarian,
primarily blond and boring tribe, the Ba'ku.
</P>
<P>
   The Ba'kus' happy, ``Lost Horizon''-style planet turns out to be
a place of eternal youth. A leader of the mud-ugly Son'a tribe
named Ru'afo (F. Murray Abraham under a bunch of facial gunk) plots
with a Star Fleet admiral (Anthony Zerbe) to evacuate the Ba'ku
residents, destroy their planet and bottle its rejuvenating
qualities for their own life-of-leisure purposes. It's up to
Captain Picard (Patrick Stewart), Commander Riker (director
Jonathan Frakes), android Data (Brent Spiner) and the rest to stand
up for the rights of the taut and tawny.
</P>
<P>
   Fine by me. But while they're at it, I wish the crew would also
save the galaxy from so many apostrophes.
</P>
<P>
   The plot basically exists as a framework to keep those
unfamiliar with ``Trek'' convinced that they're watching a
stand-alone movie. It's a spine supporting little bits of business
to excite the hard-core audience. Think of it as an intergalactic
vaudeville act: Here comes an outer-space dogfight for action
buffs, for the date-night crowd a flirtatious bathtub scene for
Riker and Lt. Commander Troi (Marina Sirtis) _ and look, there's an
adorable, computer-generated rodent to make kids say ``aaaah.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Stewart gets to wear tight shirts to show his
biceps. Frakes shaves off his beard but still looks like William
Shatner. Worf (Michael Dorn) gets tough. La Forge (LeVar Burton)
experiences changes in his vision.
</P>
<P>
   And Spiner's inevitable, groanable,
android-learns-the-joy-of-being-human shtick is learning to play
with a kid in a haystack.
</P>
<P>
   It's a little like watching a family photo album flicking by at
warp speed. Fans will be charmed. Others might find themselves
remembering the tedium of some family reunions. (Listening to the
persistent gadgetry-gabble in the script is like getting stuck in
an elevator with your cousin the Internet geek.)
</P>
<P>
   The new film doesn't have a villain approaching the
seductive-lethal Borg Queen (played by Alice Krige) in the superior
``First Contact.'' Nor does Picard's character (or Stewart's
considerable acting chops) get tested, except for his mild
infatuation with a throaty, 300-plus-year-old vixen named Anij
(Broadway Tony-winner Donna Murphy, who lends a classy air).
</P>
<P>
   For all its universal aspirations, the series still seems
profoundly Californian in its surface values. The good guys are the
handsome-pretty ones. The bad guys have the wet-paper-bag
prosthetics on their faces. And the female crew is woefully
undeveloped. The main difference between Gates McFadden (Dr.
Crusher) and Sirtis seems to be their hair color. Then again,
that's Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``Star Trek: Insurrection''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Patrick Stewart, Brent Spiner and Donna Murphy.
Directed by Jonathan Frakes. Rated PG for sci-fi violence. At metro
theaters. 1 hour, 44 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: The Enterprise crew saves some blonds and has
</P>
<P>
   a few laughs in this so-so entry
</P>
<P>
   in the series.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
