<HEADER>
A3140 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-JACKFROST-TEX     12-10 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-JACKFROST-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THAT'S POWDERED SUGAR, NOT SNOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When a movie's soundtrack includes songs by Hanson and Foghat,
you know it's got at least one eye on marketing demographics, and
``Jack Frost'' makes no bones about how it's putting itself out
there as something for late baby boomers and their kids. Cynics
will object to such manipulation, and to much more, but then ``Jack
Frost'' isn't a movie for cynics.
</P>
<P>
   It is instead a sweet, sentimental, formulaic movie about death,
second chances and closure. It goes on too long, and you know where
it's going every step of the way. But even though it has all the
depth of a greeting card, it succeeds by not being too crass or
self-serious and by building an easy chemistry among its lead cast.
</P>
<P>
   Its plot doesn't sound that great: Michael Keaton plays a blues
musician named Jack Frost who dies in a car accident, then comes
back a year later as an animated snowman to try to patch some
things up with his 12-year-old son, Charlie (Joseph Cross, who also
played Keaton's son in the much worse ``Desperate Measures'').
Keaton has a thing for masks _ see ``Beetlejuice'' and the first
two ``Batmans'' _ but it's while he is human here that he does some
of his freshest, most unforced work in years. Jack's open, witty
relationship with Charlie is almost more brotherly than paternal,
and their good times together early on make for some of the movie's
most charming moments.
</P>
<P>
   The movie can't resist playing on yuppie guilt, though, and Jack
_ on the edge of a big record deal _ can't always find time to
spend with his son. Although Jack's good-natured wife (''Holy
Man's'' Kelly Preston, playing sweet again) tries to understand,
Charlie feels put out, and just as Jack starts to come to his
senses, he has that wreck.
</P>
<P>
   When he comes back as the snowman, it takes some getting used
to. A few years ago, the special effects might have been
impressive, but in the wake of ``Antz, A Bug's Life'' and the
second ``Babe,'' this movie's walking, talking snowman looks like
nothing so much as Michael Keaton in a snowman suit. And Keaton
seems just as restrained; he gets a chance to do some rambling
shtick and to have some touching scenes with Cross, but because
there's only so much you can do with a snowman's face, Keaton's
voice-overs sound too low-key and obvious.
</P>
<P>
   You do have to wonder why Jack the snowman keeps his identity
secret from everybody but Charlie and Charlie's hockey coach (Henry
Rollins in an annoyingly bombastic performance); most guys would
head straight for Preston right away, but Jack doesn't want her to
see him like this. The movie also overstuffs itself with subplots
about bullies, Charlie's hockey team and bonding attempts between
Charlie and one of his dad's former band members (''The Full
Monty's'' Mark Addy).
</P>
<P>
   As afterlife movies go, however, it's not that bad; it doesn't
bog itself down with solemnity, like ``What Dreams May Come,'' or
pull a last-minute bit of intelligence-insulting, like ``City of
Angels.'' It strives to be nothing more or less than what it is, a
simple, touching family movie for the holiday season. If that makes
it a trifle instead of a classic, well, sometimes trifles make for
pleasing gifts.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Jack Frost''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Troy Miller
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Michael Keaton, Joseph Cross, Kelly Preston
</P>
<P>
   Length: 96 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG _ language and occasional bits of mild rude humor
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a film critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
