<SLUG> BC-FILM-WAKINGNEDDEVINE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOTTERY CAPER IS A WINNING TICKET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I'm too old for jail,'' chuckles Jackie (Ian Bannen) in
``Waking Ned Devine,'' and he's not just being glib, either. Jackie
and his boon pal Michael (David Kelly) are a couple of old duffers
who spend a good deal of their time trying to chase down the
lottery winner in their small town. It's Jackie who's doing most of
the pursuing. Michael just tilts that head at the end of his long,
birdlike neck and trails along after Jackie.
</P>
<P>
   This little village looks like one of those locales where
everyone gets a good night's sleep. Even the lottery-obsessed
Jackie, whose eyes sparkle as he gets closer to discovering the
identity of the big ticket-holder. It's not much of a search,
though _ there are only 52 people in town. That includes a pig
farmer determined to win the heart of the woman he loves, although
he's a ways from winning her nose _ you can smell him in the
distance. (Jackie does give the poor fellow ``fruity soaps'' to
wash the odor away. ``Try the raspberry,'' he advises.)
</P>
<P>
   The movie kicks into gear when Jackie tromps off in the rain to
find the person holding the winning ticket. He hatches a plan that
includes Michael, ``who's never lied a day in his life.'' The
scheme gets bigger and sillier as it rolls along. It's probably
appropriate for Fox Searchlight to release a movie about winning
the lottery since ``The Full Monty'' did essentially that last
year, catching everyone off guard and claiming a top box-office
pride. ``Devine'' takes its ``Full Monty'' lineage seriously,
offering a view of the tan-free posteriors of its two stars, and a
sequence in which a nude Kelly races through the countryside on a
motorcycle _ he's visible only from the chest up, but that's enough
to show that he is wearing a helmet at all times.
</P>
<P>
   Writer-director Kirk Jones uses a sure, deft hand, even though
the movie is at best a slight delight. And the cast includes a
tight and polished group of professionals, with Bannen and Kelly
chief among them. This minor tease of a movie provides the moist,
clean air of a small seaside town not far from Dublin (the movie
was filmed on the Isle of Man.) Its likability comes from the
actors and the location. The picture itself lacks personality,
being a little indistinct but resolute in its need to charm. You
almost feel as if your pocket is being picked while it takes care
to brush off your lapels.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Waking Ned Devine''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Kirk Jones
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Ian Bannen, David Kelly
</P>
<P>
   Length: 90 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG _ mild language and brief nudity of the stars' rear
ends
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-98 1504EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
