<DOCNO> NYT19981210.0211 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 15:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3147 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-JASONCOLLIER13-CO     12-10 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-JASONCOLLIER13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    GA. TECH'S COLLIER TO PLAY FIRST GAME IN A YEAR SUNDAY
 &HT;    PHOTOS ARE AVAILABLE TO GO WITH THIS STORY
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jason Collier refuses to talk about the bad old days.
</P>
<P>
   Those were the 450 or so days he spent in Bloomington, Ind.,
participating in war games under the iron hand of Bobby Knight,
``The General.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the 7-0, 250-pound product of Springfield, Ohio, was
one of the most highly recruited high school players. He eliminated
overtures from Duke, Notre Dame and North Carolina and narrowed his
choices to Georgia Tech and Indiana. Indiana won out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just two hours and forty-five minutes away from home,''
he said. ``It was the closest big-time basketball program around.''
</P>
<P>
   It also was a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Collier started 27 of 33 games at Indiana as a freshman and
eight of nine as a sophomore, averaging 10 points and six rebounds
a game. He walked away one Wednesday morning last December. The
night before, he had had 11 points, seven rebounds and four assists
in a win over South Alabama. The next morning, he was gone.
</P>
<P>
   The word out of Bloomington was that Collier felt he was more of
a perimeter player and wasn't allowed to play his game. Supposedly,
his parents were pressuring him to leave after they weren't allowed
free access to him on a trip to a tournament in Hawaii. One story
is that when his roomates, Luke Recker and Michael Lewis, threw him
a going-away dinner the night he left, some of the team members
didn't come, splitting the team. Some Hoosier players thought that
once he returned for his sophomore year he had made a commitment
and should see it through, not walk out during the season.
</P>
<P>
   By January, Collier had enrolled at Georgia Tech and when the
Yellow Jackets play Georgia on Sunday, the big man will be eligible
to play for the first time in a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to dip into it,'' Collier said about his time at
Indiana. ``Every time I talk about it, it gets in the Bloomington
newspapers, and I get letters.''
</P>
<P>
   When he made his decision to attend Indiana, he said, it wasn't
what his mother or sister had expected. ``They both cried,'' he
said. ``They love Atlanta, and coach Cremins has been a friend of
the family for years.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting out a year was excruciating for Collier, who had to sit
and watch when he knew he could be helping.
</P>
<P>
   Having gone through it, Collier said he thinks the NCAA rules
governing transfers need to be changed. ``If you get married and it
doesn't work out, you can get divorced and re-marry the very next
day,'' he said. ``But if you're a 17- or 18-year-old kid and make a
mistake, you lose a year of your life.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he must come out of the gate at full speed against Georgia,
with Kentucky and North Carolina following in the next two weeks.
``With Travis (Spivey) and Pablo (Machado) gone (as transfers) and
Dion (Glover) hurt, it's been a hard year,'' he said, ``but with
what I've been through over the past two years, that's not a
problem with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Collier will wear No. 52 Sunday afternoon, the same number worn
by his father, Jeff, when he played for Dwane Morrison at Tech,
1973-76.
</P>
<P>
   His presence will add immediate depth to a depleted Tech lineup
without Glover, who is out for the year, and Jon Babul, who hurt an
ankle. He will complement the inside game of Tech's 6-11 Alvin
Jones and give the Jackets a big body to take up some of the
rebounding slack in Babul's absence.
</P>
<P>
   Coller started his athletic career as a swimmer and won national
awards as an 11- and 12-year-old. But by the sixth grade, he was
six feet tall, and he gave up swimming in the seventh grade to
concentrate on basketball. When he entered Catholic Central High as
a freshman, he was 6-6 and weighed 156. ``I was a toothpick,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But the toothpick grew, and so did his value. By Collier's
senior year, he was rated as the best big man in the country by
four different recruiting services.
</P>
<P>
   Although Collier won't talk about his off-court differences with
Knight, he said his on-court expectations at Georgia Tech are
different than what was expected of him by Knight. ``I was
inside-oriented all the time at Indiana,'' he said. ``I was told
not to shoot threes, not to do this, not to do that. There was a
lot more I wasn't allowed to do than I was.''
</P>
<P>
   But on Collier's first day at practice at Tech, he says he knew
things were going to be different. ``Coach Cremins handed me the
ball out beyond the three-point line and told me to shoot it,'' he
said. ``I shot it and made it. He said, 'We're going to try to get
you back to where you were.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Collier will be listed as a power forward on the basketball
program, but his role will be more of a small forward, much like
Matt Harpring played last year. Cremins plans to exploit all of
Collier's talents, including his long-range abilities. ``The reason
people talk about my perimeter game,'' Collier said, ``is that not
many big guys can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
