<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 15:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3164 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-     12-10 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ED HARRIS TO DIRECT AND STAR IN `POLLOCK' 
JOHN MADDEN AND `SHAKESPEARE IN LOVE' 
`RUSHMORE': A GEEK'S STORY
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   `Pollock,' Priced At $6.5 Million
</P>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Looking at the Jackson Pollock canvases at the
painter's retrospective at the Museum of Modern Art in New York has
a special resonance for actor Ed Harris. Harris, who has spent
hours at the show and who has read numerous books on Pollock's life
and career, has been consumed for years with the artist. Now, he is
going to do something about it.
</P>
<P>
   The 48-year-old actor is set to start making a film about
Pollock in March or April. Not only will Harris portray the
Abstract Expressionist, who died in a drunken-driving crash in 1956
at the age of 44, he is also going to direct the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been dealing with this for years, probably five, six
years, maybe more,'' Harris said. ``I'm just very, very curious
about exploring this guy, about trying to understand him. He had a
difficult time being a human being. He put most of his feelings and
a sense of purity into his work. I'm curious about tracking that
down and seeing what happens to me.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been a good week for Harris, a character actor for more
than a decade. Tuesday the National Board of Review, a film critics
group, announced that he had won an award for his supporting roles
in two films: Peter Weir's ``Truman Show,'' in which he played the
man who manipulates the Jim Carrey character, and Chris Columbus'
``Stepmom,'' opening Christmas Day, in which he plays a man who
leaves Susan Sarandon for Julia Roberts. The announcement was a
sign that Harris is a contender for an Academy Award nomination,
especially for ``The Truman Show.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris said that his compulsion to play Pollock was difficult to
explain, and that even he didn't understand it. ``It's an
instinctive desire I have,'' he said. ``I guess I feel there are
certain similarities between him and me, but he was more extreme
than I've ever been. He was, of course, an original. And he really
fought to get to a place where he was creating something that was
not derivative of anything.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I do identify with him on some level. Here's a guy
who put a huge canvas on the ground, totally blank, and he's driven
to fill it up. I'm just very curious about the process of creation
through his eyes, his being. I'm really not sure where the film
will lead. It will have a life of its own, in some sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood has been attracted before to Pollock's tormented life
and career. Several years ago there was talk that Robert De Niro
and Barbra Streisand would play the artist and his wife, the
painter Lee Krasner. But nothing happened.
</P>
<P>
   Harris has not yet cast an actress for the Krasner role in his
film, ``Pollock,'' which is based on the book about the artist by
Steven Naifeh and Gregory White Smith. Harris said that the
Pollock-Krasner estate was cooperating on the movie, but that he
was seeking permission from museums and private collectors to show
Pollock's art in the film. The film, independently made, is
budgeted for a relatively modest $6.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Harris, who is married to actress Amy Madigan, grew up in
Tenafly, N.J., attended Columbia University for two years and later
graduated from the California Institute of the Arts. He worked for
years in theater, mostly off- Broadway and in Los Angeles.
Currently, he's completing ``The Third Miracle,'' a drama directed
by Agnieszka Holland and co-starring Anne Heche.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he liked Pollock, Harris said, after a pause: ``It was
not easy for him to be in society. He struggled. I like him, I
guess, because he was full of contradictions _ he was a fighter, he
was scared, he was arrogant, he was humble, he was inarticulate yet
very bright. And he was searching for love. And he found it in his
work.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Stratfordians
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 18 months ago, John Madden, a British director whose last
film was the highly successful historical drama ``Mrs. Brown,''
received a telephone call from Harvey Weinstein, co-chairman of
Miramax. Weinstein, whose company released ``Mrs. Brown,'' said he
was sending Madden a script called ``Shakespeare in Love,'' hoping
he would direct it.
</P>
<P>
   Madden said: ``I've never had such an instantaneous reaction. I
barely got past the first four pages. It was the first of many
times I threw the script in the air.''
</P>
<P>
   He accepted the job immediately.
</P>
<P>
   The film, an elegant comedy starring Gwyneth Paltrow, Joseph
Fiennes and Geoffrey Rush, opens Friday with strong advance
reviews. Written by Zack Norman and English playwright Tom
Stoppard, the film explores life in a theater troupe in
16th-century England and raises the question: what if Shakespeare
had writer's block while writing ``Romeo and Juliet''?
</P>
<P>
   The film depicts well-known figures like Queen Elizabeth I and
Christopher Marlowe, as well as Shakespeare, of course, in
fictional situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about Shakespeare's life is: no one knows
anything,'' said Madden, a 49-year-old film and theatrical
director. ``And what's special about the movie's approach, I hope,
is the way it gets behind the iconic nature of the persona and
paraphernalia that is Shakespeare now and deals with him in a fresh
way, with a glorious mischievous attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare, he said, should be treated almost as a pop writer
who wrote for mass audiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a guy with a knack for writing on deadline,'' Madden
said. ``He was a superlative popular entertainer at one level, a
bloke good at writing words rather than just a genius composing
great literature in a solitary environment.''
</P>
<P>
   The film has a somewhat tortuous history. It was taken to
Universal Studios by the director Edward Zwick in 1996 and set to
star Julia Roberts and Daniel Day-Lewis. That deal fell apart, and
Zwick later brought the script to Weinstein of Miramax. The company
paid $4.5 million for the movie and picked up the preproduction
costs at Universal, the largest amount Miramax had ever paid, at
that time, for a project.
</P>
<P>
   Because Zwick had signed on to direct ``The Siege,'' the
director's job went to Madden, who taught in the late 1970s and
early '80s at the Yale School of Drama and who has staged plays at
the New York Public Theater and the Mark Taper Forum in Los
Angeles. Eventually, Miramax and Universal shared the costs of the
$30 million to $35 million movie.
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare's personal life is largely a mystery. Indeed, the
time between 1585, when he was 21 and already married, and 1592 are
known as ``the lost years.'' In 1593, Shakespeare published some of
his most erotic sonnets, and one year later wrote ``Romeo and
Juliet.'' The film begins with ``the lost years'' and continues
through his work on ``Romeo and Juliet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Was it possible for a man to write this way about love and
sexuality and passion without having experienced something close to
it in his life?'' Madden asked. ``I doubt it.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``There's a stigma attached to Shakespeare by many
people now, a feeling that he's remote and inaccessible and
elitist. But none of those things are true.''
</P>
<P>
   A Geek's Story
</P>
<P>
   Max Fischer is the kind of 10th-grader at Rushmore Academy whose
first choices for college are Oxford and perhaps the Sorbonne.
Harvard is his safety school. Unfortunately, Max is also one of the
school's worst students, has been placed on probation and is deeply
and futilely in love with a British first-grade teacher and tries
to win her over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Max invents his own reality, he sees himself as a young don at
Oxford, he says his father's a neurosurgeon when he's actually a
barber, he's totally oblivious to what other kids think,'' said Wes
Anderson, the 29-year-old director and co-author with his friend,
Owen Wilson, of ``Rushmore,'' a quirky and off-center movie that
has already earned positive reviews at film festivals. The comedy,
released by Disney, opens Friday for a week in New York and Los
Angeles so that the film can qualify for the Oscars (review on page
X). It opens nationwide Feb. 5.
</P>
<P>
   As they did on their first film together, ``Bottle Rocket,''
Anderson and Wilson have used their common experiences as
teen-agers growing up in Houston and Dallas, respectively, to make
``Rushmore.'' The film stars an unknown, Jason Schwartzman, a
recent high school graduate in Los Angeles, as the geeky Max.
Schwartzman was selected after a nine-month search. Also in the
cast is Bill Murray as an oddball businessman who befriends the
youth but also falls for the first-grade teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world of this movie is sort of unreal, like a fable,''
Anderson said. ``You have a broadness and strangeness not based on
reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Roth, chairman of Walt Disney Studios, agreed to a $10
million budget for the film _ and then left the filmmakers alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sent us to Texas, we made the film, edited it, showed it to
him and he said the movie was ready to be released,'' Anderson
said. ``They were not at all intrusive.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Anderson and Disney are a bit worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned that it's an unusual movie, and I don't know of
any specific group that it's for,'' Anderson said. ``Do you think
people will show up for it? I hope so.''
</P>
</TEXT>
