<SLUG> BC-POWER-LIABILITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO TALLIES LOSSES FROM BLACKOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VICTORIA COLLIVER AND JACOB H. FRIES  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANACISCO _ Facing the likelihood of claims resulting from
a massive power outage this week, the Pacific Gas and Electric Co.
has mobilized a team of investigators to evaluate damages.
</P>
<P>
   ``PG&AMP;E has acknowledged the blackout resulted from human error,
and not an act of God, so we hope to address all these claims as
quickly as possible,'' PG&AMP;E spokesman Tony Ledwell said Wednesday,
a day after the outage that affected more than 1 million people.
``The blackout came right at the height of the shopping season, so
it makes sense lots of retailers would say they lost business.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,000 people have requested claim forms from the power
company, a subsidiary of the PG&AMP;E Corp., while businesses and city
departments were tallying the losses.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Willie Brown and other city officials have said city
departments would add up losses and submit the claims to PG&AMP;E
within 90 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We intend to have the city attorney handle all aspects of any
claims filed with the appropriate review,'' Brown said Wednesday.
``Each department will look at its daily spending to determine what
was lost and what was incurred.''
</P>
<P>
   Treasurer Susan Leal said the city lost interest on property tax
collections _ which typically amount to $30 million to $40 million
each day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only do we lose the interest, but we were overdrawn,''
Leal said. ``We got a double whammy.''
</P>
<P>
   Other city losses incurred during the blackout included the
overtime incurred by the police, transit workers and other
employees.
</P>
<P>
   PG&AMP;E said mistakes made by workers at a power substation in San
Mateo triggered a shutdown of two San Francisco substations,
pulling the plug on most of the city and the northern half of San
Mateo County. Only one death was blamed on the outage, an elderly
woman who was struck and killed at an intersection where the
traffic signal was not working.
</P>
<P>
   PG&AMP;E spokesman Len Anderson said he expected many claims to be
from homeowners seeking compensation for lost perishables; computer
damage from surges; and business lost due to the blackout.
</P>
<P>
   Tapan Munroe, who spent 17 years as PG&AMP;E's chief economist and
is now a community economic development consultant, said the San
Francisco-based utility appeared to be taking the problem seriously
by owning up to its responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ought to give us a real wake-up call, and we should
mobilize to make sure we have the most reliable systems possible,''
he said, adding that companies should learn from those that had
back-up systems that minimized losses.
</P>
<P>
   A number of businesses were reluctant to say whether any claims
would be filed until the losses were calculated.
</P>
<P>
   The Starbucks Coffee Co. lost business at 36 coffeehouses in the
affected area, but a spokeswoman for the Seattle-based company
would not say whether a claim would be filed.
</P>
<P>
   Lucky Stores spokeswoman Judie Decker said the grocery chain
hoped to have enough information by Friday to know whether to file
a claim.
</P>
<P>
   While Nordstrom was the only major retailer in downtown San
Francisco to remain open Tuesday because of its backup generator
system, representatives said the department store had incurred
significant losses but had not yet determined what action to take.
</P>
<P>
   At Neiman Marcus, which held its ``InCircle'' party Tuesday
night to honor customers who spend more than $3,000 a year at the
store, attendance was up 50 percent over last year. Ann Paolini,
general manager of the Neiman Marcus store at Union Square, said
the store had entertained 1,600 shoppers after opening at 2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a huge surprise to us. We couldn't have been happier,''
she said, adding that sales for the two-day event were up ``double
digits'' over last year. ``Certainly there's no lost revenues to
discuss, and there were no expense issues to speak of.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Hauge, head of Cal Insurance Co., said that even though he
had losses of at least $5,000, he would not go after PG&AMP;E.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an accident; those things happen,'' he said. ``I could
make a mistake in my business, too, and I would hope nobody would
sue me. It didn't destroy me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
