<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PLAN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`A SIMPLE PLAN' FEATURES GREAT CAST, BUT WEAK SCREENPLAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sam Raimi wasn't the first choice to direct the film version of
Scott B. Smith's 1993 novel, ``A Simple Plan.'' He wasn't even the
second or third.
</P>
<P>
   Raimi is known more as a schlock-master (he's directed ``The
Evil Dead,'' ``Darkman,'' and ``The Quick and the Dead'' among
other cult favorites), than as a serious filmmaker.
</P>
<P>
   But even if he got the job by default, it may have been a
blessing.
</P>
<P>
   He has cast the film sensibly, with earthier actors who fit the
``everyman'' theme of the story better than flashy leading men Brad
Pitt and Nicolas Cage, who were originally supposed to star under
Mike Nichols' direction.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Paxton, Billy Bob Thornton, Bridget Fonda and Brent Briscoe
are the glue that hold this somber re-telling of Smith's moral
fable together. It's a simple story: Hank (Paxton), his older
brother Jacob (Thornton) and Jacob's friend Lou (Briscoe) stumble
upon a snow-covered single-engine plane crashed in the woods.
Inside are a decomposing pilot and a canvas bag holding $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   For Lou and Jacob, who are suffering through unemployment and a
harsh Minnesota winter, the find equals heaven. For Hank, who works
in the feed mill and has a pregnant wife, Sarah (Fonda), earning a
little income at the library, it presents a different dilemma. The
trio agree to stash the money at Hank's, tell no one and, once the
heat dies down, take the loot and move on to better and bigger
lives.
</P>
<P>
   But, predictably, everything goes awry and before long the body
count builds. The perfectly thought-out scheme unravels, loyalties
fray and tensions build.
</P>
<P>
   Lou gets greedy. While greed has been a dramatic ploy since
human beings began to write, add the maxim, ``anything that can
happen, will,'' and the seed is sown for betrayal and marital
discord that is right in line with Shakespeare's ``Macbeth.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the film's setup is paced well, something fails to click.
Smith's screenplay excises some of the book's violence but it also
extinguishes much of its soul. Its moral fiber feels muted and the
entire movie reeks of too much reverence toward the source
material.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Thornton and Briscoe are amazing as Jacob and Lou. The
pair are a studied contrast in ethical extremes, with Jacob acting
as the conscience and Lou as the hot-headed linchpin who pushes the
scheme toward disaster. Ultimately, it's up to Paxton to provide
the equilibrium, and he does it well.
</P>
<P>
   Because of its script problems, ``A Simple Plan'' has too much
lag time. Though the climactic moment where Jacob is forced to
choose between his brother and Lou crackles with sadness, dread and
impending violence, the rest of the film is humorless and dreary
and drifts endlessly without making much of a point or fully
finding its potential.
</P>
<P>
   A Simple Plan. Directed by Sam Raimi. Written by Scott B. Smith.
Cast: Bill Paxton, Billy Bob Thornton, Bridget Fonda. Paramount
Pictures. 110 minutes. Rated R for violence, language.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-98 1531EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981210.0220 </DOCNO>
