<SLUG> BC-TV-SCHRODER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO BUTS ABOUT IT: RICK SCHRODER IS A SMASH ON `NYPD BLUE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This e-mail from a friend and colleague was one of the first to
greet me after nearly two weeks away from the beat: ``Rick Schroder
is terrific. His first two episodes were as smooth a transition as
I ever saw on episodic TV. I want to know all his secrets (and I
bet he has plenty), and if ABC is smart the secrets will be
revealed agonizingly slowly. This guy is just as appealing as Bobby
Simone, but in so many different ways.''
</P>
<P>
   It's exactly what I would have said about Schroder's addition to
the ``NYPD Blue'' cast if my brain cells hadn't been stored in the
upright and locked position for so long. Without benefit of a
little post-vacation WD-40, the best I could come up with was:
``Schroder good, Bochco smart.''
</P>
<P>
   Any way you say it, the Schroder move is already looking boffo
for ``Blue'' and its estimable producer, Steven Bochco. Though I
liked Jimmy Smits a lot, Schroder's new character, Detective Danny
Sorenson, has me itching for next week's episode the way I did
during the first season, when David Caruso brought a tantalizing
mysteriousness to the character of Detective John Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   Part of it is the newness, of course. Bochco is nothing if not
clever. His decision to cast a former child star in a gritty role
raised the curiosity quotient higher than Andy Sipowicz's blood
pressure. High fives to Bochco and co-executive producer David
Milch for not making Detective Danny a wide-eyed neophyte in need
of mentoring from Andy, the wise old cop (Dennis Franz). I like how
Danny's swagger has caught Andy a little off guard. I like even
better that Danny has some ``secrets,'' as my correspondent noted,
and that Schroder is being allowed to dribble them out slowly. Is
there a question about his sexuality? About violence in his past?
</P>
<P>
   Schroder is coyly keeping the answers under the shell of his
tough, street-smart character. But sure as Andy is likely to hurl
an insult his way, the answers are likely to emerge as Danny
Sorenson helps us to forget Bobby Simone.
</P>
<P>
   Also nice to see that Bochco and Milch haven't lost their senses
of humor. Only two episodes into Schroder's tenure and we've
already seen his ``bottom line'' performance _ the continuation of
a cheeky tradition that began with Caruso and has now included
Smits, Franz, Amy Brenneman, Kim Delaney, Sharon Lawrence and
Andrea Thompson in their ``Blue'' moon phases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-98 1532EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981210.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 15:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3208 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-DEVINE-SPI &LR;      12-10 0496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-DEVINE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WAKING NED DEVINE' IS A FINE, FEEL-GOOD COMEDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Waking Ned Devine'' is sure to be classified as this year's
``The Full Monty'' with its feel-good tone and crowd-pleasing
comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that this comic fable is rather clunkily edited,
contains some gaping plot holes and is so wispy thin it could blow
away on a breeze.
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, writer and director Kirk Jones has no lofty
pretensions about what his movie means: it's just plain
sweet-natured and gentle with a bit of a black comedic twist.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the Irish village of Tully More. The population is
all of 52, but after the Saturday night lotto game, Ned Devine's
ticker gives out when he learns he's holding the winning ticket,
and the head count in the town shrinks by one. ``I always thought
the sea would take him, not a few lottery balls,'' says Jackie
O'Shea (Ian Bannen) to his lifelong friend, Michael O'Sullivan
(David Kelly).
</P>
<P>
   The ``boys'' are the town's mischievous old-timers; they're 60+
but have been getting into trouble since they were lads. This time,
even Jackie's gruffly loving wife, Annie (Fionnula Flanagan),
thinks they've gone too far: when the friends learn someone in the
village has the winning numbers worth more than 6 million pounds,
they hatch a plan to find out who has the prize in order to share
the wealth.
</P>
<P>
   When the boys discover Ned Devine dead in his cottage by the sea
with the lotto card in his hand, they devise a way to revive Ned,
get the money and split it among the economically depressed
township. Everyone can then be a winner they argue, but first the
boys have to learn a lesson about the real meaning of loyalty and
luck.
</P>
<P>
   Briskly paced without ever digging too deeply into any of the
characters' motivations, ``Waking Ned Devine'' owes a lot to its
fine cast. Veteran actors Ian Bannen and Fionnula Flanagan are
charming and vital as Jackie and Annie and Irish actor David Kelly
(``Fawlty Towers'') is a joy as the more sensible Michael. They're
such consummate pros that they give depth to the slender script and
the film the gusto and energy it sorely needs to spring to life.
</P>
<P>
   The film was shot in a tiny, government-protected village called
Cregneash, located in the Irish Sea on the Isle of Man. The
brooding, isolated locale is a rugged contrast to the light story
and also contributes a needed layer to the simple work.
</P>
<P>
   Both these elements _ actors and setting _ combine to make what
Bannen calls ``simply a damn good comedy'' that's sure to whet
American moviegoing appetites for Anglo fare. This may just be the
next innocuous sleeper to overcome the limitations of the ``art
house'' label.
</P>
<P>
   Waking Ned Devine. Directed and written by Kirk Jones. Cast: Ian
Bannen, David Kelly, Fionnula Flanagan, Susan Lynch. Fox
Searchlight. 91 minutes. Rated PG for nudity.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
