<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-RESEND-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME URGE FIRMS TO BOOT HIGH HEELS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Working column from Dec. 4 being resent; Dec. 11 column will
move Friday) 
 
(Attn: Rocky Mountain News) 
 
By L.M. SIXEL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Are high-heeled shoes discriminatory footwear for
women? Many workplaces require women to wear shoes with heels, some
as high as three inches, but men can wear sensible wing tips.
</P>
<P>
   While the subject may sound odd, the mandatory wearing of
high-heeled shoes has become the focus of a lawsuit as well as
serious academic research.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the case of Karla Qwist, a cocktail server at the Rio
Suite Hotel &AMP; Casino in Las Vegas, who told her boss she couldn't
wear the high stiletto heels that are part of her ``Girl from
Ipanema'' costume because she has foot problems.
</P>
<P>
   When the casino refused to accommodate her request to wear flat
shoes, Qwist sued under the Americans with Disabilities Act. Qwist
and other waitresses also sued the casino, alleging gender
discrimination and contending the 2- to 3-inch-high shoes caused
women physical deformity. Men are allowed to wear low-heeled shoes
as part of their costume.
</P>
<P>
   Qwist's initial lawsuit was rejected by a lower court judge who
contended that she wasn't sufficiently disabled to require her
employer to accommodate her, and that she didn't file the gender
discrimination claim within required time limits.
</P>
<P>
   Cathy Ruckelshaus, Qwist's attorney and litigation director for
the National Employment Law Project, a nonprofit advocacy group in
New York that represents low-wage workers, said she plans to argue
that Qwist's disability is indeed severe and that the
discrimination case was filed on time.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Bogatz, vice president and general counsel of the Rio,
said he couldn't comment on pending litigation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
FEET SMART IN STUPID SHOES &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's an interesting case because many employers force women to
wear shoes that have a deleterious health effect, said Marc Linder,
professor of law at the University of Iowa and author of the
article, ``Smart Women, Stupid Shoes and Cynical Employers: The
Unlawfulness and Adverse Health Consequences of Sexually
Discriminatory Workplace Footwear Requirements for Female
Employees.''
</P>
<P>
   High heels are especially common in the airline industry as some
carriers require their flight attendants wear at least 1.5-inch
heels, he said. Instead of concentrating on passenger safety,
airlines want their flight attendants to look glamorous and leggy
as they serve beverages and pass out magazines, he said.
</P>
<P>
   While Dallas-based Southwest Airlines went to the U.S. Supreme
Court to keep its flight attendants in hot pants and go-go boots
(it lost), the carrier now encourages its attendants to wear
sneakers. They're more comfortable for people who are on their feet
all day long, said Melanie Jones, Southwest spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Houston-based Continental Airlines lowered shoe heights in 1995
to reduce slips and falls, which was one of the biggest
occupational injuries plaguing the airline. The strategy worked _
women can wear heels as low as 1/4 inch _ and the number of falls
fell by 80 percent, a spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   High heels can cause severe foot problems, said Lynnelle
Gabriel, a podiatrist in Houston who sees many working women hobble
into her office on high heels.
</P>
<P>
   Hammertoes, caused by wearing pointy-toed shoes, are the most
common complaint, Gabriel said. Hammertoes form when two or more
toes get pushed together and curl up and then a corn appears that
grows into the foot.
</P>
<P>
   High heels cause toe, heel and lower back problems, she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
EXPECTATIONS AT WORK &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gabriel said she recommends to her clients that they wear heels
less than one inch high, but many tell her that they must wear
heels higher than that. It's largely social pressure, said Gabriel,
adding that many women just want to get their foot problems fixed
and go back to their same high heels. Men, on the other hand, heed
her advice to stop wearing pointy-toed casual shoes and their foot
problems typically disappear.
</P>
<P>
   Two women who work for a prominent Houston bank said they feel
pressure to wear heels at work. The two women, who were spotted
recently wearing sneakers during a lunchtime break, said nothing
has ever been said, but they just know that to look the part, high
heels _ in the 2-inch variety _ are part of the uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Other women who were spotted on the street recently said they
don't wear high heels to work out of any job requirement but more
because heels ``finish'' their outfit, make them look taller or
make their big feet appear smaller.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're hell aren't they?'' said Irene Alexander, a legal
secretary in Houston spotted recently wearing black stiletto heels.
She works for a law firm and the shoes lend authority to her short
frame.
</P>
<P>
   Another woman was surprised at all the fuss over high heels.
What about the discrimination of panty hose? she asked.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
L.M. Sixel can receive electronic mail via the Internet. Address
your comments and questions to lm.sixel(at)chron.com, or call (713)
220-2000 and enter access code 1002. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
