<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 15:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3251 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MERGER-REGULATORS-TEX     12-10 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MERGER-REGULATORS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OIL MERGER LIKELY TO DRAW CLOSE SCRUTINY OF EUROPEAN REGULATORS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL D. TOWLE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Exxon Mobil may be an oil giant made in America.
But the merger partners can expect foreign antitrust regulators to
take a close look at their proposed deal because of the worldwide
impact it could have.
</P>
<P>
   Before Exxon and Mobil form the world's largest company, the
European Union and foreign antitrust regulators will examine the
likely effect on prices at the pump and dominance in refining.
</P>
<P>
   Although unlikely, a ``no'' vote by a foreign regulatory agency,
or a move to force the companies to divest a large number of core
assets, could slow the merger or stop it, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Foreign antitrust authorities have become increasingly
active,'' said Mark Schechter, an antitrust expert in the
Washington law firm Howrey &AMP; Simon. ``If a transaction has a
substantial, direct and foreseeable impact on consumers, they would
assert that they have jurisdiction.''
</P>
<P>
   The European Union, through its antitrust regulator, the
European Commission, has become involved in some major American
mergers. The commission forced MCI Corp. of Washington to agree to
sell its Internet business before it merged in September with
WorldCom, based in Jackson, Miss. European regulators estimated
that the combined company would have controlled about half the
world's Internet traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the commission endorsed Boeing Co.'s $14 billion
purchase of rival McDonnell Douglas only after Boeing agreed not to
enforce 20-year exclusive contracts with Fort Worth-based American
Airlines and two other major U.S. carriers.
</P>
<P>
   Ignoring the European Union's objections to a deal could result
in billion-dollar sanctions, and the EU could move to close
companies out of key markets by blocking shipments, rejecting
licenses or taking other measures.
</P>
<P>
   In the Boeing case, some commissioners said Boeing planes could
be seized if the deal went through and their problems were not
dealt with.
</P>
<P>
   ``If firms have assets and facilities in your country, you have
some control over those,'' said James Brock, a professor of
economics at Miami University in Oxford, Ohio. ``In the extreme,
you can seize those and use them as leverage. They can get nasty
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Such strong-arm tactics are not likely to result from the
Exxon-Mobil merger. Most observers expect the EU and other foreign
agencies to look primarily at the same issues important to U.S.
regulators: the number of gas stations in each market and the
company's ability to control prices.
</P>
<P>
   Most experts expect the deal to go through if Mobil and Exxon
agree to pare a portion of their 48,000 stations worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be certain countries in Europe where they face
certain constraints, but there is also very broad competition
there,'' said Steve Smith, a Houston-based analyst with the
brokerage firm Dain Rauscher Wessels.
</P>
<P>
   ``My gut feeling is that they will get more scrutiny here than
abroad,'' said Eugene ``Chip'' Hodge, an analyst with John Hancock,
an insurance and investment firm.
</P>
<P>
   Brock said foreign regulators are unlikely to attack Exxon and
Mobil if they did not balk at the other mergers the industry has
seen, such as British Petroleum's proposed purchase of Amoco this
year.
</P>
<P>
   The marriage of two of the world's biggest oil companies comes
amid a wave of mergers in the industry, which is trying to cope
with the lowest oil prices in 25 years and high costs for producing
and refining.
</P>
<P>
   The new company, to be called Exxon Mobil Corp., would be the
world's largest company in terms of revenue, surpassing General
Motors.
</P>
<P>
   The $80 billion merger is the biggest in U.S. corporate history,
topping the $72.6 billion paid this year by Travelers Group for
Citicorp. It brings together companies with combined 1997 net
income of $11.8 billion and revenue of $203 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The companies have said the new corporate home will be at
Exxon's current headquarters in Irving. But both companies have
vast global operations.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon is the world's second-largest oil company, selling about
65 million gallons of fuel to more than 8 million motorists daily.
The company markets or produces products in more than 100
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon also produces petrochemicals, mines coal and other
minerals, and it owns about 60 percent of an electric
power-generating station in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Mobil is similar to Exxon in many ways. The company is the
world's fourth-largest oil company, behind Royal Dutch/Shell, Exxon
and British Petroleum.
</P>
<P>
   Mobil has exploration and production activities in 25 countries
and has operations in about 115 others. The company produces
petrochemicals, wood and polymer building materials, plastics and
other products.
</P>
<P>
   Combined, Exxon Mobil would control 4 percent of world oil
production and about 14 percent of U.S. gasoline sales.
</P>
<P>
   Schechter, the Washington antitrust lawyer, said that in most
cases such market-share figures would not raise regulator
objections. They will focus on market share in regions of each
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is most interesting about the merger is that the shares
of the two companies are far from extraordinary,'' he said. ``If
this was a deal in any other industry, no one would be raising
eyebrows. It's fair to guess that in the end the deal will go
through.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
