<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEVIDEO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME VIDEO NOTES AND NEWS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; The Fast Way To See Films &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Films leave theaters and move on to home viewing. Where will you
find them first, in video stores or on pay-per-view? According to a
video industry survey, almost half the people who rent films on
videocassette are under the impression that they are available
either at the same time or sooner on pay-per-view.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the opposite is true. Somehow, almost 20 years into the
video age, many people are apparently unaware that movie studios
grant home video exclusive first use of movies for 30 to 60 days on
average before they are offered on pay-per-view and longer still
before they are shown on cable.
</P>
<P>
   Alarmed at the misperception, Blockbuster, the country's largest
video chain, is running a commercial in which a jellyfish gradually
evolves through the eons into a modern couch potato. That, the
message contends, is about how long it takes for a film to reach
cable.
</P>
<P>
   Cable people don't argue the point. ``If you want movies first,
the video store is the place to go,'' said Ted Hodgins,
pay-per-view manager of Media General in Fairfax County, Va. But he
added that the success of pay-per-view via satellite, if not cable,
has finally made home video pay attention to the competition.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `Antz' Goes Marching &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, video hurries along. Though ``Antz'' is expected to
play in theaters through December, Dreamworks Home Entertainment
has scheduled the video release for Feb. 9, only four months after
the film opened. Big movies typically take closer to six months to
reach stores.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Brown, head of Dreamworks' home entertainment operations,
said the idea was to join theater and video promotions. ``Keep the
ad campaigns right on top of each other,'' he said. Then focus on
the first week of release. ``That's when you get your shot,'' he
said, which is pretty much the way it works in movie theaters.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Jerusalem's Children &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Are there patrols around?'' asks Yacoub, a 9-year-old
Palestinian boy, speaking into his walkie-talkie as he scans the
streets from the rooftop. In ``Yacoub,'' one of seven half-hour
documentaries in Beverly Shaffer's series ``Children of Jerusalem''
from the National Film Board of Canada, he and his younger brother
pretend they are on the lookout for Israeli soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   For the rest of the film he engagingly describes his close
family life, his pride in his rigorous schooling, his job helping
out in his uncle's falafel shop and the devout religious regimen of
a Christian Arab boy.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Shaffer lets Yacoub and six other children, both Israeli and
Arab, talk about themselves as she films their families and homes.
</P>
<P>
   Asya, a 12-year-old Russian immigrant, revels in her new life as
an Israeli. Others in her household describe the frightening
tendency to blame Jews for worsening conditions in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Troubles are present or alluded to, but these are satisfying
little films, full of hope and gratitude, strong values, old
stones, sunny streets, well-kept flowers and delicious-looking
bread. The films are distributed by Ergo Media (information:
800-695-3746).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW RELEASES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Truce &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In a departure from his more frenetic roles, the gaunt-faced
John Turturro quietly portrays the Italian writer and Holocaust
survivor Primo Levi in the period immediately after his liberation
from Auschwitz by Russian soldiers. Based on ``The Reawakening,''
an autobiographical account by Levi, who committed suicide in 1987,
Francesco Rosi's film follows the writer as he makes a long journey
home through a series of displaced person camps. While there are
some flashy moments thrown in for effect, Stephen Holden wrote in
The New York Times, ``the anguished uncertainty clouding Turturro's
haunted face is all the drama this film really needs.'' _1996.
Miramax. $104.16. 128 minutes. Closed captioned. R. Release date:
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lethal Weapon 4 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   With its familiar pieces in place, the old action series rattles
along on the same jokey, often wincingly banal camaraderie between
the detectives Riggs (Mel Gibson) and Murtaugh (Danny Glover). As
always, ridiculous situations _ in this case involving Chinese
gangsters who are smuggling illegal aliens _ serve as the
connective between fireballs. This time, Riggs' pregnant girlfriend
(Rene Russo) participates in the martial arts, but the attitudes
and banter, about homosexuality and other matters, are as benighted
as ever. That understood, ``the formula still has some zip'' (Janet
Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   _1998. Warner. $107.37. 127 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Madeline &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The 12 little girls from Ludwig Bemelmans' ``Madeline'' stories
are still in straight lines, but for the screen they've been taught
to lisp. A picture-book prettiness pervades this too terribly sweet
tale drawn from four Bemelmans books. Frances McDormand contributes
her usually adept performance as the mother hen, Miss Clavel, and a
production team not known for treacle has given the film a spare
visual sophistication. Otherwise it is ``best watched by viewers
who approach the material in a state of pre-adoration'' (Maslin).
_1998. Columbia Tri-Star. $23.95. 89 minutes. Closed captioned. PG.
Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Halloween: H20 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The H20 has nothing to do with water but refers to the fact that
the film commemorates the 20th anniversary of ``Halloween,'' John
Carpenter's very good original starring Jamie Lee Curtis. In this
film, directed by Steve Miner, Ms. Curtis is back (along with her
mother, Janet Leigh, a star of the original ``Psycho,'' whose minor
role here adds a nice touch). A campus, the locale of choice in
many recent horror films, is the setting for some grisly doings by
a vengeful slasher. But on this occasion, despite rustling
curtains, underlighted hallways and much suspenseful atmosphere,
``frankly, it's more marketing trick than moviegoer treat''
(Lawrence Van Gelder). _1998. Dimension. $107.37. 86 minutes.
Closed captioned. Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release at one time or appeared on television. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KING LEAR. &LR;  Ian Holm stars in Richard Eyre's Royal National
Theater production, shown on Masterpiece Theater in October. A
minimalist ``Lear'' uses its spareness as part of the performance.
``This is Shakespeare filtered through Beckett and Brecht,'' Caryn
James wrote in The New York Times, ``but it's far from a slick
attempt to update the play. The result is a production of such
freshness that it seems we are seeing the old story anew.'' 1998.
Anchor Bay. $29.98. 150 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MARIAN ANDERSON: THE STORY OF THE VOICE THAT BROKE BARRIERS. &LR; 
The contralto reminisces about a career that caught fire on the
Town Hall stage in December 1935 and helped open the way for black
performers, particularly in the South. Clips span 30 years of
concert appearances, and those interviewed include Isaac Stern and
Jessye Norman. 1998. Kultur. $19.95. 60 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UMM THULUM: A VOICE LIKE EGYPT and NASSER 56. &LR;  Two videos share
origins and themes. Michal Goldman's documentary ``Umm Thulum'' is
the story of the Egyptian singer who helped galvanize resistance
against British occupation and overthrow the monarchy in 1953 (four
million people attended her funeral in Cairo in 1975). 1996.
Vanguard. $39.98. 67 minutes. English and Arabic with English
subtitles.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Nasser 56,'' Mohamed Fadel combines documentary and
dramatized elements to recreate Gamal Abdel Nasser's
nationalization of the Suez Canal. 1996. Vanguard. $39.98. 140
minutes. Arabic with English subtitles. Release date: Tuesday.
Information: (800) 218-7888.
</P>
</TEXT>
