<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-IMPEACH (Washington) _ The lawyers for the Democrats and
Republicans on the House Judiciary Committee make their cases on
impeachment, while House Speaker Newt Gingrich notifies the full
House to prepare for a vote next week. By JOHN C. HENRY.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-VIDEO (Washington) _ The House Judiciary Committee is
treated to a multimedia show as lawyers for the Republican majority
and the Democratic minority play dueling videos featuring
previously undisclosed segments of President Clinton's Jan. 17
deposition in the Paula Jones sexual harassment lawsuit. By MARK
HELM.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-DEFENSE (Washington) _ The White House considers a new
line of defense in the impeachment struggle with the Republican
Congress, weighing an address to the nation and personal telephone
appeals to GOP House moderates. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   GOP-MODERATES-NY (Washington) _ Five of the crucial undecided
House Republican moderates on impeachment are from upstate New
York. We look at their views and why they're waiting until the last
minute to decide President Clinton's fate. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   CHINESE-SMUGGLING (Washington) _ The Immigration and
Naturalization Service announces the breakup of the largest
immigrant-smuggling operation on the northern border. Thirty-five
people have been arrested for smuggling Chinese nationals through
Canada to New York. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CANADIAN-DEATHROW (Huntsville, Texas) _ The 5th Circuit Court of
Appeals in New Orleans lifts a stay of the execution of Joseph
Stanley Faulder, clearing the way for the Canadian national to be
put to death by lethal injection for killing an elderly woman in
1975. By KATHY WALT and ALLAN TURNER.
</P>
<P>
   FLOOD-FOOTBALL (Cuero, Texas) _ 1998 will be remembered as the
year of the Great Flood, when a third of this town was inundated
and hundreds of people were left homeless. But depending on what
happens Saturday at the Houston Astrodome, a minor footnote may be
added: it's also the year when the 11-3 Fighting Gobblers of Cuero
take on the Aledo Bearcats for the Class 3A Division I crown in a
state where high school football is serious business. By JOHN
MacCORMACK.
</P>
<P>
   SHUTTLE-STATION (Houston) _ Another milestone in the
construction of the international space station is reached as the
crew members from shuttle Endeavour enter the station. The crew
will connect power lines and prepare the first two modules for
longer-term residents, who start arriving next year. By MARK
CARREAU.
</P>
<P>
   LOUISIANA-PRISONER (Baton Rouge, La.) _ Convicted murderer
Wilbert Rideau, editor of a prison magazine and sometimes referred
to as ``the most rehabilitated prisoner in America,'' is getting a
shot at freedom before a federal judge. U.S. District Judge Frank
Polozola hears arguments on whether he should accept the
recommendation of a U.S. magistrate that Rideau be re-tried or
freed. By KIM COBB.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., who
was defeated for re-election last month, is no fan of President
Clinton. And his fellow Republicans should heed his warning that
House impeachment of Clinton would be a self-defeating, ``grave
mistake'' for the GOP. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GLF-PRESIDENTS (Melbourne, Australia) _ Coverage of the opening
day of competition in the Presidents Cup golf event. By EDDIE
SEFKO.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-REYNOLDS (Houston) _ The Houston Astros call a news
conference to announce that they have agreed to a contract
extension with 19-game winner Shane Reynolds, who would have been
entering the final year of his deal. By JOSEPH DUARTE.
</P>
