<HEADER>
A3305 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-RIGHTS11-COX     12-10 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-RIGHTS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JOHN LEWIS, 3 OTHERS HONORED AS HEROES OF HUMAN RIGHTS
 &HT;    330&AMP;add.
 &HT;    Cox photos for this story will be placed in the National folder
on the Cox server.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Casting the American civil rights movement as part
of a broader global struggle for human rights, President Clinton
honored Rep. John Lewis on Thursday for his lifetime fight against
racial segregation.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, D-Ga., was one of four Americans to receive the inaugural
Eleanor Roosevelt Award for Human Rights. Clinton authorized the
awards to mark the 50th anniversary of the Universal Declaration of
Human Rights, which the United Nations adopted in 1948, largely at
Mrs. Roosevelt's urging.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, 58, was cited for ''uncompromising heroism in the face of
bigotry'' during an activist career that has spanned four decades.
</P>
<P>
   ''From Freedom Rides to the House of Representatives, he has
educated and mobilized generations of Americans in the crusade
against injustice,'' read Lewis's award citation. ''He often did so
at great personal risk, yet he never deviated from his commitment
to peaceful change through nonviolent means.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis suffered repeated beatings that resulted in enduring
injuries and was arrested more than 40 times during the 1960s, the
height of a national confrontation between civil rights activists
and authorities enforcing segregationist policies.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was deeply touched and I was pleased to see the connection
between civil rights and human rights,'' Lewis said after receiving
his award. ''That's what our whole civil rights movement was all
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Also receiving human rights awards from Clinton and First Lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton were:
</P>
<P>
   _ Robert Bernstein, regarded as the father of the New York-based
investigative and advocacy group Human Rights Watch, based in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bette Bao Lord, a novelist and current chairman of Freedom
House, another New York-based human rights group.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dorothy Thomas, also of Human Rights Watch, an advocate of
women's rights around the world.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks, Clinton cited the story behind the title to
Lewis's autobiography, ''Walking With the Wind,'' a tale of how
Lewis, as a small child, and several other youngsters held hands
and walked from one corner of a wooden frame home to the next
during a storm, using the weight of their bodies to keep the wind
from blowing over the fragile structure.
</P>
<P>
   ''That has become a metaphor for his life,'' said Clinton, who
went on to use the tale to symbolize the global quest to end
torture, murder and other forms of mistreatment, as embodied in the
Universal Declaration of Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
   ''By walking with the wind, hand in hand, they saved the house
and the family and the children,'' Clinton said. ''John says that
that walk is a struggle to find the beloved community. The
Universal Declaration of Human Rights applies to individuals, but
it can only be achieved by our common community.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, wearing a dark blue suit and seated on the dais near the
Clintons in a small auditorium in the Old Executive Office
Building, was far from the violence and the social turbulence of
the civil rights struggle.
</P>
<P>
   Images, however, swirled near his heart.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just had a flashback to the sit-ins, the Freedom Rides, the
whole struggle,'' Lewis said after receiving the award. ''We still
have such a long distance to go.''
</P>
<P>
   He praised Clinton, saying, ''I think the president has a deep
understanding of the significance of the struggle for people to
come together to create a beloved world where we can forget about
race and color and sex and nationality and just see people as human
beings.''
</P>
<P>
   One man inspired by Lewis was Wade Henderson, director of the
Leadership Conference on Civil Rights, a Washington coalition of
national groups concerned with civil rights and social welfare
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ''Congressman Lewis is an icon for all Americans,'' said
Henderson, who came up to congratulate Lewis after he received his
award. ''He is a living symbol of the importance of perseverance
and commitment to purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
