<SLUG> BC-FBN-MOBILE-QUARTERBACKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOBILE QUARTERBACKS ARE MORE IN DEMAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JEFFRI CHADIHA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The sight has never been one to excite a
defender. For the most part, it's one of the worst situations to
face.
</P>
<P>
   A nimble quarterback drops back, finding his receivers covered
and his options limited. He steps up in the pocket, maybe shuffles
a bit to his right or left, then escapes with all hell breaking
loose in his wake.
</P>
<P>
   Massive linemen lumber after the guy. Linebackers question
whether to stay put or leave their pass defense zones in order to
smack a moving target. The defensive backs chase receivers, who can
break in any direction to find some open space. On the sidelines,
coaches utter profanities that would rival Richard Pryor on his
best days.
</P>
<P>
   No defender is happy, to say the least. At such a moment, one
certainly would opt for the time when most quarterbacks were
considered adequate if they were big, strong-armed and slow. But
the face of the pro quarterback is undergoing a subtle makeover,
with more scrambling models appearing in the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that the consummate drop-back passer is dead. He just
needs to be able to scoot every now and then.
</P>
<P>
   The latest phenomenon is Buffalo's Doug Flutie. Before him there
were Kordell Stewart, Mark Brunell, Brett Favre, Steve Young,
Randall Cunningham and John Elway. After him, there will be Jake
Plummer, Charlie Batch and countless others. They come in all
shapes and sizes, with varied levels of success. But most
importantly, they come with wheels.
</P>
<P>
   Now, anybody in an NFL player personnel position will tell you
how valued mobility and improvisational skills are in a pro
quarterback. They also will suggest this is nothing new. After all,
Roger Staubach and Fran Tarkenton made more than a few defenders
look silly in their day. What can't be denied, though, is how vital
elusiveness has become to a signal-caller's credentials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what created my opportunity was Steve Young, Randall
Cunningham and Brett Favre having their success, making things
happen,'' Flutie said. ``It's starting to be looked at as an asset
when a guy can make plays on his own. That mode of thinking has
changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Flutie knows the old knock on athletic quarterbacks _
that some are too eager to bolt the pocket at the first hint of
danger. But the bottom line is whether a man is a playmaker.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, athleticism maximizes a quarterback's chances of
avoiding a long-term relationship with the medical staff. More than
half of this year's starting quarterbacks have missed a game due to
injury, primarily because defenses are filled with imposing
athletic specimens unleashed from such a multitude of angles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The changes in defenses have made it harder to protect the
quarterback,'' said Steve Young of the San Francisco 49ers. ``The
thing is, if you can't make the first guy miss when you drop back,
and I mean the first defender who comes free, you're going to have
a tough time in the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   The age of free agency has made the dearth of playmakers even
more glaring. Fewer offenses stay together today, making it more
difficult to maintain cohesiveness on that side of the ball. You
just can't have Montana-to-Rice going on for half a decade anymore.
Without that advantage, teams need someone who can produce when
disaster strikes, or at least sense when it's on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   This year's college stock, the deepest at quarterback since
1983, includes some players with the potential to do so. Excluding
Kentucky's Tim Couch and Washington's Brock Huard, that list of
mobile players includes Central Florida's Daunte Culpepper,
Syracuse's Donovan McNabb, Oregon's Akili Smith, Kansas State's
Michael Bishop and Cade McNown of the University of California at
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some guys who can run and move around,'' said Ken
Herock, the Oakland Raiders' director of player personnel. ``But I
don't think anybody knows how good these guys are. There will
always be some failures in every crop. The tough thing is figuring
out who's not going to be a failure.''
</P>
<P>
   That has always been the catch, and given the record for NFL
teams of late, their gauge for determining success at quarterback
is somewhat flawed. There are enough bad quarterbacks. There are
enough aging ones. Now it's time to prepare for the future. Because
there are sure to be plenty more elusive ones.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
