<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RAIDERS-QB-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAIDERS' WILSON TO START AGAINST THE BILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SAMUEL CHI  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALAMEDA, Calif. _ Doug Flutie may be old, but he's not older
than Wade Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   The Oakland Raiders will have the senior starting quarterback
when they play the Bills on Sunday in Buffalo. With their playoff
lives at stake, the Raiders have decided that Wilson, 39, will give
them their best chance.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Hollas, who has been the Raiders' de facto starting
quarterback since Jeff George went down with a groin injury on Oct.
4 against Arizona, has a banged-up left wrist. That and his
ineffective performance against Miami Sunday were enough for
Raiders coach Jon Gruden to make the switch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wade Wilson is a veteran quarterback,'' Gruden said. ``He's
healthy, he's experienced. He's a good athlete, with solid
mobility. He could make all the throws. And he's a system player
and he's a good leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's experience plays no small part in Gruden's decision.
Unlike Hollas, who's started only two games in his NFL career
before this season, Wilson is an 18-year veteran and a former Pro
Bowl selection. He took the Minnesota Vikings to three playoff
appearances and was with the Dallas Cowboys when they won the Super
Bowl in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm fresh _ I haven't played that much since last year,''
Wilson said. ``I'm hoping (my experience) will help. It's a big
game. The crowd noise and the elements will make it difficult. I
hope to use the experience to handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson took all of the snaps in practice Wednesday and is
expected to get most of them again Thursday. Hollas, who sat out of
practice Wednesday, will be Wilson's backup in Sunday's game if his
wrist recovers in time. If not, Pat Barnes might be named as the
No. 2 quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Donald is resilient enough to come back,'' Gruden said. ``He
will come back. He's not relinquishing his job. A lot of it has to
do with his injury and (lack of) preparation because of it. It's
the logical thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders are probably more concerned about Hollas' state of
mind than the state of his wrist following his six-interception
performance Sunday. Hollas, though, said he had forgotten all about
the Miami game already.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went home and got my calendar and cut out the date Dec. 6,''
Hollas said in jest. ``It never happened. So I don't even know what
you're talking about. It's like selective amnesia, you just put it
out of your mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollas had an exam on Monday for his injured wrist and it
revealed no serious damage. While the injury won't hamper his
ability to throw, it poses a problem for him to take center snaps
and handoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hurt it on the play right before I got yanked,'' Hollas
said. ``I really didn't think of it at the time and after the game.
But I went home and by the next morning it was really swollen.
Nothing's broken, but unfortunately we didn't arrest (the swelling)
in time.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollas, with 10 touchdowns and 16 interceptions, saw his
quarterback rating plummet to 59.7, the worst of any quarterback
still starting in the NFL. Hollas is 4-2 as a starter this season
and 1-2 in relief of George.
</P>
<P>
   Hollas' injury prompted the Raiders to look at Wilson, who had
been the team's No. 3 quarterback since signing in the offseason.
He wasn't given the opportunity to compete for the backup
quarterback job in training camp and served mostly as insurance
policy. Wilson last started a game in 1996, when he was with the
Dallas Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson has appeared in only two games this season, both in
relief of Hollas. In the Oct. 11 game against San Diego, he
replaced the ineffective Hollas late in the fourth quarter and
threw a 68-yard touchdown pass to James Jett with a minute
remaining to lift the Raiders to a 7-6 victory. Last week, he was
8-for-12 for 75 yards, with a 2-yard TD pass to Tim Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson knows Sunday's game is the most important of the Raiders'
season. A win will keep the Raiders in the playoff hunt. A loss
could mathematically eliminate them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a sense of urgency,'' Wilson said. ``If we lose,
there's a possibility that we could be done. What I have to do is
be consistent, not to make big mistakes that hurt the team. We
can't lose the turnover battle.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
