<SLUG> BC-WHITEHORSEINN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISTORY IS THE FIRST COURSE AT THE WHITE HORSE TAVERN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN BAUMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWPORT, R.I. _ For centuries, New England innkeepers have lured
tourists with the promise of rest in a bed where George Washington
once slept. The father of our country, it would seem, slept in lots
of places.
</P>
<P>
   But at Newport's White Horse Tavern, it's possible to gulp a
beer where Washington himself _ plus Paul Revere and Benedict
Arnold _ used to belly up to the bar for a tot of ale.
</P>
<P>
   The tavern acquired a liquor license in 1687 and hasn't stopped
serving since, making it one of the oldest food-and-beverage
establishments in the original 13 colonies _ plus 37. Although the
original, wide-beamed floorboards have long since been replaced,
careful stewardship has retained an authentic Colonial atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   That has been the goal of the current owners, who have a strong
North Texas heritage.
</P>
<P>
   The tavern ``goes back to the early days of colonial times,''
said O.L. Pitts, an 82-year-old Fort Worth resident who, with
several other friends, acquired the White Horse in 1981. ``There's
nothing like it. At night, having dinner by candlelight and a light
snow falling outside the window ...''
</P>
<P>
   The purchase was prompted by a 1980 conversation between Lee
Smith of Fort Worth and cable TV mogul and sailing enthusiast Ted
Turner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ted said the White Horse Tavern was taking Chapter 11, and we
couldn't let it go under,'' Smith said. ``He said, `You guys need
to buy it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Smith and Turner were in Newport for the America's Cup sailing
competition. It took 10 minutes to decide to make the purchase,
Pitts said, and a year to close the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Melissa J. Rogers, also of Fort Worth, has joined
the White Horse ownership. Working together, the North Texas troika
has kept the tavern's doors open _ and then some.
</P>
<P>
   Modern-day revelers enjoy White Horse hospitality just as much
as the Man on Mount Rushmore once did. Newport Life magazine named
the White Horse its area's ``most romantic restaurant''; it has
also been cited for excellence by the ``New England Travel Guide,''
The Wine Spectator, Yankee Magazine, and, most recently, by Rhode
Island Monthly, whose readers found the White Horse a premium site
for romantic dining.
</P>
<P>
   It's no wonder. Walking through the White Horse doors is like
stepping back in time, if food servers of old wore tuxedos.
</P>
<P>
   Fireplaces host welcoming blazes; rough wooden floors and other
rustic amenities are more 17th-century than 20th. Even the
plastered walls are textured with horsehair. The only telltale sign
of the Fort Worth owners is a Fort Worth Boat Club pennant hanging
in the bar.
</P>
<P>
   If the look of the White Horse is vintage, the libations and
food are modern. Although it calls itself a tavern, the White Horse
has evolved into an eating establishment offering reasonably priced
lunches and dinners. A New England lobster salad is $14; a ragout
of shrimp and scallops is $18.
</P>
<P>
   But the past is never forgotten. A ghost supposedly lurks in the
dark corners.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't change anything about it under the conditions we
bought. It has to stay as it is, as it was,'' Pitts said.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The White Horse Tavern accepts reservations, but not men without
jackets.
</P>
<P>
   The tavern is at 26 Malborough St. in Newport, R.I.; call (401)
849-3600 for more information, or E-mail whitehorsetavern.com.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
