<SLUG> BC-FILM-STARTREK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE'S RICARDO MONTALBAN WHEN YOU REALLY NEED HIM?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Because one of the pleasures of ``Star Trek'' movies is the way
they reveal their mysteries layer by layer, it's best to take a
minimalist approach when writing about them. So here's a bare-bones
plot summary of ``Star Trek: Insurrection:''
</P>
<P>
   The Ba'ku, a peaceful tribe that shuns technology (sort of like
futuristic Amish), is living a quiet existence on an Eden-like
planet. The Son'a, an alien race that looks like
pantyhose-mask-wearing robbers crossed with shar peis, wants
something the Ba'ku have, and are willing to use force to get it.
The Enterprise intervenes. Action ensues.
</P>
<P>
   Here's one surprise, though, and it's a little unpleasant to
report: After 1996's lively and entertaining ``First Contact,''
also directed by series star Jonathan Frakes, ``Insurrection''
comes off as flat and uninspired. It's not bad, really, but it
looks like an expanded episode of the ``Next Generation'' TV show,
where ``First Contact'' and 1994's ``Generations'' looked like
feature movies, even if ``Generations'' was a little leaden with
Capt. Kirk hero-worship.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to put a finger on what's wrong; the writing is as
literate as ever _ despite a brief, misguided detour into hoary
cliche _ and although no one will ever confuse Frakes with Martin
Scorsese, he's a competent enough director. It may be that the
movie is just too democratic. The previous ``TNG'' movies focused
on one or two crew members, with everyone else relegated to the
background, but ``Insurrection'' gives everyone but poor Dr.
Crusher a mini-subplot. Even Marina Sirtis' Deanna Troi gets one,
after two movies of nothing but doe-eyed reactions to other crew
members' actions.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's an effort at reviving an ensemble feel, the upshot
of all this story-spreading is that it leaves everyone's little
plot underdeveloped and/or unresolved. The movie could have had a
lot more fun, for instance, with the story it gives the Klingon
Worf (Michael Dorn), but instead it lets it peter out, as if
screenwriter Michael Piller forgot it was there.
</P>
<P>
   Also curious is F. Murray Abraham's performance as the lead
Son'a. He's not over-the-top enough. It's as if wearing all those
pounds of makeup took something out of him; he's not so much
maniacal as he is cranky. This robs his inevitable showdown with
Capt. Picard (Patrick Stewart) of much of its payoff; where's some
good scenery-chewing when you need it?
</P>
<P>
   On the plus side, the movie does have some cool effects _
although it's a little too obviously filmed on the planet Sierra
Nevada _ and the script keeps a light touch, with some
laugh-out-loud lines when you least expect them. But the action
scenes are a bit anemic, and there's often too much talk between
them. It may be best to be minimal when describing the plot, but
that doesn't mean the movie should be minimal as it lets the story
unfold.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Star Trek: Insurrection''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Jonathan Frakes
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Patrick Stewart, F. Murray Abraham, Donna Murphy
</P>
<P>
   Length: 99 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG _ TV-level violence
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a film critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
