A3348 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-ASIMPLEPLAN-TEX     12-10 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-ASIMPLEPLAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TOO-SIMPLE PLAN FOR A MOVIE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Director Sam Raimi's high-octane style _ twitchy, hyperkinetic
camera movement _ sounds like an exciting way to crank the rust out
of a film adaptation of ``A Simple Plan.'' Scott B. Smith wrote a
somber genre piece based on the Dostoevskian line that there is no
clean money. Three men find over $4 million in a small aircraft
that crashed in the snowbound woods near their hometown, and the
money divides them.
</P>
<P>
   It's ``The Treasure of the Sierra Madre'' with a wind chill
factor. I expected a surge of addled camera adrenaline, to loosen
the self-consciousness of the material, from Raimi, whose ``Evil
Dead'' trilogy brought parodistic glee to the horror genre.
Instead, Raimi has settled down into what could be called his first
adult movie. It's wintry and grown-up in a way that seems like an
apology for all the pleasure he has given.
</P>
<P>
   Hank (Bill Paxton), the closest thing to a moral center in
``Plan,'' wants to turn the money in, initially. ``Maybe there's a
reward,'' he says, mildly anxious, a line that's sure to get a
laugh. Lou (Brent Briscoe), who's been out of work for a while, is
already figuring out what he'll do with the dough. Jacob (Billy Bob
Thornton), Hank's brother, is a wasted innocent who'll point in
whichever direction causes the least amount of friction. After they
convince themselves that the loot is drug money, they decide to
keep it, hiding it away ``until the spring,'' Hank says. Then,
they'll split it up and go their separate ways.
</P>
<P>
   As played, Paxton's Hank sets the tone. It's as if he's
suffering from lower-back discomfort _ he's miserable before the
picture gets started. His resolute glumness is reflected in the way
Raimi directs. There's not much here but the inevitable weight of
greed driving these men apart, and some vitality might have
distracted us from the eventuality. These guys seem to be friends
only because there aren't many people in the town, or the movie for
that matter. You just wait for Lou's wild hair to cause trouble;
he's the kind of lout who's almost as much trouble sober as he is
drunk, and he ain't sober too often. Thornton has shaped Jacob into
the most intriguing character in the movie, even though he's
inconsistently drawn. He's a dim martyr, the center of attention.
But Thornton's resigned and out-of-it, and his deliberate
showoffiness works. You do pay attention to him, and you long for
Jacob when he's not on screen.
</P>
<P>
   The bright, snowy expanses offer some relief from the glumness.
And Bridget Fonda, as Hank's wife, has a sudden twist of conscience
that's funny. But all that's missing is one of the characters
getting a gleam in his eye and cackling about the cash. As ``A
Simple Plan'' grinds to its conclusion, several diverting moments
arise. But you may find yourself thinking it's a little too simple.
Raimi picked the wrong occasion to show that he doesn't have to
upstage his material.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``A Simple Plan''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Sam Raimi
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Bill Paxton, Billy Bob Thornton, Bridget Fonda
</P>
<P>
   Length: 121 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ violence and adult language
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
