<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-FOOD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME FEAR THAT MILLENNIUM BUG COULD PUT THE BITE ON FOOD SUPPLIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WORTH WREN JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the millennium bug has you in a tizzy about your computers,
bank accounts and utilities, there's one more thing you might start
sweating: your food supply.
</P>
<P>
   Let's be clear up front: Most experts say you have nothing to
fear.
</P>
<P>
   But that hasn't stopped some folks from starting to stock up,
say those who sell survival supplies. Even traditional grocers and
grain executives have fielded calls from fretful consumers.
</P>
<P>
   For many, the fear centers on the computer glitch predicted to
explode when 2000 hits. Older computers that designate years with
two digits won't know whether it's 2000 or 1900. Technological
doomsayers have suggested that the so-called Y2K bug could
interrupt the flow of foods and water, electricity, money and
information.
</P>
<P>
   Other people have less specific concerns tied to the turn of the
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the motivation, many businesses are starting to report
runs on items such as toilet paper, canned and dehydrated foods,
kerosene stoves and survival books.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even ammo and gun sales are rising on those worries,'' said
Mark Abbott, a technical adviser at Cheaper Than Dirt!, a
sporting/survival goods supplier and gun dealer in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   While technology experts say the Y2K bug may affect some
dealings that depend on computers, most grocers say the food supply
will not be hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's panic over nothing,'' said Larry Sadlowski, president of
the Winn-Dixie Texas division, which is based in Fort Worth. ``I
don't think we'll even notice it.''
</P>
<P>
   Like other major grocery chains and suppliers, Sadlowski said,
Winn-Dixie Stores is upgrading its computer systems. Winn-Dixie's
systems will be 2000-compliant by early next year, and ``we're not
alone,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   There probably will be some glitches in the food distribution
chain, Sadlowski said, but nothing on a scale to cause food
shortages.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, what Sadlowski fears most are efforts by untrained
consumers to store large supplies of grains or uncanned food.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've already got rats pestering many of the neighborhoods,''
Sadlowski said. ``If you store wheat in the basement or the garage,
those rats or mice are going to think they've hit the food lotto.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the case, Y2K has turned into a business opportunity
for some entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   The Fort Worth-based Texas Grain &AMP; Feed Association reports it
is receiving two to four weekly telephone calls and e-mail queries
for sources of ``survival grains.'' That compares with a typical
one or two per year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always a market for people's fears,'' said Ben
Boerner, the association's president.
</P>
<P>
   At Cheaper Than Dirt!, orders for ready-to-eat meals _
comparable to military field rations that can be stored without
refrigeration _ are approaching 5,800 cases (at 12 meals per case)
per month, up from about 500 in November last year.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K demand also has spilled over into solar-powered lights,
military-surplus wool blankets and sleeping bags.
</P>
<P>
   Demand for survival items such as ready-to-eat meals generally
rises in the fall and winter as customers prepare for hunting trips
and weather emergencies in the northern United States.
</P>
<P>
   But Darrell Kidd, a buyer for Cheaper Than Dirt!, credits Y2K
concerns for most of the rising demand for the ready-to-eat meals.
</P>
<P>
   One customer, a Miami doctor, recently bought $10,000 in silver
coins and 48 cases of ready-to-eat meals. The same customer loaded
up on gun ammo to be used if law and order breaks down. The coins,
presumably, could substitute for cash if chaos occurs.
</P>
<P>
   Walton Feed, the 50-year-old dean among U.S. retailers of
dehydrated and other long-term storage foods and equipment, says
many shipments are five to 12 months behind schedule. Walton is
based in Montpelier, Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   In Stephenville, Texas, career social worker Barbara Gaume has
formed Millennial Basics. Its offering, which it hopes to bring to
market by January: food-grade whole wheat in extra-tough plastic
bags.
</P>
<P>
   A case of six airtight, 6-pound bags will cost $25 plus
shipping, which could run almost as much as the case. Gaume figures
she will have no trouble selling all 22,000 pounds of bulk wheat
she bought.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not a doom-and-gloom type of person,'' said Gaume, whose
full-time job is executive director of the Star Council on
Substance Abuse. But she advocates these precautions: ``Store what
you will use and use what you store.''
</P>
<P>
   Morrison Milling in Denton, Texas, said it receives up to six or
seven phone calls a day from people, including homemakers and
corporate executives, who want to buy and store bulk wheat or corn
or purchase grinders for the grains, said Fred Bursey Jr., the
flour miller's vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suggest, `Buy a big sack of flour or several small sacks and
put 'em in the freezer,''' Bursey said.
</P>
<P>
   Former Dallas policeman Greg Bowen, who started Millennium
Resources of Texas about a year ago in the East Texas city of
Mineola, said his monthly sales rose about 30 percent in the past
three months on assorted nitrogen-packed whole grains, dried beans,
peas, dehydrated milk and soup mixes, grain grinders, water
purifiers and other emergency items.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
