A3364 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES1     12-10 0275
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHORT TAKES: A brief history of weatherphobia
 &HT;    By Arnold Rosenfeld
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The weather turned a bit snappier and more appropriate
the other day. We had a few rain showers. People seemed happier.
They had mostly been griping about all the nice weather we were
having. There was a small thrill of fear in their griping. Then,
finally, nice, normal, gray, dark clouds. Aren't they great?
</P>
<P>
   We all probably have a gene somewhere that remembers the ice age
and the great glaciers. Weather, like its big sister Nature, makes
us feel smaller and less in control. There is considerable evidence
supporting that view.
</P>
<P>
   There is now a body of evidence _ enough to convince even a
House Republican _ that all this strange weather is our fault. As
they say in the old sci-fi films, ``Man was not meant to tamper
with the unknown.'' And we have done it. The quite resilient
natural air and water that sustains life may have suffered a
critical insult.
</P>
<P>
   So, suddenly, we have summer in the fall, and the trees and the
animals seem confused, put out buds, go to sleep at the wrong time.
We have started noticing. We look around and discover it's a nice
day, when the part of us that is still connected with Nature tells
us we should be covered with snow and have icicles on the tips of
our noses.
</P>
<P>
   Nice day, we say to our neighbors on those rare occasions we see
them. Isn't it awful?
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rosenfeld is editor-in-chief of the Cox Newspapers.
E-mail: arnold.rosenfeld(at)cox.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
