<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3373 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATHEY-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     12-10 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATHEY-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
``HALLELUJAH! RON ATHEY: A STORY OF DELIVERANCE': BLOOD AND
RAPTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Body artist, extreme masochist, HIV-positive gay man, heavily
tattooed freak, former heroin addict, onetime grant recipient from
the National Endowment for the Arts and thorn in its side (after a
1994 performance at the Walker Center drew complaints), Ron Athey
has turned his life into the most radical kind of performance art.
</P>
<P>
   In his collaborations with a traveling troupe of self-described
outcasts, Athey swirls his experiences into mock-Christian rituals.
In one he is ecstatically tormented with a crown of thorns
consisting of hypodermic needles that spill blood across his face
as they are inserted into the skull. At the moment of insertion,
Athey, his eyes rolling heavenward, wears an expression of
rapturous calm.
</P>
<P>
   The crowning is only one of several blood-letting scenes in
Catherine Gund Saalfield's documentary portrait ``Hallelujah! Ron
Athey: A Story of Deliverance,'' which opens today at Cinema
Village. This is a movie that is definitely not for the squeamish
or the sexually prudish. In addition to the blood-smearing, the
film offers a methodical catalog of advanced sexual kinkiness, with
scenes of piercing, bondage, branding, flogging, enemas and dildos.
</P>
<P>
   As Athey tells it in a disarmingly boyish manner, he was born an
extremist, having been raised by a Pentecostal grandmother to be a
prophet. Anyone who is brought up in such an extremely devout
environment is probably bound to have a hyperdeveloped sense of
good and evil, of Jesus and the devil locked in perpetual combat.
When Athey flashes a sly grin and widens his blue eyes, you have
the sense of a performer taking pleasure in being the naughtiest
little boy in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Athey's performance art is admittedly a desperate act. As an
HIV-positive man, he insists he wants to make the most creative use
of whatever time he has left. And his performances take body art
about as far you can go, short of suicide and actual dismemberment.
The most disturbing excerpt from his work shown in the film is a
section from ``Martyrs and Saints,'' in which impassive white-robed
``doctors and nurses'' brutally parody invasive medical procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Athey lacks the wit of the late Bob Flanagan, whose masochistic
demonstrations were the subject of last year's memorable
documentary film ``Sick,'' a much more intimate exploration of
similar material, minus the religious iconography.
</P>
<P>
   Are Athey's performances art or psychodrama? They're both, of
course. Sacred or profane? Again, both. With their emphasis on
visceral and spiritual extremes, they're also blatantly obvious
attempts to shock.
</P>
<P>
   The most revealing statement Athey makes is an offhanded
voice-over comment heard at the very end of the film. ``Which came
first, the evangelist tent or the circus tent?'' he muses.
``Sometimes there isn't any difference.''
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `HALLELUJAH! Ron Athey: A Story of Deliverance'
</P>
<P>
   Produced and directed by Catherine Gund Saalfield; director of
photography, Ms. Saalfield; released by Artistic License Films. At
the Cinema Village, 22 E. 12th St., Greenwich Village. Running
time: 90 minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   With: Ron Athey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-98 1642EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981210.0252 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 16:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3376 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIEGUIDES-TEX     12-10 1145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIEGUIDES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CAPSULE REVIEW OF THE NEW MOVIE-AND-VIDEO GUIDES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the perfect holiday gift for a movie lover: a
movie-and-video guide. Several are on the stands, and each has
something to recommend it. We've done a quick study in an attempt
to sort them out for you. Although their ratings systems differ,
our ratings are on a scale of one to five stars.
</P>
<P>
   Blockbuster Entertainment Guide to Movies and Videos 1999, six
editors credited (Island Books, $7.99)
</P>
<P>
   Number of entries: More than 23,000, including individual
reviews of TV episodes (you should see the ``Star Trek'' section).
</P>
<P>
   Rating system: One to five stars.
</P>
<P>
   Most recent title: ``Spice World,'' released Jan. 23.
</P>
<P>
   The good stuff: Reviews that are less mainstream than you might
expect; neither ``The English Patient'' nor ``Titanic'' merits even
four stars. Reviews include genre categories that don't always jibe
with what you'll find on the video stores' shelves.
</P>
<P>
   The bad stuff: Although some folks will be glad to see that the
guide doesn't list X or NC-17-rated movies, it seems to pick and
choose: the NC-17 ``Bad Lieutenant'' (unrated here) is included,
but the controversial ``Kids'' isn't.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Halliwell's Film &AMP; Video Guide 1999, edited by John Walker
(Harper Perennial, $22.50)
</P>
<P>
   Number of entries: More than 23,000, almost all theatrical
releases.
</P>
<P>
   Rating system: Zero to four stars.
</P>
<P>
   Most recent title: ``Godzilla,'' released May 20.
</P>
<P>
   The good stuff: This thing's a monster, but if you've got the
patience, it has some fun things: trivia bits, outtakes from other
critics' reviews, cast lists that italicize the names of actors who
made impressive contributions.
</P>
<P>
   The bad stuff: Man, is that rating system confusing. Indexes to
three- and four-star films help. The entries are so cumbersome, you
practically need a map; fortunately, a guide is printed on the
inside front cover.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 1/2
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Maltin's 1999 Movie &AMP; Video Guide (Signet Reference,
$7.99)
</P>
<P>
   Number of entries: More than 19,000, including made-for-TV
movies but not TV series episodes or miniseries.
</P>
<P>
   Rating system: BOMB to four stars.
</P>
<P>
   Most recent title: ``Six Days, Seven Nights,'' released June 12.
</P>
<P>
   The good stuff: Almost indispensable. Few movie-reference books
are as timely as Maltin's (it often covers films still in
theaters). Maltin has been accused of being too middlebrow, but he
can be contrary (he dismisses the highly regarded ``Taxi Driver,''
among others). The book's largely easy-to-follow format helps call
attention to quality foreign films, sleepers and movies of
historical importance. BOMB reviews are often laugh-out-loud funny.
</P>
<P>
   The bad stuff: The literal alphabetization technique can be
confusing. ``Star Trek: First Contact _ the most recent ``Trek''
film before today's ``Insurrection'' _ is the first listed among
the eight ``Trek'' entries. The selective actor and director
filmographies seem arbitrary.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 4
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Roger Ebert's Movie Yearbook 1999 (Andrews McMeel Publishing,
$16.95)
</P>
<P>
   Number of entries: About 630.
</P>
<P>
   Rating system: Zero to four stars.
</P>
<P>
   Most recent title: ``Armageddon,'' released July 1.
</P>
<P>
   The good stuff: Ebert's guide, the only annual with full-length
reviews, includes everything the Chicago Sun-Times critic has
written from Jan. 1, 1996, to June 30, 1998. Few reviewers have a
more relaxed style. The book's appendixes _ Ebert's 1997 top-10
list, his informative and clever ``Questions for the Movie Answer
Man'' feature _ are unbeatable.
</P>
<P>
   The bad stuff: Sometimes, Ebert's reviews seem to be as much
about him as the movie, and he can still be a soft grader. Previous
Ebert books have included info on how to order hard-to-find videos;
that's missing here. Obviously, there are fewer reviews than in
other guides.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 1/2
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Time Out Film Guide, edited by John Pym (Penguin Books, $22.95)
</P>
<P>
   Number of entries: More than 12,000.
</P>
<P>
   Rating system: None.
</P>
<P>
   Most recent title: ``The Truman Show'' (June 5) is the most
recent significant U.S. release.
</P>
<P>
   The good stuff: This compilation from British film magazine
``Time Out'' is the capsule-review book for the film-snob crowd,
although it's not above praising the first ``Speed.'' It includes a
top-100 readers' poll (''The Godfather'' is No. 1), a thoughtful if
somewhat smug foreword, and an index that's practically insane with
categories (''Attila the Hun, film about'').
</P>
<P>
   The bad stuff: It brags that it covers more offbeat fare _ and
doesn't give you one clue how to go about finding it. Many people
will find its stuffily superior attitude unnecessarily snotty. Most
weekend renters would be better off with other guides.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Video Movie Guide 1999, edited by Mick Martin &AMP; Marsha Porter
(Ballantine Publishing Group, $19.95)
</P>
<P>
   Number of entries: More than 17,000.
</P>
<P>
   Rating system: ``Turkey'' (a silhouette) to five stars.
</P>
<P>
   Most recent title: ``Out of Sight,'' released June 26.
</P>
<P>
   The good stuff: The only one of these guides to list only titles
available on video, excluding brand-new releases. New reviews are
marked with a bullet (), making them easy to find. Probably the
only book brave enough to give three stars to the infamous ``Plan 9
From Outer Space,'' because the movie's so bad that it's
entertaining; the ``turkey'' rating is reserved for stuff that's
absolutely worthless.
</P>
<P>
   The bad stuff: The reviews aren't very in-depth, even by the
necessarily shallow standards of capsule reviewing. There seem to
be four- and five-star reviews on every page.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 1/2
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   VideoHound's Golden Movie Retriever 1999, edited by Martin
Connors and Jim Craddock (Visible Ink, $21.95)
</P>
<P>
   Number of entries: More than 23,000.
</P>
<P>
   Rating system: Woof! to four bones.
</P>
<P>
   Most recent title: ``The Negotiator,'' released July 29
(synopsis only); ``Six Days, Seven Nights'' is the most recent
review.
</P>
<P>
   The good stuff: This flagship book in the VideoHound series
belongs on any VCR owner's shelf. The editors have a fun, cheeky
attitude (''Citizen Kane'' is there, but so is the Tom Hanks
slob-comedy ``Bachelor Party''). More than a dozen great indexes
include chronological filmographies and a Web-site guide. It also
has the best how-to-order information.
</P>
<P>
   The bad stuff: This book may actually be too big _ it's
overwhelming. The cheeky attitude too often doesn't come out in the
reviews, which is surprising for a book that uses ``Woof!'' to rate
bad movies. But although the Maltin guide has better reviews, this
has replaced it as the one to beat.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 4 1/2
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a film reviewer for the Star-Telegram. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
