A3404 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-NOTES-NYT &LR;      12-10 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: U.K.)  
 ART NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COW ORGANS? YOUNG ART SELLS
</P>
<P>
   A naked polyester baby boy, a polished steel gun, a man's suit
shot through with holes and four cabinets containing assorted jars
of cow's organs were among the 130 works by 97 contemporary artists
that were sold by Christie's in London on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't just any auction of contemporary art. It represented
about 5 percent of Charles Saatchi's famed collection. Saatchi, the
advertising magnate who is one of London's biggest contemporary art
collectors, has been able to use his promotional skills to market
and sell his art over the years.
</P>
<P>
   The auction was for a good cause. Its proceeds will be used, in
part, to set up a scholarship program to help pay for students'
projects and commissions at four London art schools: Chelsea,
Goldsmiths', the Royal College and the Slade. The money will also
help pay for the projects of young British artists who have
finished college. The benefits will not all flow in one direction.
Some of these artists will also show their work at Saatchi's
gallery on Boundary Road in the St. John's Wood section of London,
and he may in turn buy their work.
</P>
<P>
   The sale took place in an abandoned warehouse in London's
financial district, a space that could better accommodate the large
scale of some of the pieces than could Christie's more intimate
salesrooms at its King Street headquarters. The auction's sales
totaled $2.6 million, $1 million more than Christie's estimate,
proving that the market for young art is booming.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the sale's art was by leading ``YBAs,'' or Young British
Artists, like Damien Hirst, Rachel Whiteread and Jenny Saville.
Also on the block were works by contemporary American artists like
Cindy Sherman, Charles Long, Jessica Stockholder and Kiki Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years Saatchi has helped create a booming market for
many of the artists he buys, in part by showing them at his
13-year-old gallery. But last year he received worldwide attention
when he lent 120 works, all by young British artists, for
``Sensation,'' a show at the Royal Academy in London that attracted
record-breaking crowds. It has since traveled to Berlin and is at
the Hamburger Bahnhof through Jan. 17. (Experts in the museum world
say the Brooklyn Museum of Art will mount the show some time next
year, although officials there said it was too early to confirm
that.)
</P>
<P>
   But even as Saatchi has been credited with boosting sales of
contemporary artists, he has occasionally sold some artists' works
in bulk, causing their prices and desirability to plummet. As a
result, before Tuesday's sale many experts said Saatchi was taking
a big gamble.
</P>
<P>
   If so, the gamble paid off. Prices for many artists reached more
than twice the pre-sale estimates. Some of the high prices were for
works by artists who had never been at auction before. Among the
top sellers was ``Grosse Geister,'' a group of three
larger-than-life robotlike aluminum figures from 1996 by the
cerebral German sculptor Thomas Schutte, which sold to an
unidentified London dealer for $245,000, above its $200,000 high
estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Past and present winners of the coveted Turner Prize, an award
given annually by the Tate Gallery in London to a contemporary
British artist, performed well. Hirst, the 1995 winner, broke a
record for his pharmaceutical paintings when ``Acetic Anhydride,''
a 1991 example, sold to an unidentified telephone bidder for
$202,125, more than five times its $42,000 high estimate. Hirst's
``Lovers (Spontaneous, Committed, Detached, Compromising),'' a
series of four cabinets containing jars of cow's organs, sold to
another unidentified telephone bidder for $229,350, way above its
$170,000 high estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Whiteread, who won the Turner Prize in 1993 and has received
much attention in New York for the translucent resin water tower
that was installed on a SoHo rooftop this summer, scored a record
price for her work, too. Her ``Untitled (Square Sink),'' a 1990
negative plaster cast of a sink, sold for $220,275, nearly three
times its $84,000 high estimate. A record price for work by Chris
Ofili, this year's Turner Prize winner, was set when his ``Them
Bones,'' a 1995 painting of a skeleton holding in each hand balls
of the artist's signature elephant dung, brought $36,052, more than
twice its $17,000 high estimate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nearly 4,000 people visited the viewing,'' said Graham
Southern, who heads Christie's contemporary art department in
London. ``And about 50 percent of the people had never been to an
auction before.'' Christie's said 74.8 percent of the buyers were
European and of those, 39.1 percent were British. Americans
represented 24.6 percent of the buying pool and Asians 2.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly `Sensation' helped,'' Southern said, adding that
excitement over the construction of the Tate Gallery of Modern Art,
scheduled to open in 2000, also motivated buyers. ``It's now
obvious to the public that these artists are making a place in
history,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A $3.6 MILLION RICHTER
</P>
<P>
   If few buyers at the Saatchi sale were identified, one of the
most conspicuous consumers at another major auction in London this
week was the Pritzker family, who bought Gerhard Richter's
``Cathedral Square, Milan'' (1968) at Sotheby's sale of
contemporary art on Wednesday. It is the largest of his photo
paintings from the '60s _ 9 feet by 9{ feet _ and shows the Piazza
del Duomo.
</P>
<P>
   The Pritzkers paid $3.6 million, nearly twice the works' $1.98
million high estimate. The family plans to put it in the lobby of
their Park Hyatt Hotel, which is being built on Michigan Avenue in
Chicago. But until the hotel is completed, a Sotheby's official
said, the family will lend the painting to the Art Institute of
Chicago, which has the largest collection of Richters in America.
</P>
<P>
   A CURATOR FOR THE GETTY
</P>
<P>
   After a six-month search the J. Paul Getty Museum announced that
Scott Schaefer, an expert in Sotheby's Old Master department, will
be the museum's new curator of paintings. He succeeds David Jaffe,
who resigned in September to become senior curator at the National
Gallery in London. Schaefer begins his new job early next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
