<SLUG> BC-STEEPLEJACK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS IS ALL UP AND DOWN FOR THIS ENTREPRENEUR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JACOB H. FRIES  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Fifth-graders and men in hard hats get weak in
the knees and queasy in the stomach when they see him.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Phelan is like a rock star. He's been featured on
television. Adoring fans ask for his signature, and he doesn't even
play the guitar.
</P>
<P>
   He's a steeplejack, the guy paid about $80 per hour to climb and
paint the tallest flagpole outside the San Francisco City Hall this
week, a job he says is just another day at the office. Except his
office is usually about six stories above the pavement, swaying in
the breeze.
</P>
<P>
   It's a rare occupation, although not in this family. Phelan's
grandfather was a steeplejack in Ireland before coming to America.
His dad followed in his father's footsteps. Now Phelan's doing it
here. And so is his sister and her son.
</P>
<P>
   Are they crazy?
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't pay me enough to scale that thing,'' said John
Kyrk, 60, as he took a picture of Phelan lashed to the top of the
City Hall pole. ``There's only one way down from there, and it's
right beneath you.''
</P>
<P>
   Before painting the 90-foot pole this week, Phelan replaced the
head-sized gold ball at the peak as construction workers, city
officials and children pointed up and smiled, oftentimes with a
starry-eyed gaze.
</P>
<P>
   Children fearlessly swinging across monkey bars and diving
head-first down slides at a nearby playground had the most
incredulous looks on their faces as they watched Phelan sway and
twist in the wind.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least when you're flying, you can't see that far down,''
said Webb Allen, 10, a rambunctious daredevil who knows of one
profession in which he doesn't want to climb to the top.
</P>
<P>
   Phelan, 46, said there's nothing to fear as a steeplejack,
except perhaps a pigeon perched above you. He would think that. His
family has climbed to the top of steeples for nearly 100 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a job I was born and raised into,'' he said. ``It's in
the blood.''
</P>
<P>
   Phelan's wife has a baby due in July, and though he promises not
to pressure his child to follow the family business, he said, ``I'm
sure their life will include climbing of some sort.''
</P>
<P>
   Phelan started scaling trees when he was yea-high, he said,
leveling his hand at his hip. His parents weren't worried. By the
time he was 13, Phelan was climbing with his father into the lights
at Candlestick Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're a kid, climbing on top of things is something you
do,'' he said. ``My family's just made a living out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   In more than 30 years of roping and rappelling, Phelan has been
on top of many of San Francisco's highest highs. What he can't
carry up on his utility belt, he has a helicopter lower to him.
</P>
<P>
   Not much shakes him, but he still gets a mild case of stage
fright when performing in front of an audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get really worried when lots of people gather below me,''
Phelan said. ``I'm afraid something might fall and kill them.''
</P>
<P>
   As a high-wire performer, he knows safety always comes first.
And so, as Phelan pivots around the pole, painting from top to
bottom, on the street below people gawk and inevitably ask the
million-dollar question:
</P>
<P>
   ``How's the weather up there?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
