 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Friday, Dec. 11. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PLO-CHARTER (Gaza City) _ In keeping with the terms of the new
Israeli-Palestinian accord, the Palestine Liberation Organization's
Central Council Thursday reaffirmed its vote to remove the call for
Israel's destruction from its charter, setting the stage for a vote
before the full body next week during a visit here by President
Clinton. By Joel Greenberg. With map.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-BUDGET (Moscow) _ After three months of wrangling and
vacillation, the Russian Government finally hammered out a spending
plan for 1999 that is intended to halt the nation's economic
tumble. Parliament's approval is required. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.N. (United Nations) _ The government of Saddam Hussein
toughened its refusal to allow arms inspectors into the ruling
party's offices Thursday, as the chief inspector, Richard Butler,
sent the Security Council a letter charging Iraq with violating a
host of Council directives. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   IVORY-COAST-ROMANCE (Abidjan, Ivory Coast) _ The sun was setting
far, far away, casting a mysterious glow on Ebrie Lagoon here. From
her villa, Vanessa Toualy, a former hostess for Air Afrique,
watched the sunset with rather sad downcast eyes, for she did not
know that the athletic and dashing Christian Magou was thinking of
her. So unfolds a scene from ``Un Bonheur Inattendu,'' or
``Unexpected Happiness,'' one of the six titles in a new series of
African romance novels believed to be the first of its kind. By
Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IMPEACH &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH (Washington) _ The House Judiciary Committee began
debating four articles of impeachment tonight after Republican and
Democratic lawyers made their final arguments about President
Clinton's removal from office, marshaling videotapes, tape
recordings, the words of the nation's founders and former
Presidents as well as competing views of the evidence. By Alison
Mitchell. With photos and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-CLINTON (Washington) _ The president will call wavering
Republicans to argue against impeachment and signal his willingness
to accept the toughly worded Democratic censure alternative; White
House quietly tries to persuade Republicans that impeachment is
against their political interest. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-SCENE (Washington) _ The committee finally has the
articles of impeachment: The anger, the gloom of Democrats, the
resolve of the Republicans. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-DEBATE (Washington) _ A look at the tone of the debate,
and its contrast with 24 years ago. Are there any Barbara Jordans
here? By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GENERAL-ADULTERY (Washington) _ The Army charged a retired
two-star general Thursday with 17 counts of criminal misconduct
stemming from adulterous relationships he had with the wives of
four officers under his command in a case that forced the Army to
revise its retirement policy for officers facing charges of
wrongdoing. The officer, Maj. Gen. David R.E. Hale, had served only
four months as the Army's deputy inspector general when he was
allowed to retire honorably last February even though one of the
women had filed a complaint that accused him of coercing her into a
sexual relationship. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL-GENERAL &LR;  (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   HIRSCHFELD-INDICT (New York) _ Developments in the indictment of
the real estate developer Abe Hirschfeld, 79, in a plot to murder
his longtime business partner, Stanley Stahl. By Randy Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   ALIEN-SMUGGLING (Undated) _ American and Canadian authorities
Thursday announced the break-up of a sophisticated smuggling ring
that spirited illegal aliens into the United States via Canada and
a Mohawk reservation. Authorities said the ring, made up primarily
of Chinese nationals and members of the Mohawk tribe, transported
more than 3,500 Chinese aliens across the St. Lawrence River and
into upstate New York during the last two years. By Steven A.
Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WORM-GENOME (Undated) _ Biologists have for the first time
deciphered the full genetic programming of an animal, a landmark on
the way to deciphering the human genome. The animal is a
microscopic roundworm whose full DNA, has been found to consist of
97 million chemical units and is predicted to contain 19,099 genes.
If printed in ordinary type, the DNA sequence, would take up 2,727
pages of this newspaper. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   AETNA-PRUDENTIAL (Undated) _ Aetna agreed to acquire Prudential
Healthcare for $1 billion in cash and debt issuance, expanding its
health benefit membership in nine states by about 6.6 million
people. Aetna will also more than double its dental coverage to
more than 15 million people. The transaction gets Prudential out of
the increasingly competitive managed-care industry, while giving
Aetna, which earlier this year bought New York Life's healthcare
business for $1.05 billion, increased leverage to negotiate prices
with providers. By Milt Freudenheim. With graphic.
</P>
