   The New York Times News Service calls your attention to the
following personal finance stories moved during the last week.
</P>
<P>
   For retransmissions of these stories, please call 888-346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INVESTING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-FLAWS-NYT (Undated) _ The near-collapse of Long Term
Capital Management tested some fundamental assumptions of the
investment world and found them severely flawed. By Diana B.
Henriques.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-OIL-NYT (Undated) _ Big oil's future: What a merger may
mean for investors. By Youssef M. Ibraham.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-COLUMN-NYT (Undated) _ Strategies column: Risk
adjustment. By Mark Hulbert.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A-NYT (Undated) _ A question and answer with a
market insider. This week: Charles I. Clough Jr., chief investment
strategist at Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-WITH-BERGHUIS-NYT (Undated) _ Investing with Brian W.H.
Berghuis of T. Rowe Price Mid-Cap Growth fund. By William R. Long.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-GE-NYT (Undated) _ General Electric is pushing mutual
funds now. By Carole Gould.
</P>
<P>
   MUTUAL-FUNDS-BLOOM (Boston) _ As a group, few investments are
outperforming large-company U.S. stocks these days. And, of the
mutual funds that invest in this area, none is doing better than
White Oak Growth Stock Fund. By Tim Quinson.
</P>
<P>
   PERSONAL-FUNDS-BLOOM (San Antonio, Texas) _ The USAA Aggressive
Growth Fund, which has had an increase in assets of $200 million
and 27 percent returns in the past few months, hopes its retail
holdings can lead to big gains in this Christmas shopping season.
By Jon Friedman.
</P>
<P>
   PERSONAL-WEALTH-BLOOM (New York) _ The road to riches, it would
seem to late night television viewers, is paved with foreclosed
real estate. Informercials fill the airwaves touting that wealth
can be gained by buying foreclosed property at deep discounts with
little money down. If only it were that simple. By Robert Burgess.
</P>
<P>
   FLOW-OF-FUNDS-BLOOM (Boston) _ Fidelity Magellan Fund, after
four years of sub-par performance, is back. By Tim Quinson.
</P>
<P>
   MUTUAL-FUNDS-BLOOM (Boston) _ Fewer U.S. mutual funds are being
created this year than at time since 1992, as money managers find
it increasingly difficult to sell funds in an already-crowded
marketplace, according to an industry report. By Tim Quinson.
</P>
<P>
   BEYOND-INDEX-FUNDS-BLOOM (Boston) _ ``Superdiversifiers'' _
mutual funds with little correlation to the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
Index and top performers in their own right _ may be a good bet for
investors looking beyond the formula of index funds. Morningstar
Inc. came up with a list of six such funds. By Tim Quinson.
</P>
<P>
   FUND-WINNERS-LOSERS-BLOOM (New York) _ Investors who own
technology stock funds can boast of 50-percent gains this year,
while holders of natural resources funds can consider themselves
lucky if they lost anything less than half their money. Many
emerging markets stock and bond funds also are money-losers. Story
includes list of 10 winning funds and 10 losing funds. By Tim
Quinson.
</P>
<P>
   RATES-OF-RETURN-BLOOM (New York) _ Yields on mortgage securities
are high enough that investors in that $2 trillion market are more
likely than a year ago to outperform buyers of Treasuries even
though mortgage prepayments are at a record. By Jonathan Tower.
</P>
<P>
   MUTUAL-FUND-BLOOM (Boston) _ As a group, few investments are
outperforming large-company U.S. stocks these days. And, of the
mutual funds that invest in this area, none is doing better than
White Oak Growth Stock Fund. By Tim Quinson.
</P>
<P>
   MUTUAL-FUNDS-BLOOM (New York) _ Scudder AARP Mutual Funds says
the most profound change in investing among its members is their
acceptance of risk, after years of showing fear toward investing in
international funds and other risky investments. By Jon Friedman.
</P>
<P>
   MORNINGSTAR-MUTUAL-FUNDS-BLOOM (New York): John Rekenthaler,
research director of Morningstar, said mutual fund companies will
use the Internet more in 1999 to give investors fund-related
information as a way of cutting their own costs. By Jon Friedman.
</P>
<P>
   MORNINGSTAR-STOCK-FUNDS-BLOOM (New York) - John Rekenthaler,
research director of Morningstar, said large-company stock funds
will end their long run of market dominance in 1999 and predicted
that small-company funds will rebound. By Jon Friedman.
</P>
<P>
   MUTUAL-FUNDS-BLOOM (Denver) _ Stock-picker Thomas Marsico is the
second mutual fund manager this year to attract more than $1
billion to a new fund, Marsico Focus Fund. By Tim Quinson.
</P>
<P>
   MUTUAL-FUNDS-BLOOM (Boston) _ Vanguard Windsor Fund, one of
America's biggest stock mutual funds, is having a bad year _ plain
and simple. By Tim Quinson.
</P>
<P>
   PERSONAL-FUNDS-BLOOM (Boston): The Eaton Vance Utilities Fund is
banking on strong performance from such non-traditional utilities
are telephone stocks to boost its performance while hoping that the
telecommunications issues won't be too risky for its cautious
investors. By Jon Friedman.
</P>
<P>
   MAGELLAN'S-BACK-BLOOM (Boston) _ Fidelity Magellan Fund, the
world's largest mutual fund, is back after four years of sub-par
performance. For the first time since 1993, it's on pace for a
higher annual return than the stocks in Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
Index. By Tim Quinson.
</P>
<P>
   NEW-MUTUAL-FUNDS-BLOOM (Boston) _ Fewer U.S. mutual funds are
being created this year than at any time since 1992, as money
managers find it increasingly difficult to sell funds in an
already-crowded marketplace, according to an industry report. By
Tim Quinson.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCE-COMPANY-BONDS-BLOOM (New York) _ The bonds of banks and
securities firms have been good performers since late October. Some
investors figure there is room for more gains. By Kathleen
Spillane.
</P>
<P>
   IPOs-RETURN-BLOOM (New York) _ Just three months ago, the market
for initial stock sales was in one of its worst droughts in 20
years. Now IPOs are back. A total of 23 companies have raised about
$4.35 billion since the beginning of November. By Per H. Jebsen.
</P>
<P>
   JOBS-AND-BONDS (New York) _ A surprise jump in U.S. jobs
reported Dec. 4 won't stop Treasury bonds from climbing in months
ahead, since inflation isn't a problem and economic growth will
probably slow, investors say. By Wes Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   MARSICO FUND (Denver) _ Stock-picker Thomas Marsico is the
second mutual fund manager this year to attract more than $1
billion to a new fund, Marsico Focus Fund. That's because it
performs. By Tim Quinson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS (Undated) _ New data shows a slew of
Fidelity funds that overlap more with the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index than any other shop in town, making Fidelily king of Boston's
big-stock investors. By Steven Syre and Steve Bailey.
</P>
<P>
   ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS (Undated) _ Questions about the mutual
fund directors are more easily asked than answered. But this much
is clear: The industry believes the system works and is moving to
protect it. By Steven Syre and Steve Bailey.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS (Undated) _ Time is definitely on
26-year-old's side. By Kenneth Hooker.
</P>
<P>
   JOHN-DORFMAN-BLOOM (Boston) _ Insider buying is a good omen for
some small-company stocks. By John Dorfman.
</P>
<P>
   MONEY-COLUMN-HNS (Undated) _ This is the season to teach your
kids about money, say financial experts. They are not suggesting a
miserly Christmas, just a time when you teach your children to
spend within their means by establishing a holiday budget to help
them decide what they afford for themselves and others. By Pamela
Yip.
</P>
<P>
   JOHN-DORFMAN-BLOOM (Boston) _ This year will go down in stock
market record books as one of those rare years in which small
stocks fell while big stocks rose. And you'll find the bargains
these days among those small stocks - as insiders already have. By
John Dorfman.
</P>
<P>
   ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS (Undated) _ Talk about putting your money
where your mouth is. Money manager starts a new small cap fund,
putting his entire net worth into the kitty. By Steven Syre and
Steve Bailey.
</P>
<P>
   ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS (Undated) _ Joe McNay, the truest believer
among Internet investors, cuts his Internet positions roughly in
half. By Steven Syre and Steve Bailey.
</P>
<P>
   ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS (Undated) _ New data shows a slew of
Fidelity funds that overlap more with the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index than any other shop in town, making Fidelily king of Boston's
big-stock investors. By Steven Syre and Steve Bailey.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONSUMER NEWS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LAYOFFS-NEWSTYLE-NYT (Indianapolis) _ Plant closings and layoffs
are rising sharply again. The cutbacks announced recently at
Bankers Trust and Boeing are only the latest examples. But the
outcries and conflict that characterized the waves of downsizing in
the 1980s and early 1990s are gone. Rather than protest, unions are
more likely now to help their laid-off members make the transition
to other jobs. By Louis Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   BUYING-FORECLOSURES-BLOOM (New York) _ The airwaves are filled
with infomercials touting the wealth to be gained by acquiring
houses that have fallen into foreclosure. Just spend a few hundred
bucks, the infomercials say, for a how-to manual. It's not that
simple, of course, but if you learn the ins and outs of this
market, bargains can be had _ at 10 percent to 25 percent below
market value. By Robert Burgess.
</P>
<P>
   AARP-ACCEPTS-RISK-BLOOM (Boston) _ The 34 million members of the
American Association of Retired Persons, ages 50 and older, accept
investment risk more willingly now than in the past. By Jon
Friedman.
</P>
<P>
   RETIREMENT-SAVINGS-HNS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Financial planners and
money managers say this year's topsy-turvey stock market may be a
blessing in disguise. They say people can learn valuable, lasting
lessons about how to handle their retirement planning from the ups
and downs. We offer some retirement-planning tips for weathering
the best and worst of times. By Jo-Ann Johnston.
</P>
