<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENERAL-SEX-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETIRED GENERAL CHARGED WITH IMPROPER SEXUAL RELATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ED OFFLEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT LEWIS, Wash. _ A retired Army major general has been
charged with having improper sexual relations with the wives of
four subordinates and obstructing a Pentagon probe into the affair,
Fort Lewis officials announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Gen. David Hale faces the military equivalent of a grand
jury hearing at Fort Lewis as a result of the decision by I Corps
commander Lt. Gen. George Crocker to prefer charges against him,
Fort Lewis spokeswoman Lt. Col. Melanie Reeder said yesterday.
Crocker was appointed to direct a review of the Army evidence in
October with the authority to convene a court-martial if the facts
warrant it.
</P>
<P>
   No date has been set for the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Hale retired under honorable conditions in February after
serving only four months as the Army's deputy inspector general in
the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   An Army statement summarizing the case said Hale has been
charged on 17 counts of violating the Uniformed Code of Military
Justice, including six alleged violations of Article 107 (making
false official statements) including lying to the Army inspector
general, the Army's vice chief of staff, and the Defense
Department's deputy inspector general. Hale also faces nine charges
of violating Article 133 (conduct unbecoming an officer), including
having improper relationships with the wife of a subordinate
officer in Hawaii from 1994 to 1997, and the wives of three
subordinate officers at Izmir, Turkey, from 1996 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
   He also is accused on two counts of violating Article 134 of the
military code (obstruction of justice), including threats to a
subordinate's spouse and telling a civilian government employee to
delete computer files relevant to the Pentagon probe.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted on all 17 counts, Hale could receive a maximum
punishment of 49 years in a military prison and loss of all pay and
benefits, said Army spokesman Lt. Col. Guy Shields.
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to reach Hale or his lawyer were unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   Accusations against Hale first surfaced last January when one of
the women with whom he is accused of having an affair reported it
to Army investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Several weeks later, Hale requested retirement. Senior Army
officials were later criticized for allowing Hale to leave active
duty on Feb. 23 as the accusations became public.
</P>
<P>
   In a report released earlier this year, Defense Department
Inspector General Eleanor Hill concluded that Hale ``engaged in a
pattern of inappropriate behavior'' with the wives of four
subordinates while he was a senior officer based in Turkey. Hale
also was accused in that report of sanctioning misuse of government
funds for travel and making false and misleading statements to Army
investigators and Pentagon officials.
</P>
<P>
   Crocker has appointed Col. Gary Holland, a military circuit
judge from Fort Campbell, Ky., to conduct a formal investigation
under Article 32 of the Uniformed Code of Military Justice. The
proceeding will allow ``a thorough and impartial investigation of
those charges,'' Reeder said. Both Army prosecutors and lawyers for
Hale will take part in the hearing, which can include the
presentation of evidence and witness testimony.
</P>
<P>
   At the conclusion of that hearing, Holland will make a report to
Crocker that could include recommending the dropping of some or all
charges; adding additional charges, and recommending a general
court-martial on charges the investigator has confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Reeder said it will not be necessary for Hale to be recalled to
active duty to face either the Article 32 hearing or a
court-martial, should one be ordered. General officers in retired
status are still subject to the military legal code, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The charges against Hale surfaced in a report published by The
Washington Times earlier this year. It reported that a woman named
Donnamaria Carpino charged that Hale ``forced her into a four-month
sexual relationship'' in Izmir, Turkey, while her husband, an Army
colonel, was posted there. At the time, Hale was the deputy
commanding general of NATO's allied land forces in southeastern
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   As the Army probe intensified against him last August, Hale
filed a slander lawsuit against Carpino accusing her of ``character
assassination'' against him but dropped the suit two months later.
</P>
</TEXT>
