<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3572 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-2ap1210a     12-10 0239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-2ap1210a </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Warm weather chills donations
 &HT;    By Jingle Davis
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jingle bells just sound more appealing in colder weather, said
Salvation Army officials, lamenting the fact that donations to
their 180 Atlanta-area Christmas kettles are down.
</P>
<P>
   They're blaming the decline, in large part, on the unseasonably
warm weather of recent weeks, said Jamee Smith, director of
development for the Salvation Army of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kettles do better when the weather's colder because donors
feel sorry for the bell ringers standing out in the cold,'' Smith
said. ``Also, in cold weather, people get in more of a Christmas
spirit of giving.''
</P>
<P>
   Donations to metro-area kettles, often manned by Santas outside
busy shopping centers, are down 5 percent to 7 percent from last
year, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said she had no hard statistics to back up her assertion
that colder weather warms donors' hearts.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I've worked with the Salvation Army for 25 years and it's
always been that way,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   This week's drop in temperatures may prompt donations to rise,
Smith predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Highs for the rest of the week are not expected to climb above
the mid-50s under partly-cloudy skies.
</P>
<P>
   Rain and temperatures in the lower 50s are predicted for this
weekend, according to the National Weather Service.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
