<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3574 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRANCE-LEPEN-NYT &LR;      12-10 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-LEPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWER STRUGGLE HAS THE FAR-RIGHT NATIONAL FRONT IN DISARRAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Nine months ago the National Front, for years the most
powerful far-right movement in Western Europe, turned French
politics upside down: It lured moderate conservatives into regional
political alliances that had previously been anathema.
</P>
<P>
   Now the party is in disarray after its leader, the irascible
Jean-Marie Le Pen, 70, threw out the man who was behind its drive
for right-wing respectability.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno Megret, the 49-year-old architect of the new policy, was
Le Pen's principal deputy until Wednesday, when he broke openly
with the party patriarch after months of subterranean dissension
and called for a special party convention in January to thrash out
their differences.
</P>
<P>
   Le Pen then dismissed Megret, had bodyguards evict Megret
loyalists from their offices in the party's headquarters, in
suburban St.-Cloud, and said there would be no convention. He
charged that he had been the victim of ``subversion.''
</P>
<P>
   Megret, whose wife is the mayor of Vitrolles, on the outskirts
of Marseilles, countered, ``The National Front does not belong to
anyone.'' This in itself was considered an affront by Le Pen, who
founded the National Front in 1972 and has said, echoing an
aphorism of Louis XIV, ``I am the National Front.''
</P>
<P>
   Le Pen's plan to have his wife, Jeanne-Marie, lead the party's
ticket for next June's elections for the European Parliament if he
could not do so himself was opposed earlier this fall by Megret,
who thought that as Le Pen's deputy, he should step in. Le Pen
quickly countered that his wife would run if he wanted her to.
</P>
<P>
   A court in Versailles has convicted Le Pen of assaulting a
Socialist politician there who was running against his daughter
during French legislative elections last year, and suspended his
right to vote or run for office for two years.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, another court reduced the sentence to one
year, suspended, but Le Pen has appealed to the highest court and
can run for office next spring if, as is almost certain, his appeal
is still pending then.
</P>
<P>
   A German court is also investigating him for describing the Nazi
gas chambers in World War II as ``a detail of history'' in a speech
in Munich, a possible violation of a German law that forbids
trivializing the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   Megret said earlier this year that he could not deny that Le Pen
had said such things, but insisted that such views were not part of
the party platform.
</P>
<P>
   Le Pen, in a rare national television appearance recently, said
it was his opponents in the party who were racists, not him. He
added that he would indeed head the ticket next June, and that he
hoped it would win about 20 percent of the vote, placing 21 members
in the European Parliament to fight plans to submerge Europe's
nation states in federalism, instead of the 11 the party won in the
last elections, in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Le Pen ran for the French presidency in 1995 and won 15 percent
of the vote, as the party does routinely nationwide. It had even
higher showings in suburbs of cities like Paris and Strasbourg,
where there are high concentrations of immigrants from Turkey and
North Africa, which the party platform promises to send back home
if it ever wins power.
</P>
<P>
   Until Megret and his moderate strategy came along, it seemed
unlikely that the National Front would ever run the country. But
Megret, a former Gaullist, succeeded last spring in getting
conservative leaders in five of the 22 regional assemblies to
accept support from the National Front to stay in power after the
Socialists gained ground in regional elections.
</P>
<P>
   The conservatives, who defied President Jacques Chirac and other
leaders, were later expelled from their own parties, which have
been trying to make a comeback ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Now it is the National Front that is at war with itself, with Le
Pen claiming victory Thursday over what he described as an
``attempted putsch'' and Megret saying he had enough support among
the party's 50,000 members to force the special convention he wants
to hold.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
