<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, Dec. 11, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Bitterly cold air will remain locked in far northern Canada and
Alaska for the next several days as vigorous jet stream winds
continue to direct Pacific air masses into southern Canada.
Meanwhile, expansive high pressure will promote dry conditions over
much of the northern and central United States.
</P>
<P>
   Gusty breezes from the northwest will deliver slightly colder
air to the New York and New England on Friday, but temperatures
will remain a few degrees above seasonal levels. A few snow showers
will dust the mountains of northern New England as well as areas
east of Lake Ontario, especially early Friday. Otherwise, partly to
mostly sunny skies will prevail.
</P>
<P>
   A warming trend will develop from the northern Plains to the
Great Lakes states. A weak front will produce patchy clouds near
the Canadian border. Otherwise, sunshine will be plentiful.
</P>
<P>
   Periods of rain will occur from eastern parts of Texas and
Oklahoma to the southern Mississippi Valley as low pressure moves
slowly east through the western Gulf of Mexico. Some patchy light
snow will fall in western Texas, but direr air will begin to spread
south through the panhandle Friday afternoon. Farther east, clouds
and few patchy showers will move through the Tennessee Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Onshore winds will foster coastal showers and intermittent
mountain snow in the Northwest. After a cold dawn with patchy fog
and low clouds in the valleys of the interior Southwest, ample
sunshine will boost temperature to near seasonal readings in the
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Imitation Chill &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures fell into the single digits and, in some places,
below zero degrees in the Great Basin across parts of Nevada, Utah,
Idaho and southeast Oregon before dawn Thursday. But the deep
nocturnal chill was not the result of a frigid Arctic air mass.
Rather, it was an imitation chill that was manufactured by the
ground. At night, the ground lost much more infrared energy than it
gained from the clear, calm and dry atmosphere. In turn, the
rapidly cooling ground chilled overlying air. Moreover, cold air
drained down from mountains, setting the stage for a convincing
imitation chill. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
