<HEADER>
A3628 &Cx1f; paxxx
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-IMPEACH-PA     12-10 0369
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-IMPEACH-PA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        FOX HAS ONE MORE VOTE BEFORE LEAVING OFFICE: WHETHER TO
IMPEACH
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Lisa Fine  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Dec. 10 -- Rep. Jon Fox may have been voted out of
office, but the Montgomery County Republican still has one last
vote to cast -- whether to impeach President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   How he'll vote, he said, he hasn't decided.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought I would end my tenure in Congress with a vote
like this. I am still listening to all of the evidence and haven't
made up mind,'' Fox said this week. ``I know voters expect me to be
fair minded.''
</P>
<P>
   While many members of Congress have already decided how they'll
vote, Fox is among a group of between 20 to 30 ``swing''
Republicans and Democrats, whose undecided votes could determine
the president's future.
</P>
<P>
   With the House Judiciary Committee almost certain to approve at
least one article of impeachment against Clinton, a vote in the
full House is expected late next week. And, despite his narrow loss
to Democrat Joseph Hoeffel, Fox's term does not expire until the
first week of January.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike many hold-outs, weighing whether to be loyal to their
party or to the more moderate voters who elected them, Fox can vote
on the controversial issue and then leave office without ever
facing the voters again.
</P>
<P>
   Fox says that doesn't make his vote any easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather have been reelected and know I was returning to
office,'' said Fox, a former assistant district attorney in
Montgomery County. ``I don't think being an outgoing member would
help someone vote their gut feeling and be done with it. I think
everyone has to evaluate and vote fairly. It is their
constitutional obligation.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox was defeated in 1992 in his first run for Congress, elected
in 1994 and reelected in 1996 by 84 votes. A self described
``independent Republican,'' Fox, during the 1998 campaign, always
said he would consider the evidence against Clinton and not
pre-judge the outcome. Hoeffel, however, said early on that he
would support a congressional censure against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Hoeffel, who is out of town and could not be reached for comment
on Fox's pending vote, won by more than 9,000 votes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-98 1806EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981210.0294 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3629 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2NDTA     12-10 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: (Janet Maslin) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   `HOME FRIES,' starring Drew Barrymore. Directed by Dean Parisot
(PG-13, 105 minutes). An absurdist satire of sex, sibling rivalry,
Oedipal ties, homicidal jealousy, fast food and helicopters in the
American heartland, ``Home Fries'' isn't funny enough in its
particulars to make you break up laughing, but at least it tries
for a sophistication beyond the typical gross-out Hollywood comedy.
Most of the humor comes from the collision of caricatures that
suggest refugees from ``Tobacco Road,'' reinvented for a '90s
version of the parodic '70s soap opera ``Mary Hartman, Mary
Hartman.'' Ms. Barrymore, who is winsome throughout, plays a very
pregnant server at a burger outlet who falls in love with the
stepson of her recently deceased married lover. (Stephen Holden)
</P>
<P>
   `LITTLE VOICE,' starring Jane Horrocks, Brenda Blethyn, Ewan
McGregor and Michael Caine. Directed by Mark Herman (R, 99
minutes). The main attraction here is watching wispy Ms. Horrocks
put on a spectacular one-woman diva festival, with her phenomenal
mimicry of musical grande dames from Judy Garland to Marilyn
Monroe. What works less well is the broad and stagy story built
around her. As the timid title character, she is harangued by her
blowsy mother (Ms. Blethyn), latched onto by the talent agent who
is the mother's boyfriend ( Caine) and courted by a nice young man
who loves his pet pigeons. In that last role, McGregor makes a
telephone installer scintillating and once again shows that he can
do anything. Incidentally, the soundtrack is divine. (Janet Maslin)
</P>
<P>
   `MEET JOE BLACK,' starring Brad Pitt, Anthony Hopkins and Claire
Forlani. Directed by Martin Brest (PG-13, 170 minutes). Hopkins
zestily plays a noble tycoon in this otherwise somnolent,
emotion-free, nearly three-hour (!) weepie. And Pitt appears
blankly as Death with blond highlights, serving as a kind of
personal afterlife trainer to the tycoon, whose number is up. Ms.
Forlani plays the big man's beautiful daughter in a story based on
``Death Takes a Holiday.'' In a suffocatingly lavish film that
cries out for a trip to the cutting room, virtually every character
is allowed to overstay his or her welcome, with Pitt especially
diminished by the watching-paint-dry pace. The story drags on so
slowly that there's room for a subplot about party planning, and
several scenes establish how much Death loves peanut butter. (Janet
Maslin)
</P>
<P>
   `PSYCHO,' starring Vince Vaughn and Anne Heche. Directed by Gus
Van Sant (R, 100 minutes). It turns out that the apparent rocks in
Van Sant's head, as he contrived this near-exact color replica of
Alfred Hitchcock's 1960 classic, were only pebbles. His remake (a
modest term, but it beats plagiarism) is artful and good-looking,
faltering only when it tries to improve on the brilliant original
blueprint. The casting of Vaughn as Norman Bates is the film's
biggest Achilles' heel, since the performance Hitchcock elicited
from Anthony Perkins remains an impossible act to follow. Still,
Van Sant has tried an outlandish experiment and come up with what
are, especially for fans of the original, intriguing variations on
a theme. (Janet Maslin)
</P>
<P>
   `VERY BAD THINGS,' starring Jon Favreau, Christian Slater,
Cameron Diaz and Daniel Stern. Directed by Peter Berg (R, 100
minutes). A film that means to make the most of black-humored
misanthropy had better be funnier than this mirthless exercise in
witlessness and sadistic humor. Five dull middle-class buddies
accidentally kill a prostitute while at a bachelor party in Las
Vegas, and that's only the beginning of the fun. While it's
possible to share the screenplay's eagerness to see these
unappetizing guys wind up dead, the direction reveals so little
point of view that it doesn't much matter who lives or dies. Ms.
Diaz, so cleverly funny in ``There's Something About Mary,'' plays
a wedding-obsessed ninny this time. (Janet Maslin)
</P>
<P>
   `WAKING NED DEVINE,' starring Ian Bannen, David Kelly and
Fionnula Flanagan. Directed by Kirk Jones (PG, 91 minutes).
Delightful shenanigans greet the news of a winning lottery ticket
in a tiny Irish village. Especially after the winner turns out to
be dead. Bannen and Kelly are wonderfully funny as two old coots
who concoct a plot to claim the winnings, and unite the town's cast
of hearty characters in the process. Jones' prize-winning career
directing television commercials means that everyone here is an
amusing eccentric with colorful quirks, and that the septuagenarian
stars' naked motorcycle-riding scenes are played for all they're
worth. This comedy doesn't have the tart edge of ``The Full
Monty,'' but it knows how to coax laughs from making a spectacle of
elderly gentlemen in the buff. (Janet Maslin)
</P>
<P>
   `THE WATERBOY,' starring Adam Sandler, Kathy Bates and Fairuza
Balk. Directed by Frank Coraci (PG-13, 91 minutes). The team behind
``The Wedding Singer'' looks like honorary Farrelly brothers with a
comedy that, like ``There's Something About Mary,'' is both
cheerfully outlandish and genuinely endearing. Sandler plays an
amazing 31-year-old freshman who morphs from water-distribution
engineer to sports hero, and he succeeds in doing to football
whatever he did to golf in ``Happy Gilmore.'' There's a lot more
innocence to his happy-idiot antics here than there is in many a
film made specifically for children. Ms. Bates is a great hoot as
the waterboy's overprotective mama, perfectly in tune with the
film's sneaky sense of fun. (Janet Maslin)
</P>
<P>
   Film Series
</P>
<P>
   SPANISH CINEMA NOW! Contemporary Spanish films are in the
spotlight at the Walter Reade Theater, where the Film Society of
Lincoln Center is presenting its seventh edition of this series.
This weekend, the 23-film series turns to works by Ventura Pons and
Salvador Garcia Ruiz. The attraction Friday at 2 and 6:15 p.m. and
Saturday at 6:30 p.m. is the 1997 Pons roundelay of contemporary
lust and love called ``Caresses.'' The attraction Friday at 4 and
8:20 p.m. and on Sunday at 6:30 p.m. is the 1998 Garcia Ruiz drama
``Paginas de una Historia, Mensaka,'' about a motorcycle messenger
by day and a drummer by night. Admission, $8.50 ($5 for Film
Society members, $4.50 for the elderly at weekday matinees). The
series continues through Dec. 31 at the Walter Reade, at Lincoln
Center. Information: (212) 875-5600. (Lawrence Van Gelder)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
