<HEADER>
A3639 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-BRIDGETFONDA-TEX     12-10 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BRIDGETFONDA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRIDGET FONDA TALKS ABOUT LOVE AND MONEY
</HEADLINE>
 (Accompanies FILM-ASIMPLEPLAN-TEX) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bridget Fonda, looking poised and businesslike at the head of a
nearly empty conference table, is musing about how her latest film
_ the violent, downbeat ``A Simple Plan'' _ qualifies as a
Christmas movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, all that snow,'' she says. ``And greed.''
</P>
<P>
   Lots of greed. ``Plan'' is about how the discovery of $4.4
million in cash changes _ for the worse _ the lives of a handful of
people. Fonda plays Sarah, the wife of Hank Mitchell (Fort Worth's
Bill Paxton), the respected small-town accountant who stumbles onto
the money along with his slovenly brother, Jacob (Billy Bob
Thornton), and Jacob's low-life friend Lou (Brent Briscoe).
</P>
<P>
   Screenwriter Scott B. Smith, who adapted his 1993 novel, saw a
hierarchy in the characters, with Sarah at the top _ she's the one
who begins driving the more weak-willed Hank. But although Sarah
becomes the most ruthless of the bunch, Fonda says that there's
more to her than meets the eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a survival-instinct kind of ruthless,'' the 34-year-old
actress says. ``You really start to feel where (Hank) didn't
realize how much she'd sacrificed and what she really wanted. She's
a complicated, but very good and fair, caring, loving person. She
doesn't want to hurt people. But she's fierce. And that comes
out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Plan'' isn't the first Fonda film to address greed; in 1994's
``It Could Happen to You,'' she played a waitress who is far more
altruistic than Sarah after she receives a $2 million tip from
Nicolas Cage's lottery-winning cop. They are a small part of a
long-standing tradition of greed in the movies _ and we're not
talking about the business, but the plots. Fonda says she believes
that lately, the theme is often that no good will come of money,
and she thinks she knows where that sentiment comes from.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a general discontent that's bred by advertising,'' she
says. ``The consumer society in general feeds your dreams of all
you want to do and want to have. And you get to a point where I
guess you can only be frustrated for so long.''
</P>
<P>
   A few years back, Fonda was best-known as Peter Fonda's
daughter. Now, despite a career resurgence that began with last
year's ``Ulee's Gold,'' he's just as likely to be referred to as
``Bridget Fonda's dad.'' Credit that to her hard work: In 11 years,
she has appeared in nearly 30 films, from a notorious scene in
1988's ``Aria'' (in her vignette, she appears nude, makes love and
then slits her wrists) to a noteworthy turn as a stoned-out beach
bunny in last year's ``Jackie Brown.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, the younger Fonda worked with ``Plan'' director
Sam Raimi, with a small role in his ``Army of Darkness.'' The rest
of ``Plan's'' lead cast had its own history. Paxton and Thornton
co-starred in 1992's ``One False Move;'' Briscoe appeared in
Thornton's ``Sling Blade.'' Fonda says that it wasn't a boys' club,
however; she and the other cast members hit it off right away. She
plays most of her scenes with Paxton and says they were a good
match.
</P>
<P>
   ``He, like me, gets really excited about it,'' she says. ``And
knowing the limited amount of time that we had to get across what
we wanted to about this couple, we wound up spending a lot of time
together talking about it, enjoying it. Enjoying what we knew might
not be able to be fulfilled, necessarily, with the time
constraints.''
</P>
<P>
   According to most reviews, they achieved fulfillment. Even
lukewarm reviews praise Thornton's performance, which is receiving
Oscar buzz, and some people say Paxton is also an Oscar contender.
Fonda had one advantage over both, though: She played all of her
scenes indoors. The book's plot is based in Ohio, but because of
unseasonably warm temperatures, the production was moved to
Wisconsin, right off of Lake Superior, where the wind-chill factor
was sometimes 60 below zero.
</P>
<P>
   Fonda, a California girl, isn't used to such temperatures. She's
more used to life in LA, where she spends her spare time watching
older movies (especially '40s and '50s film noir) and just hanging
out. But don't count on her to just hang out anywhere for too long.
As much as it is about greed, ``A Simple Plan'' is also about fate
_ and Fonda says she enjoys courting fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Living safe can become so stagnant,'' she says. ``It's part of
that whole `nothing ventured, nothing gained' theory. There's more
to it, I think, in that it's better to attempt and fail than to do
nothing. Because some kind of movement forward or backward is
better than no movement. Because whenever you can tempt fate, at
least you're active.''
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a film critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
