<SLUG> BC-BURT-BIO11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Burt Reynolds bio box
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE BURT REYNOLDS FILE
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Born: Feb. 11, 1936 in Lansing, Mich. The family moved to
Rivera Beach, Fla., when he was about 9.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The FSU football connection: He played halfback at Florida
State University and suffered a knee injury his sophomore year. At
Christmastime 1955 he was in a car accident and a passerby,
assuming he was dead, robbed him. Reynolds then quit football and
FSU.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The acting bug: Studied theater and eventually was spotted by
Joanne Woodward who recommended him to an agent. In the late '50s
he got TV parts on ``Twilight Zone'' and ``Riverboat,'' eventually
being fired from the latter. One big break came in 1962 on
``Gunsmoke,'' playing a half-breed blacksmith named Quint Asper.
The role _ and his eventual relationship with Dinah Shore _
ultimately led to appearances on Johnny Carson's ``The Tonight
Show,'' lead roles in TV's ``Hawk'' and ``Dan August'' and films.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The women: Among them were Judy Carne (whom he married in 1963
and divorced), Shore (19 years his senior), Sally Field, Loni
Anderson and his current squeeze Pam Seals.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Among roles and films he reportedly turned down: James Bond,
``MASH,'' ``One Flew Over The Cuckoo's Nest,'' ``Terms of
Endearment.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Awards: Golden Globe and Emmy in 1991 for TV's ``Evening
Shade.'' Golden Globe and Oscar nomination this year for ``Boogie
Nights.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
