<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A few hits and outright misses from Burt Reynolds film career
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A SELECTED FILMOGRAPHY
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Deliverance'' (1972) _ Aiming straight with a bow and arrow,
Reynolds leads Jon Voight, Ned Beatty and Ronny Cox on a Georgia
rafting adventure that turns deadly. Reynolds agrees ``without a
doubt'' it was his role of a lifetime. Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Boogie Nights'' (1997) _ He's understated but electric as a
porno film director showing Dirk Diggler (Mark Wahlberg) the ropes.
The film brought him his only Oscar nomination. Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Longest Yard'' (1974) _ Hugely popular, overtly physical
prison yarn with Reynolds leading an inmate football team against
the guards. Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Starting Over'' (1979) _ The late director Alan J. Pakula
took a chance casting Reynolds as a lonely divorced man. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Smokey and the Bandit'' (1977) _ Reynolds was adamant about
casting Sally ``The Flying Nun'' Field as a runaway bride to his
fast-driving, smooth-talking CB-radio beer smuggler. It ignited
their three-year off-screen relationship. Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Sharky's Machine'' (1981) _ Made in Atlanta, Reynolds
directed and played a hard-nosed vice cop. The film's budget
apparently ensured an unlimited supply of bullets. Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``City Heat'' (1984) _ He teamed with Clint Eastwood in a
lackluster 1930s-era gangster comedy. Reynolds maintains a stunt
injury in this film led to his dependence on a painkiller with a
resultant weight loss that sparked false rumors he had AIDS. Grade:
C
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``All Dogs Go to Heaven'' (1989) _ He voiced, naturally, the
canine hero in a rather lame, nearly forgettable animated musical.
Perk up your ears and you'll also hear Loni Anderson. Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Cannonball Run'' (1981) _ Reynolds and his misguided
six-pack of un-Sinatralike pals (Dom DeLuise and Bert Convy among
them) race cars for little reason. Grade: D
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``At Long Last Love'' (1975) _ Singing and tap dancing with
Cybill Shepherd in Peter Bogdanovich's painful-to-watch musical.
Grade: F
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
