<HEADER>
A3649 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BURTQ&AMP;A11-COX     12-10 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BURTQ&AMP;A11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Burt's back in familiar role as a
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just when it looks like Burt Reynolds is about to finally shed
that nagging image of a hardboiled, gun-toting, past-his-prime
go-getter, here he is at 62, pistol in hand, running and running
and running. Isn't this the guy who stunned much of Hollywood with
a searing acting performance last year as a porn director in the
critically acclaimed ``Boogie Nights''? If it wasn't for ``Good
Will Hunting's'' Robin Williams, wouldn't Reynolds now be holding
an Oscar instead of the pump-action rifle he grips in the final
scenes of TNT's ``Hard Time''?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe yes. Maybe no.
</P>
<P>
   Hal Needham, who directed Reynolds in such disco-era fast-wheels
films as the immensely popular ``Smokey and the Bandit'' and the
immensely bad ``The Cannonball Run,'' says he and Buddy, as close
friends call Reynolds, share the same flaw _ ``We're both addicted
to adrenalin.''
</P>
<P>
   ``True. Very true,'' Reynolds says, calling recently from a Los
Angeles hotel to promote ``Hard Time,'' which debuts at 8 p.m.
E.S.T. Sunday on TNT. ``We both forget that we're not 30 anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds is quick to admit where his performance passion lies.
Is it the high he gets from the knockout acting job of coaching
Dirk Diggler in ``Boogie Nights'' or picking up that pump-action
rifle and dueling with bad cops?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a close call,'' Reynolds says. ``I suppose if I was
smart I'd pick the straight-out acting. But, truly, it is the
other.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's what viewers will see if they tune in to ``Hard
Time.''
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds also directs the film, one of three ``Hard Time''
movies he's made for TNT. The second airs in February with the
third slated for later in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The directing gig is one of two promises Reynolds made to
himself after getting an Oscar nomination this year for the
independent film ``Boogie Nights.'' Reynolds, sometimes openly
bitter about past run-ins with Hollywood executives and the media,
is quite relaxed and polite this day during his phone call to plug
``Hard Time.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you step through how ``Hard Time'' and this three-picture
deal with TNT came about?
</P>
<P>
   A: When I talked with (executive producer) Larry Levinson, it
was a western called ``Hard Ground.'' I was attracted to the
character in terms of how he pushed the envelope. How in pushing,
how rough he was and whether the audience could forgive him for
that.
</P>
<P>
   As for TNT, it's very hard out here in Hollywood to get an
answer from most studios. With Ted Turner it was like ``OK'' and a
handshake. Q: ``Hard Time's'' got a lot of what you'd call classic
Burt Reynolds deadpan humor. Was stuff like that in the original
script or did you work that in?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, I did work that in. When you have baggage like I have
with (Charles) Durning, it's like it would be dumb for, say, Walter
Matthau in a film with Jack Lemmon to say, ``I love you.'' With
Durning, I knew we brought that. I wanted to play dark humor and
sarcasm and have fun with him.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In your lifetime, who's the sexier co-star? Catherine Deneuve
or Charles Durning?
</P>
<P>
   A: That's close. Maybe more in love with Durning. But Deneuve's
the answer.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You still swear off marriage?
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm trying. But they're closing in.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You did a lot for Georgia making all those films here. You
visit Atlanta much? See any changes?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's been a long time. Too long. I have so many friends
there. I think it's gotten like out here _ $1 million fixer-uppers,
you know. I had so many great times there. It was my good luck
state. Those films were such huge hits for me. I had the best time
making ``Sharky's Machine'' right in downtown Atlanta. Couldn't do
it today. Couldn't have access to that many buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Just one thing about the Oscars. What happened after it was
over, later that night?
</P>
<P>
   A: When I didn't win and went back to the hotel, I ordered some
soup or something. I'm just watching an old movie. The door was
pushed open. This French guy came in and started talking to me
about the soup. I look up. It's Jon Voight _ in the entire waiter's
outfit with a black bow tie. We sat there laughing until about 2 in
the morning. It was so sweet of him to think of me on that night.
He knew. It was the best joke.
</P>
<P>
   TV PREVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``Hard Time''
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. E.S.T. Sunday on TNT
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
