<HEADER>
A3664 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THEATER-NOTES-ART-NYT     12-10 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEING SPACEY WILL BE PRICEY  
 SUCCESS STORIES  
 ROUNDABOUT PLAYS IT SAFE  
 PANIC DRESSING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JESSE MCKINLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The $100 ticket is back.
</P>
<P>
   Emanuel Azenberg, producer of ``The Iceman Cometh,'' starring
Kevin Spacey, said this week that orchestra seats for the
ballyhooed revival, which opens in April at the Brooks Atkinson
Theater, would go for a single crisp C-note. Other tickets will go
for $50, and 100 seats for each performance will cost $20.
</P>
<P>
   The hefty price stems from the show's length, Azenberg said. At
four hours, ``Iceman'' will require overtime for backstage staff;
the length has also limited the number of weekly performances to
seven, as opposed to the Broadway standard of eight, cutting
revenue. The show's set, by Bob Crowley, will also require
producers to lose about 100 seats.
</P>
<P>
   The price also reflects the modern economics of Broadway. The
show will cost $1.5 million to mount, and about $225,000 a week to
run. Even paying the 19-member cast Equity minimum _ Spacey will
make only $1,100 a week _ the producers need to make a profit of at
least $100,000 to break even over the limited 12-week run. ``This
is expensive, and it has a short life,'' Azenberg said. ``I can't
be accused of trying to make a profit.''
</P>
<P>
   The first Broadway play to reach the $100 mark was ``Nicholas
Nickleby'' in 1981. ``Miss Saigon'' also had $100 tickets during
its first year, and a few shows now offer equally expensive
packages, with amenities like champagne at preshow receptions.
</P>
<P>
   TRAGEDY'S HAPPY TURN
</P>
<P>
   Before a review runs or a bottle of opening-night champagne
flows, the producers of ``The Blue Room,'' the scantily clad David
Hare drama at the Cort Theater, can declare themselves in
possession of the season's first unqualified hit.
</P>
<P>
   With the play's star, Nicole Kidman, on the cover of Newsweek,
advance sales topped $4 million this week, an almost unheard-of
figure for a straight play. About 95 percent of the 10-week run is
sold out, with the only tickets remaining in the second balcony,
and after Jan. 23.
</P>
<P>
   But if the reason for the ``Blue Room'' mania is transparent, a
more traditional success story was brewing at the Barrymore
Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Buoyed by strong reviews last Friday in The New York Times, The
New York Post and elsewhere, ``Electra'' had $305,000 in ticket
sales that day alone. The day before, the show took in a a measly
$22,000.
</P>
<P>
   The box office continued to hum, and by Thursday producers were
predicting their tally for the week would top $1 million. Not bad
for a play with a small Broadway budget of $800,000 and weekly
running costs of about $150,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody said doing Greek tragedy on Broadway is absolutely
mad,'' said Eric Krebs, one of the play's producers. ``And it is.
But everything has fallen into place.''
</P>
<P>
   The reaction has inspired talk of an extension for the show and
of Tonys for the cast, which is led by Zoe Wanamaker. Krebs said
the show was very likely to extend past its scheduled Jan. 17
close, though he would not say for how long.
</P>
<P>
   One complication is that the Barrymore, owned by the Shubert
Organization, is expected to welcome another play, ``The Visitor,''
in February. But this week, that show's star, Eli Wallach, said he
was uncertain about its prospects this season. ``I don't even know
what's going on, and I'm in it,'' Wallach said.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Schoenfeld, chairman of the Shubert Organization, said
Wednesday that he was committed to ``The Visitor,'' but stopped
short of confirming its run in the Barrymore. As for ``Electra,''
Schoenfeld said it would have a home.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Krebs said he'd talked to Schoenfeld about other Shubert
theaters. And if the ``Visitor'' is postponed, ``Electra'' could
conceivably extend at the Barrymore until late March, when the
producers of another David Hare play, ``Amy's View,'' hope to move
in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know yet where it will be,'' Krebs said. ``But it
will be.''
</P>
<P>
   ROUNDABOUT SOLUTION
</P>
<P>
   The Roundabout Theater will soon inform subscribers that the
last show of the season will be a non-Roundabout production:
``Death of a Salesman,'' the Goodman Theater revival opening on
Feb. 10 at the Eugene O'Neill Theater.
</P>
<P>
   The subscribers had been expecting a revival of ``Sweet Bird of
Youth,'' opening in June. But Ellen Richard, general manager of the
Roundabout, said the show was canceled because of the uncertainty
surrounding the company's current home at the Criterion Center,
which was scheduled to be the site of a new building for Random
House.
</P>
<P>
   That deal unraveled earlier this week, but Ms. Richard said the
Roundabout had decided to play it safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're being conservative rather than risk there being a big
problem and us trying to desperately find a theater,'' she said.
``Plus we think it's a great show.''
</P>
<P>
   The theater will pay more than $1 million to the producers of
``Salesman'' for 40,000 tickets for its members, said Ms. Richard.
</P>
<P>
   PULL UP THE SOCKS!
</P>
<P>
   As erotic as the undressing and dressing may be onstage in ``The
Blue Room,'' the action backstage is considerably less so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Panic,'' said Iain Glen, who like his co-star, Ms. Kidman,
plays five characters. ``A hysterical personality change in 30
seconds flat.''
</P>
<P>
   The play requires four costume changes for each actor, a device
complicated by the much-hyped nude scenes. Why?
</P>
<P>
   Alyce Gilbert, the wardrobe supervisor, explained that because
the actors took their clothes off onstage, they had to forgo
traditional quick change tricks like Velcro ``zippers'' and shirts
sewn into jackets, because they would be visible to an audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything has to be real,'' Ms. Gilbert said.
</P>
<P>
   But this makes for some fumbling with cumbersome fastenings.
When Glen, for example, exits as the character of the playwright to
change into the politician, off goes the frumpy sweater, shirt,
pants, socks, shoes, underwear. (Not always in that order.) And on
comes the slick slacks, silk boxers, designer shoes and socks,
shirt, tie, jacket and wristwatch. Oh, yes, and a new hair style.
All in about 25 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for Glen, the bigger test is the psychological quick
change.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're always taught about preparation and such,'' said Glen,
36, a Scotsman who trained at the Royal Academy of Dramatic Arts.
``But in those moments, it's a free fall.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-98 1816EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
