</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-MODERATES-NY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UPSTATE N.Y. GOP LAWMAKERS UNDECIDED ON IMPEACHMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When the House votes on impeachment next week,
President Clinton's fate may well rest with five moderate
Republican lawmakers from upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   The five _ Reps. Benjamin Gilman, Sue Kelly, Sherwood Boehlert,
John McHugh and James Walsh _ are among the 34 or so Republicans
whose votes on impeachment remain in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the five represent the largest geographic
concentration of undecided votes in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Their districts cut a swath through New York City's Westchester
County on the south to the St. Lawrence River and the Canadian
border on the north. They represent GOP-leaning rural and
small-city constituencies that have not gone down the same
hard-conservative path that some Republican districts in the South
and West have.
</P>
<P>
   With the GOP dominating the House 228-206 (and one independent
who usually votes Democratic), Republicans need 218 votes to pass
an impeachment resolution.
</P>
<P>
   For this reason, each of the New York lawmakers can expect a
deluge of phone calls in the coming days as White House operatives
and GOP congressional leaders vie for their loyalties.
</P>
<P>
   Two Republicans from Long Island, Rick Lazio and Michael Forbes,
also are undecided. And three New York Republicans _ Jack Quinn and
Peter King of Long Island and Amo Houghton of northwestern New York
_ have said they will oppose impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   None of the five upstate lawmakers responded to telephone
interview requests Thursday. Kelly, whose district runs from
Westchester County through Dutchess County, ``will wait for the
Judiciary Committee to complete its work and wait until all the
facts are presented,'' said her spokesman, Drew Cantor.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh, whose district centers around Syracuse and Cortland, has
actually made up his mind, said his spokesman, Jim O'Connor, but is
adhering to a request of Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde
not to make a public commitment until the committee winds up its
work.
</P>
<P>
   For Gilman, impeachment ``is no different from any other vote,''
said Robert Becker, his chief of staff. ``He takes a deliberative,
independent-minded approach to every issue that comes before him.''
</P>
<P>
   Press aides to Boehlert and McHugh said they are undecided on
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   While upstate voters generally are not as liberal as their
counterparts in New York City, they tend not to be hardline
conservatives either, according to Jeffrey Stonecash, a political
scientist at Syracuse University.
</P>
<P>
   Upstate voters are independent-minded, he said, adding that 25
percent of voters in the Syracuse area are registered independents.
</P>
<P>
   For upstate lawmakers, ``this is a real chancy vote,'' said
Stonecash, who has done polling for Walsh. ``This isn't like voting
on some gas tax. It may stay out there as an issue. You don't know
if it's going to go away ... This is a tough one.''
</P>
<P>
   Upstate polling on impeachment reflects national trends showing
voter antipathy to impeachment and a strong percentage favoring
some kind of congressional censure, Stonecash said.
</P>
<P>
   Some upstate Republican leaders voiced qualms over impeachment.
For instance, Robert Cardillo, Oneida County Republican chairman,
said, ``I hear a lot of street talk and people are saying `let's
move on' and `we don't want to hear this anymore. However we can
expedite this, let's expedite it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Martin Donnelly, Delaware County GOP chairman, said that while
something must be done to ``restore respect and honor to the
presidency,'' few people he talks to want an impeachment. ``It's
bad for the country, bad for the American people,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
