<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON WILLING TO ACCEPT CENSURE, NOT PUBLIC CONFESSION
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton is ready to accept a toughly
worded congressional censure, but is not ready to answer the calls
of moderate Republicans for a public confession to avoid
impeachment, a White House spokesman said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president is open to an idea of censure put forward in
good faith that is reasonable,'' said Joe Lockhart, the
presidential press secretary.
</P>
<P>
   But Lockhart said he was not aware of any plan for Clinton to
make a public address on the issue, which some wavering Republican
House members say would make it easier to cast their vote against
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Such members, including Brian Bilbray of California and Rick
Lazio of New York, have urged the president to abandon his
legalistic defense and publicly confess that he lied under oath
about his affair with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would have to recognize the violations of law that have
occurred,'' said Rep. Mark Foley, R-Fla., comparing the president
to a criminal defendant who throws himself on the mercy of the
court for a reduced sentence.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton were to make a new public statement, few expect it
before next week. The president leaves for the Middle East on
Saturday and is due to return late Tuesday. House members have been
advised that debate will begin next Thursday on impeachment
articles that the House Judiciary Committee is expected to approve
this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Some, therefore, see Wednesday as the most likely date for a
speech, if the White House still deems one necessary to influence
the impeachment vote. Clinton's attorneys are advising against an
address, because the very admissions that could help sway House
members could increase his vulnerability to criminal prosecution
after he leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   At his White House briefing, Lockhart said presidential aides
had begun calling both Democratic and Republican House members to
push for a floor vote on censure.
</P>
<P>
   He said the administration believes there should be a vote on
``something that gives members a choice, members who believe that
there should be some recognition of the president's behavior, but
believe, as we do, that these allegations fall well short of
impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has not personally made any of these calls to lobby
members, Lockhart said, but ``I can't rule out that that may be
something he'll do in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   While demurring on the specific wording of a Democratic proposal
to censure Clinton for making ``false statements concerning his
reprehensible conduct with a subordinate,'' Lockhart said such a
reprimand was ``generally'' acceptable to the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president believes that people who in good faith come
forward with a reasonable solution to put this matter behind us, in
a prompt way, short of impeachment, should be considered,'' he
said. ``And looking at that proposal, I think it meets the
criteria.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lockhart would not declare flatly that the president would
sign this proposed censure _ a requirement of the Democratic
proposal _ or to accept all the wrong-doing that it specifies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that he's sat down and looked at it word by word,
line by line, and said, 'This is definitely something that's
acceptable','' Lockhart conceded. ``I just wanted to give you some
sense from the White House point of view about this proposal,
because it'll go before the committee.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said he did not know how much the president would
personally be involved in the effort to avoid impeachment in the
next few days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not aware that he's spoken to any of the members who are
undecided,'' said Lockhart. ``We have got a lot going on. We have
got a big trip coming up. He is certainly aware of this, takes some
time to get briefed, but hasn't had a chance to watch much of it.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Clinton would never give up the fight to retain his
office, but did not say where the campaign will next lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we will judge our efforts here both by what we view as
what's appropriate and what's effective,'' said Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Lipman of The Palm Beach Post contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
