<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SABBATH11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SABBATH IMPEACHMENT VOTES CAUSE JEWISH MEMBER DISCOMFORT
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If the House Judiciary Committee's impeachment
votes carry over into Saturday, Rep. Robert Wexler faces an
uncomfortable choice: participate in the votes and violate his
observance of the Jewish Sabbath, or observe the Sabbath and
neglect his congressional duties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm uncomfortable with having to work on the Sabbath, (but)
there is no question where I need to be this Friday night and
Saturday. I need to be part of the Judiciary Committee and the
debate on impeachment,'' said Wexler, a Florida Democrat who is one
of President Clinton's staunchest advocates on the panel.
</P>
<P>
   Wexler, a member of an Orthodox synagogue, said he tries to
observe the Sabbath commandant of not working or riding from
sundown Friday to sundown Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   While declaring that he does not consider himself an expert on
Jewish laws and customs, Wexler said he believes there is an
allowance in Jewish tradition for public officials to perform their
duties on the Sabbath.
</P>
<P>
   Six of the 15 Democrats on the Judiciary Committee are Jewish.
None of the Republicans are Jewish. In addition to Wexler,
spokesmen for four of the members _Reps. Barney Frank of
Massachusetts, Howard Berman of California, Charles Schumer of New
York and Steven Rothman of New Jersey _ said voting on Saturday
would not cause a religious conflict for them. A spokesman for Rep.
Jerrold Nadler of New York could not be contacted.
</P>
<P>
   Wexler said he did not seek to delay votes on Saturday and did
not feel there was any attempt by the Judiciary Committee chairman,
Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., to be disrespectful of Jewish members.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is any conspiracy of neglect or
purposefulness in trying to do things on Jewish holidays,'' Wexler
said. ``It would be unfair of me or anyone else to make that
allegation of Mr. Hyde or any of the Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Jews bristled in September when the Judiciary Committee
decided to release the tape of Clinton's Aug. 17 deposition on Rosh
Hashana, the Jewish New Year and one of the holiest days on the
Jewish calendar. Like the Sabbath, it is supposed to be observed by
not working, riding, or watching television.
</P>
<P>
   After a series of marathon committee hearings this week, Wexler
said he doesn't fault Hyde for trying to press for a final vote as
quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``This committee has been going day and night all week, and if
it could be done by Friday sundown, it would be done,'' Wexler
said. ``I can't fault the chairman. It would be unrealistic to
expect the impeachment of the president to be based on the Jewish
calendar.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
