<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOOD-FOOTBALL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLOODED TOWN FINDS RELIEF, HOPE IN ITS FIGHTING GOBBLERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MacCORMACK  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CUERO, Texas _ In the future, 1998 will be grimly remembered
here as the year of the Great Flood, when a third of the town was
inundated and hundreds of people were left homeless.
</P>
<P>
   But depending on what happens Saturday at the Houston Astrodome,
a footnote may be added, one to be savored as a bright spot in a
bleak year.
</P>
<P>
   At the Astrodome, the Cuero High School Gobblers (11-3 this
season) face the Aledo High School Bearcats (13-1) for the Class 3A
Division I crown. Flood or no flood, football is serious business
in small-town Texas, and for Cuero, the game is an escape for a
community that is still struggling to get back to normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We estimate probably half the team was flooded out, and the
staff had four or five members who were also,'' Cuero coach Mickey
Finley said at a midweek practice.
</P>
<P>
   With three state championships already, the quarter-final finish
last year and regular playoff success, expectations are very high
for the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very excited. The whole high school is decorated inside.
I think they'll do good. They really want it bad,'' said Jessica
Brennan, 14, a Cuero High School freshman.
</P>
<P>
   For Cuero, which is 85 miles southeast of San Antonio, a fourth
state crown couldn't come at a better time.
</P>
<P>
   The mid-October floods that swept through South Texas affected
many communities, but none as brutally as Cuero, a town of 6,700
that lies along the Guadalupe River.
</P>
<P>
   Here, the Guadalupe rose to record levels in record time and
swallowed up unsuspecting neighborhoods miles from its channel.
With almost no warning, few people saved anything but themselves.
</P>
<P>
   City officials said 1,076 homes _ more than 40 percent of the
housing _ were damaged, and 643 were destroyed. A preliminary
estimate shows the floods reduced the city's $132 million tax base
by 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   And because of the housing shortage, scores of families have
abandoned Cuero. The school district lost more than 40 students.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have five campuses, and every campus lost kids. The special
education campus was flooded, and the students have been
temporarily placed at other campuses,'' said Maggie Martinez,
secretary to Superintendent JohnHall.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father-in-law and sister-in-law lost everything. He just
moved back into his house, but my sister-in-law and her family are
living with me. We went from a family of three to a family of 10,
and everyone is in that situation,'' Martinez said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, nearly two months after the flood, the affected
neighborhoods remain nearly deserted, with scattered cleanup and
construction crews the only signs of life.
</P>
<P>
   Some wrecked houses remain at peculiar angles, just as the flood
waters left them. Many yards and street corners are still piled
high with debris. In a gravel pit west of town, 4,000 truck loads
of debris have been dumped, with much more to come.
</P>
<P>
   Christine Barfield, 41, whose home of 17 years was damaged, said
she understands how football can help.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids can't even go home to where they used to live. Half
of them are piled up in people's apartments,'' she said. ``They
want to win. It sure takes their minds off a whole lot of
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   The coach said this year's squad is considered the underdog to
Aledo, a town of about 1,400 some 15 miles west of Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people are probably favoring them, but I don't think our
players believe that. These guys have a chance to put themselves in
a pretty elite group,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Finley agreed that the Gobblers' performance this season has
probably helped the town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think its kind of a release for people. Some of them look at
bad things all day long. You worry about money. You don't know
where you're going to live,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then on Friday nights you can go out for two or three
hours, and put it all out of your mind.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
