<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOTHS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Insecticide sprays aim to permanently ground pesky gypsy moth in
South
 &HT;    By John Harmon
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The gypsy moth, that bane of the Northeastern forests
for a century, has munched its way southward and for the third time
this decade has infested an area of North Georgia's mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Federal and state forestry officials plan the aerial spraying in
April of biological insecticides across some 30,000 acres of rugged
and picturesque mountains along the Georgia-North Carolina border
near the tourist town of Highlands, N.C. The area includes the
remote Ellicott Rock Wilderness in Rabun County, Ga., as well as
parcels in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Without the spraying, foresters fear, the caterpillars of the
exotic pest will within a few years begin to ravage the majestic
hardwoods in and around Highlands.
</P>
<P>
   Introduced into Massachusetts in 1869, the European insect has
slowly spread its territory and now is found in large numbers as
far south as the Virginia-North Carolina line. Each spring when the
caterpillars hatch, they devour hardwood leaves, especially oaks,
and have defoliated large tracts of forests in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   The recent outbreak in the Highlands area was first detected in
1996. Foresters think this isolated outbreak resulted from either
egg masses or moth cocoons that became attached to camper vehicles
in the Northeast and were left behind by visitors to Highlands.
</P>
<P>
   Foresters said that since oaks are the dominant tree of the
Southern Appalachians and produce acorns essential to wildlife, the
moth infestation could cause serious ecological problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had several of these outbreaks in the Southeast over the
years, but this one in the Highlands area is one of the worst
examples we've seen,'' said Jeff Witcosky, an entomologist with the
U.S. Forest Service who is coordinating the control effort. ``It's
spreading very rapidly.''
</P>
<P>
   The $1 million-plus attack on the gypsy moths will be overseen
by the Forest Service, chiefly because most of the land infected is
within the national forests of the three states.
</P>
<P>
   Twice before in the mountains of North Georgia_near Helen in1992
and near Blue Ridge in 1994_isolated infestations of the moths have
been eradicated by spraying the biological controls. ``We're going
to keep trying to stamp it out here in Georgia every time we find
it,'' said Terry Price, chief of pest control for the Georgia
Forestry Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike chemical insecticides that can poison all insects and
many other creatures, the biological agent kills only moth and
butterfly larvae. Commonly known as BT, the agent has been used for
years to control garden cabbage worms.
</P>
<P>
   But even this environmentally friendly insecticide has its down
side. Other butterfly or moth caterpillars merging at the time of
the spraying will be killed. Two rare species of butterfly are
thought to be present in portions of the spray area.
</P>
<P>
   To protect those butterflies, the Forest Service is considering
using two other biological controls that kill only gypsy moths.
Those controls are Gypchek, a virus that infects gypsy moths, and
Disrupt II, a compound that interferes with the mating of adult
gypsy moths.
</P>
<P>
   Those controls are not as effective as BT and will likely be
used only in areas where the butterflies would be endangered and in
the wilderness area, Witcosky explained.
</P>
<P>
   Because of these efforts and due to the devastation the moths
can inflict, the spraying campaign has the backing of several
environmental groups that focus on National Forest issues. Those
include Georgia ForestWatch, Friends of the Mountains and the
Chattooga River Watershed Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The result of doing nothing will be a loss of (tree) diversity
in the forest,'' said James Sullivan of ForestWatch. ``We think the
impact of doing nothing is worse than spraying these biological
controls.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
