<HEADLINE>
TEXAS HUNTERS DWINDLING IN NUMBER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARRY SHLACHTER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LLANO, Texas _ Despite a cold, autumn drizzle, a crowd quickly
circled Joe W. Self, an off-duty deputy sheriff from East Texas,
after he parked his pickup bearing a large antlered buck.
</P>
<P>
   A standout hunting season was less than two weeks old. Business
had been so overwhelming in this Hill Country county, whose
abundant game has earned it the title ``the deer capital of
Texas,'' that butcher Bryan Miiller has been turning away clients
after accepting more than 600 field-dressed deer for processing on
opening weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of lost track of my days,'' said Miiller, 36. ``It was
the best first weekend since we've been here _ - 13 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunting, in economic terms, is booming in Llano County.
</P>
<P>
   However, wildlife officials and others who follow the sport say
all is not well beyond the deer blind.
</P>
<P>
   The number of Texans who hunt has dropped 18 percent in the past
10 years. The decrease is even larger, 31 percent, when the state's
17 percent population growth is factored in.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those crowding into hunting hot spots like Llano are
coming from other parts of Texas or other states, having been
driven from their traditional hunting land by urban sprawl or
soaring lease costs.
</P>
<P>
   Some see a crisis looming for a sport long associated with the
Lone Star identity. Also at issue is the future direction of the
Texas Parks and Wildlife Department, which derives nearly 60
percent of its budget from hunting and fishing licenses and, in
turn, spends a good portion of its budget on measures aimed at
enhancing hunting and fishing conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's integral to our Texas heritage,'' says Jerry Warden, 51,
executive director of the San Antonio-based Texas Youth Hunting
Association, which was started four years ago in an attempt to
reverse the trend. ``It's part of our history, part of our culture,
and we need to retain it.''
</P>
<P>
   In rural East Texas, where children once learned to hunt a
decade before they learned to parallel park, sales of hunting and
fishing licenses have plummeted _ by 34 percent in Trinity County,
46 percent in San Jacinto County, 27 percent in Angelina County.
</P>
<P>
   Even in Llano, an area strongly identified with deer hunting,
license sales have declined.
</P>
<P>
   A July study by Texas A&AMP;M University found a myriad of social
and economic causes, including:
</P>
<P>
   _ The state's increasing urbanization.
</P>
<P>
   _ Competition from other leisure activities.
</P>
<P>
   _ The reluctance of women and minorities to fill a gap left by
fewer white men who are hunting.
</P>
<P>
   _ The rising cost of hunting leases.
</P>
<P>
   Other wildlife experts cite the loss of traditional hunting
areas to urban sprawl and the growing number of children raised by
single mothers, who don't hunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hunting can never go back to the way it was because we have a
society that has changed so dramatically,'' said Clark Adams,
director of human dimensions in wildlife management research at
Texas A&AMP;M's Department of Wildlife and Fishery Sciences in College
Station.
</P>
<P>
   The state's fast-growing minority population is less prone to
hunt. Hispanics comprise about 26 percent of the state's population
but represent just 8.6 percent of its licensed hunters.
African-Americans comprise about 12 percent of Texans but just 2.6
percent of licensed hunters, according to the Texas A&AMP;M study by
Myron F. Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   But demographics explains only part of the decline.
</P>
<P>
   Adams, who began hunting ``as soon as I could carry a .22''
rifle, has backed off from the sport for many of the reasons that
have sidelined others. ``I just lost my interest in it because it's
so darn hard to find a place to hunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you or your relatives own land, you're set,'' the Texas A&AMP;M
professor said. ``One-third of the hunting population will have
problems with access as more land is sold for development, more
land is fragmented into little rancheros sold by the square inch.''
</P>
<P>
   As hunting is made more difficult and more expensive, people
will weigh their leisure options, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is the best possible investment for your recreational
dollar if you're an urbanite with $1,000 in discretionary money?
Use it for a hunting lease or for a golf club membership?''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the loss of veteran hunters through natural
attrition. The average age of Texas hunters was 36 in 1974. By
1996, it had risen to 41, according to Parks and Wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   And there are gender issues.
</P>
<P>
   Men are introduced to hunting in their youth by fathers, older
brothers or other male relatives, the Texas A&AMP;M scholar said.
``Females, for the most part, are recruited by their spouses or
significant others later in life _ their mid-20s,'' he said.
Generally, ``if the family doesn't hunt, the female doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest hurdle is finding accessible and affordable
places to hunt.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
