<HEADER>
A3692 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-WEEKEND-850&AMP;ADD-NY     12-10 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-850&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE TEMPEST': PROSPERO ON A BAYOU BEFORE THE STORM  
 `THE CATER STREET HANGMAN' 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes for `Tempest' are at end of review. Time,
channel are for New York area. Check local listings.) 
(bl)  
By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For its next reality special, maybe NBC could produce a live,
on-air book-burning. That would be right in line with what they've
done to the classics this season. For a blip of time, after the
success of several bookish, special-effects-laden films
(``Gulliver's Travels,'' ``The Odyssey'' and ``Merlin'') the
network turned to literature for inspiration. That may sound
high-minded, but the results might have played better as a satire
called ``Books Go Hollywood.''
</P>
<P>
   First there was ``Crime and Punishment,'' plodding but nothing
to be ashamed of. When the film got dismal ratings, NBC declared it
was reassessing future literary adaptations. That Dostoyevsky's
dark psychological work was falsely hyped as a tale of lurid
suspense and romance apparently meant nothing. NBC was determined
not to let any more sneaky dead writers destroy its ratings, so the
network yanked ``The Tempest'' from its original slot in the
high-stakes sweeps month of November, and dropped it into this
weekend, when people are presumably too busy with the holidays to
notice.
</P>
<P>
   This ``Tempest'' is a clunker, but don't blame Shakespeare, who
can sleep peacefully knowing he has a minimal connection to the
project. Half-baked in its conception and direction, it is a
colorful but mush-brained version that takes Shakespeare's basic
story and characters and drops them into a Mississippi bayou during
the Civil War era. Along the way it drops Shakespeare's language
entirely.
</P>
<P>
   Now the magical Prospero is a Mississippi plantation owner named
Gideon Prosper, played by Peter Fonda. In 1851, as he says when
setting the leaden tone at the start, he was ``unaware of the
tempest that was coming.'' Gideon spends his time learning voodoo
from a slave named Ezeli (Donzaleigh Abernathy) and leaves the
running of the plantation to his vile brother, Anthony (John
Glover), who forces Gideon, his daughter, Miranda (Katherine Heigl)
and Ezeli's son, Ariel (Harold Perrineau Jr.) into exile.
</P>
<P>
   Gideon describes their new home as ``my sanctuary, a tiny island
in the bayou protected by snakes and alligators.'' The island is
also the home of the uncivilized character Shakespeare knew as
Caliban. Here he is the Gator Man (John Pyper-Ferguson), brutish
but not naturally evil; he simply has not made the acquaintance of
Miss Manners.
</P>
<P>
   None of these changes are outrageous. It would have been daring
for a network to have kept Shakespeare's language; the success of
Baz Luhrman's MTV-style film, ``Shakespeare's `Romeo and Juliet'''
proves the language is not box-office poison (though having
Leonardo DiCaprio speak it definitely lessens the risk). Yet even
in the realm of the loosely adapted, this ``Tempest'' is pallid.
</P>
<P>
   The battle between Gideon and Anthony echoes the
brother-to-brother battles of the Civil War in the most ham-fisted
way. And without Shakespeare's poetry, these characters are mere
outlines.
</P>
<P>
   The film is most disappointing because there are glimpses of
potential that quickly flicker away. Though his Southern accent
sways in and out, it is easy to see what Fonda might have done with
a more focused production. Here he can only hint at the character
of a man who wrong-headedly isolates his beloved daughter and must
finally surrender her back to the imperfectly civilized world. And
there is no sense that his magic goes beyond special effects.
</P>
<P>
   They are, at times, striking. Gideon conjures a fierce storm:
leaves swirl, wind and rain are gradually whipped into a true
tempest. Ezeli can see visions in pools of water, and at one point
her face appears to Gideon within the giant flames of a fire. But
the effects always seem dropped in, detached from character and
story.
</P>
<P>
   The only wholly successful element is Perrineau, whose unlikely
Ariel is no sprite but a believable flesh-and-blood individual, a
slave caught in a powerful struggle for freedom. Better known as
the wheel-chair-bound inmate and narrator of the scathing HBO
series ``Oz,'' Perrineau has a greater challenge here; he must make
Ariel more than a heavy-handed metaphor for slavery.
</P>
<P>
   When Anthony is tossed ashore on Gideon's island, the Civil War
plot becomes central and the themes even more labored. ``No magic
can stop a bullet,'' Anthony growls. Of course, he's wrong;
Gideon's special effects can do wonders. The true magic of poetry
is what's missing from this ``Tempest.''
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE TEMPEST'
</P>
<P>
   NBC, Sunday at 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   (Channel 4)
</P>
<P>
   Written by James Henerson and based on the story by William
Shakespeare. Jack Bender, director; Steve Shaw, director of
photography; Stephen Storer, production designer; James Bigwood,
producer; Todd Sharp and Ronna Slutske, co-producers. Produced by
Bonnie Raskin Productions in association with NBC Studios. Bonnie
Raskin and Jack Bender, executive producers.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Peter Fonda (Gideon Prosper), John Glover (Anthony
Prosper), Harold Perrineau Jr. (Ariel), John Pyper-Ferguson (Gator
Man), Katherine Heigl (Miranda), Eddie Mills (Frederick Allen),
Dennis Redfield (Willy Gonzo) and Donzaleigh Abernathy (Ezeli). &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   `The Cater Street Hangman'
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;E, Sunday at 9 p.m. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Based on an Anne Perry mystery novel, ``The Cater Street
Hangman'' is more modest than ``The Tempest'' in its ambition and
literary source, but infinitely more satisfying.
</P>
<P>
   Set in foggy Victorian London, the film is a luxurious tale of
romance, class and murder. When a series of young servant women are
strangled on posh Cater Street, the handsome police inspector
Thomas Pitt (Eoin McCarthy) investigates. At the Ellison household,
the indignant and proper Edward (Peter Egan) sends Pitt around to
the servants' entrance, but he gets a warmer reception from
Edward's lovely, headstrong daughter, Charlotte (Keeley Hawes).
</P>
<P>
   Pitt's carefully tousled hair and Charlotte's independent spirit
mark them as our contemporaries, ahead of their time in the 19th
century and clearly meant for each other. Their romance and the
unwinding mystery make this film smartly entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
