<HEADER>
A3694 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-HUNTING-2ndTake     12-10 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-HUNTING-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
LLANO, Texas: places to hunt. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At Cooper's Old Pit Barbecue, a Llano institution where
2-inch-thick pork chops are served on butcher paper, a throng in
hooded sweat shirts or camouflage jackets talked of drawing a bead
on a trophy buck.
</P>
<P>
   At one long table, three men and a teen-ager sat down for their
evening meal after arriving from Brownsville. High costs had driven
them from South Texas, where a weekend hunt can range from $1,000
to $7,500, they said. And that's just for access.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before firing, you have to turn to your guide and ask, `How
much is that going to cost me to shoot?''' said George Dominguez,
40, a school district administrator. ``It could be another $3,000
for a trophy deer,'' he said, referring to a buck with antlers
large enough to merit mounting or a place in the record books.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to have the bucks, and a middle-class worker can't
afford a $3,000 hunt,'' said Dominguez, whose group paid $250 each
for a three-day hunt. ``So people from South Texas are moving to
Central Texas.'' They in turn are displacing residents who had
hunted locally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been priced out of hunting,'' said G.R. ``Willie''
Gonzalez, an accountant turned game warden based in Llano.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanying Dominguez was Brownsville architect Stanford
Knowles and his son, Chris, 14, who was on his first deer hunt.
Belying the hopeful view at Parks and Wildlife that if the father
hunts, the heritage will be passed on, Dominguez said his son
turned down an opportunity to join them, asking instead to be
dropped off in San Antonio so he could ``girl watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Zeske of Dallas hunts for free, like many Texans have for
generations. His friend, former Lewisville resident Bob Powers, who
now lives in Alabama, has a scenic, deer-rich Llano County spread
that had been in his wife's family for generations. In exchange for
their help keeping the place in shape, Powers allows his buddies to
hunt without charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average person in Dallas couldn't find a good place to
hunt that he could afford,'' Zeske, 61, a mail-order marketing
consultant and sports memorabilia entrepreneur, said as he and
Powers finished off their morning bacon and eggs. ``If Bob didn't
allow me to come out here, I'd have a hard time.''
</P>
<P>
   In East Texas, the Trinity County judge, Mark Evans, insisted,
``Hunting is as much of being Texan as having been born in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   The 44-year-old judge, himself a deer hunter, was then taken
aback when told that hunting license sales had dropped a third in
his bailiwick during the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   Evans blamed subdivisions built on prime hunting land, pitting
hunter against hunter for smaller acreage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then there's the advent of hunting clubs,'' he said. ``Much of
the land is now leased out to them and many of these people are
from out of the county, some from out of state.''
</P>
<P>
   While the number of resident hunters dropped 18 percent, those
from out of state nearly doubled from fiscal year 1987 to 1997,
from 27,274 to 54,125.
</P>
<P>
   Over in Austin, the Parks and Wildlife Department sees the glass
as half full.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question there's been a decline in the number of
people hunting in Texas and buying licenses,'' said Gary Graham,
chief of its wildlife division. ``We're moderately concerned. We
still have a million people in Texas, more or less, actively
engaged in hunting. That's a substantial constituency base.''
</P>
<P>
   By no means is the department ignoring the issue, Graham said.
</P>
<P>
   It has opened up more than 1 million acres to public hunting for
a nominal $40 fee. Last year, it received 79,029 applications for
2,550 hunt positions distributed on a lottery basis. All
license-carrying youths under 17 can hunt at designated areas free
of charge if accompanied by a fee-paying adult. Only 415 youths
took advantage in 1984; by 1997, the number had increased to 8,206.
</P>
<P>
   Warden's Texas Youth Hunting Association has 500 enrolled in
this season's 40 sponsored hunts, up from 225 participants last
year and 100 the year before. Some 70 percent to 80 percent hail
from hunting families, he said. So, in many cases, the organization
is preaching to the faithful.
</P>
<P>
   Many wildlife experts see hunting in Texas increasingly becoming
a sport of the affluent who are willing to pay top dollar for
trophy game reared on ranches bordered by 12-foot wire fences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hunting is going to change dramatically, with landowners
creating more `high-fence operations' _ walling in deer and calling
it their own,'' predicted Texas A&AMP;M's Adams. ``A guy drives through
a gate, shoots a deer, and that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
