<DOCNO> NYT19981210.0320 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3704 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT11-COX     12-10 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MICROSOFT TRIAL JUDGE PROMOTES INNOVATION
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Why shouldn't Microsoft enjoy the fruits of victory
if it can improve the technology it licensed from a smaller rival,
the judge presiding over the Microsoft antitrust trial asked
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson posed his pointed
question after James Gosling, who created a programming language
known as Java, argued that Microsoft's high command had sought to
undermine the ``write once, run anywhere'' version of Java created
by Sun Microsystems Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``Didn't they simply grasp the significance of what you were
doing and run with that?'' Jackson said, turning to Gosling as he
was about to leave the witness stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``They represented it as better,'' Gosling, who is also Sun's
chief scientist, replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' Gosling added, ``their definition of better is tied
into the Windows platform. If they had technical difficulties with
what we were doing, we would have worked very hard with them to go
through a process of resolving them. But they were trying to force
us to swallow various poison pills. There was no inclination to
discuss it, to say, 'let's work this out.' It was boom _ here it
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who is trying the landmark case without a jury,
appeared somewhat mollified by Gosling's response. ``You were
trying to bring other people along,'' Jackson noted as Gosling
nodded in assent.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the judge's sudden intervention seemed to unnerve David
Boies, the government's lead attorney, who had just told Jackson
that he had completed his response to Microsoft's three-day
cross-examination of the Sun scientist. Instead, Boies rose once
more to hammer home his main points until Jackson, eager to finally
call it a day, said, ``I think you are finished with your
witness.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the courtroom, the normally unflappable Boies sought to
recover from what Microsoft's attorneys clearly took to be a signal
that, after eight weeks of testimony, the trial seemed to be going
their way.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two aspects to the judge's question,'' Boies said.
It reflects a fair point that Microsoft is making in
cross-examination _ one of the things that was going on was
Microsoft's attempt to compete on the merits and come up with
better software. But ... in addition, Microsoft was forcing people
to take its version and preventing people from having access on a
level playing field to the version submitted by Sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``So that if all that was going on in the Java controversy was
Microsoft's attempt to come up with a better version, the judge
would believe, as he indicated in his question, that there's
nothing wrong with simply trying to innovate.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other hand, if the evidence is, as Dr. Gosling
testified, that ... Microsoft attempted to inhibit the distribution
of Sun's cross-platform Java and forced people to take the
Microsoft non-compatible version for the explicit reason of
preserving its monopoly, you probably would not have had Microsoft,
in its internal documents, describing its efforts to 'pollute'
Java.
</P>
<P>
   After 30 trial days, it remains to be seen whether the
government's contention that Microsoft pursued an illegal pattern
of seeking to sabotage any outside technology that might pose a
challenge to its near-monopoly in the operating system for personal
computers will prevail.
</P>
<P>
   The next corporate officer in a parade of witnesses who will try
to make that point will be William Harris, president and chairman
of Intuit Corp. Although Microsoft, which has $17 billion in cash
in its coffers, had sought to buy Intuit, it pulled back with
Justice Department officials signaled they would move to block the
deal.
</P>
<P>
   Harris, however, will not take the witness stand until Jan. 4,
when the trial is scheduled to resume after a holiday break. Next
week's witness will be Princeton computer professor Edward Felten,
an expert on Windows' browsing technology.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
