<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3706 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-DEFENSE-HNS &LR;      12-10 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-DEFENSE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE PREPARES TO FIGHT IMPEACHMENT IN HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House mustered a second line of defense
in the impeachment struggle with Congress Thursday in a effort to
save President Clinton from suffering the humiliation of being only
the second president in U.S. history to be impeached.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its strategy to prevail in the full House, White
House officials endorsed the proposed censure of the president,
laid the groundwork for personal presidential appeals to GOP
moderates and weighed the possibility of a presidential statement
of contrition before an expected House impeachment vote next week.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's aides, conceding they had little hope of dissuading
the House Judiciary Committee from approving one or more articles
of impeachment, focused instead on the showdown next week when some
30 undecided members will decide the verdict by the full House.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Craig, coordinator of the president's effort to combat
impeachment, appealed for members of the full House to keep an open
mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me make just one plea to the members of the House of
Representatives on behalf of the president of the United States,''
Craig said. ``Before you vote to impeach and remove the president,
read the defense of the president.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's team delivered to each of the 435 House members
a 184-page point-by-point rebuttal of allegations against Clinton,
according to White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart. The White
House gave the same rebuttal of House Judiciary Committee members
previously.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said White House counsel Charles F.C. Ruff and Craig
were available to meet undecided lawmakers to help clarify any
questions that might persuade them to decide against impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Senior White House officials unleashed a torrent of telephone
calls to both Republicans and Democrats in an effort to rally
bipartisan support for House consideration of a Democratic motion
of censure when the full House meets next Thursday to debate
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart promised that Clinton would personally sign a censure
resolution and accept the risks of subsequent legal penalties and
fines after leaving office, even if the House failed to approve
articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart conceded, however, that White House entreaties to the
GOP House leadership had yet to win a pledge to permit a censure
vote on the House floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see a commitment now to do that, but I think we will
continue to make the case,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said Clinton had not decided whether to
address the nation prior to the House vote.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton leaves Saturday for Israel and returns to Washington
late Wednesday _ giving him the option of delivering a nationally
televised address next Thursday night _ the eve of the expected
House vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an issue where twisting arms isn't appropriate, but
bending ears is,'' Lockhart said. ``We want people to read the
submission we've made; we want them to look at the facts; we want
them to ask us if there are any questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Suhail Khan, spokesman for Rep. Tom Campbell,
R-Calif., said Republican and Democratic lawmakers had called for
Campbell to talk about his undecided stance on impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   But Khan said Campbell, who is traveling in Africa, had not
spoken to any senior White House staffers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The congressman is still undecided,'' Kahn said. ``He wants to
wait until the inquiry is complete and give the president every
opportunity to rebut any of the accusations that have been made
before making a final decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart embraced the thrust of the censure resolution proposed
by three Democrats on the House Judiciary Committee as an
alternative to impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal by Reps. Rick Boucher, D-Va., Thomas Barrett,
D-Wis., and William Delahunt, D-Mass., calls for Clinton to sign a
censure resolution in which he would admit making ``false
statements'' about his ``reprehensible conduct'' with former White
House intern Monica Lewinsky, admit ``wrongly'' trying to ``delay
discovery of the truth'' and accept the risk of remaining ``subject
to criminal and civil penalties for this conduct'' after leaving
office.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said Clinton had not approved the wording of any
proposed censure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president is looking for a reasonable way to put this
behind us, short of impeachment,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats' censure proposal ``seems to meet the criteria of
people moving forward and making a good-faith effort and being
reasonable,'' Lockhart said. ``I don't know that he's sat down and
looked at it word by word, line by line, and said, `This is
definitely something that's acceptable.'''
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., worked to shore
up Democratic ranks with telephone calls to the 31 Democrats who
had voted with Republicans to approve an open-ended impeachment
inquiry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-98 1831EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
