<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3711 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDUCATION-TEXAS-1211-     12-10 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUCATION-TEXAS-1211-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REPORT SHOWS TEXAS SCHOOLS IMPROVING
 &HT;    630 words
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By NICHOLE MONROE
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- Texas schools have steadily boosted student math
scores, participation in math and sciences, parental involvement
and teacher training, according to a national report released
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 National Goals Report released by the National
Education Goals Panel gives U.S. states a snapshot of how much
their students are improving compared with others across the
country. Texas was one of the most improved states.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton in a written statement said he was pleased
with the nation's progress, but it ``still has a long way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I will continue to press Congress to help give our students
smaller classes, well-prepared teachers and modernized school
buildings,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   States were evaluated in eight areas: children's readiness for
school, graduation and dropout rates, academic achievement, teacher
education, international standing in math and science, adult
literacy, school safety and parental participation in schools.
</P>
<P>
   In each area, states were evaluated on several factors. The
following are highlights:
</P>
<P>
   The number of Texas fourth- and eighth-graders who are at least
proficient on the math section of the National Assessment of
Educational Progress has increased. The NAEP measures student
ability on three levels: basic, proficient and advanced. Proficient
students demonstrate competency over challenging subject matter and
are well prepared for the next level of schooling.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1992 and 1996, the number of proficient fourth-graders
jumped from 15 percent to 25 percent, compared with an increase
from 18 percent to 21 percent nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1990 and 1996, the number of proficient eighth-graders
increased from 13 percent to 21 percent, compared with an increase
from 15 percent to 24 percent nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Panel members attributed the increase in achievement to the
Texas Assessment of Academic Skills, which students are required to
take.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Texas and North Carolina, the leaders recognized very early
that their economic success was dependent on the success of the
students in their schools,'' said James Hunt, governor of North
Carolina. ``They're using appropriate tests to measure how students
and schools are really doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, more Texas students are receiving degrees in
mathematics and science, including women and minorities. Between
1991 and 1995, the number of women receiving degrees in mathematics
and science increased from 29 percent to 34 percent. The number of
minorities receiving such degrees increased from 35 percent to 37
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, 37 percent of women and 40 percent of minorities
received such degrees in 1995. Texas also has done a better job in
supporting new teachers, according to the report. In 1994, 30
percent of teachers participated in formal induction programs,
compared with 22 percent in 1991. Nationally, 27 percent of
teachers participated in such programs in 1994. Parents in Texas
are having more of an influence on school policy than before. In
1994, 24 percent of public school principals said parent
associations have influenced school policy, compared with 14
percent in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the goals panel said they hope the report will help
states improve their practices and encourage them to become more
competitive internationally.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's often said that there's no problem in American education
that is not already solved in some American school or school
system,'' said panel chairman and West Virginia Gov. Cecil
Underwood. ``The pressing need is to discover those practices that
are working and the lessons we can all learn as we strive to
improve achievement and opportunities in our own communities.''
</P>
<P>
   To view the National Education Goals report on the Internet,
visit the panel's Web site at (http://www.negp.gov).
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
