<HEADLINE>
DESIGNER BILL BLASS, 76, SUFFERS MILD STROKE IN HOUSTON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: New York) 
 
By LINDA GILLAN GRIFFIN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ New York designer Bill Blass was admitted Thursday
morning to Methodist Hospital after suffering what doctors
described as a mild stroke.
</P>
<P>
   The 76-year-old designer was in Houston to attend a benefit
luncheon for the Museum of Fine Arts. Blass will remain in
Methodist's Intensive Care Unit for further tests and at least 24
hours observation.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Chu characterized Blass' problem as a TIA _ transient
ischemic attack _ or a mini-stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Blass said that he woke up in his hotel room about 4 a.m.
feeling ill. He later had breakfast in the hotel with longtime
friend and public relations consultant Helen O'Hagan, then appeared
at a breakfast for local clients at Saks and conducted at least one
interview before deciding to seek medical attention.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston event, sponsored by Saks Fifth Avenue, went on
without Blass, as models showed his Spring/Summer 1999 collection.
</P>
<P>
   Known for his humor and sarcasm, Blass quipped on the his way to
the hospital, ``At least I don't have to see that collection
again.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he has felt fine recently except for some problems with
what he described as possibly pinched nerves in his legs.
</P>
<P>
   While he was having trouble putting some words together,
according to doctors, immediate tests indicated that there appears
to be no evidence of paralysis or other lasting damage.
</P>
<P>
   The designer said in an afternoon interview from his hospital
bed that he had emerged from the MRI testing unit to find a priest
waiting in the hallway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you here for me?'' Blass said he asked the priest.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I don't think so,'' the priest replied, much to the
designer's relief.
</P>
<P>
   At 76, Blass is considered one of the premier U.S. fashion
designers and one of the first designers to establish New York as
the sportswear capital of the world.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years he has cut back on the number of days he spent
in his New York studio, preferring his country estate and the
company of his dogs instead.
</P>
<P>
   Blass also confirmed that in recent months he has been trying to
sell his company.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the camels hair jackets, cashmere sweater sets, finely
tailored suits, basic black dresses and luxury evening wear he
designed, Blass is also known for many licensed products
manufactured under his name, licenses that have numbered in the
40s. These include not only items such as belts, scarves, bags,
sunglasses, fragrances and household linens, but Bill Blass
outfitted Lincoln Continentals and a recent line of home
furnishings.
</P>
<P>
   He dresses celebrities such as Barbara Walters, Nancy Kissinger,
Angelica Huston, Veronica Hearst, the editors of Harper's Bazaar
and Vogue, and former first ladies Nancy Reagan and Barbara Bush.
Recently a younger generation, led by their mothers' examples, has
increasingly beat a path to his door.
</P>
<P>
   Blass is his own best publicist, joking and gossiping in his
deep, booming voice. A generous man known for his love of antiques
and books, he has served on the board of the New York Public
Library to which he donated $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   He served three and a half years in the U.S. Army during World
War II, before turning to designing on New York's Seventh Avenue,
and his was one of the first names of U.S. designers to be
recognized abroad.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
