<SLUG> BC-AMC-COCHAIRMAN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMC ENTERTAINMENT CO-CHAIRMAN RESUMES TREATMENT FOR ESOPHAGEAL
CANCER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER MANN  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Stan Durwood, co-chairman of AMC
Entertainment Inc., has started treatment for a recurrence of
esophageal cancer that was first detected in early 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Durwood, 78, plans to remain active in the day-to-day operations
of the Kansas City company while undergoing radiation treatment,
AMC spokeswoman Brenda Nolte said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   News that Durwood is again undergoing medical treatment renewed
speculation that AMC, one of the nation's largest theater
companies, will become an acquisition target. AMC shares gained 1
7//8 Wednesday on the American Stock Exchange and closed at 18
7//8, up 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The same stock run-up occurred the first time AMC revealed
Durwood had cancer, on Jan. 10, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But Nolte said the scenario was different this time.
</P>
<P>
   When Durwood was first diagnosed with cancer, the company
created a succession plan, which included naming Peter Brown as
president of AMC Entertainment and Phil Singleton as president of
American Multi-Cinema Inc., the operating division of AMC.
</P>
<P>
   Then in May 1998, Brown was named co-chairman of AMC.
</P>
<P>
   ``All our major shareholders understand that management
succession is in place,'' Nolte said. ``That puts us in control of
our own fate and our own destiny.''
</P>
<P>
   The news should not affect the Power &AMP; Light District proposed
for downtown Kansas City. The entertainment and retail project, a
longtime dream of Durwood's, is being developed by Centertainment,
a subsidiary of AMC.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Kansas City Tax Increment Financing Commission
approved the formal agreement with Power &AMP; Light LLC. The agreement
now goes to the Kansas City Council for approval.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement puts into writing all the conditions the
commission and the City Council had said must be met before the
city puts any public money into the $454 million project that could
revitalize a large section of downtown.
</P>
<P>
   The project would rely on an estimated $176 million in
city-assisted financing supported in part by tax increment
financing. That allows developers to use a part of new real estate
taxes created by a project to help pay for improvements.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-98 1839EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
