A3729 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TWA-PLANES-KAN &LR;      12-10 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TWA-PLANES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWA TO BUY 125 PLANES FROM BOEING, AIRBUS IN MOVE TO MODERNIZE
FLEET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDOLPH HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Trans World Airlines has agreed to acquire 125 new
planes for its fleet, the biggest aircraft order in the company's
history.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the estimated $3.9 billion order, which includes
an option on 125 additional planes, TWA will receive 50 narrow-body
jets from the Boeing Co. and 75 later from Europe's Airbus
Industrie.
</P>
<P>
   The order continues a modernization effort by the struggling
airline that will cut the average age of its planes by more than
half. But the upgrading of the fleet _ at one time the oldest in
the industry _ has raised concerns about the fate of TWA's overhaul
base in Kansas City, which employs more than 2,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald L. Gitner, TWA's chairman and chief executive officer,
said the new aircraft would reduce the average age of TWA's planes
from 19 years in 1996 to 11.3 years by January 2000. As more new
planes arrive and older ones are replaced, the average age of a TWA
jet is expected to drop to 7.3 years by 2007.
</P>
<P>
   Delivery of the 50 Boeing 717-299 aircraft will begin in
February 2000, replacing TWA's DC-9 fleet. TWA will then begin
taking delivery on 50 of Airbus' new planes, the A318, in 2003. An
additional 25 Airbus planes from its A320 series will begin being
delivered in 2005.
</P>
<P>
   TWA already is scheduled to receive 37 previously ordered planes
from Boeing in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The new aircraft are medium-range jets with about 110 seats. TWA
said the Boeing 717 would save the airline 35 percent in operating
costs over the DC-9s it now operates.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will give TWA a modern fleet that is second to none,''
Gitner said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   How TWA's new planes will affect its maintenance operations has
been the subject of much speculation. Employment at TWA's overhaul
base in Kansas City has shrunk in recent years, and local union
officials are concerned about what will happen to workers as the
newer planes require less maintenance. For instance, the Boeing
727, one of the oldest planes still operating in the industry, will
be retired from TWA's fleet by the end of next year.
</P>
<P>
   TWA has about 3,650 employees in Kansas City, including about
2,200 at its overhaul base. TWA's lease with the city on its Kansas
City facilities expires in May 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Gitner declined to comment on the new order's effect on TWA's
maintenance operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the process of evaluating that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But establishing a modern fleet, Gitner said, ``can only bode
well for all TWA employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Gitner said that the new orders would give TWA an opportunity to
expand operations in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would be able to go into a growth mode by the year 2001,''
he said. ``But that would depend on the economy at that time, the
competition, etc.''
</P>
<P>
   The Machinists union, which represents about 16,500 TWA
employees, declined to comment on TWA's aircraft order Wednesday
because of its contract talks with the company. If no progress is
made during a current series of meetings, the National Mediation
Board could allow a 30-day countdown to begin, after which the
union would be able to strike.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, union officials have criticized TWA's strategy of
shrinking the airline, particularly its international operations,
and focusing more on its St. Louis hub. Union officials were vocal
after TWA lost money in its third quarter, a period in which most
other airlines reported record profits.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts commended TWA's latest aircraft acquisition, saying
that the airline must continue its strategy of trying to become a
carrier for business travelers with a Midwestern hub.
</P>
<P>
   TWA declined to discuss the financing of its two orders
Wednesday, except to say the planes would be leased and not owned.
That will require less cash from the airline.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Boyd, president of Aviation Systems Research Corp. in
Golden, Colo., said TWA probably got bargain deals from Boeing and
Airbus, both of which have experienced slow sales on the aircraft
involved.
</P>
<P>
   The Boeing 717 and Airbus 318 are about the same size, Boyd
said, and any disadvantages of acquiring similar aircraft from two
manufacturers were more than offset by the cost savings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think TWA found two manufacturers that were desperate to get
some sales in the books,'' he said. ``I bet TWA whipsawed
them...and got excellent deals from both of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Boyd said the airline would have to change and modernize its
fleet for its business plan to work in the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is definitely positive for TWA,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But other analysts continue to wonder about TWA's long-term
prospects. After emerging from two bankruptcies in the 1990s, TWA
remains strapped for cash and continues to have problems posting a
profit, as the last quarter showed. The company has had only two
profitable quarters in the past two years and has poor credit
ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Beyer, editor of Avmark Inc.'s industry newsletter, said TWA
eventually might have to find a partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, we've been saying that for years, and they've
managed to stay independent,'' he said. ``Maybe TWA will survive as
the smallest of the major carriers.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyer said TWA was ordering planes now in anticipation of the
next upturn in the airline industry's economic cycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something they have to do,'' he said. ``TWA is hoping
that they are timing the market so that when these new planes
arrive, the industry will be in the midst of a travel boom so they
can pay for them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-98 1841EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
