<SLUG> BC-CHILDREN-GUNS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OWNER OF GUN USED BY BOY IN FATAL SHOOTING MAY FACE CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE LAMOY  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Kan. _ Forty-three percent of the American
households with children have guns, according to a survey taken
last month. One of those houses sits atop a hill in Kansas City,
Kan.
</P>
<P>
   In that house last Friday, 10-year-old Derrick Morris was shot
once in the face. He died before police arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Derrick's 12-year-old cousin has been charged as a juvenile
with involuntary manslaughter. He was released from custody
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   And Wyandotte County District Attorney Nick Tomasic said charges
may be filed against whoever left that gun in a place where
children could get to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't locked up, we know that,'' Tomasic said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The tragedy occurred just after 8 p.m. Friday in the basement of
the small house after Derrick and his cousin apparently found a
revolver. The gun belonged to one of the adults who lives at the
house, police said.
</P>
<P>
   No adults were home at the time of the shooting, but a
6-year-old child and 4-month-old infant also were at the house.
</P>
<P>
   Police said that the victim and his cousin were playing with the
revolver, a weapon without a safety lock. Originally, the officers
who investigated the shooting said Derrick's death appeared to be
an accident.
</P>
<P>
   But Tomasic said that under the law, a child who commits a crime
for which an adult would be charged, also may be charged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something has to be done,'' Tomasic said. ``This definitely
was a reckless killing.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the outcome of the criminal case involving the
12-year-old boy, Derrick's shooting underscores the need to secure
guns inside homes, said law enforcement officials and an emergency
room physician at Children's Mercy Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (guns) are not doing you any good when you're not at
home,'' said Kansas City, Kan., Detective William Howard Jr. ``You
need to lock them up and secure them when you're not there.''
</P>
<P>
   Guns in a household should be treated like any other potential
hazard for youngsters, said Howard and others. For example, adults
routinely keep medicines and toxic cleaning supplies out of
children's reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't leave our keys in the car when we're not at home,
even if the car's in the garage, so that the kids won't drive
off,'' Howard said.
</P>
<P>
   Parents also should make sure no guns are left unsecured in
households where children visit, said Denise Dowd, an emergency
room physician who works with the Center for Childhood Safety at
Children's Mercy Hospital in Kansas City, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   Besides finding that 43 percent of the households in America
with children ages 3 to 17 have guns, a Peter Hart Research
Associates survey found that the guns were kept loaded at least
some of the time in 23 percent of those households.
</P>
<P>
   Dowd suggests that parents telephone before sending their
children to an unfamiliar household to make sure that guns are
locked up. Dowd admits that making that call can be difficult
because of shyness about invading privacy and the
sometimes-political issue of gun ownership. Nevertheless, she
recommends a bold approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guns are very intriguing and very attractive to kids,'' Dowd
said. ``All we're talking about is keeping kids safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Among other precautions:
</P>
<P>
   - Keep all guns unloaded and locked up away from the ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   - Don't leave keys to gun closets where children can find them.
</P>
<P>
   - Teach children not to touch guns and to tell an adult
immediately if they find a gun, even if it's in someone else's
house.
</P>
<P>
   - Children in households with firearms should participate in
hunter safety or gun safety courses.
</P>
<P>
   - Familiarize youngsters with firearms to discourage curiosity
and fascination.
</P>
<P>
   - Teach youngsters three basic rules: Assume all guns are
loaded; never put a finger on the trigger; and never point a gun.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-98 1842EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
