<HEADER>
A3742 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATWORK-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      12-10 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATWORK-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR MANY WORKERS, BAD BOSSES OVERSHADOW GOOD TIMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Wouldn't want the happy hustle of the season to put a
rosy glow on the workplace. No, sir. There are plenty of unhappy
workers out there.
</P>
<P>
   Did you know that you couldn't even get on the {disgruntled.com}
Internet site this week? Its server was so overloaded by so many
teed-off workers trying to feed it or read it that it temporarily
shut down.
</P>
<P>
   What's the deal? Times are good. Why are so many people so
alienated, so eager to share tales of workplace revenge taken
against bad bosses?
</P>
<P>
   Here's a Letterman-like list of reasons I hear and see. They're
printed partly to commiserate but mostly to plead with those who
have the power to make needed changes.
</P>
<P>
   Remember: Times are good. Good people can get good jobs
elsewhere. They will leave _ they are leaving _ unfulfilling,
unhappy workplaces.
</P>
<P>
   And then employers wonder why their costly turnover rates are
high.
</P>
<P>
   The gripes:
</P>
<P>
   10. Managers that play obvious and undeserved favorites.
</P>
<P>
   9. Staffs downsized so far that employees think they can never
catch up.
</P>
<P>
   8. Lack of up-to-date, efficient, ergonomic and appropriate
tools to do the job.
</P>
<P>
   7. Inadequate time or money compensation for the added strain of
on-the-job traveling.
</P>
<P>
   6. Too many, too long and too unproductive meetings.
</P>
<P>
   5. No format _ indeed, no welcome mat _ for ideas from the front
line to be shared with management.
</P>
<P>
   4. A widening gap between executive salaries and others' pay.
</P>
<P>
   3. One-size-fits-all annual staff evaluation forms that provide
little individual recognition or timely feedback.
</P>
<P>
   2. Company budget tightening that eliminates employee
recognitions (parties, gifts, awards and so forth) while the bosses
still have big expense accounts and club memberships.
</P>
<P>
   1. Managers who are stingy with public praise but quick with
public criticism.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, this must be said: Good workplace relationships are
a two-way street. Shirking, irking workers don't deserve rewards.
They deserve the boot. Appeals for recognition apply only to those
who perform honestly and well.
</P>
<P>
   But remember: Several years of annual average raises that barely
crept ahead of inflation have not left a cushion of good will.
Workers who have performed honestly and well complain that their
rewards haven't been much greater than those who barely toed the
line.
</P>
<P>
   It's sad when the good performers need disgruntled.com, too.
</P>
<P>
   Swearing update: In this column last week, I wrote about Charles
Corry, a Colorado man who swore excessively at work. Complaints
from a Christian co-worker about Corry's taking the name of the
Lord in vain contributed to his firing.
</P>
<P>
   Corry, who testified that he was a Buddhist, sued on the basis
of religious discrimination. He contended that his supervisor told
him the Ten Commandments were followed in that workplace. The
company disputed his account.
</P>
<P>
   After a six-day trial in Denver, a federal jury this week
decided that Corry had been wrongfully fired. Because of
``intentional interference with his work contract,'' he was awarded
$34,160 in lost wages and emotional distress.
</P>
<P>
   The jury ruled against Corry, though, on his allegation of
religious discrimination.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
