<SLUG> BC-VETERAN-FUNERAL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD WAR I VETERAN REMEMBERED AS MAN WHO `LIVED TO THE FULLEST' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By OSCAR AVILA  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEVADA, Mo. _ Life was a long walk for McKinley Wooden. Friends
say he lived at a steady pace, standing straight and tall, always
moving forward.
</P>
<P>
   In World War I, his battery walked 100 miles through the
blood-soaked fields of France. As a cattle rancher, he would stride
through his lots for hours. When a young neighbor got fidgety, he'd
say: ``Walk, don't run.''
</P>
<P>
   His life's journey took him all over the world, but it ended
Wednesday where it began 103 years ago. He was buried in a Vernon
County field, less than 10 miles from his birthplace.
</P>
<P>
   Most didn't make it as far as he did. No relatives. No former
mates from his Army battery, not even commanding officer Harry S.
Truman.
</P>
<P>
   He outlived them all.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a life lived to the fullest,'' said the Rev. Leonard W.
McIntire, a friend of 14 years.
</P>
<P>
   Some joined his journey near the end. For that, they were sad.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Richard Kempker met Wooden on Veterans Day when he
received the French Legion of Honor at the Liberty Memorial in
Kansas City. Kempker now commands Wooden's old unit, Battery D of
the Missouri National Guard's 129th Battalion.
</P>
<P>
   Wooden, who lived in Lee's Summit, Mo., couldn't get up from his
wheelchair. He sat as rigid as a statue while the medal was placed
around his neck. Dignified. This was the man, after all, whom
Truman had described in a letter as ``the straightest, stiffest
soldier I have.''
</P>
<P>
   Kempker and Wooden, two Missouri farm boys 72 years apart,
swapped stories. Kempker invited him to the battery post in
Independence. They were going to wait until spring when it got
warmer.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Kempker stood as rigidly as Wooden used to while the
current members of Battery D carried his casket to the cemetery.
Kempker saluted the casket with a white-gloved hand as a bugler
played taps. The grass reflected in his polished black shoes.
</P>
<P>
   As his mates fired rifles in a salute, Kempker didn't flinch. He
stared at the casket, draped in an American flag.
</P>
<P>
   Then he closed his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just thinking that I wished I'd known him better,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
