<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE POLITICS OF A SENATE TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ New York Republican Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, who was
defeated for re-election last month, is neither a sweet guy nor a
fan of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But nobody ever said he was stupid. So when he warned this week
that a House impeachment of Clinton would be a self-defeating,
``grave mistake'' for his party, it was worth noting.
</P>
<P>
   It is one thing for the president's Democratic defenders to
argue that a prolonged trial in the GOP-controlled Senate triggered
by a House impeachment would be a political disaster not only for
the country but for the party in charge. They are naturally
predisposed to paint a grim picture to save Clinton further legal
liability and embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   But it is quite another thing when a dedicated Republican
partisan like D'Amato sees it as a political calamity as well.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato himself was burned two years ago by displaying excessive
zeal as chairman of a Senate committee investigating charges that
the president and first lady were involved in a corrupt Whitewater
land speculation deal and covered it up. The hearings ended
inconclusively, having proved nothing. Polls showed 55 percent of
those surveyed disapproved of the partisan way D'Amato handled the
sessions. Even 4 out of 10 Republicans disapproved of his conduct.
</P>
<P>
   What D'Amato is saying now is so obvious the wonder is that it
doesn't seem to have occurred to more than a handful of other
Republicans. House GOP leaders are virtually in hiding, washing
their hands of the whole affair and pretending only House Judiciary
Committee chairman Henry Hyde has a duty to deal with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the Senate to spend weeks and weeks mired in this doesn't
make sense,'' D'Amato says. In his mind, House approval of any
impeachment articles ``would result in great and unnecessary
discord.''
</P>
<P>
   Such discord is already here. It is the chief consequence of the
partisan posturing in the House committee, where the anti-Clinton
outcome is preordained. No member of either party is listening to
the debate, despite serious disputes about the evidence and the
process.
</P>
<P>
   No minds are being changed. There will be no crossing of party
lines for anything so flimsy as principle or conscience. Chairman
Hyde, once highly respected, has only a 31 percent favorable rating
in this week's CNN/USA Today/Gallup poll.
</P>
<P>
   The committee subscribes to the flippant Gerald Ford theory that
an impeachable offense is whatever they decide it is. That is not
the way most Americans think the constitutional system ought to
work.
</P>
<P>
   After the Judiciary Committee votes to impeach, the House will
be recalled next week to pass judgment on the president's conduct
and the committee's verdict. The seriousness of this act is not
reflected in the time expected to be spent on this issue. One hour
of debate is the current estimate!
</P>
<P>
   That casual approach demonstrates beyond a doubt the real truth
of this ugly episode. It is not rooted in the law, despite all the
pretense to the contrary. The law is fuzzy and can be interpreted
to suit its manipulators. Except for the perjury question, the
charges against the president spring mainly from investigators'
rage that he failed to passively confess to everything they
suspected.
</P>
<P>
   This is only about hard-edged politics. But politics is a
two-way street.
</P>
<P>
   The danger to Republicans of continuing this farce is that the
public may conclude the GOP majority is unable to meet its
responsibility to govern. The party seems accountable only to its
own conservative furies, not to the country _ which statistically,
remember, is only about one-third Republican.
</P>
<P>
   In the November election and the public opinion polls, a
majority of voters have made it clear they do not want Clinton
kicked out of office for lying about sex. His job approval rating
is in the upper 60s, where it has remained all during the scandal.
A CNN/USA Today/Gallup poll this week showed 59 percent of those
surveyed do not believe he deserves impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   What voters really want is national bipartisan cooperation on
the basic economic and social issues before the country. This has
worked for the popular moderate GOP governors and for the
president, who talks a real good game on this subject. But we don't
hear it from the impeachment-oriented GOP congressional leadership.
</P>
<P>
   For any semblance of credibility, a Senate trial would have to
seem fair and garner some Democratic support, which means providing
more opportunity for the White House to present its side than the
House committee has allowed. The president, having selfishly
decided not to resign, can be counted on to fight this every way he
can.
</P>
<P>
   That means calling as witnesses Monica Lewinsky, Linda Tripp and
other dreary participants, rehashing in person all the repulsive,
prurient details we have heard on tape. It could go on for months.
It wouldn't be pretty, and most folks would blame the Republicans
for forcing it upon the world.
</P>
<P>
   Barring some unanticipated smoking gun, in the end Clinton will
still be president. There is no two-thirds majority to convict him
in the Senate. The circus will have been for nothing, except to
expose the arrogance of the clowns.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a good prescription for consolidating and enlarging
the GOP congressional majority in the 200O elections.
</P>
<P>
   The House Judiciary Committee is deaf to this reality. It cares
not a twig about history or the political swamp it is leading the
Republican Party into. The question now is whether a majority of
the full House has more common sense. If it does, it will vote to
censure Clinton instead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-98 1845EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
