<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-VIDEO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPEACHMENT HEARINGS ENTER THE VIDEO AGE 
</HEADLINE>
   A News Analysis  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In defending President Clinton, lawyer Abbe Lowell
treated the House Judiciary Committee Thursday to a slick,
MTV-style video show aimed at viewers at home as well as members of
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   During his two-hour presentation, Lowell used four video screens
in the committee hearing room to jump quickly from subject to
subject, patching previously unpublicized video excerpts of
Clinton's testimony in the Paula Jones case and snippets of earlier
testimony by Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   The Lowell extravaganza even had a video segment showing only a
tape recorder while the audio carried the voices of Linda Tripp and
Monica Lewinsky talking about the definition of sex.
</P>
<P>
   The show appeared to rivet the attention of the committee
members and the jammed hearing room, often eliciting laughter from
the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone, Lowell's Republican counterpart, David
Schippers, countered with his own video show that presented Clinton
as a scheming conspirator who deserved to be removed from office.
But it was Lowell's fast-paced presentation that appeared most
geared toward attracting the all-important television audience
outside the committee room.
</P>
<P>
   He provided the cameras with a bevy of sound-bites such as
``impeachment is the political equivalent to the death penalty''
and ``As my daughter would say, `duh.''' His props included a stack
of transcripts that Lowell said reflected the witnesses whose
testimony he would use during his presentation.
</P>
<P>
   Using a bit of Perry Mason gimmickry, Lowell announced at the
start of his presentation that he would call witnesses to the stand
to prove the president was innocent. He said those witnesses
included Monica Lewinsky, Betty Currie, Vernon Jordan, Tripp and
Clinton _ then hastened to add that these people would not be there
in person but instead would appear before the committee through
their prior video testimony, audio transcripts and written
responses.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the segments were less than a minute or two, with many
brief enough to be played by television stations in their entirety.
</P>
<P>
   One video showed a recent interview with former Rep. Peter
Rodino, D-N.J., chairman of the Judiciary Committee during the 1974
Watergate hearings. On the video, Rodino said the impeachment
process must be bi-partisan, a characteristic that so far has
eluded these hearings.
</P>
<P>
   One video segment was a collage of Starr testifying before the
committee last month and responding to committee questions with
such answers as: ``I don't recall'' and ``I don't remember.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowell used the segment to counter Republican allegations that
Clinton was actually lying when he gave such answers as ``I don't
recall'' or ``I don't remember'' in his sworn testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The video drew laughter from the audience and several Republican
committee members.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Republican committee members conceded that Lowell had
produced an eye-catching show.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to look great on camera,'' said Rep. Ed Bryant,
R-Tenn., adding that Lowell was ``selling his case to the American
public, not Republican committee members.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican counsel Schippers also employed videos to help his
case.
</P>
<P>
   One video used a collection of clips from Clinton's deposition
in the Jones case to show the president repeatedly saying he had no
recollection of being alone with Lewinsky despite the fact the two
had engaged in oral sex on several occasions.
</P>
<P>
   Other segments showed the president giving evasive answers to
questions about calls he made to Lewinsky or his conversations with
Currie.
</P>
<P>
   And like Lowell, Schippers used plenty of sound-bites,
including: ``Truth is not decided by the outcome of polls'' and
``Conspirators don't just specifically say to each other, `Go in
and lie.'''
</P>
<P>
   But Schippers workman-like pace and nearly three-hour
presentation seemed better suited to a courtroom than Court TV.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
