<HEADER>
A3761 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDUCATION-FLORIDA11-C     12-10 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUCATION-FLORIDA11-COX-1st </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    1st LEDE WRITETHRU-
 &HT;    EDS: SUBS grafs 7-9 to define NAEP profiency standard and
clarify that percentages in math scores denote students at least
proficient.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    REPORT SHOWS FLORIDA SCHOOLS IMPROVING
 &HT;    630 words
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By NICHOLE MONROE
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Florida schools have steadily boosted college
enrollment and improved eighth-grade math scores and teacher
training, according to a national report released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 National Goals Report released by the National
Education Goals Panel gives U.S. states a snapshot of how much
their students are improving compared with others across the
country.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton in a written statement said he was pleased
with the nation's progress, but it ``still has a long way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I will continue to press Congress to help give our students
smaller classes, well-prepared teachers and modernized school
buildings,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   States were evaluated in eight areas: children's readiness for
school, graduation and dropout rates, academic achievement, teacher
education, international standing in math and science, adult
literacy, school safety and parental participation in schools.
</P>
<P>
   In each area, states were evaluated on several factors. The
following are highlights:
</P>
<P>
   The number of Florida eighth-graders who were at least
proficient on the math section of the National Assessment of
Educational Progress has increased, though the numbers continue to
lag behind the nation. The NAEP measures student ability on three
levels: basic, proficient and advanced. Proficient students
demonstrate competency over challenging subject matter and are well
prepared for the next level of schooling.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, 17 percent of eighth-graders were at least proficient
in mathematics, compared with 12 percent in 1990. Nationally, 24
percent of eighth-graders were at least proficient in math in 1996,
compared with 15 percent in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Florida fourth-graders who were at least proficient in math has
remained constant at 15 percent from 1992 to 1996, while math
proficiency among fourth-graders nationwide increased from 18
percent in 1992 to 21 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, more Florida students are receiving degrees in
mathematics and science, especially women.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1991 and 1995, the number of women receiving degrees in
mathematics and science increased from 29 percent to 32 percent.
However, the number of minorities receiving such degrees decreased
from 36 percent to 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, 37 percent of women and 40 percent of minorities
received such degrees in 1995. Florida has become one of the
nation's leaders in support programs for new teachers, according to
the report. In 1994, 48 percent of teachers participated in formal
induction programs, compared with 42 percent in 1991. Nationally,
27 percent of teachers participated in such programs in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The state also was highlighted in a ``Promising Practices''
report for its progress in increasing college enrollment. In 1994,
50 percent of high school students enrolled in college, compared
with 45 percent in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Many attribute the rise in college enrollment to the Florida
Bright Futures Scholarship Act. Under this provision, Florida high
school students who are enrolled in a college-preparatory program
and achieve at least a 3.0 grade point average receive a 75 percent
discount on tuition at any of the state's colleges or universities.
Students with at least a 3.5 grade point average may receive full
scholarships and a book allowance.
</P>
<P>
   The news isn't all good. The report showed more Florida teachers
report classroom disruptions that interfere with learning. In 1994,
48 percent of teachers made such reports, compared with 42 percent
in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the goals panel said they hope the report will help
states improve their practices and encourage them to become more
competitive internationally.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's often said that there's no problem in American education
that is not already solved in some American school or school
system,'' said panel chairman and West Virginia Gov. Cecil
Underwood. ``The pressing need is to discover those practices that
are working and the lessons we can all learn as we strive to
improve achievement and opportunities in our own communities.''
</P>
<P>
   To view the National Education Goals report on the Internet,
visit the panel's Web site at (http://www.negp.gov).
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
