NYT-12-10-98 1858EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981210.0350 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3764 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDEAST-CLINTON     12-10 1269
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-CLINTON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON DEPARTS SATURDAY ON HIGH-RISK MIDDLE EAST JOURNEY.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton leaves Saturday for a three-day
Mideast visit where he will try to salvage the imperiled peace
process amid political and security conditions that are
deteriorating by the day.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the Palestinian-Israeli agreement reached at the Wye
River Plantation in rural Maryland in October, Clinton, who
brokered the deal, vowed to visit Jerusalem and
Palestinian-controlled Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   ''The president's agreement to the trip was an important part of
the agreement made at Wye
</P>
<P>
   River,'' said White House spokesman Joe Lockhart. ''He believes
that the trip is important to moving the
</P>
<P>
   process forward, to implementing the Wye River accords, and he's
doing it in the best interests of the peace process.''
</P>
<P>
   That process, though, is in tatters.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's in very, very bad shape,'' said former State Department
Middle East specialist Charles Hill. ''There is no negotiation,
there is violence, there is terrorism, there is disarray.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton didn't know in October that his visit would be preceded
by a week that began with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
narrowly averting or perhaps merely postponing a political coup
that could bring down his government. The week is has seen some of
the most widespread Palestinian-Israeli confrontations in months.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian protesters have hurled rocks and taunted Israeli
soldiers across the West Bank this week. Thousands of Palestinians
marched Thursday in the funeral procession of a 17-year-old stone
mason, Jihad Iyad, who was killed on Wednesday by Israeli army
gunfire, the Associate Press reported.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton didn't know, either, that he'd be traveling as the House
Judiciary Committee debates and votes on articles of impeachment
against him stemming from the Monical Lewinsky sex-and-deception
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   By Thursday, expectations for Clinton's visit were so low that
some analysts were questioning whether he should go at all.
</P>
<P>
   ''This trip is probably not desirable and it's not going to be
what it was designed to be when it was agreed, and yet we're
trapped into it,'' said Hill, diplomat in residence at Yale
University. ''I think that the best thing the president can do is
to get through it without doing more damage.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton hopes for more than that, and some analysts believe more
is essential.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've got to provide all the cotton we can to be sure this
fragile egg doesn't turn into an omelette,'' said Emory University
Mideast politics and history professor Kenneth Stein, speaking of
the Wye agreement. ''And it is a fragile egg.''
</P>
<P>
   In his visit with Netanyahu on Sunday, Clinton hopes to persuade
the Israeli leader to move forward with promised troop deployments
from the Israeli-occupied West Bank. Netanyahu promised at Wye to
pull back from an additional 13 percent of the West Bank territory,
but after a troop withdrawal last month he suspended further
pullouts in the face of escalating Palestinian attacks against
Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   A bulls eye for Clinton would be a promise by Netanyahu to lift
his suspension and go forward with pullouts scheduled for next
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu, though, is in a tight box.
</P>
<P>
   Hard-liners in his conservative Likud political party are
outraged at the pullouts. Many regard Wye as a sell-out of Israeli
security and some have threatened to abandon him in parliament,
where Netanyahu's coalition governs with a razor-thin majority.
</P>
<P>
   Moderates, at the same time, are losing patience with him for
precisely the opposite reason. They claim Netanyahu is dragging his
feet on a comprehensive peace process that began five years ago
with a signing of the Oslo peace accords on the White House lawn.
It quickly bogged down amid fresh violence on the streets and the
assassination of Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin, who had
signed the Oslo accords with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu has survived more than 20 attempts to unseat him in
his brief two and a half years in office. He could face renewed
attempts within a week.
</P>
<P>
   His situation is so tenuous that he suggested earlier this week
that Clinton might best stay home. But by Thursday Netanyahu made a
perfunctory statement suggesting that Clinton is welcome.
</P>
<P>
   The reluctance stems from Clinton's plan to visit
Palestinian-controlled Gaza on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu fears the president's visit to Arafat's territory will
be hailed in Gaza as the legitimization of Palestinian sovereignty
just one step away from endorsing Palestinian statehood.
</P>
<P>
   The mere prospect sets teeth on edge in Israel, which sees the
subject of a Palestinian state as a matter to be discussed only in
the context of so-called final status talks, aimed at a
comprehensive Mideast peace.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will see this odd spectacle of Palestinians dancing in the
streets for an American president, and Israelis demonstrating
against him,'' predicted Middle East expert William Quandt, who
served on President Jimmy Carter's National Security Council.
''This is such a volatile situation that I think they're almost
going to have to play this as they go.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton hopes to throw Netanyahu a bone from Gaza, where he
plans a speech before the Palestinian National Council.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat agreed five years ago to remove from the Palestinian
charter all of the calls for the destruction of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Whether he's done so is in dispute, but Israel isn't satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat agreed at Wye to invite the more than 700 members of the
Palestinian National Council to Gaza for a meeting Monday to take
up the matter. So far fewer than half have agreed to show up. Many
are expatriates and some are guerrilla fighters more inclined to
fight Israelis than to negotiate with them.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to finesse the standoff, Arafat led a sub-group of his
allies the Palestine Central Council in a vote Friday to declare
null and void all charter references to Israel's destruction. It
isn't clear whether that will satisfy Netanyahu's threat to hold
further West Bank withdrawals in suspension until the full national
council votes to rescind the offending clauses.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton urges Netanyahu to accept Arafat's approach, he'll
have something to help the bitter medicine go down.
</P>
<P>
   He has asked Congress for an additional $1.2 billion in U.S. aid
to Israel next year _ on top of the $3 billion in economic and
military aid that's already planned.
</P>
<P>
   The additional money, Clinton claims, is justified to help
Israel in the adjustments it needs to deploy from the West Bank and
other measures required to keep peace alive.
</P>
<P>
   He's also asked Congress for $400 million in Palestinian aid _
on top of $100 million already planned.
</P>
<P>
   To help sell the program to Congress, Clinton is bringing along
more than a dozen members of Congress _ a large delegation for such
a trip.
</P>
<P>
   The question, though, is whether even those billions and all the
rest of the influence Clinton can bring to bear can help salvage
peace from a region mired in street violence and political turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   ''Clinton can bring some glue to the Wye agreement,'' said
Emory's Stein, who has just completed a book, entitled ''Heroic
Diplomacy'' on three decades of attempts to make peace in the
Mideast. ''The problem is that when he leaves, the glue dries and
it comes unstuck again. The Wye agreement didn't renew the trust or
change the habits of the heart of the people who signed it.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
