<SLUG> BC-EDUCATION-GEORGIA11-COX-1ST </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 LE &HT;    1st LEDE WRITETHRU-
 &HT;    EDS: SUBS 8th graf to define NAEP profiency standard and clarify
that percentages in math scores denote students at least
proficient.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    REPORT SHOWS GEORGIA SCHOOLS MISSING MARK
 &HT;    660 words
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By NICHOLE MONROE
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Georgia schools need to decrease classroom
disruptions, improve teacher education and boost minority
participation in math and science, according to a national report
released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 National Goals Report released by the National
Education Goals Panel gives U.S. states a snapshot of how much
their students are improving compared with others across the
country.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton in a written statement said he was pleased
with the nation's progress, but it ``still has a long way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I will continue to press Congress to help give our students
smaller classes, well-prepared teachers and modernized school
buildings,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While the report shows more Georgia students are attending
college and more mothers are receiving prenatal care, minority
participation is still an uphill battle, and fewer teachers hold
certificates in the subjects they teach.
</P>
<P>
   States were evaluated in eight areas: children's readiness for
school, graduation and dropout rates, academic achievement, teacher
education, international standing in math and science, adult
literacy, school safety and parental participation in schools.
</P>
<P>
   In each area, states were evaluated on several factors. The
following are highlights:
</P>
<P>
   While the number of students who were at least proficient on the
math section of the National Assessment of Educational Progress
increased nationally from 18 percent to 21 percent between 1992 and
1996, Georgia achievement remains stagnant at 13 percent. The NAEP
measures student ability on three levels: basic, proficient and
advanced. Proficient students demonstrate competency over
challenging subject matter and are well prepared for the next level
of schooling.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, most states have increased the number of minorities
who receive degrees in mathematics and science, while Georgia
numbers have decreased. In 1995, 43 percent of minorities received
those degrees, compared with 44 percent in 1991. Nationally, 40
percent of minorities received the degrees in 1995, compared with
39 percent in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The number of teachers holding a certificate in their main
teaching assignment also is dropping in Georgia and the nation. In
1994, 94 percent of Georgia teachers had certificates, compared
with 98 percent in 1991. Nationally, that number decreased from 94
percent to 93 percent.
</P>
<P>
   More Georgia teachers are reporting that students disrupt
classroom instruction. About 46 percent of teachers said these
disruptions interfered with instruction in 1994, compared with 37
percent in 1991. Those percentages were the same for the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The news isn't all bad. Georgia made more progress than any
other state in increasing the percentage of mothers who receive
prenatal care. In 1996, 85 percent received care, compared with 73
percent in 1990. Nationally, 82 percent received care in 1996,
compared with 76 percent previously.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say prenatal care is important to student achievement
because children who are born healthy perform better in school.
</P>
<P>
   The state also was highlighted in a ``Promising Practices''
report for its progress in increasing college enrollment. In 1996,
56 percent of high school students enrolled in college, compared
with 54 percent in 1992. The report also showed that community
college enrollment jumped 25 percent between 1990 and 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Many attribute the rise in college enrollment to the HOPE
scholarship program started in 1993. Under this provision, Georgia
high school students who earn a B average or better receive free
tuition to any of the state's colleges or universities.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the goals panel said they hoped the report would help
states improve their practices and encourage them to become more
competitive internationally.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's often said that there's no problem in American education
that is not already solved in some American school or school
system,'' said panel chairman and West Virginia Gov. Cecil
Underwood. ``The pressing need is to discover those practices that
are working and the lessons we can all learn as we strive to
improve achievement and opportunities in our own communities.''
</P>
<P>
   To view the National Education Goals report on the Internet,
visit the panel's Web site at (http://www.negp.gov).
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
