A3783 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-DEM11-COX     12-10 0469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-DEM11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PRO-IMPEACHMENT DEMOCRAT NOT SWAYED BY CLINTON DEFENSE
 &HT;    With IMPEACH-REPUB.
 &HT;    By EUNICE MOSCOSO
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Ralph Hall, D-Texas, said Thursday that
President Clinton's defense team did not change his mind on voting
in favor of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty set on the perjury and the fact that it's a felony.
There's not any way hardly to sugar-coat that,'' he said. ``It's
almost an affront to anybody to say that the act that he and the
girl were carrying out was not sex. Give me a break. That's just
not sellable.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's defense, presented this week to the House Judiciary
Committee, offered no new evidence, Hall said. ``I didn't hear any
of them that were witnesses ... that were in the Oval Office at the
time. I don't know what they can say.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall is one of fewer than 10 House Democrats believed to support
impeachment. Because the Republicans hold an 11-seat majority,
Clinton would have to win about 20 Republican votes to avoid
impeachment if Democrats such as Hall stand firm.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer himself, Hall analyzed the defense strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have the law, we argue the law. If we've got the facts,
we argue the facts. If we don't have either one of them, we beat on
the table. ...They've been beating on the table,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hall said the president should have testified before the
committee himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was a lawyer and I had the most persuasive guy in the
world for a client, I'd sure put him on the stand,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Hall said he could understand why Clinton didn't testify.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he testifies anything different now than what he said, then
that's perjury. He's in a bad situation, `` he said. ``But he's
probably the only one that could change anybody's mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall said he has received ``all kinds of calls'' from fellow
Democrats to talk about the impeachment vote. He said he had also
received invitations to the White House, but not to talk directly
to the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would come if he asked me to come over there,'' Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   But he said, ``I don't want to cross-examine the president. I've
read his cross-examination and I think he's been put through
enough,'' Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   Although he doubts anything could change his mind, Hall said he
never says no to evidence.
</P>
<P>
   A simple House majority of 218 votes is enough to impeach
Clinton. If the House approves articles of impeachment, the Senate
would be forced to hold a trial. It takes a two-thirds Senate
majority to convict a president and remove him from office, and few
people believe the Senate, which will have 55 Republicans and 45
Democrats next year, will find the 67 votes needed to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
