<HEADER>
A3784 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-REPUB11-COX     12-10 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-REPUB11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FOLEY SAYS WHITE HOUSE DEFENSE HASN'T PERSUADED HIM
 &HT;    With CLINTON-DEM.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For Rep. Mark Foley, a Republican leaning toward
voting for impeachment, this week's parade of witnesses defending
President Clinton had virtually no effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gave me a chance to look further and more deeply into the
case,'' said Foley, of West Palm Beach, Fla., but ``it hasn't done
much to convince me at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Foley, who has not declared how he would vote on impeachment,
said he is leaning toward supporting the perjury articles prepared
by the House Judiciary Committee and is also seriously weighing the
obstruction of justice article.
</P>
<P>
   While many House members have not declared their intentions,
surveys by several news organizations indicate that Clinton would
have to win the votes of up to 20 Republicans to avoid impeachment,
while no more than half a dozen have said they would vote in his
favor.
</P>
<P>
   Foley, unlike many Republicans, acknowledges that the White
House might be able to persuade him to vote against impeachment
next week. But he said it would require an additional statement
from Clinton acknowledging wrongdoing, comparing the president to a
criminal defendant who throws himself on the mercy of the court for
a reduced sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would have to recognize the violations of law that have
occurred,'' Foley said. ``That would be an essential process for me
to look at,'' he said, although it would ``not be a guarantee''
that he would vote against impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as he continues to go out and have all these people
mount an offensive,'' Clinton appears to be ``an unrepentant person
doing his best to avoid jeopardy, either through an impeachment and
removal from office or from future criminal charges after he leaves
office,'' Foley said.
</P>
<P>
   The second-term lawmaker said he had not been actively lobbied
by either fellow Republicans seeking to impeach Clinton or by the
White House seeking opposition to impeachment. Meanwhile, he said
the dozens of daily telephone calls and the hundreds of e-mail
messages his office receives on the issue continue to run about 70
percent in favor of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Despite testimony from Clinton's defenders that his deposition
answers in the Paula Jones sexual harassment case and his answers
to Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's grand jury did not
constitute perjury, Foley said he was unconvinced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly he was not only evading, but deliberately lying under
oath, `` Foley said, adding that ``when you put your hand on the
Bible (you) must come clean with all the evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Particularly bothering him are Clinton's statements that he
could not recall giving former intern Monica Lewinsky a series of
gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Foley acknowledged that a president might not recall all the
trinkets someone in his position gives away on a daily basis, but
he said it was hard to believe Clinton would not recall giving
Lewinsky such personal gifts as a book of poetry.
</P>
<P>
   Foley said he was also concerned that Clinton attempted to
obstruct justice by having his secretary, Betty Currie, retrieve
the gifts from Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems highly unlikely (Currie would have retrieved the
gifts) without some involvement of the president,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
