<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3785 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDUCATION-OHIO11-COX     12-10 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUCATION-OHIO11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REPORT SHOWS MIXED NEWS FOR OHIO SCHOOLS
 &HT;    580 words
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By NICHOLE MONROE
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ More Ohio students are heading straight to college
and obtaining degrees in math and science, but drug use in public
schools has increased and math test scores remain stagnant,
according to a national report released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 National Goals Report released by the National
Education Goals Panel gives U.S. states a snapshot of how much
their students are improving compared with others across the
country.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton in a written statement said he was pleased
with the nation's progress, but it ``still has a long way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I will continue to press Congress to help give our students
smaller classes, well-prepared teachers and modernized school
buildings,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   States were evaluated in eight areas: children's readiness for
school, graduation and dropout rates, academic achievement, teacher
education, international standing in math and science, adult
literacy, school safety and parental participation in schools.
</P>
<P>
   In each area, states were evaluated on several factors. The
following are highlights:
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the number of eighth-graders who are at least
proficient on the math section of the National Assessment of
Educational Progress increased, but Ohio remained the same. The
NAEP measures student ability on three levels: basic, proficient
and advanced. Proficient students demonstrate competency over
challenging subject matter and are well prepared for the next level
of schooling. Between 1992 and 1996, about 18 percent of
eighth-graders were at least proficient on the test. Nationwide,
that number increased from 15 percent to 21 percent. Overall, more
Ohio students are receiving degrees in mathematics and science,
including women and minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1991 and 1995, the number of women receiving degrees in
mathematics and science increased from 31 percent to 34 percent.
The number of minorities receiving such degrees increased from 36
percent to 37 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, 37 percent of women and 40 percent of minorities
received such degrees in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio also has increased the number of high school graduates who
immediately enroll in college. About 55 percent of students did so
in 1996, compared with 51 percent in 1992. Comparable national data
was unavailable, but Massachusetts did the best of all states at 73
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The news is not all good. In 1997, about 25 percent of students
said they used marijuana at least once in the past 30 days. That
number was up from 16 percent in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   More students also reported that drugs were available on school
property. Between 1993 and 1997, that number increased from 20
percent to 28 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Though no comparable data was available nationally, the Virgin
Islands had some of the lowest percentages of all the states at 15
percent for marijuana use and availability of drugs. Members of the
goals panel said they hope the report will help states improve
their practices and encourage them to become more competitive
internationally.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's often said that there's no problem in American education
that is not already solved in some American school or school
system,'' said panel chairman and West Virginia Gov. Cecil
Underwood. ``The pressing need is to discover those practices that
are working and the lessons we can all learn as we strive to
improve achievement and opportunities in our own communities.''
</P>
<P>
   To view the National Education Goals report on the Internet,
visit the panel's Web site at (http://www.negp.gov).
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
