<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3788 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIRELAND-NOBEL-NYT &LR;      12-10 0470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-NOBEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIMBLE WARNS CATHOLIC MILITANTS IN NOBEL SPEECH 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OSLO, Norway _ The Protestant leader of Northern Ireland, David
Trimble, accepted his share of the 1998 Nobel Peace Prize on
Thursday and warned militant Roman Catholics against delays in
turning over their arms caches.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble acknowledged that splinter groups on the pro-British
side had weapons, too. But he said the Irish Republican Army and
its political wing, Sinn Fein, were to blame for resurging tensions
that have stalled the peace drive and that cast a pall over the
awards Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   His Catholic counterpart, John Hume, who shared the prize, said
Trimble was premature to insist on disarmament, because the accord
provides two years to achieve it.
</P>
<P>
   `The real issue about guns and arms is that they have been
totally silent,' Hume, head of the Social Democratic and Labor
Party, said. He added that some militants linked disarmament to
surrender, a ``psychological factor'' that he predicted would
diminish with time.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the recognition of continuing problems, the tone was one
of thanks for obstacles surmounted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is now up to political leaders on all sides,'' Hume said,
to deliver ``agreed structures for peace that will forever remove
the underlying causes of violence and division on our island.''
</P>
<P>
   The laureates have come to personify hopes for peace in a
province where 3,200 people have been killed in 30 years of
conflict. On May 22 a referendum overwhelmingly endorsed the
accord.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble is first minister in the new provisional Assembly. But
he has threatened to put off forming the multi-party cabinet called
for in the accord reached in April until paramilitary groups begin
to hand in their weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any further delay will reinforce dark doubts about whether
Sinn Fein are drinking from the clear water of democracy or still
drinking from the dark stream of fascism,'' Trimble, head of the
Ulster Unionist Party, told an audience of 1,000 at Oslo City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   The disarmament issue is also blocking progress on prisoner
releases and the creation of institutional bodies linking Northern
Ireland with the Republic of Ireland to the south.
</P>
<P>
   Francis Sejersted, chairman of the Nobel committee, praised both
men but called Hume `the architect of the peace process' and a
bridge to Catholic hard-liners without whom any agreement would be
meaningless.
</P>
<P>
   While Trimble and Hume represent the largest mainstream parties
in Northern Ireland, each must mollify extremists on his own side
of the religious divide for peace to take root. This week, John
Taylor, deputy chief of Trimble's Ulster Unionist Party, told The
Irish Times that conflicting views on the way ahead posed ``a
possibility of a major collapse.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-98 1915EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981210.0365 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3789 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDEAST-CLINTON-BOS &LR;      12-10 1199
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON GOES TO MIDEAST ON PEACE RESCUE MISSION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and w coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton flies to Israel and
Palestinian-controlled West Bank and Gaza Saturday on a trip that
was to celebrate peace and make history. Instead, it will be a
desperate mission to prevent the demise of the Mideast peace
process.
</P>
<P>
   Facing a wounded Israeli government, violent Palestinian
demonstrations and an impeachment vote at home, the White House has
dampened expectations for the four-day trip. Officials suggested
that it will be deemed a success if there is no bloodshed and if
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat simply agree to fulfill promises they made at a White
House ceremony six weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the goals of the visit, a senior official, partly in
jest, said, ``I just want to physically survive.''
</P>
<P>
   Far from reveling in cooperation of two ``partners in peace,''
as the administration had hoped, Clinton will arrive to a tense
atmosphere of violence between Palestinians and political carnage
within Netanyahu's fragile coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Logistics experts are still massaging the itinerary to avoid
alienating either side. But that has proved difficult.
</P>
<P>
   The White House first considered landing Air Force One at the
new Yasser Arafat International Airport in Gaza. But the
president's jet will now touch down at Israel's Ben Gurion airport
because of logistics and Israeli complaints that a Gaza arrival
would appear as an endorsement of Arafat's call for an independent
Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will light a Christmas tree in Bethlehem, the
traditional birthplace of Jesus, in a stop that Palestinian
officials said will help legitimize their claims of statehood.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton trip is not an official state visit, which is why,
American officials say, the president will not address the Knesset,
the Israeli parliament. Also, there is no Palestinian state, and
the White House wants to minimize differences between the two
sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Clinton is going to do is what the two leaders have not
done _ they did not really go home and sell the Wye agreement to
their people,'' another administration official said. But he
cautioned against too much optimism about Clinton's chances,
saying, ``As in any situation, there's only so much Americans can
do.''
</P>
<P>
   As State Department officials followed Netanyahu's steadily
plummeting political star Thursday, White House aides drafted
stirring speeches to revive the hopes for peace among embittered
Israelis and Palestinians. They said the president will speak
glowingly of the benefits of peace but will temper his remarks with
warnings about the surging violence.
</P>
<P>
   Since Netanyahu and Arafat signed the Wye Plantation peace
agreement on Oct. 23 and spoke warmly about each other, US
officials have watched with trepidation as they began attacking
each other verbally.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has been extraordinarily cautious about
trumpeting the gains to be made from the trip. The customary press
briefings before presidential trips overseas, when State Department
and National Security officials wax about the benefits of improving
relations with a given country, have not been held or even
scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is that some of the most important
arrangements still have not been concluded. Clinton has scheduled
separate visits with Arafat and Netanyahu, and his staff spent
spent days trying to secure promises for a three-way talk. But such
a meeting, tentatively scheduled for Monday evening, is not yet
definite.
</P>
<P>
   Then, too, Clinton has never had a comfortable friendship with
Netanyahu, whom American officials see as stubborn and
unpredictable. Indeed, a year ago, senior officials shrugged at the
possibility of an early end to Netanyahu's governing coalition. But
after nine days of tense talks at the Wye Plantation, on Maryland's
Eastern Shore, Netanyahu made significant concessions to Arafat and
saluted Clinton as a ``warrior for peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Those very concessions have enabled hard-liners in Israel to
move against Netanyahu, who earlier this week managed to postpone
for two weeks a vote of no confidence against him. Aides said that
Clinton, whatever his past misgivings about Netanyahu, feels
obliged to support him. For that reason, Clinton praised Netanyahu
during an interview in Washington with Israeli television.
</P>
<P>
   ``Initially, the administration viewed Netanyahu as a serious
obstacle, but now it appears he may be the conservative leader who
can deliver elements of peace in a very complex Israeli political
situation,'' said Steve Yetiv, a political science professor at Old
Dominion University.
</P>
<P>
   The senior White House official echoed such thinking by saying,
``The president does feel that the prime minister took some brave
polticial risks when he made the deal at Wye, and he would like to
tell taht to the Israeli people.''
</P>
<P>
   To improve the mood among the Israeli right, an aide said,
Clinton will lavish compliments on Israel for its perspicacity and
its heroism as it celebrates its 50th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   But that might not be enough. Along the Jerusalem-Tel Aviv
highway, someone has pasted photo-montages of Clinton wearing a
traditional Arab headdress as well as ``Clinton go home'' posters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very scary. There's no internal trust among either the
Israelis or the Palestinians, and there's no external trust,
either,'' said David Lukin, a senior adviser to Senator Daniel
Patrick Moynihan, the New York Democrat. ``The last thing the
president needs right now is to have this whole thing collapse.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, too, there is the specter in Washington of an impending
impeachment vote in the House Judiciary Committee, perhaps
Saturday, the day that Clinton departs on Air Force One. When this
trip was first planned in October, few, if any, officials predicted
that it would be framed by such crucial votes on Capitol Hill. The
full House may vote articles of impeachment against Clinton on
Thursday, two days after he returns.
</P>
<P>
   But if Clinton gives powerful speeches and persuades Israelis
and Palestinians to return to the path of the peace accords, the
trip could benefit him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton has a vital interest in entering every American home
when Congress is debating his impeachment, as the world leader who
comes on Chrismtas Eve to bring peace to the Holy Land,'' columnist
Yosef Lapid wrote in Thursday's Maariv newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   During past trips to Ireland and Russia, Clinton had hoped to
talk about peace and partnership only to face questions from
American reporters about his affair with Monica Lewinsky. The White
House will not say whether Clinton will field questions in the
Mideast, but he is likely to be shadowed by reporters asking about
impeachment, not West Bank troop withdrawals.
</P>
<P>
   This trip could resemble the visit to Panama in 1992 by
President George Bush. Bush had hoped to be welcomed as the
liberator who ousted a dictator, Manuel Antonio Noriega. Instead,
he faced angry crowds who accused the US of raising false hopes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-98 1916EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
