<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3803 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASTEROID-IMPACT-BOS &LR;      12-10 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASTEROID-IMPACT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY DETAILS DEVASTATION TO LARGE MAMMALS, BIRDS BY ASTEROID 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A mile-wide asteroid slammed into the coast of &UR;  &LR; what is today
Argentina 3.3 million years ago, and may have caused an abrupt
cooling of the climate and killing off of 36 species of huge,
lumbering animals.
</P>
<P>
   Giant armadillos, marsupial sloths and beasts that all towered 8
to 10 feet tall, and flightless birds larger than ostriches, were
wiped out; average temperatures around the world soon dropped by 2
degrees Celsius, according to the data.
</P>
<P>
   The impact, detailed in a paper in the current issue of the
journal Science, was far smaller than the one that was believed to
have caused the extinction of dinosaurs and many other species 65
million years ago. It probably had only regional rather than global
effects, according to the paper's lead author, Peter Schultz, a
planetary geologist at Brown University.
</P>
<P>
   But because the impact was so much more recent, its effects on
climate, the local geology and living organisms may be far easier
to study in detail, and may thus provide new insight into the
details of impacts in general.
</P>
<P>
   It was only in 1980 that scientists first reported evidence of
the dinosaur-killing impact, and over the years since then a
growing body of evidence from around the world has been filling in
details of the results of that impact, and of the existence of many
other impact events in Earth's history.
</P>
<P>
   The relatively recent, well-preserved layers of rock on the
coast of Argentina, where the signs of the impact were found, make
this ``like a mystery story where we can go out and look at the
crime scene'' to learn more about what happens in such impacts,
Schultz said. ``That is what makes this so exciting to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The discovery of the site was a classic case of scientific
serendipity. Schultz, a specialist in impact events who studies the
effects of objects slamming into the Earth by simulating such
impacts in his lab at Brown, has spent six years studying craters
in western Argentina that were produced by a different, later
impact. When he was giving a talk there about his research, the
woman who had been his interpreter for the talk showed him
afterward some small pieces of green natural glass that she had
picked up as a child because they were so pretty. She wondered what
they were.
</P>
<P>
   Schultz recognized them at once as being glass produced by the
heat of an impact _ a familiar relic of such events that he had
seen before at other sites. Analysis in the lab quickly proved that
his guess was correct: the glass had the characteristic
composition, including traces of the element iridium that is rare
on Earth but common in asteroids, that proved it had been produced
by an object striking the Earth.
</P>
<P>
   He soon teamed up with Argentinian geologist Marcelo Zarate, who
for many years had been studying the unusual coastal cliffs where
the glass was found. These cliffs, world-famous for their amazing
fossils of large, ancient mammals, were peppered with large chunks
of the glassy impact material, known as ``escorias,'' and reddish,
bricklike rock, known as ``tierras cocidas.'' Some of these chunks
are as much as six feet across, and Schultz refers to them as
``impact bombs.''
</P>
<P>
   By comparing the size of these chunks with those found in other
impact craters, Schultz concluded that the impact must have been
caused by an asteroid about a mile across. So far, no sign of the
actual impact crater has been found, he said. It may now lie
underwater, since the coastline has moved inland by 10 to 20 miles
since the time of the impact.
</P>
<P>
   The fossilized animals known from the area are found in
abundance in the layers of rock that formed before the impact, but
are completely absent in the more recent layers, showing that they
died off just at that time _ either because of the impact itself,
or perhaps because of changes in the climate caused by dust ejected
by the blast.
</P>
<P>
   Cores of sediment drilled from the nearby sea floor show that a
sudden drop in temperature took place at about the same time. The
colder climate lasted about 50,000 years before returning to
normal. Soon after that, the Earth entered an ice age, and began a
series of oscillations between glacial and interglacial periods
that has continued until the present time.
</P>
<P>
   While there is no way of knowing yet exactly how these events
are linked, Schultz says it is possible that the impact and the
cooling produced by its ejected dust may have provided the trigger
that pushed the climate over the edge and into an unstable pattern.
</P>
<P>
   Schultz says that discovery of this impact will make a big
difference in the study of the fossil remains from those coastal
cliffs, because there is no other material in that whole formation
that could allow scientists to determine their exact age _ although
changes in the magnetism of layers in the rock do give a good
record of the relative ages of the layers. But the impact glass
could be dated very precisely by analyzing tiny traces of
radioactive isotopes inside it, and that provides a benchmark to
calibrate the ages of the rest of the layers.
</P>
<P>
   Schultz said it's as though they had a clock that gave precise
times, but didn't know if the times were a.m. or p.m. until the new
discovery came along. ``This provides a way to pinpoint the dates
of these fossils,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And, he said, it could help scientists to understand better the
range of possible effects produced by impacts. Some, like the one
believed to have killed the dinosaurs, cause global calamity and
widespread extinction of species, and others, perhaps including
this one, do only regional damage.
</P>
<P>
   And it provides yet another warning about the reality of the
threat to Earth posed by such celestial objects, he said. ``It can
happen. If it happened to the dinosaurs, it can happen to mammals.
We're not immune.''
</P>
</TEXT>
