<SLUG> BC-MA-DURAND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ENVIRONMENT CHIEF HUNTS, BUT SAYS HE HAS OPEN MIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ State Senator Robert A. Durand, named Thursday as the
new environmental affairs secretary, promised that despite being a
hunter he will keep ``an open-door policy'' with animal-welfare
activists as he decides wildlife management issues.
</P>
<P>
   The Marlborough Democrat, who will take the post in early
January, said: ``I'll do everything I can to have an open-door
policy to all the groups out there and listen to all sides.
Ultimately, when a decision has to be made, I'll do that based on .
. . relying on the experts'' and resisting pressure from both
hunters and their critics.
</P>
<P>
   But news of Durand's selection prompted a veteran animal-rights
activist, Dorothy Checchi-O'Brien, to declare: ``God help the
animals.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like putting the fox in charge of the chickens,'' said
Checchi-O'Brien, who has been lobbying for animals at the State
House for more than 25 years. ``He does have concern for the
environment, but not for animals. He looks at wildlife as game for
his fellow blood sportsmen to kill. We should advise all the
wildlife to hide.''
</P>
<P>
   Marsha Rockefeller Westropp, legislative liaison for the
Massachusetts Audubon Society, said, ``We have disagreements (with
Durand) over some issues, but 99 percent of the time we see
similarly, and he's been an aggressive fighter for the
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be some hunting issues where we have a
disagreement, and we will fight him on that, but the positive
aspects of Bob Durand and his heart being in the right place on
environmental issues will greatly overshadow any disagreements we
have on hunting issues,'' Rockefeller Westropp said.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing her sentiments, James R. Gomes of the Environmental
League of Massachusetts praised Governor Paul Cellucci for picking
``the best environmentalist in the state Legislature, someone who
is not just committed to the environment but has the political
skills and personal contacts to get things done on Beacon Hill.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago Durand infuriated hunting foes by attaching
language to a land-buying bill that changed state law to presume
all newly acquired land is open to hunting unless state officials
decide otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Many animal-rights activists also feel that under Cellucci's
administration the hunter-dominated Division of Fisheries and
Wildlife has been scheming to undermine the 1996 ballot question
that banned use of certain animal traps and encouraged the governor
to name people other than hunters to the wildlife board.
</P>
<P>
   Durand said he has ``actually had a good working relationship''
with the Massachusetts Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to
Animals on several issues. When questions arise about how much
hunting should be allowed, Durand said he will rely on biologists
to guide his decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've been fair to both sides in the past,'' Durand
said, adding that burgeoning state populations of wild turkey,
bear, bald eagles and peregrine falcons show that well-regulated
hunting can be part of a policy to promote wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   Although he said he thinks the 1996 trap ban has created
``tremendous beaver disruption in the commonwealth,'' Durand said,
``It's premature for me to say whether Question 1 should be changed
or not'' by legislators.
</P>
<P>
   Durand said he will wait to become secretary until shortly after
he is sworn in to the Senate in January so he can vote to reelect
Thomas F. Birmingham as Senate president. His resignation is
expected to set off a frenzied, multi-candidate race for the Senate
seat he has held since 1991. The district ranges from Westborough
to Acton to Shirley.
</P>
<P>
   Durand is succeeding Trudy Coxe, who has moved to a
historic-preservation job in Newport, R.I. While pursuing largely
the same agenda as Coxe, Durand is expected to have much stronger
relationships with the Legislature, as a former member of the House
and Senate, and also with the regional US Environmental Protection
Agency office, with which Coxe has clashed over water treatment and
other issues.
</P>
<P>
   The regional EPA chief, John P. DeVillars, was a top aide to
former governor Michael S. Dukakis, and Durand moved to South
Dakota for several months in 1988 to run Dukakis's presidential
campaign there _ and, famously, hunt elk in his free time. Coxe and
DeVillars have had an edgy, at times bitterly hostile relationship
that has complicated state dealings with the EPA.
</P>
<P>
   Durand is expected to replace many or all of Coxe's top aides,
including assistant secretaries Jan Reitsma and John Rodman, her
chief spokesman. ``I'd be crazy not to bring in my own leadership
team'' for the executive office itself, Durand said, but added that
``there's not a commissioner in that secretariat I can't work
with.''
</P>
</TEXT>
