<SLUG> BC-TRANSPLANT-CONTROVERSY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTI-TRANSPLANT GROUP SEEKS FEDERAL BAR OF RESEARCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ An activist coalition Thursday petitioned the federal
government to halt clinical research on animal-to-human
transplants, saying the risk of spreading dangerous infections to
recipients and other people is too great.
</P>
<P>
   The Campaign for Responsible Transplantation, which says it
represents public interest groups, environmental organizations,
scientists and medical professionals, said it has filed a petition
with the US Department of Health and Human Services to ban
xenotransplantation, as such transplants are called, saying it may
``unleash new viruses into the human population.''
</P>
<P>
   Alix Fano, a representative of the CRT, said the group is asking
the government to prohibit clinical trials of xenotransplantation,
which are at present regulated by the Food and Drug Administration.
</P>
<P>
   She said the only such trials currently under way are
transplants of pig nerve tissue to treat Parkinson's disease, and
experiments using pig livers _ outside the patient's body _ to
cleanse the circulation.
</P>
<P>
   An HHS spokesman confirmed that the petition had been received,
but had no further comment.
</P>
<P>
   The group's announcement came at a press conference in Boston,
which is also the site of a two-day conference on
xenotransplantation.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists pursuing xenotransplantation say that using organs
from pigs or other animals is the best potential solution to the
drastic shortage of human donor organs. Although pig brain cells
have been transplanted in the Parkinson's experiments, the problem
of immune rejection has so far been a barrier to implants of
hearts, kidneys and other animal organs.
</P>
<P>
   Concern about transmitting known or unknown infectious agents
through such transplants is not new: last January federal
scientists and regulators held a two-day hearing on the risks and
decided that researchers could continue the work cautiously.
</P>
<P>
   The critics at Thursday's press conference included two doctors,
a lawyer, a veterinarian, a biochemist, a nurse and an author of a
book on animal testing. They said they oppose xenotransplantation
on a variety of grounds: that it is dangerous, unlikely to be
successful, is being driven by profit motives, will cause harm to
animals, and is the wrong way to solve the shortage of donor
organs.
</P>
<P>
   When asked, six of the seven said they were vegetarians.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Gary Block, chief of staff at a veterinary hospital in Rhode
Island, said that pigs and nonhuman primates harbor at least 50
known organisms that may infect people. ``Most infectious agents
start in animals,'' he said, adding that there's no way to test for
all of them and it would be impossible to create herds of donor
animals that would be free of all such agents.
</P>
<P>
   He said there is particular concern about a type of virus that
routinely infects pigs and which has been shown to be capable of
infecting human cells in the laboratory. The viruses are known as
porcine endogenous retroviruses or PERVs. Xenotransplant
researchers say there is no evidence that they infect humans
outside the laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   However, Block told the press conference that the potential for
transmitting the viruses to patients in an animal transplant is
``an undeniable risk to public health and safety.'' he told the
press conference.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Richard G. McLellan, an emergency medicine specialist from
Los Angeles, warned that xenotransplants would endanger not just
graft recipients but anyone with whom the recipients came in
contact, threatening a ``worldwide epidemic.'' He and others called
for intensified efforts to get people to donate organs after their
death. At present there are about 70,000 people in the United
States waiting for donor organs, and many die without receiving
them.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at the xenotransplant conference, sponsored by IBC
Group plc, defended their work as necessary and said there is no
evidence to suggest that transplants pose an unacceptable risk of
transmitting infections. The conference was to be followed by a
special workshop Friday on ways to check for ``xenozoonoses'' _ the
technical term for human-to-animal infections.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jeffrey L. Platt, a transplant surgeon and researcher at the
Mayo Clinic and chairman of the xenotransplant conference, said
scientists are looking carefully at the problem of PERV and other
animal infectious agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is even less reason to be concerned today than there was
a year ago,'' said Platt, because of research on the question.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have searched for any evidence that people exposed to
pigs or pig products, including workers in slaughterhouses, have
been infected with any unusual agents, said Platt. ``There is no
evidence I know of'' that any such infections have occurred, he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
