<SLUG> BC-MA-INSURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTORNEY GENERAL SEEKS SANCTIONS AGAINST AUTO INSURERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The process of setting next year's auto insurance rates
is proving to be contentious to the very end, as the attorney
general's office said Thursday it is seeking hefty sanctions
against the insurance industry for failing to provide sought-after
executive salary information.
</P>
<P>
   Citing the industry's ``deliberate and inexcusable''
noncompliance with his information request, Attorney General Scott
Harshbarger asked Insurance Commissioner Linda Ruthardt to sharply
limit how much the industry can recover for expenses in next year's
rates.
</P>
<P>
   An insurance industry spokesman said the sanctions were
unwarranted. If approved, he said, they would cost companies more
than $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   The spat over salaries is only the latest dogfight in what
insiders say has been one of the most bitterly fought rate cases in
state history. The industry is seeking a 15.5 percent rate hike in
1999, while opponents are pushing for a rate cut of about 12
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Ruthardt is supposed to issue her rate decision by Tuesday, but
many expect the decision to be delayed. This year the industry and
its opponents did not stipulate agreement on any part of the case,
as they have in past years. They also filed more than 500 pages of
briefs, about twice the volume of previous years.
</P>
<P>
   The salary issue epitomized the no-holds-barred nature of this
year's hearings. Joanna Connolly, an assistant attorney general,
said the industry is seeking a double-digit increase in the expense
portion of the 1999 rates and the attorney general's office wanted
the salary information to determine whether that increase was
warranted.
</P>
<P>
   But industry officials said they suspected Harshbarger's office
asked for the salary information during a close race for governor
to grandstand with voters.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general's office asked for the compensation of the
10 highest-paid employees at each company whose salaries were
included in whole or in part in the expense portion of the
industry's rate request.
</P>
<P>
   According to the attorney general's office, the industry had to
be repeatedly ordered to turn over the information. What was
reluctantly produced was unintelligible and of no use, Connolly
said.
</P>
<P>
   In seeking sanctions, the attorney general's office said
penalties were needed ``to ensure that the public does not view the
rate-setting hearing as a process `controlled' by the insurers, a
process in which the insurers provide just as much information as
they want and no more, flouting orders to provide additional
information with impunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Johnston, president of the Automobile Insurers Bureau of
Massachusetts, said the information supplied to the attorney
general was easily understandable. ``It's quite readable,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston said the information, which was not made part of the
public record, did not include employee or company names. ``We
never could figure out what they wanted the information for,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
