<HEADER>
A3824 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDUCATION-NC11-COX     12-10 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUCATION-NC11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REPORT SHOWS NORTH CAROLINA SCHOOLS IMPROVING
 &HT;    650 words
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By NICHOLE MONROE
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ North Carolina student test scores are rising,
fewer students are carrying weapons and more high school students
are graduating, but drug use in public schools has increased,
according to a national report released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 National Goals Report released by the National
Education Goals Panel gives U.S. states a snapshot of how much
their students are improving compared with others across the
country.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton in a written statement said he was pleased
with the nation's progress, but it ``still has a long way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I will continue to press Congress to help give our students
smaller classes, well-prepared teachers and modernized school
buildings,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   States were evaluated in eight areas: children's readiness for
school, graduation and dropout rates, academic achievement, teacher
education, international standing in math and science, adult
literacy, school safety and parental participation in schools.
</P>
<P>
   In each area, states were evaluated on several factors. The
following are highlights:
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina improved more than any other state in the
percentage of students carrying a weapon on school property.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1993 and 1995, the number of North Carolina students
carrying a weapon decreased from 14 percent to 9 percent. Most
states saw no change in this area.
</P>
<P>
   Panel members attributed the state's success to zero-tolerance
policies, increased law enforcement presence in schools and other
community efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The number of North Carolina students who are at least
proficient on the math section of the National Assessment of
Educational Progress increased. The NAEP measures student ability
on three levels: basic, proficient and advanced. Proficient
students demonstrate competency over challenging subject matter and
are well prepared for the next level of schooling. Between 1990 and
1996, the number of proficient eighth-graders jumped from 9 percent
to 20 percent. Nationally, that number increased from 15 percent to
24 percent. Overall, more North Carolina students are receiving
degrees in mathematics and science, including women and minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1991 and 1995, the number of women receiving degrees in
mathematics and science increased from 36 percent to 42 percent.
The number of minorities receiving such degrees increased from 38
percent to 45 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, 37 percent of women and 40 percent of minorities
received such degrees in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina also has increased the number of high school
graduates. Between 1990 and 1996, the completion rates rose from 83
percent to 89 percent. Nationally, graduation rates have remained
stagnant at 86 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The news is not all good. In 1997, about 22 percent of students
said they used marijuana at least once in the past 30 days. That
number was up from 15 percent in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Though there was no comparable data available nationally, the
Virgin Islands had some of the lowest percentages of all the states
at 15 percent for marijuana use and availability of drugs.
</P>
<P>
   More teachers also reported that student disruptions in class
interfered with learning. Between 1993 and 1997, the number of
North Carolina teachers reporting disruptions increased from 42
percent to 53 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the goals panel said they hope the report will help
states improve their practices and encourage them to become more
competitive internationally.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's often said that there's no problem in American education
that is not already solved in some American school or school
system,'' said panel chairman and West Virginia Gov. Cecil
Underwood. ``The pressing need is to discover those practices that
are working and the lessons we can all learn as we strive to
improve achievement and opportunities in our own communities.''
</P>
<P>
   To view the National Education Goals report on the Internet,
visit the panel's Web site at (http://www.negp.gov).
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
