<HEADLINE>
ARMY ACCUSES GENERAL OF AFFAIRS WITH 4 SUBORDINATES' WIVES
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Army charged a retired two-star general
Thursday with 17 counts of misconduct stemming from adulterous
relationships he had with the wives of four officers under his
command in a case that has forced the Army to revise its retirement
policy for officers facing charges of wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   The officer, Maj. Gen. David Hale, had served only four months
as the Army's deputy inspector general when the Army granted his
request to retire last February, even though one of the women had
filed a formal complaint accusing him of coercing her into a sexual
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Hale, who was deputy commander of NATO ground forces for
southeastern Europe at the time of the relationship, now faces the
military equivalent of a grand jury hearing to determine whether he
should face a court-martial, even though he has retired.
</P>
<P>
   If so, Hale would be only the second Army general to face
court-martial since Congress enacted the Uniform Code of Military
Justice in 1951.
</P>
<P>
   The other case was in 1952, when Maj. Gen. Robert Grow, the
military attache in Moscow, was charged with dereliction of duty _
in what one historian considered Cold War hysteria _ after his
diary was stolen from a hotel room in Germany and published by East
Germany's Communist government.
</P>
<P>
   The charges come only a week after the Navy accepted what
amounted to a plea bargain by a one-star admiral accused of
steering $150,000 worth of military contracts to a woman with whom
he was having an adulterous affair. That officer, Rear Adm. John
Scudi, agreed to resign at a lower rank with a significantly
smaller pension, to pay a $7,000 fine and to spend 30 days under
house arrest rather than face a court-martial.
</P>
<P>
   Both cases _ involving sexual liaisons and lies about about them
_ played out against the backdrop of the impeachment inquiry now
moving ahead against President Clinton in the House Judiciary
Committee. Some Republicans and retired military personnel have
argued that Clinton, as commander in chief, should be held to the
same moral standards as those spelled out in the Uniform Code of
Military Justice.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted of all the charges, which include ``conduct
unbecoming an officer and a gentleman,'' making false statements
and obstructing justice, Hale could face a maximum of 56 years in
prison, as well as a reduction in rank and benefits.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Army's handling of Hale's case led to accusations of a
double standard of justice, which allowed senior officers to
sidestep discipline while junior officers or enlisted personnel
faced more-vigorous prosecution. The charges surfaced only weeks
after the highly publicized court-martial of the Army's top
enlisted soldier, Gene McKinney, sergeant major of the Army, who
faced 18 counts of sexual misconduct involving six women, although
he was convicted of only one charge of obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   The Army's chief of staff, Gen. Dennis Reimer, has acknowledged
that he knew that an internal inquiry had begun against Hale when
he approved Hale's retirement in February.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with reporters Thursday, Reimer said he believed
he made the right decision at the time but that additional
information had come out, including a report by the Pentagon's
inspector general in July. He added that General Hale's retirement
never precluded an investigation and that the Army pursued the case
aggressively once the gravity of the allegations became known.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given what I knew at that point in time, I think the decision
was a solid decision,'' Reimer said.
</P>
<P>
   The charges against Hale, 53, grew out of accusations by
Donnamaria Carpino, whose husband served under the general's
command at the NATO base in Izmir, Turkey. She accused Hale of
trumping up adultery charges against her husband and then promising
not to pursue them if she agreed to have sex with him.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Hale was divorcing his wife after 30 years of
marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Carpino's accusations prompted an investigation by the
Pentagon's inspector general, who concluded in July that Hale had
engaged in a pattern of ``inappropriate behavior'' with her and the
other women beginning as early as 1994, when Hale served in Hawaii.
The inspector general's report found, however, that the general's
relationship with Ms. Carpino was consensual, not coerced.
</P>
<P>
   Hale has denied the accusations to the Army and the Pentagon,
submitting a 40-page rebuttal to the inspector general's report.
</P>
</TEXT>
