<HEADLINE>
TWO SPACECRAFT TO FOLLOW THE WATER FOR SIGNS OF MARTIAN LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you want to find life, ``follow the water,'' NASA science
chief Edward Weiler once said. That's what two new spacecraft,
about to be launched to explore the planet Mars, plan to do, along
with another craft that is already there, waiting to begin its real
work.
</P>
<P>
   Water is the key to finding life elsewhere in the universe. The
other ingredients needed for life _ energy and organic molecules _
exist virtually everywhere on other planets, moons, comets, and
even in clouds of gas and dust. So to find out where else life may
exist, Weiler says, it comes down to the water.
</P>
<P>
   The Mars Climate Orbiter, which is to be launched at 1:45 p.m.
Friday, and the Mars Polar Lander, to follow on Jan. 3, will probe
for evidence of water in the air, on the ground, and beneath the
planet's surface. The plan is to pin down whether, and if so where,
water has existed on Mars to support the origin and evolution of
living organisms.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the most compelling questions'' facing scientists ``is
whether life on Earth is unique,'' Weiler said Thursday at a
National Aeronautics and Space Administration briefing on the Mars
missions. ``The upcoming launches of Mars Climate Orbiter and Mars
Polar Lander are part of the process of fulfilling that goal.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mars Climate Orbiter, originally scheduled for launch
Thursday, was delayed after a software glitch was discovered in a
last-minute check. But officials said Thursday that the software
had been fixed and checked out, and that the launch could go ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The craft will function much like weather satellites above the
Earth do, monitoring the planet's clouds and studying the surface
for signs of moisture, including the occasional snow or frost known
to appear on Mars' surface. It will also analyze the moisture
content of the air itself.
</P>
<P>
   The Mars Polar Lander will set down on what is believed to be
one of the wettest parts of the red planet _ the south polar
icecap. It will study the soil, and look up to examine moisture in
the air from the ground to two miles up. Together, the two craft
will scrutinize the entire atmosphere of Mars with far greater
detail than any previous spacecraft.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, two tiny devices resembling lawn darts, carried by
the Polar Lander, will be fired shortly before the landing and will
strike the ground with a force of about 30,000 times the force of
gravity, to penetrate an estimated two to three feet deep. They
will look for traces of water in the soil, which many scientists
consider the most promising place to look. While liquid water
cannot exist on the Martian surface because of its low air
pressure, water could flow just below the surface.
</P>
<P>
   And living organisms, which scientists say would be destroyed by
ultraviolet light on the surface because Mars lacks a protective
ozone layer, could survive underground _ if there is water to
support them.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to follow the water, and that's what these two
missions are all about,'' Weiler said. ``You have to track water
over the whole globe.''
</P>
<P>
   The two spacecraft were developed and built for a combined cost
of $190 million, less than the cost of the Mars Pathfinder lander,
which was touted as a sterling example of NASA's new ``cheaper,
faster, better'' philosophy. ``We have accomplished this
development of two spacecraft for the price of one,'' said project
manager John McNamee.
</P>
<P>
   The new craft will supplement information already gathered by
the Mars Global Surveyor spacecraft, which has been orbiting the
red planet since September of last year and has discovered evidence
that Mars had water on its surface for much longer than most
scientists suspected. The Global Surveyor will not begin its
primary mission of mapping the planet until March, but it has taken
preliminary pictures that reveal clear signs of the effects of
flowing and standing water.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have known from pictures taken in the 1970s that Mars
was marked by channels apparently carved by flowing water, but they
have vigorously debated whether those features could have been
caused by brief flash-floods, perhaps caused by large meteorites
striking frozen ground and causing a brief melting, or whether
water existed on the surface for longer periods.
</P>
<P>
   Now, pictures from Global Surveyor show the first clear evidence
for long-lasting water. Michael Malin, the geologist who designed
Surveyor's main camera, said Wednesday: ``Mars has had a
significantly more interesting history than we had conceived of''
before this mission.
</P>
<P>
   One picture in particular, Malin said, changes the whole picture
of Mars' climate history. It shows a large, deep canyon with a
tiny, meandering river channel at its bottom, providing ``one of
the most profound geological observations we've made'' on Mars.
</P>
<P>
   On Earth, such formations are seen only where flowing water has
been at work on the landscape over millions of years, for example,
the channel of the Colorado River within the Grand Canyon. ``The
fact that we see the channel within the valley argues that this was
a long-term flowing river,'' he said. ``This is the first evidence
we've ever had from Mars of this sustained fluid motion.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's just the beginning, he added. When Global Surveyor
begins its full two-year mission in March, it will produce pictures
that are ``three to 30 times better than anything'' seen so far,
Malin said. Those pictures, he said, could help pinpoint the places
to focus on in planned missions in 2003 and 2005, which will
retrieve samples of rock and soil to be brought back to Earth by a
later mission, to search for traces of life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
