<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOUISIANA-PRISONER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AWARD-WINNING INMATE JOURNALIST SEEKS TO APPEAL MURDER CONVICTION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KIM COBB 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BATON ROUGE, La. _ An award-winning inmate journalist is
attempting to convince a federal judge that he was unaware for two
decades that the race-conscious method of selecting his grand jury
might be a viable avenue for appealing his murder conviction.
</P>
<P>
   But Wilbert Rideau, editor of the prison magazine The Angolite,
may have an uphill battle. Rideau has been incarcerated at the
Louisiana State Penitentiary at Angola since 1962.
</P>
<P>
   The Calcasieu Parish district attorney is moving to dismiss
Rideau's motion for habeas corpus, based on the claim that the 37
years which have passed since the commission of the crime would
make it difficult for the state to mount another trial against him.
</P>
<P>
   A state appellate court denied his last appeal in 1973, and U.S.
District Judge Frank Polozola was skeptical Thursday when Rideau's
attorney argued that his client learned only recently through
researching another inmate's case that the composition of his grand
jury was not a dead issue.
</P>
<P>
   But a federal magistrate has recommended Rideau be either
released or re-tried, saying the Louisiana Supreme Court applied
the wrong legal standard more than two decades ago in requiring him
to prove ``prejudice'' as a result of the grand jury composition.
``To the contrary, the (Supreme) court has specifically held that a
showing of prejudice is not necessary to prevail on a claim that
there was racial discrimination in the selection of a grand jury,''
U.S. Magistrate Christine Noland wrote in her late 1997
recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   Rideau was tried, convicted and sentenced to death three times
for a murder stemming from a Calcasieu Parish bank robbery. The
U.S. Supreme Court overturned Rideau's first conviction because of
the prejudicial nature of pre-trial publicity. His second
conviction was overturned by the Louisiana State Supreme Court
because the judge improperly excluded from the jury people who said
they did not believe in capital punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Rideau's third conviction was upheld despite Rideau's arguments
(for the second time) that the parish grand jury system violated
his constitutional rights. The Louisiana Supreme Court ruled on
that last appeal in 1973 that Rideau had not proved that the system
actually discriminated against him, and that a disparity between
the percentage of blacks in the parish and the percentage of blacks
selected for the grand jury was not in and of itself
discriminatory.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court outlawed the death penalty in 1974, and
Rideau's death penalty was commuted to life in prison. Attorney
Julian Murray told Polozola on Thursday that other attorneys
subsequently told Rideau there were no other legal avenues
available to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, Mr. Rideau just waited too long,'' Polozola
said, noting that this latest appeal was filed 20 years after the
Louisiana Supreme Court last addressed the question of the grand
jury's racial makeup.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not dealing with an incompetent defendant here,''
Polozola said, noting that the first line of the magistrate's
report is in praise of Rideau's legal ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he takes the stand, he's going to say he was not keeping up
with the new law?'' Polozola asked rhetorically.
</P>
<P>
   Murray countered that Rideau, 56, entered prison with an 8th
grade education, and that his sophistication and legal knowledge
developed over the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``From 1994 on, he's sophisticated?'' Polozola asked.
</P>
<P>
   Polozola further noted that he was always inclined to disregard
procedural questions if the defendant's innocence was at question.
But even his attorney conceded that he could not argue that point.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been interviewed too many times ... for me to try to get
up here and say he didn't do it,'' Murray said.
</P>
<P>
   Polozola ordered an evidentiary hearing after the first of the
year on both the state's specific problems in mounting a new trial
(missing evidence, dead witnesses) and Rideau's lack of knowledge
of the legal remedies available to him.
</P>
<P>
   Calcasieu Parish District Attorney Rick Bryant and assistant
district attorney Mike Stratton were buoyed by the judge's remarks.
But Bryant said he felt certain they could still re-convict Rideau
if a new trial is ordered, based on the testimony of witness Dora
McCain, who survived a gunshot wound to the head, and Rideau's
previous statements about the crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been on Ted Koppell (network television) admitting the
crime, he's been before the Pardon Board admitting the crime,''
Bryant said. He called Rideau ``the darling of a lot of criminal
defense lawyers around the state'' but added that Dora McCain is
still afraid of him.
</P>
<P>
   Rideau has published two books on prison life and has received
some of America's highest journalism awards _ including the George
Polk Award and the Robert F. Kennedy Journalism Award. He
co-directed a 1998 film about Angola called ``The Farm'' that won
the Sundance Grand Jury Prize for documentaries.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
