   ABOUT-CARS-ESCALADE (Undated) _ Escapade? Escalate? No, it's
Escalade, defined by Webster's as ``the act of scaling or climbing
the walls of a fortified place using ladders.'' While these trucks
_ the first in Cadillac's 96 years of existence _ are perfectly
capable of scaling heights, few will venture much farther off-road
than the valet parking lane at the yacht club. The Escalade's
capabilities will rarely be used to their potential. By James G.
Cobb.
</P>
<P>
   CAR-SMART-LINCOLN (Undated) _ After nearly six decades as the
undisputed leader of the U.S. luxury market, Cadillac is poised to
lose its crown to Lincoln this year. As of Nov. 30, Lincoln had
sold 170,265 cars and trucks in 1998. That was nearly 7,000 ahead
of Cadillac. The gap grew in November, prompting Cadillac to
virtually concede the race. By Michelle Krebs.
