A3847 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COD-RESTRICTIONS-BOS &LR;      12-10 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COD-RESTRICTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOARD TO CUT COD FISHING BY 80 PERCENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WAKEFIELD, Mass. _ Fisheries officials said Thursday they will
slash cod fishing in the Gulf of Maine by 80 percent next year in a
drastic attempt to restore the species, and warned that government
will have to pick up the pieces of a fishing industry that stands
to be similarly decimated.
</P>
<P>
   Fishermen predicted that the clampdown on fishing in the Gulf of
Maine, which includes the near-shore waters from northern
Massachusetts to eastern Maine, will drive many small-boat owners
out of business because their vessels aren't equipped for fishing
farther from shore, leaving them nowhere to go.
</P>
<P>
   But, faced with a new biological study that found the
once-bountiful cod population has reached a dangerous low, members
of the New England Fishery Management Council said they have to act
now to prevent the ``commercial extinction'' of the cod.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bruce Tarr, a Gloucester Democrat, predicted that the cod
cutbacks will ``necessitate unprecedented levels of social
relief,'' and said, ``You are looking squarely at the possible
extinction of an entire segment of fishing families.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps 700 boats rely on cod and other groundfish in the Gulf
of Maine for an important part of their livelihood _ including 200
small boats on Cape Ann _ and they in turn support thousands of
fishing industry jobs. Unlike larger vessels that can steam out to
the Georges Banks cod fishing ground, these boats have limited
range.
</P>
<P>
   Since the closure of large sections of Georges Bank in 1994,
however, bigger boats have come into the Gulf of Maine and,
combined with increased effort from the near-shore fleet, quickly
drove the cod populations to record lows.
</P>
<P>
   The fishing ground ``is collapsing and we need to protect it
now,'' said Capt. Paul Howard, executive director of the Fishery
Management Council.
</P>
<P>
   The council, planning to adopt rules for the fishing season that
begins next May, chose three options for more study that would
reduce gulf cod landings from last year's 4,075 tons to 782 tons
next year. All of the choices, ranging from broad closures of the
gulf to drastic reductions in fish landings per trip, will be
painful to the small-boat fishermen.
</P>
<P>
   Making the limits even tougher, some of the measures that will
protect the cod, such as area closures, will also prevent fishermen
from catching other so-called groundfish such as flounder, for
which the same type of nets are used.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the region's congressional delegation sent
representatives to Thursday's meeting, calling for compassion in
the cutbacks and more aid like the $5 million Sen. John Kerry of
Massachusetts secured this fall for the groundfish crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Council members were regretful that their more modest fishing
limits over the past three years had not stopped the crash of the
cod population, forcing harsher measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are on the verge of some of the most radical measures in
the council's history and it would not do justice if we don't come
out of the crisis with a new way of thinking,'' said Erik Anderson,
a New Hampshire fisherman on the council, calling for an end of the
cycle of crises and regulations that has plagued New England
fishing.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, fishermen and their advocates were angry, but, unlike
past meetings where most were skeptical of overfishing claims, many
seemed to accept that the cod crisis is real. ``We are all in the
same boat, and it is leaking,'' said Vito J. Calomo, director of
the Gloucester Fisheries Commission.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Gulf of Maine Fishermen's Alliance put forward one
of the three options for study, a plan that calls for the gulf to
be divided into near-shore and offshore waters, with fishermen
choosing which area they want to fish. That way, they argued,
fishermen can help manage a fishing ground rather than moving from
one to another.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you know this is your playground, your backyard, you're
certainly going to take better care of it than if you know it's
just a transient place,'' said alliance president Paul Cohan.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts for the Fishery Management Council said the
alliance proposal, while keeping boats on the water, would only
meet the fishing goals if fishermen were limited to 100 pounds of
cod on each trip, a limit so small that few would bother.
</P>
<P>
   The council also agreed to study a proposal from National Marine
Fisheries Service that would reduce the number of groundfishing
days a year from the current 88 to 70, close big swaths of the gulf
to groundfishing, and lower the cod limit from the current 400
pounds to 200 pounds per trip. That idea was the least popular with
fishermen.
</P>
<P>
   The council staff will have until next month to assess the
social and economic impacts of the three choices, allowing the
council to select the least painful cutbacks, which would then be
reviewed by the National Marine Fisheries Service.
</P>
<P>
   But Angela Sanfilippo, president of the Gloucester Fishermen's
Wives, said she already knows what will happen to the fishing towns
if fishermen can't fish. ``The Gloucester waterfront will be gone.
Condominiums, luxury hotels, and tourists will take its its
place,'' she said. ``Who will benefit when the fish come back?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
