<HEADER>
A3848 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BANNEN-MOVIE-AZR &LR;      12-10 1187
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANNEN-MOVIE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTOR BANNEN FOUND CAREER, ARIZONA BY CHANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MESA, Ariz. - In ``Waking Ned Devine,'' Ian Bannen is the
perfect Irishman. When you meet him, he appears to be the
quintessential British actor.
</P>
<P>
   So what's he doing living in Mesa?
</P>
<P>
   Bannen fell in love with the Arizona desert when acting in his
first American movie, ``Flight of the Phoenix,'' which was shot in
Yuma in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   Bannen's latest film, ``Waking Ned Devine,'' is a winsome comedy
about two old Irishmen who scheme to get a share of big lottery
winnings in their small village. The film has the same kind of
lilting, nostalgic humor that made ``The Englishman Who Went Up the
Hill and Came Down the Mountain'' so popular.
</P>
<P>
   Bannen is the Englishman who came to Arizona and never went home
again.
</P>
<P>
   He had a small role in ``The Flight of the Phoenix,'' which
starred James Stewart, Peter Finch and Richard Attenborough.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cast stayed in Yuma, and we had to make our own fun
because there weren't any girls in the movie,'' Bannen recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``James Stewart led us to a different cafe every night, and we
sang ``Happy Birthday to You'' every 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dicky Attenborough, who never drank at all, had such a red
face that everyone thought he was drunk.''
</P>
<P>
   The next time he worked in Hollywood, Bannen took his wife to
Yuma. ``At first she thought I had brought her to the end of the
Earth,'' he said. ``But she got to like the place, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Bannen then made ``Bite the Bullet'' with Ben Johnson, who had
just bought a home in the Valley, and he tipped them off. The
Bannens bought a Mesa house in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   They live here in the winter months and call London and the Isle
of Wight their other homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in Mesa as much as we can,'' Bannen said. ``But
moviemaking is so all over the place now. When I first started,
they used to shoot them in the studios.''
</P>
<P>
   Bannen has spent most of his career as a character actor, the
kind whose face you recognize but whose name you can't quite place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Waking Ned Devine'' could change all of that by becoming one
of the year's big sleeper hits.
</P>
<P>
   But the movie began as a questionable prospect for Bannen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read the script and liked it, but wondered if they'd ever
get the money for it,'' he explained. ``You get a certain amount of
scripts, but they never get off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``The director took four years to write the screenplay, walking
around Ireland on and off, meeting these wonderful characters.''
</P>
<P>
   When writer-director Kirk Jones finally found funding for
``Waking Ned Devine,'' he searched Ireland for the perfect village
to shoot the story _ and didn't find it.
</P>
<P>
   They ended up shooting on the Isle of Mann, where they found a
village as quaint as a magazine advertisement for Irish travel.
Many of the village residents appear in the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were very jolly,'' Bannen said. ``Irish actors are easy
to get on with. The villagers joined in the fun, and they liked the
free food and the occasional champagne.''
</P>
<P>
   Bannen enjoyed filming there because ``there's a wonderful air
on the Isle of Mann, the sweet smell of wildflowers and things you
don't smell in England anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   As a tale of ordinary men who grasp a chance to turn con
artists, ``Waking Ned Devine'' is full of amusing surprises _ not
the least of which is the scene where Bannen and his elderly
co-star, David Kelly, go skinny-dipping in the sea.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first nude scene Bannen had ever done. ``I've been in
my knickers before,'' he said, ``but that was the first time I had
to go all the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``The director made it easy for us. Kirk asked everyone but the
camera and sound crews to disappear behind the rocks. Then we
dropped our trousers, and he yelled action.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly had to go further than Bannen. He hops aboard a motorbike
without having time to dress.
</P>
<P>
   ``David was terrified out of his wits riding the motorbike
naked,'' Bannen recalled. ``I don't think he'd ever been on a
motorbike before.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me, `I don't care a damn if I was stark naked, I was
in fear of my life.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He envisioned himself arriving at St. Peter's Gate stark
naked, wearing only a motorcycle helmet, and he'd be asked, `Now,
where have you been?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Although they seem like old friends throughout the movie, Bannen
had never worked with Kelly before.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all of an age,'' Bannen said, explaining the easy
camaraderie. ``From the moment we started in rehearsal, we seemed
to get on.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could talk about people like Terry Thomas and Peter
Sellers. When you tell younger people about them, they don't know
who you're talking about because they're dead.''
</P>
<P>
   If Bannen takes a rather off-handed approach to his career as a
movie actor, it's because he fell into it by accident.
</P>
<P>
   As a teenager, he was visiting Dublin on a holiday with a friend
who said, ``We must get hold of some popsies.''
</P>
<P>
   That meant girls. His friend knew the wife of a movie producer
who lived there. The boys figured wherever a movie producer goes
there would be actresses around, so they wangled an invitation for
dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the middle of dinner, she asked me if I had ever done any
acting,'' Bannen said about the first time the muse called.
</P>
<P>
   Figuring she might know something he didn't, Bannen ended up
with a small part in a production at the famous Gate Theater in
Dublin.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't stick with acting because he knew he was going into
the army soon. He returned home to do some farming to toughen up
for the army.
</P>
<P>
   ``The army was better than the farming,'' Bannen said.
</P>
<P>
   When he returned from the service, he didn't want to go to
acting school, ``which is what I should have done. So I bought a
good suit, a bowler hat and an umbrella, and started going around
to producers' offices.''
</P>
<P>
   One secretary took pity on him, told him her boss was busy but
if he came back she'd try to get him in the door.
</P>
<P>
   Bannen came back 12 times before the boss wasn't busy.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, he had learned two monologues by heart. He
performed one for the producer, who asked him: ``Do you like doing
this sort of thing?''
</P>
<P>
   Bannen said, ``No, I'm just desperate for a job.''
</P>
<P>
   The producer sent him to an agent, and the agent got him into
the Royal Shakespeare Theater, under the theory that if he was
going to be an actor it would be a good idea if he learned how to
act.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched all the great British actors every night from the
wings, Richard Burton, Michael Redgrave,'' Bannen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You gradually get the idea that way. So when your chance
comes, you remember things that you saw, like the way Burton was so
still onstage. He never moved his hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stage training gives you confidence, like it does for
stand-up comedians.''
</P>
<P>
   Bannen turned that confidence into a movie career stretched over
70 films, including ``Gandhi,'' ``Gorky Park'' and ``Braveheart.''
</P>
<P>
   Now with his starring role in ``Waking Ned Devine,'' people will
remember his face _ and perhaps other parts, too. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
