<SLUG> BC-EDUCATION-COLORADO11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REPORT SHOWS MIXED RESULTS FOR COLORADO SCHOOLS
 &HT;    610 words
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By NICHOLE MONROE
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Colorado schools have steadily boosted student math
scores and parental involvement, but fewer teachers have degrees in
their areas of instruction and classroom disruptions remain a
problem, according to a national report released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 National Goals Report released by the National
Education Goals Panel gives U.S. states a snapshot of how much
their students are improving compared with others across the
country. Texas was one of the most improved states.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton in a written statement said he was pleased
with the nation's progress, but it ``still has a long way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I will continue to press Congress to help give our students
smaller classes, well-prepared teachers and modernized school
buildings,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   States were evaluated in eight areas: children's readiness for
school, graduation and dropout rates, academic achievement, teacher
education, international standing in math and science, adult
literacy, school safety and parental participation in schools.
</P>
<P>
   In each area, states were evaluated on several factors. The
following are highlights:
</P>
<P>
   The number of principals reporting parent associations are
influencing school policy jumped from 28 percent to 50 percent
between 1991 and 1994. Most states saw no change in this area.
</P>
<P>
   Panel members attributed the state's success to several programs
that require that parents be included in decision-making
committees. Increased public interest in education and
correspondence with parents also have helped, they said.
</P>
<P>
   The number of Colorado fourth- and eighth-graders who are at
least proficient on the math section of the National Assessment of
Educational Progress has increased. The NAEP measures student
ability on three levels: basic, proficient and advanced. Proficient
students demonstrate competency over challenging subject matter and
are well prepared for the next level of schooling.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1992 and 1996, the number of proficient fourth-graders
rose from 17 percent to 22 percent, compared with an increase from
18 percent to 21 percent nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1990 and 1996, the number of proficient eighth-graders
jumped from 17 percent to 25 percent, compared with an increase
from 15 percent to 24 percent nationally. Overall, more Colorado
students are receiving degrees in mathematics and science,
including women and minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1991 and 1995, the number of women receiving degrees in
mathematics and science increased from 43 percent to 47 percent.
The number of minorities receiving such degrees increased from 46
percent to 48 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, 37 percent of women and 40 percent of minorities
received such degrees in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The news is not all good. Between 1991 and 1994, the number of
Colorado teachers holding a degree in their main teaching
assignment decreased from 74 percent to 66 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, about 49 percent of teachers reported that student
disruptions in the classroom were interfering with learning. That
number was up from 40 percent in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the goals panel said they hope the report will help
states improve their practices and encourage them to become more
competitive internationally.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's often said that there's no problem in American education
that is not already solved in some American school or school
system,'' said panel chairman and West Virginia Gov. Cecil
Underwood. ``The pressing need is to discover those practices that
are working and the lessons we can all learn as we strive to
improve achievement and opportunities in our own communities.''
</P>
<P>
   To view the National Education Goals report on the Internet,
visit the panel's Web site at (http://www.negp.gov).
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
