<SLUG> BC-COATES-NOT-GUILTY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS PLAYER FOUND NOT GUILTY IN ASSAULT CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL LANGNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WRENTHAM, Mass. _ Patriots tight end Ben T. Coates was found not
guilty Thursday of assault and battery on his former girlfriend and
the mother of one of his children.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Marshall had accused him of knocking her down and
throwing her onto the hood of her car during a confrontation last
July 26 at his Franklin home over his seeing another woman.
</P>
<P>
   The six-person District Court jury deliberated less than an hour
after three days of trial before acquitting Coates of the single
count.
</P>
<P>
   Coates was not present to take the verdict. With the permission
of Judge Daniel B. Winslow, Coates left as soon as the jury retired
and flew to Greenwood, S.C., to attend to the funeral of his
mother.
</P>
<P>
   She died Wednesday night while Coates was still on trial. The
jury was not informed of the reason Coates was missing for the
taking of the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Sander, a spokeswoman for Coates's defense team, said
that Patriots' owner Robert Kraft had furnished a private jet that
took his star player from Norwood to Greenwood.
</P>
<P>
   Coates's chief accuser Jennifer Marshall, too, was absent when
the verdict was read.
</P>
<P>
   Coates's attorney Mark Berthiaume said he was sure Coates would
feel vindicated and added, ``These charges should never have been
brought. There was no merit to them. This was a woman that was
motivated by greed. This was a woman who tried to take advantage of
this man.''
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Norfolk District Attorney Glenn Cunha had told the
jury he would show that on the July evening Coates knocked Marshall
down, and when she got up, picked her up by the arms and threw her
onto the hood of her white Mercedews Benz 420.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall testified she suffered abrasions on her arms and a sore
neck and a bump on the head. Three Franklin police officers
testified they found Marshall crying when they were called to the
scene by Coates and neighbors who heard the altercation.
</P>
<P>
   But two neighbors of the expensive circular condominium complex
testified for the defense that Marshall had shouted an unbroken
string of obscenities and threats at the impassive Coates, had
struck him, slapped his face twice, taunted him to hit her back,
telling he would be arrested, and began crying only when police
arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Other neighbors testified that as Coates stood with his arms
folded across his chest and urged Marshall to leave, she slapped
his face and bumped him with her chest and ``just waled at him,''
in the words of witness Donna Dumont.
</P>
<P>
   Only when Marshall began to hit Coates' visitor, office manager
Cynthia Modica, did he shove her away, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   Berthiaume told the jury that Marshall had been involved in a
probate court proceeding with Coates at the time of the incident
and had tried to get more than the current $54,000 a year in child
support and had tried to get him to buy her a $46,000 Mercedes Benz
and a $750,000 house.
</P>
<P>
   Among witnesses Berthiaume called was a North Shore car dealer,
Manuel Cintron, who testified that when he suggested that Marshall
might not be able to raise the money for an expensive car she was
looking at, she told him that she could make the payments with her
child support money and that, besides, she would soon be in the
news and that he should keep reading the papers.
</P>
<P>
   Another witness was real estate broker Catherine Sullivan who
showed Marshall a $750,000 house on Aug. 4, nine days after the
incident. Concerning the question of whether she could become
qualified to buy it, Marshall replied she was the girlfriend of
Coates and expected to come into some money before the probable
cause hearing on Aug. 25.
</P>
<P>
   ``What were her exact words?'' asked Berthiaume.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said she owned his contract and he would be running on the
field for the rest of his life for her.''
</P>
<P>
   Pausing for about five seconds for effect, Berthiaume concluded
drily: ``I have no more questions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
