<HEADER>
A3852 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SICKLE11-COX     12-10 1180
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SICKLE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Experimental procedure may cure sickle cell
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For seven years, sickle cell disease got the best of
Keone Penn.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it's payback time.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the 12-year-old Centerville, Ga., boy is scheduled to
undergo an experimental procedure that could mean the end _ forever
_ of blood transfusions, unpredictable bouts of severe pain and the
worry of suffering a second stroke.
</P>
<P>
   In short, a cure for sickle cell disease, which
disproportionately affects African-Americans. More than 2,000 metro
Atlanta residents suffer from it.
</P>
<P>
   If all goes as planned, blood cells taken from the placenta and
umbilical cord of a new mother will grow inside Keone's body into
healthy new bone marrow. It will replace his defective bone marrow,
which churned out sticky, odd-shaped red blood cells, making him
vulnerable to infections and organ damage since infancy.
</P>
<P>
   Transplanting cord blood into a sickle cell patient to regrow
bone marrow has never been done, said Dr. Andrew Yeager, director
of pediatric hematology, oncology and bone marrow transplant at
Emory University School of Medicine(Ga.). Cord blood transplants
have been successful for leukemia and immune disorders, and a
similar procedure _ a bone marrow transplant from a related donor _
has cured some sickle cell patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keone and his mother are akin to pioneers,'' said Yeager,
who's overseeing the team of doctors treating Keone at Egleston
Children's Hospital. ``They are going into unknown territory
knowing there are clearly risks, some known and some unknown. But
they understand the potential justifies the means.''
</P>
<P>
   Keone's mother, Leslie Penn, puts it another way. ``I don't
really want to be the first. I'd feel much better if it'd been done
20 times before,'' she said, taking a break in the hallway outside
Keone's isolation room, which is equipped with a special
ventilation system. ``But if it works, he'll be cured of sickle
cell. Wouldn't that be wonderful?''
</P>
<P>
   Using bone marrow transplants to cure sickle cell disease is
relatively new. Emory University researchers in collaboration with
Grady Memorial Hospital are leading the nation in such procedures,
which take bone marrow from a healthy sibling and infuse it into a
brother or sister with severe sickle cell disorder. Emory has done
five such transplants in the past five years in patients ages 4 to
12; the most recent one was just two months ago, Yeager said. So
far, all are doing well, with four far enough along in recovery to
be considered cured.
</P>
<P>
   Yeager gives 50-50 odds that the world's first cord blood
transplant for sickle cell will work. Doctors should know in about
three weeks, by New Year's Day, whether it's ``taken hold.''
</P>
<P>
   Two unwanted outcomes: Keone's own unhealthy blood factory
growing back because the chemotherapy did not kill it; or the new
cells reacting against his tissues, such as the skin and liver,
Yeager said.
</P>
<P>
   Another possibility is that the transplant doesn't take hold and
Keone's bone marrow remains depleted, leaving him at high risk for
infection. Should that happen, some of Keone's own bone marrow has
been saved and could be given back to him, but it would contain
sickle cells. The rest of Keone's bone marrow was killed during 10
days of chemotherapy at Egleston, a procedure that also impaired
his immune system. He runs the risk that an overwhelmingly
infection could turn fatal.
</P>
<P>
   But then there's that other 50 percent of the odds: success.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I wanted to be conservative, I'd say there's a one in four
chance he'll be cured,'' said Yeager. ``But it's more like there's
a 50 percent chance he'll be cured. The first six to 12 months will
be critical. But two years out, we would definitely talk about a
cure.''
</P>
<P>
   Keone is a seventh-grader at Shiloh Middle School(Ga.), but he
started being home-schooled two months ago after missing so many
classes. Leslie Penn, 37, is a nuclear medicine technologist at
Gwinnett Medical Center(Ga.). Her employer's health insurance has
agreed to pay for the procedure, estimated to cost $200,000, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, bone marrow transplants match a patient with a
relative, usually a brother or sister. But none of Keone's
half-brothers and -sisters was a good match; neither was his mother
or father, David Hynes of North Carolina. Another possibility is
being matched with a volunteer donor enrolled in the National
Marrow Donor Program of the American Red Cross. However, it's hard
for blacks to find a match because only a small percentage of
African-Americans offer to be donors.
</P>
<P>
   The cord blood found for Keone is from the nonprofit New York
Blood Center Placental Blood Bank, and it matches five of the six
inherited traits of Keone's blood. An anonymous woman provided the
cord blood after the birth of her child. Placental and cord blood
are rich in stem cells, which eventually grow into different types
of blood cells.
</P>
<P>
   Bone marrow is the body's blood factory, supplying red and white
cells and platelets. Those cells carry oxygen to organs, fight
infection and help with clotting. People suffering from sickle cell
disease have crescent-shaped, sticky and hard red blood cells
instead of round, smooth red blood cells.
</P>
<P>
   Flowing through blood vessels, sickle cells get stuck, resulting
in excruciating pain throughout the body. These bouts of pain,
called ``crises,'' along with numerous infections, landed Keone in
the hospital seven times this year alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would hurt so much, I wouldn't even want to blink,'' Keone
said.
</P>
<P>
   After his blood disorder led to a stroke at age 5, Keone started
monthly transfusions through the American Red Cross' Partners for
Life donor program. Keone has no physical reminders of the stroke,
but he does have learning disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, before becoming a medical case study, before
starting a regimen of drugs and discomfort, Keone chowed down on
Papa John's pizza and popcorn when two buddies and his 16-year-old
half-sister, Seterria, visited the hospital. But the past week has
turned into chills, fever, nausea, mouth sores and no interest in
food _ all side effects of his oral chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an easy decision to make,'' Leslie Penn admitted.
``Do you take a child who feels pretty good and make him sick? He's
gone through seven years of blood transfusions, but he's just not
responding to them as well anymore. They can't say how much longer
he'd live. He didn't want to die but he didn't want to live like he
was.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd rather go for the chance.''
</P>
<P>
   INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   About 70,000 Americans have sickle cell disease, and 4,000 to
6,000 Georgians suffer from it. About 95 percent are
African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Information on sickle cell:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sickle Cell Foundation of Georgia at 404-755-1641 or
1-800-326-5287.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Sickle Cell Disease Association of America at
1-800-421-8453.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Guthrie writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
