<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: HERE'S HOW A CAPTAIN OPERATES  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ Sometimes captains lead by example, even if it
costs them two minutes in the penalty box. Last week, Trevor Linden
of the Islanders creamed Ulf Samuelsson of the Rangers because he
felt Ulf was doing ugly things, if you can imagine that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was late in the game, and he took a cheap shot, so it
seemed like the right thing to do,'' Linden said later.
</P>
<P>
   This was no Ewingian ramble to the edge of a brawl, costing a
season-crippling suspension. This captain did the minor crime and
he did the minor time, which is why Linden wears the ``C'' on his
jersey, 3,000 miles away from the last town he wore the ``C.'' He
is that rare breed, an instant captain, having shifted to the
struggling Islanders last season after Mike Keenan and Mark Messier
forced him out of Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   Linden is a former farm boy from Alberta, who used to wrestle
cattle to the ground for branding. (So what is an Ulf Samuelsson to
him?) In appearance, he seems like a teacher, tall and slim and
reserved, wearing glasses and reading books, particularly about
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the assistant equipment manager, Eric Miklich, gave
him ``The Boys of Summer,'' Roger Kahn's loving look at the
Brooklyn Dodgers. The hockey captain felt a kinship with the
baseball captain, Pee Wee Reese, who once told a young Dodger, ``If
you're in a hurry to get out of the clubhouse, you're in a hurry to
get out of baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Real captains say those things, rather than appear to be in a
hurry to get out of the clubhouse themselves. They are even allowed
to speak to the referee, not to win the last call but to set up a
fair shake on the next one. And when the team is slumping, some
captains call a team meeting, the way Linden did recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also got to organize our Halloween party,'' Linden said.
</P>
<P>
   Linden, 28, was recently elected president of the players
association _ captain of his peers, so to speak. Captains set a
tone. Don Mattingly exuded his love of baseball and his love of
Yankee stripes. Franco Baresi seemed a foot taller when he wore the
yellow arm band for AC Milan and the Italian national soccer team.
I call Willis Reed ``Cap'n,'' because that is who he is.
</P>
<P>
   A hockey captaincy, formalized by a serious ``C'' on the jersey,
is perhaps more wide ranging than in other sports. The Vancouver
captain was also known for giving real time to terminally ill
children, and was a favorite adopted son of that urbane Canadian
city.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was going to play there my whole career,'' Linden
said.
</P>
<P>
   Two summers ago, Vancouver acquired Mark Messier, who felt
unwanted with the Rangers, although money had nothing to do with
it, you understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was great, getting Mark,'' Linden said. ``He's a
great player, a leader. I thought the situation would help me.
Maybe I was just naive.''
</P>
<P>
   When Linden drove around Vancouver and saw Messier's jaw on
billboards, linked with the word ``Commitment,'' he began to get
the picture. The Canucks went to Japan to open the season, and
Japanese reporters kept asking if he was going to give up his
captaincy. He did, before the first game, and said it wasn't the
jet lag, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted it to happen before the first game, not after the
10th game,'' Linden said the other day. ``I didn't want a
controversy. It wouldn't change the way I played.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it would have worked out, except that Keenan, who has done
it to other people, openly maligned Linden, who recently said:
``The situation had deteriorated. It was evident there would be a
trade.''
</P>
<P>
   Linden came to the Islanders, now operated by neophyte owners
who seem most enthusiastic about building just what Long Island
needs _ oh, goodie, another mall.
</P>
<P>
   A week after Linden arrived, there was a ceremony with the old
Islanders _ the Boys of Winter, if you will _ coming back to lend
some credibility to the new operation. Management arranged for
Denis Potvin to hand Linden the Islanders' ``C.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Milbury, who runs the Islanders, said, ``There was no need
to dally.''
</P>
<P>
   Linden said: ``It was a delicate situation. I didn't expect it
with 25 games left in the season. I was leery of it, and I told
them so.''
</P>
<P>
   He was also leery of Long Island, but eventually he discovered
it is not all a blight of shopping centers. This summer he showed
his commitment by taking a one-year contract for less money than he
wanted. (``I bit the bullet,'' he said.) Linden felt he was needed
in camp. That is a captain.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
