<SLUG> BC-AETNA-REACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME PHYSICIANS ARE DISTRESSED AT AETNA MERGER 
</HEADLINE>
  (With AETNA-PRUDENTIAL) 
(lb) 
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Aetna and health-care providers have different views
about how the company's merger with Prudential Health Care will
affect patients and doctors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It couldn't be worse,'' said Dr. David Kaufmann, a New York
internist, who accepts Prucare, Prudential's health-maintenance
organization, but dropped Aetna when the company bought U.S.
Healthcare. ``Aetna U.S. Healthcare is essentially a low-cost
provider that is highly controlling of the delivery of medical care
and pretty unresponsive to physician concerns,'' he said. ``We will
probably have to drop Prucare now.''
</P>
<P>
   Aetna is largely viewed as one of the most stringent
managed-care companies, pushing hard for cost reductions, disputing
claims, questioning out-of-network services and insisting on
mountains of documentation.
</P>
<P>
   But Aetna said Thursday that doctors and patients had little to
fear. ``We will be looking at those areas where Prucare rates are
out of touch with the market,'' said Joyce Oberdorf, an Aetna
spokeswoman. ``But our chairman doesn't believe the future of
health care is squeezing pennies from providers.''
</P>
<P>
   Patients may have more physicians to choose from, and doctors
who already accept Aetna may pick up some business, but both groups
may also find stringent reimbursement policies and tougher stands
on treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aetna is going to be more rigid and disciplined,'' said Alex
Chernoff, managing partner of Chernoff Diamond &AMP; Co., a benefits
consulting firm in New York. ``Providers will be upset to the
extent that they will get paid less and to the extent that they
have more patients on Aetna requiring more of them in terms of
processing claims.''
</P>
<P>
   A dozen calls to doctors' offices Thursday informing them of the
merger were met with deep sighs and exclamations of distress.
``U.S. Healthcare was felt to be pretty draconian and to have
become even worse with Aetna,'' said Dr. Charles Aswad, the
executive vice president of the Medical Society of the State of New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers enrolled in Prucare may face some of the same issues
doctors fear. They may have enjoyed programs that offered services,
such as expensive fertility treatments, that Aetna packages will
not offer. What is more, they may not find their claims honored as
easily as before.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were in Prucare,'' Chernoff said, ``chances are your
plan will not be as liberal.''
</P>
<P>
   Even consumers who have nothing to do with Aetna or Prucare may
find themselves affected simply because doctors may raise prices on
fee-for-service procedures to shift some of the pain from possible
lower reimbursements from Aetna.
</P>
<P>
   Employers who offered Prucare, Chernoff said, may also be in for
sticker shock when it comes time to negotiate rates. ``Aetna
believes in controlling costs,'' he said. ``They are not reaching
to please everybody. They will walk away. That is not what
employers have seen in Pru. Pru would reach.''
</P>
<P>
   However, patients already enrolled in Aetna may find a few new
doctors added to their lists of choices. Prucare never developed a
deep network, and many doctors who dropped out of Aetna will rejoin
through the merger. ``Over time, as our networks combine, we
believe it will result in more choices for customers,'' Ms.
Oberdorf said.
</P>
<P>
   Further, there are some experts who think that this merger will
ultimately benefit consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``My opinion is that it will be better for everyone,'' said
Bradley Hamburger, vice president of Halland Companies LLC, an
insurance broker in Jericho, N.Y. ``Rather than 12 medium-sized
networks, in the not-too-distant future you'll have five very large
ones. The advantage in that is that there won't be a choice for
providers which network to be in. Everyone will be in every network
and the ones that serve the patients best will get the lion's share
of the business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
