<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3861 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDEAST-PLO-$ADV13     12-10 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-PLO-$ADV13 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ONCE BRANDED AS TERRORISTS BY AMERICA, NOW THEY HOST THE
AMERICAN PRESIDENT
 &HT;    EDS: Pls note time element. This story should run no later than
Sunday because Clinton's Monday visit with Palestinian leaders will
likely have taken place by the time our readers get their papers.
 &HT;    Advance for release Sunday, Dec. 13, but may be used prior to
that.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service(at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAMALLAH, West Bank This unassuming man, a dentist, has a
controversial past that still makes it hard for him to visit the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the United States is coming to visit him.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, Palestinian legislator Azmi Shuaibi was on the
secret council that coordinated the Palestinians' (ital)Intifada
(endital) uprising. Israel and its ally, the United States, both
viewed him as an outlaw.
</P>
<P>
   Though he has since made several trips to Washington for peace
talks, each one required special permission because, he says, he is
on a ``black list.''
</P>
<P>
   But Monday, President Clinton will go to Gaza City to be hosted
by Shuaibi and hundreds of leaders many of whom America once
consider terrorists of Yasser Arafat's Palestine Liberation
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides have come a long way. Many of the Palestinian leaders
have converted from warriors to politicians as their people verge
on self-rule. American security forces that used to hunt
Palestinians now train Palestinian police.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is some point of crossing between the demands of the two
people,'' Shuaibi explains. ``The United States cannot resolve this
region without solving the Palestinian problem, and you cannot
solve the Palestinian problem without good relations with the
PLO.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, he points out, ``Palestinians understand that
the world has changed. We cannot rely on the Cold War. We must deal
with the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's meeting in Gaza was the original purpose of Clinton's
three-day trip to the region. It will be the first visit by a U.S.
president to a Palestinian-controlled area. There, he is supposed
to witness the PLO leaders reaffirm that they no longer seek the
destruction of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The event evolved from last October's Israeli-Palestinian peace
deal that Clinton mediated at the Wye River Plantation in Maryland.
The Wye agreement was an attempt to restart the faltering
5-year-old Oslo peace process. Under Oslo, Israel conducts phased
troop pullouts from the occupied Gaza Strip and West Bank in return
for a Palestinian cessation of hostilities.
</P>
<P>
   That is where the Gaza meeting comes in. Though the PLO
maintains that it already, in 1996, revoked passages of its charter
that call for the destruction of Israel, the process was unclear
and unfinished. As part of the Wye agreement, Israel demanded
another meeting of the Palestinian leadership.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, Clinton was asked to attend to make sure the
event happens. There is great uncertainty over just who will show
up to see him on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Those eligible include Palestinian legislators known to be
affiliated with Hamas, a group that opposes the peace process and
sponsors terror attacks in Israel. They, however, are expected to
boycott the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Another is Mohammed Abbas, who attended the 1996 meeting.
Intelligence services consider him the organizer of the Achille
Lauro cruise ship hijacking in 1985, in which an elderly American
was executed. Abbas lives in Gaza now, but is said to be out of
town.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine, a
PLO faction led by Arafat rival and guerrilla-in-exile George
Habash might show up.
</P>
<P>
   Several Palestinian groups are urging a boycott of the meeting.
They say that Israel should not dictate to them how to form their
goals and that they have already revised their charter.
</P>
<P>
   But even moderate Palestinian politicians, like Shuaibi, have
had what the U.S. and Israeli officials have considered outlaw
pasts. They were fighters against Israel in Lebanon or served
repeated terms in Israeli jails. Some were on the run with their
military leader, Yasser Arafat, now president of the Palestinian
National Authority.
</P>
<P>
   While many Israelis disagree with the procedures laid out for
the meeting, they do not seem to mind that Clinton is meeting the
group itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arafat is as much a terrorist as any of them,'' says right
wing Israeli parliament member Reuven Rivlin. ``It's not who you
are talking to, but what you are doing (that matters).''
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, Andrew Young lost his job as U.S. Ambassador to the
United Nations because he met with PLO representatives in New York.
But, Israeli political scientist Efraim Inbar notes that when
former Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin shook Arafat's hand during a
1993 White House ceremony sealing the Oslo accords, it made it
acceptable for Americans to meet openly with the PLO.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Israelis, he said, who gave Arafat his ``kosher
certificate.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
