<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CONYERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONE WATERGATE PANEL VETERAN IS IMPORTANT FORCE FOR DEMOCRATS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-HYDE, IMPEACH-MOOD, IMPEACH-LEWINSKY,
IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-CLINTON, IMPEACH-VIDEO, IMPEACH-LAMEDUCKS,
IMPEACH-DEBATE, ROSENTHAL-COLUMN, BAKER-COLUMN) 
(th) 
 By JULIAN E. BARNES    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As he presides over the Judiciary Committee's
Democrats, speaking in a deliberative cadence, Rep. John Conyers
Jr., the ranking minority member, projects a quiet tone and almost
disinterested demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   The Michigan Democrat, the only Watergate veteran on the
committee, has shouldered the task of leading the committee's
Democrats, a normally fractious group credited with never letting a
view go unexpressed. And Conyers' loose hand has meant that he
seldom reels in committee members when their monologues take them
in peculiar directions.
</P>
<P>
   But he remains an important back-room dealer for the Democrats
on the Judiciary Committee. It was Minority Leader Dick Gephardt
who took control of the Democratic response last summer and who has
remained in charge of keeping his caucus together.
</P>
<P>
   In private meetings, however, Conyers takes the lead in
suggesting strategies for minority members on the committee and his
views often, although not always, carry the day, colleagues said.
</P>
<P>
   Conyers' early strategy was to shift the focus from Clinton to
Starr when ever possible. Even before the Judiciary Committee's
inquiry began, Conyers took up the well-known list of charges that
the prosecutor's inquiry was tainted by leaks and ties to
conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   In his statement to the committee Thursday evening, Conyers
offered a plea to moderate Republicans to vote against impeachment
and again criticized Starr for delving into sexual details, calling
him the ``occasionally obsessive counsel.''
</P>
<P>
   Conyers has argued that Starr abused his powers and launched
investigations into matters best left alone. He has gone so far as
to argue that Starr's decision to probe Clinton's extramarital
affair was worse than Clinton's decision to initiate it.
</P>
<P>
   The day Starr appeared before the Judiciary Committee, Conyers
was attacking Starr before the prosecutor had a chance to open his
mouth. Conyers condemned the referral as ``tawdry, salacious and
unnecessarily graphic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all that we had in the beginning, it was only Starr,''
Conyers said Thursday. ``And his excesses were pretty apparent to
all.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the Detroit lawyer, whose district includes
impoverished parts of the city and well-to-do Grosse Pointe, made
it plain that he is not finished with Starr. He plans to turn the
committee's attention again to the independent counsel during next
year's discussion on renewing the statute that created the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``The methods Starr employed will be studied with great detail
long after the impeachment process itself,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The only member of the Judiciary Committee to weigh the articles
of impeachment against President Richard Nixon and Clinton,
Conyers' service on the Watergate committee has at times appeared
as much a liability as an asset.
</P>
<P>
   His scathing comments against Nixon have come back if not to
haunt him, at least to make off-the-cuff defenses of Clinton more
difficult. Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., the Judiciary Committee
chairman, invoked Conyers' Watergate-era words several times,
including during a debate over whether to limit Charles Ruff's role
in the committee inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the charges of hypocrisy, Conyers firmly believes his
experience with Watergate has been an asset. And, Conyers has not
so gently reminded his Republican colleagues: ``Watergate was not
about an extramarital affair.''
</P>
<P>
   Faced with some of the most partisan Republicans in Congress on
the Judiciary Committee, Conyers' assigned task has never been seen
as easy or perhaps even possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have I failed?'' Conyers said, his voice tinged ever so
slightly with sarcasm directed toward his Republican colleagues.
``Yeah, I failed to persuade any of the 21 Republicans to consider
more reasonably the fact that even if the whole narrative of Ken
Starr's was assumed to be accurate, there would be nothing that
would reach an impeachable offense.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
