<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ECKERSLEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECKERSLEY GOES OUT SATISFIED HE DID THE JOB   WELL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ As he pulled up to a parking meter outside Fenway Park
Thursday, Dennis Eckersley fumbled around for change like any other
fan attending an event at the 600 Club.
</P>
<P>
   For him, admission to the exclusive club was still free because
for one last time, he was the chief attraction. But soon he became
a civilian. At an 11 a..m. press conference, Eckersley announced
what had been expected after the Red Sox declined to offer him
arbitration: After 24 years, the party's over.
</P>
<P>
   It was during the long drive from his home in Sudbury that it
began to sink in.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that kept coming to me on the way to the ballpark
was how much I loved baseball and how much I'm going to miss it,''
he said as he made his retirement official. ``A big part of my life
is behind me. I'm looking to the next part.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to say goodbye. You almost need some help. I
finished good, and that's a nice memory. But I'm looking at the
whole picture now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not quite ready to be reflective. Right now I'm just going
to concentrate on the good stuff. The stories are quite frankly
getting out of hand. How I punched out so many people; how I was
the baddest dude in the league. What I had was a run, a good run. I
had some magic that keep me around for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   The magic, of course, was in Eckersley's arm _ and heart and
guts. That's why he's a shoo-in for the Hall Of Fame. For almost a
quarter-century, in Cleveland, Boston, Chicago (Cubs), Oakland, St.
Louis, and, finally, Boston again, he transformed himself from a
premier starting pitcher into one of the most devastating relievers
in baseball history, coping with alcoholism as he came back from
the depths. A 20-game winner for the 1978 Red Sox, Eckersley went
on to register the third-highest save total ever _ 390, trailing
only Lee Smith (478) and John Franco (397). He won the 1992 Cy
Young and American League Most Valuable Player Awards for his epic
1992 season with Oakland, when he posted 51 saves in 54 chances.
And he made the most pitching appearances in baseball history _
1,071. Along with his career 197-171 won-lost recordf (48-41 as a
reliever), all that gives him a guaranteed membership card in
Cooperstown.
</P>
<P>
   But on his second tour of duty with the Red Sox, Eckersley
became the setup man for Tom Gordon last season. He wound up with a
4-1 record, 1 save, and a 4.76 ERA. Now 44, he said he'd like to
return for one more year, but only with the Red Sox. When general
manager Dan Duquette told him this week that the Sox wanted
longer-term options in their bullpen, Eckersley mulled his options
before deciding that this was it. Now he'll be free to spend more
time with his family _ wife Nancy, and children Mandee (22, from
his first marriage), Jake (8), and Alexandia (2) _ and to savor his
credentials.
</P>
<P>
   But then, Eckersley never bothered with numbers. He dwelled on
winning. And perhaps that's what he'll miss most.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just starting to get the feel of what it's like when you
quit,'' he said. ``Initially, it was like, `Wow!' But now I realize
the pressure is off. I woke up one morning and had just started
gearing back. All of a sudden, I didn't feel like running. I
started thinking about my family. I realize that once you retire,
that's all that matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Eckersley has been waiting to hear those words for 18
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to a summer trip to the Cape,'' she said.
``We're never had one. Once he gets over the initial feeling that
it's over, things will be fine. We're becoming a tight family. And
he knows he can do things without the interruption of baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Living with the Eck has been no picnic, she added. Her husband
had a drinking problem in the '80s and lived life on the edge much
too much. She's seen him rise and fall and then rise again. That's
the best part.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he won that MVP Award, that did it for me,'' said Nancy.
``It really sticks. It came after he had really achieved a lot.
He'd been through starting and had done so-so. He went to the
bullpen and did well but got hurt. Then he came back as a
champion.''
</P>
<P>
   Eckersley said he'd been around too long to pinpoint the
highlights of his career with the Red Sox _ 1978-84 and last
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first arrived,'' said Eckersley, ``it was like a
coming-out party for me. I had played in Cleveland. But I had no
idea of what the big leagues was. This place was an awakening, and
I'll remember those times (1978, when the Sox lost the AMerican
League East title to the Yankees in a one-game playoff). It was a
great team, one of the best I ever played for. I'll always remember
the 1978 team.''
</P>
<P>
   And what of his return?
</P>
<P>
   ``You're lucky to be in the big leagues, much less play where
you live,'' he said. ``I was lucky to finish up here. To come out
of it now is like being rescued. I'm glad it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   It was in his second incarnation that Eckersley earned his most
enduring fame. Rescued from the scrap heap in Oakland, he pioneered
the role of the one-inning closer. He also perfected it, as
evidenced by the A's three straight World Series appearances
(1988-90) and one world championship (1989).
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't really take credit for it,'' said Eckersley. ``Tony La
Russa did it with me, and it changed the game. A short man 1 1/3
inning, mamixum. That is what relief pitching is today.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was smart. You lasted longer. You were ready to pitch (more
often) and you were more effective. Problem is, no one can keep it
up all the time. I did it in 1992, but that was the end of it.''
</P>
<P>
   As parting gifts, Eckersley received a Red Sox uniform and the
apparent promise of a spot in the organization, if he is
interested.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to thank Dennis for coming home to the Red Sox and
being a part of the family for this past year,'' said general
manager Dan Duquette. ``I know he has a great future ahead of him,
whatever he decides to do. He's a real professional.''
</P>
</TEXT>
