<HEADLINE>
NINTH `STAR TREK' VOYAGE BUMPY FOR CASUAL FANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - ``Captain, Captain, the hypothermal vents in the
positronic metaphasics are threatening the flux levels of the
tachyon harmonics, and the substrata may go
supercalifragilisticexpialadosis!''
</P>
<P>
   Dialogue like that would be music to my ears if I were a Trekker
and had the slightest idea what they were talking about.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Star Trek'' movie series has always flown along that thin
warp line between working in enough in jokes and technically starry
references to keep the loyal fans happy and making the story simple
and exciting enough for non-fans to follow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Star Trek: Insurrection'' plunges across that line with a
Trekker-pleasing, jargon-intensive story that should satisfy the
cult but leave outsiders wondering: Are they actually speaking
English?
</P>
<P>
   ``Star Trek: Insurrection'' also challenges the tough odds of
being an odd-numbered movie in the series (No. 9). ``Trek''
insiders promote the theory that the even numbers are the good ones
</P>
<P>
   and the odd numbers the bad ones.
</P>
<P>
   To disarm that attitude, director Jonathan Frakes (who also
plays Commander Riker) overloads the movie with Trekker trivia.
Along the way, he sacrifices the story.
</P>
<P>
   That tale concerns a planet that's a demi-paradise, whose Ba'ku
inhabitants live in a technology-rejecting society.
</P>
<P>
   But the Federation and Ru'afo (F. Murray Abraham) of the Son'a
are plotting to take over that planet.
</P>
<P>
   When Captain Picard (Patrick Stewart) and his crew intervene,
they are ordered to leave the Ba'ku planet and must decide which to
violate: their orders or a Prime Directive.
</P>
<P>
   That story is just barely substantial enough for a thoughtful
science-fiction movie. The ideas and analogies to our world are
there, as they always are in ``Star Trek'' stories, but they're not
presented in particularly dynamic fashion.
</P>
<P>
   What gives the movie its grace is how well Picard's crew works
together, with Worf (Michael Dorn) and Data (Brent Spiner)
providing just enough humor, and Picard enough character
dimensions, to humanize the technologically enwebbed proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Star Trek: Insurrection'' needs those amusing touches because
of the sluggish pace and the tinny special effects.
</P>
<P>
   If you're not already a ``Star Trek'' fan, this isn't the best
one to start with. You'll be able to follow the story even if
you're not ``Trek'' conversant, but it's a bumpy ride.
</P>
<P>
   If you are a fan, you're probably reading this standing in line
at the theater. You won't be sorry you went, but then, are you
ever? Even the bad ``Star Treks'' satisfy the Trekker urge.
</P>
<P>
   Rated PG, ``Star Trek: Insurrection'' has a few moments when the
violence approaches semi-gruesome. 2 stars. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
