u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRININTY-TALKS-BOS &LR;      12-10 0377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRININTY-TALKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRINITY INVESTMENT WON'T CONFIRM OPPENHEIMER RUMORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Trinity Investment Management Corp. has intensified
talks with suitors, but it declined to comment on persistent rumors
it would be acquired by New York-based OppenheimerFunds Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Trinity's seven executive owners, who are spread out across
Boston, Denver, and the firm's headquarters in Bellefonte, Pa.,
told clients in late 1997 that they were seeking a new corporate
owner. Trinity chairman and chief executive Stanford Calderwood,
78, who owns more than half of the firm, wants Trinity sold before
he retires.
</P>
<P>
   Citing conversations with Wall Street bankers, a mutual fund
source in Boston named OppenheimerFunds, a fund company with $97
billion in assets under management, as Trinity's likely future
owner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can confirm that over the last several months, we have been
in serious talks with several entities,'' said Trinity spokesman
Richard Tucker Thursday in Boston , where the firm's marketing
operations are located. The firm retained New York investment bank
Goldman, Sachs in March to look at strategic options, Tucker said,
but no sale deal had yet been signed.
</P>
<P>
   OppenheimerFunds is owned by Massachusetts Mutual Life Insurance
Co. of Springfield. MassMutual spokesman James Lacey said it was
against company policy to comment on any deals under discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Boston is home to a host of privately held investment firms that
are likely to be sold off as their owners near retirement. Such
sales are more than estate planning _ they are also part of a trend
of consolidation in the investment industry.
</P>
<P>
   Trinity uses computerized, quantitative models to manage $8
billion for over 100 institutional clients, mainly state and
corporate pension funds.
</P>
<P>
   By selling to Oppenheimer, rather than to an investment holding
company, Trinity's owners may win a quick sale amid calmer markets
but greater tax burdens, too. For its part, Oppenheimer would gain
in Trinity coveted access to pension plan clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could probably go straight out and sell the business,''
Tucker said. ``But we want the right strategic combination.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
