<SLUG> BC-REDSEA-MOVIE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANY WAY YOU SLICE IT, A SPECIAL-EFFECTS TREAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON RENFROE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - One of the more dramatic events of the Old Testament
required dramatic cinematic interpretations: the parting of the Red
Sea and the walk across by the children of Israel. This is how two
films tackled it: &QL; 
 &QL; 
``The Ten Commandments'' (1956) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many would say the Red Sea parting was the most memorable scene
in Cecil B. DeMille's epic. For years, viewers would wonder, ``How
did they do that?''
</P>
<P>
   In his autobiography, DeMille makes it sound simple: Over the
course of 18 months and by spending $1 million (big bucks in those
days), shots ``from the Red Sea itself and in the studio were
combined.''
</P>
<P>
   A little more light is shed in Charles Higham's 1973 biography
of DeMille. He says the Red Sea shots were ``matched to the pouring
of tanks into a vast adjoining set, then the shots reversed as the
water rushed out.''
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, a viewing of the scene today is a lot less mystifying
than it used to be. But on the 1956 big screen, shot in
VistaVision, it must have really wowed 'em. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``The Prince of Egypt'' (1998)
</P>
<P>
   You'd think, heck, in a cartoon they just draw the darned thing.
Maybe in years past, but this is the age of digital animation, and
nothing's as easy as it looks.
</P>
<P>
   DreamWorks required 10 digital artists, two programmers and 16
traditional animators to create the one scene. The studio claims it
took 318,000 hours of rendering time to create the 7-minute
sequence.
</P>
<P>
   New computer tools were developed to blend two- and
three-dimensional artwork. In the end, the parting of the Red Sea
combined traditional animation, traditional painting techniques and
3-D computer animation.
</P>
<P>
   One other detail: This ``parting'' will have more of a circular
pattern than a split. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
