<SLUG> BC-NATSEMI-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATIONAL SEMICONDUCTOR HAS SMALLER-THAN-EXPECTED LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ National Semiconductor Corp. reported a
smaller-than-expected second-quarter loss Thursday excluding
one-time items, but sales were still down and executives remained
cautious about the company's outlook.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter ended Nov. 29, National Semiconductor reported a
deficit of $94.4 million, compared with earnings of $28.9 million,
or 17 cents a share, in the same period a year earlier. Sales fell
29 percent, to $510.1 million from $719.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   The quarter included previously announced one-time charges
related to plant closings and the termination of a foundry
agreement with IBM. Without the charges, the net loss for the
quarter would have been $48.6 million. Analysts expected the
company to lose 49 cents a share, according to First Call Corp.,
which tracks company earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of National Semiconductor fell $2, to $14.625.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a difficult year for National Semiconductor, with
many of its factories running well below capacity. The company's
microprocessor business suffered from a glut in personal computers
earlier in the year, while its analog products were hurt by the
Asian economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The company also lost market share in the key networking segment
because it was slow to introduce new products. But National gained
ground in the fast-growing market for computers that cost less than
$1,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm quite pleased with the progress we made in the second
quarter,'' Brian Halla, National Semiconductor's chairman,
president and chief executive, said in a telephone conference call
with securities analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The execution of our manufacturing and Cyrix groups, working
together, exceeded our expectations and brought us along much
quicker on our road to profit recovery,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   National acquired Cyrix in November 1997 in a bid to move into
the more profitable realm of microprocessor chips.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-98 2007EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
