<DOCNO> NYT19981210.0405 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3881 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARTREK-BOOK-AZR &LR;      12-10 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARTREK-BOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TREK' CLOUT SPANS GLOBE, AUTHOR FINDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVE WALKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - With the holidays closing in, I'll use the release of
``Star Trek: Insurrection'' to suggest a fine gift for anyone
interested in the ``Trek'' saga(s), science fiction, television,
our culture in general.
</P>
<P>
   It's a book called ``Future Perfect: How Star Trek Conquered
Planet Earth,'' by Jeff Greenwald. Released over the summer by
Viking Press, it's the best writing about television I've read in a
month of parsecs, although I wouldn't know if a parsec is
measurement of time or distance, neither or both.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, I'm not nuts about space opera. But Greenwald, author
of several cool travel books as well as articles and columns in
such cutting-edge publications as ``Wired,'' ``Details'' and
``Salon,'' made me care about a topic that normally drives me to
dreamland.
</P>
<P>
   Greenwald spanned the globe to chase down the meaning of ``Star
Trek,'' a grand global myth now powering through its fourth decade.
En route, he interviewed fans in Germany, Japan and Ind ia _ not to
mention Patrick Stewart, Michael Dorn, Leonard Nimoy, Kurt
Vonnegut, Jr., Arthur C. Clarke, and none other than the Dalai
Lama.
</P>
<P>
   I started reading ``Future Perfect'' somewhere in the middle.
(It's a terrible habit called `'surfing for the good bits.'' Any
idea where I might've picked that up?) But Greenwald's writing is
so supple, and his wit so wicked, I quickly found myself sucked in.
This almost never happens when I book-surf, but I eventually turned
back to the beginning and read the whole thing, in just a couple of
sittings, front-to-back.
</P>
<P>
   While making his way to an audience with the Dalai Lama _ with
whom he also discussed such ``Tre''k-tangential topics as the
Internet, human cloning and artificial intelligence _ Greenwald
witnessed a Klingon wedding in Germany, visited a space-themed
nightclub called NASA in Bangalore, India, and hung with an
intrepid British rocketeer pursuing his own personal space program.
</P>
<P>
   While there's enough inside-the-soundstage interviews with
``Trek'' actors, writer and producers to satisfy any hard-core fan,
the most interesting chapters deal with far-flung rerun-watchers,
whom Greenwald discovered to be ``educated, active and insightful
people, and not at all the kinds of people who need to get a
life,'' he said in a recent telephone interview from his Oakland
home. ``They're people who have lives, and ``Star Trek'' is a big
part of their life.''
</P>
<P>
   According to legend, Gene Roddenberry, a former airline pilot
and motorcycle cop, sold the original ``Star Trek '' series to NBC
as kind of an interstellar ``Bonanza.'' It might've begun as mere
(and marginally successful) TV product, but the impact that
frequently cheesy little series and its sequels have had on the
world is significant and measurable, Greenwald says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hundreds of millions of dollars are now spent by people in
technology, in industries like computers and aerospace, who are
trying to build what they saw on ``Star Trek,'' said Greenwald.
``It's life imitating art.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, ``There's an amazing feedback loop going on here
that's unique in human history,'' he said. ``The people creating
the mythology _ the writers and actors and producers of ``Star
Trek'' _ get real-time feedback from the audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if _ in the ancient days of Greek and Roman
myths, of African myths, Hindu myths _ people writing the myths
ever even know who their audience would be, or how it would affect
them.''
</P>
<P>
   The resulting creative synergy has created an ongoing phenomenon
that deserves just this kind of detailed examination. Greenwald
writes with humility and great humor, and has a veteran travel
writer's gift for transporting readers to strange places _ other
worlds, even _ and showing them around.
</P>
<P>
   (For example, visit the online version of this story _ at
www.azcentral.com _ for a link to a wonderful piece Greenwald wrote
for ``Salon'' about his recent cameo on the NBC sitcom
``NewsRadio'').
</P>
<P>
   Odd, but Greenwald claims to be no more than a casual fan of the
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one of the things that's important about ``Star Trek''
is that, when you look at a bunch of murals on the walls of ruins
in Pompeii, you don't have to like the paintings to appreciate how
they are as a record of their society,'' he said. ``That's true of
``Star rek'' as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if you're not a big fan of the show, you have to
appreciate the story cycle, and how it is a reflection of our
society and culture.''
</P>
<P>
   If you're into ``Star Trek'' _ or have a friend or loved one who
is who you'd like to understand better _ treat yourself to ``Future
Perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, it'd make an ideal stocking-stuffer for the Vulcan
who has everything.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
Contact Dave Walker via e-mail at dave.walker(at)pni.com &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
