u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AETNA11-COX     12-10 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AETNA11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Aetna buying Prudential's health unit
 &HT;    By Andy Miller
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Aetna would double its managed-care membership in
metro Atlanta and Georgia by acquiring Prudential HealthCare in a
$1 billion deal.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna's plan to purchase Prudential's health care business,
announced Thursday, would make the combined entity the leading HMO
and overall managed-care company in metro Atlanta. Statewide,
Aetna/Prudential would rival the size of Blue Cross and Blue Shield
of Georgia in managed-care members.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the acquisition would make Aetna the No. 1 health
insurer, covering one in 10 Americans, the company said. It would
add 6.6 million Prudential members _ about 5 million of them in
managed-care plans_ ballooning Aetna's health-benefits membership
to 22.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the proverbial offer we couldn't refuse,'' said Richard
Huber, chairman and CEO of Hartford, Conn.-based Aetna. ``We've
been talking to Prudential for a long time. The price has come
down.''
</P>
<P>
   Aetna officials said the purchase, for $500 million in cash and
$500 million in debt, gives it new health care members at a cost of
about $200 apiece. That's much lower than the per-member price the
company paid for New York Life Insurance Co.'s health care business
earlier this year _ about $1 billion, or $600 a member. Aetna's
acquisition of U.S. Healthcare in 1996 for $8.9 billion cost it
even more per customer.
</P>
<P>
   That deal accelerated Aetna's transition from traditional
fee-for-service health insurance to managed care, which aims to cut
costs.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna shares fell $1.62 1/2 Thursday, closing at $79.18 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   Prudential, in the process of converting to a publicly traded
company from one owned by policyholders, had been seeking to sell
its money-losing health care business to concentrate on becoming a
global financial company.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're getting Prudential's members at an incredibly low
price,'' Ira Zuckerman, a Nutmeg Securities Ltd. analyst, told
Bloomberg Business News.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Prudential was reported in talks to sell its
business to Louisville-based Humana. Another previous suitor
reportedly was California-based WellPoint Health Networks, which is
buying Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   The deal would vault Aetna U.S. Healthcare into a top-three
position among managed-care providers in nine states, including
Georgia, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Prudential, whose health care headquarters is in New Jersey, has
more than 270,000 managed-care members in Atlanta, most of whom are
in its HMO or a similar plan, called Point-of-Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prudential has had one of the better health plans here in
Atlanta,'' said Lew Yeouze of consulting firm William M. Mercer.
</P>
<P>
   Among Prudential's current health care clients in Atlanta are
SunTrust, Georgia-Pacific, NationsBank, BellSouth, Emory University
and Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna, by doubling in membership, would be able to negotiate
better deals with doctors and hospitals, said Brent Layton of
Atlanta consulting firm Layton &AMP; Associates. Those providers would
receive more patients through those contracts, but their
reimbursement may be less, he said. That way, Aetna can offer a
lower premium to attract employers.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna spokesman Walt Cherniak said the acquisition's effect on
pricing would be hard to predict. But he added: ``We hope our size
will make us more affordable.''
</P>
<P>
   Aetna's HMO premiums increased about 7 percent for Atlanta-area
employers for next year, while its other health insurance products
climbed about 10 percent. That range of increases has been typical
for the entire insurance industry, reeling from losses in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But such insurer consolidation could lead to fewer choices of
health plans for employers _ and thus their workers, Yeouze said.
``We're getting toward a real end game'' on consolidation, he
added.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction also makes Aetna the nation's largest provider
of dental benefits, more than doubling its coverage to more than 15
million people, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna said it could cut about 1,000 to 2,000 jobs from
Prudential HealthCare's work force of 16,000 over the next two
years.
</P>
<P>
   Prudential HealthCare has 540 employees in Atlanta. Its local
headquarters is on Paces Ferry in Vinings. Aetna's local health
care headquarters is in the North Point area of Alpharetta.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition, subject to regulatory approval, is expected to
close in the second quarter of 1999. Huber said he doesn't foresee
regulatory snags. ``This is still a very fragmented industry,'' he
said. ``It's a highly competitive environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Frino, a senior research analyst with A.M. Best Co., told
Dow Jones News Service that the timing and size of the Aetna
acquisition are surprising.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought they'd do a smaller, local-market type deal, but I
guess they saw this as a great opportunity, given the price,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna will have to prove, though, that it can integrate both
NYLCare and Prudential, Frino said. ``That's the big question about
all of this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna encountered widespread problems in integrating U.S.
Healthcare. Earlier this year, about 20,000 metro Atlanta members
of Aetna failed to receive new ID cards in time for the new year,
or weren't entered in the Aetna computer system.
</P>
<P>
   The company doesn't expect the same problems with integrating
Prudential, Huber said. ``You get better the more (acquisitions)
you do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
