<HEADER>
A3924 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-KOLLAR11-     12-10 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-KOLLAR11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kollar's line plays in his style
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With Jackson Browne playing on the radio in his
office, it's tempting to think that Bill Kollar has an easy-going
demeanor. But after watching him yell on the practice field, it's
obvious that he's anything but mellow.
</P>
<P>
   There's more to Kollar, the Falcons defensive line coach, than
his trademark hollering, and defensive end Chuck Smith knows that
as well as anyone on this team.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's genius to his madness,'' Smith said. ``He yells, but
for a reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Kollar, the senior member of the Falcons coaching staff, arrived
in 1990. When Smith arrived as a second-round draft choice in '92,
they mixed like gunpowder and matches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember being in meetings, and I thought him and Chuck were
going to come to blows,'' defensive end Lester Archambeau said.
``They both care so much about what they're doing. It's like
anything else. You're going to butt heads, but Chuck has developed
into a great player.''
</P>
<P>
   Kollar, 46, has become very adept at developing great defensive
lines.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons are ranked No. 2 in the league against the run,
yielding 76.6 yards per game, and the line has contributed mightily
to that statistic. Last year, Atlanta was No. 8 against the run,
and the defensive linemen accounted for 43 of the team's
franchise-record 55 sacks.
</P>
<P>
   In short, Kollar's linemen play as he did when he was with the
Bengals (1974-76) and the Bucs (1977-81) _ like madmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't one of those guys who was that big and strong, so I
always ended up having to work hard to get where I was getting,''
he said. ``I've always been sort of high-energy. I can't just go
out and stand on the practice field. I don't give a (darn) what
other people are doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever it takes to get my guys going ... if that means
hollering or whatever, that's what I'll do. No matter what, I'm
responsible for what happens with the defensive line. If you go out
and work hard ... you can be proud of what you put on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, too, is a prideful man.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had some knock-down drag-outs,'' he said. ``We had our
words years ago, and we moved on. He keeps wanting to do better.
The thing is, he says what he means, and I respect that.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no mixing words with Kollar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Abe Gibron was my defensive line coach (at Tampa Bay), and he
was a guy who would stay on you,'' he said. ``A lot of my coaching
style comes from Abe. If you let people slide, they'll try to slide
as much as they can. But if you're pushing them to get better,
they're going to get better. You rely on their pride.''
</P>
<P>
   Kollar and his wife, Jan, love living in Atlanta. Although he's
had offers to coach elsewhere the last two seasons, he has stayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The organization has been nothing but great to me,'' he said.
``I had chances to go other places, but unless you get fired ... or
get a great opportunity ... I'm not the type to pull up stakes
every two years. If (a chance to be a coordinator) comes, great; if
it doesn't, it won't bother me. I like the hands-on action of
coaching guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Kollar won't be able attend his oldest son's graduation at SMU
on Saturday. Chad was a defensive back there for three years before
a neck and shoulder injury prevented him from playing this season.
Kollar's other son, Clint, is a junior linebacker at Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   Kollar is pleased that both sons appear to be on their way to
high-paying jobs in the white-collar world.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, he'll gladly remain a member of the proletariat. And
he'll continue to wear sweat pants and a sweatshirt on the practice
field, whether it's 50 degrees or 95.
</P>
<P>
   ``My legs are too damned skinny to go out in shorts, and I like
sweating to where you feel like you're in the action, so I wear the
sweats,'' he said. ``I like it where you're sweating like crazy
just like those guys. I'm always into it. From Day 1, that's how
I've been.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
