</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELECTIONS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Money laundering allegations against Voinovich go to special
investigator
 &HT;    By Jim Bebbington
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The Ohio Elections Commission on Thursday voted
to name a special investigator to look into allegations that Gov.
George Voinovich and others laundered 1994 campaign money.
</P>
<P>
   The commission also dismissed a second complaint filed by
Democrats seeking to participate in the case.
</P>
<P>
   The seven-member commission unanimously decided to have a
special investigator with subpoena power look into allegations that
Voinovich and others laundered about $60,000 from his 1994 campaign
to reimburse Voinovich's brother, Paul, and a lobbyist for payments
made to a campaign supporter.
</P>
<P>
   The commission did not say who the investigator would be or when
the appointment would be made, but officials said he would have 90
days to look into the case and would be given wide latitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll look at evidence, test responses, and he will determine
his own course,'' said Philip Richter, the commission's executive
director.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for the parties named in the elections complaint all
said they agreed with the appointment of a special investigator and
hoped it would clear up the matter.
</P>
<P>
   At Thurday's preliminary hearing before the commission, they all
reiterated that their clients did nothing wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor did not approve of any diversionary scheme,''
said Voinovich's attorney, David Young.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint filed Oct. 28 by Secretary of State Bob Taft names
George and Paul Voinovich; former lobbyist Michael Fabiano; Frank
Fela, vice president of Paul Voinovich's company; and Vincent
Panichi, Gov. Voinovich's campaign treasurer. The allegations
surfaced in an ongoing FBI and IRS investigation and were forwarded
to Taft by federal authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Young said the person most able to explain what happened,
political consultant Nick Mamais, had died by the time the governor
became aware of the allegations late last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was never an opportunity to go back to Mr. Mamais and
say, `What in the world; how can you explain these bizarre events?'
'' Young told the commission.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint says Gov. Voinovich approved a deal to send
$60,000 to Mamais, who would forward money to Fabiano and Paul
Voinovich to reimburse them for payments made to a campaign
supporter, Anthony ``Ray'' Gallagher.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign reported the Mamais expenditure as voter
registration services.
</P>
<P>
   Panichi told a federal grand jury last year he was present when
Voinovich approved the deal, but he recanted some of that in a
recent affidavit to the commission, saying he did not know what the
governor heard during the meeting and that he may have
misinterpreted the governor's comments.
</P>
<P>
   Panichi's attorney, Donald Brey, said the parties need to know
more about what has come out of the federal investigation in order
to defend their clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should see the court order that sent the information to the
commission,'' Brey said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the grand jury testimonies included with the complaint
have portions deleted and that could lead to inaccurate
conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're talking about who said what to whom, you have to see
it in context,'' Brey said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Court Judge Sandy Beckwith issued an order, the
contents of which are sealed, allowing Taft's office to use the FBI
and IRS information to enforce Ohio election law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beyond that, we have no authority to discuss it,'' said John
Bender, the secretary of state's election counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Commission member Norton Webster criticized the handling of the
information from the federal investigation, saying he is ``troubled
the Department of Justice did not come forward earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unfair to the governor. I think it was unfair to his
opponent,'' Webster said.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint was filed just five days before the Nov. 3
election and came to light the day before the vote in which
Voinovich defeated challenger Mary Boyle for a U.S. Senate seat.
</P>
<P>
   After voting to appoint an investigator, the commission
unanimously dismissed a similar complaint filed by labor leader
Harold Nichols. Nichols' attorney, Don McTigue, argued against the
dismissal but said afterward he was satisfied an investigator would
take up the case now.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
