</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORWOOD11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Norwood: I'll vote to impeach
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ One of the two Georgia Republicans in the House
targeted by Democrats as potential opponents of impeachment said
Thursday he will vote to impeach President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charlie Norwood, a conservative from Augusta, broke his
silence on the matter to say he believes Clinton is guilty of
perjury and obstruction of justice, charges included in the four
proposed articles of impeachment under consideration by the House
Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``My intention is to vote for impeachment,'' Norwood said in a
telephone interview from Augusta.
</P>
<P>
   The 57-year-old Republican, in his second term, said he could
hold his tongue no longer in the wake of his appearance on a list
20 to 30 undecided Republicans the White House and other Democrats
planned to lobby.
</P>
<P>
   Norwood said he considers the list, leaked to news organizations
earlier this week, one more piece of misinformation put out by the
``tricksters at the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said they believed Norwood might have been open to
persuasion because his district is more than a third
African-American.
</P>
<P>
   Black Americans overwhelmingly oppose impeachment, according to
public opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   But Norwood said his constituents are strongly in favor of
impeachment. And, he said, ``I have not had one black Georgian from
the 10th District come up to me and say, 'Don't vote for
impeachment.'''
</P>
<P>
   Norwood is the fourth Georgia Republican representative to
commit publicly to voting for impeachment. The others are Bob Barr,
a member of the Judiciary Committee, Mac Collins and John Linder.
</P>
<P>
   Two Georgia Democrats in the House, John Lewis and Cynthia
McKinney, have said they will oppose any article of impeachment
approved by the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Saxby Chambliss, the other Georgia Republican on the White House
wish list, indicated he will not make his views on impeachment
known until after the Judiciary Committee votes.
</P>
<P>
   The other members of the Georgia congressional delegation _
Democrat Sanford Bishop and Republicans Newt Gingrich, Jack
Kingston and Nathan Deal _ have not said how they will vote.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
