<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3930 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-ODDS-BOS &LR;      12-10 1186
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-ODDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EFFORT UNDER WAY TO MOLD OPINION IN IMPEACHMENT CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The jostling over the impeachment of President
Clinton fanned out over several fronts Thursday, as the White began
actively courting Republican moderates and interest groups on both
sides of the issue urged members to flood congressional offices
with calls and letters.
</P>
<P>
   With the climactic vote in the full House a week away, the
Democratic National Committee has sent a set of talking points to
state party leaders suggesting they ``write letters right away'' to
their local newspaper and call talk radio programs to speak out
against impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Urge your constituencies to call or write members of Congress,
and remind them that these are not impeachable offenses, and that a
lengthy Senate trial will keep members of Congress from doing what
people sent them to Washington to do,'' according to the talking
points.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, the Christian Coalition dumped the last batch
of more than a quarter-million petitions on Capitol Hill urging
members of the House and the Senate to vote for impeachment. Many
of the petitioners have followed up with calls to their
congressional representative, said coalition Executive Director
Randy Tate.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a Washington-based group called People for the
American Way has mobilized against impeachment, setting up a
toll-free number number this week for people to call to urge their
member of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   As the flurry of lobbying intensified in the shadows of the
impeachment hearings, there was no public change Thursday among the
20 to 30 Republicans who are undecided whether to vote for
impeachment, including Representative Charles F. Bass of New
Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   With Republicans holding an 21-seat majority in the House and at
least three Democrats expected to vote for impeachment, Clinton
will need the votes of at least 14 Republicans. Some Democratic
aides say that as many as seven Democrats may vote for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials, worried that the president may end up on
the short end of a close vote, Thursday said they would open their
doors to any undecided House member who wants to talk to Clinton's
attorneys, Charles Ruff and Gregory Craig, or other senior
officials about the law and the facts of the president's case.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, officials sent every member of the House a copy of
Clinton's 184-page rebuttal document that was delivered to the
House Judiciary Committee this week. Senior White House officials
also burned up the phone lines talking to House Republicans and
Democrats about the effort to get a vote on censure to the floor of
the House as an alternative to impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   White House Press Secretary Joseph Lockhart said it was ``very
hard to assess'' whether the administration was making progress in
rounding up the votes to avoid impeachment. ``We believe that to
the extent there are people with open minds and open hearts, that
this is a convincing case.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite some clamor for Clinton to make a personal appeal to
House members before he leaves Saturday on a four-day trip to the
Middle East, White House aides indicated it was unlikely. More
possible, some said, was that Clinton might reach out to moderates
with phone calls while overseas or make some sort of statement
before the full House vote next week.
</P>
<P>
   One undecided moderate Republican, Representative Rick A. Lazio
of New York, will decided Friday whether to accompany the president
on the trip. Lazio was a replacement for retiring House Speaker
Newt Gingrich, who had been invited to join Clinton, but asked
Lazio to go in his place.
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, House Minority Leader Richard A.
Gephardt of Missouri began calling some of the 31 Democrats who
voted for the impeachment inquiry in October, and plans to make
more calls. The congressman also is expected to formally announce
his opposition to impeachment on NBC's ``Meet the Press'' on
Sunday, and plead with Republicans to bring a censure vote to the
floor, said a source close to the leadership office.
</P>
<P>
   At least three Democrats _ Representatives Gene Taylor of
Mississippi, Virgil Goode of Virginia and Ralph Hall of Texas _ say
they plan to vote for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor's chief of staff, Wayne Weidie, said the congressman
believes that ``censure is a copout. If people are allowed to lie
under oath, our judicial system would crumble.''
</P>
<P>
   At least two Democrats are undecided on impeachment, including
Representatives Charles W. Stenholm of Texas and William Lipinksi
of Illinois, they said Thursday through aides.
</P>
<P>
   Though Representative Jack Metcalf, a Republican of Washington,
had appeared on a White House list of undecided Republicans, an
aide said the congressman would vote in favor of at least one
article of impeachment _ the charge that Clinton lied to a grand
jury.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Ratcliff, a DNC spokeswoman, said many Americans have
not focused on the possibility that Clinton may be impeached.
``It's a very serious issue and people have been calling and saying
what can we do to help.''
</P>
<P>
   The literature contends that the entire impeachment process was
being ``controlled and manipulated by partisan elements of the
Republican party led by House Majority Whip Tom DeLay of Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative Dan Miller, a Florida Republican and a member of
DeLay's whip organization, said Thursday: ``This is strictly a vote
of conscience.'' In the most the recent conference call with DeLay
on Tuesday, ``we were told not to whip it,'' said Miller, who
personally is ``leaning'' to impeach the president.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said he has no idea where the counts of Republican
pro-impeachment votes are coming from, since neither he nor any of
the other whips have been instructed to contact or lobby members.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Coalition's Tate said his group was not lobbying
members of Congress, but certain individuals were calling their
representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Robert Ney, whose Eastern Ohio district includes
the conservative but union-affiliated residents of steel and coal
mining towns, has seen a surge in phone calls from constituents in
the last few days.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, ``we received about 250 phone calls from within
the district, and they were running 8-to-1 for impeachment,'' said
Neil Volz, an aide to Ney. ``We're getting even more calls today.''
</P>
<P>
   Bass of New Hampshire is also being flooded with calls, said
Sally Tibbetts, his press secretary. ``The calls have been steady.
In fact, we have been getting calls outside the district and
outside the state.'' Most calls, she said, seemed to be in favor of
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The congressman is always happy to hear from his
constituents,'' said Tibbetts. ``But public opinion is not one of
the things he will weigh heavily as he makes his decision. It will
be based more on the evidence, the testimony and the
recommendations of the Judiciary Committee.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Aaron Zitner and Mary Leonard of the Globe staff contributed to
this story)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-98 2033EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
