<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKWAYS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Landing a Job in France  &HT;       
 By Ilana DeBare  
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  I'd like to move to France but don't know how to find
work there. I have an associate's degree in landscape horticulture
but am willing to take any kind of job. Unfortunately, I don't
speak French. What should I do?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  You've got as steep an uphill climb ahead of you as if
you were you were standing at the foot of les Alpes.
</P>
<P>
   First, there's the eternal Catch-22 of work permits: As in many
countries, foreigners can't legally get work in France unless they
have work permits. But the government won't issue a work permit
unless you already have a job offer in hand.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, because French unemployment is over 10 percent,
you'll be competing with a lot of local people for work.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, the French are notoriously unforgiving of visitors
who don't speak their language.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than any other place in Europe, France will be difficult
to find work if you don't speak the language _ and speak the
language well,'' said Cheryl Matherly, co-author with Robert
Sanborn of ``How to Get a Job in Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Matherly suggests lowering your sights and aiming for temporary
work such as seasonal farm labor.
</P>
<P>
   Joining a grape-harvest crew, for instance, would let you get a
feel for French culture, start learning the language and perhaps
use your horticultural skills to make connections toward a
permanent job.
</P>
<P>
   Jeunesse at Reconstruction, a group that recruits grape pickers
for French vineyards, can be reached by telephone at
33-1-47-70-15-88. Nature et Progres, which provides lists of French
organic farmers seeking temporary help, can be reached by writing 3
Place Pasteur, 84000 Avignon, France.
</P>
<P>
   Other ideas: Check with the trade association for your
profession to see if there's a similar group in France with leads
on horticultural jobs or internships. Pick the brains of anyone you
know with friends in France.
</P>
<P>
   And sign up for classes at a French cultural center like the
Alliance Francaise in San Francisco _ both to start learning French
and to meet other people with an interest or contacts in France.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  Fired Without Notice
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm an independent contractor who was fired by phone call
from my position. However, my contract had said that I would be
given five days' written notice before termination. Can I file an
unpaid-wages claim for those five days of pay?
</P>
<P>
   A: You can't file an unpaid-wages claim because you weren't an
employee: You were a contractor.
</P>
<P>
   But you can pursue your case another way _ by filing a
breach-of-contract suit in small-claims court.
</P>
<P>
   In California, small-claims courts handle disputes of $5,000 or
less. You don't need a lawyer to file a claim. And the small-claims
court in your county can give you instructions about how to file.
</P>
<P>
   Your case sounds straightforward enough that merely filing a
claim may be enough to make the company pay whatever it owes you.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the company is served with a complaint, they will pay up
if they have any brains,'' predicted Stephen Fishman, a Berkeley
attorney and author of ``Wage Slave No More! Law &AMP; Taxes for the
Self-Employed.''
</P>
<P>
   Contractor Factors
</P>
<P>
   Q: I used to work as the word processing coordinator for an
appraisal firm. I was considered an independent contractor and had
a contract that said either party would give 10 days' written
notice before terminating the relationship. One day, I called in
and said I'd be taking the day off because it was a slow day and
that my assistant could handle things. The following day, I was
fired for taking that time off. Was this legal?
</P>
<P>
   A: This situation is more complicated than the previous one
because it raises two separate questions:
</P>
<P>
   _ Did the company violate its contract with you by firing you
without 10 days' notice?
</P>
<P>
   _ Were you incorrectly classified as an independent contractor
to begin with?
</P>
<P>
   On the first question, it does sound like the company violated
your contract by denying you 10 days' notice. And like the
contractor in the previous item, you could pursue that issue in
small-claims court.
</P>
<P>
   But that still leaves the interesting question of whether you
may have been illegally misclassified as a contractor.
</P>
<P>
   The Internal Revenue Service looks at a number of different
things to determine whether someone is legally an employee or a
contractor. One of the main things the IRS considers is whether you
direct and control your work or whether the company does.
</P>
<P>
   ``A hiring firm normally does not have the right to control the
way an IC (independent contractor) performs agreed-upon services,''
Fishman said. ``Its control is limited to accepting or rejecting
the final results.''
</P>
<P>
   In your case, the company's decision to fire you for missing a
day of work seems like the way an employee would be treated, not a
contractor.
</P>
<P>
   That alone wouldn't necessarily jeopardize the company's right
to consider you a contractor. But it's enough of a red flag that
you should consult with a lawyer who is familiar with
employee/contractor issues.
</P>
<P>
   If it turns out you were misclassified, the IRS would refund
half of the Social Security taxes you paid. You also might qualify
retroactively for employee benefits. And you might be owed a heap
of back wages if you worked overtime but were never paid
time-and-a-half for it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send your work and career questions to Ilana DeBare, Workways, San
Francisco Chronicle, 901 Mission St., San Francisco 94103. Or send
e-mail to workways(at sign)sfgate.com. &LR;   &LR; Or call (415) 764-2815. We
can't respond to each query, but we will answer as many in print as
we can. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
