<SLUG> BC-CARSON11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Carson sells Cutex, gets help with debt
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Carson Inc. has sold its Cutex nail care business for $30
million as part of its strategy to focus on its core ethnic
products business.
</P>
<P>
   It's the second major transaction this week for the
Savannah-based company, which has struggled to pay a $50 million
note to Ivax Corp. after Ivax sold its Johnson Products hair care
line to Carson in July.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Carson received an $83 million loan to help
pay the debt, and indications are the loan came from billionaire
George Soros' Quantum Fund. Neither Quantum, one of the world's
largest hedge funds, nor Carson would comment on the source of the
loan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very pleased to have been able to close on the
refinancing of our debt and divest ourselves of Cutex,'' said
Carson Chairman Leroy Keith. ``With those two things we have
accomplished a lot, and it allows us to put our focus and attention
on growing the value of our overall business.''
</P>
<P>
   Warren Beck, an analyst with Cromwell, Miller &AMP; Greer in New
York, said the loan deal ``has to be constructive. This is a
tremendous opportunity to recapture some of the lost ground in the
marketplace. Really, that is the critical focus of management now
that they have cured some of their balance sheet problems.''
</P>
<P>
   The nail care business was sold to Cutex Co., a new entity
formed by San Francisco-based investment firm the Shansby Group.
Carson, however, can continue to sell Cutex nail polish and
treatment through a licensing agreement with Shansby.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had expressed concern that Carson, which makes such
flagship brands as Dark &AMP; Lovely, Magic Shave and Excelle, would
not be able to repay the debt to Ivax.
</P>
<P>
   In September, Merrill Lynch downgraded Carson's stock to
``neutral'' from ``buy.'' The stock, which closed at $3.31 1/4
Thursday, is down from its 52-week high of $10.75 in April.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the company had planned to pay Ivax with proceeds
from a partial equity sale of its South African operations and the
sale of its Cutex and Dermablend lines. But that plan did not
materialize as quickly as the company had expected.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last 18 months, Carson has experienced highs and lows.
It acquired several strong brands, including Cutex and Johnson
Products, and expanded its international operations.
</P>
<P>
   But it also was saddled with more debt and suffered from a
softening in its domestic business. Carson also recently underwent
a management realignment, which included the removal of Joyce Roche
as president, a title assumed by Chief Executive Officer Gregory
Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the $83 million loan has been used to pay off the note
to Ivax, and the rest will be used for general purposes.
</P>
<P>
   The company is already using $8 million from the Cutex sale to
begin repaying some of the $83 million loan. Carson Chief Financial
Officer Robert Pierce said the rest of the proceeds from the sale
will be applied to the remainder of the loan. Pierce said the
company was no longer ``aggressively'' trying to sell the
Dermablend line, ``at least for the time being.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
