A3948 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFLBEST11-COX     12-10 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLBEST11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Will Parcells fall to SI-cover jinx?
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ On the desk in Bill Parcells' second-floor office at
Weeb Ewbank Hall are a half-dozen elephant figurines, all with
their tusks and trunks pointed toward the ceiling for good fortune.
A ceramic four-leaf clover serves as a paper weight.
</P>
<P>
   So why is the New York Jets coach fretting as his team prepares
for its Sunday night showdown with AFC East co-leader Miami?
Because his face graces the cover of this week's Sports
Illustrated. While Parcells attempts to debunk talk about his
superstitious nature, he's aware of the alleged jinx that
accompanies the SI-cover-boy status. In fact, Parcells claimed
earlier this week that he had a guarantee from the editors that his
picture would not be out front.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, my gosh, why don't you just cover him in salt or put some
black cats and ladders out there on the way to the practice
field?'' backup guard Alex Bernstein asked when told of the cover
portrait.
</P>
<P>
   His protests aside, Parcells' superstitions are well-documented.
Earlier this season he booked dental appointments three consecutive
Tuesday mornings, each preceding a Jets victory. The fourth week,
he went back again, even though he didn't need any more work. When
his team lost to the Colts, the dental streak ended with the
winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   In the week's marquee matchup _ Parcells versus Jimmy Johnson in
``The Tuna and the Kingfish'' _ the high-octane New York offense
will need both skill and luck against the Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami defense, arguably the quickest in the NFL, has sparked
a 6-0 home record while surrendering a paltry 6.7 points per game.
In last week's victory against Oakland, the defense had eight sacks
and six interceptions, two returned for scores.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the standpoint of a pressure scheme and having incredibly
quick personnel, they are the best we'll see all year,''Jets
quarterback Vinny Testaverde said.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the ``bests'' for this weekend:
</P>
<P>
   _ Upset opportunity: Without injured quarterback Mark Brunell,
the Jacksonville Jaguars could have some problems with a Tennessee
team still in the playoff race. The best bet of the weekend,
though, could be Monday night's Detroit-San Francisco matchup. If
the Lions' Barry Sanders can stop giggling at the 49ers' depleted
defensive line, he might run for more than 200 yards.
</P>
<P>
   _ Individual matchup: After an early-season slump, Jets center
Kevin Mawae has played at a Pro Bowl level. He'll need to maintain
that excellence against Miami middle linebacker Zach Thomas, who
will be keying on tailback Curtis Martin.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fantasy play: The beleaguered Bad News Bears can't stop the
run, and with all the injuries to wide receivers, Green Bay
quarterback Brett Favre will rely more on the running game. Look
for Packers tailback Darick Holmes to post big numbers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Grudge match: There is mutual respect between Parcells and
Johnson, but that doesn't mean they like each other. The New York
Daily News conducted a poll of NFL personnel directors and coaches
last week and asked this question: With one game to win, would you
want Parcells or Johnson as your coach? Parcells won in a
landslide, 14-7. The real-life battle of wits will be even more
interesting.
</P>
<P>
   _ Division game: Because of Atlanta's seven-game winning streak,
the rivalry with New Orleans has waned a bit in recent years. It
will be restoked, however, on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
