<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3962 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABORTION-TEX     12-10 0512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By CHARLOTTE HUFF 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The number of abortion providers continues to decline, making
the procedure less accessible to many rural women, according to an
Alan Guttmacher Institute report being released today.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-abortion intimidation has contributed to the 14 percent
national decline in providers from 1992 through 1996, said Stanley
Henshaw, author of the report.
</P>
<P>
   Texas reported an even steeper 19 percent drop, from 79 to 64
providers, during the same period. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There is now actual fear among abortion providers,'' said
Henshaw, deputy director for the New York City-based nonprofit
institute, which describes itself as pro-choice. ``It's not worth
the harassment or inconvenience.''
</P>
<P>
   That's fine with the Rev. Flip Benham, national director of
Dallas-based Operation Rescue.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the people that are telling the truth are out front and
that's bothering (doctors), then maybe they should stop doing it,''
Benham said.
</P>
<P>
   The report _ the 12th analysis by the institute since the 1973
Roe v. Wade decision _ also found that the number of Texas
abortions declined 6 percent from 1992 through 1996 compared with
11 percent nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Another abortion analysis, published last week by the Centers
for Disease Control and Prevention, found that the number of
abortions rose slightly from 1995 to 1996, after falling steadily
every year since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Some Texas women travel from as far away as Wichita Falls and
San Angelo to reach the Fort Worth clinic operated by Planned
Parenthood of North Texas, executive director Michael Comini said.
</P>
<P>
   Kae McLaughlin, executive director of the Texas Abortion and
Reproductive Rights Action League, said she worries most about poor
women in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``A woman with four children on an hourly wage who is not paid
for time off, who already can't afford the procedure, you are
doubling the cost of the procedure for her,'' McLaughlin said.
``Sometimes it really does make it impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   Physician practices and hospitals, which perform 9 percent of
the nation's abortions, are most likely to have eliminated
services, Henshaw said. Young doctors are less likely to be taught
the procedure in residency, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A number of factors may contribute to the declining abortion
rate, including better contraception use in the wake of AIDS and
the decreased stigma of teenage motherhood, Henshaw said.
</P>
<P>
   As with slavery, an emotional shift will occur before the laws
can change, Benham said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is happening here in this country is heart by heart, the
truth is getting out and the battle is being won in the streets,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, 86 percent of U.S. counties and one-third of the cities
had no identified abortion provider, according to the institute's
report. That same year, the number of pregnancies ending in
abortion _ 26 percent _ reached its lowest rate in two decades, the
report said.
(Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
