<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELECTRONIC DATA SYSTEMS NAMES NEW CHIEF EXECUTIVE
</P>
<P>
   Electronic Data Systems, seeking a marquee leader able to
restore its primacy in computer services, named Richard H. Brown,
chief executive of Cable and Wireless, as its chairman and chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who is leaving Cable and Wireless after just 29 months,
brings a reputation as a tireless deal maker and management
shuffler, credited by analysts with raising the company's sales,
profits and share price in his short tenure there.
</P>
<P>
   LONDON LOWERS BENCHMARK RATE
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of England lowered its benchmark interest rate by half
a percentage point, the third cut in as many months and the second
consecutive time it did so by a half-point, citing persistent
``deterioration across the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   ERICSSON TO CUT 10,000 JOBS
</P>
<P>
   Ericsson, the Swedish maker of cellular phones, said its
fourth-quarter profit would be 15 percent to 20 percent lower than
expected and that it would cut 10,000 more jobs because of flagging
demand for its phones and public switching systems.
</P>
<P>
   ELECTION UPSET AT CHICAGO EXCHANGE
</P>
<P>
   In a surprise election victory, a 41-year-old soybean trader
unseated the chairman of the Chicago Board of Trade. The vote to
oust Patrick Arbor, who had been in office for six years, could
reassert the power of floor traders fearful that their positions
are being eroded by the incumbent's aggressive push for
technological change.
</P>
<P>
   ORACLE REPORTS SURPRISING GAIN
</P>
<P>
   Oracle, the world's largest database software company, reported
a 46 percent rise in quarterly profits as strong computer-services
revenue helped propel results past expectations. Oracle stock,
which fell $1.6875, to $34.9375, during regular Nasdaq trading,
rose to $36.50 in after-hours activity. The company reported its
results after the close of regular U.S. trading.
</P>
<P>
   National Semiconductor reported a smaller-than-expected
second-quarter loss excluding one-time items, but sales were still
down and executives remained cautious about the company's outlook.
The company's shares fell 12 percent, or $2, to $14.625.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICAN AIRLINE EXECUTIVE ARRESTED
</P>
<P>
   The top official at Taesa, Mexico's third-largest airline, was
arrested and charged with tax fraud. The prosecution of Alberto
Abed Shekaiban pointed to toughened enforcement of Mexico's fiscal
laws.
</P>
<P>
   JOBLESS APPLICATIONS INCREASE
</P>
<P>
   Initial jobless applications inched up in early December,
increasing for the second consecutive week, the Labor Department
said.
</P>
<P>
   SUN AND MICROSOFT'S WARY DANCE
</P>
<P>
   The Microsoft trial offered an inside view of the wary,
distrustful relationship between that company and Sun Microsystems.
</P>
<P>
   HASBRO SETTLES ANTITRUST SUIT
</P>
<P>
   Hasbro will donate $6 million in toys, books and money for
children in order to settle an antitrust suit in which it is
charged with unfair trade practices intended to withhold popular
toys from some retailers.
</P>
<P>
   YBM MAGNEX EXPECTS INDICTMENT
</P>
<P>
   A scandal-ridden magnet and bicycle maker, YBM Magnex
International, filed for receivership in Canada and said it
expected to be indicted in a U.S. organized-crime investigation.
</P>
</TEXT>
