<SLUG> BC-BKC-BIG12NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGGIES' PROGRESS LOST IN THE SHUFFLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Great football season in the Big 12. Good
thing, too. It's kept the focus away from a rather ignoble start to
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma State's octogenarian winning streak against
nonconference opponents at Gallager-Iba Arena comes crashing down
after 80 games to _ Florida Atlantic? Equally stunning, mighty
Kansas falls to a lightly regarded Iowa team in Allen Fieldhouse,
putting an end to the nation's longest home-court winning streak
after 62 games.
</P>
<P>
   The Harry Miller watch is on at Baylor. Texas struggles to a 1-5
start under new coach Rick Barnes, who inherited a depleted roster
and the nation's 16th-ranked schedule, according to statistics guru
Jeff Sagarin.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes, however, is not upset.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be fine,'' he says with that trademark confident
attitude, and the track record says believe him.
</P>
<P>
   And almost unnoticed in the hullabaloo over a Big 12 football
championship, Texas A&AMP;M and its new coach Melvin Watkins have
started the season 7-1 _ in eight games having carved out a number
of victories equal to last season's total under deposed coach Tony
Barone.
</P>
<P>
   Unnoticed? Well, yes. Watkins' Aggies are playing before crowds
of 3,000-and-change in new Reed Arena. But the scenario is fitting
perhaps, since even Watkins' hiring last spring took second notice
to the Tom Penders melodrama and his subsequent ``resignation'' at
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   None of which makes any difference to Watkins, a most pleasant
person who focuses on perspective and the big picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't care,'' Watkins said of the relative lack of
notice. ``Because I do understand the process. All things
considered, I'm pleased where we are. We should be 8-0. But I know
the road is going to get tougher, and we've got to get tougher as
well. I don't want to get people bent out of shape because we have
had some success. We always talk to our players about balance _ not
getting too high or two low.''
</P>
<P>
   Comparing the two situations _ A&AMP;M and Texas _ is fudge to
fruitcake.
</P>
<P>
   First, Watkins managed to stoke his program last spring with two
junior college transfers (point guard Clifton Cook, center Paul
Jacobs) who have stepped into starting roles, because he had
scholarship openings. Two, the Aggies have played an early schedule
that Sagarin ranks 241st in degree of toughness.
</P>
<P>
   But the Aggies are winning the kinds of games they began to lose
about this time last season after a 5-1 start.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, we didn't keep our composure like we do this
year,'' guard Michael Schmidt said after Wednesday's Tulane victory
_ in which A&AMP;M lost 10 points of an 11-point lead before rallying
to win, 59-53. Seven times last year the Aggies lost games they led
by nine or more points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just know I see a positive attitude on their faces when my
kids come to practice,'' Watkins said. ``And we surely want them to
feel good about themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   That's progress. Any way you measure it.
NO FORWARDS LEADS BACKWARDS
</P>
<P>
   Kansas' problems are evident, as is the fact that the Jayhawks
are over-ranked at No. 10 this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of us is wrong,'' coach Roy Williams said, referring to
The Associated Press poll. ``And I see this team every day.''
</P>
<P>
   What Williams sees is a lack of scoring punch and a weak front
line beset by injuries. Lester Earl (knee) and T.J. Pugh (ankle),
the top two returning rebounders, have been slowed all season by
injury. Doctors shaved the back of Earl's kneecap earlier this week
in hopes of curing a continuous swelling problem since
reconstructive surgery last spring, but he may be out two more
weeks. Transfer Ashante Johnson, at 6-8 expected to be another
strong rebounder, has yet to play after October knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas is averaging seven fewer boards a game than last season
and, Williams said, fewer points than any team he's had at Kansas.
The 85-81 loss to Iowa boosted Kansas' scoring average to 71.1
points a game _ 13 less than a year ago. A Kansas team has not
averaged less than 70 points since 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Guard Ryan Robertson, who was in the 11th grade the last time
Kansas lost at home, is the only player to score in double figures
through seven games. A NEED-TO-KNOW BASIS
</P>
<P>
   Baylor's NCAA-berth hopeful Lady Bears (4-3) may not have made
the early-season impact for which coach Sonja Hogg had hoped _
losing at home in the second round of the Women's National
Invitation Tournament by Florida (70-58) and dropping another home
game to Southwest Missouri State (87-86). But Hogg was encouraged
by Tuesday's win at Arkansas State _ significant because Arkansas
State had defeated No. 21 Virginia and No. 23 Kansas (the Big 12
preseason favorite) on their home court, where they had won 39 of
their last 40 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I waited until after the game to tell our players that they
had won 39 of 40 at home,'' Hogg said. ``This was a major step in
the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Further clue should come tomorrow night, when Baylor plays No.
25 California-Santa Barbara in the Ferrell Center. BACK AT YOU
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma (4-1) aptly demonstrated the radical bounces of
December college basketball last week. The Sooners lost at home to
Murray State, then a week later in their next game shocked then-No.
18 Arkansas, 87-57.
</P>
<P>
   ``Losing is not a crime, but you don't have to accept it,''
Oklahoma coach Kelvin Sampson said. ``We're not 30 points better
than anybody. \RThe Arkansas game\S was a fluke in a lot of ways.
We're not that good and they're not that bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``But being able to bounce back like we did spoke a lot about
our team's character. The week we went through, if we'd had a bunch
of knuckleheads on our team, we couldn't have responded like we
did.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory was the Sooners' first over a ranked opponent since
beating No. 15 Colorado in February 1997 and the only victory by a
Big 12 team over a ranked opponent in nine such matchups this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Guard Tim Heskett, who played in only two of Oklahoma's 33 games
last season before undergoing back surgery, has added needed
scoring punch to help compensate for the loss of Corey Brewer's 20
points a game. Twenty-one of Heskitt's 23 baskets are 3-pointers.
He's averaging 15.4 points and playing 33 minutes a game. He also
averages 3.6 assists and is shooting .909 from the free-throw line.
FREE THROWS
</P>
<P>
   O.J. Simpson defense lawyer Johnnie Cochran is heading the legal
team of Hampton University women's basketball coach Patricia Bibbs,
her husband Ezell and assistant Vanetta Kelso. They were falsely
detained in Lubbock (Nov. 17) for alleged participation in a
pigeon-drop scheme before a subsequently canceled game with Texas
Tech. Cochran said this week his clients will ``demand justice''
(read big bucks) after his own investigation, which he estimates
will take 30 to 60 days.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma State point guard Doug Gottlieb leads the league in
assists and technical fouls _ three in the last two games. He was
tossed at halftime of the loss to Florida Atlantic after elbowing
the Owls' Baron Davis in the face. Davis retaliated by practically
blocking Joe Atkins' last shot in the Cowboys' 83-81 loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doug and I have had a long talk,'' Oklahoma State coach Eddie
Sutton said. ``He needs to control his emotions if he's going to
play basketball at Oklahoma State.''
</P>
<P>
   Go figure. Texas wins against a good Oral Roberts team in Tulsa
without Kris Clack (dislocated shoulder), who plays most of the
second half in a subsequent loss at San Diego State.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was our worst game of the season,'' sophomore Gabe Muoneke
said of the loss to the Aztecs. ``We need to play harder. It's
ridiculous to know how good we are and then to play like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes, incidentally, says he and the sometimes volatile Muoneke
_ of all his inherited players _ probably most see eye-to-eye.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas State coach Tom Asbury says 6-8, 230-pound transfer Tony
Kitt could be a great player if he ever gets in shape. Kitt pulled
down 20 rebounds 10 days ago against Loyola-Chicago and also has
19- and 16-rebound games. He plays only about 20 minutes a game,
yet leads KSU in scoring (13.3 points) and rebounding (10.5).
</P>
<P>
   ``He never coasts or rests,'' Asbury said. ``But if we can get
him playing 30-32 minutes _ and that may not happen until next
season _ we're looking at some amazing numbers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
