<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS WENT ABOUT TASK TOO EASILY IN THE BIG EASY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Ah, Christmas in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   The food. The Royal Street shopping. The streetcar ride along
moss-draped St. Charles Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   The football game.
</P>
<P>
   Oops. Clearly, as they escorted their wives and/or girlfriends
around The Big Easy last weekend _ as many of them reportedly did _
the Cowboys forgot something.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence exists in the videotaped lowlights of the team's 22-3
defeat, a game in which coach Chan Gailey suggested the Cowboys had
``the dog'' beaten out of them.
</P>
<P>
   He should hope so. Because as some of us saw it, there was
plenty of dog in the Cowboys to go around.
</P>
<P>
   The statistics from last weekend suggest a thorough, physical
domination by the New Orleans Saints, hard as that is to fathom.
The Saints were 5-7 for a reason. They were ranked 27th in the
league in total defense.
</P>
<P>
   If the Cowboys are no better than the Saints _ something that
the casual observer could have deduced by watching the 22-3
spanking _ then the joke has been on us. The Cowboys are paper
tigers, and the paper is the NFC East standings.
</P>
<P>
   But there's no joke. If you buy into the paper-tiger theory, the
loss in New Orleans stands as evidence of a disturbing trend.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't _ and I don't _ you're left with the equally
disturbing notion that the Cowboys, mentally, were not ready to
play. It happens.
</P>
<P>
   In private this week, Gailey was asked if he felt his team
didn't treat the weekend in New Orleans as enough of a business
trip.
</P>
<P>
   He said he'd rather not answer that.
</P>
<P>
   To answer it, I believe, would intrude upon wives, girlfriends,
bar tabs at Pat O'Brien's, etc., etc.
</P>
<P>
   No one is saying exactly how many Cowboys wives/girlfriends
accompanied their player-husbands on the weekend trip. But it was
more than just a few.
</P>
<P>
   One of them accidentally left her bill in the same hotel room
that I was assigned Sunday night. Forgive me, I peeked. The lady
and her husband clearly had a marvelous, fun-filled time.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the game, presumably. Oops.
</P>
<P>
   Add it up. The Cowboys had neither blocked nor tackled anyone in
earnest for 10 days. The NFC East was a gimme. The offense had
stamped itself as a bona fide scoring machine. The owner had been
telling everyone that he likes what he sees. And then there were
Mike Ditka's allegedly cowardly Saints, speedbumps on the planned
promenade down Bourbon Street.
</P>
<P>
   The end result was that the Cowboys numbly staggered through the
motions, ofttimes appearing confused or disinterested.
</P>
<P>
   The offensive line, mostly Flozell Adams and Mike Kiselak, never
did adjust to the blitzing pressure put on by the Saints' 46
defense.
</P>
<P>
   Two other things happened. First, tight end David LaFleur tore a
ligament in a knee early in the game. Gailey had planned to utilize
LaFleur as a pass target, even splitting him wide on some plays. It
likely would have forced the Saints to cover the big tight end with
a linebacker, which would have meant one less blitzer.
</P>
<P>
   The second thing was that the sold-out Superdome crowd was much
louder than the Cowboys had planned. As a result, there were times
when quarterback Troy Aikman came to the line, saw that a bad play
had been called, but was unable to do much about it.
</P>
<P>
   Things snowballed. The Big Easy was anything but.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, as has been well-chronicled, Gailey did not read
his chihuahuas the riot act in the post-game dressing room. His
idea of admonishment apparently was to wait until they returned to
Valley Ranch and then tell the players how disappointed he was in
them. He also made them watch tape of the entire game _ ouch _
leaving them to squirm as he pointed out each mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're a good team, we'll respond,'' Gailey said, simply.
</P>
<P>
   He is correct, of course. If the Cowboys play poorly in Kansas
City this weekend, then the paper tigers could well be in for a
brief and bogus playoff run.
</P>
<P>
   More than likely, however, they are still the same team that won
eight of its first 11 games. In New Orleans, they were on vacation.
Yeah, that's it. A vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the mission. Or bust.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
