<HEADLINE>
SMITH MAY BEAT SANDERS TO FIELD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ In a surprising twist, Cowboys coach Chan Gailey
said that cornerback Kevin Smith (sprained back) has a better
chance of playing against the Kansas City Chiefs than Deion Sanders
(sprained toe).
</P>
<P>
   Neither player practiced with the team yesterday because of
rain. And Gailey said he would like to wait until today's practice
before making a final decision on their playing status.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin is probably now a little closer than Deion,'' Gailey
said. ``I was encouraged about what Deion did in practice
Wednesday. But I'd like to see him do a little more.''
</P>
<P>
   The prospects of both players were reversed earlier in the week
when Smith was listed as doubtful on the injury report and Sanders
was listed as questionable. Gailey said the situation is more
indicative of progress by Smith than of Sanders being set back.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Mathis and Charlie Williams are still slated to start at
cornerback. Warren frustrated Cowboys running back Chris Warren,
who has missed the past two games with a strained groin, is growing
frustrated with his injury woes this season.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't practice yesterday, and the Cowboys are not optimistic
about his chances for the Chiefs game.
</P>
<P>
   Warren, who played the past eight years with the Seahawks, came
to the Cowboys in the off-season to be an insurance policy for
starting running back Emmitt Smith, who has been hampered by a
variety of injuries the past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   However, Warren has been the one unable to stay healthy. He also
missed the first three games of the season with a similar groin
injury.
</P>
<P>
   What's most troubling to Warren is that he doesn't have a
history of injury problems, missing only five games over the
previous eight years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just can't understand it,'' Warren, 30, said. ``I've played
with broken ribs before. Nothing has ever kept me from playing
until now.'' Flag fest Among the subplots in Sunday's
Cowboys-Chiefs game is the it shapes up as a possible flag fest.
</P>
<P>
   The Chiefs are the league's most penalized team with 125
infractions for 1,052 yards, while the Cowboys are third with 112
penalties for 981 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey's biggest issue is with pre-snap penalties that have
plagued the Cowboys all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to do what it takes to prevent those,'' Gailey said.
``I can live with the judgment calls by the officials after the
ball has been snapped but it's the pre-snap penalties that really
hurt.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
