<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LANGENBRUNNER'S FIRST-LINE PLAY HAS BEEN STELLAR FOR THE STARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Stars coach Ken Hitchcock deflects the question
as quickly and decisively as Ed Belfour kicks aside a shot on goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' he said. ``I don't want to think about that
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   What is it Hitchcock can't face? The prospect of playing without
Mike Modano? Whether or not to send Bryan Marchment a Seasons
Greeting?
</P>
<P>
   No, nothing that horrible. Hitchcock merely has been asked what
he will do when Brett Hull returns to the lineup, which likely will
happen tonight against Montreal or Sunday at Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, it seems as though it should be a no-brainer.
Restore Hull to the ``Firing Line'' with Modano and Jere Lehtinen.
Easy, right?
</P>
<P>
   Not necessarily.
</P>
<P>
   The complicating factor is the outstanding play of Jamie
Langenbrunner.
</P>
<P>
   The third-year forward has rebounded from a training-camp
holdout to become one of the most productive Stars of late. His
first-period assist against the San Jose Sharks on Wednesday night
gave him 11 points in the past 10 games. He is third on the team
with 18 points and second with 14 assists.
</P>
<P>
   Much of that has come on the first line. He has been playing
alongside Modano and Lehtinen since a slight groin strain caused
Hull to miss five of the past six games.
</P>
<P>
   ``That line's really played well,'' Hitchcock said. ``You've got
three people that work hard. That's not to say the
Modano-Lehtinen-Hull combination hasn't been sound and good; it
has. When Hull left our group, he was playing as well as he's ever
played. We're assuming that's the way he's going to start up. If he
does, we've got some real hard decisions to make.''
</P>
<P>
   Langenbrunner is prepared for whatever the coach decides.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely an adjustment, but it's something I've gotten
used to over the last couple of years,'' he said. ``I'm kind of the
yo-yo guy who can move back and forth to where I'm needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Wherever he plays, Langenbrunner will skate with the all-out,
reckless style that's become his trademark.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way I've got to play,'' he said. ``I've got to play
with a lot of energy and try to outwork the other team. I don't
have the skills to go out there and skate around everybody. Just
going out there and working hard is my calling card.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the season, though, that style was missing.
</P>
<P>
   Langenbrunner missed most of training camp in a contract holdout
before signing a two-year deal five days before the season opener.
But Hitchcock dismisses that as a factor in Langenbrunner's slow
start. He said Langenbrunner was playing the way he did in the
playoffs last season, when he had five points in 16 games and a
plus/minus rating of minus-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was trying to play a skilled game rather than an
in-your-face game,'' Hitchcock said. ``Now, he just plays in your
face. When the work is there first, the skill will be a reflection
of the work.''
</P>
<P>
   Another factor in Langenbrunner's scoring surge is a move to
right wing. He began the season playing the left side on a line
with Joe Nieuwendyk and Pat Verbeek, which is not a natural
position for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no coincidence that he's up and running since moving over
to the right side,'' Hitchcock said. ``He's a very competent left
winger, but if I want to get a lot out of him, there's a better
position.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever decision Hitchcock makes when Hull returns almost
surely won't involve moving Langenbrunner back to the left wing.
He'll stay on the right side somewhere, or perhaps move to center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Langenbrunner is a better center-iceman and a better right
winger than he is a left winger,'' Hitchcock said. ``When Brett
comes back in, the change might be in the middle of the ice or on
the right side. I think that has to be our focus.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
