<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMITTEE DEBATE BEGINS ON ARTICLES OF IMPEACHMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Working in the shadow of history and the
Constitution, the House Judiciary Committee began debating
impeachment articles on Thursday as President Clinton looked to
moderate Republicans to end the threat to his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a grave matter we're about today,'' Rep. Bill
McCollum, R-Fla., said as the panel took on the solemn task of
deciding Clinton's fate. ``Sadly, I conclude that, when all is said
and done, I must vote to impeach President William Jefferson
Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Judiciary Committee all but certain to approve articles
of impeachment Friday or Saturday, Clinton's allies focused on
Thursday's showdown vote in the full House.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials made a flurry of telephone calls to
undecided lawmakers and sent every member of Congress a
point-by-point rebuttal of the allegations against the president.
The draft resolution of the four articles of impeachment accuses
Clinton of 17 counts of perjury, obstruction of justice and abuse
of power in his efforts to hide an extramarital affair with Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people may wake up next Friday morning to
discover that the House of Representatives has indeed impeached the
president,'' said Rep. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y. ``I think the
American people are waiting for us to come to our senses and end
this political game of chicken.''
</P>
<P>
   Partisans on both sides agree that the outcome in the House will
be determined by about two dozen undecided Republicans. The
30-member Texas delegation is expected to vote along party lines,
with the exception of Rep. Ralph Hall of Rockwall, one of three
House Democrats who publicly support impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   In another development, House Majority Leader Dick Armey and
Republican Whip Tom DeLay, both of Texas and the No. 2 and No. 3
House leaders, reaffirmed their opposition to any House vote on a
compromise censure resolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of censure is born out of a desperate imagination by
those too timid to uphold their own sworn oath to `support and
defend' the Constitution,'' DeLay wrote in an opinion piece for the
Washington Times.
</P>
<P>
   Michele Davis, Armey's spokeswoman, said the majority leader
adamantly opposes a censure vote. Speaker-elect Bob Livingston of
Louisiana has not taken a position on censure, which some of
Clinton's backers believe is his best hope for avoiding
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of partisan sniping, Judiciary Committee members
adopted a somber tone as they opened a debate that has occurred
only rarely in the nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, lawmakers sitting in the same high-ceilinged hearing
room approved articles of impeachment against Richard Nixon, but he
resigned to avoid a vote in the full House. The House impeached
Andrew Johnson in 1868, but the Senate fell one vote short of the
two-thirds majority needed to remove him from office.
</P>
<P>
   As if to underscore the echoes of history, committee Republicans
labored beneath a portrait of former Rep. Peter Rodino, the New
Jersey Democrat who presided over the Watergate investigation
nearly 25 years ago. Rep. Henry Hyde of Illinois, the current
chairman, gazed over the Democrats from his portrait on the other
side of the dais.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are standing perched on a constitutional cliff, staring
into the void below into which we have jumped only twice before in
our history,'' said Rep. John Conyers of Michigan, the panel's
leading Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans argued that Clinton's behavior left them no choice
but to pursue the ultimate punishment for the nation's chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only did the president tell a judge and then a grand jury
less than the truth, he also told lies to the American people, the
news media, members of Congress, his Cabinet and senior White House
advisers,'' said Rep. Lamar Smith, R-San Antonio. ``If we keep
excusing away the president's actions, we as a nation will never
climb upward because there will be no firm rungs.''
</P>
<P>
   Representatives took up the impeachment resolution after final
arguments by committee lawyers for both parties. Democratic counsel
Abbe Lowell warned that a House vote for impeachment would clear
the way for a lengthy Senate trial that would almost certainly
include detailed, graphic testimony about Clinton's relationship
with the former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   ``The perjury that some in the majority have said `tears at the
fabric of our judicial system' comes down to whether the president
lied about whether he touched Ms. Lewinsky,'' Lowell said. ``Is
that what you want to put the country through?''
</P>
<P>
   Majority counsel David Schippers, a Chicago Democrat who was
hired by the committee's Republican majority, countered with a
scathing recitation of Clinton's efforts to keep the relationship
secret.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not about sex or private conduct. It is about multiple
obstructions of justice, perjury, false and misleading statements,
witness tampering and abuses of power,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Directing the committee's attention to oversized television
screens, Schippers played damaging snippets from videotapes of
Clinton's sworn statements in the Paula Jones' sexual harassment
case and to a Washington grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about Lewinsky in the Jones case, Clinton denied
having a sexual relationship with her. He told the grand jury that
he had engaged in ``an inappropriate intimate relationship'' but
insisted that his earlier statements had been legally accurate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The answers are a gratuitous insult to your intelligence and
common sense,'' Schippers told the panel of 21 Republicans and 16
Democrats. ``He lied to the people, he lied to his Cabinet, he lied
to his top aides and now he has lied under oath to the Congress of
the United States. There is no one left to lie to.''
(Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
