<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISPUTE-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: TRUE NORTH TO ARBITRATE ON VALUE OF ITS PUBLICIS
STAKE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Bickersons of Madison Avenue _ Publicis SA in
Paris and True North Communications in Chicago _ are back in court
again as True North has submitted a dispute over the valuation of
its stake in Publicis to arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   The two giant agency companies have become known for their
fractious relationship after years of tangled disagreements over
expansion and other issues.
</P>
<P>
   The war seemingly ended in May 1997, when Publicis and True
North dissolved an international cooperative agreement. But six
months later, Publicis unexpectedly began a hostile takeover bid
for True North, which only intensified the enmity between them.
</P>
<P>
   When True North defeated the unfriendly deal in late December,
the bitterness between the former partners appeared to subside.
Last month, Publicis announced that it would begin to sever its
remaining ties with True North by merging a subsidiary, Publicis
Communication, into Publicis.
</P>
<P>
   True North owns 26.5 percent of Publicis Communication, which is
not publicly traded. The stock swap to complete the merger would
give True North shares in Publicis that represent about 8.8 percent
of the total outstanding, which could then be sold by True North to
close the books on l'affaire Publicis. A special shareholder
meeting to vote on the merger is scheduled to be held Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But when Publicis executives detailed terms of the merger, True
North executives pronounced themselves displeased. The reason, they
said, was that the book value of the True North investment in
Publicis was higher than the value of the Publicis shares that True
North would receive. That would result in a pretax loss for True
North of about $30 million in the fourth quarter, according to a
10-Q filing it made with the Securities and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   There were reports in the trade publications Adweek and Campaign
that True North executives were considering legal action to block
the merger. But True North said Thursday that it would ``not
institute legal action to impede the merger of Publicis
Communication and Publicis.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, True North said, it had decided to submit the issue of
the share valuation to the London Court of International
Arbitration. Hearings on a request by True North for unspecified
monetary damages from Publicis have been scheduled for the week of
Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully this is the beginning of the last chapter of a very
bad book _ the tortured saga of True North and Publicis,'' Bruce
Mason, chief executive at True North, said in the statement. ``This
will enable us to finally exit the acrimonious relationship with
Publicis.''
</P>
<P>
   There did seem to be an effort by True North to tone down some
of the rhetoric against Publicis, which became bitterly caustic at
the height of the takeover fight. The tone of Mason's remarks was
more conciliatory, and the decision to seek arbitration was
disclosed not in the first paragraph of a news release but in the
second.
</P>
<P>
   The release even carried a kinder, gentler headline: ``True
North Nears Final Chapter With Publicis.''
</P>
<P>
   And Publicis sidestepped an opportunity to fire back at True
North. Asked Thursday for a response to the True North
announcement, Seth Goldschlager, a spokesman for Publicis, replied
that Publicis would have no comment.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Geanuleas, a spokeswoman for True North, declined to
disclose how True North would vote its shares at the special
meeting Friday.
</P>
<P>
   At a special meeting of True North shareholders a year ago,
Publicis voted its shares in True North against a deal for True
North to acquire Bozell, Jacobs, Kenyon &AMP; Eckhardt. Other True
North shareholders supported the deal and it was overwhelmingly
approved.
</P>
<P>
   As of the end of 1997, True North ranked as the world's
sixth-largest agency company, with $10.8 billion in billings.
Publicis was ranked No. 14, at $4 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-98 2111EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
