<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981210.0459 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4018 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH11-COX     12-10 1335
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Judiciary feels weight of history, House prepares
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman, Ken Foskett and Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House Judiciary Committee stood on the brink
Thursday of a historic decision to recommend the impeachment of
President Clinton, the panel's partisan divide as wide as ever.
</P>
<P>
   With at least one of four proposed articles of impeachment
virtually certain to win committee approval either today or
Saturday, Speaker Newt Gingrich formally put the House on notice to
be ready to do its duty next week.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to every House member, Gingrich said the impeachment
debate in the full House would begin Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's videotaped image from his deposition in the Paula
Jones sexual harassment lawsuit, used in closing arguments by the
chief Republican and Democratic lawyers, dominated Thursday's
hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, committee members one by one began delivering their
statements, which will be followed by the consideration of the
proposed articles of impeachment and a Democratic alternative, to
censure Clinton for his efforts to conceal his relationship with
former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   More than five hours of presentations by the lawyers appeared to
change no minds in the tense, partisan environment that has marked
the Judiciary Committee's work.
</P>
<P>
   David Schippers, the Republicans' lead investigative counsel,
told committee members they have a ``sorrowful duty'' to remove
Clinton from office because he committed perjury, obstructed
justice and abused the powers of his office.
</P>
<P>
   Abbe Lowell, his Democratic counterpart, said the lack of public
support for impeachment should be a powerful signal to Republicans
that they should embrace the Democratic proposal to censure Clinton
instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen to the American people, who are asking you to find a
truly bipartisan way to avoid the course you are about to
undertake,'' Lowell said.
</P>
<P>
   New polls released Thursday continue to reflect public distaste
for impeachment and the attractiveness of censure as a way to
punish Clinton for his sex-and-lies scandal.
</P>
<P>
   A Wall Street Journal-NBC News poll contained troubling news for
Republicans. The Republican Party's popularity has dropped to
levels not seen since the early 1990s, and its negative rating has
almost doubled from where it stood in January 1995, when the GOP
took control of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans on the Judiciary Committee, however, said they would
take no notice of the polls as they lined up, one after another
Thursday, to declare their support for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot erase from my mind ... the falsehoods uttered under
oath,'' said Rep. George Gekas (R-Pa.).
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, on the other hand, restated their intention to vote
against impeachment. Summing up his view of the case against the
president, Rep. John Conyers (D-Mich.) said, ``The president tried
to hide an extramarital relationship from the glare of his family
and political opponents.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the intended target of most of Thursday's commentary
was the small band of undecided, mainly moderate, Republicans who
appear to hold the key to impeachment in the closely divided House.
</P>
<P>
   Schippers, a Chicago Democrat who is working for the
Republicans, barely concealed his contempt for the White House's
defense of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   He spiced his account of the president's relationship with the
young former intern and efforts to cover it up with repeated digs
and sarcastic remarks about Clinton's behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Schippers painted a picture of a devious chief executive who
would stop at nothing to conceal the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not about sex or private conduct, it is about multiple
obstructions of justice, perjury, false and misleading statements,
witness tampering and abuses of power, all committed or
orchestrated by the president of the United States,'' Schippers
declared at the start of his three-hour narrative.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer proceeded to weave together a long list of meetings,
phone calls and exchanges among Clinton, Lewinsky, presidential
secretary Betty Currie and adviser Vernon Jordan that, taken as a
whole, suggested a ``sinister, or even criminal connotation when
observed in the context of the whole plot.''
</P>
<P>
   Schippers attempted to undercut Lewinsky's grand jury testimony,
which was not contained in independent counsel Kenneth Starr's
referral to Congress, that ``no one ever told me to lie, nobody
ever promised me a job.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course no one said, 'Now, Monica, you go in there and
lie,''' said Schippers, speaking in a low, conspiratorial voice.
``They didn't have to. Monica knew what was expected of her.
Similarly, nobody promised her a job, but once she signed the false
affidavit, she got one, didn't she?''
</P>
<P>
   Schippers charged that Clinton's deceptions might have succeeded
if not for the semen-stained blue dress that was found in
Lewinsky's possession.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life was so much simpler before they found that dress, wasn't
it?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Schippers concluded his summation on a loftier note.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you do here will be incised in the history of the United
States for all time to come,'' he said. ``Unborn generations ...
will learn of these proceedings and will most certainly judge this
committee's actions. What will be their verdict?
</P>
<P>
   ``Will it be that you rose above party and faction, and
re-established justice, decency, honor and truth as the standard by
which even the highest office in the land must be evaluated? Or
will it be that you announced that there is no abiding standard and
that public officials are answerable only to politics, polls and
propaganda? God forbid that that will be your legacy.''
</P>
<P>
   White House special counsel Gregory Craig, speaking at the White
House after Schippers presentation, sharply criticized the attorney
for resorting to ``innuendo, anger and unfair, unsubstantiated
charges.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to Schippers' argument, Lowell offered a lofty
discussion of the standards of impeachment and the paucity of
evidence to impeach Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   He urged Republicans to think twice before removing the
president for lying and concealing a sexual affair, contrasting it
with what he said were far more serious affairs of state.
</P>
<P>
   The case against Clinton is not, he said, about the president
directing his staff to spread misinformation about the progress of
the war in Vietnam. It is not about breaking into the Democratic
headquarters at the Watergate apartment complex or about how funds
from arms sales in Iran were diverted to aid the Contras in
Nicaragua.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a president repeating to his staff the same denial of
an inappropriate and extremely embarrassing relationship that he
had already denied to the public directly,'' Lowell said. ``Bill
Clinton's alleged crimes are not those of an errant president, but
that of an unfaithful husband.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee started its day by meeting in closed session to
authorize the release of Clinton's videotaped deposition in the
Jones civil lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Schippers and Lowell made use of snippets of tape to bolster
their arguments.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in a dark suit, the president appeared in the ornate
Judiciary Committee chambers on large-screen television sets. He
sat silently through a discussion among lawyers and U.S. District
Judge Susan Webber Wright about what constitutes sexual relations.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's understanding of that term is a key question in one of
the proposed impeachment articles that allege he committed perjury.
</P>
<P>
   Lowell also broadcast parts of independent counsel Starr's
testimony before the committee last month to demonstrate that even
Starr at times said that he would have to ``search my
recollection,'' before answering committee questions.
</P>
<P>
   Before Republicans use similar constructions from Clinton to
justify his impeachment, they should consider ``what an unfair
tactic that really is,'' Lowell said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
