<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE OPTIMISTIC IT CAN DEFEAT IMPEACHMENT RESOLUTION IN
HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: 2NDTAKE will move by 9:30 ET.) 
(See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-HYDE, IMPEACH-CONYERS, IMPEACH-MOOD,
IMPEACH-LEWINSKY, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-VIDEO, IMPEACH-LAMEDUCKS,
IMPEACH-DEBATE, IMPEACH-LIVINGSTON, EDIT-IMPEACH, ROSENTHAL-COLUMN,
BAKER-COLUMN) 
(sw) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House is expressing growing confidence
that it can defeat proposed articles of impeachment on the House
floor and is quietly exploring with Republican leaders a deal under
which President Clinton would accept a punitive censure resolution
to escape impeachment, officials said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   As part of a broad effort to sway undecided Republican House
moderates, presidential aides have contacted 45 potentially
persuadable members of Congress in the past few days to offer
further evidence or explanation in the president's defense and to
urge them to vote against impeachment, according to White House
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton himself spoke to ``a handful'' of House members this
week to try to answer their concerns, a White House official said
on Thursday night. The official would not provide the members'
names.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the White House said that two undecided House
members, Reps. Rick Lazio and Michael Forbes, both Republicans from
New York, are scheduled to travel with the president on his trip to
the Middle East on Saturday, giving Clinton a further opportunity
to make his case. Lazio said on Thursday that he had not yet
decided whether to make the trip.
</P>
<P>
   Another undecided Republican, Rep. Jon Fox of Pennsylvania, is
also scheduled to accompany the president to Israel, according to
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The shape of a compromise that would save Clinton from
impeachment was fuzzy Thursday night, but advisers to the president
suggested that Republican leaders in the House might permit a vote
on a harsh censure resolution, including a substantial fine to be
paid by Clinton, if it appeared that the impeachment bill was going
to fail.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders have so far been adamant that the full House
would vote only on articles of impeachment, not on censure. Rep.
Robert Livingston, the speaker-designate of the House, refused on
Thursday to say whether he would allow a vote on censure.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston said that Republican leaders were not putting
pressure on members to vote for impeachment, but that the White
House is engaged in an aggressive anti-impeachment campaign. ``The
president's administration and his people have not hesitated to
lobby,'' Livingston said. ``We hear they're lobbying in all
sectors.''
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary discussions with members of Congress have cheered
White House partisans, leading to at least momentary optimism that
Clinton can avoid a Senate impeachment trial on any of four
impeachment articles charging perjury, obstruction of justice and
abuse of power.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're fine, today,'' said one presidential adviser,
speaking on condition of anonymity. ``Today,'' he cautioned.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Thursday's greater sense of optimism among presidential
advisers, the Clinton White House has frequently misread the mood
of Congress. As recently as last weekend, Clinton and his top aides
were certain that the full House would approve at least one article
of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   One senior administration official said privately Thursday that
the White House was engaged in wishful thinking and predicted that
the House would vote to impeach Clinton next week.
</P>
<P>
   In another danger sign for the president, a senior Republican
aide in Congress said that four moderate Republicans that the White
House is actively courting will announce on Friday that they will
vote to impeach the president.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to pleas from his own advisers and fence-sitting
members of Congress, Clinton is considering a public statement on
the impeachment matter before he departs for Jerusalem on Saturday
or shortly after his return on Tuesday. If the Judiciary Committee
approves one or more articles of impeachment, as expected, the full
House will begin debate on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
