<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACCOUNTING-RULE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANGE IS PROPOSED BY ACCOUNTING BOARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The board that sets the United States' accounting rules agreed
Thursday to proceed with a plan that would require more companies
to consolidate their financial statements with those of companies
they control.
</P>
<P>
   The Financial Accounting Standards Board is concerned that when
a company controls another, the controlling concern may be able to
profit at the expense of the smaller company's shareholders. For
example, the larger company may sell goods to the other at inflated
prices, creating big profits for itself while causing losses for
its smaller partner.
</P>
<P>
   Although a current rule requires related companies to
consolidate their financial statements, companies can now avoid
that accounting by owning less than 50 percent of the other
company's stock. For example, Coca-Cola Co. now owns about 44
percent of its largest bottling company, Coca-Cola Enterprises, and
does not consolidate.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed rules would eliminate the 50 percent ownership rule
and instead look at the relationship of the two companies to
determine whether one controls the other. The board plans to issue
a draft of the new rules in February. Companies will then have 90
days to comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-98 2112EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
