<DOCNO> NYT19981210.0462 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4022 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PEACE-PIPEDREAM-MIDEA     12-10 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEACE-PIPEDREAM-MIDEAST-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WYE HOPE?: THE MIDEAST'S LONG, POTHOLED ROAD TO PEACE  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (TIMELY for Bill Clinton's trip to Mideast)   (This excellent 800-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 12 Dec. 1998) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from New York Times
Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``i''
international news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k''
commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1998 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just over five years ago, President Bill Clinton stood on the
White House lawn watching Israel's Yitzhak Rabin and the
Palestinians' Yasser Arafat shake hands on a historic peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   This ``Oslo'' accord truly was historic _ the first such deal
after 45 years of mutual hatred and non-recognition _ and much has
changed since then. Yet much, much more remains to be changed _ and
much has not changed at all, or even changed for the worse.
</P>
<P>
   This paper in 1993 foresaw a long, hard, potholed road to peace.
When Clinton arrives to visit both sides on Dec. 12 he will find
that the road has been even harder, and the potholes deeper, than
skeptics foresaw; and that the road ahead may well prove longer and
harder still, or even lead nowhere at all.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate sign of that has been the row over the recent Wye
mini-accord. Palestinians have been angered _ into disorder and
violence, some of them _ to find that a promised release of
Palestinian prisoners in practice meant more common criminals than
of the 2,000-odd political prisoners held by Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli government replied last week that freeing people
``with blood on their hands,'' or Hamas members, was no part of
Wye, and that it would stop implementing the accord unless the
Palestinian Authority admitted as much, halted and punished
violence and incitement to it, and renounced Arafat's threat to
declare a Palestinian state next May whether Israel agreed or not.
</P>
<P>
   Such roadblocks are removable; Arafat went halfway on Dec. 6,
talking only of ``agreement'' on a Palestinian state, not of a
unilateral declaration if none could be reached. But the spirit
that sets roadblocks up is far harder to shift.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at the five years since Oslo, Palestinians gravely doubt
that Rabin's current successor (and old opponent), Benjamin
Netanyahu, really wants peace at all; and he does not trust them to
mean peace when they say it.
</P>
<P>
   Next May was supposed _ hence Arafat's deadline _ to see the end
of the ``final-status'' negotiations. They have not yet begun.
</P>
<P>
   Why not? The straightforward answer is that things were always
bound to get bad and bitter as the final-status talks, and the
really hard issues such as Jerusalem grew nearer, and neither side
was ever likely to be in a hurry to grapple with those decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there are other answers too, which make a normal
deadlines-concentrate-the-mind optimism hard to share.
</P>
<P>
   Israel, in particular, has dragged its feet, though not without
reason: more Israelis have been killed by terrorism since Oslo than
before it, and Arafat is widely blamed for failing to prevent such
outrages by Hamas and others.
</P>
<P>
   It was shock at suicide bombings that brought Netanyahu to
office; now, having engaged reluctantly (and damagingly late) in
the Oslo and Wye procedures, his government looks on the verge of
collapse thanks to right-wing desertions.
</P>
<P>
   The side that must give up most if a durable peace is to be
found _ Israel _ remains profoundly unwilling to do so.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say nothing has altered. Palestinians do not
govern most of ``their'' land, but nearly all Palestinians are
under their aegis.
</P>
<P>
   And although the result is more of a patchwork than a country,
Netanyahu talks of a Palestinian state in terms that he would have
denounced as treason five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is change overdue only among Israelis. Palestinians and
their media are readier to vilify them than the other way about;
Palestinian hate is a barrier to peace, like Israeli contempt, and
uglier.
</P>
<P>
   However, the onus is inevitably on Israel, for it is Israel that
rules. It is Israel that since 1967 has occupied another people's
homeland, making changes _ after Oslo almost as before _ that may
yet render real peace unreachable.
</P>
<P>
   It has walled off Arab east Jerusalem with Jewish suburbs. It
has colonized the West Bank, under rules that allow any Israeli, be
he newly arrived from Omsk or Alaska, to settle, while exiled
Palestinians whose family may have lived there for centuries
cannot. Even now it confiscates Palestinian land and water.
</P>
<P>
   All this is natural enough in a people with Jewish history
behind it, and in a state whose neighbors long denied its right
even to exist.
</P>
<P>
   And it does require a leap of faith to believe that the
Palestinians, with no democratic history, few resources, fledgling
institutions and at least as many fundamentalist hotheads as Israel
itself, will quickly be capable of assuring the security of their
future state, let alone Israel's.
</P>
<P>
   Yet that is just what has to occur. President Clinton's task _
and no one should envy him it _ must be to help persuade Israelis
to make that leap. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
