<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4023 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-N     12-10 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUN MICROSYSTEMS EXECUTIVE TELLS OF MICROSOFT RIVALRY
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By STEVE LOHR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Microsoft trial Thursday offered an inside view
of the wary, distrustful relationship between Sun Microsystems Inc.
and Microsoft Corp., like two scorpions circling each other.
</P>
<P>
   They joined by a common interest in Internet software, a
programming language called Java, developed by Sun. Two years ago,
Microsoft signed a license agreement with Sun to use the Java
technology, but as testimony and e-mail evidence chronicled, there
was always more antagonism than cooperation between the two
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our view was that when Microsoft was holding out its hand,
there was a knife in that hand and Microsoft was asking us to grab
that knife,'' said Dr. James Gosling, a Sun vice president.
</P>
<P>
   The Microsoft-Sun clash is an issue because the government
alleges that Microsoft saw Java as a threat to its dominance of the
personal computer software market and illegally used its market
power to squelch the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   The promise of Java is that programs written in the language _
from word processors to games _ can run on any operating system,
making it a ``cross-platform'' technology. But Microsoft introduced
its own version of Java tailored for Windows. The company says it
did this to make Java applications work better with Windows, which
helped consumers and software developers.
</P>
<P>
   The government _ and Sun, in a separate contract suit in
California _ say Microsoft's tactics were intended mainly to stifle
Java's cross-platform challenge to Microsoft by making the Windows
version incompatible with versions for other operating systems.
Last month, a federal judge in San Jose sided with Sun and ordered
Microsoft to make its version compatible with Sun's Java within 90
days.
</P>
<P>
   The government introduced documents and e-mail showing that
Microsoft did indeed regard Java as a serious threat. One internal
Microsoft document said that is was a ``strategic objective'' for
the company to ``kill cross-platform Java'' by expanding the
``polluted Java market'' _ an apparent reference to Microsoft's
altered version of Java.
</P>
<P>
   An e-mail on July 14, 1997, from Paul Maritz, a senior Microsoft
executive, to a group of Microsoft executives including chairman
Bill Gates, identified Sun's Java technology as ``our major
threat'' and added that the Internet browsing software of its
rival, Netscape Communications Corp., was Java's ``major
distribution vehicle.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft agrees that it viewed Java as a threat, but says its
response was to build a superior version of Java technology. ``What
we saw in court today is that competition between Microsoft and Sun
is strong and vigorous,'' said John Warden, Microsoft's lead trial
lawyer. ``Microsoft competed hard and got ahead of Sun, and Sun is
understandably unhappy about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft hit that theme repeatedly Thursday in the
cross-examination of Gosling, one of Java's creators.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson asked Gosling a
question that suggested the Microsoft legal team might have made
some headway. The drift of Microsoft's cross-examination, Jackson
said, was that ``Microsoft recognized the significance of what you
did and ran with it. They produced a better product and couldn't
wait for you to catch up. What's your response to that
implication?''
</P>
<P>
   Gosling replied, ``Their version of better was tied to the
Windows platform.'' Later, he added that Microsoft's
Windows-tailored Java seemed intended to ``completely destroy our
goal for Java _ to make it run on many platforms.''
</P>
<P>
   On the courthouse steps Thursday evening, David Boies, the
Justice Department's lead trial lawyer, said Jackson's inquiry
seemed to indicate that he was impressed by points Microsoft had
made in its cross examination but added that the judge also seemed
impressed by Gosling's answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue in this case is whether Microsoft used its monopoly
power to forcd people to take its incompatible version of Java and
to inhibit the distribution of Sun's Java,'' he said. ``Yes,
Microsoft was trying to compete and make better software, but it
also had its thumb on the scale.''
</P>
<P>
   Gosling testified that Java's goal was to ``break the coupling
between software applications and the underlying operating system,
effectively decoupling these two markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, to be sure, has a huge vested interest in making sure
that the markets for applications and operating systems remain
tightly coupled. Its dominant position in work-related applications
like word processing and spreadsheets and the dominance of its
Windows operating system reinforce each other.
</P>
<P>
   With Windows running on more than 90 percent of personal
computers sold, Microsoft is a crucial partner, even for rivals
like Sun.
</P>
<P>
   In an e-mail on Sept. 12, 1996, after visiting senior Microsoft
executives, Eric Schmidt, then Sun's chief technology officer,
urged that Sun collaborate with Microsoft on Java. Schmidt, who is
now chairman of Novell Inc., offered a simple rationale:
</P>
<P>
   ``They will ship 50 million-plus copies of Java next year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
