<HEADER>
A4026 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-ART-3RDTAKE-N     12-10 0240
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-ART-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: Linda Tripp.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He showed how a defense lawyer might attack the case against the
president in a trial, by using tapes and videotapes. He attacked
the credibility of Ms. Lewinsky by playing a tape of her telling
Ms. Tripp on the phone how she had learned how to lie and deceive
her whole life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are the issues of the president's conduct in this case so
grave,'' he asked, ``that you would doom the country to additional
months of this ordeal and government paralysis _ on the slimmest of
votes on the House floor and no likely conviction in the Senate?''
</P>
<P>
   The committee is to begin voting on four separate articles of
impeachment Friday. They charge Clinton with perjury in testimony
before a grand jury, perjury in the Jones lawsuit, obstruction of
justice and abuse of power.
</P>
<P>
   Republican aides said the committee Republicans, who have a
21-16 majority, have solid support for perjury and obstruction of
justice charges. But Rep. George Gekas, R-Pa., said he was still
undecided on abuse of power, based on the president's claims of
legal privileges.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are expected to debate the articles vigorously but are
not expected to try to water them down, which might make them more
palatable to Republican moderates. ``We have no interest in
improving what we regard as a fatally flawed proposal,'' said
Julian Epstein, the committee's Democratic counsel.
</P>
</TEXT>
