<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-MIDLIFE-CRISIS-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTINENTAL DRIFT: RIFT WIDENS BETWEEN NATO PARTNERS  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This excellent 975-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 12 Dec. 1998) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from New York Times
Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``i''
international news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k''
commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1998 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just as it was preparing to hang out the bunting for its 50th
birthday next April, the world's strongest military alliance has
teetered on the brink of real trouble.
</P>
<P>
   In backroom discussions, NATO diplomats found they could not
agree on what the alliance was for, what weapons it would threaten
to use and in what circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of the Soviet threat that once glued NATO and its
16 members together, such disagreements have an ominous feel about
them; however effective it has been in the past, nothing guarantees
that this partnership will last forever.
</P>
<P>
   Such existential traumas were successfully covered up at this
week's gathering of NATO foreign ministers. Madeleine Albright, the
American secretary of state, assured her allies that future NATO
missions would take them a bit further afield, but not all over the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Presumably this means the alliance might set off to keep the
peace in the Caucasus or rescue hostages in North Africa, but it
will not be dragged off to fight wars in South America or
Indochina.
</P>
<P>
   Joschka Fischer, the German foreign minister, beat a tactical
retreat after his proposal that NATO renounce the first use of
nuclear weapons was dismissed as unrealistic.
</P>
<P>
   Other Europeans, for their part, assured Mrs. Albright that they
shared American worries about ballistic missiles and chemical or
biological weapons in the hands of dictators or terrorists. She in
turn promised them that NATO would never abandon its core function
of protecting its members from invasion.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no room for complacency about the future of a
partnership that was created half a century ago, in a different
world. Perhaps because they do not follow the mood of the American
Congress closely enough, European governments were thrown into a
state of shock by some of the messages they have received recently
from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, American taxpayers have little enthusiasm for an
alliance designed to fight yesterday's wars in Europe. So America's
interest in transatlantic cooperation will be proportional to
Europe's willingness to face future challenges: poison gas, germ
warfare, rogue missiles, ethnic wars on _ or a little beyond _
NATO's periphery.
</P>
<P>
   Such talk makes Europeans feel distinctly queasy. They felt
comfortable with a military structure that was mainly geared to
warding off conventional threats to their own territory _ and where
all the hardest strategic decisions were, and are, taken and
implemented by Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, NATO will not disappear overnight, even if the
Europeans dig in their heels and refuse to adapt. But the alliance
could very rapidly lose its place in the pecking order of America's
overseas security commitments.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from transatlantic tiffs over military theory, there have
also been squabbles about military practice _ especially in the
Balkans. While Americans have longstanding doubts about Europe's
competence in handling the multiple crises of former Yugoslavia,
the Europeans are now grumbling about the tactics of the United
States in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   They say it handled the high-wire diplomacy almost unilaterally
_ and left them alone with the risky job of preparing an
intervention force to stand by, in nearby Macedonia, in case the
cease-fire in Kosovo fails and international monitors there need
rescuing.
</P>
<P>
   To this complaint, Americans will reply that Kosovo would never
have reached boiling point if, at earlier stages in the crisis, the
Europeans had not been complacent.
</P>
<P>
   How much do these differences matter? The practical ones maybe
more than the theory. If NATO ever does break up, the occasion is
likelier to be some real-world crisis than a difference over
mission statements or military doctrine.
</P>
<P>
   No strategic theory will compel a NATO government to risk its
soldiers unless it feels vital interests are at stake; and no
doctrinal nicety will stop NATO acting when it sees a deadly
danger.
</P>
<P>
   The Kosovo crisis _ in which NATO made a highly unusual threat
to intervene in a sovereign state, because the alternative seemed
disastrous _ shows how far practice comes before theory.
</P>
<P>
   No diplomatic formula can foresee all the crises of the future;
that is why NATO should pledge to respect international law, but
not always wait for a U.N. Security Council resolution, which
implies Russian and Chinese consent.
</P>
<P>
   Yet arguments about NATO's mission, and grumblings about its
practice, as in Kosovo, both highlight an important geopolitical
reality. The alliance will not survive, in any solid sense, unless
Europeans and Americans do some hard, honest talking about their
division of labor.
</P>
<P>
   America will not indefinitely bankroll the security of wealthy
countries whose military budgets are a fraction of its own, and
falling _ let alone if those countries are unwilling to adapt to
new security challenges.
</P>
<P>
   As well as tinkering with institutions, European governments
should spend more money on modernizing their arsenals. This does
not mean vastly increasing their power; but it does mean deploying
firepower more efficiently by harnessing information technology.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, a transatlantic partnership in which Europe
pulls more weight can only be developed successfully if Europeans
are convinced of American good faith.
</P>
<P>
   Even when Europeans provide most of the troops for peacekeeping
operations, they need to be assured that America stands ready to
support them with logistics and intelligence and to extract them if
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   There is one other, very tangible way in which European and
Americans can demonstrate good faith _ and that is by procuring
weapons from one another, or jointly developing new technology to
cope with 21st-century threats.
</P>
<P>
   With the future of the defense industry at a crossroads it is
more important than ever that NATO governments face down
protectionist lobbies and ensure themselves the broadest possible
choice of modern weaponry and electronics.
</P>
<P>
   A dense network of relationships between defense companies could
do more than any form of words in a summit communique to keep NATO
intact. &QL; 
