<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAGUE'S LAST STAND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Exhale? Not George Teague. Yes, he'll make his
second consecutive start of the year in Kansas City on Sunday. But
he will be desperately fighting to show he can be a starting free
safety in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   From Green Bay, to Atlanta, to Dallas, to Miami, and back to
Dallas, Teague's six-year tenure has been marked by the
all-too-frequent assertion that he wasn't good enough. At 27, he
has been waived, traded, or demoted more times than he'd care to
remember.
</P>
<P>
   ``Depending on how I play and how we do,'' he said, ``these next
few months will probably determine my future. I've got another
chance here to make it as a free safety.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys gave that chance to Omar Stoutmire. He received most
of the reps with the first team in training camp and most of the
starts in the preseason. At 24, Stoutmire was younger, faster, and
stronger against the run than Teague, which is where the Cowboys
felt they needed the most help going into the season.
</P>
<P>
   Teague began the year as a reserve used primarily in passing
situations. Stoutmire played the run fairly well, but struggled as
the quarterback of the Cowboys' pass defense.
</P>
<P>
   He broke up just two passes and had no interceptions. He was
often replaced in passing situations with Teague. Stoutmire's
demise hastened with the toe injury to Deion Sanders. Without
Sanders the past four weeks, the Cowboys' pass defense has dropped
from 13th to 24th.
</P>
<P>
   A change in the secondary was needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a good idea of what kind of player George was,''
defensive coordinator Dave Campo said. ``We felt like we'd like to
have one of the younger guys step up and do it. We gave Omar as
much of an opportunity as we could. We just thought it was time to
get a veteran and George has been known as a playmaker.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coach Chan Gailey is confident that Teague's insertion
into the starting lineup will not compromise the club's
run-stopping ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel like what you gain in other aspects offsets George not
being involved in the running game,'' Gailey said. ``And Omar
hasn't gone out and been one of those guys lighting people up in
the running game. That \Rrunning game\S has not been the
difference. It's pass defense that we need expertise in and wanted
George back there.''
</P>
<P>
   Teague has been here before. Drafted in the first round by the
Green Bay Packers in 1993, Teague started 43 games in three seasons
before the club traded him to Atlanta. The Falcons waived him a
month later and he signed with the Cowboys, where he started eight
games in 1996 after Brock Marion was lost for the season with an
arm injury.
</P>
<P>
   Teague thought he was gone from Dallas for good after the 1996
season, when he signed a three-year, $2.1 million contract to play
free safety for Jimmy Johnson in Miami. But Johnson made him
compete for a job at strong safety, where he'd be needed more for
his play against the run, not the pass.
</P>
<P>
   Teague made six starts for the Dolphins and was benched midway
through the season. The club terminated his contract when he would
not take a paycut in the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me and Jimmy disagreed on a lot of things,'' Teague said.
``They didn't tell me I was playing strong safety until after they
signed me. My strengths have always been as a cover guy. It was
tough because we were not on the same page. I fought through that,
but it was hard with all of the ins-and-outs of the rotation. From
week to week, I didn't know if I was going to be the nickel safety,
or not be playing at all, or be put on the inactive list.''
</P>
<P>
   He knows where he stands with the Cowboys. If he continues to
play well, he'll continue to start. There will be competition for
the job next year, Campo said, but Teague knows he can get ahead of
the game by making big plays the rest of the year. In his first
start against the Saints last week, he had eight tackles and two
sacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best place, system-wise, for me, and I'd love to
continue playing here,'' said Teague, who signed a two-year deal
with the Cowboys last spring. ``This defense compliments my style
of play, which is aggressive on the ball. They like the free safety
to cover and try to make plays. And that's exactly what I try to
do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-98 2119EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
