<HEADER>
A4039 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUPERMAN-DALEY-CHICAG     12-10 1244
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPERMAN-DALEY-CHICAGO-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHICAGO MAYOR'S LESSONS FOR OTHER AMERICAN CITIES  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Chicago)   (This excellent 1,050-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 12 Dec. 1998) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from New York Times
Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1998 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a small, cluttered antechamber just off the mayor's office,
Richard M. Daley leans forward over a conference table like an
excited schoolboy, balancing on the front legs of his chair.
</P>
<P>
   He is talking about public education. Not all his sentences have
verbs. Some stream off to nowhere. He pauses occasionally to chew
on an unlit cigar. But in the process of making George Bush sound
like Cicero, Daley is actually quite clear.
</P>
<P>
   The key to Chicago's future is keeping the middle class. And the
key to keeping the middle class is to improve the schools.
</P>
<P>
   To no one's surprise, Daley announced this week that he will be
seeking a third full term as mayor of Chicago. He will probably
trounce his one declared opponent and anyone else who enters the
race. He won his previous election handsomely.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, the Daley operation delivered 207,000
nominating signatures to the board of election commissioners, eight
times the number required by law. The Chicago Tribune called this
display ``Schwarzenegger-esque.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Chicagoans are now thinking of Daley as they used to think
of his father: mayor for life. Richard J. Daley ran Chicago with a
rod of iron for 21 years, and was considered one of the most
impressive mayors in the country.
</P>
<P>
   His eldest son has personally picked 19 of the 50 city council
members, filling vacancies created by those who have died, retired,
or (not infrequently) gone to prison.
</P>
<P>
   He has established strong ties to the business community,
precluding any serious Republican opposition and availing himself
of deep campaign pockets.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he has defended minority set-asides for city
contracts. His campaign manager is black; some of his top
appointments, including the chairman of his school reform board of
trustees, are Latino.
</P>
<P>
   None of this is surprising; in political shrewdness, he is
obviously his father's son.
</P>
<P>
   But it would be wrong to dismiss Daley as a skillful
vote-gatherer whose policies would not work without the magic of
the Daley name. This mayor has much to teach America's other
cities.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, if he succeeds in his bid to reform the public
schools, he will do something that no big-city mayor has ever done,
including his father.
</P>
<P>
   Daley's political success was hardly preordained. He failed the
bar exam twice before passing. As a state senator, he was named by
Chicago magazine as one of the ten worst legislators in Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   In his first bid for mayor in 1983, he finished third in a
three-person Democratic primary. Nonetheless, he inched his way
back until, in 1989, he finally reached City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, he has focused like a laser on making the city a
better place for the middle class to live in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think cities should be dirty and filthy,'' he says. As
he is driven around Chicago, he makes lists: abandoned cars to be
towed away, trash piles to be moved, fences to be mended.
</P>
<P>
   His ``graffiti-blasters'' program has attracted attention as far
away as Milan. Spray paint is banned in the city; there is a
24-hour anti-graffiti hot line; city crews have the legal right to
remove graffiti from private property.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's positive passion is greenery: the city has planted
over 200,000 trees. Pavements have been widened and street lights
replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Even the cynical admit that Chicago, already an architectural
gem, is a prettier city because of Daley's green thumb and
fastidious housekeeping.
</P>
<P>
   But, as he tended his beloved trees, Daley realized that he was
missing the forest. No amount of greenery could stem the flight
from a school system long considered one of the country's worst.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the mayor struck a deal with the Republican-controlled
state legislature to wrest control of the schools away from the
city's semi-independent school board and its impenetrable
bureaucracy. ``I'm the only mayor that wanted the responsibility,''
Daley reflects.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder. The system was chronically in debt; students
performed abysmally by national standards; striking teachers were a
ritual of autumn.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers speculated that the Republicans gave the system
to Daley in the hope that it would blow up in his face. Instead,
the gamble has paid off handsomely for him.
</P>
<P>
   His reform team has deflated the bureaucracy, sacked teachers at
the worst-performing schools, and demanded that students actually
learn things before being promoted to the next grade.
</P>
<P>
   Test scores are up. After years of fiscal crises, the budget is
balanced. The city has just negotiated a new agreement with the
teachers' union, almost a year before the old one was due to
expire.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the mayor realizes where the proof of the pudding lies:
whether middle-class parents en masse will feel happy to send their
children to inner-city schools. Making sure they do is the task for
a third term.
</P>
<P>
   If Daley has the enthusiasm of a schoolboy when he talks about
his plans, friends and enemies know that he can also be the class
bully. Unprepared staff members are often on the receiving end of
his tantrums. So is anyone who stands in the way of his grand
plans.
</P>
<P>
   When the city began preparing for the 1996 Democratic National
Convention, the mayor was keen to have decorative wrought-iron
fences erected along the route most visitors would be taking, at
the property-owners' expense. When some balked, city inspectors
began to take special interest in their properties.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a patience boiling-point of about ten degrees,'' notes
one observer. And he never forgets an enemy.
</P>
<P>
   For all that, the people of Chicago seem to like their mayor, in
part because of his passion for the city.
</P>
<P>
   He says quite credibly that he has no aspirations for higher
office. His mangled syntax is refreshing; most politicians, though
more articulate, say less.
</P>
<P>
   When your Economist columnist Lexington begins a question, ``One
hundred years from now...,'' the mayor's brow furrows, like a pupil
at the blackboard who knows that a tough one may be coming. But
it's a softball: ``How would you like to be remembered?''
</P>
<P>
   He answers almost immediately: ``Education mayor. That's it.''
Of course, some of those trees may still be around as well. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 1,050-word article, it must be purchased from New
York Times Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS in New York
at 1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at 212-499-3382.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
