A4040 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-ARGUMENTS-HNS     12-10 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ARGUMENTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP, DEMOCRATIC COUNSELS SEE CLINTON'S CONDUCT DIFFERENTLY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Republican and Democratic counsels for the
House Judiciary Committee on Thursday offered starkly different
characterizations of President Clinton's conduct and its impact on
the country in closing arguments at the impeachment hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Describing Clinton's effort to conceal his extramarital
relationship with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky as
criminal, Republican counsel David Schippers accused the president
of using the power of the Oval Office to weave a cover-up that
involved lying under oath and trying to influence the testimony of
his friends and staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not about sex or private conduct,'' Schippers told the
committee of 21 Republicans and 16 Democrats. ``It is about
multiple obstructions of justice, perjury, false and misleading
statements, witness tamperings and abuses of power, all committed
or orchestrated by the president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Schippers called on the panel to recommend impeachment to the
full House, saying that to do anything less would amount to
``dishonor and abandonment of the high principles'' that Americans
rely on ``for our safety and happiness.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't impeach ... then no House of Representatives will
ever be able to impeach again,'' the Republican counsel declared.
``The bar will be so high that only a convicted felon or a traitor
will need to be concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic counsel Abbe Lowell, however, implored the committee
not to be swayed by the argument that Clinton's transgressions were
as serious as those that led to President Nixon's resignation over
Watergate. Lowell said the president's conduct amounted to no more
than ``insignificant offenses'' concocted not by an ``errant
president but ... an unfaithful husband.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not surprising, improper or impeachable for the
president to want to hide his improper relationship,'' Lowell said,
adding that most people would think it reasonable that the
president would want to keep it ``from anyone and everyone he
could.''
</P>
<P>
   Calling impeachment ``the equivalent of the death penalty'' for
a president, he warned that the panel could be taking the first
step in a process that might end in the ``horror'' of a Senate
trial that would disrupt the business of the country next year.
</P>
<P>
   Lowell said the trial, which would necessarily dwell on details
of the sexual relationship, would further erode Congress' standing
with an American public already fed up with scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public has been telling us for months, and in every way
they can, they do not want to see a trial in the Senate where the
issues will be sex, and they want there to be censure and other
alternatives to impeachment as the means to demonstrate that the
president is not above the law,'' Lowell said.
</P>
<P>
   In their presentations, both counsels relied heavily on
videotaped exerpts of President Clinton's deposition last January
in the Paula Jones sexual harassment lawsuit, which has since been
settled. The videotape, which had not been seen publicly before,
was released by the committee Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Schippers used it to bolster his argument that Clinton knowingly
lied under oath and to reinforce his claim the president had
engaged in a pattern of conspiracy from late 1997 through August of
this year to hide the details of his relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Lowell, on the other hand, used it to contend that Clinton
testified truthfully, given the  &UR; `` &LR; twisted &UR; ''  &LR; definition of
sexual relations presented to him by Jones' attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   Where Schippers saw ``a performance ... calculated to mislead
and deceive'' on the videotape, Lowell said he saw only the
tortured ``confusion'' of a president trying to figure out the
legalistic definition of sex.
</P>
<P>
   Lowell played an excerpt from the Jan. 17 deposition, in which
lawyers for Jones, Clinton and state Trooper Danny Ferguson argue
over what definition of sexual relations will be adopted for the
proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   Finally the trial judge strikes two of the three paragraphs from
the definition originally given to the president and says she fears
that he might not grasp the significance of all of the terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knew some collusion was going on to embarrass him, not
about sexual harassment but about a consensual affair,'' Lowell
said. ``So, his responses were an attempt to answer evasively. ...
We all know he could have _ should have _ acted better. But are his
responses so hard to understand that you would impeach him?''
</P>
<P>
   Schippers, who offered a day-by-day, point-by-point account of
what he portrayed as a conspiracy designed to subvert the rule of
law, played his own video clips in which Clinton repeatedly
insisted that his relationship with Lewinsky was not sexual.
</P>
<P>
   In one clip, Clinton read an affidavit from Lewinsky also
denying sexual relations and then told Jones' lawyers that her
statements were ``absolutely true.''
</P>
<P>
   The majority counsel also stressed that Clinton had lied when he
told Jones' lawyers that he could not recall ever being alone with
Lewinsky in or near the Oval Office when, according to Starr's
investigation, they were alone on at least 21 occasions, 11 of
which involved sexual encounters.
</P>
<P>
   Schippers observed sarcastically: ``Life was so much simpler
(for the president) before they found that dress, wasn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   The comment was in reference to a dress that Lewinsky kept with
DNA evidence on it belonging to the president.
</P>
<P>
   The remark angered a few members of the committee, including
Republicans who said it was an unnecessary slap at the president.
Some also criticized Schippers for beginning his presentation by
observing that ``many other allegations of possible serious
wrongdoing'' by the president are still under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Asa Hutchison, R-Ark., accused Schippers of ``overstepping
his bounds'' with the remark.
</P>
<P>
   White House special counsel Gregory Craig also issued a response
to the Schippers presentation, saying that it had reduced a
``solemn constitutional process ... to a level of innuendo, anger
and unfair, unsubstantiated charges.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
