<DOCNO> NYT19981210.0484 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4055 &Cx1f; tab-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GHOSTS-HAUNT-GERMANY-     12-10 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GHOSTS-HAUNT-GERMANY-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE EXPLOITATION OF GERMAN GUILT  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This excellent 900-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 12 Dec. 1998) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from New York Times
Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``i''
international news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k''
commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1998 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BONN _ Nothing underlines the German paradox better than a new
debate, even shriller than its predecessors, over the Nazi era and
the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   It may seem odd, on the face of it, that the row has re-erupted
now, and so bitterly. After all, it is more than 50 years since
Hitler's death, eight since Germany was reunited. And for the first
time a chancellor, Gerhard Schroder, has come to office with no
personal experience of the Second World War.
</P>
<P>
   A country more or less like any other at last? That is what
Schroder implied in his first government declaration to parliament
last month. Germany, he said, had ``the self-confidence of a nation
that has come of age, that feels neither superior nor inferior to
anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   That is also very much what Martin Walser, a 71-year-old author,
claimed a few weeks earlier in a speech after receiving the
country's highest book award. But he went further, charging that,
although Germany had become a normal country, its shame over the
Holocaust was being exploited (he did not define by whom).
</P>
<P>
   Auschwitz, Walser declared before the nation's political and
social elite, should not become a ``tool of intimidation, a moral
cudgel or just a compulsory exercise.'' He for one had learned to
turn away when this part of Germany's past was drummed home ``every
day in the media.''
</P>
<P>
   Walser got a big hand from most present, but notably not from
Ignatz Bubis, leader of Germany's Jews: he stayed seated when
others rose to applaud.
</P>
<P>
   Bubis waited until Nov. 9, the 60th anniversary of
``Kristallnacht,'' when Hitler's thugs smashed Jewish shops and
synagogues, before replying. But he then accused the author, long
best-known as a wry critic of Germany's postwar consumer society,
of ``spiritual arson'' likely to delight and egg on neo-Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   Since then the row has been joined by other authors and
editorial writers, politicians and historians; and it has gained so
much in venom that a worried ex-president, Richard von Weizsacker,
begged the participants to ``cool it.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most cutting ripostes to Bubis came from Klaus von
Dohnanyi, a former Social Democratic mayor of Hamburg whose father
was a resistance hero killed by the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   Would Jews really have shown more courage than most other
Germans under Hitler, he asked, if they had been spared the gas
chambers and ``only'' cripples, homosexuals and gypsies had been
massacred?
</P>
<P>
   ``Anti-Semite,'' snapped back Bubis. He and von Dohnanyi met on
Dec. 8 and resolved some of their differences, but the general
debate rolls on.
</P>
<P>
   Why now? Partly because of the claims now being made against
German firms by lawyers, particularly in America, acting on behalf
of former slave laborers under the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of Germans grumble that the government has paid
compensation enough to Nazi victims already (albeit little for
slave labor). The huge sums being demanded in the wake of those
extracted earlier this year from the Swiss are, they reckon, only
partly justified at best.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Walser did not directly refer to slave laborers,
most of whom were not, in fact, Jews; but, with the claims issue
highly topical, his talk about exploiting German shame struck a
powerful chord and helps account for the force of the reaction.
</P>
<P>
   There is more to it than that, though. Walser was right when he
referred to the flood of material _ television documentaries,
books, plays _ about the Nazi era now pouring forth in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   What a contrast with the drought until only about two decades
ago, when the American television serial ``Holocaust'' finally
brought the breakthrough. Plenty of old people who lived through
Hitler's Reich, whether as fans or victims, find the near nonstop
reminders of it nowadays hard to take.
</P>
<P>
   For the young, though, it is an often-fascinating
semi-historical drama for which they feel little or no guilt. It is
notable, for instance, that they are flocking to Potsdam to see the
first comprehensive show in Germany since the Second World War of
films and pictures by Leni Riefenstahl, a photographer Hitler
favored.
</P>
<P>
   Should they feel guilt? Behind the current debate lurks the
question how to keep the shame and warning of the Nazi era alive
for a generation which did not experience it.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Walser's message is that Auschwitz is a matter for
personal conscience, not oft-repeated ritual that eventually
becomes little more than lip service. Perhaps, but will that
formula do, when no survivors of the Nazi era remain?
</P>
<P>
   Nothing reveals the dilemma better than the long-running battle
over a scheme to build a memorial to victims of the Holocaust near
the Brandenburg Gate in the center of Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   Some do not want a memorial at all, many more do _ but think the
current plan for some 2,500 concrete pillars spreading across a
swathe of central Berlin far too intimidating.
</P>
<P>
   A decision was due before the September general election but was
shelved. Now there are hints that the scheme may be dropped in
favor of some sort of link-up with Steven Spielberg's Shoah
Foundation and its filmed interviews with Holocaust survivors.
</P>
<P>
   Stand by for more agonized debate on the past, and how to mark
it, as the government prepares to move east next summer from Bonn
to the old and new capital Berlin. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 900-word article, it must be purchased from New
York Times Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS in New York
at 1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at 212-499-3382.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
