<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAULDER-EXECUTE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Supreme Court puts execution on hold
 &HT;    By Mike Ward
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The U.S. Supreme Court, with just 15 minutes to
spare, blocked the execution Thursday of a Canadian-born killer
whose case had triggered the latest international controversy over
how Texas puts to death its worst criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Without elaboration, the high court put the execution on hold _
presumably for more time to review Faulder's pending appeal. Court
spokesman Ed Turner said no date for that review had been set.
</P>
<P>
   The decision means Faulder will live into early 1999, since
executions cannot be rescheduled for at least 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   At age 61, he would have been the oldest Texas convict ever
executed and would have been the first Canadian to be executed in
the United States since 1952.
</P>
<P>
   ``Far out. That suits me,'' prison officials quoted Faulder as
responding when they gave him the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he hoped the decision will help others down the
road,'' prison spokesman Larry Fitzgerald said. ``He was a very
happy man. Stan didn't have a lot of emotion. He wasn't dancing,
but he obviously was very happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Five relatives of Faulder's victim who were in Huntsville to
witness the execution _ including her son and two granddaughters _
left the prison without speaking to reporters. ``I'm sorry for the
Phillips family and this is not about the Phillips family,'' Sandra
Babcock, Faulder's attorney, said. ``What they suffered was tragic.
I'm very sorry for what happened to them. That's not the issue
here. The issue here is whether Stan Faulder received a fair trial.
And he did not.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Faulder's case has stirred intense interest
from death-penalty opponents worldwide and from Canadian officials
who asked that he be spared. Last week, U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright joined with Canadian Foreign Minister Lloyd
Axworthy in seeking a reprieve for Faulder and, on Wednesday, the
president of the American Bar Association joined them.
</P>
<P>
   Faulder was sentenced to death for the July, 1975, murder of
Inez Phillips, the matriarch of an East Texas oil family. Her body
was found inside her Gladewater home with her skull fractured and a
butcher knife buried 6 1/2 inches in her chest.
</P>
<P>
   Faulder has never denied his guilt, confessing at one point that
he had become enraged after finding her safe empty. But in recent
appeals, Faulder's attorneys argued that his execution would
violate an international treaty that requires that foreign citizens
jailed in the United States be allowed to contact a diplomat from
their country for help. Texas officials said he was not given that
option because he had a Colorado drivers license and had applied
for a Texas license at the time, and he never claimed Canadian
citizenship until long after he had been imprisoned.
</P>
<P>
   ``The highest court in the land has now spoken,'' said Karen
Hughes, press secretary to Gov. George W. Bush, who had been under
pressure in recent days to stop the execution. ``The governor hopes
the courts will review and resolve this legal matter as quickly as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's last-minute intervention by the Supreme Court marked
only the latest of several legal turns in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Until midday, his execution had remained on hold. U.S. District
Judge Sam Sparks of Austin on Wednesday had blocked the executions
of both Faulder and Danny Lee Barber until lingering legal
questions about the secretive process by which Texas considers
clemency for its condemned criminals could be resolved.
</P>
<P>
   But three judges on the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals then
overturned Sparks' order in Faulder's case. Their reason: ``Federal
courts lack jurisdiction to stay the execution'' in civil-rights
cases such as Faulder's.
</P>
<P>
   Three other judges on the same court reached the opposite
conclusion Wednesday night, when they upheld Sparks' order in
Barber's case _ a decision that spared him from the executioner's
needle for at least 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   Faulder's attorneys immediately asked the New Orleans-based
court for a hearing to resolve the conflict between the two
decisions. With no reply to their request, they asked the U.S.
Supreme Court to halt the execution _ a request that increasingly
has been routinely denied.
</P>
<P>
   By 2 p.m., the former auto mechanic had been escorted under
heavy guard from the Ellis prison just outside Huntsville, where
death row is located, to the ``death house'' inside an historic
downtown Huntsville prison known as ``The Walls.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to thank the people of Canada for being supportive of
me,'' Faulder told prison spokesman Larry Fitzgerald as he arrived
at a holding cell just outside the death chamber.
</P>
<P>
   At about 5:45 p.m., the Supreme Court blocked the execution.
Within two hours, Faulder was back in his death row cell.
</P>
<P>
   Just a day earlier, Barber, 43, had walked out of the same
red-brick bungalow that houses Texas' execution chamber to return
to his death row cell, thanks to Sparks' order and the decision by
the New Orleans court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm delighted he got a stay, but the last couple of days have
been pretty hellish,'' Babcock said. ``I think it's absolutely
abominable that we learned that he had a stay 15 minutes before his
scheduled execution.''
</P>
<P>
   In Austin, state officials said they likely will seek to
dissolve the Supreme Court's order so Faulder's execution can
proceed.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks has scheduled a Dec. 21 hearing in Austin to review
whether Texas' clemency process is legally flawed, as Faulder's
attorneys insist. A separate hearing on the same issue has been
scheduled the following day in Barber's case.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's office continued Thursday to be flooded with phone calls
and mail about the case. By day's end, aides estimated the governor
would have received 2,000 letters _ a volume that, while much
larger than most execution cases, is far less than the 9,000
letters received about Karla Faye Tucker's execution last February.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker, a convicted Houston pickax killer who said she had
become a Christian and changed, was the first woman executed by the
state for a crime since the Civil War. Her case also spurred
international interest.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Edwards, a Bush spokeswoman, said that by Thursday, the
governor had received 1,769 letters and e-mail messages _ 1,623 of
them supporting clemency for Faulder. Of the total, 915 were from
Canada and most of the rest were from outside the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Canada abolished the death penalty in 1976. Texas has executed
163 people since it started using the death penalty again 14 years
ago this month, the most of any state.
</P>
<P>
   This article includes material from The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
