<HEADLINE>
U.S., RUSSIAN SPACEWALKERS MARK ENTRANCE INTO SPACE STATION 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The U.S. and Russian crew of the shuttle Endeavour
made an emotional first entrance into the new international space
station Thursday, stopping to commemorate the occasion before
tackling a long list of move-in tasks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an absolutely super place. It's unbelievable,'' gushed
Endeavour commander Robert Cabana as he and Russian cosmonaut
Sergei Krikalev floated side-by-side from the shuttle into the
dimly lit American ``Unity'' module. ``Words can't express it. It's
unbelievable to be part of such a great program, bringing all these
countries together, working in space for everybody's betterment.''
</P>
<P>
   Krikalev and U.S. astronaut Nancy Curry embraced and turned lazy
somersaults in the soft pink and off-white confines of the boxy
module. With its half-dozen docking ports, Unity serves as a
structural gateway to future Russian and American modules as well
as to the European, Japanese and Canadian equipment that will be
added during a six-year construction period.
</P>
<P>
   The six astronauts made their way through about 75 feet of
previously uninhabited corridors, pausing to open a half-dozen
hatches before reaching the furthest recesses of the Russian
``Zarya'' power and propulsion module. The trek took nearly 90
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Zarya was joined to Unity by the shuttle crew Sunday. Before
floating from Unity to Zarya, Cabana and Krikalev shook hands
firmly, then hugged one another before leading their colleagues
into the more confined grey-green interior of the Russian module.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say how much this means to all of us,'' said Cabana,
recalling the five-year effort to work post-Cold War Russia into a
floundering effort by the United States and the other partners to
develop a new global outpost. ``We can't wait to see the outcome of
what we've started.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's small,'' said a grinning Krikalev. ``We need more
modules.''
</P>
<P>
   Endeavour, with the first two of the station's module towering
eight stories above its combination airlock and docking assembly,
soared 247 miles over the Indian Ocean, just south of the Saudi
Arabian peninsula, as the astronauts made their way aboard the
station at 1:54 p.m., CST.
</P>
<P>
   Once inside Unity, the astronauts' first task literally was to
turn on the lights. Even though a spacewalk by astronauts Jerry
Ross and Jim Newman on Monday night routed electrical power from
the Russian to the U.S. module, Unity was launched with its master
interior light circuit mistakenly switched off.
</P>
<P>
   Ground control teams had hoped to warm the cold module to a
comfortable 70 degrees for its first occupants, but they overshot
their mark. With all the human activity and the activation of
electronic gear, the interior of Unity warmed to 84 degrees.
Cabana's crew snaked air ducts from Endeavour into the station
modules and installed fans for circulation. The shuttle life
support systems removed the carbon dioxide and excess humidity.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle crew was to retreat from the two station modules
Friday after installing equipment and storing clothing, a laptop
computer and other gear aboard the fledgling station for its first
resident crew.
</P>
<P>
   That three-man crew, of which Krikalev will be a member, is to
take residence in early 2000. Its arrival, however, depends on
Russia's launching of the massive service module, a crew living
quarters. Its assembly has been stalled by that country's economic
problems. The module is scheduled for launching no sooner than July
1999. It, too, will be joined to the Zarya module.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most crucial of the tasks the Endeavour astronauts
were to perform before their retreat was the hookup of three large
electronics boxes and cabling to complete the installation of a
satellite communications system. Astronauts Ross and Newman began
the task during a spacewalk Wednesday night in which they attached
a pair of suit-case sized antennas to the outside of Zarya.
</P>
<P>
   The communications gear will permit NASA's mission control team
in Houston to monitor the station when it is not staffed and send
commands over a satellite network rather than through Russia's
control facility in suburban Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Krikalev and Currie joined forces to install a new charge
controller on one of Zarya's six power storage batteries. The
controller faltered soon after the module's Nov. 20 launching. The
device automatically regulates the power dispensed by the battery
after it has been charge by the module's power-generating solar
panels.
</P>
<P>
   Among the least glamourous of the chores was the removal of 774
bolts used to secure protective panels within Zarya before its
launching, a task assigned to Endeavour pilot Rick Sturckow.
</P>
<P>
   The path traced by the astronauts into the new station Thursday
began at the base of the shuttle's docking assembly.
</P>
<P>
   With successive hatch openings, the astronauts made their way
from the shuttle into an eight-foot long, cone-shaped docking
compartment secured to Unity, then into the 18-foot long American
module and through a second eight-foot long docking cone. Then it
was into the 41-foot-long Russian module, which is segmented into a
small and a large chamber.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
