<HEADER>
A4076 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOLF-COURSE-SHOOTING1     12-10 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLF-COURSE-SHOOTING11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Golfer shoots teen during robbery
 &HT;    By R. Robin McDonald and Bill Torpy
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A golfer at a metro Atlanta country club shot a
student in the face Thursday afternoon after the youth and two
fellow students tried to rob a foursome at gunpoint on the golf
course's 15th hole, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives said they suspect the teen-agers are involved in a
string of bold, daylight robberies that for months have victimized
golfers at the Hidden Hills Golf and Country Club in east DeKalb
County less than a mile from a local high school.
</P>
<P>
   The wounded student remained in critical condition Thursday
night at a local hospital that police declined to name. They would
not release his name because he is a juvenile. Detectives said they
intend to charge him and his two cohorts with attempted robbery,
kidnapping and aggravated assault.
</P>
<P>
   All three students had been suspended from Redan High School,
but detectives could not say what prompted the disciplinary action.
</P>
<P>
   The golfing foursome was traveling in three golf carts on a
wooded trail between holes about 4 p.m. when they were accosted by
the robbers, said DeKalb Sgt. Ron Eunice.
</P>
<P>
   As the second cart rounded a small curve, the golfers
encountered the three robbers, at least two of them armed, who had
been lying prone on the ground. The robbers leaped up, grabbed the
cart's two occupants, and forced them face-down on the ground at
gunpoint and began rifling through their pockets, Eunice said.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, the third cart rounded the curve.
</P>
<P>
   When the driver, whom detectives declined to name for his own
safety, saw the robbery in progress, he pulled a gun from his golf
bag and fired, striking one of the robbers in the face, Eunice
said.
</P>
<P>
   The two other robbers ran away. But detectives said they have
``good information'' on their identities and had detained a
teen-ager for questioning Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives said they have not charged the golfer who fired the
shot and that, based on their preliminary investigation, they
probably won't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good for him,'' said club member Ted Marvin when he learned of
the shooting Thursday afternoon. ``This is one of my favorite
places to be. We come out here to unwind, to get away from the
world. It's a sad commentary when you have to worry out on the
course.''
</P>
<P>
   The golf course snakes through an upscale neighborhood of newer
suburban homes.
</P>
<P>
   The club has complained repeatedly about students using the golf
course as a cut-through, said DeKalb County school spokesman
Spencer Ragsdale. ``We told them over and over not to trespass on
their property,'' said Ragsdale.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives said Thursday that robbers have been plaguing the
golfers for months, even on the day after Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 6, police arrested a 16-year-old Redan student at the
golf course shortly after two masked robbers on the fourth tee
stole cellular phones and a pager from golfers, detectives said.
</P>
<P>
   The teen-ager, whose name remains confidential because he is a
juvenile, was charged with robbery after police saw him toss one of
the stolen telephones into the woods, detectives said.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the golfers had been warned that it was becoming a
pattern,'' said club member Fred Myrer, a Gwinnett County sheriff's
deputy.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
