<P>
   The following photos accompany the Hearst News Service four-day
series called ``Fortress Europe,'' which examines the European
Union and its immigration crisis. The series by the Houston
Chronicle is available for use beginning this Sat., Dec. 12.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) LONDON -- Dec. 10, 1998 -- ADV. FOR MON., DEC. 14 --
EUROPE-SUCCESS-HNS, 12-09 -- Andrew Ramroop, a black immigrant from
the Caribbean island of Trinidad, does a final fitting for an
Italian client at Maurice Sedwell, the Savile Row establishment
which he owns and runs. ``Yes, there is an element of surprise when
customers come in off the street and are welcomed by a West
Indian,'' says Ramroop. Many see his success as a sign that the
immigrant story in Europe is not all exclusion and failure. (Kerwin
Plevka/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) LONDON -- Dec. 10, 1998 -- ADV. FOR MON., DEC. 14 --
EUROPE-IDENTITY-HNS, 12-09 -- A couple shares an intimate moment on
London's Trafalgar Square. In Britain, half of black men and a
third of black women have married or have lived with a white
partner. (Kerwin Plevka/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) ANTWERP -- Dec. 10, 1998 -- ADV. FOR MON., DEC. 14 --
EUROPE-ACCEPTANCE-2-HNS, 12-09 -- Because getting a job in Belgium
is very difficult for black people, some resort to selling
black-market jewelry to tourists. Recent research by the
Geneva-based International Labor Organization suggests that, in
many European countries, one in three immigrant job applicants
suffers discrimination. (Kerwin Plevka/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) ANTWERP -- Dec. 10, 1998 -- ADV. FOR MON., DEC. 14 --
EUROPE-ACCEPTANCE-1-HNS, 12-09 -- Professional soccer player Dennis
Amoah and three black friends were refused admission to a popular
disco in Antwerp, Belgium. Minutes later, several white Belgians
were let in with no questions asked. ``I used to lose my temper,
but now it just hurts,'' says Amoah, an immigrant from Ghana. ``It
makes you feel ashamed of what you are.'' (Kerwin Plevka/Houston
Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) BADOLATO, Italy -- Dec. 10, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC.
13 -- EUROPE-WELCOME-2-HNS, 12-09 -- Ali Cayundar, who helps run
the busy Ararat restaurant, is the second Kurd in Badolato to find
an Italian girlfriend. ``You hear of racism and skinheads in
Europe, but I've never felt any rejection in Badolato,'' he says.
``They have given us a great chance to make a home.'' (Kerwin
Plevka/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) BADOLATO, Italy -- Dec. 10, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC.
13 -- EUROPE-WELCOME-1-HNS, 12-09 -- Ali Serri, a Turkish Kurd, has
been working since July at Badolato's Il Castello pizzeria, where
young Kurds and Italians hang out together in the shade of the
terrace. ``People have really opened their arms to us,'' he says.
``They did not turn us away when we needed help.'' (Kerwin
Plevka/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
