<P>
   (NYT5) MELILLA, Spain -- Dec. 10, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SAT., DEC. 12
-- EUROPE-TEXAS-HNS, 12-09 -- Spain is building this fence near its
port of Melilla in North Africa to keep illegal immigrants out.
Many Europeans, however, oppose the use of barriers along their
border. A little more than a million immigrants settle legally in
the European Union every year - about the same number as in the
United States and Canada put together. (Kerwin Plevka/Houston
Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) EISSENHUTTENSTADT, Germany -- Dec. 10, 1998 -- ADV. FOR
SUN., DEC. 14 -- EUROPE-BORDER-2-HNS, 12-9 -- A German border guard
brings in a man who was caught near Guben while swimming across the
narrow Neisse River. The Neisse and its wider counter part, the
Oder River, are favorite crossing point for illegal immigrants
seeking a better life in the West. (Kerwin Plevka/Houston Chronicle
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) EISSENHUTTENSTADT, Germany -- Dec. 10, 1998 -- ADV. FOR
SUN., DEC. 14 -- EUROPE-BORDER-1-HNS, 12-9 -- German border guard
Jan Steenfatt scans the banks of the Oder River, which divides
Germany and Poland. The Neisse and Oder rivers are favorite
crossing points for illegal immigrants seeking a better life in the
West. (Kerwin Plevka/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) MELILLA, Spain -- Dec. 10, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SAT., DEC. 12
-- EUROPE-MIGRANTS-2-HNS, 12-9 -- A stray pig searches for scraps
of food in Melilla, a Spanish port on the coast of North Africa.
``I have made too many sacrifices, and suffered too much, to turn
back now,'' says, Hamid Uld-Mohamed, who is 18 and from Mauritania.
``Whether they want me or not, one day I will make a home over
there in Europe.'' Uld-Mohamed is just one of the Africans trying
to take advantage of European Union. (Kerwin Plevka/Houston
Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) MELILLA, Spain -- Dec. 10, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SAT., DEC. 12
-- EUROPE-MIGRANTS-1-HNS, 12-9 -- More than 300 men from all over
Africa and the Middle East are crammed into this camp for migrants
in a Spanish port on the coast of North Africa. Like the
southwestern United States, the European Union is grappling with an
immigration crisis. Melilla borders Morocco, making it a front line
between the EU countries and the Third World. (Kerwin
Plevka/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
