<SLUG> BC-BBO-MEETINGS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Meetings may include Klesko-to-Tampa talk
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Barry Larkin will be there for the taking, if the deal
is right. So will Greg Vaughn and Fernando Vina. The Kevin Brown
sweepstakes could go straight through the roof of the Opryland
Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball executives convene in Nashville today for five days of
talks as the major leagues conduct their first winter meetings
since 1992. And while there has already been plenty of action thus
far in both the trade and free agent markets, there will be more.
</P>
<P>
   The meetings begin with Brown seeking the highest bidder and
Toronto still listening for the right deal to trade five-time Cy
Young winner Roger Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Braves, having already signed or acquired
outfielders Brian Jordan and Otis Nixon, second baseman Bret Boone
and pitcher Mike Remlinger, are not expected to be a player in the
remaining bartering.
</P>
<P>
   But left fielder Ryan Klesko's future remains cloudy. His name
has been linked with Atlanta's discussions with the Tampa Bay Devil
Rays, who are said to be offering right-hander Esteban Yan (the
former Brave farmhand) and either outfielders Quinton McCracken or
Randy Winn.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Blue Jays had hoped to deal Clemens before the
meetings began, trade talks are now expected to drag through the
weekend. That could steal come spontaneity from the Brown auction,
which is expected to go beyond $84 million (at six years).
</P>
<P>
   A primary reason the meetings were discontinued five years ago
was the executives' distaste for how agents manipulated the
proceedings to drive up contract offers, a practice Scott Boras,
Brown's agent, is quite ready to resume. Colorado, Baltimore and
San Diego are among the finalists.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds may part with Larkin, the club captain, who is incensed
at Boone's departure and notified Cincinnati brass it can trade
him, but only to Los Angeles, San Diego, St. Louis, Texas or the
Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres, while squeezing every dime to stay alive in the
Brown bidding, are shopping Vaughn, their top home run hitter, as
well as pitchers Joey Hamilton, Donne Wall and Dan Miceli.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
