<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-AA-BACKS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stopping Stecker key for Ga. Southern
 &HT;    By Earnest Reese
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Western Illinois, which plays top-ranked Georgia
Southern in a semifinal round of the I-AA playoffs Saturday at
Paulson Stadium in Statesboro, features 1997 consensus All-America
running back Aaron Stecker on the cover of its media guide.
</P>
<P>
   The glossy presence of the 5-foot-10, 205-pound senior, who
holds 29 offensive records at the Gateway Conference school in
Macomb, Ill., should have been expected. As a junior, he rushed for
2,293 yards and 28 touchdowns on an 11-2 Leatherneck team.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, however, Stecker, who missed two games this year
because of a groin injury, will share the spotlight with a Georgia
Southern player having a remarkable season of his own. Georgia
Southern (13-0), which has posted 492 yards of offense and 43.7
points a game, will counter Stecker with redshirt freshman Adrian
Peterson, a 5-10, 207-pound combination of power and speed from
Alachua, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   In setting 34 school, conference and national records this
season, Peterson rushed for 2,342 yards and 32 touchdowns. His
rushing yardage total is more than six teams in the Southern
Conference, as well as Georgia Tech (2,021) and Georgia (1,674).
</P>
<P>
   ``Aaron had a great junior year for us, and even though he's
been injured, he's still our main man on offense,'' Western
Illinois coach Randy Ball said. ``He's got all of the ingredients
you want in a back: He's got speed, he can make you miss, and he
can run over people. He's a complete deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Stecker was by far the most impressive I-AA back Ball had seen _
before the ninth-year head coach started to watch videotapes of
Peterson and his exploits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen enough of him,'' Ball said. ``It's amazing he's at
Georgia Southern. He could play at a lot of places in the country.
I just wish he was down there with his brother (linebacker Michael
Peterson) at Florida.''
</P>
<P>
   With Adrian Peterson working with junior quarterback Greg Hill,
Georgia Southern fought back from deficits to defeat Colgate and
Connecticut in its previous playoff games. Against UConn last
Saturday, Peterson eclipsed the 200-yard rushing mark for the sixth
time this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no earthly idea that he had 232 yards until I saw the
stat sheet after the game,'' Georgia Southern second-year coach
Paul Johnson said. ``I've run out of ways to describe him. I guess
we sort of take what he does for granted now. But if you had a
class of players like him, it wouldn't take long to call the roll.
There's not that many in his class.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
