<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A VERY GOOD YEAR FOR BAFFERT _ AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ Only one thing seemed impossible for Bob Baffert in
1997: It seemed impossible he could do even better in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But he has surpassed himself this season, with his Santa
Anita-based barn leading North America in earnings and major-race
winners, probably enough to give the 45-year-old Baffert his second
straight Eclipse Award as outstanding trainer. And he can add to
his lead this weekend at Hollywood Park when he runs Premier
Property and Prime Timber in the $450,000 Hollywood Futurity on
Saturday and Excellent Meeting in the $200,000 Hollywood Starlet on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `How could I beat last year?' '' Baffert said,
while admitting he's not the reflective type. ``This year, we beat
it, and now it's `What can we do next year?' ''
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't been an altogether easy season for Baffert.
</P>
<P>
   His most talented 3-year-old, Santa Anita Derby winner Indian
Charlie, was retired after injuring himself in the Kentucky Derby.
His most talented 2-year-old, Del Mar Futurity winner Worldly
Manner, was sold out from under him. Last year's Derby and
Preakness winner, Silver Charm, was as much a handful as ever on
his way to earning $4.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert won the Derby and Preakness again this year with Real
Quiet, yet seems to remember this year's Triple Crown more for the
disappointment of losing the Belmont Stakes in a photo finish.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert himself _ glib, unpretentious, iconoclastic _ began to
wear thin for some people during the summer when he engaged in
verbal sniping with Skip Away trainer Sonny Hine and Hollywood Park
executives.
</P>
<P>
   Still, what a year.
</P>
<P>
   His barn's earnings: $11.9 million (not counting Silver Charm's
$2.4 million for winning the Dubai World Cup) in '98, after $8.8
million in '97. Baffert leads Bill Mott by more than $2 million,
according to Daily Racing Form statistics through last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   His major victories: Baffert won five Grade I races _ accounted
for by Real Quiet (two), Indian Charlie, Excellent Meeting and
Silverbulletday. That's one more than in '97. Hine also won five
Grade I's this year _ but all were by Skip Away.
</P>
<P>
   His Breeders' Cup day: Baffert ran 1-2 in the Juvenile Fillies
with Silverbulletday and Excellent Meeting, and second in the
Classic with Silver Charm _ his best Breeders' Cup yet.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend's races, the 1 1/16-mile Futurity for 2-year-olds
and the 1 1/16-mile Starlet for 2-year-old fillies, also are Grade
I's. Baffert would be the first trainer to win both in the same
year.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert has been telling people that Aaron Jones' Prime Timber
is his Real Quiet for '99. In other words, a sleeper. But there's
not much else to compare.
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet didn't get good until Baffert put him in longer
races; the '97 Hollywood Futurity was only his second victory in
nine starts. But Prime Timber is 2 for 2, both races being sprints,
the latter a narrow allowance victory at 7 { furlongs on Nov. 22.
</P>
<P>
   He'll be ridden by Chris McCarron on Saturday while regular
jockey Gary Stevens is in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Hal Earnhardt's Premier Property, ridden by David Flores, will
be favored in the six-horse field. He's 3 for 3, all in sprints,
and has never trailed, winning the 7-furlong Hollywood Prevue by 3{
lengths on Nov. 21.
</P>
<P>
   The question now is how the son of Out of Place will handle two
turns and the possibility he'll be challenged for the early lead _
by Norfolk Stakes winner Buck Trout and Eddie Delahoussaye and D.
Wayne Lukas-trained Tactical Cat and Laffit Pincay.
</P>
<P>
   ``He should be able to get it (the distance),'' Baffert said
from his Santa Anita barn. ``He doesn't move like a dirt-bike speed
horse. He's got that long stride.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert has already trained six 2-year-old stakes winners in
'98, including Exploit, a popular pick for the May 1 Kentucky Derby
after his victory in the Brown &AMP; Williamson last month at Churchill
Downs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully the Derby winner is in my barn,'' Baffert said. ``I
just don't know which stall.''
</P>
<P>
   The Futurity will share the Saturday card with the $500,000
Hollywood Turf Cup (with Yagli and Dushyantor, second and third to
Buck's Boy in the Breeders' Cup Turf) and the $100,000 Vernon O.
Underwood Stakes for sprinters.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Baffert will be favored again in the Starlet with John
and Betty Mabee's Excellent Meeting, whose four defeats in seven
starts include two seconds to stablemate Silverbulletday and a
second to stablemate Hookedonthefeelin. Excellent Meeting won the
Del Mar Debutante and the Oak Leaf and is clearly the leader of the
local 2-year-old fillies while Silverbulletday races back east.
</P>
<P>
   Excellent Meeting, with Kent Desormeaux riding, will try to come
from off the pace in what's expected to be a six-horse race.
California Cup Juvenile Fillies winner Lacquaria and Western Woman
look like the front-runners. Rayelle is the other prominent
stretch-runner.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the Starlet program is the $100,000 Dahlia Handicap for
fillies and mares. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
