<HEADER>
A4091 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTES11-C     12-10 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTES11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons lost out on a winner in Glover
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ New Orleans Saints defensive tackle La'Roi Glover may
not make the Pro Bowl this season because it's hard for third-year
players on mediocre teams to do. But if he doesn't make the squad,
which will be announced next Wednesday, it won't be because he's
not worthy. The 6-2, 285-pounder is fourth on his team with 57
tackles, and leads all interior linemen with 10 sacks. He also has
an interception, and has forced three fumbles.
</P>
<P>
   When the Falcons (11-2) play at New Orleans (6-7) Sunday, there
will be no player on the Saints' defense who could cause more
problems for Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   If the Saints play a lot of the ``Bear'' defense they used so
much in last week's 22-3 win over Dallas, in which the Cowboys had
a meager 8 rushing yards, Glover will line up at nose guard.
</P>
<P>
   While matching up against Atlanta center Robbie Tobeck, Glover
will try to use his outstanding speed and quickness to get in the
backfield and also open up a blitz lane for linebackers.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Cowboys, he sacked Troy Aikman twice and tackled
Emmitt Smith twice for losses. He was named NFC Defensive Player of
the Week.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for a guy who was waived after a year with the Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought he would try hard, had a chance to be pretty good,
but no one predicted the way La'Roi turned out,'' Saints defensive
coordinator Zaven Yaralian said.
</P>
<P>
   Glover did not dress for 13 of 16 games with the Raiders in
1996, and in training camp in '97, Oakland opted to stick with
bigger defensive tackles Russell Maryland, Chester McGlockton and
Darrell Russell.
</P>
<P>
   Raiders personnel executive Ken Herock, who left the Falcons
eight months earlier after Dan Reeves was hired as coach, offered
to trade Glover to the Falcons, but Atlanta declined.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing the Raiders would likely waive him, the Falcons put in a
waiver claim on Glover, thinking they would probably get him since
they had the No. 3 claiming spot by virtue of the NFL's third-worst
record a year earlier. But the Saints had the No. 2 claiming spot,
and took Glover.
</P>
<P>
   He started just two games last year, but has played so well this
year the Saints extended his contract by four years, giving him an
$11 million deal and bonuses such as $700,000 for 15 ``big plays''
(interceptions, forced fumbles and fumble recoveries) and 11 sacks
per season, and $1.3 million for 17 big plays and 12 sacks a
season.
</P>
<P>
   Makeup call
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons made out quite well after not getting Glover,
signing defensive tackle Shane Dronett after he was waived by
Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Dronett alternated last year with starting tackles Travis Hall
and Dan Owens, and had 40 tackles, three sacks, two blocked field
goals, and five passes batted down.
</P>
<P>
   Like Glover, he became a starter this year, and is fifth on the
team with 67 tackles, is third with 6.5 sacks (a half sack short of
a career high), has forced two fumbles, recovered one, and swatted
three passes.
</P>
<P>
   And Dronett is doing it for a relative bargain, as he is in the
first year of a two-year, $1.6 million contract that pays him a
salary of $550,000.
</P>
<P>
   Injury update
</P>
<P>
   Falcons defensive end Lester Archambeau practiced Thursday for
the first time since breaking his left thumb in last Sunday's game
against the Colts. The results were pretty good. ``It worked better
today than I thought it would,'' said Archambeau, who had surgery
last Sunday to insert pins in the thumb. ``We won't know for sure
until Sunday when there are real, live bullets flying, but I was
able to use it today pretty good.'' ... Receiver Tim Dwight did not
practice, resting a hamstring. ``We're going to test it tomorrow,''
coach Dan Reeves said. ``He thinks it's just a cramp that made it
sore.'' ... For the Saints, middle linebacker Kevin Mitchell, who
suffered a partial tear of a medial collateral knee ligament
against Dallas, will not play. ... Reserve linebacker Vinson Smith
(knee) is questionable.
</P>
<P>
   Bear solution?
</P>
<P>
   If the Saints do play a lot of the ``Bear'' front, the Falcons
can count on a lot of pressure up the middle, in what they refer to
as the ``A gap.'' Although quarterbacks Tony Graziani and Steve
DeBerg went with a shotgun snap several plays at St. Louis Nov. 29,
starting quarterback Chris Chandler has used the shotgun very
little since the beginning of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves doesn't favor using the shotgun on the road, especially
in domes, because it is difficult for offensive linemen to hear the
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can hear a lot better when he's under center. But any time
somebody is testing your A gap, you've got a better chance in the
shotgun, no doubt about it,'' Reeves said. ``(Chandler) has the
ability to go to it any time he wants. Chris likes being under
(center), but he'll go to the shotgun sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Hot or cold
</P>
<P>
   In 10 straight games, the Saints have given up either 31, 30, or
three points, winning the three games in which they've allowed just
a field goal (all at home), and losing the others.
</P>
<P>
   No running room
</P>
<P>
   The Saints have had problems generating a running game behind a
line that has a rookie tight end, a rookie left guard in Kyle
Turley, a second-year right guard in Chris Naeole, and a third-year
center in Tom Ackerman.
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans' leading rusher is Lamar Smith, who has 411 yards on
121 carries, a 3.4-yard average.
</P>
<P>
   The Saints averaged just 64.2 in nine games before last week,
when they rushed 36 times for 113 yards against Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Cowboys, 1997 third-round draft choice Troy Davis
started at running back, and Aaron Craver was the up-back. But
rookie Wilmont Perry, the teams' fifth-round draft choice out of
Livingstone College, ended up the team's leading rusher, with 38
yards on 12 carries.
</P>
<P>
   Ditka waived the team's second-leading rusher, Ray Zellars (56
carries, 162 yards), earlier this week because he wasn't happy with
his blocking.
</P>
<P>
   Extra points
</P>
<P>
   The Saints were about 6,000 tickets short of a sellout Thursday.
... Saints second-year left defensive end Jared Tomich has just 20
tackles, but he has six sacks, and has forced two fumbles. ... New
Orleans leads the NFC with 18 interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
