EUROPE-IDENTITY-HNS, 12-09 -- A couple shares an intimate moment on
London's Trafalgar Square. In Britain, half of black men and a
third of black women have married or have lived with a white
partner. (Kerwin Plevka/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) ANTWERP -- Dec. 10, 1998 -- ADV. FOR MON., DEC. 14 --
EUROPE-ACCEPTANCE-2-HNS, 12-09 -- Because getting a job in Belgium
is very difficult for black people, some resort to selling
black-market jewelry to tourists. Recent research by the
Geneva-based International Labor Organization suggests that, in
many European countries, one in three immigrant job applicants
suffers discrimination. (Kerwin Plevka/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) ANTWERP -- Dec. 10, 1998 -- ADV. FOR MON., DEC. 14 --
EUROPE-ACCEPTANCE-1-HNS, 12-09 -- Professional soccer player Dennis
Amoah and three black friends were refused admission to a popular
disco in Antwerp, Belgium. Minutes later, several white Belgians
were let in with no questions asked. ``I used to lose my temper,
but now it just hurts,'' says Amoah, an immigrant from Ghana. ``It
makes you feel ashamed of what you are.'' (Kerwin Plevka/Houston
Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) BADOLATO, Italy -- Dec. 10, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC.
