<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HMOMERGER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Aetna to Buy Prudential HealthCare  &HT;       
 By Tom Abate 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Aetna Inc. said yesterday it would pay $1 billion in cash and debt
to acquire Prudential HealthCare, cementing its position as the
largest health insurer in the nation, and making it the
sixth-largest in California.
</P>
<P>
   Financial analysts hailed the deal, under which Aetna would get
an additional 6.6 million customers and end up insuring 22.4
million people, or roughly one out of 12 Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're getting Prudential's members at an incredibly low
price,'' said Ira Zuckerman, an analyst with Nutmeg Securities.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; According to Aetna, the purchase price would give it
Prudential's customers for about $200 each compared with the $500
to $600 it costs to acquire a customer through advertising and
marketing. The Hartford, Conn., insurer said the acquisition was
part of its plan to become a dominant force in managed health care.
</P>
<P>
   For Prudential, the deal made sense because the health unit was
losing money.
</P>
<P>
   But health insurance buyers, doctor's groups and consumer
activists expressed reservations about the deal, which is &UR;  &LR; the
latest in a series of health insurance mergers, and Aetna's third
such combination in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trend is worrisome because we think it could result in
less competitive rates than if we had more plans,'' said Margaret
Stanley, who negotiates health insurance rates for the California
Public Employees Retirement System.
</P>
<P>
   Lori Hack, executive director of the Alta Bates Medical Group in
Berkeley, said doctors in California have increasingly banded
together into independent practice associations to negotiate rates
with insurers. Now with mergers such as Aetna's acquisition of
Prudential HealthCare, she said, those negotiations would be even
more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once a health plan has a critical mass of your business you
can't walk away from them,'' said Hack, adding that Aetna and
Prudential combined would insure about 20,000 out of her group's
145,000 patients.
</P>
<P>
   But Walter Zelman, president of the California Association of
Health Plans, the industry's lobby, said the proposed merger would
not have a large effect in California. Before the merger,
Prudential insured about 1 million Californians, and Aetna about
500,000. Combined, they would be the sixth-largest health insurer
behind Blue Shield of California, which has 2 million customers.
</P>
<P>
   But Doug Heller, an industry critic with Santa Monica's
Consumers for Quality Care, said the more important fact is that
the merged Aetna would be a health maintenance organization, a type
of insurer that has greater power than other insurers to control
health care choices.
</P>
<P>
   According to Heller, Aetna, with 1.5 million members, would be
second only to Kaiser with 5.4 million members in the HMO business.
He said this would make Aetna an ``HMO powerhouse'' and mean ``less
choice for consumers, less leverage for doctors negotiating
contracts, and that means the downgrading of medical care.''
</P>
<P>
   Zelman countered by saying, ``There is pretty vigorous
competition between health plans in California.'' Mergers can
actually lower administrative costs, he said, ``and end up being
pro-consumer.''
</P>
<P>
   Cost-cutting was what Aetna Chairman Richard Huber promised
yesterday, saying he expected to cut up to 2,000 jobs, or 12
percent, of Prudential HealthCare's workforce to save upwards of
$130 million during the next two to three years.
</P>
<P>
   Steve McDermott, executive director of the Hill Physicians
Medical Group in San Ramon, the state's largest independent
doctor's group, said he doubted the Aetna merger would have a big
impact on Northern California because neither Aetna nor Prudential
are dominant insurers here.
</P>
<P>
   But McDermott said this latest merger among health plans served
as a reminder that doctors' groups need to combine with each other
to get more bargaining clout and lower their own administrative
costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physicians have been reluctant to participate in strong
organizations, but doctors are going to have to consolidate,''
McDermott predicted.
</P>
</TEXT>
