<HEADER>
A4101 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BARR11-COX-1STLEDE-WR     12-10 0513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARR11-COX-1STLEDE-WRITETHRU </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    1ST UPDATE
 &HT;    EDs: Changes throughoutSensing victory, Barr savors moment
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the U.S. Capitol looming in the backdrop,
Georgia Republican Bob Barr looked directly into the television
camera like a man on the verge of victory.
</P>
<P>
   Reciting the articles of impeachment against the president as if
they were the alphabet, Barr told the CNN audience that impeachment
case against President Clinton is ``strong, very strong.''
</P>
<P>
   As the House Judiciary Committee prepares for a vote on four
articles of impeachment against Clinton today or tomorrow, perhaps
no single member of Congress has lusted after his impeachment more
than Bob Barr.
</P>
<P>
   One year ago, Barr stood alone in his resolve to oust Clinton
from the Oval Office. He even introduced a resolution to impeach
him three months before the nation had even heard the name Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Now Barr is on the cusp of a historic vote recommending to the
House of Representatives that the president be impeached.
</P>
<P>
   And he is hitting the media circuit at every turn to make sure
that this particular moment does not slip away.
</P>
<P>
   There he was at 7:30 a.m. Thursday morning gulping coffee and
nibbling on pancakes at the posh Carlton Hotel, telling
Washington's media elite at the Sperling Breakfast that now is the
time to get rid of Clinton. (Although he still thinks that the
investigation into campaign fund-raising abuses will yield fruit if
this one fails.)
</P>
<P>
   One hour later, Barr was back in the ornate Judiciary chambers
on Capitol Hill listening with rapt attention to the closing
arguments of the Republican and Democratic investigative counsel.
</P>
<P>
   While some Republicans have reserved judgment, Barr almost beams
when the ``I'' word comes up. ``All of the charges are very strong
and can be defended in terms of the facts and the Constitution,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   After a full day of hearings, Barr went straight to the
microphones, followed by a gaggle of reporters that routinely
swarms around him down the marble corridors of the Rayburn House
Office Building.
</P>
<P>
   And while this may be what is known as The Bob Barr moment, he
worries that the White House will take away his dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I feel is a great deal of apprehension,'' said Barr, in
between television spots. ``An awful lot can happen in one week.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House, he said, would stop at nothing to prevent the
House vote. So is he worried that he will become a target? Of
course. Is he going to do anything about it? No.
</P>
<P>
   ``The moment I am waiting for is after the floor vote,'' Barr
said.
</P>
<P>
   Does that mean he won't rest until he is sure there are 218
votes to remove Clinton?
</P>
<P>
   Well, lunch did consist solely of a handful of Georgia pecans.
</P>
<P>
   Where exactly does Barr's palpable antipathy for the president
stem from?
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't that I hate him,'' Barr said. ``I just take great
offense to what he has done to our country.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
