A4108 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COYOTE-SHARES-LADN     12-10 0506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COYOTE-SHARES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASDAQ HALTS TRADING ON COYOTE
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attention editors: ``Vik'' spelling for first name is correct.) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DEBORAH ADAMSON  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Nasdaq officials halted trading of Coyote Network
Systems on Thursday as they look into allegations that the
company's biggest customer could be a figment of its imagination.
</P>
<P>
   A series of articles published by TheStreet.Com, an online
investment site, said its reporters couldn't find Coyote's top
client, Crescent Communications. It even dispatched a reporter to
the company's Long Beach, Calif., address, with no success.
</P>
<P>
   When the news hit, shares of Westlake Village, Calif.-based
Coyote plunged 45 percent to $7.8125 on Wednesday. Officials at
Coyote, a telecommunications equipment and network services
company, did not return calls for comment Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Daily News tried to contact Crescent Communications, but
there was no listing for its phone number in Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Kansas, editor in chief of TheStreet.Com, said his
reporters have tried to find Crescent since before Thanksgiving.
Coyote itself was not much help in locating the company, Kansas and
the articles contend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did a lot of exhaustive work on it,'' he said. ``We stand
by our stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Coyote defended itself in a press release Thursday, calling the
stories ``potentially misleading.'' The company said second-quarter
revenues rose to $15.2 million from $106,000 a year ago due to
sales of equipment to Comdisco, an established telecommunications
company, which then leased it to Crescent.
</P>
<P>
   Coyote also said its officers don't intend to short-sell the
stock, an accusation made by TheStreet.Com after examining
Securities and Exchange Commission filings.
</P>
<P>
   Vik Grover, an analyst for Kaufman Bros. who found himself under
fire for his ``buy'' recommendation on Coyote just before
TheStreet.Com's articles were released, said that while he has
never spoken with any executive at Crescent, he believes it was
incorporated in Nevada, based in Long Beach and operates in Mexico
as Crescent Communications SA de CV.
</P>
<P>
   Grover said he has visited Coyote's operations, which he
described as real and valid. He characterized TheStreet.Com's
stories as ``disinformation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a ridiculous sell-off. We still remain favorable on the
stock,'' he said, although there's no guarantee the recommendation
will stay.
</P>
<P>
   In September, Coyote announced it was buying a 20 percent
ownership stake in Crescent Communications. In the second quarter,
Coyote reported a 143-fold increase in revenue from a year ago,
largely due to business related to Crescent. As a result, the
company's stock doubled to around the $14 range.
</P>
<P>
   A Nasdaq spokesman said he is not sure how long trading will be
halted, but no shares were traded Thursday. Trades are stopped to
protect investors and markets as officials dig for the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Comdisco officials did not return calls for comment. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
