<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4117 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-REFS-TEX     12-10 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-REFS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOILING UNDER DURESS: REFS FEEL THE PAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ In a matter of seconds, he knew his call was
wrong. By then, however, it was too late. The team that benefited
was celebrating a tainted victory. He was standing there on the
field, every bit as deflated as the losing club.
</P>
<P>
   Consistently rated as one of the NFL's best officials, he had
seen such a mistake happen to others in the profession, felt for
them, even phoned the next day to say, ``shake it off _ keep your
head up.''
</P>
<P>
   But this was much different. This was him. And this mistake
would lead /Sports Center,/ and the Fox guys would slo-mo it from
every camera angle. Sports page headlines would be coming the next
morning, complete with pictures. And he had no answer. No defense
of his call.
</P>
<P>
   Taking the heat is part of the job. But he also knew he was
wrong. His job in the NFL is not to be wrong. Ever.
</P>
<P>
   He knew what the losing coach would probably say. He had heard
and read it for years. ``Those guys \Rthe officials\S are back home
Monday morning, working in their real jobs. Not a worry in the
world. Meanwhile, we get fired for their mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   He had always hated that response from a coach. Like nobody who
officiated cared or had pride. Like it was that easy to forget a
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   The flight home that night was the longest of his life. The
plane landed right on time, three hours after takeoff. But it felt
like three days.
</P>
<P>
   Walking in his house, he would only think about the play. Not
about family, and certainly not about the phone already ringing as
friends called to offer support.
</P>
<P>
   It still was early on a Sunday night, but he went right to bed.
He can't remember sleeping, but probably did. Fifteen hours later,
he was still in bed, blowing the coaching theory that ``these
guys'' are back at work Monday morning, not a worry in the world.
</P>
<P>
   It was 2 o'clock that afternoon when he finally climbed out of
bed to answer the phone. But only because the caller was Jerry
Seeman, director of NFL officials. His football boss.
</P>
<P>
   Seeman made him feel better. He was supportive. Seeman reminded
him about his years of excellent grades and work in the league.
``Shake it off _ keep your head up,'' the boss told him.
</P>
<P>
   He'd always considered Seeman a stand-up guy, but this phone
call was special because Seeman himself was under plenty of fire.
Every Sunday, there seems to be ``something.'' It is currently open
season on NFL zebras. Way too many mistakes, or at least what
owners, coaches and players think are mistakes. And some of those
mistakes were blatantly wrong. Like his call had been.
</P>
<P>
   He knew Seeman hears it first and hears it often. Commissioner
Paul Tagliabue is getting nervous, and rightfully so. Owners all
over the league are screaming. Tagliabue wants answers from Seeman.
</P>
<P>
   But here's Seeman, calling him at home, not to criticize, but to
tell him, ``shake it off _ keep your head up.''
</P>
<P>
   He feels better after that, but still awful about making the
mistake. By Tuesday, however, he knows it's time to try and clear
his head. Not just for his family's sake, or the return Tuesday to
his ``real job'' after a ``sick day'' absence on Monday. But on
Saturday, there will be another flight to another city, and he has
to be mentally right for that Sunday game.
</P>
<P>
   Doing your job while scared, or with doubt, invites another
mistake. Perfection is not possible, but a repeat of the previous
Sunday can't happen.
</P>
<P>
   By midweek, I was talking to this official about instant replay.
Was he in favor? ``Yes,'' he said. ``Anything the league thinks
will help the game, or us, I'm for it. I've never opposed it.''
</P>
<P>
   For what it's worth, his wrong call at the end of that game on
that Sunday would have been easily corrected by instant replay. It
fell under the category of the three situations covered by instant
replay, meaning possession, goal line and sideline.
</P>
<P>
   Personal theory _ in the NFL's last fling with instant replay,
the officiating crews and replay judges helped sabotage it with
incessive ``plays under review'' and prolonged decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's silly,'' he said. ``It didn't happen.'' OK, I will take
his word for it.
</P>
<P>
   Instant replay, however, will happen again. If not for the
playoffs in January, then by next season. Enough is enough, and
this season has had enough wrong calls that impacted the outcome of
a game. Not all wrongs can be overturned _ such as pass
interference _ but that's not the point.
</P>
<P>
   The objective should be to fix what can be fixed.
</P>
<P>
   One NFL official _ a good one, too _ could have had his mistake
``fixed.'' He would have benefited from replay on that one Sunday.
But these guys are human, mainly when it comes to personal regret
and hurt, which will linger for a long time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-98 2153EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
