<HEADER>
A4131 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEAGRAM-MUSIC-LADN     12-10 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEAGRAM-MUSIC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAGRAM ANNOUNCES STREAMLINED MUSIC OPERATIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Seagram Co. has confirmed it significantly will
reduce employment at its music operations by what's widely believed
to be about 3,000 jobs over the next six months.
</P>
<P>
   The cuts will start in mid-January as part of a massive
reorganization announced Thursday by Seagram as it completed its
$10.4 billion buyout of PolyGram. The combined operations, which
have 15,500 employees, will be called Universal Music Group and be
based in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will job cuts but we're not commenting on how many,''
said spokesman Robert Bernstein. He also confirmed previous
statements that Seagram's restructuring has a target of generating
$300 million in annual cost savings.
</P>
<P>
   An employee at one of Universal's local labels said the
announcements contained no surprises. ``We're trying to pretend
there's nothing going on because there's nothing we can do about
it,'' said the employee, who asked to remain unnamed. ``We just
wish they'd get on with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The moves come against a backdrop of uncertainty in the music
industry, which has seen stagnant sales, lack of new blockbuster
artists and a more fractured worldwide market no longer dominated
by American and British acts. ``This past decade has been a
lackluster time for pop music in two key areas _ commercial success
and cultural impact,'' said Kevin Skislock of Laguna Research
Partners.
</P>
<P>
   Sources in the company confirmed Thursday that about 20 percent
of the combined work force will be eliminated by June. Seagram
offered few details about the restructuring, other than
reconfiguring several labels and spelling out executive
responsibilities, but the takeover undoubtedly will lead to
reductions in artist rosters, and closures of duplicative offices
and plants.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have said the music giant will be far better able to
generate profits than its four chief rivals _ EMI, Sony, Warner and
Bertelsmann. UMG Chairman Doug Morris left little doubt Thursday
that deep cuts are coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``The integration of these two companies presents a rare
opportunity to create an organization that is well positioned for
profitable growth,'' Morris said in a statement. ``UMG will be a
lean, flexible organization that will benefit from economies of
scale while nurturing a strong local entrepreneurial spirit in its
management team around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The changes announced Thursday include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Combining the Island and Mercury labels into a New York-based
operation.
</P>
<P>
   _ The formation of an East Coast label group in New York,
composed of Universal Records and Motown Records.
</P>
<P>
   _ The merger of jazz labels Verve and GRP, which will be located
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   _ The creation of a West Coast group of labels, located in Los
Angeles, that will be composed of Interscope, Geffen and A&AMP;M.
Seagram said it expects to buy the half of Interscope it does not
already own.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Hack, formerly chief financial officer for Universal
Studios, was named vice chairman of the music unit and will oversee
strategy, finance, manufacturing and sales. Zach Horowitz, who has
been chief operating officer, was named president and will oversee
daily operations with Morris.
</P>
<P>
   The PolyGram deal is the biggest move yet for Seagram Chief
Executive Officer Edgar Bronfman Jr., whose family owns 32 percent
of Seagram, since buying Universal Studios in 1995. Skislock said
the strategy, which has included generating $3.3 billion by selling
off juice maker Tropicana, can work despite the current doldrums in
the music business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time to commit capital to a business is when those assets
are out of favor,'' the analyst said. ``Someone like Bronfman will
get the best value so it's very savvy. It shows he has a very
long-term commitment to this business.''
</P>
<P>
   Skislock believes that the merged company's size will give it an
advantage in the most critical area _ attracting superstars with
transcendental appeal, like Elvis Presley, the Beatles, Frank
Sinatra, the Bee Gees and Michael Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you're looking for is a creative force to emerge, like
Steven Spielberg and George Lucas in film, who connects with the
public and gives the medium direction,'' he said. ``We'll continue
to see merging and downsizing in the business until we have a true
breakout artist. In the absence of that, you have to gear your
strategy toward movie soundtracks and music videos.''
</P>
<P>
   Montreal-based Seagram also announced Thursday it would
integrate PolyGram's film operations and 800 employees into
Universal's struggling movie business but gave no indication
whether it will cut jobs. Seagram put those assets up for sale in
May but found no buyers at its reported $1 billion asking price.
</P>
<P>
   Seagram previously agreed to sell most of PolyGram's library to
Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer for $250 million and that deal will close at
the end of the year. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-98 2158EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
