<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4146 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-MOVE-BOS     12-10 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-MOVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICIALS SAY TAXPAYER MONEY WILL BE SPENT ON NEW STADIUM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ Elected officials Thursday for the first time
said taxpayer money would be used to construct the proposed new
stadium for the New England Patriots, but claimed they ``found''
another $400 million in revenue that had not been factored into the
project's bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   While Governor John Rowland said the legislature would authorize
dipping into Connecticut's budget surplus for $100 million, the
state budget director astonished officials when he announced that
two recent analyses of the project, which produced widely divergent
conclusions, had failed to consider projected revenues from games
played in the stadium by the University of Connecticut football
team.
</P>
<P>
   Adding in revenues from UConn games means that the stadium, for
which the state will borrow up to $375 million, will pay for itself
far sooner than had been originally predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state will now be in the black by year five,'' said House
Speaker Thomas Ritter, after emerging from a two and a half hour
meeting with Rowland and other House and Senate leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier estimates said it might take the state 30 years to break
even. Another study said the stadium was a money loser.
</P>
<P>
   Officials Thursday also confirmed that the state is asking team
owner Robert Kraft to back down on the luxury seat guarantees it
originally offered. Those lucrative guarantees would pay Kraft the
difference if he was unable to sell all of the expensive club seats
and luxury boxes in the proposed 68,000 seat stadium. Those
guarantees hold a potential liability for taxpayers of $175 million
over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   After emerging from the meetings Thursday the bipartisan group
of legislators said they agreed that the seat guarantees would have
to be cut somewhat and they designated Rowland as the bearer of bad
news to Kraft.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've asked the governor to go back to the Krafts on the
guarantee,'' Ritter said. ``We only want to have one person
negotiating with him. We feel comfortable, in a bipartisan way, to
do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ritter declined to say just how much the state would be asking
Kraft to concede.
</P>
<P>
   ``Substantive negotiations have to be private,'' he said. ``I
think what's happening is because we're getting near the end, it's
a more reasonable thing to ask for. I will say it's a very
important issue to my caucus.''
</P>
<P>
   A Patriots spokesman declined to comment Thursday night.
However, individuals close to the negotiations said that while the
team expects some changes in the seat guarantees, any substantial
change could upset the deal.
</P>
<P>
   But legislative leaders clearly wanted to talk more about the
new found money. Puzzled over why two recent analyses of the
project could produce such different results, state officials asked
Marc Ryan, the executive director of the Office of Policy and
Management, to investigate. A report issued Wednesday by the
independent Office of Fiscal Analysis found the deal could lose
$322 million while an earlier commissioned study by consultants
KPMG Peat Marwick, determined Connecticut would just about break
even over three decades.
</P>
<P>
   However, neither study factored in revenues from the UConn
football team, which will play in the facility. Right now, the
Huskies lose $2 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It adds to his legend,'' Ritter said of Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   But legislative leaders considered Thursday a hallmark day in
the stadium saga for other reasons as well.
</P>
<P>
   Because the leaders agreed on using $100 million from the budget
surplus. The state will now borrow just $250 million to pay for the
stadium and surrounding roads and infrastructure. The construction
will also support a convention center in the $1 billion Adriaen's
Landing project along the Connecticut River.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time the six legislative leaders have agreed
on what we are doing internally and what we want the governor to
do,'' Ritter said. ``It's just up to the governor and Kraft to do
their bit and as far as I'm concerned we're in pretty good shape.
UConn helps tremendously. And unfortunately, PR-wise, UConn is
magical here and not having used them was a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Ritter declined to blame KPMG Peat Marwick or other state number
crunchers for the oversight.
</P>
<P>
   Although most Capitol observers believe the deal with team owner
Robert Kraft would pass unaltered before the General Assembly,
Rowland, who was just re-elected, clearly wants to appease
lawmakers whose support he may need over the next four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``My responsibility is to the legislators and I want them to
feel comfortable with this vote,'' said Rowland, a Republican.
``We're never going to satisfy naysayers...(But) if we make some
changes to the guarantee that makes it more palatable.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers and members of the general public who spoke at
Wednesday's hearing here frequently slammed that component of the
deal as being too risky and expensive for the state.
</P>
<P>
   Another theme at the hearing was union job guarantees for
stadium construction and operations. But Rowland said Thursday he
did not think labor clauses would be written into the legislation.
</P>
</TEXT>
