A4151 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNDERGROUND-MAN-BOS &LR;      12-10 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNDERGROUND-MAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECOND HIDEAWAY ATTRIBUTED TO MAN LIVING IN SECRET 10 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A second home hidden on Nantucket Island has been
linked to underground man Thomas Johnson, and authorities said
Thursday it may be dismantled within a week.
</P>
<P>
   This home, a hand-built log cabin obscured by brush and beech
trees, is about a quarter mile from the 8-foot-deep, three-room
dwelling where Johnson says he has lived in near-secret for 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   The cabin, built of hand-notched pine logs from a nearby state
forest, appears to be on property of the Wannacomet Water Co., a
town agency. Wannacomet general manager Robert Gardner said
Thursday state law prohibits residences within a 400-foot radius of
municipal wells.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner said the Nantucket Board of Water Commissioners is
likely to vote to dismantle the structure when it meets Tuesday for
a monthly session. If that action is taken, he said, the home could
be leveled within days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another refuge is discovered,'' Johnson said Thursday.
``They're closing in on me. They're doing their best to make things
hot for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities have known about the structure for more than a year,
state Environmental police Sergeant Donald La Haye said, but did
not take action because the home did not appear to be occupied.
</P>
<P>
   But when recent surveillance showed renewed activity there _ and
after Johnson's more-elaborate underground home was discovered _
authorities noticed similarities in construction and decided to
act.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner said he was impressed when he first viewed the home
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty well-built log cabin with a couple of windows
and a table,'' Gardner said. A bench is placed against one wall in
the cabin, he added, along with a slate floor and a tarp roof
covered with brush.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could get within 50 feet and not know it is there,''
Gardner said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the clock has begun ticking toward Johnson's eviction
from his underground home. The process could take more than two
months. But when the time comes to leave, Johnson said, he will not
provoke a confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   `I'm not going to make a standoff,'' Johnson said. ``I'll move
when they tell me to move. But I'll stay in here as long as I
can.''
</P>
<P>
   A Nantucket deputy sheriff served Johnson with a 30-day eviction
notice Saturday at his subterranean hideaway on a Boy Scout camp.
If he does not leave within that time, the Boy Scouts are expected
to go to court to force his removal.
</P>
<P>
   Bert Johnson Jr., a Nantucket lawyer who represents the Scouts
in this matter, said the troop will allow Johnson a reasonable
amount of time to relocate.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer said the Scouts' hand was forced once the home was
discovered by a deer hunter alerted by its stovepipe. Code
violations were discovered by the Nantucket health officer, who
then served the Scouts with a notice of his findings.
</P>
<P>
   Scout executive Michael Riley of the Cape and Islands Council
said Nantucket scouting officials ``are going to do what has to be
done and whatever's the right thing to do in this case.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time,'' Riley continued, ``they're trying to show
some compassion and dignity for Tom Johnson in accordance with the
three points of the Scout code: to be courteous, friendly, and
kind.''
</P>
<P>
   Bert Johnson, who serves on the troop committee and is handling
the case for free, said the Scouts ``are looking into some way that
the home can be saved'' as a teaching tool.
</P>
<P>
   However, he continued, the home ``could become an attractive
nuisance'' and pose a danger to the curious.
</P>
<P>
   In the interim, Thomas Johnson said local support for him has
been heartening. ``It's incredible,'' said Johnson, who created a
subterranean life on Nantucket after fleeing a prison sentence in
Italy for heroin smuggling.
</P>
<P>
   The two years he spent in a Rome cell changed his life, Johnson
said, and led him to an underground existence where he could
strengthen himself morally and avoid the chafing routine he sees in
mainstream living.
</P>
<P>
   Italian authorities confirmed this week that Johnson fled the
country in 1985, following 26 months in a Rome prison and one month
of subsequent house arrest.
</P>
<P>
   An Italian law enforcement official, who did not wish to be
identified, said authorities had not known if Johnson was still
alive. The prospect of extradition is not high, he said, because
the United States generally does not return one of its citizens on
such a charge.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he was apprehended at the Rome airport in May 1983
while attempting to smuggle 2 kilograms of Thai heroin into Italy
via Amsterdam. The heroin had a street value of $2.6 million at the
time, he estimated.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he was to have been paid $10,000 for stashing the
heroin, stitched into a suitcase, in a locker at the Rome train
station. The trip was his third in Europe as a heroin courier,
Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Other details about Johnson's past also have been confirmed,
including statements that his father was a city judge in
Binghamton, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   According to Broome County historian Gerald Smith, Johnson was
one of seven children born to William H. Johnson Jr., a prominent
arts supporter, judge, and municipal official who resigned from the
Binghamton Housing Authority after he alleged there had been
political interference in tenant selection.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Johnson served as city judge from 1959 to 1962. He
also had been chairman of the Tri-Cities Opera.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Johnson said his father died in his arms, of liver and
colon cancer, in 1981. The family fell apart after the death,
Johnson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
