<HEADLINE>
PIN PLACED IN BLEDSOE'S INJURED FINGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Patriots quarterback Drew Bledsoe reportedly has
undergone surgery on his broken right index finger.
</P>
<P>
   Sources say Bledsoe underwent minor surgery earlier this week at
Massachusetts General Hospital and had a pin inserted to give the
finger stability. He is expected to start Sunday in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe injured the finger on the climactic drive in a thrilling
last-minute victory over the Miami Dolphins Nov. 23. While
following through after throwing a pass, he hit his hand on a
Dolphin pass rusher, fracturing the finger in two places.
</P>
<P>
   The following week, he led the Patriots to a second
come-from-behind win over Buffalo when he hit Ben Coates with a
1-yard touchdown pass with no time remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Last week he quarterbacked the Patriots to another vital
victory, beating the Steelers, 23-9, in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   But during the third quarter, he experienced numbness in the
finger. He said after the game that some of his passes were off the
mark because he'd lost his feel for the ball. Coach Pete Carroll
was ready to send in backup Scott Zolak, but Bledsoe left the
field, had the finger placed in a longer splint and retaped, and
returned to action.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the wear and tear, doctors reportedly felt the best
thing to do was to insert the pin, which will stay in place for the
rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors have said Bledsoe could not do further damage to the
finger by playing.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe has one fracture running under the fingernail which is
more like a bruise. The second is in the middle of the finger, not
near any joints. One doctor says the fractures are more like bone
chips. The pin reportedly will help keep the chips in place,
reducing the chances of injury that would prevent Bledsoe from
playing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-98 2207EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
