<DOCNO> NYT19981210.0544 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4158 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-FLEMMI-BOS &LR;      12-10 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-FLEMMI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE SEEK BODY OF INFORMANT'S GIRLFRIEND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHELLEY MURPHY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Years after the FBI dropped an investigation into
allegations that its prized informant Stephen ``The Rifleman''
Flemmi murdered his girlfriend, the Boston Police are planning to
search a basement for her body.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-six-year-old Debra Davis, who lived with Flemmi in
suburban Randolph, was planning to leave him for another man when
she vanished on Sept. 17, 1981, according to her family.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knew he was losing her, he knew it was over and on top of
that thought she may have known a little bit too much about his
relationship with the feds,'' said Davis' brother Victor. He said
the family immediately suspected Flemmi had killed her.
</P>
<P>
   The year after his sister vanished, Victor Davis said, the FBI
interviewed his mother, Olga, on several occasions, but the case
went nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   According to sources familiar with the investigation, the FBI
never confronted Flemmi _ an FBI informant since 1965 _ about his
girlfriend's mysterious disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's sick that a known criminal is going with a girl
and she disappears and it's never thoroughly investigated,'' Victor
Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Sources say the Boston Police recently received information that
Debra Davis may have been murdered inside the now-defunct Marconi
Club, a private club in Boston's Roxbury section once operated by
Flemmi, and buried in the basement.
</P>
<P>
   Police spokesman Peter Norton confirmed Thursday that
investigators will search the ground beneath the building for
Davis' remains, but ``there has been no determination as to when
that investigation will take place.''
</P>
<P>
   Sources said the investigation could begin as early as Friday or
some time next week.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are expected to use ground-penetrating radar to
look for signs of a body beneath the soil, then drill holes in the
concrete floor, according to sources. Cadaver-sniffing dogs would
be brought in to determine if a human scent is emanating from the
area.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Police Patrolman's Association, which purchased the 2
1/2-story building on Shetland Street three years ago, has agreed
to allow the search.
</P>
<P>
   The Marconi Club was operating in the basement of the building
at the time Debra Davis disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Kenneth Fishman, who represents Flemmi, said his client
``vigorously denies'' that he had anything to do with Debra Davis'
disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're confident that there is going to be no evidence
discovered that will in any way implicate Mr. Flemmi in the
disappearance of Ms. Davis,'' Fishman said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Suffolk County Medical Examiner's office
wouldn't comment on the Davis case, but said ``hypothetically''
investigators could expect to find bones or a mummified body if a
person was buried under a basement floor 17 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Albert Harper, director of the Lee Institute of Forensic
Sciences at the University of New Haven, said finding a body
beneath the ground ``is an extremely difficult proposition. There's
really no absolute way of locating it without actually doing the
digging.''
</P>
<P>
   If a body was buried beneath the Roxbury basement 17 years ago,
Harper said, the skull, jaw and teeth should all be intact. DNA
analysis from teeth could determine the identity of the victim.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Victor Davis was skeptical about the possibility that
his sister's remains will be found in Flemmi's old club because
``it's too obvious and I don't think he's that stupid.'' He also
worries that it will be a victory for Flemmi if police come up with
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Davis said it will be a relief if investigators find his
sister's remains because they'll finally know what happened to her.
</P>
<P>
   Debra Davis had fallen in love with a Mexican businessman she
met while vacationing in Aculpulco and was planning to end her
nine-year relationship with Flemmi, according to her brother.
</P>
<P>
   Flemmi, 64, has been in jail for four years while awaiting trial
on federal racketeering charges along with reputed New England Mob
Boss Francis ``Cadillac Frank'' Salemme and Robert DeLuca Flemmi's
longtime partner and fellow FBI informant, South Boston crime boss
James J. ``Whitey'' Bulger remains a fugitive in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a protracted pre-trial hearing over the past year
exploring the controversial relationship between Flemmi and Bulger
and the FBI, including numerous crimes the pair allegedly
committed, Debra Davis' name never surfaced.
</P>
<P>
   Victor Davis said FBI agents tape recorded at least one meeting
with his mother and took notes. Yet none of that information
surfaced in Flemmi's informant files, which were made public during
the hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Bureau spokesman Peter Ginieres declined to comment on the Debra
Davis case.
</P>
<P>
   But sources confirmed that FBI Special Agents James Crawford,
who is now retired, and Matthew Cronin &UR;  &LR; interviewed Olga Davis and
vigorously tried to solve the case _ without letting Flemmi know
that they had spoken to Debra Davis' mother.
</P>
<P>
   Victor Davis, one of 10 children, concedes that his mother was
afraid to confront Flemmi. She feared he might harm her other
children because he was already showing an interest in her younger
daughter, Victor Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Still Victor Davis said he thinks the FBI protected Flemmi.
</P>
<P>
   ``I blame the FBI as much as I blame him because they gave him a
ticket to rob, to steal and kill.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's missing and they're working with him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
