<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-HOUSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMITTEE DEBATES HOW FAR TO GO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House Judiciary Committee began a solemn debate
Thursday night on whether President Clinton's sex scandal warrants
an official censure that would further mar his legacy or a
``political death penalty'' _ a formal charge for his removal from
office.
</P>
<P>
   The committee lurched toward a historic final vote tomorrow
after the chief investigative counsels for both parties alternately
cast Clinton, in closing arguments, as an ``unfaithful husband''
who was ensnared by overzealous prosecutors, and a fallen leader
who betrayed the nation and may no longer be fit to govern.
</P>
<P>
   After the committee formally introduced articles of impeachment
against a president for the first time since the Watergate scandal,
one member of the panel's Republican majority after another sounded
a steady drumbeat for Clinton's ouster.
</P>
<P>
   The opening debate reflected tones that ranged from anguish to
anger. There was Representative Elton Gallegly, a California
Republican, who said he passed ``many sleepless nights'' before
deciding to support impeachment charges. And there was
Representative Mel Watt, a North Carolina Democrat, who decried the
investigation as unjust and recalled his own days as a lawyer when
he was the target of racist epithets in a courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   The four articles of impeachment charge Clinton with two counts
of perjury, one count of obstruction of justice, and one of abuse
of power. Each count stems from the president's alleged coverup of
his sexual liaisons in the White House with a former intern, Monica
S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, based upon evidence that the president lied, obstructed
and abused power in an effort to prevent the court from
administering equal justice under law, I cast my vote in favor of
impeaching William Jefferson Clinton,'' said Representative F.
James Sensenbrenner Jr., a Wisconsin Republican and senior
committee member. ``I do so with no joy but without apologies, just
as those on this committee who voted to impeach President Nixon 24
years ago did.''
</P>
<P>
   Committee Democrats portrayed the GOP majority, which is all but
certain to approve at least one, if not all, of the impeachment
counts, as pushing the country toward a constitutional crisis over
a sadly common human endeavor: a desperate effort to conceal an
adulterous affair.
</P>
<P>
   Most Democrats on the bitterly divided committee joined
Republicans in denouncing Clinton's misdeeds and his
``hair-splitting'' legal defenses for them. But the Democrats were
united against impeaching the president for actions arising from a
private, consensual sexual relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Several recent polls show the public overwhelming opposes
Clinton's impeachment and favors a lesser sanction such as a
congressional censure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Censure is the appropriate response, and I hope the Republican
leadership will not allow partisanship to keep the American people
from seeing the decision they want and have a right to have made,''
said Representative Barney Frank of Newton, a senior Democrat on
the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Frank noted that he and House Speaker Newt Gingrich each have
been reprimanded by the House for ethical wrongdoing. Frank's
reprimand stemmed from his relationship in the 1980s with a male
prostitute.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would tell you that having been reprimanded by this House of
Representatives, where I'm so proud to serve, was no triviality,''
Frank said. ``It is something, when people write about me, they
still write about. It is not something that is a matter of pride. I
wish I could go back and undo it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the final hours before the debate opened Thursday night, the
committee's chief investigative counsels supported the escalating
effort to sway a bloc of 20 to 30 undecided lawmakers when the full
House votes next week on impeachment charges by presenting starkly
divergent views of the evidence against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Each investigator _ David P. Schippers for the Republicans and
Abbe D. Lowell for the Democrats _ dramatized his summation by
airing, for the first time publicly, portions of Clinton's
videotaped deposition in the sexual harassment lawsuit that Paula
Corbin Jones filed against him and settled last month for $850,000.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after their presentations, the White House special
counsel, Gregory B. Craig, renewed his appeal to the undecided.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me make just one plea to the members of the House of
Representatives on behalf of the president,'' Craig said outside
the White House. ``Before you vote to impeach and remove the
president, read the defense of the president, read the majority
counsel's brief and the minority counsel's brief, and then be
guided by your conscience and your judgment in the national
interest.''
</P>
<P>
   The other two Massachusetts Democrats who serve with Frank on
the 37-member committee, Representatives William D. Delahunt of
Quincy and Martin T. Meehan of Lowell, blasted Clinton for the
sexual scandal but pressed for his censure rather than impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Delahunt, an architect of a Democratic censure plan the
committee will vote on after the impeachment charges, blasted what
he characterized as a one-sided, unfair inquiry into the Lewinsky
matter by the panel and the independent counsel, Kenneth W. Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Invoking George Orwell, Franz Kafka and Cold War show trials in
the Soviet Union, Delahunt said, ``This has been the most partisan
impeachment inquiry since the infamous trial of President Andrew
Johnson five generations ago. It is like a runaway train.''
</P>
<P>
   Delahunt also cited Democratic gains in the House in the
November elections as evidence of public opposition to Clinton's
impeachment. ``The voters did not condone the president's
behavior,'' he said. ``But they knew the difference between
misdeeds that merit reproach and abuses of office that require a
constitutional coup d'etat ... a political death penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   The articles of impeachment charge that Clinton committed
perjury by lying under oath in both his Jones deposition and his
testimony before a federal grand jury investigating the Lewinsky
matter. The other counts stem from the alleged coverup, including
his conversations with White House aides and his friend, Vernon E.
Jordan Jr., about his relationship with Lewinsky, a job search on
her behalf, and gifts the two exchanged.
</P>
<P>
   Meehan was particularly tough on Clinton. ``We have learned that
he is more reckless in his private life than we ever imagined,
maddeningly reckless for someone with so much potential and so much
to lose,'' Meehan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I disparage Bill Clinton's relationship with Monica
Lewinsky,'' he added. ``I disparage what he did in his testimony,
legal or not. I disparage what he said to the American people about
this matter. I disparage what he has put this country through over
the past 12 months.''
</P>
<P>
   But Meehan said he could not conclude that Clinton ``lacks the
capacity to govern,'' and he accused the committee of pursuing ``a
lawless path to impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Schippers, a sharp-tongued Chicago prosecutor, laid out
a long, scathing narrative of allegations that Clinton engaged in
an elaborate conceit to conceal the intimate details of his
relationship with Lewinsky: 11 sexual encounters, 17 episodes of
phone sex, and 64 gifts they exchanged.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president elected to follow a pattern of selective memory,
blatant untruths, artful distortions, outright lies and half-truths
_ the blackest lie of all,'' Schippers said.
</P>
<P>
   He accused Clinton of lying to so many people that ``there is no
one left to lie to.''
</P>
<P>
   Over nearly three hours, Schippers mixed venomous rhetoric with
searing sarcasm in attacking Clinton's actions. Referring to the
alleged phone sex, Schippers said, ``If what happened on these
phone calls is banter, then Buckingham Palace is a house.''
</P>
<P>
   But he enraged committee Democrats when he claimed, without
elaborating, that the Justice Department and Starr had prevented
his staff from investigating ``more incidents involving probable
direct and deliberate obstruction of justice, witness tampering,
perjury, and abuse of power.''
</P>
<P>
   By issuing the claim without substantiating it or allowing
Clinton's lawyers an opportunity to respond, Schippers engaged in
an ``irresponsible'' act of ``McCarthyism,'' Frank said.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, Craig said: ``We are disappointed and
saddened that the committee majority brought this solemn
constitutional process down to a level of innuendo, anger and
unfair, unsubstantiated charges.''
</P>
<P>
   During the Schippers presentation, the Judiciary Committee
released previously sealed transcripts of conversations between
Linda Tripp and her friend, Lucianne Goldberg, about how to
publicize Clinton's then-secret affair with Lewinsky. It was Tripp
whose secret recordings of Lewinsky later launched Starr's
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trick,'' Goldberg told Tripp, was to disclose just enough
information to a news reporter ``to titillate the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Lowell presented a methodical defense of Clinton and
appealed to the committee to not ``put the country through the
unseemly spectacle of a trial requiring Ms. Lewinsky to describe
what part of him touched what part of her.''
</P>
<P>
   If the House approves articles of impeachment, the constitution
requires the Senate to hold a trial, presided over by the chief
justice of the Supreme Court. Removing Clinton from office would
require 67 votes.
</P>
<P>
   Lowell urged the Judiciary Committee to ``listen to the American
people, who are asking you to find a truly bipartisan way to avoid
the course you are about to undertake.''
</P>
<P>
   The first phase of the committee's debate was expected to span
more than six hours as each of the panel's 37 members delivered
10-minute opening statements.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the committee will begin amending the articles, one
by one, and could approve at least one article of perjury before
the end of the day. Although all the Republicans generally support
all four articles, several GOP members said they will not vote for
them unless changes are made in some of them.
</P>
<P>
   Representative George W. Gekas of Pennsylvania, for example, has
said he will not support the abuse of power charge unless the
committee drops an element related to Clinton invoking executive
privilege to try to prevent his lawyers for discussing their
confidential conversations with prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   The committee is expected to complete voting on the articles of
impeachment tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   The lame-duck speaker, Newt Gingrich, notified all 435 House
members Thursday to prepare for the Judiciary Committee to issue a
final report on the impeachment investigation next week. The report
is expected to be circulated next Wednesday, and the House is
tentatively scheduled to debate and vote on the matter Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
