<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADIAN-EXECUTIONSTAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT STAYS EXECUTION OF CANADIAN IN TEXAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN MORITZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joseph Stanley Faulder, the Canadian whose pending execution
brought international protests, won a reprieve from the U.S.
Supreme Court on Thursday night, 30 minutes before he was to be
taken to the Texas death chamber.
</P>
<P>
   The stay, handed down about 5:30 p.m., ended marathon
maneuverings that had been in high gear since Wednesday morning,
when the Texas Board of Pardons and Paroles rejected Faulder's bid
for clemency.
</P>
<P>
   Faulder's lawyers gained a stay of execution Wednesday afternoon
when U.S. District Judge Sam Sparks of Austin ruled that Texas
could not show that its clemency procedures safeguard the rights of
condemned inmates. But that order was reversed about midday
Thursday by the U.S. 5th Circuit Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   The final word came from the Supreme Court, which said it needs
more time to consider all of the issues. The high court's action
means that the execution will be delayed at least 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Far out,'' Faulder said through a prison system spokesman in
Huntsville. ``That suits me.''
</P>
<P>
   Death penalty opponents from Canada, which outlawed capital
punishment in 1976, have spent much of the past week in Austin and
Huntsville petitioning Texas leaders to reduce Faulder's
punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian Foreign Minister Lloyd Axworthy and Raymond Chretien,
the country's ambassador to the United States, were joined by U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright in an official request for
leniency in Faulder's case.
</P>
<P>
   Faulder, 61, was condemned for the stabbing and bludgeoning
death of oil matriarch Inez Phillips during a robbery of her
Gladewater home in July 1975. Faulder was arrested two years later
when he was taken into custody on unrelated charges in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Although he never denied his guilt, Faulder has long argued that
he was denied his right under international law to speak with a
representative of his country at the time of his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   In their petition to the Supreme Court, Faulder's lawyers cited
terms of the Vienna Convention on Consular Relations. They argued
that Canadian authorities should have been told of the arrest.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers also said Texas authorities should have informed
Faulder of his right to contact the Canadian government.
</P>
<P>
   Texas officials said that they knew Faulder had served prison
time in Canada, but that he did not tell them he was a Canadian
citizen. And it was 15 years later when the Canadian government and
Faulder's family, who believed he was dead, realized that he was on
Texas' Death Row.
</P>
<P>
   Faulder, who would have become the oldest inmate to be executed
in Texas, drew little sympathy from state officials despite the
protests.
</P>
<P>
   Victor Rodriguez, chairman of the Board of Pardons and Paroles,
called his petition for clemency ``weak.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush was more blunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``People can't just come in our state and cold-blood murder
somebody,'' said Bush, a strong supporter of capital punishment.
``That's unacceptable behavior, regardless of their nationality,''
Bush told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Death penalty critics hammered Texas' procedures, chiefly
because the 18 members of the pardons and paroles board are not
required to meet as a body or state a reason for their decisions.
One member abstained and the others voted to reject clemency.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks, in his ruling to stay the execution, also was critical
of the procedures.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the court knows for certain is that (Faulder) filed a
petition for clemency, and the board voted against clemency,''
Sparks wrote. ``The record is void of any reason for the board's
action. The board had an opportunity to identify its process, but
merely trumpeted its ability to rule on clemency without meeting or
giving reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Austin lawyer Maurie Levin, who is assisting in Faulder's
appeals, said, ``I'm just really glad that the questions about the
clemency procedures in this state are finally being addressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez defended the procedures and pointed out that the board
is exempt from state open meeting statutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what these (death penalty) opponents would like to do
is to get us in an open meeting and start challenging the evidence
and hold a whole new trial,'' Rodriguez said. ``They want to say,
`OK, we lost in the first criminal procedure, let's get another
shot at this.' We don't agree with that.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
