<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOK LIKE A MILLION, WITH BILL TO MATCH  
 SHIPYARD SOIREE FOR OPERA DEBUT  
 HOME OF THE ARCH LOSES MONKEY BAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo.)  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The unasked question at a party for DR. GERALD IMBER,
a plastic surgeon and author, was ``Who has and who hasn't?''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd at the East Side brownstone of the advertising
executive JERRY DELLA FEMINA on Wednesday included BILL BEUTEL, an
anchor on WABC-TV; the actor BEN GAZZARA; the restaurateur KENNETH
ARETSKY; LINDA FAIRSTEIN, chief of the sex-crimes prosecution unit
in the Manhattan district attorney's office; and FERN MALLIS,
executive director of the Council of Fashion Designers.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, there were plenty of practically perfect noses
and unfurrowed brows at the party. But were they Imber's handiwork?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very secretive _ you'll never know,'' said Della Femina,
speculating that 20 percent to 25 percent of the guests had had a
nip here or a tuck there.
</P>
<P>
   Imber gave up no secrets. But he did say that his latest book,
``For Men Only: Looking Your Best Through Science, Surgery and
Common Sense'' (William Morrow), proved that vanity is not just the
province of women.
</P>
<P>
   CANDACE BUSHNELL, who wrote the ``Sex and the City'' column for
The New York Observer, lingered with CLIFFORD STREIT, the
curly-haired manager of many one-time models now scribbling away as
writers. Streit said he had never been under the knife, adding,
``Based upon some of the results I've seen in this room, I would.''
</P>
<P>
   A moment or two later, he changed his story and confessed to
having had some work done under his eyes. By Imber? He did not say.
</P>
<P>
   Like Imber, Ms. Bushnell said more men should consider having
plastic surgery. ``At one time it didn't matter how men looked _ it
only mattered how women looked,'' she said, pausing for a sip of
wine. ``How shallow do we sound?''
</P>
<P>
   Shipyard Soiree for Opera Debut
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK It was as if ``On the Waterfront'' had been transformed
for the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   The Brooklyn Academy of Music took over a cavernous building at
the Brooklyn Navy Yard for its Next Wave gala on Wednesday. Instead
of shipyard workers in dirty overalls, the guests tended toward
basic black. And instead of the Andrews Sisters, the musical focus
was the experimental opera of PHILIP GLASS.
</P>
<P>
   The gala has in the past been held in places like a performance
space near the Manhattan Bridge, but the Navy Yard was a logical
choice this year, what with plans afoot to convert part of it into
a film-production complex. Among those who attended the night's
events, which marked the opening of Glass' new opera, ``Monsters of
Grace,'' were PAUL SIMON, NATALIE MERCHANT, CHUCK CLOSE and BIANCA
JAGGER.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounding the diners were dozens of television monitors
showing the same things they could have seen at home _ cable fare
like the Weather Channel and the Cartoon Network. At one point, a
pornographic film came on. But it was a BAM gala. Few seemed more
than mildly distracted.
</P>
<P>
   Home of the Arch Loses Monkey Bar
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Monkey Bar, a restaurant on East 54th Street in
Manhattan, accused the Monkey Bar, a St. Louis nightclub, of
monkeying around with its trademark and copying its olive-shaped
bar stools.
</P>
<P>
   ``We say by no stretch of the imagination has the Monkey Bar
established a national reputation,'' said DEMPSTER HOLLAND, a
lawyer for the St. Louis owners. ``We don't compete with New York,
and they don't compete with us.''
</P>
<P>
   But last week, a federal judge in St. Louis sided with PETER
GLASIER, the owner of the New York Monkey Bar, and barred the St.
Louis club from using the name. Holland said his clients were
searching for a new name.
</P>
</TEXT>
