<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4194 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBO-GRAPEVINE-TEX     12-10 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-GRAPEVINE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAPEVINE'S ON BRINK OF SECOND STATE TITLE IN THREE YEARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK HERRIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAPEVINE, Texas _ Even one of Grapevine's most outspoken
players didn't expect to be playing for a state championship
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heavens, no,'' Mustangs senior wide receiver Jason Schindler
said. ``Here we were just scratching for the playoffs. And now,
we've got to this point, it's like, well, we might as well win it
all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still not believing this.''
</P>
<P>
   Believe it.
</P>
<P>
   Grapevine (10-4) can win its second state title in three seasons
with a victory against Bay City (12-1) at 1 p.m. tomorrow in the
Class 4A Division I state championship.
</P>
<P>
   The Mustangs have the fewest victories of any team to reach the
state class finals since Trinity qualified with nine victories in
1992. But they also have the opportunity to join La Marque and
Sealy as the only schools this decade to win at least two state
titles in a three-year span.
</P>
<P>
   Fueled by second-half comebacks, the Mustangs have made the
unexpected possible. They have overcome a 1-2 start, won two
must-win games to end the regular season and rallied for playoff
victories the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I can explain it,'' Grapevine senior linebacker
Jared Brown said. ``All of the teachers at school are saying we're
giving them heart attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   But not the players or coaches. They have become accustomed to
this.
</P>
<P>
   The Mustangs have trailed at intermission in half their games
]this season. Grapevine is 4-3 in those games, including two
victories to end the regular season and victories against
Greenville and Plainview in the playoffs the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Against 10th-ranked Greenville in the Region II final, the
Mustangs rallied from a 21-10 halftime deficit and won, 34-31, in
three overtimes. In the state semifinals against Plainview on
Saturday _ the Mustangs' third playoff opponent with at least 10
victories _ it was more of the same.
</P>
<P>
   The Mustangs trailed 13-0 in the first half and 13-9 at
halftime. Grapevine took a 23-19 lead on Schindler's 42-yard
touchdown reception from Jordan Wilson with 4:25 remaining. The
defense then had to stuff Plainview with 1:08 left at Grapevine's
26-yard line to preserve the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last Saturday, we're trailing at halftime and we're going up
the ramp, and I heard the kids saying we've got them right where we
want them,'' Grapevine coach Mike Sneed said. ``That's pretty
confident.''
</P>
<P>
   Undersized defensive backs Stewart Records and Brad Balla are
two of the biggest reasons the season is still going. Records
(5-foot-7, 155 pounds) blocked a field-goal attempt in the second
half, then had an interception in the third overtime against
Greenville. Balla (5-8, 155) was the regular-season savior, with
three interceptions in season-ending comeback victories against
rivals Colleyville Heritage and Keller.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teams let up on us after kicking us around in the first
half,'' Records said. ``Teams have heard a lot about us getting
down early, but we just come back in the second half and tear them
apart. At halftime, we take care of business. No one's yelling. We
just figure out, `What does it take to win?' ''
</P>
<P>
   More times than not, they have.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it's because we're in better shape or want it
more, but something happens,'' Grapevine junior defensive tackle
Andrew Marr said. ``The whole team just ignites, catches on fire.
No one can stop us, and everyone knows it's coming.'' /
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
