<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-ALEDO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALEDO COACH STAYS THE COURSE AND PUMPS BEARCATS INTO POWER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TROY PHILLIPS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALEDO, Texas _ Steve Reid had other things on his mind besides
coaching in 1991, namely retirement.
</P>
<P>
   As part of a search committee charged with putting a jam in the
revolving door of football coaches at Aledo, Reid wanted no part of
the job. He had served his coaching tenure in the Parker County
town decades earlier, leading Aledo to a 52-12 record from 1967-72.
</P>
<P>
   The committee tabbed Brewer assistant James Roller, who lasted
two days at Aledo after a misunderstanding with Aledo officials
over retaining assistant coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Willard Stuard, the then-superintendent, turned to his friend,
Reid, for a favor _ a ``big'' one.
</P>
<P>
   Reid coached for one season, stipulating that Aledo find a
replacement in 1992. Two years and two coaches later, Aledo finally
found its man.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, A&AMP;M Consolidated assistant Tim Buchanan became Aledo's
fifth football coach in five years. Six seasons after taking the
reins of a losing program, the energetic Buchanan has Aledo (12-1)
in its second state championship game. The Bearcats are scheduled
to face Cuero (11-3) in the Class 3A Division I championship at 5
p.m. tomorrow at the Astrodome in Houston. Aledo was a Class A
state finalist in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Not since the 1987-89 tenure of coach Chuck Curtis has Aledo
seen such football madness. The past three seasons, Buchanan's
teams are 37-4-1, including runs to the 1996 state quarterfinals
and '97 semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hit a downturn at the end of the '80s, and it was
terrible,'' said David Milton, a 30-year resident of Aledo and
local youth baseball coach. ``When Buchanan came, he completely
turned it around in about two years.''
</P>
<P>
   Most wondered after 1993, in which Buchanan's first team went
2-8, if anyone could reverse Aledo's fortune.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have any doubts about coming that year,'' Buchanan
said. ``It was cut and dried; we weren't very good.''
</P>
<P>
   Aledo missed the playoffs in 1994 with a 7-2-1 record, and
1995's 6-3-1 mark left Buchanan doubting himself. Needing to beat
3-6 Decatur to make the playoffs, Aledo lost, 20-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we'd turned the corner,'' he said. ``That team was
good enough to make the playoffs, and it was the first time I
questioned whether I would be able to get Aledo back to the
playoffs. I considered stepping aside and letting someone else
try.''
</P>
<P>
   Playoffs or not, Aledo was winning again. Fans and
administrators had sensed stability in the overall athletic program
during Buchanan's three-year stay. Participation and morale in all
sports was up, and no one was calling for the coach's head.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're changing coaches all the time, the state of your
team's not good,'' said local barber G.L. Lowe, who has had a son
and two grandsons play football for Aledo.] ``Some of them before
Tim just couldn't coach. The best thing he's done is put in the
weight program and getting the boys believing they can win.''
</P>
<P>
   If Buchanan knew anything, it was how an off-season program
worked. A&AMP;M Consolidated, in College Station, had been in four
consecutive Class 4A title games from 1989-92. The Tigers didn't
get there by sitting around after November.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a kid works for six to seven months getting pushed to
where they think they'll die if they take another step,'' Buchanan
said, ``it makes them think a lot more on Friday nights. Few quit
after going through what we put 'em through.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan was one of seven A&AMP;M Consolidated assistants who
eventually became head coaches elsewhere. Now, he oversees an
athletic program that fields regional powerhouses in almost every
sport.
</P>
<P>
   Aledo programs in all sports now are built from middle school
up. Aledo school board President Steve Reid II, son of the former
coach, said Buchanan abolished an old party line of having athletes
specialize in one sport, a policy that hindered all sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was Tim's biggest challenge,'' Reid II said. ``He broke
down those barriers. You know you can't have kids specializing in a
small town like Aledo. They need to learn the fundamentals of as
many sports as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Middle linebacker Jordan Porter said Buchanan and his staff have
``made athletes out of normal people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach is on top of everything,'' Porter said. ``We trust him
to the point of doing whatever he says, knowing it'll come through
for the best, and it has.''
</P>
<P>
   For Buchanan, the Bearcats have come through with his first
title shot as a head coach. Mere days before kickoff, Buchanan said
it ``hasn't sunk in.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The greatest thing in high school football is to be playing
and coaching in December,'' he said. ``We've become like a family.
Like any family, we've had our arguments and disruptions.''
</P>
<P>
   Bigger schools have contacted him, but Buchanan can't imagine
moving again, as he has six times in his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I've come here,'' he said, ``it's convinced me that this
is one of the best jobs in the state.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
