<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-VARGAS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VARGAS HAS COME A LONG WAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
 &HT;     By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Fernando Vargas' sleeveless shirt exposed a tattoo
around his bicep that he described as an Aztec war band. As he sat
down for an interview moments after completing 12 rounds of
sparring at his Big Bear Lake training camp, he explained its
significance.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the Aztec God of war,'' he said, pointing to a
particular part of the tattoo.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he would sacrifice his victims, he would de-bone them and
use their skin. It's part of my heritage,'' he said with a
dead-serious expression and obvious pride.
</P>
<P>
   This is Vargas' game face _ one of the many he has _ in the days
preceding the biggest night of his life. The Oxnard resident,
barely 21 and with only 14 fights behind him, faces experienced
slugger Yory Boy Campas for Campas' IBF junior middleweight
championship on Saturday in Atlantic City, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   As strong and determined as he is, Vargas does have a profound
weakness. Just mention his 2-year-old son, Fernando Jr., and watch
him evolve instantly from that proud warrior into a loving and _ if
you hit just the right nerve _ tearful father who has devoted his
life to his boy a generation after his own father abandoned him.
</P>
<P>
   That's Vargas, a confident and profoundly talented boxer who has
matured into a sensitive young man with a sense of responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the !ital!real!off! Fernando Vargas,'' said Rolando
Arellano, his manager and close friend. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Vargas was a troubled kid, like many in his rough La Colonia
neighborhood of Oxnard.
</P>
<P>
   He was a street fighter from as early as he can remember. A
!ital!good!off! street fighter. A week didn't go by, he said, that
he wasn't suspended from school for beating up a classmate.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many, however, he was both lucky and smart.
</P>
<P>
   At 10, he found boxing, then trainer Eduardo Garcia, an
upstanding man who served as both his teacher and principal male
role model. And, well aware of the perilous direction he was
heading, Vargas stuck with both.
</P>
<P>
   Within in a few years, he was among the best amateur fighters in
the nation. In 1994, at 16, he became the youngest national
champion in history and represented the United States in the 1996
Olympics, where he was eliminated in the second round, in large
part because of a ridiculous scoring system.
</P>
<P>
   ``In less than a month (at age 10), I could see he had the
qualities to be a great fighter,'' said Garcia, who also trains his
son, IBF junior lightweight champion Roberto Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas began to develop a bad-boy image just before the Atlanta
Games.
</P>
<P>
   It started with comments he made about Oscar De La Hoya. In
simple terms, he resented being called the next De La Hoya because
he doesn't like the WBC welterweight champion _ whom he believes is
a phony _ and wasn't afraid to say so.
</P>
<P>
   The image was bolstered by two incidents late last year: Vargas
was arrested for reckless driving and had an out-of-the-ring run-in
with a rival fighter. His neighborhood and his appearance also
supported the perception. Most conspicuously, a tuft of blond hair
just above his forehead is becoming a trademark.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas makes no apologies.
</P>
<P>
   He admits he was cocky but attributed his comments to youth and
his lingering dislike for De La Hoya. He was being honest. The
arrest and ill-advised fight? He makes mistakes. And his
appearance? Hey, just Fernando being Fernando, something he
promises will never change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll always be myself,'' he said. ``I think it's better that
way. I think people are more attracted to that than if I try to be
like De La Hoya, try to be good and dandy. That's something I'm
not.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a good person, don't get me wrong. I have a good heart, I
like working with kids,'' he said. ``People are going to have to
like me or not the way I am, though, that's all.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk to Vargas about those closest to him and it's impossible
not to like him, or at least respect him.
</P>
<P>
   He's fiercely loyal. Garcia has been with him all the way, and
Arellano, an attorney, came along three years later. They'll be
there at the end, too.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas said a managerial firm offered him roughly $2 million
after the Olympics if he would agree to leave his handlers behind
and train on the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   He gets angry when he thinks about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were asking me to do something impossible,'' he said.
``To cut my trainer, a guy who busted his (behind) in the
strawberry fields, a guy who had nothing. My trainer deserves
everything he's getting now, believe me.
</P>
<P>
   ``And Rolando has been there through thick and thin, too. He's
not just a manager, he's a friend. This is a guy who used to help
me work on my car.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me about two seconds to say no.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, he's there for his family. His mother now works for
him and he takes his role of big brother seriously, pushing his
siblings to succeed and admonishing them to avoid any bad elements.
He's also been known to throw a few dollars their way these days.
</P>
<P>
   However, the subject of fatherhood takes Vargas to a different
level of passion.
</P>
<P>
   His father, Javier Vargas, left Fernando and his siblings to be
raised by their mother and grandmother, as well as by a stepfather
with whom he only now is building a relationship. Even with Garcia,
he missed many lessons he might have learned from a dad. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Vargas said he will never forgive his father _ and he won't make
the same mistake.
</P>
<P>
   The center of his universe is Fernando Jr., who was home in
Oxnard with Martha Lopez, the baby's mother, while the boxer
trained for nearly two months for Saturday's fight.
</P>
<P>
   As the conversation gradually shifted from his father to his
son, his emotions shifted back and forth from anger to love and
everywhere in between until he broke down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad I'm not like him,'' Vargas said of his father, anger
still in his voice. ``That man to me is like nobody. He's probably
in jail right now; I don't really care where he's at. He tries to
pop up every once in a while. You know, I'm not gonna have that.
He's not playing a role in my life; he's not playing a role in my
son's life.''
</P>
<P>
   His eyes started to get glassy and his voice cracked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts sometimes, you know,'' he said. ``But what can you
do?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I'm bitter. I don't want (Fernando Jr.) to go through
life thinking he did something wrong and wonder why that person
isn't there. But what can you do? You gotta be a man about things.
I guess I had to learn to be a man very young in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   He smiled a weak smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``But with my son, all I have to do is see those big brown eyes
and everything feels much better. I just love him so much,
!ital!so!off! much. He's a part of me.''
</P>
<P>
   At that, the tears started falling and he excused himself.
</P>
<P>
   Any questions as to where Vargas finds his inspiration?
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say Vargas doesn't have dreams for himself. He
does.
</P>
<P>
   He has the same routine every night before he goes to sleep. He
closes his eyes and sees himself being raised into the air with the
championship belt around his waist.
</P>
<P>
   When they put him back on the ring canvas on Saturday, be
assured that those closest to him will be clustered tightly around
him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
