<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4203 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RETURN-TO-MARS11-COX     12-10 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETURN-TO-MARS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NASA returns to the Red Planet
 &HT;    By Eliot Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ NASA is going back to the Red Planet.
</P>
<P>
   Today's scheduled 1:45 p.m. launch of Mars Climate Orbiter, and
next month's launch of Mars Polar Lander, are the next steps in a
series of missions to study the planet and its past _ perhaps for
clues that life once existed.
</P>
<P>
   They may also be the forerunners to an ambitious manned mission
to Mars a little more than a decade from now.
</P>
<P>
   The missions follow the 1996 launches of the Mars Pathfinder,
whose rover beamed back dramatic views of Mars' surface in the
summer of 1997, and the Mars Global Surveyor, which is now circling
the planet, sending overhead pictures at unprecedented resolution.
</P>
<P>
   A Delta II rocket will launch the Orbiter from the Cape
Canaveral Air Station, next to Kennedy Space Center. The launch was
set for today but was delayed by a problem with software that keeps
the Orbiter's batteries from overcharging and exploding.
</P>
<P>
   NASA could launch any of the next several days, with only a only
a 30 percent to 40 percent chance of a weather scrub through the
weekend, project managers told a pre-launch news briefing Wednesday
at Kennedy Space Center.
</P>
<P>
   The Orbiter is about the size of a Volkswagen Beetle _ 5 1/2
feet by 6 1/2 feet by 7 1/2 feet high _ and weighs only 1,400
pounds, and nearly half of that is fuel. It will travel 416 million
miles and arrive at Mars in September, then move into orbit and
unfold its solar energy panels.
</P>
<P>
   Its first role: radio relay for the Mars Polar Lander, which
launches from the air station Jan. 3 and arrives in December 1999
at the northern edge of Mars' southern polar cap.
</P>
<P>
   During entry the Lander will drop two basketball-sized ``Deep
Space 2'' probes during entry; each will slam to the surface at
30,000 to 40,000 times the force of Earth's gravity, driving it
about 3 feet into Mars soil, to search for evidence of ice.
</P>
<P>
   Once on the surface, the Lander will use a robot arm to dig up,
collect and study soil samples. It will search for ice and for
evidence of climate changes over the centuries.
</P>
<P>
   The Lander is expected to work for about three months before
Mars' cold drains its batteries.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in February 2000, the Orbiter will meticulously map the
face of Mars and conduct a daily survey of the planet's atmosphere
for a Martian year _ 687 Earth days. It will remain as a radio
relay for future Lander missions.
</P>
<P>
   The two Mars missions reflect a change in attitudes about life
elsewhere in the universe, said Ed Weiler, NASA's associate
administrator for space science.
</P>
<P>
   NASA and college scientists created a buzz in 1996 when they
said a meteorite that may have come from Mars contained what might
have been the fossils of ancient microbes. Their findings were
challenged by other scientists, but reopened the debate about life
on Mars.
</P>
<P>
   ``One bacterium found anywhere in the universe, even Mars, would
be a stupendous discovery,'' Weiler said Wednesday. ``Will we find
evidence bacteria existed on Mars 5 billion years ago? Perhaps.
Will we find existing life on Mars? That's a longer shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Scientists, Weiler said, once followed the ``Goldilocks''
theory: one planet was too hot, one too cold; Earth was just right.
Now, he said, life has been found in such inhospitable corners of
Earth as its polar ice caps and deepest ocean depths.
</P>
<P>
   ``People started finding life everywhere on Earth, in the most
extreme environments you could imagine,'' Weiler said. ``Life may
be a cosmic imperative _ if you have water, you have energy, if you
have organic compounds.''
</P>
<P>
   The key, he said, is water. Mars' deep canyons and channels are
strong evidence that water once flowed; the question is where it is
now.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to look for life. . .you have to follow the
water,'' Weiler said. ``That's what these two missions are all
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Mars' atmosphere is so cold and thin that water quickly freezes
or evaporates but does not rain. Polar frosts are mostly condensed
carbon dioxide, which accounts for 95 percent of Mars' atmosphere.
Because there are water-ice clouds and dust storms, some staggering
in size, NASA believes the top three feet of Mars' surface may be a
well-preserved snapshot of the last 1,000 centuries.
</P>
<P>
   The Mars project will cost about $328 million, including launch
vehicles and continuing research. But only about $190 million of
that is for the two ships; at about the cost of the Mars Pathfinder
alone, it's ``two spacecraft for the price of one.'' Project
Manager John McNamee said. He said the mission's relatively low
cost is part of NASA's goal to fly cheaper and more efficient
missions.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we have not compromised the science either,'' McNamee
said. ``We will accomplish exciting science.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
