A4246 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH.X3-HN     12-10 1352
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH.X3-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS LINING UP FOR IMPEACHMENT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In somber, often lofty terms, members of the House
Judiciary Committee late Thursday began debate over four articles
of impeachment, the final and most dramatic steps leading to a vote
on whether to impeach President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   As the committee's Democrats and Republicans laid out their
now-familiar views over Clinton's alleged ``high crimes and
misdemeanors,'' the White House and its allies intensified efforts
to persuade lawmakers to censure, not impeach, the president for
covering-up his affair with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   With little doubt over the outcome of the Judiciary Committee's
deliberations, expected to run into the weekend, the committee
members' pitches and the White House campaign were directed toward
the next phase of the impeachment fight, the debate and vote on the
House floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people are waiting for us to come to our senses
and end this political game of chicken,'' said Rep. Charles
Schumer, D-N.Y., who predicted that a vote Friday by the full House
would result in the president's impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think many from the other party are willing to buck
the siren calls of the radical right.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, said committee members and their
congressional colleagues ``must resist the temptation'' to let the
president's misbehavior pass unpunished.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is above the law. Actions have consequences. Always
tell the truth. We should insist on these high ideals,'' Smith
said. ``That the president has fallen short of the standard doesn't
mean we should lower it.''
</P>
<P>
   Opening remarks by all 37 committee members _ 21 Republicans and
16 Democrats _ are expected to be finished shortly before noon
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The first article, one of two accusing Clinton of lying under
oath, was expected to be voted on by the end of the day. Debate on
the other perjury charge and the two others alleging obstruction of
justice and abuse of power were likely to be finished by late
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, perhaps as late as Tuesday, the committee will
consider a Democratic-sponsored alternative to impeachment, a
resolution censuring the president for making ``false statements
concerning his reprehensible conduct with a subordinate.'' The
resolution would require Clinton to acknowledge the rebuke by
signing it.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., sent a tersely worded
``Dear Colleague'' letter to all 435 House members advising them
they would be needed in Washington by midweek to consider the work
being completed by the Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the House will begin considering the first
impeachment of a president since the House voted to put Andrew
Johnson on trial in the Senate in 1868. Twenty-four years ago, the
Judiciary Committee approved articles of impeachment against
President Richard Nixon, who resigned before the House could vote
to send his case to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to avoid a similar fate for Clinton, top presidential
aides began calling moderate Republicans and some conservative
Democrats who are considered swing votes in the impeachment fight.
Previously, the White House had used emissaries outside the
administration to quietly approach House members who could be
decisive in Clinton's effort to remain in office.
</P>
<P>
   While labor unions, Democratic Party leaders and Democratic
leaders in the House were making pitches on behalf of the
president, Clinton was staying on the sidelines _ at least for now.
On Friday, he is to leave Washington on a three-day trip to the
Middle East, and among the lawmakers accompanying him are
Pennsylvania Rep. Jon Fox and New York Reps. Rick Lazio and Michael
Forbes, all Republicans who have not decided how they will vote on
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an issue where twisting arms isn't appropriate, but
bending ears is,'' said White House spokesman Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   House Democratic leader Dick Gephardt of Missouri was planning
to contact the 31 Democrats who abandoned Clinton and sided with
Republicans earlier this fall to approve an open-ended impeachment
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, House Republican Whip Tom DeLay of Texas was
canvassing his network of deputies about movement among GOP members
and issued a public alert for them to hold fast against anything
less than an impeachment vote.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay, the No. 3 ranking Republican in the House, criticized the
Democrat's proposal to let Clinton off with a censure resolution
rebuking his behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think a resolution censure by Congress is going to do
the trick,'' DeLay wrote in an opinion piece for the Washington
Times. ``The idea of censure is born out of a desperate imagination
by those too timid to uphold their own sworn oath to `support and
defend` the Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Rep. Bob Barr, a Republican on the Judiciary Committee
and an early advocate of impeaching Clinton, said the lobbying
effort is barely underway. ``We haven't seen anything yet,'' Barr
told reporters over breakfast Thursday. In the four days following
the committee's vote on impeachment, ``you'll see more pressure put
on members than any you've seen in 10 years,'' he predicted.
</P>
<P>
   A key element in the Democratic effort to head off articles of
impeachment is a harshly worded censure resolution drafted by four
Judiciary Committee members, including Texas Rep. Sheila Jackson
Lee.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said that the president was ``open to any proposal that
seeks to put this matter behind us that people in good faith bring
forward that is fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Late Thursday, the White House was being pressed by some
Democrats, at the urging of moderate Republicans, to accept an even
stronger censure resolution, one that would require the president
to pay a monetary penalty in addition to leaving him open to
criminal and civil penalties.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press quoted unnamed sources saying that Rep. Bob
Livingston, the Louisiana Republican in line to become House
speaker, has said privately that he is unlikely to allow a vote on
censure if the issue reaches the floor next week. In public
comments to reporters, Livingston offered no definitive comments on
the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, two polls released Thursday show more than 60 percent
of Americans want the Judiciary Committee to vote against articles
of impeachment. One of the surveys, conducted by the Gallup
organization for CNN and USA Today, found that 55 percent of
Americans favor a censure of the president.
</P>
<P>
   An NBC/Wall Street Journal poll found two-thirds of Americans
opposed to impeachment. The same survey found that the Republican
Party has slipped to its lowest level of popularity since 1990 and
its negative rating has almost doubled from 39 percent this week
compared to 22 percent in January.
</P>
<P>
   One Republican on the Judiciary Committee warned Thursday night
against paying too much attention to polls when weighing the
president's effort to hide his extramarital affair from lawyers in
Paula Jones' sexual harassment lawsuit and later from independent
counsel Kenneth Starr's investigators.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say that a thousand historians and a swarm of political
opinion polls and a gaggle of media programs and talk shows,
nothing, none of those things can change the vital facts in this
case,'' said Rep. George Gekas, R-Pa. ``And that is that falsehoods
were uttered in a court proceeding under oath, both in the
depositions and later in a criminal federal grand jury.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Howard Berman, a California Democrat on the committee,
disagreed and said House members should not ignore public
sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlike every other vote we cast, where conscience may play a
determinative role, regardless of public opinion, a vote for
impeachment cannot be blind to the views of those who vested power
in the president,'' Berman said. ``It would be very, very wrong to
expunge the results of an election for the President of the United
States without the overwhelming consent of the governed.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
