<DOCNO> NYT19981210.0567 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 23:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4370 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-HIV-BABIES-420&AMP;ADD     12-10 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HIV-BABIES-420&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBANY TO SPEED DATA ON INFANTS' H.I.V. TESTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By LYNDA RICHARDSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York state health officials are moving to
alleviate delays in letting mothers and doctors know whether
newborns have the virus that causes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   A state program mandates testing of all newborns for the virus,
HIV. A new regulation will require hospitals to speed up the
testing of women whose HIV status is unknown at the time of birth,
and to return the results within 48 hours in order to identify
newborns at risk for HIV.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors and advocates for people with AIDS have complained that
it has taken more than a month in some cases to receive HIV test
results on newborns from the state laboratory in Albany. And a
nonprofit advocacy group, the HIV Law Project, has sued the state
over the delays. The group had asked a justice in State Supreme
Court in Manhattan to order that positive HIV test results be
returned within 72 hours, or to halt the program _ the first and
only mandatory testing program for newborns in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the New York State Health Department said
Thursday that scientific advances, not the court case, had caused
the agency to put forward the regulation, which is to go into
effect next year.
</P>
<P>
   A study by the State Health Department found that if the
antiviral drug AZT is given to newborns with HIV antibodies within
48 hours of birth, the drug can substantially reduce the baby's
chances of becoming infected. The study also said the transmission
rate was reduced even more if the mother took AZT prenatally and
during delivery. The study was completed in February and published
last month in The New England Journal of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Theresa McGovern, the executive director of the law project,
said that she had been engaged in settlement talks with the state,
adding that the regulation would address a major part of the
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is they should have done this as soon as they
passed the law,'' Ms. McGovern said. ``All these politicians were
taking credit for saving infants but nobody was dealing with the
fact that many mothers weren't hearing until four or five weeks
that they were HIV-positive, and some had been breast-feeding their
children.''
</P>
<P>
   The mandatory program went into effect in February 1997 after a
furious battle among politicians, civil libertarians and advocates
for women and people with AIDS. Fending off criticism over the
issue of confidentiality _ since a positive test on the newborn
always means the mother is infected _ legislators had argued that
early detection of HIV could help save babies' lives.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But health care professionals have said the delays in test
results have undermined efforts to provide better infant care.
</P>
<P>
   According to court papers filed over the summer, Justice Sheila
Abdus-Salaam of State Supreme Court also expressed concern. The
justice said the State Health Department had offered several
reasons that results could not be provided to a mother within 72
hours of her child's birth. But she added that the state's
opposition to the law project's request for a quicker turnaround of
HIV test results ``raises more questions for this court than it
answers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For example, why can't HIV testing be performed separate and
apart from the testing for other diseases for which specimens
cannot be taken right after birth?'' court papers quoted the judge
as asking the department.
</P>
<P>
   The Health Department's spokeswoman, Ms. Tarlton, said Thursday
that the new regulation would place the responsibility on hospitals
to supply test results within 48 hours in cases in which there is
no record of the mother's HIV status.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tarlton said the tests would need to be conducted in
hospital-based or commercial laboratories, rather than in the state
lab.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
