<SLUG> BC-GEn-HOFFARTH-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUBIOUS DOZEN LEAVE THEIR MARK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's actually quite simple to escape the clutches
of the annual Daily News Dubious Dozen list of sports media fiends
of the past year.
</P>
<P>
   _ No. 1: Don't do anything stupid that could tarnish your
career.
</P>
<P>
   _ No. 2: See No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Let's not even get started on last year's 12 Angry Men and
Women. From Marv Albert's ``experimental phase'' to Frank Gifford's
bosom buddy to Gary Miller's bladder problem, it set a bad
publicity standard that those who aspire to star in the sports
media could only dream of matching.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, they did worse in 1998. Judge for yourself:
</P>
<P>
   1. Jim Hill: The KCBS-Channel 2 sports anchor showed up at the
NFL meetings in Kansas City in the last week of October to cover
the event for his station.
</P>
<P>
   But how do you define ``cover?'' Hill marched in with the
delegation lobbying for Michael Ovitz's Carson stadium project.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Shapiro of the Washington Post, covering the meetings in
the proper way for his paper, thought that to be strange. So he
asked Hill about it.
</P>
<P>
   Hill said he saw ``nothing wrong'' with helping ``my friend
Mike.'' When he returned to L.A., he did a story on the meetings,
interviewing Ovitz. Then the station made him read a disclaimer
that basically absolved him from reporting any more on the subject
_ but apparently allowing him to act independently in his support
for the group.
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro correctly wrote that Hill's ``endorsement and
promotion'' of the Ovitz bid was a ``conflict of interest and a
breach of ethics. In any reputable newsroom in America, print or
broadcast, Hill's participation as a member of Ovitz's team almost
certainly would be considered a suspendable, if not a firing
offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro obviously has never covered the L.A. media.
</P>
<P>
   2. Chris Berman: Prior to ESPN's nationwide coverage of the
Angels' home opener at the new and improved Edison Field, Berman
lumbered down from his press box vantage point to host (and lead
cheers) in the pregame festivities down on the field _ all of which
was included in ESPN's coverage.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so Disney owns ESPN and Disney owns the Angels. But why drag
Berman from the ``Country Bear Jamboree'' attraction and deprive
all those Disneyland customers?
</P>
<P>
   3. Ahmad Rashad: In the September issue of ``Playboy'' in a
story entitled ``The Sweet Life of Ahmad Rashad,'' the NBC
courtside microphone holder detracts readers from further enjoyment
of the publication by complaining throughout the piece that he
doesn't understand why other media folk hate him so much.
</P>
<P>
   Then his cozy relationship with Michael Jordan came up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before every game, Michael and I spend about 20 minutes
together, someplace nobody can find us, just laughing and hanging
out,'' Rashad admits. ``I suppose the sports press would hate me
even more than they already do if they knew that.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, we do now.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the story, writer Craig Vetter follows Rashad into the
Bulls locker room. Rashad sneaks into a trainer's room, where
Jordan is tying his shoes. Coach Phil Jackson walks in and looks at
Vetter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you with the press? This room is off limits to the
media.''
</P>
<P>
   As Vetter leaves _ and Rashad stays _ it finally occurs to the
writer why other journalists hate Rashad, who'll have the rare
opportunity to spend Christmas at the Jordan home all day this
year.
</P>
<P>
   4. Boomer Esiason: Before his seat was warm as the newest member
of the ABC ``Monday Night Football'' team, Norman (his real name)
was enlisted to co-host the Miss America Pageant for the network
and was included in the list of TV's ``40 Most Fascinating Stars of
'98'' by ``People.''
</P>
<P>
   And to think he could have made millions from the Cincinnati
Bengals to remain as their star tackling dummy.
</P>
<P>
   5. Chris Lincoln: On live TV, ESPN's horse-racing host was put
in charge of drawing, then announcing, the post positions for the
Kentucky Derby _ a first-time ever event.
</P>
<P>
   Those two tasks apparently were too much. Until someone figured
out Lincoln's mistake, the greatest horse race in America had what
amounted to a scramble start from the snack bar on the infield.
</P>
<P>
   Go, baby, go.
</P>
<P>
   6. ESPN: In April, it hosted a town-hall meeting on race
relations in sports. President Clinton was the special guest
participant.
</P>
<P>
   During the 90-minute live show, a commercial ran for Hooters _
featuring a Clinton look-alike talking about how fun it was to come
down to the restaurant and check out the babes.
</P>
<P>
   A little foreshadowing, sure. But not a real good public
relations move for future favors from the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   7. Fox: For its dedication to style-over-substance in the sport
of hockey.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Fox Sports won the Grand Clio Award _ the Oscars for TV
commercials _ for the ``Sports Would Be Better . . .'' campaign it
used to promote the NHL. It marked the first time a network sports
TV campaign won the industry's coveted award, tops among 6,000
entries.
</P>
<P>
   The commercials showed sports by juxtaposing the physical nature
of hockey with non-contact sports like billiards, bowling, golf,
etc., with the tag that their sports would be better if they were
more like hockey.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, it's the other way around. Four months later, Fox
was trying to give away its network rights to the ratings-draining
league, glowing puck and all. ABC bought it _ starting in 2000, and
leaving Fox one more season to run the commercials.
</P>
<P>
   8. Keith Olbermann: Last month, he convinced Fox he'd like
return to sports. In fact, he never left in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Although his full-time gig was now anchoring ``The Big Show'' at
MSNBC (no relation to ``The Big Show'' name he said he retired at
ESPN), Olbermann, who said sports was behind him, managed to keep a
high profile writing weekly pieces for ``Sports Illustrated,''
doing radio commentary (in June, he apologized on his SportsFan
Radio Network show for his lack of maturity when he left ESPN),
reporting on postseason baseball games for NBC and, indirectly,
having his life played out on the ABC dramedy ``Sports Night.'' He
did everything but appear as himself on HBO's ``Arli$$.''
</P>
<P>
   When Fox brought him over to try to inject life into its Fox
Sports News cable show, it started an ad campaign: ``Same Keith,
New Network,'' even though the oft-tormented Olbermann claims he's
a new man because of therapy sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Caution: If it !ital!is the same Keith, Fox might line someone
up to replace him when he leaves for The History Channel sometime
next summer.
</P>
<P>
   9. Hannah Storm: She quite literally took a pregnant pause
during halftime of a prime-time NBA playoff game between Chicago
and Indiana to announce a ``major development in the world of
sports.''
</P>
<P>
   The news? NBC and Turner Sports are ``still considering'' a new
football league that would rival the NFL, but right now, ``no
details are available.''
</P>
<P>
   In August, Storm (whose real name is Storen and is married to
Dan Hicks) gave birth to a 7-pound., 12-ounce girl. The name? No
details are available.
</P>
<P>
   10. Peter King: The ``Sports Illustrated'' crack pro-football
writer, in a follow-up to the NBC-Turner football story, reported
to viewers of CNN/SI that the new league will ``be a much cheaper
avenue for some advertisers who right now feel they're getting
squeezed by the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   Did Ted Turner write that down on cue cards for you, Pete, or
was that something you just came up with yourself?
</P>
<P>
   11. Ben Wright: Suspended by CBS two years ago for sexist
remarks about the LPGA Tour, he found his way back to TV in
September doing commentaries _ called ``Quite Wright'' _ for a
syndicated show called ``Golf 2000 with Peter Jacobsen.''
</P>
<P>
   The response (from women's groups especially) wasn't all that
supportive.
</P>
<P>
   Said executive producer Jason Charles: ``I'm looking for all the
publicity I can get on this show _ good, bad or indifferent.''
</P>
<P>
   12. Marv Albert: Madison Square Garden rehired the convicted
female batterer to host a nightly sports news wrap-up show.
</P>
<P>
   Again, the response (from women's groups especially) wasn't all
that supportive.
</P>
<P>
   MSG head man Dave Checketts, admitting it was done in part for
ratings and publicity, asked: ``How long do we have to hold some
people out and punish them?''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's a question for some of Marv's sleazy friends. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
