<SLUG> BC-NY-STREET-PREACHERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACK STREET PREACHERS SUE OVER DENIAL OF PERMITS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A group of street preachers who have been a loud and
boisterous presence in Times Square for years sued New York City on
Thursday, accusing Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's administration of
trying to stifle its message.
</P>
<P>
   The group, which is known as the Black Israelites and teaches
that whites are devils and blacks are the true descendants of the
lost tribes of Israel, contended in the lawsuit that the Police
Department had revoked its permits for amplified sound while
allowing more mainstream productions.
</P>
<P>
   The group, which says its permits had been routinely approved
for the last 10 years, also accused the Police Department of a
campaign of harassment by preventing it from using the Times Square
traffic island, arresting members on trumped-up charges and
illegally taking their tables and books.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit is the latest to accuse the administration of
seeking to suppress dissent through the power of the Police
Department to grant or deny permits for rallies, protests and
marches.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is selective and unconstitutional and must stop
immediately,'' said Norman Siegel, the executive director of the
New York Civil Liberties Union, which filed the suit on behalf of
the Black Israelites.
</P>
<P>
   The civil liberties group has become a familiar opponent of the
mayor on First Amendment issues; last month it settled a lawsuit by
another group of protesters in which the city agreed to handle such
permits in an evenhanded way.
</P>
<P>
   The suit filed Thursday contends that in revoking the permit for
the Black Israelites, the Police Department had reneged on that
pledge.
</P>
<P>
   To bolster its contention that the group was singled out, the
suit also cites a comment by one of Giuliani's senior aides, Bruce
Teitelbaum, in The Jewish Week that the mayor decided to restrict
the group at Times Square because ``the people in that neighborhood
don't have to be subjected to that profane, vulgar, abusive
language.''
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Mode, the Police Department spokeswoman, said Thursday
night that the department would have no comment on the specifics of
the suit, because of the pending litigation. In the past, she has
defended the department's handling of the permit process, saying
that police officials take into account considerations of public
safety and the constitutional right to protest.
</P>
<P>
   Judge John Koeltl of U.S. District Court in Manhattan has
scheduled a hearing for Friday on the group's request to have its
sound permits immediately restored and to be allowed back in Times
Square without being harassed.
</P>
<P>
   One member of the Black Israelites, Stacy Williams, said after
the suit was filed Thursday that the group had preached peacefully
in Times Square for 20 years, using amplified sound for the last
10. The group hands out leaflets and books and is not shy about
engaging pedestrians and others in debate, Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit asserts that starting in the fall of 1997, the city
denied all the group's requests for sound permits in Times Square,
forcing its members to move nearby to the corner of 44th Street and
Broadway, where they continued to preach but without amplified
sound.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, which seeks compensatory and punitive damages, says
that the group's members were the object of repeated harassment,
including three false arrests. Eventually, the group was forced off
the street corner entirely, the suit says.
</P>
<P>
   After the city agreed to begin issuing permits early last month
to demonstrators on a uniform basis, the suit says, the Black
Israelites obtained a permit for Times Square and began preaching
there again.
</P>
<P>
   But on Nov. 12, the suit says, police officers approached the
group's members on the Times Square traffic island and revoked
their permit, telling them that they were acting on orders from the
mayor's office.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Williams said, he and other members of the group
were preaching without amplification at 44th Street and Broadway,
and the police approached again, telling the group that it was
creating a traffic hazard and ordering it to leave, Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   The suit contends that while the group has been denied permits
and access to Times Square, other commercial and entertainment
groups have been allowed to use amplified sound there.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said that the Giuliani administration had, in its
effort to clean up New York, put tourism and big business ahead of
the rights of citizens. ``We basically don't fit in,'' Williams
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
