<SLUG> BC-NY-VACCO-ELECTION-675&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHALLENGER'S CAMPAIGN GATHERS ITS OWN INQUIRY TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JONATHAN P. HICKS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Thwarted in the effort to use police officers to
investigate claims of voter fraud, the campaign of Attorney General
Dennis Vacco on Thursday began assembling its own makeshift team of
investigators _ including workers on leave from the attorney
general's office _ to try to determine the voting eligibility of
thousands of New York City residents.
</P>
<P>
   Vacco, the Republican incumbent, has been locked in a bitter
legal challenge to the unofficial results of the Nov. 3 election,
which show him trailing his Democratic challenger, Eliot Spitzer,
by slightly more than 26,000 votes.
</P>
<P>
   A major step was taken Thursday night toward an official
acknowledgment of Spitzer as attorney general when the New York
City Board of Elections unanimously certified results that showed
the Democrat as a runaway winner in the five boroughs. The city
results showed Spitzer with a 3-to-1 lead over Vacco _ 924,459 to
307,707. The state's Board of Elections is required by law to
certify the statewide election results by next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Employees in the attorney general's office have said that
several staff members were asked to take vacation time, sick days
or personal days to assist Vacco in his investigation of the New
York City voter rolls. ``People have been told to do this out of
loyalty to Dennis Vacco,'' said one senior staff member, who spoke
on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The staff member added that several employees had been asked
``to report to the campaign and to do whatever they ask you to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Spargo, the lawyer for Vacco's campaign, said that the
campaign had enlisted the help of about 50 volunteers, but that he
could not confirm whether they were employees on leave from the
attorney general's office.
</P>
<P>
   Spargo said that the Vacco campaign was also ``looking into
getting more experienced people than our volunteers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we're trying to verify that the voters live where
they say they live,'' Spargo said. ``We're not going to be looking
into citizenship. But we will make phone calls and go out in the
field and try to determine who is eligible.''
</P>
<P>
   Other senior advisers to Vacco said that the campaign had hired
a private investigator, Richard ``Bo'' Dietl, to help with the
canvassing. Dietl is a former New York City police detective who
now runs a private detective agency, Beau Dietl and Associates, of
Maspeth, Queens.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign has only days left before its representatives must
return to the state Supreme Court in Albany and substantiate their
charges of widespread voter fraud in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   The action by the city's Board of Elections came one day after
Justice Thomas Keegan of state Supreme Court signed an order
compelling the 10 commissioners to meet and certify the results,
and pass the figures on to the state. On Tuesday, the city board's
members split along party lines and failed to certify the returns
from the five boroughs.
</P>
<P>
   Vacco, who maintains that tens of thousands of New York City
voters cast ballots illegally, filed lawsuits in state Supreme
Court asking that he be named the winner or that the court
authorize a new election.
</P>
<P>
   This week the Vacco campaign sought to invoke a seldom-used
state law providing for the police to question residents whose
eligibility is challenged. Varying interpretations of the law
resulted in the derailment of that effort, however.
</P>
<P>
   Vacco's lawyers argued that only a single commissioner's
complaint was required for a police canvass. But the president of
the City Board of Elections said it was a matter for the board as a
whole to decide. Keegan also maintained that it was an electoral
matter, and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani declined to act without the
judge's order.
</P>
<P>
   For the next few days, Spargo said, his team of volunteers will
go through the voter rolls and the data from the credit firm, make
calls and drive through the streets of New York City to see whether
voters live at the addresses listed on their voter registration
forms. No door-to-door visits are expected, Spargo said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He said that 70,000 people on the voter rolls had filed
change-of-address forms indicating that they had moved to other
states, and that by the time the two campaigns appear before Keegan
in Albany on Monday, he hopes he will have established that there
were more than 26,000 illegally cast votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect we'll be working around the clock,'' he said. ``One
of our problems is that there is a massive amount of checking that
we have to do between now and Monday.''
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer's campaign lawyers contend that any finding of
fraudulently registered voters casting ballots on Nov. 3 could
result only in those people being purged from the voter rolls, but
that any such finding could not legally cause the result of an
election to be voided. They added that any information based on
verifications of credit history derived by a group of volunteers
would scarcely be admissible in court.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Goldstein, Spitzer's press secretary, said that the
Democrat was utterly unworried about what the Vacco campaign
investigators might uncover.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not very serious,'' Goldstein said. ``Mr. Vacco's
conduct is getting to be a daily joke, and people around the state
wake up each day asking themselves what wacky thing Dennis Vacco
will do next. His behavior is more frightening than the remake of
`Psycho.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-10-98 2322EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981210.0572 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 23:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4380 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-RODBELL-NYT &LR;      12-10 0423
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-RODBELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.)  
 MARTIN RODBELL IS DEAD AT 73; CHEMIST AND NOBEL LAUREATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Martin Rodbell, a biochemist who shared the 1994 Nobel Prize
in Medicine and Physiology for shedding light on the mysteries of
life's basic processes, died on Monday at the University of North
Carolina Hospitals in Chapel Hill, N.C. He was 73 and lived in
Chapel Hill.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was cardiovascular disease, his family said.
</P>
<P>
   Rodbell's career spanned more than four decades with the
National Institutes of Health, in Bethesda, Md. He formally retired
in 1994 from the National Institute of Environmental Health
Sciences in Research Triangle Park, N.C., but continued his
research.
</P>
<P>
   Rodbell and Dr. Alfred G. Gilman, a pharmacologist, won the
Nobel Prize for their work on a component of the communications
system that regulates cellular activity, known as G-proteins.
Proceeding separately on parallel research projects, the two men
discovered those proteins and how they work.
</P>
<P>
   G-proteins are natural substances that help cells translate
signals emitted by the environment and from within the body into
cellular chain reactions that govern fundamental life functions.
The discoveries led to the knowledge that some types of cancer are
caused by mutated and hyperactive G-proteins.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, Rodbell found that the signal transmission, or
transduction, by which the body's cells get their directions
requires a tiny intracellular molecule called guanosine
triphosphate, or GTP. That finding had many implications for the
treatment of many diseases, from cholera to cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Rodbell joined the staff of the National Institutes of Health in
1956 as a nutrition and endocrinology chemist.
</P>
<P>
   He was a native of Baltimore, graduated from Johns Hopkins
University in 1949 and received his doctorate from the University
of Washington in Seattle in 1954. After doing postdoctoral work in
chemistry at the University of Illinois, he joined the laboratory
of Christian Anfinsen, who shared the 1972 Nobel Prize in
chemistry, at the National Heart Institute.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, he transferred to North Carolina as scientific director
of the environmental health institute.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife of 48 years, Barbara Ledermann
Rodbell; three sons, Paul, of Silver Spring, Md., Andrew, of
Bethesda, and Phillip, of Hingham, Mass.; a daughter, Suzanne
Richardson, of Cabin John, Md.; a sister, Judy Risberg of
Baltimore, and seven grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
