<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: IN V FILES, INVISIBLE, DEAD AND ALIENS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CLYDE HABERMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dennis C. (for Can't Get Me Out of Office) Vacco has
been sprucing up his image. Until the last few weeks, Vacco was
destined to be best known as the New York attorney general who lost
Ellis Island to New Jersey. Now he may go down only as the
politician who did not get it when he heard the fat lady sing. In a
year or two, who will remember?
</P>
<P>
   Vacco has also given New Yorkers a reminder of how the crime
rate continues to fall. The police must have a good deal of time on
their hands if the state's chief law-enforcement officer thinks
that hundreds, possibly thousands, of them can be pulled off the
job to bang on doors searching for ineligible alien voters.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani also felt that this might be a
constructive use of police manpower, until he had second thoughts.
But then the mayor has dispatched his troops on all sorts of
assignments that were not standard when New Yorkers were being
bumped off at the rate of six a day.
</P>
<P>
   The police have been told to go after jaywalkers, wayward
bicycle riders, barricade-bashing pedestrians, people driving too
fast, cars stopped in no-standing zones, smokers tossing cigarette
butts into the street, ticket scalpers, errant taxi drivers and
assorted others deemed motes in the mayoral eye. That last category
includes citizens who think they have a right to just drop by City
Hall to see local government in action.
</P>
<P>
   Do New York police officers feel that politicians are asking an
awful lot of them these days? You bet, said James Savage, first
vice president of the Patrolmen's Benevolent Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``The police are expected to give out an extraordinary number of
summonses _ more than ever,'' he said. ``The more they give out,
the more the city wants.'' And the more public annoyance with the
police builds, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, there's a lot of resentment,'' Savage said, a view
echoed by Marie Rosen, publisher of Law Enforcement News, a
publication of John Jay College of Criminal Justice. One reason
many officers are resentful, she said, is that ``their pay is not
too hot.''
</P>
<P>
   It now appears that the Ballot Box Police will not be sent out
just because Vacco and the state Republican Party have trouble
accepting the slender victory of the Democratic candidate, Eliot
Spitzer. Still, the amount of creative energy spent on discrediting
Spitzer's vote totals has been impressive.
</P>
<P>
   First, the Republicans challenged absentee ballots from
Democratic strongholds with pettifoggery like objecting to ballots
on which voters wrote down Brooklyn instead of Kings as their
county of residence. That tactic went nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   So the Vacco camp then protested that graveyards were opened on
Election Day (most dead people, apparently, being Democrats). That
failed, too. Now the charge is that perhaps 100,000 people, many of
them immigrants, voted illegally in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   The basis for the allegation? A private credit-checking company
has no record of those people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think about my mother,'' Ms. Rosen said. ``She's 87. She
doesn't have a passport. She doesn't have a driver's license. She
doesn't have a credit card. And I haven't seen her
voter-registration card in 20 years.'' All the same, her mom has
lived in the same house in Brooklyn for years, and is a legitimate
voter.
</P>
<P>
   The big mystery is why New York Republicans think this is how to
reach out to future voters among the new immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   As for Vacco, he is hunkered down in his office, out of sight
and refusing to consider transition talks with the man elected to
succeed him on Jan. 1. There are important matters to discuss, and
time is short.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Vacco could explain how you go about, as he did,
replacing dozens of staff members with lawyers tied to your party's
leadership. Or how to make a top deputy of someone who failed the
bar exam seven times. Or how to set up a Web page like the one
Vacco created so the public could speak out on possible parole for
Joel Steinberg, the convicted child-killer _ a thumbs-up,
thumbs-down approach to criminal justice not used much since the
heyday of the Roman Colosseum.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, the two men could pass the time on pleasantries
like what they want for the holidays. Videos make nice gifts.
Here's a shopping tip for Spitzer. Judging from Vacco's recent
performance, two of his favorites are ``Night of the Living Dead''
and ``Alien Resurrection.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
