<HEADLINE>
WHEN LIBRARIES AREN'T FREE TO ALL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind., Vt., Texas, Mo., Ala., Ore.)  (lb) 
 By JOHN T. McQUISTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VALLEY STREAM, N.Y. _ Go to the public library and borrow a
book: Most Americans give it little thought.
</P>
<P>
   But there are almost 7 million people who do not have access to
a public library, according to the American Library Association.
And although New York City has three systems that make the largest
public-library network in the nation, New York state has more
people without a library _ 1.3 million _ than any other state.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when some of those people go to a neighboring town looking
for books, they find that the sign above the door _ ``Free
Library'' _ does not apply to them. They must pay annual fees of
from $25 to $300 a year for library privileges.
</P>
<P>
   But state officials say that these fees are wrong and they are
getting ready to take action to stop them.
</P>
<P>
   Local librarians agree in principle _ free access to everyone _
but they say they can't afford to comply.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ideally and philosophically, the state's position sounds fine,
but in reality, there is no free lunch, and that includes library
services,'' said Andrew Geddes, who for more than 22 years has
directed the Nassau Library System headquartered in Uniondale.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have long believed that library service is free,
especially if they come from New York City, where they can walk
into any branch and get service,'' he said. ``Most do not realize,
however, that they pay for that service through taxes collected one
way or another by the city.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So when somebody comes in from a neighboring town that doesn't
have a library and expects free service, it comes as a shock when
they're asked to pay for it,'' Geddes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't get the same reaction when they're asked to pay for
using a neighboring town's swimming pool,'' Geddes said.
</P>
<P>
   When Martha Jacovides moved here 30 years ago from New York
City, one of the attractions was a nearby public library. But when
she went to take out her first book, she was shocked to find that
she had to pay a special membership fee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was told I lived outside the boundaries of the incorporated
village of Valley Stream, so I had to pay for library services,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   At first Mrs. Jacovides paid a service fee of $30 a year. She
now pays $100 a year.
</P>
<P>
   But these user fees are in violation of guidelines established
50 years ago by the State Board of Regents, which charters public
libraries, according to Janet Welch, the state librarian.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rules are going to be enforced,'' said Mrs. Welch, who
since taking over the post of state librarian 14 months ago has
made free access to local libraries a top priority. She said there
had been a growing number of complaints and the state Board of
Regents, which had long been willing to overlook the access rules,
was ``now taking an activist role in enforcing the regulations.''
</P>
<P>
   She said that the board appointed a 17-member panel four months
ago to recommend solutions to the problem that could be carried out
in the year 2000. Until then, she said, the regents will ask local
librarians to adhere to an interim set of rules to be announced by
the board on Friday. Penalties will also be discussed, and Mrs.
Welch said they could include the discontinuation of interlibrary
loan services that are now financed by the state.
</P>
<P>
   Although public libraries will no longer be permitted to charge
nonresident fees under the new rules, they will be permitted, for
example, to place limits on some of their costlier services, such
as heavily attended story-telling hours or the ability to borrow
current best sellers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The use of libraries is exploding,'' Mrs. Welch said. ``The
Internet has made them important centers for information, so
everyone wants access, and no one should be denied.''
</P>
<P>
   Although New York has the largest population without library
service, the American Library Association says that six other
states _ Indiana, Vermont, Texas, Missouri, Alabama and Oregon _
report that 5 percent to 10 percent of their populations are
unserved.
</P>
<P>
   But 27 states report no unserved areas, because statewide and
state-financed reciprocal borrowing programs, such as the Colorado
Library Card, as well as other arrangements, provide some kind of
access to library services, according to Linda Wallace, a
spokeswoman for the library association.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Most of the local library districts on Long Island and elsewhere
in the state evolved more by chance than design as farming
communities became suburbs, and although chartered by the state,
they have remained fiercely independent and resistant to outside
interference.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Bayville Free Library, which began in 1903 when
a 14-year-old boy started lending books from a shelf in the corner
of his grandmother's candy shop, is among the smallest on Long
Island. The 6,000 residents of the village have resisted offers to
merge with a larger library in neighboring Locust Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Welch said there were 770 public-library systems throughout
the state; she did not know how many libraries were charging access
fees. ``Since they know they are in violation of a state regulation
by doing so, it's not something they tell us,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said complaints about fees had been increasing in recent
years after libraries came under pressure to install computers.
Many libraries now have Internet access for their patrons, but the
installation and maintenance has put pressure on already-squeezed
budgets.
</P>
<P>
   The state's 770 libraries have annual budgets totaling $700
million, paid for with local tax revenues, plus an additional $300
million from endowments, gifts and special funding. The state
contributes an additional $90 million a year and the federal
government $8 million, Mrs. Welch said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the local libraries that will be hardest hit by the new
state rules will be Mrs. Jacovides' library, the Henry Waldinger
Memorial Library in Valley Stream, which draws nonresident
borrowers from neighboring Millbrook and North Valley Stream in
Nassau County and from across the border in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had about 450 customers last year who paid access fees,''
said Marshal Botwinick, director of the library. He said the fees
were based on a system recommended by the Nassau Library System and
the amount of taxes paid by Valley Stream's 33,900 residents. The
library's $860,000 annual budget comes from tax revenues from
12,000 properties, most of them residential. He said revenue from
the special access fees totaled $20,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people don't object when you tell them it's the same
amount that local residents pay to support the library,'' he said.
The fees, he said, ranged from $25 per child to $100 for an entire
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Board of Regents orders us to drop those fees, then we
will not be able to provide people from other communities with
library services,'' Botwinick said.
</P>
<P>
   In Bay Park on the South Shore, 65 families seeking library
services went next door to East Rockaway and paid fees ranging from
$100 to $170. A dispute over the fees led to a referendum in which
voters in Bay Park approved the collection of a library tax in a
three-year experiment that will begin in January 2000. The
arrangement insures them full service at the East Rockaway Public
Library, according to Ellen Rockmuller, the library director.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an excellent idea and one of a number remedies the
state will definitely consider,'' Mrs. Welch said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
