<SLUG> BC-CIGARETTE-ADS-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CREATIVE TIME FOR MARKETERS OF CIGARETTES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.D., Wash., U.K.)  (js) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Under the recent tobacco settlement, cigarette manufacturers can
no longer give away lighters, clothing and other products bearing
their logos in exchange for the Camel Cash and Marlboro Miles
coupons included in cigarette packs.
</P>
<P>
   But the lists of customers who redeemed those slips could be the
first place the companies look when planning their new advertising
campaigns, providing a valuable data base for direct marketing
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to see more direct marketing,'' said Emanuel
Goldman, a tobacco and beverage industry analyst for Merrill Lynch.
``One of the outgrowths of a product like Marlboro gear is a big
address book. When you have constraints on marketing, people become
enormously creative.''
</P>
<P>
   The companies have relied heavily on direct marketing in the
United Kingdom, where cigarette advertising is more severely
restricted than in the United States. ``They've had to learn to
deal with, overseas, an environment that is far more severe than
anything the U.S. is going to see for years, if ever,'' Goldman
said.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement also bans outdoor billboard advertisements, the
use of cartoon characters, product placement in movies and
advertisements in magazines for young readers.
</P>
<P>
   Cigarette companies have until April 22 to take down their
signs, according to the Washington state attorney general's office.
</P>
<P>
   Although opponents of smoking have applauded the ad
restrictions, the limits may benefit the big cigarette companies by
making new competition virtually unthinkable. Without a data base
of customers or an established brand image, analysts say, it will
be difficult for a new company to sell products to smokers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The obvious forms of marketing are being removed from the
industry,'' said Martin Feldman, a tobacco business analyst for
Salomon Smith Barney in New York. ``Even in a more benign
advertising environment, how many new brands have there been in the
U.S.?''
</P>
<P>
   The four companies that dominate the industry are the Philip
Morris Cos.; R.J. Reynolds Tobacco, a subsidiary of RJR Nabisco
Holdings Corp.; Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco, a subsidiary of B.A.T.
Industries, and Lorillard Tobacco, a subsidiary of Loews Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Direct marketing could also fuel sales of the big four
companies' lower-priced brands to known smokers, Feldman said after
Philip Morris and RJR Nabisco raised their prices 45 cents a pack
on Nov. 24.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of direct mail efforts aimed at current smokers, the
states achieved the ``major intent of trying to stop marketing to
kids,'' said Fred Olson, a spokesman for the Washington state
attorney general, Christine Gregoire, who took up the negotiations
in June after an earlier $368.5 billion settlement failed in
Congress. Olson cited the bans on outdoor advertisements and
clothing bearing cigarette logos as important victories in that
effort.
</P>
<P>
   But some smoking opponents remain leery of the cigarette
marketers' resourcefulness. The companies have historically found
ways around advertising restrictions, including circumventing the
ban on television advertisements by buying attention-grabbing
billboards at widely televised sports events.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have always been creative in finding loopholes despite
restrictions they would consent to,'' said Randolph Smoak, chairman
of the American Medical Association's Board of Trustees. ``They
will continue to target young people.''
</P>
<P>
   The settlement allows state attorneys general to file lawsuits
against companies for violating the agreements, or consent decrees,
that bar them from marketing cigarettes to under-age smokers. The
companies will also be subject to lawsuits from the states if they
fail to enforce their trademarks by allowing retailers to illegally
advertise their products.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But even some lawyers for the states said the agreement's limits
might be difficult to enforce.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the imagery effectively used in cigarette advertising is
simply too vague to ban, said Laurie Loveland, the North Dakota
solicitor general who helped draft the advertising restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's basically just a picture of the West,'' Ms. Loveland said
of the Phillip Morris Cos.' advertisements for the Marlboro brand.
The company spends $115.5 million annually on print advertisements
for Marlboro, analysts estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Deliberately vague images that trigger brand associations have
also been successful in the United Kingdom, where advertisements
for Silk Cut cigarettes have featured nothing more than a light
blue roll of silk flapping in the breeze.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Marlboro, all you have to show are the spurs with the
right colors,'' said Goldman, the Merrill Lynch analyst.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
