A4400 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-KINGS-LBPT     12-10 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS LACK SCORING PUNCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Luc Robitaille says it is immaterial who is
lighting the red light _ as long as somebody is _ which is very
easy for him to say because he leads the Kings in goal-scoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who cares who scores?'' Robitaille said with a laugh Thursday,
the day after the Kings recorded a rare victory by defeating the
Washington Capitals 2-1. ``We've just got to find a way to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact is it matters quite a bit, because for most of this
season, if Robitaille (13 goals) or Glen Murray (11) don't score
for the Kings, no one scores at all. And with just a little more
production, the record of the Kings (7-17-3) might be much better,
13 of their losses having come by one or two goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``To win, you have to have two lines scoring and producing,''
Murray said. ``It's a fact around the league. Look at the teams
that are winning _ Dallas, Detroit, Colorado, Phoenix. You've just
got to have that to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings don't, and the numbers don't lie. In five of 27 games
this season, Robitaille or Murray (or Robitaille and Murray) have
been the Kings' only scorers, and in four other games, the team has
been shut out. In three other games, Robitaille and Murray scored
two of the Kings' three goals; in two other games, Robitaille and
Murray scored three of the Kings' four goals.
</P>
<P>
   In the last six games, in which the Kings are 1-5, Robitaille
has three goals, Murray has three, Vladimir Tsyplakov and Yanic
Perreault have one each and the rest of the team has as many goals
as the entire staff of this newspaper. In fact, 13 of the 18
forwards to wear a Kings uniform in 1998-99 have less than a hat
trick for the entire (begin ital)season.(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   ``We're having trouble scoring goals right now,'' said Murray,
whose recent linemates have been Robitaille and Perreault (one goal
in the last 23 games). ``We need another line scoring and helping
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Making matters worse, the Kings, who will seek their first
winning streak of the season when they play host to Vancouver at 7
p.m. Saturday, are getting little offensive production from their
defensemen, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Blake, who is expected to return to the lineup Saturday
after missing six weeks with a broken foot, leads Kings defensemen
with two goals, despite missing 15 of 27 games. Kings defensemen
have scored just six goals all season, and only one in the last 18
games (by rookie Mark Visheau against the New York Rangers in a 5-1
loss on Nov.19).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult,'' said Blake, who led NHL defensemen with 23
goals last season en route to winning the Norris Trophy. ``We've
got two guys scoring _ Glen and Luc. If you watch their goals, the
majority are coming from the front of the net. Guys have to watch
that. They have to get in front of the net and crowd it.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Larry Robinson has been saying that all season, that the
lack of traffic is a big part of the Kings' offensive impotence,
not just on the power play but also at even strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``The part that worries me is that if you take away the
shorthanded goals and the power-play goals, you're looking at
(1.41) goals per game 5-on-5 and 4-on-4,'' Robinson said. ``That
was our strength last year. We talked about our power play not
being very good last year, but 5 on 5, we were scoring goals in
bunches (2.01 a game).''
</P>
<P>
   The good news for the Kings is that Jozef Stumpel, besieged by
injuries all year, finally appears to be healthy and in good shape.
Robinson has been playing Stumpel, his best center and the Kings'
leader with 79 points last season, with Tsyplakov and Craig
Johnson. If they can start to click, the offense finally may
achieve some badly needed balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't expect to get all the scoring from the same people
all the time,'' Robinson said. ``It's time for other people to pull
their socks up.''
</P>
<P>
   Loose pucks: Winger Steve McKenna, who returned to the lineup
Wednesday only to re-injure his strained abdomen late in the game,
is listed as week-to-week, though trainer Pete Demers said it did
not appear he was injured as severely as the first time. McKenna
missed a month with his initial injury.... With McKenna sidelined,
Robinson said he is considering moving the 6-foot-6, 222-pound
Visheau to right wing to capitalize on his size and toughness along
the boards.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
