<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 23:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4433 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-1STLD-WRITETH     12-10 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPEACHMENT DEBATE BEGINS AFTER DAY OF FAR-FLUNG FINAL ARGUMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for general rewrite)  (Eds.: See also IMPEACH-HYDE, IMPEACH-CONYERS, IMPEACH-MOOD,
IMPEACH-LEWINSKY, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-CLINTON, IMPEACH-VIDEO,
IMPEACH-LAMEDUCKS, IMPEACH-DEBATE, IMPEACH-LIVINGSTON,
EDIT-IMPEACH, ROSENTHAL-COLUMN, BAKER-COLUMN) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(htv) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL with LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House Judiciary Committee began debating four
articles of impeachment Thursday night after Republican and
Democratic lawyers made their final arguments over President
Clinton's fate, marshaling videotapes, the words of the nation's
founders and competing views of the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   As the committee began pushing to finish its impeachment inquiry
this weekend, Speaker Newt Gingrich instructed the lame-duck 105th
Congress to be ready to return next week. He set next Thursday as
the day that the House could begin considering the impeachment of
Clinton. It would be only the second time in the nation's history
that the House has been called on to take such a vote.
</P>
<P>
   The raucous atmosphere that had so often pervaded the
committee's hearings gave way to grim solemnity as the 37-member
panel planned to vote on Friday and Saturday on whether to charge
the president with two counts of perjury and with obstruction of
justice and abuse of power. Republicans say it is certain the
committee will recommend Clinton's removal from office. The only
question is how many charges it will approve.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. F. James Sensenbrenner Jr., R-Wisc., opened the debate
Thursday night by calling for impeachment. ``I do so with no joy,
but without apology,'' he said. ``What is on trial here is the
truth and the rule of law.'' Republican after Republican followed
his lead.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Conyers Jr., D-Mich., the committee's ranking
Democrat, who also sat on the panel in the Watergate scandal,
warned Republicans that they were ``trying to overturn the result
of two elections.'' Democrats pleaded for censure as the best way
of ending the yearlong scandal that has engulfed the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the committee room, a fierce struggle was under way for
the hearts and minds of the two dozen or so undecided Republicans
who could swing the impeachment vote one way or another in the
House.
</P>
<P>
   At the hearing, most of the day was devoted to the summations of
the committee's senior lawyers, with the Republican counsel going
beyond the case to question the president's character, and the
counsel for the Democrats imploring the committee to consider how
the nation would react to what could be a months-long Senate trial
with Monica Lewinsky on the witness stand.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, both lawyers showed the nation excerpts from
Clinton's videotaped deposition in the Paula Jones case, testimony
that has been central to the impeachment case before the committee.
</P>
<P>
   David Schippers, the Republicans' chief investigative counsel,
said: ``Today, I come to the point that, frankly, I prayed I would
never reach. It is my sorrowful duty now to accuse William
Jefferson Clinton of obstruction of justice, false and deliberately
misleading statements under oath, witness-tampering, abuse of power
and false statements to and obstruction of the Congress of the
United States in the course of this very impeachment inquiry.''
</P>
<P>
   Schippers' lofty tone changed as he went beyond discussing
impeachable offenses to describe Clinton in scathing terms as a
deeply flawed man unfit for office. The Republican counsel referred
to ``cover stories'' and Clinton's ``crafty mind'' and his ``lame
and obviously contrived'' testimony. And he charged that there were
``allegations of possible serious wrongdoing'' and of ``probable''
crimes that he could not disclose because of ongoing criminal
investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Abbe Lowell, the counsel for the Democrats, said he was not
defending the president but the sanctity of the Constitution, as he
argued that the case against Clinton did not justify his removal
from office.
</P>
<P>
   ``From listening to our constitutional scholars, we learned that
impeachment is like the wall protecting the fort around the
separation of powers,'' Lowell said. ``The crack you put in the
wall today becomes the gash tomorrow, which ultimately leads to the
wall crumbling down.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowell also spoke of a ``constitutional quagmire'' over ``the
definition of sex,'' and said impeachment was not used ``when
President Lincoln suspended the writ of habeas corpus, nor when
President Roosevelt misled the public about United States
involvement in the lend-lease program, nor when President Reagan
misled the country and Congress about involvement with
Iran-contra.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, the White House sharply protested Schippers'
presentation. ``We are disappointed and saddened that the committee
majority brought this solemn constitutional process down to a level
of innuendo, anger and unfair, unsubstantiated charges,'' said
Gregory Craig, special counsel to the president.
</P>
<P>
   Two Democrats on the committee, Reps. Barney Frank of
Massachusetts and Zoe Lofgren of California, angrily compared
Schippers' intimations of secret crimes to McCarthyism.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the Judiciary Committee, Rep. Henry Hyde,
R-Ill., Thursday signaled that he would allow a censure vote in the
committee but could postpone it until next Tuesday. He made clear
that he opposed censure.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, who are trying to put forward a censure measure in
place of impeachment, were looking at toughening their own
proposals to demand a financial payment from the president in an
effort to draw more Republicans to their side. But it was still not
clear whether Republican leaders would allow the full House to vote
on a censure measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm waiting to see what the Judiciary Committee reports,''
said Rep. Robert Livingston, R-La., the incoming speaker, as he
sidestepped the question. ``And I'll deal with the procedure
according to what they report. I've not yet found out what they
anticipate.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, the nation saw videotaped excerpts of
Clinton's deposition in the sexual harassment case of Paula Corbin
Jones, as both lawyers used different parts of the same tape to
present their contrasting views.
</P>
<P>
   Telling the committee to ``listen to the president's deceptions
for yourself,'' Schippers played on large television screens
several clips in which Clinton said he could not recall being alone
with Ms. Lewinsky in the Oval office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life was so much simpler before they found that dress, wasn't
it?'' Schippers asked, referring to the blue dress that contained
evidence of Ms. Lewinsky's sexual relationship with the president.
</P>
<P>
   The tape also showed Clinton watching intently _ staring off
screen _ as his lawyer, Robert Bennett, read aloud Ms. Lewinsky's
affidavit saying she had not had a ``sexual relationship'' with
Clinton. ``That's absolutely true,'' the president had affirmed.
Bennett later notified the judge in the Jones case that Ms.
Lewinsky had retracted her affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   On the same television screen, Lowell displayed a different
segment of the tape, showing Clinton first studying a written
definition of sexual relations given him by the lawyers for Ms.
Jones and then listening as those lawyers, his lawyer and Judge
Susan Webber Wright of the U.S. District Court in Little Rock,
Ark., squabbled over the legal description of sexual relations.
</P>
<P>
   Sounding prescient, Bennett complained that ``this is going to
lead to confusion'' and argued that a deposition is not supposed to
be ``a trap.''
</P>
<P>
   The charges of perjury against the president stem from his
denial of sexual relations with Ms. Lewinsky. Lawyers for Clinton
have argued that he was not lying because he believed that sexual
relations meant intercourse, not other kinds of sex. Time and time
again, Schippers pointed to Clinton's pattern of answers that the
lawyer called a ``gratuitous insult to your intelligence and common
sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Schippers and Lowell did more than just argue the facts.
Faced with public opposition to impeachment, Schippers, a former
prosecutor, tried to raise fundamental questions about Clinton's
character, suggesting several times that he was not fit to be
president.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that Ms. Lewinsky, then a 22-year-old White House
intern, had never spoken to Clinton before their first intimate
encounter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometime on Nov. 15, 1995, Ms. Lewinsky made an improper
gesture to the president,'' he said. ``What did he do in response?
Did the president immediately confront her or report her to her
supervisors, as you would expect? Did he make it clear that such
conduct would not be tolerated in the White House? No. That would
have been an appropriate reaction, but it's not the one the
president chose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead, the president of the United States invited this
unknown young intern into a private area off the Oval Office, where
he kissed her,'' Schippers said.
</P>
<P>
   At another point he contended that the ``president's illegal
actions constitute an attack upon and utter disregard for the truth
and for the rule of law.'' And he said Clinton had an ``arrogant
disdain'' for fellow citizens like Ms. Jones and for the other
branches of government.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Lowell, himself a defense lawyer, tried to force
the committee to think about the prospect of a long Senate trial
featuring the entire cast of characters of the scandal, from Ms.
Lewinsky to her former friend and co-worker, Linda Tripp.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Lowell, using tapes and videotapes, showed how an aggressive
criminal defense lawyer might rebut the case against the president
in a trial. He attacked Ms. Lewinsky's credibility by playing a
tape of her conversation with Ms. Tripp on the telephone in which
she said she had learned how to lie and deceive throughout her
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are the issues of the president's conduct in this case so
grave,'' Lowell asked, ``that you would doom the country to
additional months of this ordeal and government paralysis _ on the
slimmest of votes on the House floor and no likely conviction in
the Senate?''
</P>
<P>
   The committee is expected to begin voting on four separate
articles of impeachment on Friday. They charge Clinton with perjury
in testimony before a grand jury, perjury in the Jones lawsuit,
obstruction of justice and abuse of power.
</P>
<P>
   Republican aides said the Republicans on the committee, who have
a 21-16 edge over the Democrats, have solid support for perjury and
obstruction of justice charges. But Rep. George Gekas, R-Pa., said
he was still undecided on abuse of power, based on the president's
claims of legal privileges.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are expected to vigorously debate the articles but are
not expected to try to amend them because they do not want to water
them down and make them more palatable to Republican moderates.
``We have no interest in improving what we regard as a fatally
flawed proposal,'' said Julian Epstein, the committee's Democratic
counsel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
