<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-10 23:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4440 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     12-10 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
 
McNOWN'S VISION GOES FAR BEYOND PLAYING FIELD 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Everybody talks about Cade McNown's telescopic
vision, his ability to see a receiver streaking open in the end
zone even as he himself is squirming to escape the clutches of some
300-pound lineman with halitosis.
</P>
<P>
   How the senior left-hander managed to find Brian Poli-Dixon on
that game-tying 7-yard touchdown pass at Miami as he was falling
out of bounds we'll never know.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, McNown sees so far it's staggering. His range of
view extends beyond the back goal line, past the Heisman Trophy
race, farther on than the NFL and well into middle age.
</P>
<P>
   His Bruins aren't going to win a national championship. It's
doubtful he'll lug home the Heisman on Saturday despite breaking
school records for career passing yards and total offense and
setting a single-game record in the loss to the Hurricanes by
throwing for 513 yards and five scores.
</P>
<P>
   It matters not that McNown probably lost his grip on the Heisman
the moment Texas running back Ricky Williams eclipsed Tony
Dorsett's national career rushing mark. The true measure of
McNown's success is that he has such a firm grasp of reality.
</P>
<P>
   He showed us that before he completed the first of his 23
touchdown passes this season. The week of the Bruins' game against
Williams' Longhorns, some nearsighted soul asked McNown if winning
the Heisman wasn't overrated, given that the only Bruin to win
college football's most coveted prize, quarterback Gary Beban,
ended up ``a failure'' in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   McNown shifted uncomfortably in his seat and we swear we heard
his hackles snap to attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' McNown said with a smirk, ``if you consider being in
charge of one of the largest commercial real estate companies a
failure. . .''
</P>
<P>
   As usual, McNown had delivered a strike. So what if Beban's NFL
career was history after two seasons? McNown was astute enough to
discern the seamless manner in which Beban quickly checked off to
another career option when his primary one was covered.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who make insane remarks like you're not a success
(unless you have a long NFL career) are losers,'' McNown reiterated
the other day. ``That's people just trying to find something wrong
with someone who's been a success. You see that all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   McNown's getting a dose of it now. We've heard the so-called
experts say he doesn't have a strong enough arm to succeed in the
NFL and that he's too slow. Yeah, right, and Doug Flutie's too
short.
</P>
<P>
   Come to think of it, people picked apart the 1983 Heisman
runner-up, a left-handed quarterback like McNown who finished
behind Nebraska running back Mike Rozier in the balloting and then
bolted for the L.A. entry in the U.S. Football League. Seems to us
Steve Young has gone on to do pretty well for himself.
</P>
<P>
   In 1967 Beban and linebacker Don Manning became the first Bruins
to be named consensus All-Americans in the same season. As so often
is the case on tight-knit teams, they would continue adding chains
to their link long after their college days were over.
</P>
<P>
   When Beban parted company with the Washington Redskins, he
sought out Manning, who was working for the C.B. Richard Ellis Co.
From that connection sprang a second career that has taken Beban
all the way to first string on C.B. Richard Ellis Co.'s management
team.
</P>
<P>
   In his role as the senior executive managing director of the
global corporate advisory group, Beban, 52, assists multinational
companies with commercial properties worldwide. Some 30 years after
he took his last snap, he continues to build relationships and draw
on his leadership skills and make quick reads on situations, just
not on the football field.
</P>
<P>
   For four years McNown has carried a football team on his
shoulders. The skills and strength he has picked up in the process
will serve him well regardless of what the Heisman voters and pro
scouts make of them.
</P>
<P>
   Beban, a three-year starter at UCLA during an era when freshmen
were ineligible, knew the writers who vote for the Heisman Trophy
and the scouts who report to NFL teams would be circling around
McNown this year like flies to fresh meat.
</P>
<P>
   So before the season began, Beban sat down and wrote McNown a
letter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspected he'd be involved with a season that had some
components of what I went through (in 1967),'' Beban said. ``I just
passed along some thoughts.''
</P>
<P>
   McNown, 21, was blown away by the gesture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was flattered,'' he said. ``It meant a lot that a guy like
him would take the time to impart some type of wisdom and explain
his point of view.''
</P>
<P>
   All this time McNown has been meaning to express his
appreciation to Beban. On Saturday he'll finally get the chance.
</P>
<P>
   Beban has arranged to see the player before the awards ceremony
at the Downtown Athletic Club.
</P>
<P>
   Some time during their conversation Beban plans to tell McNown
the same thing he told a reporter earlier in the week.
</P>
<P>
   Namely that he knows his successor when he sees him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cade McNown is the best quarterback that ever played at
UCLA,'' Beban said.
</P>
<P>
   Coming from him, who are we to argue? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
